<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S WRITER FINDS READERS AND A PRIZE BY PUBLISHING ON THE
WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Karen Byrum wrote in near obscurity for
years. The only people who saw the children's stories she wrote
were friends and the book publishers who mailed back rejection
after rejection.
</P>
<P>
   That changed a few weeks ago when Byrum, of North Kansas City,
built an Internet site, published her work on the Web and entered a
contest sponsored by a Massachusetts software company. In the last
five weeks, more than 5,000 people have seen the rhyming children's
stories she has written, according to the counter on her Web page.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, Byrum learned that her writing and the Web site
had paid off in a more tangible way. She won the top prize _
$20,000 _ in the contest sponsored by the Trellix Corp. Her Web
site at neonpeach.tripod.com was chosen from among more than 1,000
entries nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Trellix sponsored the contest to show off its partnership with
Tripod, an online site where more than 4 million people have built
Web sites. Tripod is one of the largest of dozens of Web
``communities'' where members register and then build and publish
Web sites, all for free.
</P>
<P>
   Eric S. Sall, a Trellix vice president, said it also showed the
power of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, it's been so hard to find a place to express
yourself,'' Sall said. ``But with the explosion of the Web, all
these people suddenly have a creative outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one knows for sure, Web communities such as Yahoo's
Geocities, Tripod and Xoom play host to Web pages built by 25
million or more computer users around the world. Some pages simply
tell a little bit about the person who built it. Many are used by
families to communicate and share photos. Others are in-depth sites
talking about hobbies or family histories.
</P>
<P>
   Until taking a class at Penn Valley Community College last year,
Byrum said she didn't even know how to turn a computer on and off.
She bought a computer about 18 months ago. Using other software,
she built her first Web site last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the ugliest thing you've ever seen in your life, but I
was pretty proud of it when I got done,'' Byrum said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum, who works for Digital Graphiti Studios, said Trellix made
it easy to build the Web site, which has more than 200 pages. She
said the software made it possible to create the page without
knowing any computer code and _ with one click _ publish it on the
Web. That eliminates a lot of steps traditionally involved with Web
publishing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, called Katie Did &AMP; the Neon Peach, is a collection
of rhyming stories written by Byrum. Many of the stories are
illustrated by Eddie Henry, a full-time casino worker who doubles
as illustrator for the Katie Did site. In the stories, Henry became
``Dr. Doodles.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said she hesitated before putting her work on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, people said, `Don't put your stories on the Web;
people will steal them,' '' Byrum said. ``Finally I figured you
have to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said she saw a notice about the contest, which was
organized into seven one-week contests. She saw that week's winner,
downloaded the Trellix software and ``built my page from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The star of the Web site, Katie Did, is described by Byrum as
her alter ego. ``Can't you tell by the glasses and the belly and
the hair?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Did falls down a hole at the beach and ends up in a
strange world under the sand ruled by the ``green goopy hand.'' The
stories are the tales of that underbeach world.
</P>
<P>
   The site has Byrum's stories, Henry's illustrations, and more
than 200 jokes and puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said she started writing the stories in 1992 and had been
rejected by 200 or more publishers. Although she doesn't have
children, she said she liked writing children's stories.
</P>
<P>
   Sall said the competition was tough. Winners of runner-up prizes
included a father recounting the story of his 4-year-old son's
diagnosis for leukemia, a photojournal of a trip to Nepal and
India, and a business Web site from a company selling scented bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``This site was the standout,'' Sall said of Byrum's work. The
bright green and purple colors used on the site and the use of
Trellix features to link pages and create special effects ``were a
great use of the software,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sall said Trellix was aiming for the ``mere mortal'' market with
its software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see our role as helping people create great content without
having to spend all their time worrying about computer code and the
actual mechanics of making the site,'' he said. ``A lot of people
are creating multiple Web sites _ some pages as a creative outlet,
some pages for things they collect, pages about their family. We
think that's going to be the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And the future is what Byrum is thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   For the grand prize, Byrum had her choice of the cash or a 2000
Volkswagen Beetle. She picked the cash, hoping to use it to somehow
further her writing.
</P>
</TEXT>
