<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR KANSAS ASTRONOMERS DISCOVER A COMET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Give a child a telescope for Christmas, and
who knows what might happen?
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hug got one years ago, and now he and a friend are going
down in astronomical history.
</P>
<P>
   Hug, 49, of Topeka, Kan., and Graham Bell, 64, of Maple Hill,
Kan., are believed to be the first in Kansas to discover a comet.
The two amateur astronomers saw it early Friday morning while
peering into a dark sky from the Far Point Observatory, about 20
miles outside Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking for comets off and on for about 25 years,''
Hug said Tuesday. ``It was a terrific thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   The find was announced over the weekend by the International
Astronomical Union, the world's leading astronomical organization,
after professional astronomers confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   The Hug-Bell comet, as it has been named, could well be the
faintest comet ever discovered by an amateur, as Hug and Bell
believe, said Brian Marsden, a member of the union and director of
the Minor Planet Center at the Harvard//Smithsonian Center for
Astrophysics in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Hug-Bell should be visible to earthbound astronomers every seven
years, which is how long it will take to go around the sun,
according to the calculations made by the two Kansans and other
astronomers who have studied it, Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hug and Bell) did a great piece of work on it,'' Marsden
said. ``It's really quite an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 comets have been discovered over the years, Marsden
said. This year, about 50 have been found. Ninety percent of them
were found by either a large astronomy outfit affiliated with the
U.S. Air Force in New Mexico, he said, or by a satellite that picks
them up while observing the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is booming,'' he said, mostly because of the
sophisticated detection equipment now available. ``We are seeing
more and more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hug and Bell, who belong to the Northeast Kansas Amateur
Astronomers League, went to their club's observatory about 9 p.m.
Thursday night to look for asteroids. They noticed the comet about
1 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little fuzzy,'' Hug said. ``It didn't sharpen up like
the rest of the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The two were using an electronic camera, a 12-inch telescope and
other electronic and computer equipment worth about $10,000. They
took more pictures of the sky, increasing the exposure time to 10
minutes, and then to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finally began to show a tail,'' Hug said.
</P>
<P>
   A comet is basically a dirty ice ball. It's made of frozen gases
and ice mixed with dust. The sun's heat causes the outer layer of
the comet to evaporate and release dust and gases that form a tail.
</P>
<P>
   The Hug-Bell's orbit is believed to extend to Jupiter. Hug
estimates that the comet's width at a third of a mile to 1.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Hale-Bopp comet, which passed by Earth in
1997, measures about 25 miles across. It was one of the biggest aghtest comets this generation is expected to see.
</P>
<P>
   The only disappointing thing about the Kansas discovery, Bell
said, was that no one will ever be able to see the comet with the
naked eye or even a backyard-type telescope. It's too faint for
that.
</P>
<P>
   Hug expects he will be able to see the newly found comet for a
few more weeks. It probably will be out of sight about the time the
glow of Christmas fades.
</P>
</TEXT>
