<HEADLINE>
WIRE BARRIERS ARE PREVENTING CROSSOVER ACCIDENT, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When a car stopped suddenly in front of his
tractor-trailer on Interstate 435 early Monday, Jaime Thompson
slammed on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   His 80,000-pound rig swerved, overturned and skidded across the
grassy median near Bannister Road.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of smashing into the oncoming northbound traffic,
the vehicle slammed into flexible steel cables installed to prevent
crossover accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 29, of Anniston, Ala., walked away with minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Had Thompson's accident happened six months ago, the result
might have been more serious, Missouri Department of Transportation
officials said. While they could not state definitively that the
cables saved Thompson's life, officials said they helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really designed to stop a semi, but in this case it
did help,''said Steve Porter, a department spokesman. ``It's
gratifying to see it helped to stop an accident that could have
been a fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   Three strands of steel cable have been strung along about 15
miles of I-435 so far, part of a $3 million state transportation
project.
</P>
<P>
   When the project is completed in mid-January, the cables will
stretch 20 miles along I-435, from the Grandview Triangle north to
the I-435//Interstate 35 interchange in Clay County.
</P>
<P>
   Since the project began in mid-July, vehicles have struck the
cables 33 times, state transportation officials said, but no fatal
crossover accidents have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there were 12 accidents in which cars crossed the
median along I-435, resulting in eight deaths, said Kansas City
police Sgt. Randy Sims with the accident investigations unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we know will save lives,'' Porter said.
``Before, if you went in the median and you were going at a high
speed, you could become airborne. Now, you shouldn't become
airborne. You should stick, like in a net.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials project that there may be as many as
267 collisions with the wires next year.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri transportation officials began sorting through ideas
last summer to make commuting on I-435 a little safer.
</P>
<P>
   They considered concrete barriers. But they estimated that they
would have cost about $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Called New Jersey barriers, they are stronger than the cable
system but a lot more expensive, Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has replaced cable wire barriers with New Jersey
barriers, said Mick Halter, metro engineer for the Kansas
Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Halter said Kansas removed most, if not all, of the cable wire
barriers from its highways about 10 years ago because they did not
meet the safety designs of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we had met the current standards, but it was old stuff,''
Halter said. ``The wire barriers were from the old 1950s design and
weren't nearly as good as what is available today.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable wire barriers also require a lot of space in the
roadway's median, which often is not available in metropolitan
areas, Halter said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey barriers have a special shape that deflects
vehicles back into their lanes, preventing them from crossing the
median into oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Such barriers can be found along Interstates 35, 70 and 635 as
well as along parts of I-435.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/The Missouri cable project is being done in three phases.
The first leg, which runs from I-435 north of the river to the
I-435//I-35 interchange, was completed in late August. The second
phase, completed in late November, runs from the Grandview Triangle
north to U.S. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials estimated that the third and final
phase, which will extend from U.S. 24 to the Missouri River, will
start within a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some local residents were skeptical when we first started,''
said Joel Blobaum, a Missouri Department of Transportation
spokesman. ``But we're hoping it's proven its worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it's operating as we'd hoped it would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
