<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONTON GETS JUMP ON THE ISLANDERS IN 4-2 WIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ On paper, it seemed like a draw _ a team with
only two victories on the road visiting a team with only two
victories at home.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where any similarity between the Edmonton Oilers and
the New York Islanders began, and ended. Tuesday night, before a
crowd of 6,526 at Nassau Coliseum, the Islanders dropped their
seventh straight home game, 4-2, to the quick-skating Oilers, who
are unbeaten in three straight road games.
</P>
<P>
   Much as they did against the New Jersey Devils on Saturday in a
3-1 victory, the Oilers were quick to pounce. Right wing Bill
Guerin scored Edmonton's first goal at 4 minutes 56 seconds, and
right wing Pat Faloon made it 2-0 at 12:22 on a shot that slowly
rolled across the goal line after eluding the grasp of the rookie
goalie Roberto Luongo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get the first goal at home,'' Islanders coach
Butch Goring said. ``We're fragile. We can hear the boo-birds
coming out early. We just made a mistake on the first goal and then
another one eight minutes later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders trimmed the deficit to a goal at 6:46 of the
second period when Mariusz Czerkawski scored his 12th goal of the
season. Taking the feed from Zdeno Chara, Czerkawski shot the puck
off an Oiler's skate and past goaltender Tommy Salo. Czerkawski had
a chance to tie the score a few minutes later on a shot from right
in front of the net, but Salo was able to make the save with his
body.
</P>
<P>
   As the Islanders grew more frustrated, the Oilers scored two
goals late in the second period to put the game out of reach. Mike
Grier, despite being tied up with defenseman Jamie Rivers in the
slot, was able to shoot the puck past Luongo for a 3-1 lead at
16:49.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers made the score 4-1 when Janne Niinimaa's shot from
the left point on the power play beat Luongo on his glove side as
Ryan Smyth and Rivers were about to fall on him. Referee Bernard
DeGrace ruled that the collision came after the goal was scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way I could reach the puck because those guys
were in the way,'' said Luongo, who stopped 27 shots. ``I don't
know if that's supposed to be a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' Mats Lindgren made the score 4-2 with an
unassisted goal at 13:56. The Islanders, now 6-17-4, were unable to
score again, and were 0-5 on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brain dead as far as the power play goes,'' Goring
said. ``We did a lot of standing and thinking instead of skating
and reacting.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
