<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE'S 2ND-QUARTER RESULTS BEAT ANALYSTS' EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Oracle Corp. soared Tuesday evening in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The gains came after the company reported second-quarter
earnings that beat estimates and defied predictions of a slowdown
in software sales as corporations focused on Year 2000 computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' expectations were dampened in September, when Oracle's
first-quarter earnings just met estimates and revenue growth fell
short. Oracle executives, at the time citing a seasonally weak
quarter and a few big sales that slipped past the closing date,
predicted a strong year. Today's results were sweet vindication for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Y2K quarter, and I expected it to be tough,''
said William Epifanio, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. Oracle's
database and big applications like accounting and human resources,
he said, are exactly the kind of software purchases that analysts
had expected corporations to defer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They defied Y2K,'' he said, ``and I think from this point
forward we can expect even better performance. With everything
happening in e-commerce, the market is moving in Oracle's
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle reported after the close of the Nasdaq market, which had
seen its shares drop 2 7/8, to 76 15/16. But in after-hours
trading, they jumped 7 1/16 to 84 and were expected to lift opening
stock prices Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Nov. 30, Oracle earned $384 million, or 26
cents per diluted share, up 40 percent from $274 million, or 19
cents per share, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue grew 13 percent, to $2.32 billion, compared with $2.06
billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected per-share earnings of 22 cents, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said revenue from software licensing grew 18 percent year
over year. Database software sales increased 17 percent, to $651
million, while applications software sales grew 31 percent, to $168
million. Services, which include education, consulting and support,
rose 10 percent, to $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sixth quarter in a row that we've improved our
margins,'' Jeff Henley, the chief financial officer at Oracle, said
in a telephone interview. ``That's something we think will continue
as we convert to an e-business.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Ellison, Oracle's chairman and chief executive, said six
months ago that the company would transform itself into an Internet
company by moving most sales to the Worldwide Web, replacing
multiple computer systems around the world with central
Internet-based servers and procuring supplies electronically. His
goal was to cut $1 billion in costs within 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle also updated its products, including its core database
program, Oracle 8i, and all applications to operate over the
Internet, so that users need no software except a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle also claims to be the only vendor now offering a complete
suite of business applications, including both back-office
programs, like human resources and accounting, and front-office,
like sales force management and purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you can just buy it all from Oracle and it all works
together and it all works over the Internet,'' Ellison said in a
conference call with analysts. ``My summary for the quarter is,
`Gentlemen, you ain't seen nothing yet.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0017EST &QL; 
