<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR, OFFENSE PROVIDE PRODUCTION AS DEVILS DOWN KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the first eight minutes of the second
period Tuesday night, the Los Angeles Kings took the only six
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings swarmed Martin Brodeur, the New Jersey Devils'
goaltender, with intensity at the north end of Continental Arena.
But Brodeur held his ground to the delight of many in the crowd of
10,807, the smallest turnout in a season without a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Making his 20th start in the last 21 games, Brodeur was
magnificent during those minutes under fire, to such a degree that
his saves inspired the Devils, who went on to an easy 7-1 victory
over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty made the saves when he had to,'' Devils captain Scott
Stevens said about Brodeur, who made 34 saves and allowed only a
goal _ to Donald Audette. Brodeur's best save came against Jason
Blake when two Kings broke in alone during the second period.
Brodeur stormed out of the Devils' net for the save.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were desperate to redeem themselves for an awful
first period in their previous game here, a 3-1 loss to Edmonton
Saturday afternoon. They played with vigor for the most part, and
had some luck when the game's outcome was still in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good first period, which was important after what
happened in the last game,'' Stevens said. ``We got a couple of
good bounces, too.''
</P>
<P>
   John Madden was the luckiest of the Devils during a short-handed
situation for New Jersey with 7 minutes 41 seconds left in the
second period. His weak shot from center ice, about 80 feet away,
bounced once after it was slightly deflected around the blue line
and then the puck eluded Stephane Fiset for a goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was Madden's third goal of the season, and gave the Devils a
4-1 lead. Fiset was so rattled after it that he allowed another
goal, to Jay Pandolfo, 49 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   Madden was one of seven Devils scoring, a development that
pleased coach Robbie Ftorek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to see it spread around,'' Ftorek said. ``We got
all kinds of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux and Patrik Elias scored the first two goals 48
seconds apart, starting at 5:04, and Randy McKay gave the Devils a
three-goal lead with 2:13 left in the first period before Audette
beat Brodeur at 8:02 of the middle period.
</P>
<P>
   The first three goals for the Devils came when they gained
possession in the Kings' zone after poor clearing attempts by the
visitors. Lemieux's eighth and Elias' second of the season were
also scored with no one from the Kings near them.
</P>
<P>
   The three goals by the Devils in the first period prompted coach
Andy Murray of the Kings to replace goaltender Jamie Storr, who
faced 14 shots. Fiset faced 22 shots and allowed four goals.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott scored the sixth goal for the Devils (16-10-3) with
1:58 left in the second period and Sergei Nemchinov iced the
victory with 2:25 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take the goals any way we can get them,'' Ftorek said.
``We got all kinds of goals tonight because guys were going to the
net and we got some nice, pretty plays, and we got some ugly
ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
