<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-15 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL REGULATORS BLOW CALL ON POOR SHOWING BY PRIVATE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just when the world of pro and big-time college sports
can't get any more preposterous, an episode in high school sports
sets the bar even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Kedzie Gunderson is a junior basketball player, a good one, on
Bellevue High School's girls basketball team. At least she has been
for the past couple of weeks, once the governing board of state
prep sports reinstated her eligibility to end a sorry saga of bad
results from good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Citing harassment by teammates, Gunderson in the fall of 1998
transferred from Gig Harbor High School to Bellevue, where she
played her sophomore season, helping lead the 25-4 Wolverines to a
fifth-place finish in the Class 3A state tourney.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, some officials and parents at Gig Harbor
questioned whether Gunderson and her family actually moved to
Bellevue, suspecting they were skirting rules about establishing
residency in a new district.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Interscholastic Activities Association snapped
into action, in a way the agency had never done before.
</P>
<P>
   It hired a private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The guy followed Gunderson. He tailed her on the freeways, into
the school parking lot and back to her Bellevue home. He recorded
the comings and goings of cars at the Gundersons' former residence
in Gig Harbor, now rented to the mother of Gail Gunderson, Kedzie's
mother.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded that the Gundersons were keeping dual residences.
</P>
<P>
   But he never interviewed the Gundersons, nor anyone who had
knowledge of them. Neither did the WIAA , which received the
evidence. Nor was there due process to allow the Gundersons a
chance to rebut the findings.
</P>
<P>
   What there was, was an Oct. 25 letter from WIAA attorney and
associate athletic director John Olson to Bellevue athletic
director Chris Hoffman, saying Gunderson, because of the
dual-residency finding, was ineligible and must sit out the
1999-2000 athletic year.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to tell whether Gail and her husband, Jim, both
psychologists and social workers, were more shocked or angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kedzie was the happiest she'd been in school, and all of a
sudden, she's ineligible because some people said her parents were
liars,'' Gail said. ``It's as if the sheriff had knocked on your
door and said, `You've been tried, convicted and sentenced. Didn't
you know?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Gundersons hired an attorney for an appeal and received a
hearing before the WIAA executive board on Nov. 23. Jim Gunderson
provided evidence that he kept an office in a studio at the Gig
Harbor residence to serve area clients, and produced income tax
statements, drivers' licenses, bank accounts, utility bills and a
lease to prove their new residence was Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   Kedzie and her mother also established that they showed up
occasionally at the old Gig Harbor house to visit Gail's mother,
who lives alone and is limited by severe vision problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, the board agreed with the Gundersons, saying it
``questioned the accuracy and reliability of the information that
had been provided by an independent investigator.''
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of eligibility was a rebuke for Mike Colbrese,
the WIAA executive director who ordered the hiring of the
ineffectual gumshoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've done this,'' Colbrese said this
week. ``We've been talking about something like this for four or
five years because of the increasing number of cases where there is
suspicion of more aggressive families seeking a way around the
eligibility rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Colbrese said eligibility questions take up more than 80 percent
of Olson's work time in an organization that has administrative
authority over 200,000 prep athletes in the state.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he ``would not hesitate'' to hire a spy on another
kid in a similar circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was warranted in this case,'' he said. ``Would we
do a better and more thorough job next time? I would hope they
would do a thorough job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gundersons also hope the WIAA does a thorough job of
thinking out its policies and procedures. The affair cost the
Gundersons nearly $10,000, not to mention the heartache and lost
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   They also were dumbfounded that anyone at Gig Harbor would, a
year after the transfer, stir this up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said this isn't working well, Kedzie was ostracized, and
our only option was to move,'' Gail said. ``So we moved. We never
complained to the WIAA, we never put anything in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are people picking on a 16-year-old? Why attempt to
destroy us? Why aren't they just happy we left?''
</P>
<P>
   Gig Harbor principal Mike West said there was no vendetta. He
said he and coach Bob Boback brought the Gunderson matter to
Colbrese's attention during a routine meeting in August that
covered eligibility issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Mike that there were reports that Kedzie was still in
the community,'' West said. ``People said to me, `You're the
principal. Why do we have rules if they're not enforced? What are
you going to do about it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So Mike said he would look into it, and that was it from my
standpoint. If we were out to get somebody, why would we wait a
year? As far as Kedzie, she's a nice young lady, and I wish her the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   According to those familiar with the situation, Kedzie
Gunderson's talent created resentment among older players, and the
elder Gundersons were seen by some as overbearing. The Gundersons
denied any interference, although they often disagreed with Boback,
a longshoreman in Tacoma who walked into the controversy in his
first year as a head prep coach and his first time coaching girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad deal, it really is,'' said Boback. ``The idea they
were picked on is totally untrue. It was more like a case of a
talented freshman and her family expecting special treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the did-too, did-not aspect of the episode _ and it
is considerable _ the WIAA's hamfisted handling of the case fairly
screams for reform regarding policies about fairness and students'
rights. As anyone who has had a high school civics class can
recall, the Gunderson case is not how honest business is done in
America.
</P>
<P>
   But Colbrese and the WIAA are also flailing almost helplessly
against a national problem _ overwrought parents who futilely jerk
their kids from school to school and badger coaches and
administrators in search of playing time, glory and the elusive
college scholarship. The scourge is driving legions of quality
coaches from the profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely troubling to have to hire from outside the
school system to determine residency records of this student or
that student,'' Colbrese said. ``I don't like being there. But some
(parents) are getting more aggressive and subtle and secretive
about getting around the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than do nothing more than cough nervously over the
Gunderson case, the WIAA and its member schools would do well to
use the mess to jump-start a discussion about moving from the
autocratic to the democratic, as well as finding fresher, more
effective tools to curb those parents who are squeezing the
vitality and fun from high school sports.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
