<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      12-15 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S POSITION BINDS M'S, BUT GILLICK PERSEVERES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Griffey Jr. will accept a trade only to
the Cincinnati Reds. The Reds will not trade for him. But in the
minds of the Mariners, one plus one doesn't always equal two.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners general manager Pat Gillick left the winter meetings
Tuesday morning with the same team he had coming in. He will
continue to try to make deals, including one for Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody on the ballclub _ forget about Griffey _ if you can
improve and get better, then you've got to try,'' Gillick said. ``I
don't think you ever cease trying to improve your club, no matter
who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners still consider Griffey their most tradable player,
even if the past six weeks have proven no player may be tougher to
move. The M's have found no interest in other players they have
shopped, and continue to turn away inquiries _ from the Mets, White
Sox and probably others _ about shortstop Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   So that leaves Gillick with two options: Make more deals like
Monday's with the Mets and take them to Griffey for almost certain
rejection, or give up and start the season with Griffey on the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the Anaheim Marriott Tuesday morning, Reds GM
Jim Bowden reiterated that he didn't blame Gillick for the asking
price Bowden rejected. But Bowden implied the Mariners might have
miscalculated once they knew Griffey had cut his list to one team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Gillick) was never going to back off that player
(infielder Pokey Reese), it was never going to make any
difference,'' Bowden said. ``But if he thought there was one club
the whole time, I would think he would make the best deal he could.
... You may end up with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Mariners' risk. Griffey has changed his mind before,
but he also has been stubborn about things. Griffey apparently
feels challenged by the Mariners' statements that he changes his
mind often, and he is determined to stick to his
Cincinnati-or-Seattle stance.
</P>
<P>
   To Gillick, bringing back Griffey doesn't sound so bad.
</P>
<P>
   With Griffey, Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez and John Olerud, Gillick
said, the Mariners have a lineup that includes four of baseball's
top hitters. The GM dismissed the suggestion that uncertainty over
Griffey's future will become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distraction?'' Gillick said. ``When he gets on the field,
he's going to play. I think that's overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the organization believe Griffey's sensitivity could
affect his play, and the Mariners certainly remember Randy
Johnson's departure under similar circumstances in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillick's chance of appeasing Griffey with a Cincinnati
trade is remote. Bowden said all the Reds' offers are gone, and
explained that he already has lost the chance to maximize Griffey's
impact on Reds ticket sales. He sounded relieved to be keeping his
young nucleus intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe the number of calls I got from our
players saying thank you for not breaking up this team,'' Bowden
said.
</P>
<P>
   With no workable trades in place, the Mariners will continue
their efforts to sign free agents, including leadoff hitter Mark
McLemore, starter Chuck Finley and relievers Arthur Rhodes and
Kazuhiro Sasaki, a closer. The Mariners have included closer Jose
Mesa in trade talks, possibly indicating they believe they can sign
Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, however, was in Cleveland Tuesday night and met with the
Indians' top officials. His travel plans indicate he is not
scheduled to leave Cleveland until Thursday, which could mean an
announcement is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   A-ROD MEETING OFF? Gillick is still hopeful of meeting with
Rodriguez again this winter, but Rodriguez's agent, Scott Boras,
said he doubted a meeting would take place. Rodriguez, who has no
desire to negotiate before he becomes a free agent next fall, met
with Gillick and other officials last month after the club
presented an eight-year contract offer worth more than $15 million
per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention of the parties was made clear then, so there's
nothing pressing,'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   Does Boras think the breakdown in Griffey trade talks might
cause the M's to shop Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're contemplating,'' he said. ``Alex has
made it clear that he wants to stay and try to win there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
