   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WHITMAN (Washington) _ It once seemed that the word
failure was not a part of Bill Bradley's lexicon. He had been a
Rhodes Scholar, Olympic gold medalist, two-time NBA champion and,
on his first foray into politics in 1978, the winner of a Senate
seat from New Jersey. In 1984, he won re-election by one of the
largest margins in state history. So in 1990, when Bradley came
within 3 percentage points of losing his once safe bastion to an
unknown, poorly financed Republican named Christie Whitman, he was
devastated. To many of his critics and supporters alike, the
disastrous 1990 campaign _ both sides use the adjective _
represents the most important event in Bradley's political life. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRS-TARGETS (Undated) _ The Internal Revenue Service, under
pressure from Congress to help taxpayers more than to investigate
them, is reassigning thousands of agents who audit and collect
taxes from companies and high-income individuals to answer
telephones, staff counters and resolve the tax disputes of
estranged couples. At the same time, the agency is reducing its
efforts to find cheating by businesses and high-income individuals,
and stepping up investigations into two forms of cheating that are
more likely to involve the working poor than the rich. By David Cay
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   USED-CARS (Canton, Mich.) _ With acres of parking lots marked
with color-coded signs surrounding a large, high-ceilinged building
of tan brick and glass, the AutoNation store here in the Detroit
suburbs looks more like a gigantic Starbucks than a place to sell
used cars. But while AutoNation succeeded in its goal of creating a
cheerful, comfortable place to buy used cars, it failed to do so in
a way that would earn money. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
