<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAILS FEDS AS READY FOR Y2K 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government has licked nearly all of its
year 2000 computer problems, the Clinton administration announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But with only 16 days remaining before the New Year, a quarter
of the states and territories are still scrambling to correct and
test computer systems affecting some major, federally funded
programs, from food stamps to Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Management and Budget reported Tuesday that 99.9
percent of the key computer systems at the government's largest
agencies are ready for the year 2000 date change.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 6,175 ``mission critical'' systems are not yet Y2K
compliant, but work on those systems is slated to be completed by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Hailing the report, President Clinton said: ``The facts are
clear. We have done our job. We have met the deadline, and we have
done it at below cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is expected to spend a total of $8.38
billion to deal with the so-called ``millennium bug,'' the
seemingly omnipresent computer glitch that can render computers
unable to read the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While hefty, the government's Y2K bill will be a far cry from
the $50 billion cost some were predicting, administration officials
noted.
</P>
<P>
   With the vast majority of the work at the federal level now
completed, officials in Washington are now trying to help those
states and territories still struggling to complete their computer
work on time.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Management and Budget identified nine states, four
territories and the District of Columbia as jurisdictions which
still needed to complete computer work for programs ranging from
child nutrition to unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, American Samoa, Guam and the Virgin Islands have the
most work to finish, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas was not listed among the laggards. But the state's child
nutrition program, the report noted, had yet to be certified as Y2K
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Sherron Heinemann, a spokeswoman for the Texas Department of
Human Services, said state officials sent the necessary paperwork
to Washington more than two months ago but had had trouble getting
federal officials to update their database.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the five agencies critical to the operation of the federal
government still to be corrected, two affect military intelligence
systems. Pentagon officials noted, however, that one of those
systems is to be retired at the end of the month, while the other
will not be needed until the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium bug also affected a clock on the Abrams M-1A2
tank. Pentagon officials said that was only a ``cosmetic'' problem
that would be corrected by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The computer bug could also affect office automation projects at
the Drug Enforcement Administration and at the Justice Department's
tax division.
</P>
<P>
   Officials conversant with the Y2K issue at these agencies could
not be reached for immediate comment, although the Office of
Management and Budget report noted that both agencies had
contingency plans in place.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has not been alone in its Y2K efforts.
The Commerce Department estimates the nation as a whole will spend
$100 billion fixing the millennium bug. And despite all the blood
and sweat, not all of the work will be completed on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously too early to declare victory and go home,''
John Koskinen, the White House's Y2K czar told reporters Tuesday at
a speech at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition to the new century will not be perfect,''
Koskinen noted. ``Not every system will be fixed, and even some of
those that have been fixed and tested may experience glitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of continuing concerns, Amtrak, the nation's passenger
rail service, said Tuesday it plans to halt all train service
before midnight on New Year's Eve as a safety precaution. Service
will resume once Amtrak officials are confident the Y2K problems
will not endanger its passengers.
</P>
<P>
   To keep passengers happy during the service lull, Amtrak plans
to throw New Year's parties on its trains.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nation's chemical plants, meanwhile, plan to shut
down over the holiday rather than run the risk of encountering a
surprise Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no free lunch,'' Koskinen said. ``When you shut
complicated systems down and then start them up again, you have a
risk, in the shutdown, in the start-up. And the consensus of the
chemical industry and the nuclear industry is that people need to
do that if they think there are risks. If you thought there were no
significant risks, then you've increased the risks by requiring
everybody to shut down and start up. And the chemical plants
especially (those) that run continuously are very sensitive about
that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
