<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPING SPURS BEAT MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When the Dallas Mavericks upset San Antonio late last
season at Reunion Arena, there was a lot of yelling going on in the
Spurs' locker room after the game.
</P>
<P>
   No such screaming took place Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The defending NBA champs used a torrid second-half to squash the
Mavericks, 111-93, before 13,685 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the return of power forward Gary Trent could prevent
the Mavericks from losing. Trent started the game and finished with
12 points (6-of-14 shooting) and four rebounds in 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't nearly enough to offset a Spurs team that came in a
bit antsy after losing Saturday at home to lowly Washington, 99-89,
dropping them to 1-4 in a five-game stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were mad or angry at all,'' said Cedric
Ceballos, who led the Mavericks with 27 points and 10 rebounds. ``I
just think they dug down and did the things it took to win the
basketball game, and we didn't have all of our players at full
strength shooting very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the world champs, and they did the things they needed
to do in the stretch to win the basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks trailed only 51-46 at halftime. But little-touted
Chucky Brown scored 10 points in the third period, and the Spurs
took an 83-70 lead into the final period and poured it on from
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He surprised us with those jump shots,'' said Robert Pack, who
scored 14 points and handed out eight assists. ``He got some easy
ones on the breaks, but also was able to hit some shots from 15
feet that really dug a hole for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After an impressive two-week period, Mavericks guard Michael
Finley had a subpar performance. Finley was 5-of-15 from the field
and collected 15 points, two rebounds and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an off night,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson said. ``I
thought they played him real well. They crowded him ... and made
him be a passer, and he tried to make good passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he did have some shots, they just didn't go. He didn't
have many good looks, but when he did, he struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavericks forward Samaki Walker scored eight points and
snatched four rebounds in 17 minutes. Walker, who left the
Mavericks during the off-season via free agency, was booed when he
entered the game in the second and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised (to get booed), but it happens like that,''
Walker said. ``It's a home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was to stay focused and not make this a personal
issue. It's not Samaki against the Mavericks; it's the Spurs
against the Mavericks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan led the Spurs with 29 points and 12 rebounds, Avery
Johnson scored 16 and David Robinson had 10 points and nine
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the way back up,'' Duncan said. ``We went down for a
little while, and we hadn't been playing real well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of film sessions and a couple of practices,
and we're on our way back to where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent hopes he's on his way back, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to come back and get a feel,'' he said. ``I'll
give it a few weeks, go to practice tomorrow and work on some
things and come back Thursday and give it another try.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs shot .506 percent from the field in improving to 16-7,
while the Mavericks dropped to 8-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came and we played hard,'' Pack said. ``We didn't do a lot
of things particularly well mentally, but we played hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go back to practice tomorrow and hopefully
come back against New York and have a better effort.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
