<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH MIGHT SERVE RANGERS BEST IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball's annual winter meetings have come and gone, and the
question lingers:
</P>
<P>
   What happened to all the drunken sailors?
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the free-spending Jerry Colangelos and the
Kevin Malones? Where are the Brinks trucks? Why hasn't anyone
signed Chuck Finley for $60 million plus weekly use of a Boeing
727?
</P>
<P>
   And most of all, why doesn't anyone want to play for the
Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   You know it's time to check your girdle when a pudding-soft
streak hitter like Todd Zeile, though presented a $16 million
Christmas gift, turns up his nose at the Rangers' offer and opts
instead for the friendly environs of the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful how you overreact on this one. Zeile's midnight
signing Saturday likely says more about him than it does the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The talk-show talk has been that the home team can't close a
deal _ that general manager Doug Melvin is better at wheeling and
dealing than he is at courting and wooing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year's Randy Johnson World Tour. Not to
mention the Stottlemyre Family Rent-A-Todd Summer Package and, of
course, the Roger Clemens No Place But Texas Sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin and the Rangers landed none of the three. Nor have there
been any alleged sightings of Ken Griffey Jr., scouting for a new
house in Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the one player who did want to sign with the Rangers
is now in Detroit _ right, Juan Gonzalez?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has heard all the can't-close-the-deal talk. He quietly
reminded a caller Tuesday that John Wetteland, Ken Hill, Pudge
Rodriguez and Rafael Palmeiro all wanted to play for the Rangers
and signed on the dotted line.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each of those other cases, there were reasons,'' Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lived in Arizona and was able to match his family's
wishes with Colangelo's genuflecting checkbook. Ditto for
Stottlemyre, who made only 17 starts yet banked a 1999 salary of $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   In Clemens' case, you could argue that owner Tom Hicks was the
main one who failed to hook-'em his man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm better at trading for people,'' Melvin said, only
half-seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, this is a franchise that paid a reported $80,801,598
in players salaries in 1999. Only the New York Yankees ($92
million) spent more.
</P>
<P>
   With a superstar nucleus already in place _ Rodriguez, Palmeiro,
Wetteland and, until recently, Gonzalez _ an agent would have been
wise to shop elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks expressed his concern last week that baseball's ``drunken
sailors'' needed to be reined in. Around the NHL, they probably
choked on their back-bacon when they heard that one. Hicks has been
hockey's alleged drunken sailor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if you're going to moan about the Rangers' free-agent
failings, don't forget the Stars. Owner Hicks dug deep to sign,
among others, Ed Belfour and Brett Hull, the two heroes of the
Stanley Cup finale.
</P>
<P>
   This baseball franchise isn't stingy, and Hicks can give you
80,801,598 reasons why it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Like Melvin said, there instead can be ``reasons'' why an agent
shepherds a player elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Tony Attanasio, for instance, was confident that Mark
McLemore could get _ and wanted _ a two-year contract. The Rangers,
who had previously signed McLemore to three-year and two-year
deals, this time offered one year at $2 million, a $250,000 pay
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff happens. McLemore, who was popular among fans and
teammates, could have had the starting second base job again, and
who knows? If young Kelly Dransfeldt's struggles continue, McLemore
might have ended up with two more years here.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one likes Mark McLemore more than I do,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, McLemore reportedly is on the verge of signing a
two-year deal with Seattle to play left field.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's fault? Or Attanasio's?
</P>
<P>
   To all things, however, there is a reason. In the Rangers' case,
an infusion of young blood, necessitated by juggling the payroll,
might be just what the surgeons ordered. Melvin tells a poignant
story about a conversation he had at the winter meetings with
crusty Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds were rife with youngsters, yet finished 29 games over
.500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put them out there and let them play, and it was fun,''
McKeon told Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the Rangers, too, have to answer to their farm
system. ``At some point,'' Melvin said, ``you have to find out who
can play and who can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst-case scenario,'' he said, ``would be if we
were trying to pretend to catch the Yankees and July 31 comes, and
we're having to trade away a Francisco Cordero, a Gabe Kapler or a
Mike Lamb to try to think we can beat the Yankees again.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is right, and so was McKeon. As a consolation prize for
finishing second in the Zeile Sale, the Rangers may well get a
first-hand look at their future.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Lamb, Kapler and Ruben Mateo if they want to play here. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
