<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSIT WORKERS AND MTA REACH AGREEMENT TO AVERT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating and rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's transit workers and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority reached a deal on Wednesday morning to
avert a threatened strike, union officials said, as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said he expected that bus and subway service would be near
normal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no strike tomorrow,'' Giuliani said at a news
conference at 10:30 on Tuesday night. ``The most that we'll have to
deal with are work stoppages here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said early Wednesday morning that after five
days of intense talks, the two sides had reached agreement on all
issues, including wages.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Calhoun, the secretary-treasurer of Local 100 of the
Transport Workers Union, said, ``I'm absolutely delighted.'' As
soon as the union leaders reached an agreement, they headed to
union headquarters to present details to the transit workers'
46-member board. Metropolitan Transportation Authority officials
did not immediately make an announcement about an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While transit workers were still awaiting the details of a new
contract, the tense wait among subway and bus riders appeared to be
over after two weeks of often-heated rhetoric. As the mayor and
transit union leaders traded jibes during that time, millions were
left to wonder how they would cope with the shutdown of the transit
system.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and workplaces had put plans in place to stagger hours,
and the city drew up elaborate contingency plans to speed
transportation into Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As the two sides moved toward an agreement on Tuesday, Giuliani
warned of the possibility of disruptions on Wednesday from wildcat
actions by disgruntled transit workers. He also warned that any
workers who participate in such actions would be subject to
draconian fines starting at $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The city and the state sought to pressure the union not to
strike by getting a state judge to sign an order on Tuesday that
threatened the union and its members with crippling fines if they
went on strike in defiance of state law.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of attacking the union, Giuliani changed
course on Tuesday and praised the union's leaders, saying they
provided assurances that the union would not shut down New York
City's transit system on Wednesday morning. On Tuesday night,
rank-and-file members expressed relief that a strike had apparently
been averted, but, despite the olive branch the mayor extended to
union leaders on Tuesday, they also expressed anger over the way he
handled the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's portraying us as criminals, and we are all hard-working
people looking for a decent wage increase that we earned,'' said
Jerry Baker, 45, a bus driver from Staten Island. ``To hold a gun
to our head and say, `You take this or you're going to be fined
$25,000' is absurd and ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the agreement calls for a 14.3 percent
increase in wages and benefits over three years, including a pledge
by management to make larger contributions to the workers' pension
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides reached an agreement on wages after starting out
far apart. The union last week called for a wage increase of 9
percent a year over three years, while the MTA offered 12 percent
over four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-ROCKETS-HN     12-15 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Fans poured onto the court again. OK, so it was just one fan. And
the Rockets were not beating the Knicks for the 1994 NBA
championship. They were not even beating the Knicks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But as the Rockets begin the longest training camp in league
history, scheduled for 60 games, any success is worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   So as Matt Bullard, the only healthy Rockets player left from
1994, hit a 3-pointer while being fouled by Larry Johnson, Bullard
found himself in a tight embrace from one of the first-row fans
still showing up for games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like 1994,'' Bullard said, after his late four-point
play helped the Rockets lose by only 101-90 on Tuesday night at
Compaq Center. ``It was like high school.''
</P>
<P>
   It also might have been how things must become for the
learning-to-crawl Rockets. Frustrated by maddeningly close losses
in the first month, the Rockets could not help but notice the
improvement since their debacle in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Under usual circumstances, it might not have merited hugs from
fans during the game, but the Rockets left usual circumstances
behind last week. For the first time this season, other than
because of injuries or suspensions, they shook up the starting
lineup, sending Thomas Hamilton and Cuttino Mobley into the
starting mix. And for most of the night, they stayed within range
of the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   That did not last, of course. In the fourth quarter, the Knicks,
the top defensive team in the league, put on the defensive clamps
and the Rockets missed five of their first six shots to allow the
Knicks to pull away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a pretty good job for a good part of the game,''
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``We stayed in the game. I
thought we missed some pretty good shots. There was just not enough
firepower. They sort of wore us down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets considered that a vast improvement. They were
within six after three quarters. The Knicks pushed their lead to 13
in less than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But goals have changed. The Rockets didn't get blown out. After
the ignominy of falling 27 points behind the Nets on Saturday and
rallying to lose in a rout, giving the Knicks a game was considered
a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely look at it as progress,'' said Mobley, a guard
who started for the first time this season and had 14 points. ``The
whole aspect of the game. We passed the ball around a little bit.
We played better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets never really had an answer for the Knicks'
stars. Mobley gave Tomjanovich a second quick-footed starter, with
Shandon Anderson, to match up with Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprewell, playing with the flu, made eight of 13 shots for
22 points and had five assists. Houston made 10 of 17 shots for 20
points. Patrick Ewing, playing his third game since returning from
an injury to his left Achilles' tendon, had 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell, they were just
unbelievable the way they could shoot the ball,'' Mobley said. ``I
couldn't believe that. It's not about getting them; it's about
making them. I got them. I didn't make them. They made them.
Shandon and myself stayed in their faces, and they still made their
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup change is not necessarily long-term, Tomjanovich
said. He said he plans to adjust nightly based on matchups and
insisted he was not sending any sort of message. But struggling
forward Walt Williams, who had started every game, never so much as
removed his warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to piece the puzzle together,'' Rockets forward
Carlos Rogers said. ``We're making changes to see what pieces fit.
If they don't, we'll go to something else. Right now, we're trying
to find out what works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult part is losing and trying to stay focused and
still be ready and prepared for the next game. If we stay really
focused, we can do it. If we can just put our thoughts into
preparation for next year, we'll be a better team. But that's the
hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to match up with the Knicks was difficult enough.
</P>
<P>
   There were many times when the Knicks seemed to be on the brink
of blowing the game open. They had gotten pretty much any shot they
wanted most of the night. Sprewell and Houston seemed capable of
getting open jumpers at will.
</P>
<P>
   But they finally did race beyond the Rockets' reach with their
usual game, shutting down the Rockets for almost six minutes to
lead 87-74.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had hung around despite not shooting nearly as well
as the Knicks, largely by making enough 3s to keep pace. Down by
six midway through the second quarter, Anderson found Bullard for
consecutive 3s to tie the score. By halftime, the Knicks had made
52.8 percent of their shots, the Rockets just 41 percent, and the
Rockets trailed by just a trey.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets stayed within range, heading to the fourth quarter
within six. But as the Knicks consistently got wide-open looks, it
was just a matter of time before enough fell to end any doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Knicks had sealed the win, the Rockets did
something to regain hope for the night, and perhaps the months of
rebuilding to come. Ewing had made four consecutive free throws to
regain the 13-point lead when Bullard nailed his third trey of the
night, drawing a foul and making the free throw to pull the Rockets
within nine with 1:13 left.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the fan was more excited to find that he and
Bullard shared musical tastes. But these days, they'll celebrate
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had said something to me before when I was taking the
ball out of bounds,'' Bullard said. ``He said he saw me at the Rush
concert. I already gave him five. I was trying to give him five,
and he gave me a big hug.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
