<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-ASTROS-REDSOX-TRA     12-15 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ASTROS-REDSOX-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros on Tuesday night finalized a deal sending outfielder
Carl Everett to the Boston Red Sox in exchange for shortstop Adam
Everett and a minor-league pitcher.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox targeted Carl Everett in their efforts to acquire a
run-producing outfielder and, according to sources, became willing
to complete a trade for the talented switch hitter despite the
possibility of having his services for only one year. A stumbling
block in the trade negotiations had been Boston's inability to
discuss a long-term deal with Everett, who can become a free agent
after next season.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who is eligible for arbitration, earned $2.4 million in
1999 and will command a substantial pay raise after batting .325
with 25 home runs and 108 RBIs in helping the Astros win a third
straight National League Central title.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's first order of business will be to work out a multiyear
agreement with Everett, 28, who likely would get at least $5
million for next season through arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have entertained trade talks regarding several
players who are eligible for free agency after the 2000 season.
Others besides Everett include lefthanded starting pitcher Mike
Hampton and right fielder Derek Bell. The club is keeping a close
eye on its payroll, which is approaching $60 million. Another
consideration is the fact the Astros eventually hope to make room
in the outfield for younger players such as Richard Hidalgo, Daryle
Ward and Lance Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Adam Everett, 22, who batted .263 with 10
home runs at Class AA Trenton last season, helps address one of the
Astros' weaknesses, incurred with the departure of Ricky Gutierrez,
who was not offered arbitration and became a free agent. Everett,
the Red Sox's No. 1 draft pick in 1998, is considered an excellent
defensive prospect.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet known which pitcher the Red Sox will send to
Houston. Among the possibilities is lefthander Greg Miller, who was
10-6 with a 3.10 ERA and 146 strikeouts in 136 innings last season
for Boston's Class A affiliate at Augusta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
