<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     12-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN he was in his prime, I asked Muhammad Ali if there were any
tricks he used to psych himself before, or even during, a fight.
His eyes glowed. He looked up with those deep, dancing eyes and
said, ``Oh, yeah, I think about my bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Your what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``I worked hard for that bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   He said when he was a kid back in Louisville, Ky., known as
Cassius Clay, he had a job sacking groceries. He found a bike he
just had to have, second hand, but blue and really sharp. So he
saved his money for months to buy the used wheels and, proud and
happy, he parked it behind the grocery.
</P>
<P>
   And somebody stole it. Nearly broke his heart.
</P>
<P>
   He walked all over Louisville that summer, he said, looking for
his bicycle. This was 15 or 20 years later, and his eyes were still
hard with the memory. ``I walked and looked, looked and walked,''
he said. ``Never found it. But every time I got into a ring, I
looked across at the other fighter, and I said to myself, `Hey,
that's the guy that stole my bike!'''
</P>
<P>
   Any writer who ever crossed the path of Ali may have an anecdote
or a personal yarn to tell. It wasn't difficult acquiring one. He
rarely let a writer go away hungry. The first time I ever
interviewed him one on one, it was two in the afternoon, and he was
still in bed in a Houston hotel, the covers pulled up to his chin.
</P>
<P>
   This was during the darkest days of his exile from boxing, a
43-month absence that saw him matched against the U.S. Army. His
legal costs were staggering, and his standing with the public had
plunged to depths below sea level.
</P>
<P>
   But he was confident for two reasons. ``People forgave
Hirohito,'' he explained. ``They forgave Khrushchev, Rommel and
Jack Dempsey. If I lay low, the fans will forget about this problem
I have with the government.''
</P>
<P>
   As a secondary issue, he felt he understood the temporary nature
of fame. ``Look at Wyatt Earp,'' he said, meaning the actor who had
played him on TV. ``Look at Dave Garroway. Look at Malcolm
X.'' The world had not yet forgotten Malcolm. He was simply no
longer around to enjoy his fame, having been shot and killed by a
rival Muslim faction.
</P>
<P>
   If we have to explain to you why Ali is now the consensus choice
as the Athlete of the Century, there is really no point in trying.
Through good times or bad, through war and divorce and across the
racial divide, he took us on one of the wildest and merriest rides
in the history of sweat.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a central figure in American justice, and wherever
he goes today he is more than a hero, more than a legend. He is a
measuring stick for the last four decades, since he returned from
Rome in 1960 with a gold medal as a young boxer on the American
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can walk into any village in Africa,'' Evander Holyfield
said, ``and they know him and call out his name. Do you think they
know Michael Jordan's name in the villages in Africa?''
</P>
<P>
   His ``problem'' with the government, of course, dealt with his
refusal to be drafted during the war in Vietnam. Seeking a more
enlightened draft board than the one in Louisville, he became a
temporary resident of Houston, a city friendly to him for most of
his career. Mi casa es su casa; my house is your house. My draft
board is your draft board.
</P>
<P>
   The government won that battle, but in time the verdict was
overturned. Almost without our being aware, he went from a brash,
20-year-old Olympian to a loud-mouthed champion (who seemed
perfectly paired with Howard Cosell) to America's villain and then,
suddenly, an elder statesman who would win the title not once but
three times.
</P>
<P>
   He told outrageous stories and amused us with his poetry. It was
grade-school quality, but he recited it with the seriousness of
Yeats. He was meant to be enjoyed, not psychoanalyzed, but in the
early 1990s you found yourself fighting the temptation to feel pity
for him.
</P>
<P>
   He had grown soft with age and puffy from medication, his speech
was thick, his hands trembled, and he moved like a man pulling a
wagon. But he wasn't dying, and he wasn't punch drunk. He had not
lost his sense of humor, nor his ability to inspire awe and
affection _ among most of us.
</P>
<P>
   He has lived now for 15 years with Parkinson's Syndrome, known
to some as Left Hook Disease. But the early scare stories turned
out to be wildly exaggerated. On the day the New York Post ran a
front-page headline that read: ``ALI FIGHTING FOR HIS LIFE,'' he
left the hospital in a limousine.
</P>
<P>
   An hour earlier, he had been jiving with the press and fighting
for an extra serving of banana pudding.
</P>
<P>
   In his time on the world stage, he has been the master
puppeteer. He set the tone. He set the mood. He even set the prices
_ at least for a heavyweight title fight.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Smoking Joe Frazier in two out of their three classic
matches. He wore out George Foreman in Zaire, and he took the sport
of boxing to new levels and far-away places. Many of us grew up
with him and saw sports make the turn from a place where champions
ate Wheaties, loved humankind and spoke well of dogs to an era of
megamillions and television spectacles that devour the world.
</P>
<P>
   The voice is low and slow and slurred now, but in the ways that
count, it is the voice of sports in the American century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
