<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-BOWL-HNS &LR;      12-15 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-BOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the previous failure of the Bluebonnet Bowl to survive,
Gallery Furniture owner Jim ``Mattress Mac'' McIngvale said Tuesday
his firm will be the title sponsor for a postseason college bowl
game in Houston at a cost of approximately $2 million over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The contest will be known as the galleryfurniture.com Bowl with
the first game, pending NCAA certification, Dec. 26, 2000, in the
Astrodome. Officials hope eventually to move the game to the new
stadium in which Houston's NFL expansion franchise will play.
</P>
<P>
   McIngvale said lessons were learned from the bankrupt Bluebonnet
Bowl, and he thinks he has the means to get the message out for the
new game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be different because I spend so much money on
television and radio that I can help promote it,'' McIngvale said.
``That's one of the reasons, to be honest with you, that (bowl
officials) wanted me. I run a thousand radio and TV spots in this
market a week. So we can help promote it and sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is a football town. We have been without the NFL for
several years now, and it is coming back. And the college bowl game
is coming back. It's my job and Jerry's job (promoter Jerry
Ippoliti, president of Bowl Series Inc. in Houston) to market it
and make it exciting. Our other job is to make it a good time for
the players and teams when they come here so they will want to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the bowl faces many of the problems the Bluebonnet Bowl
found to be insurmountable. The Bluebonnet Bowl was doomed in part
because it was usually played on New Year's Eve and featured teams
that were not ranked. Similarly, the Dec. 26 date of the
galleryfurniture.com Bowl would require out-of-town fans to be away
from home for Christmas. That may force the bowl to be dependent on
local ticket sales, which waned in the final years of the
Bluebonnet Bowl. The 29th and final game, between Texas and
Pittsburgh, drew 23,282 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for the Bluebonnet Bowl was that it did not have
a solid television package. Houston's bowl has no TV deal for 2000,
but Ippoliti, the former commissioner of the Mid-American
Conference, said he is talking with Fox, Turner Sports and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have that much history on (the Bluebonnet Bowl),''
Ippoliti said. ``I don't particularly care what happened in the
past, because a lot of things have happened in football today.
There is more parity, there are fewer scholarships, and there is no
one dominating football today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not criticizing who handled the Bluebonnet Bowl. But I
think there is a better structure in NCAA policy than we had.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, 61 Division I-A teams had winning records to qualify
for spots in 23 bowls. If the Houston bowl is certified, there
would be 25 bowls in 2000, with the Silicon Valley Bowl in San
Jose, Calif., also coming on line.
</P>
<P>
   Ippoliti said that is not too many bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credibility means a lot to teams, and that means being in a
bowl game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The galleryfurniture.com Bowl currently has no conference
tie-ins. Ippoliti has talked with the commissioners of several
conferences, including the Big 12, Southeastern, Conference USA,
Mountain West and Western Athletic. All the commissioners have told
the Chronicle they are interested but will take a wait-and-see
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Ippoliti said he thought a successful bowl had to have tie-ins
with two conferences. Houston bowl officials have targeted the Big
12 as an anchor conference because it makes the most geographic
sense.
</P>
<P>
   If the bowl secures a tie-in with the Big 12, it would get the
No. 7 team from the league. The Big 12 supplies one team to the
Bowl Championship Series and teams to five other bowls (Cotton,
Holiday, Alamo, Insight.com and Independence). If the Big 12
supplies two teams to the BCS, then the galleryfurniture.com Bowl
would get the eighth team from the Big 12. The Big 12 has bowl
contracts for two more years, and the Houston bowl wants to
negotiate with the league to get a team higher in the pecking
order, Ippoliti said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Astrodome-based bowl would have gotten Texas
Tech, the Big 12's No. 7 team, which was bowl-qualified but did not
have a spot. In two previous seasons, however, the Big 12 did not
qualify enough teams to supply its current obligations, which
forces the game or games on the bottom of the Big 12's list to look
elsewhere for a team.
</P>
<P>
   A Big 12 official said the league also has been approached by
bowls other than the ones it has contracts with, meaning the
galleryfurniture.com Bowl would have to compete with other cities.
Commissioner Kevin Weiberg was noncommittal toward Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the possibilities but are withholding
comment until after the bowl is certified,'' Weiberg said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Certification is almost a foregone conclusion as long as the
bowl can come up with a $2 million letter of credit, an NCAA
official said. Ippoliti said he has the money from a bank in the
Midwest but declined to name it. He said he is trying to get a
local bank to put up the letter of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Another conference official said the bowl will have no chance
unless it gives a large payout to each team. The NCAA-mandated
minimum payout is $750,000 per team, which is what the
galleryfurniture.com bowl is guaranteeing in its first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This financial arrangement we have now secures the payments
(for the galleryfurniture.com Bowl),'' Ippoliti said. ``They (the
Bluebonnet Bowl) weren't financially secured (in the last two games
that were played).''
</P>
<P>
   Ippoliti said plans are to increase the fees given to the teams
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In several years, we hope to pay out more than the Cotton Bowl
in Dallas,'' Ippoliti said.
</P>
<P>
   McIngvale does not consider this action much of a business risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole lot less gamble than I took when I started a
little furniture store on the side of the freeway,'' McIngvale
said. ``Even my wife, Linda, didn't get nervous about this. And she
gets nervous about everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
