<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ROUT CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For everyone who's ever had an unwelcome roommate,
Tuesday night's scene at Staples Center had to be rewarding. The
Los Angeles Lakers finally met the rowdy young boys from down the
hall _ and promptly served them the NBA's version of an eviction
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a 27-point rout might qualify more as a deportation.
And after a 95-68 Lakers plastering, the Los Angeles Clippers might
just consider fleeing the country to save further embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first meeting of the Lakers and Clippers in their
shared home, and it pretty much made a mockery of any debate about
who's king of the castle.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal brutalized Michael Olowokandi. Kobe Bryant
showed up Lamar Odom. And Maurice Taylor, presumably the best power
forward in town, barely showed up at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the Clippers pulled a Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde on us
from last night to tonight,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said.
``However I misunderstand a team, I certainly misunderstood this
team. We did some nice things out there defensively, and
offensively I thought we played OK at times, but it wasn't a pretty
game to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find a single area the Lakers didn't dominate.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal muscled his way to 21 points and 19 rebounds in an
abbreviated 29-minute stint. Foul-troubled Olowokandi started
slowly but finished with 13 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Odom didn't end up guarding each other, but Bryant
still sent a clear message to those who contend the Clippers' young
phenom is the best prospect in town. Odom struggled to contain an
ill Glen Rice, and wound up with more fouls (five) than points
(two).
</P>
<P>
   Bryant simply dazzled. He scored 11 consecutive points in a
first-quarter run that established the rout and finished with 18
points.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor never found his way. He hit 1 of 7 field goals and fouled
out early in the fourth quarter with two points and two rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' rough night included 20 turnovers, a three-point
second quarter in which they made 1 of 18 shots and an injury to
forward Brian Skinner (high left-ankle sprain).
</P>
<P>
   Even the Lakers' often-subdued bench beat its counterparts,
29-21, as the Lakers improved to an NBA-best 18-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' first half raised, or perhaps lowered, the bar for
futility. Their 19 points was an all-time NBA low for a half in the
shot-clock era, and their second-quarter total _ three points _ was
one higher than the league record for a low quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Lakers managed to avoid doubling over in laughter,
or pouring it on. After a 20-0 run from the first to the second
quarter, the Lakers had established a 21-point lead, and they set
the engine on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal played just six minutes in the second quarter as the
Lakers downshifted to score 17 points, taking a mere 49-19 lead
into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, battling a lingering illness and Odom, easily beat both in
the first quarter. He played the first eight minutes and hit 3 of 6
shots for seven points as the Lakers took a 32-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rice barely left his house the prior two days, suffering from a
102-degree fever. His first attempt to play came during the
afternoon shootaround, and he felt the effects immediately _ ``My
chest started burning.... It was difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get out there and work really hard, real quick and
see where I was at, and quickly found out it's going to be a long
night,'' he said before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   His words proved prophetic, albeit only for the boys in red.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
