<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-DEVILS-LADN     12-15 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-DEVILS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ROUTED BY DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It was like something out of the Larry
Robinson years, which was fitting since he was behind the bench of
the New Jersey Devils as an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   But the Los Angeles Kings now are Andy Murray's team and it will
be interesting to see how they respond to Tuesday's grim 7-1 loss
that was played in front of far less than the announced crowd of
10,807 at Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he can say about this one,'' Luc Robitaille
said of Murray. ``He wasn't out there stinking it up. Games like
this used to do us in for awhile. The best part is that we get to
play right away. You don't want one like this to linger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (16-9-6) end their four-game trip tonight against the
improving New York Rangers at Madison Square Garden. Glen Murray,
who was on the ice for six of the Devils goals Tuesday, will be
there. So will Rob Blake, who returned from his groin strain only
to wish he hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   So will Stephane Fiset, who appeared for the first time in five
weeks and allowed an ugly, bouncing 50-footer by John Madden for a
short-handed goal just when it looked like the Kings might get back
in the game in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But if the first 30 games of Murray's coaching career are any
indication, the bad games have not started a trend.
</P>
<P>
   The team has played five bad games before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   __Oct. 6: Took a 2-1 lead into the final minutes of the third
period against Florida before allowing three goals. Beat Tampa Bay
5-2 the next night.
</P>
<P>
   __Oct. 22: Had a 3-1 lead and a power-play opportunity against
Phoenix before allowing five consecutive goals. Two nights later
beat division rival San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   __Nov. 6: Manhandled by Philadelphia 5-3 but came back to tie
Edmonton and win their next three games.
</P>
<P>
   __Nov. 20: Lost to lowly Montreal 5-3 then beat Northwest
Division-leading Colorado 6-2 in maybe their best game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   __Dec. 4: Gave up two goals in the final three minutes of a 3-3
tie with Tampa. Crushed expansion Atlanta in their next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that has faced adversity well,'' Murray said.
``It just seemed like after the first shift we weren't in it. We
came out well in the second and cut the lead to 3-1, then played
worse. This is a team built on its work ethic. Tonight that wasn't
there at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The game got so bad by the end of the second period Murray
listed nine players he would have liked to keep off the ice for the
third. But then he thought they might like that so he sent
everybody out for the end.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who was listless in his first game back from a groin
problem, and Palffy, who looked stiff after missing four games with
a sore lower back, did not play the final five minutes as a medical
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spot for the Kings was a second-period goal by
Donald Audette, which beat Devils goalie Martin Brodeur. But
Audette, who was benched for much of the third period Saturday
against Montreal, also was on the ice for four of New Jersey's
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a complete nightmare,'' said Audette's linemate
Glen Murray, who came in with eight goals in his past six games.
``I blame our line for what happened tonight. We just didn't have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murray was so upset that his usual postgame talk to the
team was delayed until the Kings returned to its hotel for the
traditional team meal.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of a food fight, which probably would have
made Murray happy. He isn't sure just how upset his team is over
the loss, but sure is glad they have a chance for redemption
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the NFL where you have seven days to lick your
wounds,'' he said. ``The Rangers are getting better and they want
to keep that going. We certainly want this to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
