<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     12-15 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT'S TRULY THE BOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This is not a true story. Kobe Bryant did not swat
a would-be Lamar Odom jumper into the second row Tuesday night,
turn to him, eyes huge, and scream:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get that weak game out of here. Man, you couldn't even play
for my team in Milan!''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, but possible. Bryant is now the only player in the
NBA, or any other known professional sport, to own another team.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is the proud half-owner of Olimpia Milano, the
professional Italian team his father _ Joe ``Jelly Bean'' Bryant _
once played for. Joe is in Italy and will run the team.
</P>
<P>
   This also makes Kobe, who reportedly paid over $1 million for
his 50 percent take, his father's employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the boss,'' he laughed. ``Nah, he tells me what's going
on. We're both very, very excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is the only player trying to win championships at the
same time. Which means he has a better chance of winning
simultaneous titles before the Clippers win one.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, Kobe Bryant, the NBA's boy wonder, is now the owner of a
professional basketball team. At age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you hadn't noticed, but things do tend to move a little
differently in his unique world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at my career, it seems like everything kinda
happens before you expect it to happen,'' Bryant said. ``The gun
just sort of goes off before anybody expects it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said the season in Italy coincides with the NBA's, only
it ends about four months sooner. So the prospect of Bryant
watching his new investment in person is weaker than a Shaquille
O'Neal one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson said he isn't overly
concerned with Bryant's interest wandering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long ways to Milan,'' Jackson said. ``It's not like he
can follow the team. Keeping a hand on is going to be a summer
occupation for him. I think he's probably not going to get involved
with them at that level until he's through playing basketball
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Jackson said he has previously had a player who
owned a team: A Puerto Rican who owned the team he was coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest scorer in Puerto Rican history,'' Jackson said.
``I got fired from that job. I couldn't find an offense to match
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant spent eight years of his youth in Milan, said he would
like to return and raise a family there.
</P>
<P>
   He said after he purchased half the team from Pasquale Caputo,
his father told him Milan residents got plenty excited over the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expected me to show up tomorrow,'' he said. ``Everybody
got all excited, like I was going to come out there and suit up or
something. Slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said there could never be any double playing duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't do that,'' he said. ``Jerry (West) would have a
heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bryant has already added former Clipper Pooh Richardson to
his 5-8 Milan team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father mentioned it to me and I said, `Can Pooh still run?'
'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said it is the unexpected beginning to his branching out
in other businesses. For now, he just plans to enjoy his new
profession, if from a distance. Already, though, he can sound like
an owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it one step at at time,'' he said. ``It's like a
basketball game. You pick and choose players. Then you start
dealing with the agents, and they're a pain in the butt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
