<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE KEEPING HIS COOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 and RANDY HILL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 and Long Beach Press-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Trade rumors involving Glen Rice are again heating
up, but coach Phil Jackson said the Los Angeles Lakers'
sharpshooter has done an admirable job of ignoring the chatter and
focusing on his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Glen. I really congratulated him on keeping
himself as professional as possible during a period of time in
which so much speculation is always on his availability, his being
a part of a trade or situation,'' Jackson said. ``And I thought
he's kept his head in the game, he's kept his mood positive, he
hasn't lost his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't shot as well as I'd like him to shoot. Glen came to
me, simply because he was disappointed that he wasn't playing
better than he felt he should play.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest rumors have Rice being involved in a highly unlikely
trade for overpaid Washington Wizards power forward Juwan Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson does think Rice has been a bit distracted by the trade
talk _ he's shooting 41.9 percent _ ``but he's still found a way to
compete and help us play. And I told him I have a lot of respect
for his game, because almost every night he comes out and outplays
the opponent that's at the other side at that position.''
</P>
<P>
   As of today, NBA teams can trade players who signed new
contracts this summer, and deals are expected to begin unfolding
soon as a result. Rice remains a commodity, and as a free agent
next summer, could be available if the Lakers can acquire a
defensive-minded power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We'll) try to improve ourselves if we can,'' Jackson said,
``and we're short big guys obviously. ... Behind Shaq (O'Neal) we
look rather sparse back there, as far as big guys go.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson ailing: Clippers shooting guard Derek Anderson _ who
missed 26 games in his first two NBA seasons as a Cleveland
Cavalier _ has returned to the wounded list. He left the fourth
quarter of Monday's victory over Vancouver with a second-degree
lateral sprain of his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to be miss two weeks, a time span that would
cover at least six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys are going to have to step up,'' said teammate
Maurice Taylor of losing the 6-foot-5, 195-pound Anderson, whose
fearless style often works at cross purposes with his thin
physique.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very high-strung out there,'' Taylor said, ``but I feel
like that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clippers coach Chris Ford also is fond of Anderson's reckless
approach, but isn't very excited about losing his 17.8 points, 5.4
rebounds and 4.1 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when we thought things were going to be OK ...'' Ford
said. ``It could be as long as two weeks; I'm hoping he's a quicker
healer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers do have a precedent for surviving without Anderson.
During the season's first extended road trip, a concussion put him
on the bench for the last three games. The Clippers won two of
those.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it before,'' center Michael Olowokandi said. ``But
we obviously will miss part of his offense and what he does for us
on defense, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kandi Man vs. Shaq: Olowokandi's learning curve as a rookie last
season included co-starring in a few poster dunks by Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi entered Tuesday night's time-share showdown averaging
17.5 points and 11.5 rebounds in the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be better equipped to play the game, per se,''
Olowokandi said, addressing his increased level of competence since
last season, ``but I'm not sure I'm better equipped to guard him.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi admitted that because of the strength of the Lakers
powerhouse, O'Neal may be his toughest matchup problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing you can do,'' he said, referring to
available tactics against O'Neal's barge-like post-up game. ``When
you get behind him, daylight just sort of shuts down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
