<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     12-15 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SIX weeks after his arena referendum went down in a bigger ball of
flames than the Hindenburg, Rockets owner Leslie Alexander finally
crawled out of the hidey hole in Florida and returned to his
courtside seat.
</P>
<P>
   One might presume Alexander's exile was spent wallowing in a sea
of self-pity, alternately licking his wounds of rejection and
howling at the moon over the injustice of it all.
</P>
<P>
   But that can't be the case with the Chairman of Clutch City.
After all, isn't this the franchise that carved out its niche in
NBA lore by fighting in the darkest hour? Surely, he has not gone
soft to the point where just one loss makes him take his ball and
go home. Or to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   No, Alexander was certainly waiting for the dawn of the Thomas
Hamilton era, which is big in every way.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first quarter Tuesday night when the partial crowd
for the early-starting cable affair made the quiet scene look and
sound like a glorified Clippers game, Shandon Anderson launched a
22-foot jumper that missed the mark badly and TV color commentator
Calvin Murphy could be heard saying, ``That was a perfect shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the silence of a library, coach Rudy Tomjanovich turned,
smiled and said, ``No, it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opening minute of the second quarter, Carlos Rogers was
stymied by the New York defense as the shot clock ran down and had
to let fly with a shot-put heave from 24 feet out. It swished.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our Statue of Liberty play,'' Rudy T said.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this already in the broken season, keeping tabs
on the comings and goings in the front row and trying to stay sane
with gallows humor.
</P>
<P>
   The losing streak is four, and at the rate they're going Charles
Barkley might give his Hall of Fame enshrinement speech before
there are signs it's going to get better.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off an embarrassing thrashing by the New Jersey Nets _
which is akin to losing a national anthem singing contest to
Roseanne _ Rudy T gave his starting five the kind of noisy, nervy
jolt that was like putting a chihuahua in a paint shaker.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley for Walt Williams, who couldn't hit water if he
were a passenger on the Titanic, was an obvious move. But His
Hugeness Hamilton for the $42 million Kelvin Cato was a shocker.
And surely intended to get a rise out of someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' Rudy T said. ``It was all about matchups. I just
felt that Kelvin is a role player and with Patrick Ewing in there
for the Knicks we wanted somebody who could be an inside offensive
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and if you'll swallow that one, then I've got a fat guy in
a red suit who's going to come down your chimney in nine more
nights.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing managed to outduel the inside presence of Hamilton 20-8;
Cato responded to having his fire lit by making one of four shots
and grabbing all of two rebounds in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This was another night of eiderdown-soft defense with the Knicks
shooting 53 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really trying out there,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to say it, then it just doesn't quite ring so true.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there will be plenty more opportunities for trying and
experimenting in the lab by the time Hakeem Olajuwon returns to the
lineup, and maybe not all of them will blow up in the Rockets'
faces.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, before we are so quick to write off the remaining
time between now and late April as just a 59-game tryout camp for a
new-look expansion franchise, maybe somebody could take a quick
look at the Knicks and their supposedly over-the-hill center Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have griped about him, talked behind his back and
moaned that he makes them less of a team, yet are 3-0 since his
return. This is today's NBA, full of punks and poseurs and Latrell
Sprewells with no respect for the past and management types who are
too quick to throw in the towel and start over.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Knicks make the NBA Finals because Ewing was hurt? Or
was it because Miami choked again? Or because Jess Kersey made a
horrendous call that killed Indiana? Or because the Eastern
Conference was easier than Madonna?
</P>
<P>
   Before Ewing came back, the young, athletic Knicks were
struggling to stay above .500. Now, bad wheels and all, he gives
them the presence of a warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Which is something to keep in mind when the schemers start
plotting ways to begin life without Olajuwon prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would be so easy to do that. Then coaches, players,
everybody gets a free pass, because they wouldn't ever be expected
to win. Just like it is now.
</P>
<P>
   But that wouldn't happen, couldn't happen here. Could it? Not in
Clutch City, where the owner sits front and center and tells us
nobody ever quits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
