<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COACHES LEAVE TROJANS AMID SHAKEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a major shakeup within the USC football
coaching staff, assistants Ken O'Brien and Mike Wilson quit Tuesday
while Hue Jackson was promoted to quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who entered private business, was expected to resign,
but O'Brien's departure was spurred by USC coach Paul Hackett's
decision to remove him as quarterbacks coach in favor of Jackson,
the Trojans' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien had been offered the tight ends position by Hackett, but
preferred to coach USC's wide receivers. When Hackett declined to
hire him as wide receivers coach during a meeting Monday night,
O'Brien quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the restructuring of the staff, he wasn't going to coach
the quarterbacks any longer, I think that's the bottom line,''
Hackett said. ``I feel strongly about Ken. I was surprised. The
best thing for him would be tight ends. I'm disappointed because I
had a place for him in the staff. It's a blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two years of (him) coaching quarterbacks, we needed a
change. It's very rough. Obviously, I didn't anticipate this would
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Cal assistant Dan Ferrigno is a leading
candidate to become the wide receivers coach.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of O'Brien stunned quarterback Carson Palmer, who
met with Hackett on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised and sad,'' Palmer said. ``Anytime you lose a
person like Coach O'Brien it's tough. Anytime there's a coaching
change it's different. The good thing is (Jackson's) a coach I
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson coached USC running backs the past two seasons, but has
always wanted to coach quarterbacks, which he did for the Trojans
under John Robinson in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson is the new quarterbacks coach, it was clear
Tuesday that Hackett will also work closely with Palmer, senior
Mike Van Raaphorst and Chatsworth High quarterback Matt Cassel, who
committed last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very, very involved,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett stressed Tuesday that the changes are the result of
USC's 6-6 season, as he searches for ways to improve the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be different,'' Hackett said. ``This season is not
going to be put on Carson Palmer (being injured). We're going to
make waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been expected to resign for at least a week. But
O'Brien had been waiting since the end of the season to hear what
role he would play, and according to sources, forced the meeting
Monday because he was tired of waiting for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Wilson nor O'Brien could be reached for comment. Wilson,
40, joined the staff in 1997 while O'Brien, 39, was hired by
Hackett in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett now has three openings to fill: tight ends, wide
receivers and running backs. He fired offensive line coach Steve
Greatwood two weeks ago and replaced him with tight ends coach
Steve Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he hoped to hire a wide receivers coach right away,
and a tight ends coach by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come during a critical recruiting period, when many
high school players are making campus visits. USC has 11
commitments and 11 scholarships remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0212EST &QL; 
