<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-NUGGETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS BLOW OUT NUGGETS WITH BIG THIRD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Remember when the Charlotte Hornets came into KeyArena
and impersonated the Harlem Globetrotters, throwing down dunks and
racking up points as if the rims were seven feet high?
</P>
<P>
   That was the Sonics Tuesday night, and the supposedly
much-improved Denver Nuggets were nothing more than the Washington
Generals.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, to understate the Sonics' 109-84 victory would be to
simply say that it was an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton and Ruben Patterson were the stars, but Jelani McCoy
or Vladimir Stepania could have walked off the floor as the heroes.
Both missed free throws in the final two minutes, hurting the
chance for fans to receive free Taco Bell chalupas when the Sonics
score 110 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Jelani and Vladimir, they ought to donate about $5,000
and buy chalupas for everybody,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal joked.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the 11,879 in attendance, the Nuggets were fast
food for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Denver (10-11) was at the end of a road trip in which it played
six games in nine nights. The Nuggets had beaten Milwaukee,
Philadelphia and New York along the way but brought very little
energy to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   So the Sonics took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In winning their third straight home game, the Sonics outscored
the Nuggets 63-37 in the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had their way with the Nuggets, especially in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 50-40 when the second half began, the Sonics scored 14
consecutive points. Patterson started the run when he converted a
three-point play. Payton then pulled up and dropped in a 3-pointer.
That was followed by a pair of dunks and another layup from
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary always finds me,'' said Patterson, who scored 10 of his
16 points in the third. ``I came out with a lot of energy, and we
said let's put this game away and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans barely made it back to their seats after halftime before
the Sonics led 64-40. Meanwhile, the Sonics harassed the Nuggets
into missing their first seven shots and turning the ball over
three times to start the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had come back a couple of times in the third
quarter from 16 down, so we just knew that we had to keep
pressuring and keep running them,'' Payton said after scoring a
game-high 25 points. ``We did a good job of doing that. They're a
good team. ... We had a lot of rest, so we just came out and played
the way we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   A better hope for the Nuggets would have been to finish the game
with star forward Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess left midway in the third quarter with back spasms and
did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, McDyess exited shortly after shooting a
pair of free throws. This is for sure: McDyess didn't strain his
back at the foul line. After badly missing the first attempt, he
shot an airball on the second.
</P>
<P>
   That trip to the line epitomized Denver's travails in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give us a little credit for coming out and playing
aggressive defense,'' said Sonics cente Horace Grant, who recovered
from a strained knee ligament and started against the Nuggets.
``Once we got them out of (going inside), they couldn't find
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics focused their defense on slowing down McDyess in the
paint after he collected 11 points and 10 rebounds in the first
quarter. At one point, the Sonics trailed 16-6.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics forced the Nuggets outside, their defensive
rotations disrupted Denver's guard play. Nick Van Exel, Ron Mercer
and Chauncey Billups combined for 7-for-32 shooting and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed with them for a while but all of a sudden those guys
started hitting shots out of nowhere,'' Mercer said. ``No excuses,
they gave us a good whipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Garbage time, er, the fourth quarter, began with the Sonics in
front, 85-59. Their biggest lead was 93-61 with 7:43 left in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed one of these,'' Sonics guard Brent Barry said.
``Every now and again we'll take a game like tonight when everybody
gets to play. Unfortunately we can't make the chalupa free throws,
but maybe next time.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The Sonics changed the start time of the Dec. 26 game
against Philadelphia to 5 p.m. The game was originally scheduled
for 12:30 p.m., which conflicts with a 1 p.m. Seattle Seahawks
kickoff that day. The Sonics suffered one of their lowest turnouts
this season on Dec. 5 when they played Charlotte opposite the
Seahawks at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012 or
</P>
<P>
   ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
