<HEADLINE>
RUSH TOOK CASH FROM AGENT, SOURCES SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Suspended UCLA forward JaRon Rush accepted several
hundred dollars from a Los Angeles-based sports agent that UCLA
believes is Jerome Stanley, according to sources close to Rush.
</P>
<P>
   One source pegged the figure at approximately $300; the other
said it was ``considerably less than five hundred.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's not a large amount in the grand scheme of
agent-related infractions committed by NCAA athletes. Former USC
football player Shawn Walters received $16,000 from an agent in
1995; he was dismissed from the team, then regained his eligibility
via the appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a sophomore from Kansas City, Mo., is suspended
indefinitely while UCLA investigates a possible violation of NCAA
rules. UCLA gave no time frame for a resolution, but athletic
director Peter Dalis said Rush won't play Saturday against DePaul
or accompany the team to Hawaii for a three-game tournament next
week.
</P>
<P>
   If Rush accepted improper gifts and/or payments, he could be
suspended and asked to make restitution, or he could have his
eligibility revoked.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is investigating two situations: Rush's relationship with
Stanley, who couldn't be reached for comment but has denied
involvement, and Rush's dealings with former AAU coach Myron
Piggie, who sources said is being investigated by the FBI for fraud
and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Rush testified about Piggie before a grand jury last month in
Kansas City _ and did it without legal representation, according to
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said to tell the truth and everything would be OK,'' Rush
told a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Rush told the grand jury enough about his relationship with
Piggie for the FBI and a U.S. attorney to conclude he might have
violated NCAA rules. They informed UCLA, which suspended Rush last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Rush's brother, Kareem, was declared ineligible by Missouri on
Tuesday while the school examines his relationship with Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source close to Piggie, the FBI and Internal
Revenue Service are investigating what Piggie did with Nike cash
and merchandise intended for his AAU team: did he give it to
players, did he declare it on his income taxes, and did he sell
Nike products, then pocket the cash?
</P>
<P>
   ``Piggie got money from Nike, and he might have given some of
that money to JaRon,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't necessarily a violation of NCAA rules.
Ultimately, Rush's future might hinge on the NCAA's interpretation
of his relationship with Piggie, who knew Rush before he was a
recruitable athlete. A pre-existing relationship could eliminate
application of the NCAA's extra-benefits rule.
</P>
<P>
   There's another factor to be considered: the role of Tom Grant,
who bought Rush a car, paid for his schooling and took Rush on
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is a Kansas booster, but his relationship with Rush was
approved by the NCAA because it began before the recruiting
process.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was also benefactor of Piggie's AAU team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Piggie gave Rush money, how will they determine if it came
from Nike or from Grant?'' the source said. ``If (the NCAA) makes
Rush ineligible because of money he took from Piggie, but they let
him take money from Grant, he might have a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rush, nor Piggie could be reached for comment. Piggie
has also denied involvement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
