<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     12-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH PLANS GRASSROOTS EFFORT IN CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner, may be arm
wrestling for first place against Sen. John McCain in New
Hampshire.
<P>
   But today in California, Bush is expected to unveil a broad
network of ground troops and volunteers whom he expects to play a
key role in his strategy to carry the state in the March primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, California has been viewed as a place where
grassroots politics takes a second seat,'' said Bush campaign chair
Gerald Parsky in an interview Tuesday. ``We're going to demonstrate
that, with this candidate, we will challenge that conventional
wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   With three months to go before the primary, the Bush campaign
says its organizational network is a measure of just how aggressive
it will be. The campaign plans to divide the state into five major
geographic regions, 18 sub-regions and 81 counties and
congressional districts, and then name 115 lieutenants to oversee a
statewide network of 1,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a California face on George Bush's message,'' said Bush
campaign spokeswoman Margita Thompson, who says campaign volunteer
leaders range from mayors to community activists. ``It will help us
create a sustained presence in the state and allow us to build on
the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Texas governor has collected a total of $57 million
in campaign contributions, far outpacing his rivals for the GOP
presidential nomination, including McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The money alone gives Bush a decided advantage in California,
where the cozy retail politics of New Hampshire are likely to be
replaced by an air war in the state's 13 major media markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush himself determined that ``the air game is very
important, but the air game alone in presidential politics in
California won't be enough for a Republican,'' said Parsky.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged the widespread belief that organizing in
California could be tough for the Republicans, who suffered
landslide defeats in last year's state elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the last election, many people thought we would had hit
rock bottom,'' said Parsky. ``But 99 percent of the credit goes to
the candidate. When he first called me and asked me to do this, he
said he was committed to California and would come often. He really
wanted to make this a full blown campaign here, and he's lived up
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's hardly unusual for political campaigns to make big
projections about the troops on hand for their cause _ failed GOP
gubernatorial hopeful Dan Lungren predicted thousands would toil
for his cause last year _ the Bush campaign's effort already looks
different.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky said the organization is ``unprecedented this early in
the primary season'' _ in part, due to the candidate's early
momentum and astounding success at fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political analysts warn that Bush, despite being
dubbed the presumptive GOP nominee months ago, may need that help,
and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if he loses to McCain in New Hampshire, Bush will
have to win big in California to have the momentum to carry him
forward,'' said Mark Baldassare, state director of polling for the
Public Policy Institute of California.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush may have money, but ``McCain has assembled quite a
bit of California intelligence,'' signing on respected veteran GOP
political strategist Ken Khachigian and communications director Dan
Schnur, the former spokesman for Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain is inching up here,'' said Baldassare, ``and he will
get a lot of free attention between February and the March 7
primary. (Bush) has got to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And others argue that the Bush organization, by touting its
strengths, is merely engaged in the political equivalent of
chest-pounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scared. They're articulating a scared philosophy.
They're envisioning people following McCain around California,
saying, `Will the juggernaut be stopped?' '' said one veteran
Democratic strategist. He added pointedly, ``There are no such
things as volunteers in a GOP primary _ unless it's the Christian
Coalition.`
</P>
<P>
   But volunteers involved say that they're confident that the
Texas governor has been farsighted enough to weather any storms in
the campaign ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``His infrastructure is in place. The people in Austin have done
a tremendous job. They haven't publicized it, but the way the
structure is now _ it's for a winner,` said Jim Blair, a San Diego
financial counselor and former marine who worked the White House
detail and has signed on to organize for Bush. ``Momentum will
build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``My phone is ringing off the hook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
