<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9397 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-VOLCANOES-WARNING-SFC     12-15 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLCANOES-WARNING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WARN OF COLLAPSING VOLCANOES  &HT;     BY CARL T. HALL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Even without the risk of an eruption, volcanoes can be deadly for
anybody nearby because of a higher risk of an avalanche or
mudslide, scientists warned Tuesday.
<P>
   Soft spots that could give way almost any time are found on the
steep upper slopes of hundreds of volcanoes, perhaps as many as
2,000 worldwide, experts said at the annual meeting of the American
Geophysical Union.
</P>
<P>
   Fiery eruptions and lava flows may be more ``glamorous'' natural
disasters in the public mind, but increasing scientific interest is
being focused on the threat of collapsing volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people have been killed in the dozen or so big
volcanic debris slides, known as lahars, that have been cataloged
during the past century. The worst, at Nevado del Ruiz in Colombia,
killed an estimated 23,000 people in 1985 _ despite advance
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just fantasy,'' said David Zimbelman, a
volcanologist at a consulting firm called G.O. Logic in White
Salmon, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the known hazards, the volcano specialists conceded that
warnings have had little effect, even on people in communities
living directly in the path of danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It generally takes a disaster,'' said Robert Watters of the
University of Nevada at Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every tall, steep-sided volcanic peak _ including
Mount Shasta in Northern California and several others along the
West Coast _ has some potential to let go, particularly when a
couple of things happen at once, such as an earthquake combined
with a heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are now using satellite observations and field study
to take stock of the hazards, although a detailed risk assessment
that takes into account human settlement, as well as geology and
other natural conditions, has yet to be attempted.
</P>
<P>
   The thickly settled areas in the drainage systems of Mount
Rainier in Washington state now loom as by far the biggest
potential disaster waiting to happen in this country, experts say,
with tens of thousands of deaths conceivable in a worst-case
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The best defense _ too late for many areas _ would be strict
zoning laws to keep floodplains clear, or at least populations
sparse, in the most slide-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
   Other protective measures might include audible warning systems
linked to alarms in urban areas and perhaps even draining mountain
reservoirs to form catch basins for cascading debris. Short of all
that, even a simple public education program could be effective if
enough people took the risk seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It often requires only a few minutes warning and a slight climb
in elevation to escape harm, said Michael Sheridan, geologist at
the State University of New York at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in some of the most deadly disasters of the past,
people instinctively headed downhill when they heard the first
rumblings of a rock slide miles away, vainly hoping to outrun tons
of mud and rock capable of attaining speeds in excess of 100 miles
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   People should instead scout around for a small hill, even if
only 150 to 300 feet above the floodplain, they can reach within 15
minutes or a half hour of home or work.
</P>
<P>
   From such a perch, ``You're going to be watching the thing go
by,'' Sheridan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     12-15 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SHOPPERS, IT'S A JINGLE OUT THERE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
AHoliday Mystery: If everyone is doing their holiday shopping on
the Internet, who are all those people in the stores and what are
they doing?
<P>
   Are they all shopping for computers to use for online shopping?
</P>
<P>
   I guess you could shop for a new computer online, too, using
your old computer. But that seems kind of cruel, doesn't it? Like
asking your dying spouse if he or she has any cute friends.
</P>
<P>
   Online shopping is unhealthy. In most of us, anger, frustration
and depression build up over the holiday season, and the No. 1
method of relieving all that pent-up hostility is by going
Christmas shopping.
</P>
<P>
   If people deny themselves the outlet of screaming and cursing at
sales clerks, pushing and trampling fellow shoppers and flipping
off fellow motorists, we're going to see a lot of people either
snap or become professional wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   THE MARRIAGE of Albertson's and Lucky has already lost its
electricity, notes Cammy Blackstone, sadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the market sign at the Lakeshore Plaza,'' reports the
Camster, ``some letters are burned out and it now reads `AL E SO
S.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One rumor is that Albertson caught Lucky getting lucky with
Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   IN ONE EAR and out the other:
</P>
<P>
   Karen Nicoletti was shopping (what else?) at the S.F. Shopping
Centre and noticed, near one of the makeup counters, a
well-dressed, thirtyish man cell-phoning. He reached over and
picked up a Q-tip from the counter and went to work on his free
ear, enthusiastically excavating.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, at least he didn't use the tip of his necktie.
</P>
<P>
   And because we all lead busy lives, why doesn't someone invent a
cell phone with a dental floss attachment near the mouthpiece?
</P>
<P>
   CELL BLOCK: At P.J. Mulhern's, the new North Beach restaurant
co-owned by Golden State Warriors' coach P.J. Carlesimo, Rich
Herrera noticed that none of his fellow diners were cell-yakking.
</P>
<P>
   Rich asked co-owner Bob Mulhern, what's the deal? What kind of
place are you running where the customers aren't self-important
enough to be cell-phoning through their meals?
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a cell?'' Mulhern asked. ``Try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrera got his out, switched it on ... No dial tone.
</P>
<P>
   The old building is wired in such a way that it blocks out cell
signals. Either that or the place is haunted by a ghost with a
sense of class.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S FUNNY, the reward system in the National Basketball League.
A couple years ago, then-Warrior Latrell Sprewell choked his coach,
the above-mentioned Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Sprewell has been found guilty of causing a very
dangerous accident (on the 680 Spreway), whined about the way he
was treated by his new team (N.Y. Knicks), skipped part of training
camp without bothering to call before or apologize after, been
informally accused of jury tampering and been fined for cursing at
fans. He continues to blame Carlesimo for the choking incident.
Upshot: Spree recently got a new contract, $61 million for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo continues to coach the Golden State Sow's Ears. Having
produced no silk purse, he is about to be (or so rumor has it)
fired.
</P>
<P>
   AT THE GOLD Coast, on California, they'll start New Year's Eve
at 8 a.m., toasting the stroke of midnight in Fiji with appropriate
Fijian libations and customs, and whatever satellite TV feed they
can get from that time zone.
</P>
<P>
   And so on, welcoming a new New Year every hour, circling the
globe like barstool-glued Magellans, until 2 a.m. (S.F. time), when
they'll attempt to pronounce ``Aloha'' and wonder why someone is
spinning the globe so damn fast.
</P>
<P>
   PEEL BACK the cold facade of big cyberbiz in Silicon Valley and
what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   No, not a peeled facade. You get a little human compassion.
Dozens of major SilVal execs will haul themselves into court today
and sentence themselves to be warmhearted sons-of-dot.com-guns.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives of the biggest companies will stand before Judge
Leonard Edwards and pledge their major long-term support for the
Y2Kids Initiative, which assists children tangled in the juvenile
dependency court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid is a startup, and they need capital,'' says Guy
Kawasaki of Garage.com, spinning corporatespeak into poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The cybermoney and moral support go to Child Advocates (to
volunteer your cash and/or love: 415-398-8001 or 408-436-6450).
It's an organization based on the principle that if you think you
have a hard time fighting The System, imagine how tough it must be
for a bruised, abused and abandoned 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ostler's column appears Monday through Friday. You can
reach him at (415) 777-7031, fax him at (415) 896-1107 or send him
an e-mail at ostler &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 0239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX     12-15 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-HELD COMPUTERS ABLE TO DELIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a holiday present, for sure, and you've scratched off
enough wrapping paper to determine that it's a handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the planning.
</P>
<P>
   You can enter home and work phone numbers into the device, but
you've got those memorized anyway. Being a sports fan, you're
probably wondering how to really take advantage of the new 3Com
Palm VII, Microsoft's Windows CE or IBM WorkPad personal digital
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the really good news. Thanks to the popularity of
these 4- to 6-ounce devices _ Forrester Research predicted 15
million of them to be in use by 2000 _ the capabilities of handheld
computers for Web use are getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Content providers for sports abound, but New York-based
FOXSports.com and ESPN.com are the apparent leaders in providing
sports channels for hand-held computer users.
</P>
<P>
   FOXSports.com is the old hand, forging an agreement with
AvantGo, a mobile information company in Mateo, Calif., in June
1998 to facilitate its FOXSports On the Go content. According to
AvantGo, FOXSports.com is accessed the second-most of its 250
content channels. ESPN.com, the Internet's most-visited sports
site, has provided content for its wireless users for a year.
</P>
<P>
   With FOXSports.com's On the Go, handheld users with a
subscription to the service can call up tiny FOXSports.com-produced
pages and surf to headlines and scores. The channels are updated as
soon as the handheld device is synchronized.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are to expand FOXSports.com's content and package it by
regions in much the way FOX Sports Net does with its broadcasts,
said Danny Greenberg, vice president of FOXSports.com. It fits into
FOXSports.com's strategy of extending its content to mobile phones
and pages and ``all forms of electronics,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com's content is much the same as FOXSports.com and
includes news, scores and standings for major professional and
college leagues, extreme sports and golf.
</P>
<P>
   Handheld devices have other functions for sports fans. They can
be used to play games such as Tiger Woods' PGA Golf Tour. Handheld
device users can access portals sites, such as Hurst-based
GoPDA.com, for news, reviews, message boards and softwares to
download.
</P>
<P>
   Handheld computers are also tearing away at the last line of
defense of Internet detractors who say the medium is fine but it
can't go to the bathroom with them. Of course, handheld computers
have limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Personal digital assistants won't susbstitute for
general-purpose Web surfing, said Jesse Berst, who monitors the
Internet industry on ZDNET.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, they'll be used to access specialized Net services
like stock quotes, weather, maps and sports scores,'' Berst said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Greenberg: ``It's not true Internet where you can download
pictures. You can't do much because the screen size is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's all about delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   ANTICYBERSQUATTING: The NFL has made one of the first challenges
related to the new Anticybersquatting Consumer Protection Act,
which will fine people who register the domain names of people
without their consent. The league filed a suit last week in U.S.
District Court in New York against an Internet site operator for
extensive unauthorized use of NFL and team trademark names. Ken
Miller of Clearlake Park, Calif., has sites identified under
addresses as NFLtoday.com, NFLtoday.net and NFLtoday.org, which
promote gambling on NFL games. Miller told The Associated Press
that the NFL had offered $270 for the names, and he countered with
$120,000. Quokka Sports also filed a suit on behalf of the New
Zealand America's Cup yachting team because it wants to use the
americascup.com. The address is owned by two New Zealand men. A
temporary injunction has been granted.
</P>
<P>
   NOTEWORTHY: FOXSports.com, which announced its creation of
regional sites to mirror its regional networks last week, plans to
cybercast Saturday's Class 5A (Garland vs. Katy) and Class 4A
(Stephenville vs. Port Neches-Groves) Division II state football
championship games ... NBA.com yesterday launched a multimedia
feature called NBA Decade: The 90s, which highlights the greatest
moments, players and coaches of the past decade ... Dallas-based
Beckett.com has listed its top athletes according to the total
number of sports memorabilia items available. Michael Jordan
slipped from No. 1 to No. 4 in this year's rankings. St. Louis
Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire replaced Jordan has has 7,772 items
available on the sports memorabilia portal. Cowboys running back
Emmitt Smith is sixth (4,581) and quarterback Troy Aikman is 10th
(3,787) ... Quokka Sports (www.quokka.com) plans exclusive live
coverage of a climbing team's three-week ascent of the Mandara
Mountains in Cameroon, Africa. Quokka's online coverage includes
still photography and the athlete's perspective through e-mail and
audio dispatches sent via satellite by the climbers.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
