<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; sci-z
r a BC-CLOSETS-OF-CURIOSITIE     12-15 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOSETS-OF-CURIOSITIES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSETS OF CURIOSITIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    SIX COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOSEPH D'AGNESE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Deep in the bellies of two science museums in Los Angeles,
Calif., lurk mountains of treasures full of old tales. They dangle
in darkened warehouses, huddle in basements, chill in industrial
freezers.
</P>
<P>
   These are the hidden wonders museum visitors rarely see: trays
of dried butterflies (some tattered, others perfectly intact),
telescopes missing lenses, ivory dolls, mounted moose heads reeking
of pesticide, space suits lacking gloves, delicate toe bones of Ice
Age mice.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts seem to bide their times, waiting for the fanciful
day that moves them front and center.
</P>
<P>
   Most, of course, will never glimpse a paying customer.
Real-estate realities work against them.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, for example,
has a collection of 33 million items, but only enough space to
display 1 percent of the booty, just the tip of the curatorial
iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   A small part of this alternative universe has been liberated, on
film at least, by Richard Ross. He recently poked his lens into the
cubbyholes of two museums, recording a realm where staffers toil as
relics encroach upon their work space. Here balding grizzly bears
guard water fountains, miniature suits of armor crowd desktops and
everyone takes this secret world of museum misfits for granted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISPLACED MENAGERIE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taxidermist Tim Bovard must skirt an alligator, a Komodo dragon
and a Galapagos tortoise to reach his office each day.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County dutifully
adopts donated trophy heads and mounted animals and usually
relegates the pieces to storage.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often the animals do a stint in temporary exhibits but,
for the most part, Bovard is their only company.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an annual dusting, he rarely gives his roommates a
thought: ``I walk right past them because I see them every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANCELED FLIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The California Science Center keeps Armory Hall closed to the
public because it's not earthquake-proof.
</P>
<P>
   The vast main hall houses file cabinets, office furniture and
aerospace artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The biplane is a full-scale replica of a 1911 Model B Wright
Flyer, the first aircraft ever contracted by the U.S. government
from Orville and Wilbur Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Other hangers-on include and ultralight aircraft, a 1/10-scale
Titan rocket, an experimental aircraft with a rear propeller and a
full-scale Air Force Agena spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOLITARY CONFINEMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This prototype of a Mercury mission training suit, like those
donned by the first U.S. astronauts, was designed by the BF
Goodrich Company.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, California Science Center aerospace curator
Kenneth Phillips trots it out for classes with area schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually let them come up and touch it,'' he says. ``It's
cool and smooth, like it has a metallic coating.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit had a brief brush with fame in 1997, when Tom Hanks'
production company borrowed it for the HBO film ``From the Earth to
the Moon.'' And it will see more action in 2001, when it will go on
permanent display.
</P>
<P>
   The boots are not authentic Mercury footgear; Phillips plans to
replace them with the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STOREROOM STOOGES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backstage lunacy prevails in wax sculptor David Robert
Cellitti's studio at the Natural History Museum, where figures from
exhibits that never came to fruition have taken up permanent
residence.
</P>
<P>
   An Aztec shaman schmoozes with Larry, Moe and Curly while Jean
Harlow's headless body slinks in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Cellitti budgets two to three months and about $5,000 to craft a
single figure. All flesh-colored parts are poured from a mixture of
beeswax, cerisin and carnauba wax and affixed to fiberglass bodies.
</P>
<P>
   To give Curly his signature near-bald buzz-cut, Cellitti spent
three days implanting human hair into the figure's skull, then
shaved it all off.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BACKROOM BUSTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cellitti doesn't understand why his profession inspires such
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think its mysterious, like Argentinean nuns off in a
cave making this stuff,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces are first shaped from clay, cast as fiberglass prototypes
and poured in wax. Finally, Cellitti decorates them with makeup,
using techniques he practices on smaller fiberglass heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost the same process as making a boat,'' the wax
sculptor says. ``Only in the end, I have Jean Harlow, not a
skiff.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SKELETAL STALKER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is that? A spider monkey? An alley cat?
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know what they're seeing without the skin,'' says
Natural History Museum taxidermist Tim Bovard.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a bobcat, but it will take about two weeks of
work before that becomes apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Bovard first removes the skin and the underlying muscle, sculpts
clay over the resulting skeleton _ as shown here _ and takes a cast
of his sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Then he fabricates a mannequin, onto which he glues the tanned
hide. the original bones, sans clay, are stored separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the highest level,'' Bovard boasts, ``this is an art.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Joseph D'Agnese is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
