<HEADER>
A9513 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-THE-NEW-LOOK-ART-NYTS     12-15 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-NEW-LOOK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROPPED TOPS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing model Stella Tennant in a cropped
haircut is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article.
The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PATRICIA REYNOSO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Fashion may have been all over the map at the recent spring
shows, but one trend was clear on both sides of the Atlantic: The
Cher-hair revival of the last several seasons has finally started
to lose its grip on our fascination.
</P>
<P>
   (Think of Helen Hunt's extensions at the Academy Awards this
year for a look that's quickly passing its expiration date.)
</P>
<P>
   In its place was a parade of shaggy, homespun hairdos and _ get
this _ bangs. Even Naomi Campbell opted to walk the catwalk with a
modern shag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hair has been long and straight for so long that it was just
begging for a new look,'' says Garren, the hair master responsible
for Maggie Rizer's new bleached blond, choppy 'do. ``That haircut
is amazing on her. It really transformed her,'' he says, throwing
the model an admiring glance backstage at the Anna Sui show.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, a new haircut is the easiest way for a restless
model to find her way back into the spotlight. Gamine Trish Goff,
who last season sported one of the most luxurious manes around _
thick, jet black and hovering low beneath her shoulders _ this
season flaunted a shaggy, disheveled haircut that barely grazed her
neck. She looked so startlingly different that photographers
practically tripped over their tripods to get a shot of her.
</P>
<P>
   In Goff's case, the cut's homemade air was authentic: The model
did the snipping herself, albeit under the watchful eye of
hairstylist Rick Haylor.
</P>
<P>
   For mere mortals, the thought of bringing a pair of scissors in
contact with one's own hair might incite a panic attack, but for
seasoned veterans of fashion's smoke and mirrors, it's just a
matter of confident practicality.
</P>
<P>
   Take Stella Tennant's nonchalant explanation for her
self-inflicted crop: ``I know what I like, and I like to be in
control,'' she says with a shrug. Plus, she adds, ``I hate going to
salons.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gordon, the owner of New York's Bumble and bumble salon,
is understandably thrilled over the return of the ``haircut'' and
declares that if he had his way, he'd do away with all long hair.
``A true haircut is much more interesting,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, see the cropped look as just a fun diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer is a good season for short hair,'' says Orlando Pita
backstage at Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   But Pita says while long tresses have a versatility and a
universal sex appeal, short hair has its limits. ``You can only be
trendy with short hair,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Pita's sentiments is Brazilian bombshell Gisele. Much
has been said about her voluptuous figure, but Gisele's abundant
auburn mane is clearly the icing on her cake. The mere mention of a
new coif causes the model to shudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not cutting it!'' she gasps, throwing herself a reassuring
look in the mirror backstage at Ralph Lauren. ``I just think women
look more feminine with long hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was hair the shortest it's been since the waif rage of
the early '90s, but many of the styles sported something that
hasn't been seen for a long time: bangs. And editorial hairstylist
Ward couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's homage to this stalwart, however, is an offbeat,
asymmetric version that covers one eye and dips below the ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bangs that are cut in the same old way,'' he says, ``just
don't turn heads, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, isn't that what hair's all about?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Patricia Reynoso is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
