<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-AFRICAN-VOICES16-COX     12-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-VOICES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'AFRICAN VOICES' A NEW PERMANENT EXHIBIT AT SMITHSONIAN
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects last graf to say museum is closed Christmas Day.
 &HT;    Moving in (l) lifestyle and (t) travel categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ``other Mayflower'' set sail from Africa with a
cargo of enslaved Asante villagers about a century after the
original landed on Plymouth Rock. It landed in the colony of
Virginia on July 4, 1719, and most of those aboard were sold to
Robert Carter to work on his tobacco plantation near Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Their story is among the tapestry of tales woven into ``African
Voices'' _ a new permanent exhibition that opens Wednesday at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Six years in the making, the $5.5 million exhibit explores the
culture and history of a continent through films, photographs,
interactive videos, more than 400 artifacts, and the words of
scores of its people.
</P>
<P>
   The 6,500-square-foot exhibition ``demonstrates how African
cultures have spread worldwide, becoming a part of the very fabric
of American life,'' said Robert Fri, director of the museum. It
``encourages people to look beyond the existing stereotypes and
assumptions about Africa and Africans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit aims ``to present the diversity and dynamism of
Africa,'' said Fri, and ``to show how African cultures have spread
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an exhibit explaining the traditional ``mud cloth
pattern'' on paper cups of Peet's Coffee illustrates how ingrained
African culture has become in everyday American life.
</P>
<P>
   Fri said the exhibit is largest cultural display in all the
Smithsonian museums.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of slavery and colonialism are only two of 10 stories
told in the ``History Corridor'' that runs down the center of the
exhibit. The other historical themes include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The story of human origins in Africa about 5 million years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tales of the Egyptian and Nubian civilizations that arose in
the ancient Nile Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ The conquests and rule of African Muslims in the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
   _ The emergence of independent African nations.
</P>
<P>
   _ South Africa's struggle for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   _ And a changing section on the challenges that Africa faces
today.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are told ``from both rural and urban settings,''
said curator Mary Jo Arnoldi. The exhibitors received input from
Brazil, Mali, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, Malawi, Tanzania, Egypt and
South Africa, as well as from experts and institutions within the
United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the exhibit:
</P>
<P>
   _ An ``aqual,'' or contemporary portable home for Somali camel
herders. With a framework of arched roots and covering of woven
mats, the structure can be quickly disassembled and carried on a
camel's back. If a Somali marriage ends in divorce, the woman
retains rights to this house and its goods.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ``airplane coffin'' from Ghana made by artist Paa Joe. This
colorful conveyance ``confirms the deceased with the prestige and
mystique of travel,'' the curators wrote. Burial in a winged coffin
``connects the spiritual journey of death with a reminder of a life
well lived.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An early 20th century carved wooden door from Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
   _ An antelope mask made from corn husks and used by the Chewa
people of Malawi.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contemporary toys and dolls of African children.
</P>
<P>
   At every corner, an African voice speaks out _ sometimes in
narration, sometimes in song, sometimes in a written proverb or
passage. ``When you reach Benin, it is still very far away,'' goes
one saying from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum of Natural History is located at 10th Street
and Constitution Avenue NW and is open daily except Christmas Day
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
