<HEADER>
A9529 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1216-     12-15 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1216-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 1216: The power of sisterly love
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To Yolanda and Ray Gomez, Sister Gertrude Levy
isn't just a customer at their tailoring shop. She's a guardian
angel.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met the elderly nun a few years ago, when she came in
to have some alterations done. They became friends after a few
visits.
</P>
<P>
   Some time later, Ray started having chest pains and other
symptoms of a heart attack. But he was too embarrassed to go to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to tell the people at the desk that I had no
insurance,'' he says. ``They make you feel like a bum, like you are
worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain worsened over the next three days. And when Sister
Gertrude heard about Ray's condition, she took action: Ray had an
angioplasty and other treatments for his blocked arteries. Today,
he's feeling fine and continues to run the family business.
</P>
<P>
   With characteristic modesty, Sister Gertrude refuses to discuss
the help she gave them, or give specifics about the care and
consolation she's provided for thousands of other families during
her 30 years in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But others are happy to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for her, I wouldn't have gone to the hospital,''
Ray Gomez says. ``And if I hadn't gone to the hospital I probably
would have died.''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Gomez now makes all of the nun's skirts free of charge.
In her view, ``Sister Gertrude is the next best thing to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Devotion to the poor
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gertrude's job is in patient and guest services at Seton
Medical Center. Technically, her hours are 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.,
Monday through Friday. But she frequently puts in 12-hour days and
is often found at the hospital on weekends visiting the ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job with these people is to see that they are comfortable
and that they are satisfied with their treatment and that their
family is comfortably taken care of while they are visiting,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Part of her job is administering an emergency relief fund for
employees who need money in a crisis. She takes their calls and
decides what should be done.
</P>
<P>
   Her work dovetails with the mission of her order, to care for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think working here is fun,'' she says. ``It's a different
kind of fun. I enjoy my job, I enjoy people and so, it's not fun
like a picnic but I enjoy doing what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Her institutional knowledge and get-it-done attitude are assets
to patients and their families, friends say. If someone has a
question about what Medicare will cover, if someone is disabled and
has trouble finding transportation to the hospital to visit a sick
relative, if a family doesn't know where to get rehab services,''
she finds the answers,'' says Dianne Schoch, a member of the Seton
Fund Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   While her efficiency is an asset, it's her sense of humor and
warmth that make her such a comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Schoch's father was in the hospital two years ago because of a
heart attack, and Sister Gertrude ``visited him and prayed with him
and my mother every day,'' Schoch says.
</P>
<P>
   Liz McDaniel Watson, the wife of Austin Mayor Kirk Watson,
credits Sister Gertrude with helping her family through traumatic
times. When Kirk Watson's mother was dying of lymphoma, and when
Watson was battling testicular cancer, Sister Gertrude was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so happy, bright, she has such joie de vivre,'' Liz
McDaniel Watson says. ``I didn't understand how important that was
until Kirk's mom died. Sister Gertrude came in and was so
comforting.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gertrude, she says, ``is the living embodiment of God's
love.''
</P>
<P>
   A bit of Bach and Elvis
</P>
<P>
   But don't go thinking Sister Gertrude is some saintly person
who's dry to be around. She's a mix of contradictions _ a nun who
plays the saxophone and bongo drums, who likes Dick Francis novels,
who had an Elvis impersonator sing at her birthday party. A woman
who ministers to those who are suffering and dying, but who is also
friends with Broadway composer Marvin Hamlisch and former Supremes
singer Mary Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   At Sister Gertrude's 80th birthday party last month, hundreds
gathered to celebrate their favorite member of the Daughters of
Charity of St. Vincent de Paul, the order of nuns to which Sister
Gertrude belongs. There was a cake sent by Wilson, with a note
declaring Sister Gertrude ``an honorary Supreme.'' Guests loved a
video from Hamlisch in which the Tony-winning composer sang two
versions of ``Happy Birthday'' _ one done the way Bach would have
sung it, another in a Mozart style. Gov. George W. Bush sent a
proclamation declaring her ``an honorary Texan.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gertrude first met Wilson and Hamlisch when each was in
town to perform at a Seton gala. It was her job to pick them up at
the airport, but the bond she has formed transcends the usual
chauffeur-passenger relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's just my disposition,'' the nun says. ``I just
like people.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish nun? he asked
</P>
<P>
   When she first met Hamlisch, who is Jewish, he stared at the
surname on her name tag and asked, ``A Jewish nun?''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gertrude Levy explained that when her Jewish grandfather
married her Catholic grandmother, the Catholic Church required him
to agree that any children from their marriage would be Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my grandfather is very faithful to his promises, so my
father and his brothers and sisters were raised Catholic. So we're
all Catholic,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The second of nine children, she was born and raised in the
French Quarter of New Orleans. She and two of her sisters became
nuns. One of her brothers became a priest.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gertrude joined the order out of high school. After
taking her vows, she earned a bachelor's degree in education,
another in science and a master's degree in counseling. She started
teaching in 1937. Over the next few years, she worked in Alabama,
California, Mississippi and Louisiana, and finally in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, she began working at what was then Seton Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Attal, president of the Seton Fund, remembers when she came
to work. At that time, she was his only employee, he told guests at
her party.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she's been bossing me around ever since,'' he says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Retire? Not yet
</P>
<P>
   At 80, Sister Gertrude's energy is unflagging. Her appointment
book is packed. Every day, there are more people in the waiting or
recovery rooms for her to check on.
</P>
<P>
   Will she ever retire?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not in my plan right now,'' she says. ``I probably will
have to, someday, but I'm not even thinking about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
