r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN16-COX     12-15 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Please, let the songs escape from my skull
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Nearly every morning I wake up with a song
in my head. Most times it's a song that I can't stand. The other
morning it was ``I Saw Mommy Kissing Santa Claus'' _ the version
sung by some screechy-voiced kid, maybe little Michael Jackson. It
took a hot shower, several cups of coffee and an Sausage Egg
McMuffin to drive that rascal out of my skull.
</P>
<P>
   I've even awakened to hear ``Achy, Breaky Heart,'' lumbering
between my ears. Yeech. I consider Billy Ray Cyrus to be the
antichrist of country music. Reminds me of a line from a Chris Wall
tune, lamenting the death of Keith Whitley several years ago:
``Lord, if you'll just send back Keith Whitley, we'll give you
Billy Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, apparently I am not alone. An informal survey of
co-workers and acquaintances indicates that just about everybody is
dogged with tunes they can't stand running through their head. For
some, it's radio or television jingles. For others, it's snatches
from nursery rhymes. It's almost always something annoying.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, one person I talked to said what first runs
through her head each time the alarm goes off is, ``Ohmigod, it's
morning already.''
</P>
<P>
   Which could make a pretty good country song.
</P>
<P>
   Pondering this, I went to the Internet, figuring there is bound
to be a Web site devoted to people who are tormented by the songs
in their heads. There is at least one Web site for any conceivable
subject in the universe. Finding it is a trick, since Web sites are
added by the bejillions each day. I read somewhere that even the
best search engines can only scan 16 percent of all the sites on
the Web. I consider this a good thing, since any search now
invariably brings up about 17,000 possible sites. If all sites were
being searched that number would increase six-fold.
</P>
<P>
   I have this theory about the World Wide Web. It was created by
the moguls of television and radio, with limited help from the
print media. They sat around one day, worrying about how they were
going to increase their budget numbers the following year. One of
them said, ``Let's use the old, stuffy Internet, long the domain of
universities and the military, to create a new medium on which any
20-year-old can found a company that loses millions of dollars at
the same time its stock value escalates at alarming rates. We'll
make the Web so huge and hard to find stuff that these companies
will have to advertise on television and radio, and in newspapers
and magazines to let people know they're on the Web. Otherwise
they'll never find them.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Click on the television tonight. Every other
commercial is about a place to buy stuff on the Web. The sites
almost certainly aren't making any money, since it apparently is
illegal to make a profit on the Web unless one specializes in
photos of naked women. But the TV station or network selling the
commercials is making a killing. The price of a 30-second spot at
the next Super Bowl is rumored to be $3 million, which will buy
about 20 shares of your typical dot.com.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after about 15 minutes, I found
songinmyhead(at)listbot.com, which is devoted to people who wish to
complain about melodies in their medulla. The entry page says:
``Join this list if you always have songs buzzing around your head
and you'd like to annoy/amuse other people by sharing them.'' There
are about 300 entries, certainly no indicator of a worldwide
problem but enough to make you wonder:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Why would anyone create a Web site devoted to songs in your
head? Does this person have a real job?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Are they selling stock yet?
</P>
<P>
   The only effective cure for exorcising an annoying jingle or
song from my head is to tune to a commercial radio station.
Listening to instrumental or classical music, as I usually do,
won't do the trick. But crank up a Top 40 station with big-haired,
high-pitched rock stars singing something unintelligible, or some
drugstore cowboy crooning about his horse, dog, mama and pickup
truck, and ``I Saw Mommy Kissing Santa Claus'' magically disappears
from my brain.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, then I'm stuck humming ``Bubba Shot the Jukebox,'' or
some such nonsense. At least I'm not alone. The Internet has proven
that.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders writes for The Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel,
Nacogdoches, Texas. E-mai: gborders(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
