<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9531 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX     12-15 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some folks got in wrong line for funny bone
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lisa L. Moore, an associate professor in the
English department at the University of Texas, thinks I'm a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's new? Hey, lady, pretend you're at Sears, and take a
number. But I'll bet she doesn't know how to pronounce ``theater.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ``thee-ay-ter.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is still honked off about a tongue-in-cheek review I wrote
last summer about an artsy-schmartsy female spoken-word performance
arts piece called The Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridge involved 100 women in white clothing sitting in
folding chairs on the Congress Avenue bridge. I made fun of this
show, if you can imagine a straight-arrow such as myself actually
poking fun at the Austin arts community. The show was unique. I
have been to several state fairs and a jalapeno-eating contest, and
I have never seen anything like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show started with the women, seated in their folding
chairs, making an extended 'Ahhhh' noise in unison, like they were
at the dentist and he had just said, 'Open wide,' '' I pointed out
in my review. ``A bit later the women rose out of their folding
chairs to their feet. They had fierce faces, and they were babbling
loudly and incoherently. All I could figure was somebody back at
the house hadn't taken out the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   The part that really seemed to set Moore off was when I opined
that when the performers began laughing ``hah hah hah hah'' during
the performance, they were probably thinking about getting half of
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Half of everything _ the oldest divorce joke in the book. A lot
of people, I'll have to admit, got really chapped about this
article. On the other hand, a lot of people thought it was pretty
darned funny.
</P>
<P>
   But one of them wasn't Moore, who didn't exactly slap her
English-teaching knees when she got to that ``hah hah hah hah hah''
part because, as she pointed out, the piece wasn't about men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a celebration of women,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   A celebration of women? Then how come there wasn't a Tupperware
party scene? And if they were celebrating, how come they were
scowling?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting to me that you didn't bring up the themes
of the piece,'' Moore told me. Of course I didn't bring up the
themes of the piece. This column is supposed to be funny, and
writing about the themes of the piece would bore the snot out of my
readers, lady.
</P>
<P>
   If Moore wants to think I'm an idiot, that's her business. But
I'll bet if she could, she'd make me write on the blackboard a
thousand times, ``I'll bet you still think you're funny.''
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering why I'm bringing this up. I needed a
way to get yet another cheap plug in for my own performance arts
piece, The Remote, which will involve 100 guys in recliners sitting
on the Congress Avenue bridge, as well as watching football on big
screen TVs.
</P>
<P>
   As you may remember, we were going to hold this deal in
November. But we postponed it, out of respect for Texas A&AMP;M and the
Bonfire tragedy, until next Oct. 14 _ when we will have it in
conjunction with the Texas-Colorado game.
</P>
<P>
   If Moore wants to come and watch, she's welcome. What is it that
tells me she won't be there?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
