<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonder kids' key to gifts
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My daughter pulled the laminated photo ornament
out of the box of Christmas tree decorations. ``There's baby
Veronica,'' she said, with a fondly nostalgic air, as she peered
through the mists of time _ half a lifetime ago _ at the 1997
photo.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas is a time to chart your children's growth, and not
just by way of those picture ornaments they so proudly bring home
from school. You can measure your kids' development from their
Christmas lists.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year Veronica has observed Christmas in its
traditional meaning of rampant consumerism. Oh, sure, in previous
years she has gotten the bit about the sense of wonderment, of the
magical. But good old-fashioned greed, that she was slow to master.
</P>
<P>
   Her lilting requests to Santa didn't get any more specific than
``a doll with brown hair.'' No brand names. I could simply stash
hand-me-down toys in the attic, and she'd be as delighted as if
they came with store tags.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, I asked Veronica what she wanted for
Christmas. ``Some toys to play with!'' she shouted, after careful
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   That was, alas, before her commercial baptism in Saturday
morning cartoons. Veronica watched the ads intently and came to me
with breathless commercial bulletins: ``I want Santa to bring me a
Miss Party Surprise Pony Party. And I want Blue's Clues Play Doh.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistaking it: My daughter has been reborn as a
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old son, meanwhile, has graduated from toys to fishing
gear. Gone are the Hot Wheels sets and Star Wars paraphernalia that
populated his lists in previous years. Alec still believes in
Santa, I think, unless he is adopting a don't-ask, don't-tell
policy. He seems to believe that Santa does most of his shopping
from the Bass Pro Shop catalogue.
</P>
<P>
   What is the right balance between a bountiful holiday and
Wretched Excess? How much do children need?
</P>
<P>
   If you ask Patricia Duff, ex-wife of billionaire Ronald
Perelman, the answer would be $132,000 a month. That's how much she
demanded in child support for daughter, Caleigh, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Caleigh would be emotionally damaged, Duff argued, by the change
in her lifestyle _ especially if she realized she was living on
less than her half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision last week fairly dripping with scorn, Manhattan
judge Franklin Weissberg refuted Duff's arguments: ``The mother's
argument assumes that only material things matter in the life of a
child, and that if Caleigh is denied any imaginable luxury, she
will be emotionally damaged,'' Weissberg wrote. ``It does not
require a degree in psychiatry to know that this assumption is
rubbish. There are far more important things in the life of a young
child than private jets, yachts, obsequious staffs and pandering
guests.''
</P>
<P>
   How much do children need? Ask them, and the answer will always
be ``More.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend has a 9-year-old who is asking the Big Questions: ``If
Santa is real, that means I can have as many presents as I want,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking on her feet, the mother replied, ``But we pay Santa.''
She winced at the memory. Why doesn't parenthood come with second
takes? ``I should have told her that there's only so much room in
the sleigh.''
</P>
<P>
   She recovered herself in time to add, ``Santa will come if you
believe he will come. And if you tell your sister, he definitely
won't come.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't need a sleighful of presents or $132,000 a month. But
they do need a sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not be in a hurry to replace visions of sugarplums with
visions of Toys 'R' Us. As long as they can, let them hold on to
Santa, and the doll with the brown hair.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
