<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some advice on giving books as Christmas gifts
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books make the best Christmas (birthday, too, in point of fact)
gifts for a number of good reasons. That is, if the recipient of
your gift can read and, especially if he or she likes to read. And
even if he or she isn't a particularly avid reader, the right book
might turn he or she into just that, and that would make it the
greatest gift of all, since you probably can't give happiness or
lifelong good health.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Which book is the right book to give to that
special, or not so special, person?
</P>
<P>
   No one can make that choice for you, but the following are a few
books discussed here during the year just past that might give you
a little help in making this important choice.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, of course, the age of the giftee has a lot to do with
the choice of a giver's book selection. But there was one that came
out this year that might take care of that special person
regardless of what age he or she might be _ if they are above the
age of Happy Meals, that is. I'm speaking of a book titled
``Holes'' by Louis Sachar (Farrar, Straus and Girouux, $16), which
to my considerable surprise, won the National Book Award for
``young readers.'' I'm no young reader by any stretch of the term,
and I enjoyed this book immensely.
</P>
<P>
   A critic named Marvin Hoffman has written about ``Holes'' that
trying to tell what this book is about is no easy task ``for a
story with as many elements as a fine watch, all arranged to mesh
so precisely as to tell perfect time.''
</P>
<P>
   Another recent book that would make a fine Christmas gift
especially for someone who likes folklore told about with
professional and nostalgic skill, there is ``Walter Benjamin at the
Dairy Queen _ Reflections at Sixty and Beyond'' by Pulitzer Prize
winning novelist Larry McMurtry.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry has never been easy to get close to personally; so this
book of essays about his life and times growing up in and around
the small West Texas town of Archer City is about as close as most
people will be able to get to a McMurtry autobiography. It is
fascinating for that and a number of other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Another book now on bookstore shelves that should interest
serious readers and thinkers is Barbara Kingsolver's ``Poisonwood
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kingsolver fans, this new one may be something of a
surprise, but, if you stick with it, a pleasant surprise. It isn't
as simple and straightforward as previous Kingsolver stories and is
set in Africa. And this go-round, she uses a style somewhat
Faulknerian with each chapter told by a different character in that
character's words and accents. But, never fear, she is still as
skillful at depicting character as ever and her story, or stories,
are just as mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like their reading material rather light and
strictly for pleasure, there are new Robert B. Parker, Robert K.
Tanenbaum and Jay Brandon novels still on bookstore shelves, as
well as the many older ones that are now in paperback.
</P>
<P>
   The new Parker adventure about Spenser and his pals is called
``Hush Money'' and is definitely up to Parker's usual high level of
entertainment. If your friend or relative is a Spenser fan (or
likely to become one) this would make a dandy gift.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite as popular yet, but should be, are the Butch and
Marlene novels by Robert Tanenbaum, former New York City assistant
D.A., whose stories featuring attorneys Butch and Marlene, who also
are married lovers, along with their precocious daughter, Lucy, are
my current favorite light reading.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't sampled one of those yet, don't delay, especially
if you love suspense stories with humor and characters you care
about deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Brandon's new one is called ``Angel of Death'' and is set in
San Antonio, home of the attorney/novelist. It's a good one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
