<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's afraid of Y2K?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Nearly a year ago, a long-time acquaintance tried
to convince me about the magnitude of the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went into business for himself, he worked at IBM. He
knows more about computers than I will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   I should be prepared, he told me, for extensive break-downs in
society right after the midnight hour ushers in a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We might even be hit before midnight on Dec. 31 as the power
grids on the east coast start to collapse due to the inability of
computers to tell the difference between the years 1900 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to know how I was going to prepare for the upcoming
calamities.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers really swing into work during disasters. I guessed
that we would be working extra hard covering all the disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   No, he said, newspapers run on computers. Computers require
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   I had to admit that we needed electricity to put out a
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But I reminded him that we live in a profit-oriented capitalist
society. That fact alone will prevent a nationwide calamity due to
an obscure computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt many Americans will figure out clever ways to make
money from the Y2K computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans in private business will move heaven and earth to
keep from losing money on a problem that has a lot of advance
notice.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later a friend said he noticed this man coming out
of the post office with a package. He inquired about the package,
which is not improper in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   The man began to rip open the package, practically breaking his
fingernails in his excitement. Once ripped open, the man showed my
friend the contents. Neat stacks of gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   After the banks collapse due to Y2K computer problems, America's
paper money will become worthless. Most Americans not only will
lose the money they have in banks, but in their investments as
well. Americans will be forced to barter for needed supplies. Gold
will become the coin of the realm. That's how he saw it.
</P>
<P>
   As 1999 wore on I heard reports that the man had stockpiled food
and other survival gear. He supposedly was telling doubters to not
come to his house if the bottom falls out of society in 2000. It
would be too late.
</P>
<P>
   There was even one report, perhaps in jest, that the man was
buying up surrounding water districts. Evidently he not only was
going to survive, he also was going to benefit from the upcoming
Y2K collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A week or so ago my friend's wife ran him off for a day while
she escorted people through their house during a holiday home tour.
</P>
<P>
   My friend invited a number of his friends to his little cabin
for a barbecue. Included in the group was his friend, and my
long-time acquaintance, who was preparing for the big Y2K
catastrophe only days away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you find out any more about his Y2K preparations?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, my friend said, the subject never came up. The subject has
gotten to the point that it is similar to someone having an unusual
religion. You simply don't inquire about it, which would be
improper in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   My mother is laying in extra supplies, ``just in case.'' She has
extra food, some extra cash and extra prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 2 newspapers, which will come out on time, will carry
round-up stories of all the Y2K foul-ups.
</P>
<P>
   I predict there will be no major Y2K breakdowns in U.S. private
businesses. In all, the Y2K computer disaster will be a ho-hum news
story. I think.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
