<SLUG> BC-CFN-CEO16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financial services site operator CFN branches out
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Online shopping is not just buying books and CDs. An
Atlanta company helps consumers shop for financial products ranging
from life insurance to mutual funds on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CFN sells its services to more than 200 corporate customers that
make the service available on their corporate intranets. The
company has also rolled out a site for individual consumers called
Youdecide.com, available to anyone on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Cathi Raffaeli, 43, has been at the helm of CFN for the past
year, overseeing its expansion into the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an aggregator of aggregators,'' she says. ``We don't
want to be a just a car site or a mortgage site. We want to be the
place you go to organize your financial life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is the ideal vehicle to combine the education process
with the buying experience,'' she says. ``We can use the Internet
to gather advice and information and make intelligent decisions. I
remember applying for my first mortgage and wondering if I was
saying some key word that would ruin everything. People do feel
intimidated about asking questions and appearing uneducated. It's
so much easier to ask a digital question than asking a broker.''
</P>
<P>
   CFN launched as a intranet product for corporations and their
employees. ``When I joined the firm a year ago, it was 80 percent
phone-based,'' Raffaeli says. ``Just looking at corporate sector
was limiting, considering the assets we had been collecting. So we
went on a very rapid plan to make a shift to the retail user.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffaeli, who spent several years in executive positions at
Citigroup in New York, says the aggregation of financial products
in one place is something she's thought about for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent my entire career in financial services working toward
the goal of one-stop shopping, because it saved consumers time. But
the difficulty of it in the old tactile world is that you could
have one-stop shopping but it was with all one brand _ one
insurance company or one bank, for example. Now on the Web you can
have one-stop shopping with many choices. What we offer is the
nation's first digital financial mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefit is that the service is very unbiased. We have
providers from all walks of life, and we have no interest in
offering one deal over another.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffaeli says the difference between operating on the corporate
intranet and being on the Web for the public involves some
tinkering to help individuals make better decisions. ``In the
corporate world, people go directly to the purchase, but in retail,
users want more information, so we set about adding all kinds of
information to help them through the processes.''
</P>
<P>
   The corporate site was also revamped to incorporate some of the
tool kits and personalization found on YouDecide. Raffaeli plans to
add more personalization and tools to help users keep track of
their insurance polices, loans and investments.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric Capital owns 23 percent of CFN, Atlanta-based
iXL Enterprises the remaining 77 percent. The company is looking
for its next round of funding. So far, YouDecide and its corporate
version have no real competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun being a pioneer, but we have to watch out,'' Raffaeli
says.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't seem too worried. ``We don't see our competitors
as competitors, but as prospective partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
