<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9537 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE     12-15 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take 1 of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember that the story line of the movie ``Apocalypse
Now'' was taken from the book ``Heart of Darkness.'' I also
remember hearing that the character Col. Kurtz, played by Marlon
Brando, was loosely based on Col. David Hackworth. Can you verify?
</P>
<P>
   A: That rumor continues to make the rounds, two decades after
the 1979 movie was released, but there's nothing to indicate that
it's anything more than a rumor. We found no record that the film's
co-screenwriters, Francis Ford Coppola (who also directed) and John
Milius, ever mentioned that they based the Kurtz character on
Hackworth.
</P>
<P>
   However, an article in the Los Angeles Times in May 1989
reported this, after describing Hackworth's exploits in Vietnam as
a commander of several elite units: ``. . . the young commander
(Hackworth) led a helicopter unit that was later immortalized in
the movie `Apocalypse Now.' '' That article was based on an
interview with Hackworth when he was in Washington, D.C., promoting
his autobiography, ``About Face,'' but Hackworth himself didn't
mention the Kurtz character.
</P>
<P>
   While Hackworth has been described in print as ``one of the more
outrageous figures to emerge from the Vietnam War,'' he had a
noteworthy military career, collecting 78 combat awards and earning
a reputation as one of the Army's most brilliant commanding
officers. That career ended after he appeared on national TV in
June 1971, denouncing America's conduct in the Vietnam War. Within
months, the outspoken colonel retired from the service under a
cloud of criticism and moved to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Atlanta Falcons had gotten into the Super Bowl next
month, would that have been been the first time for a Super Bowl
team to play in its home stadium? Or, as a friend claims, did the
Miami Dolphins do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. No host-city team has ever played in the Super Bowl on
its home field, but two have played at nearby venues. The San
Francisco 49ers played in Super Bowl XIX at Stanford Stadium in
Palo Alto, Calif, and Super Bowl XIV featured the Los Angeles Rams
at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif., not Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are movie previews called ``trailers''?
</P>
<P>
   A: The word ``trailer(s)'' is a misnomer, as The Encyclopedia of
Hollywood points out, because they precede feature films rather
than trail them. So it would be better to call them ``previews of
coming attractions.'' Although the derivation is unknown, one
theory is that the advertisements traditionally were shown after
the first film of a double feature _ or, rather, at the beginning
of the second film _ and therefore came to be known as
``trailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about the turnover of the Panama Canal used the
word ``gringo.'' What does that mean, and what is its origin?
</P>
<P>
   A: The meaning is a foreigner, especially a white North American
or Briton. It's a Spanish or Spanish-American term, usually used
with derogatory connotation, explains the World Dictionary of
Foreign Expressions.
</P>
<P>
   The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins says
many scholars trace the term to the Spanish gringo, ``gibberish,''
a corruption of the Spanish word Griego, ``a Greek.'' By this
theory, gringo would be related to the old saying, ``It's all Greek
to me,'' indicating that the Yankees were strange and unfamiliar in
their ways to the Mexicans who so named them.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible explanation traces to Maj. Samuel Ringgold, a
strategist dreaded by the Mexicans during the Mexican War (1846-48)
before he was killed at the Battle of Palo Alto in 1846. Ringgold's
name, pronounced with a trilled ``r'' and without the last two
letters as it normally would be by a Mexican, then becomes
``gringo.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sen. Edward Kennedy, who spoke at the memorial service Dec. 8
for the firemen killed in Worcester, Mass., read a quote from a
letter his father wrote many years ago to a friend after the death
of a son. Can you print that text?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the words spoken by Kennedy (D-Mass.) as part of
his remarks, which also included his reading of the firemen's poem,
``May They Not Be Forgotten'':
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1958, my father wrote a friend whose son had died. And
since then that letter, read and reread, has helped our family
endure through the difficult times. Fourteen years before, my
oldest brother, Joe, had been killed in World War II, and my dad
referred to that when he wrote his grieving friend:
</P>
<P>
   `When one of your loved ones goes out of your life, you think of
what he might have done with a few more years, and you wonder what
you are going to do with the rest of yours. Then one day, because
there is a world to be lived in, you find yourself a part of it
again, trying to accomplish something _ something that he did not
have time enough to do. And, perhaps, that is the reason for it
all. I hope so.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the meaning of the inscriptions on the one-dollar
bill, ``Annuit Coeptis'' and ``Novus Ordo Seclorum''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Annuit Coeptis: ``He (God) has favored our undertakings.''
Novus Ordo Seclorum: ``a new order of the ages.'' The mottoes on
the reverse of the Great Seal of the United States were condensed
by William Barton, designer of the Great Seal, from a line in
Virgil's ``Eclogues.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the expression ``brand new''? How does
the word ``brand'' relate to something that is new?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins
explains that ``brand new'' has nothing to do with the brand name
of a product, as some people think. Rather, it's associated with
the word ``brand'' that is cognate with ``fire,'' as in
``firebrand.''
</P>
<P>
   The product described as ``brand new'' therefore would be fresh
from the anvil, or ``fire-new,'' as Shakespeare put it in ``Twelfth
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I enjoyed watching a videotape of the movie ``The
Eddie Duchin Story'' recently. It reminded us that we haven't heard
anything in a long time about Peter Duchin, his son. Is he still
playing the piano?
</P>
<P>
   A: Indeed he is. Gina Andriolo, his spokeswoman in New York,
told Q&AMP;A that Peter Duchin just returned from Italy, where he
played at the ``Save Venice Ball.'' His 1996 best-selling
autobiography, ``Ghost of a Chance,'' is now out in paperback, she
added. And he'll perform New Year's Eve at the Ritz-Carlton Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps glitziest of all, Duchin is featured in this year's
Neiman-Marcus Christmas Book. For $35,000, he will compose an
original piece of music, record it with his orchestra for a CD, and
have lunch with the gift recipient at ``21,'' the famed New York
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The 1956 film you saw, starring Tyrone Power and Kim Novak,
tells the story not only of Peter's parents, Eddie Duchin and
socialite Marjorie Oelrichs, but also of their son. It ends with
Peter still quite young, but already demonstrating considerable
keyboard talent.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life Peter studied at Yale, where he received his B.A.
in music and French literature, and at the Sorbonne in Paris. After
a two-year tour with the Army, he returned to New York and embarked
on a career that included a lengthy engagement at the St. Regis
Hotel. He also has made more than 26 studio recordings, and has
performed at every presidential inaugural ball since 1961. He
continues to play at weddings and society engagements nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We've been trying to figure out the Roman numerals for the
years 1999, 2000, and 2001, and can't agree. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: 1999: MCMXCIX. 2000: MM. 2001: MMI.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When can those of us who applied for the random drawing for
tickets to Super Bowl 2000 in Atlanta expect to hear if we'll be
able to buy them?
</P>
<P>
   A. People will get a telepone call sometime around Dec. 24
advising them that they ``won,'' as a spokesman for the National
Football League put it. The NFL distributes about 500 pairs of
tickets to fans through the drawing. These are the only tickets
made available to the public. The tickets will cost $400 for club
and suite level, $325 for all others. Super Bowl XXXIV will be
played Jan. 30 at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A game show contestant was asked what was used to remove rock
from Mount Rushmore. She said TNT, which was ruled incorrect.
Another contestant said dynamite, which was ruled correct. Aren't
they the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   A: The McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scienfic and Technical Terms
explains that the word dynamite is a generic term ``covering a
class of nitroglycerine-sensitized mixtures of carbonaceous
materials (wood, flour, starch) and oxygen-supplying salts, used as
explosives for blasting and mining.''
</P>
<P>
   TNT is an abbreviation for 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene, defined as
``toxic, flammable, explosive, yellow crystals; soluble in alcohol
and ether, insoluble in water; melts at 81 degrees C; used as an
explosive and chemical intermediate and in photographic
materials.'' So if an explosive other than this specific chemical
mixture had been used at Mount Rushmore, it wouldn't have been TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
