 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of two.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What's the status of funding for the Ricky Ray Relief Act?
The act was passed by Congress last year, but it wasn't funded. It
involved a ``compassionate payment'' by the federal government to
hemophiliacs infected with HIV through the use of contaminated
blood products in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A: On Nov. 29, a $75 million appropriation for the Ricky Ray
Hemophilia Trust Fund was signed into law by President Clinton. The
measure had been approved previously, as you say, by both the House
and the Senate. The funding legislation was included in H.R. 3424,
an omnibus bill that authorizes $390 billion in spending for fiscal
year 2000 (which runs Oct. 1, 1999, to Sept. 30, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund was the only new program funded in the Health and
Human Services Department for fiscal year 2000. The $75 million
appropriation includes $10 million for administrative expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 trust fund legislation requested $750 million in
funding, leaving a balance of $675 million remaining to be funded.
Funding this balance will require additional appropriation(s),
which may come as soon as the midyear (fiscal) budget sessions in
early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I send a donation to the Hillary Rodham Clinton
Senate campaign?
</P>
<P>
   A: The address: Hillary Rodham Clinton for Senate Committee, 450
7th Ave., Suite 804, New York, NY 10123. Information is available
online at www.hillary2000.org or by calling 212-239-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you print an address where we can send contributions to
Rudy Giuliani's campaign?
</P>
<P>
   A: Credit card donations can be made online at
www.rudyyes.com/contents/donate or by mailing a check (or credit
card information) to Friends of Giuliani, 250 Broadway North, Suite
2014, New York, NY 10007.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the age at which people can begin receiving full
Social Security retirement benefits is going up. I also know that
the ages will differ according to the year of birth. Can you print
a schedule showing the various years and ages for full retirement?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's all posted at www.ssa.gov, the Social Security
Administration's Web site. But here's the information for those who
aren't online.
</P>
<P>
   The full retirement age is 65 for those born in 1937 or earlier.
Those born in 1938 are eligible for full benefits at 65 and two
months; 1939, 65 and four months; 1940, 65 and six months; 1941, 65
and eight months; 1942, 65 and 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Those born between 1943 and 1954 are eligible for full benefits
at age 66.
</P>
<P>
   Those born in 1955, 66 and two months; 1956, 66 and four months;
1957, 66 and six months; 1958, 66 and eight months; 1959, 66 and 10
months; 1960 and later, 67.
</P>
<P>
   If your full retirement age is older than 65 (that is, you were
born after 1937), you still will be able to take your retirement
benefits at age 62, the Social Security Administration points out.
But the reduction in your benefit amount will be greater than it is
for people retiring now.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. If your full retirement age is 67, the
reduction for starting your benefits at 62 is about 30 percent; at
63, it's about 25 percent; at 64, about 20 percent; at 65, about 13
1/3 percent; and at 66, about 6 2/3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, the agency notes, early retirement will give
you about the same total Social Security benefits over your
lifetime, but in smaller amounts, to take into account the longer
period you will receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On ``Hollywood Squares,'' the question was asked, ``Which
city is located the farthest west?'' The choices were San Diego,
Los Angeles or Reno, Nev. The correct answer was Reno. I've checked
several maps and don't see how that can be. Was the program wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A: Reno is at longitude 119.47 west. Los Angeles is at 118.24
west. San Diego is at 117.10 west. So Reno is indeed farther west
than either California city. Look at a globe, rather than a flat
map, and check the 120-degree longitude, and it will make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The likenesses of presidents on U.S. coins all face to the
left except for Abraham Lincoln on pennies. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Mint reports that the direction Lincoln faces on the cent
wasn't mandated, but was simply the choice of the designer.
Lincoln's likeness on the coin is an adaptation of a plaque
executed by portraitist and sculptor Victor David Brenner.
President Theodore Roosevelt, who was impressed with Brenner's
design of the plaque, recommended to the secretary of the Treasury
that this design be placed on a coin to be issued in 1909, the
centennial of Lincoln's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Accounts in different publications have reported on the close
relationship of the late Al Gore Sr. and the late Armand Hammer,
president of Occidental Petroleum Corp. After he left the Senate,
Gore reportedly worked for Occidental. Can you elaborate?
</P>
<P>
   A: This relationship was described recently in The Wall Street
Journal. According to the article, the senior Gore was named by
Hammer to the Occidental Petroleum board of directors after Gore
lost his 1970 Senate re-election bid. He also was named chairman of
an Occidental subsidiary, Island Creek Coal Co., and was paid more
than $500,000 a year for the positions.
</P>
<P>
   As to a ``close relationship,'' The Wall Street Journal listed
many connections and quoted from a 1992 Washington Post article
reporting that Gore Sr. was a partner, with Hammer, in a profitable
cattle breeding business, and that Hammer had provided Gore Sr. an
88-acre farm in Tennessee with rights to mine zinc. The Post
article said Occidental Minerals, an Occidental Petroleum
subsidiary, bought the land in Tennessee in 1972, and within a
year, Gore Sr. had bought the property.
</P>
<P>
   Gore Sr. obviously wasn't Hammer's only politician acquaintance.
The Wall Street Journal, in fact, pointed out that Hammer
``collected politicians.'' A longtime friend of President Ronald
Reagan, Hammer pleaded guilty to charges of making illegal
contributions to President Richard Nixon's re-election campaign in
1972 and was sentenced to one year's probation and fined $3,000. He
was pardoned in 1989 by President George Bush. Hammer died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Marianne Gingrich said she's involved in
helping Mission Specialties, which raises money for needy A: The
address: Mission Specialties, 1827 Powers Ferry Road, Building 15,
Suite 300, Atlanta, GA 30339. Those wishing to make a contribution
can mail a check, made payable to Mission Specialties; or call
770-916-9029 to have it charged to a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Most Rhodes Scholars seem to be engineers and scientists. Can
you list the undergraduate majors of all 32 of them this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jennie Han, Yale University, political science; Elizabeth
Young, U.S. Military Academy, international relations and history;
Craig Mullaney, U.S. Military Academy, European history; Jasmine
Waddell, Brown University, political science.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Adesnik, Yale, history; Brandon Dammerman, Columbia
University, biochemistry and mathematics; Jacob Krich, Swarthmore
College, physics; Paul Larsen, College of William &AMP; Mary, physics.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Gray, Amherst College, biology and philosophy; Christian
Hunt, Davidson College, English and German; Caroline Parler,
University of South Carolina, chemical engineering; Eileen
Cardillo, College of William &AMP; Mary, biopsychology.
</P>
<P>
   Neelakash Varshney, University of Alabama at Birmingham,
electrical engineering; Newman Nahas, University of Florida,
English; Julian Harris, Duke University, medical ethics; Danielle
Sered, Emory University, English.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Javaras, Harvard University, statistics; Michael Lanham,
Centre College, mathematics and music; Ilyana Kuziemko, Harvard,
economics; Cindi Dennis, Carnegie Mellon University, physics and
computer science.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna Mierau, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, brain and
cognitive sciences; Katherine Larson, St. Olaf College, American
literature, English and vocal performance; Benjamin Cannon,
Washington University, history; Robert Yablon, University of
Wisconsin-Madison, political science and economics.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Elander, Montana State University, biochemistry; Jason
Sanders, University of Oklahoma, biochemistry; Jesse Kharbanda,
University of Chicago, economics and environmental studies; Jessica
Mellinger, University of Wyoming, molecular biology and English.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Kleinfeld, Yale, ethics, politics and economics; Elisha
Peterson, Harvey Mudd College, mathematics; Melissa Sturm, U.S.
Military Academy, comparative government; Derek Lyons, Reed
College, chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT.)
</P>
