<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ADVICE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simple cooking, sensible advice
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Art Ginsburg _ Mr. Food _ offers
opinions with little prompting. Here are some of his:
</P>
<P>
   _ On overwhelming success: ``My philosophy is, we're offering
quick, easy, sensible, everyday recipes for the everyday person.
For the busy people. And all of the ingredients we use are off the
grocery shelf. If you can't find it in the common supermarket, I
don't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On health-conscious cooking: ``There are people who ask us to
write recipes for this or that diet restriction. What we found is
that they're paying lip service to it. We thought about doing a
diabetic cookbook, but we're waiting to see the response to our
diabetic cooking shows first. Giving options is the way to go, so
that's what I do _ I tell them you can use low-fat sour cream or
whatever, but I give it as an option and leave it up to them. I
would never endorse any diet _ I'm not a nutritionist.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his five-minute TV spots: ``Most people who are on TV have
a cooking show. I have a food show. I talk about food. The things
that chefs do are so complicated, most people can't and won't ever
do them. I'm doing things that everyone can do, from the new cook
to the cook who's been doing it for 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the nation's weight problem: ``That's the government saying
that (we're overweight and obese). You may look and feel fine 20 or
30 pounds overweight, while someone else may not. For different
people, overweight is relative. Now that they've settled with the
tobacco industry, what else is there to rail against? Food. We've
got to be sensible and real. Everything I do, I hope, is sensible
and real.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On ``perfection'' cooking: ``I don't like the intimidation of
perfection in food magazines or on TV shows or on a cake box. There
are crumbs on the plate when I make food. The food stylist wants to
clean it up, but I say `No! Leave them!' That's reality. If we have
a crooked cake, leaning to one side or another, or the icing isn't
perfect, that's good. That's how real cooks cook. It's time we got
back to real.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
