<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-MRFOOD-RECIPES16     12-15 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MRFOOD-RECIPES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mr. Food shares his culinary expertise
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Here are some of Mr. Food's most popular
recipes and some from his new book, ``A Mr. Food Christmas'' by Art
Ginsburg (William Morrow and Company Inc., New York).
</P>
<P>
   DEATH BY CHOCOLATE
</P>
<P>
   1package (21 ounces) brownie mix, baked according to package
directions, cooled
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup coffee-flavored liqueur, optional
</P>
<P>
   2packages (4-serving size) instant chocolate mousse or pudding,
prepared according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   8(1.4 ounce) chocolate-covered toffee candy bars (like Skor or
Heath), coarsely crushed
</P>
<P>
   1container (12 ounces) frozen whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   Use a fork to prick holes in the top of the cooled brownies;
drizzle with the coffee liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   Break up the brownies into small pieces and place half in the
bottom of a trifle bowl. Cover with half of the mousse, then 1/3 of
the crushed candy and half of the whipped topping. Repeat the
layers and top with the remaining crushed candy. Cover and chill
for at least 2 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MUFFIN TIN MEAT LOAVES
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1medium zucchini, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1cup dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1egg, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon Italian seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. In a large bowl, combine all
the ingredients except the ketchup, mixing lightly but thoroughly.
Place about 1/3 cup of the beef mixture into each of 12 medium
muffin cups, pressing lightly. Spread the ketchup over the tops.
Bake for 20 minutes, or until no pink remains and the juices run
clear. Makes 12 meat loaf muffins.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-STUDDED TENDERLOIN
</P>
<P>
   1whole beef tenderloin (5 to 6 pounds), trimmed
</P>
<P>
   6garlic cloves, slivered
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup port wine or other red wine
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Make small slits in the tenderloin and insert garlic slivers;
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all the remaining ingredients; mix
well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tenderloin, cover, and allow the meat to marinate in the
refrigerator for at least 6 hours, or overnight, turning
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the meat from the marinade and place in a roasting pan;
discard the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the meat for 40 to 45 minutes for medium, or to desired
doneness.
</P>
<P>
   Allow to sit for 20 to 30 minutes before thinly slicing. Serve
with tarragon spread (recipe follows) and focaccia for sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 to 16 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TARRAGON SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   2cups mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients together well; chill.
</P>
<P>
   NO-EGG EGGNOG
</P>
<P>
   5 1/2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1package (4-serving size) instant vanilla pudding and pie
filling
</P>
<P>
   4teaspoons rum extract
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2cups (1 pint) heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons confectioner's sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a punch bowl, combine the milk and pudding mix; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rum extract and 1/2 teaspoon nutmeg; mix well and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat the heavy cream and confectioner's sugar
until stiff peaks form.
</P>
<P>
   Add half of the whipped cream mixture to the milk mixture; stir
well until blended.
</P>
<P>
   Dollop the remaining whipped cream mixture over the top and
sprinkle with the remaining nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SPINACH-BEET SALAD
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Grated peel of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1package (10-ounces) fresh spinach, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1can (15-ounces) julienne-sliced beets, drained
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons real bacon bits
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the mayonnaise, sour cream, lemon
juice, lemon peel, salt and pepper; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the spinach and toss until well coated.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a serving bowl or on individual salad plates and top
with the beets and bacon bits.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   For the following, you can mix up the filling the night before
and roll and bake the day of serving.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY SAUSAGE ROLL-UPS
</P>
<P>
   1package (16-ounces) spicy bulk pork sausage
</P>
<P>
   1/2medium red bell pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   4scallions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2packages (8-ounces each) refrigerated crescent rolls (8 rolls
each)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine the sausage, red pepper and scallions;
mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Unroll one package of crescent rolls and press the seams
together to form one large rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the second package of rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Spread half of the sausage mixture evenly over each rectangle;
starting from a narrow end, roll up jelly-roll style.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each roll into eight equal slices and place on their sides
on a baking sheet to form a Christmas tree shape. (Create a pyramid
shape: one roll on top, then two in next row, and continue, ending
with five rolls on bottom. Add one roll, centered, for tree trunk.)
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 25 to 30 minutes, or until the sausage is no longer
pink and the crust is golden.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 rolls.
</P>
<P>
   STATE FAIR PASTA
</P>
<P>
   1pound rigatoni, penne, or Christmas pasta
</P>
<P>
   2pounds hot Italian turkey sausage, casings removed
</P>
<P>
   3large bell peppers (1 each green, red and yellow), cut into
1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1can (28-ounces) diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1jar (26-ounces) spaghetti sauce
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the pasta according to the package directions; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a soup pot, saute the sausage, bell peppers and
onion over medium-high heat for 6 to 8 minutes, or until the
vegetables are tender, and no pink remains in the sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining ingredients and cook for 5 minutes, or until
heated through and bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon over pasta and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
