<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-MRFOOD16-COX     12-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MRFOOD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life is good for Mr. Food
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ There really are test kitchens in the
Mr. Food studio. So what if Art Ginsburg _ Mr. Food to millions of
TV viewers _ never cooks in them? He could. He's just too busy with
his new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The TV success of Mr. Food has far outstripped his former life
as a caterer and butcher in upstate New York in the 1970s. So now,
cooking is his act _ his segments close with a signature tagline,
``Ooh, it's so good!'' as he mugs for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   He describes recipes, rather than demonstrates them, on
90-second spots that air in 170 stations around the country.
They've been aired in many cities since the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   He gives fast cooking tips and food information instead of
complex how-to's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my viewers are stupid,'' he said. ``Watching
fish fry for 10 minutes is boring. In a minute and a half, I can
give recipes for a whole meal. That's what they want _ they know
how to fry a fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he tells them how to choose a fresh fish, what kind of
cabbage to buy for slaw and how to store it, and how to make a
tartar sauce from bottled ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The gray-bearded, 64-plus-year-old _ he's vague about his age _
lives in Fort Lauderdale with his family and has his offices, TV
studio set and test kitchens in an industrial park there. While
talking, he's hunting up an apron and toque (chef's hat) for his
photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   The crisp, bright red apron's a sore spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People write in about the clean apron; nobody cooks every day
in a brand-new apron,'' he said, ``but they don't want to see you
wear a dirty one, either. So it's damned if you do, damned if you
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no waffling about pleasing his viewers, however. His
cookbooks are top sellers on QVC; he gets millions of pieces of fan
mail each year and he says his corporation is solidly in the black
(he won't reveal company worth).
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg says it's because he knows exactly what cooks want and
how to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Convenience is the No. 1 concern of cooks today,'' he said.
``Price and value are still important, but everybody is too busy to
cook and they want to do it faster, easier, with fewer ingredients.
They don't want to have to shop at four different stores to get the
ingredients, either.''
</P>
<P>
   So all of Mr. Food's recipes are ``quick, easy and sensible.''
He uses only ingredients available at major supermarkets. While
other chefs hide labels and boxes or cans if they use them, he
stacks them all on the counter as he gives the recipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is reality. I do sensible home cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Recipes for cakes begin with cake mixes, and breads are made
with pop-open tubes of dough _ a direct contrast to the elaborate
techniques presented on most TV cooking shows or in magazines. Home
cooks love to see those things, but never do them, he said.
``They're intimidated by those perfect-looking foods that take
hours to do. That's why we show our mistakes. I have to fight with
my food stylist about that, but we show homemade-looking foods.''
Crooked cakes happen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him,'' said David Pantone. ``The majority of the
people the majority of the time have a limited amount of time to
get dinner together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for what he does, Mr. Food does it very well. It's a
recipe; he doesn't plug a lesson into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg's down-home personality makes his fans comfortable.
They trust him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, he's just launched the At Home with Mr. Food
home parties. Set up like the Tupperware system of home selling,
Ginsburg's food props and utensils are offered to cooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got so many requests for things I used on the show _
knives, cookie jars _ we figured it was a natural.'' He tests all
the products before they're allowed in the catalog. ``They know I
won't sell something I wouldn't use.''
</P>
<P>
   He began the parties this summer in South Florida; they're now
in all the markets where he airs. The catalog features the cooking
tools and dishes, cookbooks, gadgets and Mr. Food spice blends that
appear on his segments. His easy recipes are included.
</P>
<P>
   But it's obvious that he knows fine food and cooking. Hundreds
of cookbooks from around the world line his office and hallway
walls. He keeps a staff of researchers busy helping develop menus
and recipes for the 28 cookbooks and monthly magazine, Mr. Food's
Easy Cooking.
</P>
<P>
   All of his recipes are tested several times in the test
kitchens. His company, Ginsburg Enterprises Inc., is also
responsible for testing contest recipes for magazines such as
Southern Living, and for creating recipes with his name on them for
organizations such as the American Cheese Board.
</P>
<P>
   All this, yet his name seldom comes up when successful chefs are
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, he says, he's not a chef, and doesn't do a
cooking show. ``I do a food show, and I'm entertaining at the same
time. It's about food and products and how to use them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His fans rush him in airports, and line up for hours for
autographs when he appears at state fairs. They want the Death by
Chocolate recipe that's become the most requested in his
repertoire. He, of course, features the trifle bowl to build it in,
in his home-party catalog. ``It's a big seller,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Party hostesses get a bonus if he's in their town _ he'll show
up at a party as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing it.'' Schmoozing with fans satisfies his latent
acting career, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Theater was where he was headed before he hit the food circuit.
``I was a bit player, struggling actor as it were, and couldn't
make it. When I entered catering, it was the first time in my life
I was paying the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   He no longer has time for acting, but, he said, ``I'm getting my
jollies in theater and food at the same time with the show. Life is
very, very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
