<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KAYKYSER16-COX     12-15 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAYKYSER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Show to recall band leader Kyser's life
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ He is an American icon who was born and
raised in Rocky Mount. His memory might have slipped through the
cracks of history, but with the help of his daughter, it will soon
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Mortarboard Productions, in association with the North Carolina
Museum of Art Foundation, will produce ``Kay Kyser - A Life in
Motion.'' It will document the life of Kyser from his days as head
cheerleader at UNC Chapel Hill through more than two decades as one
of the nation's most successful entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser was a big band leader. He hosted NBC's ``College of
Musical Knowledge.'' And he appeared in 11 motion pictures, seven
of which he starred in.
</P>
<P>
   He performed shows for U.S. troops during World War II - more
shows than anyone in history, including Bob Hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many viewers, `Kay Kyser - A Life in Motion' will be their
history. It will be a reliving of their own experiences,'' said his
daughter Kimberly Kyser, during a telephone interview from her
office in Chapel Hill. Kimberly also is executive producer of
Mortarboard Productions. ``For younger audiences, it will be a
discovery of their parents' and grandparents' histories, an
opportunity to learn about the world that shaped their future more
than 50 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of his career, in 1951, Kyser walked away from fame
and fortune. Out of the national spotlight, his ideas, energy and
inspiration resulted in the formation of major institutions that
are an integral part of life in North Carolina history. Starting
Memorial Hospital at UNC Chapel Hill and bringing public television
to the state were among the many retirement projects Kyser launched
from his home in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Although a biographical documentary film, ``Kay Kyser - A Life
in Motion'' is about more than the life of one man, his daughter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the uncovering of a lost saga of an American experience,
a personal pilgrimage, a unique individual's living of a very
public and private life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a bright story that intersects two dark moments in
American history, the Great Depression and World War II. Kyser
played an important role in both, but especially in World War II -
not with speeches or with guns, but with music.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser was a public figure for most of his life, and there is a
wealth of information to tell his story. Recordings provide core
documentation of his music. There are hundreds of radio programs,
11 major motion pictures, U.S. Armed Services film footage and
audio recordings of the many shows performed for the troops, still
photography, taped television appearances and rare home videos.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kyser was co-founder of UNC-TV, his daughter feels it's
only fitting that one of the many goals of the project is to
benefit the institution he helped create. Mortarboard Productions
intends to use the film to raise money for public television by
giving the right to broadcast the film and sell videos in North
Carolina to UNC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   The film is expected to be complete by year-end 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Moran writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky
Mount, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
