<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, December 16, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ My daughter pulled the laminated
photo ornament out of the box of Christmas tree decorations.
``There's baby Veronica,'' she said, with a fondly nostalgic air,
as she peered through the mists of time _ half a lifetime ago _ at
the 1997 photo. Christmas is a time to chart your children's
growth, and not just by way of those picture ornaments they so
proudly bring home from school. You can measure your kids'
development from their Christmas lists. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ An informal survey of
co-workers and acquaintances indicates that just about everybody is
dogged with tunes they can't stand running through their head. For
some, it's radio or television jingles. For others, it's snatches
from nursery rhymes. It's almost always something annoying.
(Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ No doubt many Americans will
figure out clever ways to make money from the Y2K computer problem.
But Americans in private business will move heaven and earth to
keep from losing money on a problem that has a lot of advance
notice. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ From my review of ``The Bridge'' earlier this
year _ the ``celebration of women'' that closed down Congress
Avenue in Austin, Texas. . . ``The show started with the women,
seated in their folding chairs, making an extended 'Ahhhh' noise in
unison, like they were at the dentist and he had just said, 'Open
wide,' '' I pointed out in my review. ``A bit later the women rose
out of their folding chairs to their feet. They had fierce faces,
and they were babbling loudly and incoherently. All I could figure
was somebody back at the house hadn't taken out the trash.'' The
part that really seemed to set Lisa L. Moore off was when I opined
that when the performers began laughing ``hah hah hah hah'' during
the performance, they were probably thinking about getting half of
everything. ``It was a celebration of women,'' Moore said. A
celebration of women? Then how come there wasn't a Tupperware party
scene? And if they were celebrating, how come they were scowling?
(Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
