<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 1216: The power of sisterly love
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To Yolanda and Ray Gomez, Sister Gertrude Levy
isn't just a customer at their tailoring shop. She's a guardian
angel. The couple met the elderly nun a few years ago, when she
came in to have some alterations done. They became friends after a
few visits. Some time later, Ray started having chest pains and
other symptoms of a heart attack. But he was too embarrassed to go
to a hospital. ``I didn't want to tell the people at the desk that
I had no insurance,'' he says. ``They make you feel like a bum,
like you are worthless.'' The pain worsened over the next three
days. And when Sister Gertrude heard about Ray's condition, she
took action: Ray had an angioplasty and other treatments for his
blocked arteries. Today, he's feeling fine and continues to run the
family business. With characteristic modesty, Sister Gertrude
refuses to discuss the help she gave them, or give specifics about
the care and consolation she's provided for thousands of other
families during her 30 years in Austin. But others are happy to
talk. ``If it wasn't for her, I wouldn't have gone to the
hospital,'' Ray Gomez says. ``And if I hadn't gone to the hospital
I probably would have died.'' Yolanda Gomez now makes all of the
nun's skirts free of charge. In her view, ``Sister Gertrude is the
next best thing to God.'' (Santos, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ Not available this week. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
