 Wednesday, December 15, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the
following for Thursday. If you have questions, please call Susie
McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ''HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown, who embraced the
political center to trounce the more liberal Tom Ammiano, heads
into his second term and the new millennium with an overwhelming
mandate from San Francisco voters. Brown became the first San
Francisco mayor to win re-election in more than a decade by
attracting Republicans, other conservatives and middle-of-the-road
voters into a new, broader coalition. In return, Brown promised his
new allies a voice in his administration. By RACHEL GORDON, ZACHARY
COILE and ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR-ANALYSIS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown's huge financial advantage and his vaunted political field
operation combined to turn out three voters for every two who
supported his opponent, San Francisco Board of Supervisors
President Tom Ammiano. By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR-LOSER (San Francisco) _ Supervisor Tom Ammiano is still
the odd man out. But he will never say he lost Tuesday. Ammiano is
still president of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors and a
more recognized figure - locally and nationally - with his
unsuccessful bid for the mayor's office. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   SF-BROWN-AGENDA (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown, recognizing a sizzling housing market has threatened some
San Franciscans with losing their homes, says finding a way to make
the city affordable for all to live is the major challenge of his
second term. By ZACHARY COILE and RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-FOODS (Oakland, Calif.) _ A band of children decked out
as black-and-orange monarch butterflies flitted around the plaza
outside the Federal Building, where a government agency held a
hearing on whether to tighten controls on bioengineered crops. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOBBYISTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gifts to state officials won't be
able to exceed $25, according to a bill that isn't likely to become
law in New York state. By JAMES ODATA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you listen well, you get inside
the heads of people from all sorts of backgrounds, and their
approaches might help you come up with a fresh way of doing things.
Learning to see things from other people's perspectives is a
crucial career skill. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-CULTS (Undated) _ Employees who take advantage of
corporate perks, such as on-site day care and cafeterias, may find
themselves part of a corporate cult. Dave Arnott, a professor at
Dallas Baptist University and the author of ``Corporate Cults: The
Insidious Lure of the All-Consuming Organization,'' advises workers
to avoid becoming too much of an insider. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   TAXES-ONLINE (San Francisco) _ A coalition of Bay Area
booksellers wishes their tax collector would go surfing. On the
Internet, that is. The group of independent shop owners believes
tax collectors have been lax in collecting sales tax from online
bookstores. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ ``Atlantis Found'' is Clive Cussler
at his storytelling best. Not as outrageous as some of the earlier
adventures involving Dirk Pitt, ``Atlantis'' makes Dirk more human
and less Superman. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Quarterback Jeff Garcia led
the 49ers to their first win in two months when the 49ers beat the
Atlanta Falcons. Hehrew for 437 yards in a loss to
Cincinnati two weeks ago. But he played so poorly earlier this
season that he lost his job for three games. Now, Garcia seems set
to finish the year as the team's starter. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAKEUP (San Francisco) _ Angel or devil? Millennium cutie or
retro siren. The makeup choice this holiday season is entirely up
to you. Cosmetic companies have tapped various trends for gala
looks. Traditionally, red lipstick was the holiday staple, but as
New Year's Eve draws nigh, red has been augmented by things
glimmery, silvery and space age. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The limos won. The party
transportation summed it up. A dozen gleaming limos sat outside
Alioto's restaurant where Mayor Willie Brown had an election-night
dinner, while outside Tom Ammiano's party at the Roccapulco
nightclub in the Mission was the sign ``Free bike parking across
street.'' The bikes never had a chance. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ As an institution, the 211-member
New York State Legislature tends to operate with the speed of a
glacier, the grace of a land-locked walrus and the restrained
dignity of a weasel on speed. Tuesday was no exception. The state
Senate passed a lobbying bill that the state Assembly would never
accept. The Assembly, meanwhile, was nowhere in sight and not
scheduled to appear in town before the new legislative session
begins next month. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
