<P>
   The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   CHANGERS OF OUR WORLD _ Not a week passes that most of us do not
encounter some attempt by the media to determine the most important
person, group or event of the 20th century, writes columnist Bill
Maxwell. ``While studying change in the 20th century, I realized,
obviously, that change has been the most important phenomenon
throughout history,'' he writes. ``Which group, then, has been
responsible for the world's most significant changes?'' His answer:
Young people. In this timely commentary, Maxwell offers a selection
of extraordinary individuals from several epochs who, while still
in their youth, contributed to the evolution of society.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA'S WAR OF HYPOCRISY. Twenty years ago, columnist James
Garcia and his girlfriend were decorating their Christmas tree in a
rented farmhouse in rural Indiana when they heard a knock at the
door. It was the police. Garcia was arrested for selling five grams
of cocaine to a friend-turned-police-informant and went to prison.
``I tell you all this because I want to talk about the hypocrisy of
America's `War on Drugs,''' Garcia writes. ``Over the course of the
past 20 years I have concluded that the government's escalating
battle to keep people from consuming illegal drugs has been a
miserable failure.'' Why? For one thing, America's ``War on Drugs''
demonizes an activity that our society also glorifies. ``Alcohol is
a drug,'' Garcia writes. '' ... Sell someone a beer and they'll
make a television sitcom glorifying your profession. Remember
`Cheers'? But sell someone a joint and you'll go to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTENTION EDITORS: One color slide showing The Castillo de San
Cristobal accompanies the following piece and IS AVAILABLE
ELECTRONICALLY. To receive the art by e-mail, please call The New
York Times Syndicate's Graphics Desk at (212) 499-3355.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO RICO: THE COMPLETE PACKAGE. From the New World's oldest
Spanish landmarks to water sports, natural attractions, luxury
accommodations, delicious dining and nightlife in the best Latin
tradition, Puerto Rico offers an exciting vacation choice for
Hispanic executives, writes Barbara Beckley in this feature from
Hispanic Business. For history buffs, the capital city of San Juan
is the story of Spain in the New World from beginning to end _ from
Christopher Columbus' landfall in 1493 through 1898, when Spain's
flag came down at the end of the Spanish-American War. Beckley
lists must-see tourist sights as well as the most popular nighttime
haunts. One color slide of The Castillo de San Cristobal, which is
mentioned in the story, is available electronically.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION NEEDED TO COMBAT ILLEGAL USE OF PEYOTE. Columnist
Karen Lincoln Michel is a member of the Native American Church of
Wisconsin. As part of her religious belief, she uses the peyote
cactus _ classified as a hallucinogenic drug in this country _ in
the manner that Catholics use sacramental wine. Mainstream America
misunderstands this way of worship. But there is another kind of
disregard toward Michel's beliefs. This time it is Native-Americans
themselves who are the perpetrators. Nonbelievers, mainly Navajo
teens, reportedly have been using peyote in the way some people
take recreational drugs. Many church leaders and their followers
blame themselves for failing to educate their own people about the
significance of peyote as a holy medicine.
</P>
<P>
   THE TROUBLE WITH STEREOTYPING. Columnist Akilah Monifa discuses
the race-based tipping incident that occurred on Oct. 23 in the
Thai Toni restaurant in Miami. An African-American couple had a
15-percent gratuity added to their bill, while a white couple did
not. The only posted notice of automatic gratuity applied to
parties of five or more. When the couple inquired about the bill,
the owner, Hiromi ``Toni'' Takarada, said it was added because
``blacks don't tip well.'' Bob Butterworth, Florida's attorney
general, filed a lawsuit against Takarada, which was settled for a
$15,000 fine. Takarada also agreed to sensitivity training for
himself and his staff. ``This was a case of differential treatment.
And for all who do not like the so-called `race card' being played,
I would query them as to what they think the reason was for the
differential treatment,'' Monifa writes.
</P>
