<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go around the world for Christmas feast
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the joy and good will that mark the spirit of Christmas
are the same the world over, the traditions and foods of holiday
feasts vary widely from country to country. In many regions, the
rituals and foods of Christmas are deeply embedded in the culture
and have their roots in centuries past.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, on the other hand, tend to invent their own style of
celebration, taking inspiration from anywhere and everywhere. We
are known to mix family favorites that go back generations with
anything that's new and different via the latest decree from Martha
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   While turkey, ham and roast beef are popular centerpieces for
the Christmas table, the American melting pot more often produces
an eclectic mix of holiday cuisines that varies from family to
family, neighborhood to neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian side of one family would expect nothing more than
fish on Christmas Eve, while the Polish cousins who may set an
extra place for the Holy Spirit will delight in almond soup,
pickled herring, sauerkraut and mushrooms. The neighbors from
Mexico will likely celebrate with Bacalao Vizcaina, a dry cod in
tomato sauce with potatoes, while the Russians across the street
will be feasting on suckling pig stuffed with buckwheat porridge,
pickled onions and cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   To learn how the world celebrates Christmas is to enrich your
own celebration. If you want to add an international touch to your
holiday table, a quick sleigh ride on the Internet can yield a
tantalizing array of ideas you may want to integrate into your own
family's tradition. Many sites also give fascinating information on
the origins of some Christmas traditions that you may have observed
for years _ like hanging stockings, drinking eggnog and sending
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you will find something from the country of your
forebears that can become part of your family's holiday at
</P>
<P>
   www.bconnex.net/(tilde)mbuchana/realms/christmas/. Click on
``Christmas Traditions Around the World'' and you'll find a list of
the Christmas rituals and foods of nearly 50 places, from Armenia
to Wales. Spend a bit of time here and you will surely pick up some
inspiration and learn something you didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in Greece, you will find loaves of christopsomo
(Christ bread) at the Christmas table. It is made in various shapes
and the crusts are engraved and decorated in some way that reflects
the family's profession.
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever wonder about the origin of the candy cane? At the
same site, click on ``Origins of Christmas Traditions'' and find
out that the ubiquitous candy was invented by a candymaker in
Indiana who incorporated into the candy several symbols for the
birth, ministry and death of Jesus Christ. The shape, for example,
represents the letter J and a shepherd's staff.
</P>
<P>
   And what about holly? Teutonic peoples decorated with holly,
which stays green even in the bitter cold of winter. In England,
the prickly holly is called ``he'' and the nonprickly ``she.''
Which type of holly is first brought into the house at
Christmastime determines who will rule the household through the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
   A similar site with additional countries is ``Santa's Favorites:
From North Pole to Down Under'' at www.santas.net and navigate to
Christmas around the world. Here you will find a lovely tradition
observed in Finland and other Scandinavian countries, in which a
sheaf of grain is tied to a tree for the birds. Many people refrain
from eating until the birds have had their own Christmas dinner.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER SITES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Christmas Customs Around the World'' at
</P>
<P>
   www.greeceny.com/ls/links/christmasAroundTheWorld.html has links
to sites about celebrations in Sweden, Spain, Mexico, Canada,
Belgium, Australia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At www.peders.com/christmas/christmas.html there is another
listing of dozens of countries to visit. Learn to say Merry
Christmas in 123 languages and find lyrics to a number of Christmas
carols.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Christmas stories and legends'' gives the origins of such
familiar customs as hanging mistletoe, giving gifts, Santa and
more. This is just one of the terrific links at
dtech.kennesaw.edu/web/christmas.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you don't find what you are looking for there, see
</P>
<P>
   bhsweb.norshore.wednet.edu/library/holiday-tradition-pg.html for
a complete world guide to Christmas traditions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.worldbook.com/fun/holidays/html/christ offers Christmas
recipes including Brazilian Holiday Punch, Russian Cranberry
Pudding,
</P>
<P>
   German Spaetzle, Christmas Poppy Seed Roll from Poland and Irish
Bread Pudding.
</P>
<P>
   There are also instructions on how to make a turnip candleholder
popular in Ireland, a guitar tree ornament from Spain, a Pere Noel
tree ornament popular in France and a pinwheel tree ornament from
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more recipes including the Poor Man's Cake and lutefisk
from the Norwegian Christmas table, see
</P>
<P>
   members.aol.com/acalendar/December/ChristmasEve.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And don't forget New Year's. Learn how the world celebrates at
www.mealtime.org/news/factnewyears.html
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Internet does Christmas traditions around the world
up right. By visiting some of these sites, you will be impressed by
the rich diversity of the world's celebrations and will no doubt
notice that the feeling of peace on earth and good will toward men
is what binds it all together.
</P>
<P>
   Plum Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes Cooking time: about 2 hours
Standing time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Plum Pudding, which is neither a pudding nor does it contain any
plums, has been a Christmas mainstay in Britain for centuries.
Originally it was called hackin because of its many ingredients
(sometimes reaching two dozen) that are finely chopped and folded
into a batter. It was given a more festive name in the 17th century
and made famous worldwide in Charles Dickens' ``A Christmas
Carol.'' Laced with rum or brandy, it is sometimes set aflame and
is always served with great ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Shortening for the mold
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter or margarine at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple cider or apple juice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded carrot
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup candied cherries, halved, or currants
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped candied pineapple, or currants
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   Brandied Cider Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup apple cider or apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brandy or apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a 1 1/2-quart steamed pudding mold or casserole
dish. In a medium-size bowl, stir together the flour, orange rind,
cinnamon, baking powder, ginger and cloves. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, with an electric mixer on medium, cream the
brown sugar and butter until light and fluffy, scraping side of
bowl often. Add the egg whites and beat well. Using a wooden spoon,
stir in 1/3 of the flour mixture, then 1/2 of the apple cider.
Repeat, then stir in the remaining flour mixture. Stir in the
raisins, carrot, cherries, pineapple and pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the batter evenly into the prepared mold. Cover mold with
foil; tie foil in place with string.
</P>
<P>
   Place mold on rack in a Dutch oven. Pour boiling water into the
Dutch oven until the water is halfway up the side of the mold.
Steam, covered, over low heat for 2 to 2 1/2 hours or until a
toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Place mold upright on a wire rack and let stand for 10 minutes.
Using a narrow metal spatula, loosen side of plum pudding from the
mold, then invert the pudding onto a serving plate. Serve warm with
Brandied Cider Sauce; top with vanilla ice cream if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Or, cover and refrigerate the pudding for up to a week. To
reheat, steam again for 1 hour or until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce: In a small saucepan, whisk together 3/4 cup apple
cider or apple juice, brown sugar and cornstarch. Bring to a boil
over moderate heat, whisking constantly. Cook for 2 minutes or
until the mixture is thickened, whisking constantly. Stir in brandy
(or apple juice) and butter or margarine.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with sauce): 324 calories, 6 grams protein, 9 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 26), 57 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 201 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Detail from www.bconnex.net/(tilde)mbuchana/realms/christmas/
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
