<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GIFTIDEA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A recipe for gift giving
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few Christmas gifts endure 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   I have one. There, in the honored position in my cookbook
cabinet (top shelf, first on the left). It has been treasured since
I received it in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   We started whining on Christmas Eve, my brothers and I. To the
point Mammaw broke down and said, ``OK, you can choose one present
to open tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew exactly which one.
</P>
<P>
   There were bigger, shinier presents there for me. But one flat,
square package hidden behind the tree had caught my eye. So I
tunneled through to retrieve it, and then tore the paper off in two
seconds flat.
</P>
<P>
   For a few long moments I gazed at the bright yellow cover with
the boy in a chef's hat triumphantly holding up a chocolate cake
while a red-ribboned girl with a hamburger in her hand looked on.
Their little brother had his hands on the frosting spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Then I cracked open ``Betty Crocker's New Boys and Girls
Cookbook,'' first to read the inscription from my mother, and then
to absorb this most unexpected gift page by page.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the hamburgers with the funny faces on the buns (made
with olives). I marveled at the pancakes ``branded'' with initials
and giggled at the bunny salad (pears for bodies, slivered almonds
for ears, cottage cheese mounds for tails). I couldn't wait to get
into the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, I spent countless hours following the
recipes from this book, starting with scrambled eggs and working my
way up to the pumpkin-shaped Halloween cake.
</P>
<P>
   I've packed the book with me to seven different cities. It has
survived everything from grease splatters to floodwaters. It now
requires careful handling (and tape on the binder), but just last
year I retrieved it to bake the enchanted castle cake for a
3-year-old's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   This Christmas, if you are looking for a gift that will endear
and endure, give a cookbook. What else can instruct, enrich and
entertain while helping to meet a most basic need (to eat)? Even
those who look rather than cook will enjoy the inspiration for
indulgent fantasies (ummmm, look at that chocolate mousse tart with
hazelnut cream).
</P>
<P>
   And the choices have never been greater.
</P>
<P>
   Are you buying for a young professional who's just moved into
his or her first apartment? Give them Marion Cunningham's
``Learning to Cook'' (Alfred A. Knopf, $29.95) to help them master
the basics. For those with a green thumb, Smith &AMP; Hawken's ``The
Gardeners' Community Cookbook'' (Workman, $19.95) shares recipes
from gardeners across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern culture buff won't want to miss ``A Gracious
Plenty'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $30), a collection of time-honored
recipes from community and historical cookbooks across the region.
</P>
<P>
   The international traveler (actual or armchair) will love
``Saveur Cooks Authentic French'' (Chronicle Books, $40) or Lynne
Rossetto Kasper's ``The Italian Country Table'' (Scribner, $35).
For the chocoholic on your list, give ``Chocolate Passion'' (Wiley,
$39.95).
</P>
<P>
   Today, we look at more than two dozen cookbooks ideal for the
gift-giving season. And from them we've created a Christmas menu
with recipes so good your guests will be begging for the recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could give them a whole cookbook instead.
</P>
<P>
   C H R I S T M A S M E N U
</P>
<P>
   Here are several recipes to prepare for your holiday meal:
</P>
<P>
   French Cheese Puffs (left) _ ``Saveur Cooks
</P>
<P>
   Authentic French''
</P>
<P>
   Baked Ham _ ``A Gracious Plenty''
</P>
<P>
   Marinated Beef Tenderloin _ ``Christmas 101''
</P>
<P>
   Wild Rice Salad With Walnuts and Apples _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gardeners' Community Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bean Bundles _ ``Cafe Boulud Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Golden Corn Pudding _ ``Betty Crocker's
</P>
<P>
   Best Loved Recipes''
</P>
<P>
   Scalloped Potatoes _ ``Julia and Jacques Cooking at Home''
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbird Cake _ ``The Magnolia Bakery Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Venetian Glazed Oranges _ ``James McNair's Favorites''
</P>
<P>
   Armagnac Truffles _ ``Simply Sensational Desserts''
</P>
<P>
   Long after the holidays are over and in years
</P>
<P>
   to come, friends and family will be recalling
</P>
<P>
   good times and glorious food prepared from
</P>
<P>
   cookbooks that cater to every taste and lifestyle
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
