<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX     12-15 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Figgy Pudding is a sure sign it's Christmas
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Margarett Kinton of Roswell, Ga., lost her recipe for
Figgy Pudding and wrote hoping for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters it wouldn't be Christmas without a steamed
pudding, even though they can be time-consuming to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   We were interested, then, to see that Rick Rodgers included a
lighter pudding in his new cookbook, ``Christmas 101'' (Broadway
Books, $15). Called Figgy Pudding Noel, it substitutes melted
butter for lard and goes together quickly. Like all steamed
puddings, however, it does require long stovetop steaming _ in this
case 2 hours. But even that can help bring welcome holiday warmth
on a cold, damp day.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers says that if you want to flambe the pudding with
additional brandy or cognac before serving, use apple juice to soak
the figs or the pudding will be too ``spirited.''
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Figgy Pudding Noel
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a 1 1/2- to 2-quart covered tube pudding mold,
don't worry. We tested this in a 2-quart flameproof earthenware
bowl that fit on a rack in a large covered stockpot for steaming.
We covered the bowl tightly with a double layer of aluminum foil
and it came out perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Butter and flour, for preparing the mold
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups fine, dry, freshly ground bread crumbs (about 12
slices sturdy, stale sandwich bread, crusts trimmed)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (about 8 ounces) finely chopped dried figs, preferably
Calimyrna
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cognac, brandy, liqueur (such as Triple Sec) or
apple juice
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter the inside of a 1 1/2- to 2-quart covered tube
steamed pudding mold. Dust with flour and tap out the excess.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, moisten the bread crumbs with the milk. In a
small bowl, combine the figs and cognac. Let both mixtures stand
for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk the eggs, sugar, melted butter, baking
powder and salt until well-combined. Stir in the soaked crumbs and
the soaked figs. Pour the batter into the prepared mold and cover
with the lid or aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Place a collapsible metal steamer or a rack in a large covered
kettle. Add enough water to come just beneath the steamer or rack
and bring to a full boil over high heat. Place the mold on the
steamer or rack and cover tightly. Reduce the heat to low. Simmer,
adding more boiling water as needed to keep a good head of steam,
until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean, about 2
hours. Let the pudding stand for 5 minutes while making the
topping.
</P>
<P>
   For the topping: In a chilled medium bowl, using a hand-held
electric mixer at high speed, beat the cream, confectioners' sugar
and vanilla until stiff. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Run a sharp knife around the inside of the mold to
release the pudding. Unmold the pudding onto a platter. Slice and
serve warm with a dollop of the whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with topping): 337 calories, 6 grams protein, 16
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 42), 45 grams carbohydrates,
159 milligrams cholesterol, 397 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Published recipes
