<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTIDEA-RECIPES1STTAKE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `By the book' never tasted so sumptuous
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the stockings have been hung by the chimney with care but the
Christmas menu is still up in the air, we've got some ideas for
you. From the cheese puffs to the truffles, each bite is a delight.
We found fancy French green beans and a down-home ham from the
South. Scalloped potatoes, wild rice salad and a traditional corn
pudding round out the buffet. It's a feast for friends and family
on such a special day.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   French Cheese Puffs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 dozen Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In Burgundy, these are considered the perfect hors d'oeuvre, and
we think they'll keep the crowd happy until the Christmas feast is
ready. Notes: Make sure eggs are large, not extra-large. And while
I made this the old-fashioned way, with a wooden spoon, I've been
given assurances a hand mixer would be fine for blending in the
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups grated Gruyere cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Combine butter, 1/2 cup milk and
1/2 cup water in medium saucepan over high heat. Season generously
with salt and pepper. Bring to a boil, and, when butter has melted,
remove pan from heat. Add flour all at once and stir vigorously
with a wooden spoon until mixture forms a thick dough and pulls
away from the sides of the pan, 1 to 2 minutes. Return pan to heat
for 1 minute, stirring constantly. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Let dough cool to room temperature, then beat in eggs, one at a
time, making sure each egg is completely incorporated into mixture
and dough is smooth after each addition. Dough should be thick,
shiny and smooth. Add 1 cup of the cheese and beat in until
well-combined.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon teaspoon-size mounds of dough on nonstick baking sheets,
leaving about 1 inch between them. Brush tops with remaining 1/4
cup milk, then sprinkle with remaining 1/2 cup cheese. Bake one
tray at a time in lower third of oven until puffs have doubled in
size and are golden, 20 to 25 minutes. Serve warm or at room
temperature. _ From: ``Saveur Cooks Authentic French'' (Chronicle
Books, $40)
</P>
<P>
   Per puff: 69 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 66), 3 grams carbohydrates, 48 milligrams
cholesterol, 55 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Baked Ham
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16-20 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3-3 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are plenty of places where you can pick up a fully
baked glazed ham that's ready to eat. But it's also easy _ and much
more econmomical _ to bake it yourself. And with this sherry-spiked
brown sugar-mustard glaze, the taste is sensational _ perfect for
the holiday buffet table. This makes a ton of glaze, but it's so
tasty you won't mind having the extras (it wouldn't be bad poured
over cream cheese to serve with crackers, either).
</P>
<P>
   1 10- to 12-pound whole or half bone-in ham, fully cooked or
partially cooked
</P>
<P>
   About 1 1/2 cups prepared mustard (we used Dijon)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sherry
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Rub the surface of the ham with
about 1/4 cup of the prepared mustard. Cover the ham with foil and
place it in a roasting pan. Bake for 20 minutes per pound (or until
internal temperature reaches 140 degrees for fully baked, or
155-160 degrees for partially baked).
</P>
<P>
   One hour before ham is done, remove it from the oven. Cover the
ham again with a light coating of mustard, about 1/4 cup, and
sprinkle with ground cloves. Combine 1 cup each prepared mustard,
brown sugar and sherry in a small bowl. Baste the ham with the
mustard mixture and cover with foil. Continue baking for 30
minutes. Remove foil, baste with sauce and dripping in the pan and
continue to bake, uncovered, until done. Let stand 10-15 minutes
before carving. (Leftover sauce may be placed in a gravy boat and
passed separately.) _ Adapted from ``A Gracious Plenty''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (based on 20 servings and 12-pound ham): 347
calories, 39 grams protein, 16 grams fat (percent calories from
fat, 42), 9 grams carbohydrates, 100 milligrams cholesterol, 2,719
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Marinated Beef Tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 2-4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A beef tenderloin always impresses. It is an indulgence, as it's
more expensive than a turkey or ham. The marinade here produces
succulent and delicious slices. If you'd like to save time, have
the butcher do the trimming. Our tester said that would cut
preparation time in half.
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-pound) beef tenderloin, untrimmed
</P>
<P>
   For the marinade:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hearty red wine, such as zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest and juice of 1 large orange
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, crushed under a knife
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon whole black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly milled black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Drain beef, rinse under cold running water and pat dry with
paper towels. (Do not be concerned about any odor _ it will
dissipate in a minute or so.) Using a sharp, thin-bladed knife,
trim away any fat, including the large lump at the wide end, and
discard. Pull and cut away the long, thin ``chain'' muscle that
runs the length of the tenderloin. (If you wish, trim away the fat
from the chain and reserve the meat for another use.)
</P>
<P>
   Following the natural muscle separation, cut away the large clod
of meat at the wide end and reserve for another use. At one end of
the meat, make an incision under the silver sinew covering the
meat. Slip the knife under the sinew, and pull and trim it away.
Work lengthwise down the tenderloin until it is completely free of
sinew and fat.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the thin ends of the meat underneath so the tenderloin is
the same thickness throughout its length, and tie with kitchen
string. Tie the roast crosswise at 2- to 3-inch intervals.
</P>
<P>
   To make the marinade: Whisk wine, zest, juice, soy sauce, 1/3
cup oil, vinegar, garlic, rosemary, thyme and peppercorns in a
large bowl to combine. Immerse the tenderloin in the marinade.
Cover and refrigerate, turning occasionally, for at least 2 hours
and up to 4 hours. Drain the tenderloin and let stand at room
temperature for 1 hour before roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in the center of the oven and preheat to 425
degrees. Rub the tenderloin with 1 tablespoon oil and season with
the salt and pepper. Place in a large roasting pan (no need to use
a roasting rack). Roast until an instant-read thermometer inserted
in the center of the roast reads 120 to 125 degrees for medium-rare
(the internal temperature of the meat will continue to rise about
10 degrees outside the oven), about 35 minutes. If serving hot, let
stand for 10 to 15 minutes before carving. For a buffet, cool at
least 30 minutes, then carve and serve within 2 hours. Or cool
completely, wrap tightly in foil and refrigerate for up to 2 days
before carving and serving at room temperature. _ From: ``Christmas
101'' by Rick Rodgers (Broadway Books, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 398 calories, 48 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 1 gram carbohydrates, 143
milligrams cholesterol, 617 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Green Bean Bundles
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a special presentation for green beans we borrowed from
``Cafe Boulud Cookbook'' (Scribner, $35). You can cook the beans
ahead of time, then wrap them in the strips of bacon. Just before
serving give them a quick saute.
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces haricots verts or wax beans, tipped
</P>
<P>
   2 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium saucepan of salted water to the boil, plunge the
beans into the water and cook just until they are tender, 3 to 5
minutes. Drain the beans in a colander and immediately run them
under very cold water to cool and set their color. When the beans
are cool, dry them well between layers of paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each piece of bacon crosswise in half and place the pieces
between sheets of plastic wrap. Using a meat tenderizer or the
bottom of a pot, pound the bacon gently to flatten and thin it (the
way you would veal scaloppine). Cut each of the pieces of bacon
crosswise in half again.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the beans into 8 packets. Working with one packet and one
piece of bacon at a time, lay the bacon out flat on a work surface,
place a bundle of beans close to one end of the bacon, sprinkle
with white pepper and roll up the bacon tightly around the beans.
When the bacon is wrapped tightly, you usually won't need to secure
the bundle with a toothpick. But if the bundles look a little
shaky, run a toothpick through each piece of bacon to hold it fast.
Warm the olive oil in a large saute pan or skillet over medium-low
heat. When the oil is hot, slip the bundles into the pan. Cook the
packets slowly, just until the bacon is crisp, without allowing the
beans to color.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, carefully lift the bundles out of the pan and serve
immediately, placing 2 bundles on each dinner plate or piling up a
pyramid of the bundles on a platter to serve family-style.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 68 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 76), 3 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 53 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Golden Corn Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 60-70 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here is a holiday classic from ``Betty Crocker's Best Loved
Recipes'' (Macmillan, $24.95). You'll find this easy and oh, so
popular.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frozen whole-kernel corn, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease 1-quart baking dish and set
aside. Mix the corn, margarine or butter, sugar, salt, pepper,
eggs, milk and cracker crumbs. Pour into the baking dish. Set
baking dish in pan of hot water 1 inch deep. Bake 60 to 70 minutes,
or until a knife inserted 1 inch from the edge comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 91 calories, 4 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 11 grams carbohydrates, 57 milligrams
cholesterol, 355 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Julia's Pommes de Terre
</P>
<P>
   Dauphinoise
</P>
<P>
   (Scalloped Potatoes)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These rich, crusty-topped potatoes are absolutely heavenly _ a
perfect accompaniment for any holiday meat dish. Do heed Julia's
advice to use the butter if you forgo the cream.
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk, or mixed milk and cream, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boiling potatoes, peeled and covered in water
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons butter for topping the potatoes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Put rack at the lower third level
and set a cookie sheet on it to catch boil-overs.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle 1/2 teaspoon salt on the chopped garlic and mash
together with the blade of a knife, to make a puree. Pour about
half the milk (or milk and cream mixture) into a buttered 8- to
10-cup flameproof gratin dish. Add garlic puree and the rest of the
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut potatoes crosswise, by hand or in a food processor, into
very thin slices ( 1/8 inch or less) _ do not rinse them again.
Spread them evenly in the gratin dish and pour in the remaining
milk. The liquid should come right to the top layer of potatoes _
add more milk or cream if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place the dish on a burner, bring to a slow boil, and cook for 2
to 3 minutes, until the liquid has thickened slightly. Scrape the
bottom gently with a wooden spoon to prevent scorching. Taste the
liquid and adjust the seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
