<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: and adjust the seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Turn off the heat and dot the gratin with a tablespoon or two of
butter, if you wish. Place the dish in the oven, on top of the
cookie sheet, and bake for 40 to 50 minutes, until the top is
nicely browned, most of the liquid has been absorbed and the
potatoes are tender all the way through when pierced with a knife.
If not served at once, keep warm in a turned-off oven or set over a
pan of simmering water.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (using milk and no optional butter): 155 calories, 5
grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 19), 27
grams carbohydrates, 13 milligrams cholesterol, 348 milligrams
sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Wild Rice Salad With Walnuts and Apples
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 50-60 minutes for
rice Standing time: 1-3 hours
</P>
<P>
   This makes a festive side dish that goes well with ham, beef or
chicken. It's also a substantial offering for vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   1 firm-fleshed apple, cored
</P>
<P>
   and cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped walnuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1 celery rib, trimmed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions, trimmed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced or pressed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cooked wild rice,
</P>
<P>
   at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the apples, walnuts, celery, green
onions, raisins and lemon zest. In a jar with a tight-fitting lid,
combine the lemon juice, garlic, olive oil, salt and pepper. Cap
the jar and shake vigorously to mix. Pour half the mixture over the
apple mixture and toss well. Place the cooked rice in a large bowl,
add the apple mixture and pour in the remaining lemon mixture. Toss
and set aside at room temperature for at least 1 hour or up to 3
hours. When ready to serve, sprinkle the parsley over the top. _
From ``The Gardener's Community Cookbook'' by Victoria Wise
(Workman Publishing, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 275 calories, 6 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 38 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 64 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Southern Sweet Potato Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes, plus baking potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Two Southern favorites combine to make one great bread for the
buffet. For a quick fix, go with the drop method. For a nicer look,
go with the cut biscuit method.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated or packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter, cut up, or chilled solid
shortening, plus extra for preparing pan, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cold mashed sweet potatoes or yams (9 ounces, or 2 medium
baked sweet potatoes or yams, peeled and mashed)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons milk, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk, optional
</P>
<P>
   Position rak in center of oven and preheat to 425 degrees.
Butter the cookie sheet or cover it with baking parchment.
</P>
<P>
   If working by hand, in a large mixing bowl, whisk together the
flour, baking powder, salt, sugar and nutmeg. Cut in the butter or
shortening by pinching it into the flour with your fingertips or
mixing it with a pastry blender or 2 cross-cutting table knives
until the mixture has small lumps about the size of peas. Stir in
the sweet potatoes with just enough milk to make a soft dough,
tossing the mixture only until the dough holds together.
</P>
<P>
   If using a food processor, pulse the dry ingredients and butter
until the mixture has lumps the size of peas, then add the sweet
potato and 2 to 3 tablespoons milk; pulse only until dough begins
to clump.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface. Add a few
drops more milk if the dough is still too dry, then pat it into a
rough ball.
</P>
<P>
   To make drop biscuits, scoop 10 to 12 equal portions of the
dough onto the baking sheet, placing them at least 1 inch apart.
</P>
<P>
   To make cut biscuits, pat the dough into a 6-by-8-inch rectangle
about 3/4 inch thick. Divide each side into 2-inch segments and use
a long-bladed knife to cut the dough into 12 pieces. Place them
about 1 inch apart on the baking sheet. If desired, use a pastry
brush to paint the biscuit tops with a little milk.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 15 minutes, until the biscuits rise and their golden
color is somewhat darker around the top edges. Cool on a wire rack;
serve warm. _ From: ``Family Baker'' by Susan G. Purdy (Broadway
Books, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per biscuit: 124 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 31), 19 grams carbohydrates, 11 milligrams
cholesterol, 372 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbird Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a Southern classic that's perfect for the Christmas
buffet. The banana-bread flavor is homey, the cream cheese frosting
divine.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups mashed, ripe bananas
</P>
<P>
   1 can (8 ounces) crushed pineapple in unsweetened juice, drained
(about 1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe cream cheese frosting (see below)
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely chopped or whole pecans for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (2 eight-ounce packages) of cream cheese, slightly
softened, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened slightly, cut into
small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   5 cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease and lightly flour two 9-inch
round cake pans and line the bottoms with waxed paper.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, sift together the flour, cinnamon, baking soda
and salt. Set aside. In another large bowl, beat the oil with the
sugar until smooth on medium speed of an electric mixer about 3
minutes. Add the eggs one at a time and beat until light, about 1
or 2 minutes. Add the vanilla extract. Add the bananas and the
pineapple. Add the dry ingredients in thirds, beating after each
addition until smooth. Stir in the pecans. Divide the batter
between the prepared pans and bake for 40-50 minutes or until a
cake tester inserted in the center of the cake comes out clean. Let
cakes cool in pans for 10 minutes. Remove from pans and cool
completely on wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   When cake has cooled, put the cream cheese frosting between the
layers, then ice the top and sides of the cake. Garnish with pecans
if desired.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: In a medium bowl, beat cream cheese and butter
until smooth on medium speed of an electric mixer. This should take
about 3 minutes. Then add the vanilla extract and gradually add the
sugar and beat until well-incorporated. _ From: ``The Magnolia
Bakery Cookbook'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 942 calories, 9 grams protein, 49 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 121 grams carbohydrates, 142
milligrams cholesterol, 404 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Venetian
</P>
<P>
   Glazed Oranges
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   These are absolutely lovely, especially with a couple of
chocolate truffles on the side. You want a fairly round, pretty
orange. I found peeling in a circular fashion worked best. You can
always carve the shape, but you don't want to lose too much of the
orange. You do want to lose all the bitter white pith, though. You
can add 1/4 cup cherry- or orange-flavored liqueur if desired.
</P>
<P>
   8 navel oranges or blood oranges
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint sprigs for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Using a vegetable peeler, remove enough of the zest (the colored
part of the peel with none of the bitter white pith) from the
oranges in long, narrow strips to measure 1/2 cup and set aside.
Cut away the peel and all the white membrane from the oranges,
keeping them as round as possible; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan or other nonreactive pot large enough to hold all
the oranges, combine 1 cup water with the sugar, orange and lemon
juices and orange zest strips. Place over medium-high heat and
bring to a gentle boil, then adjust the heat to maintain the gentle
boil and cook until the mixture is thickened to a thin syrup
consistency, 5 to 10 minutes. Add the oranges to the syrup and
continue cooking, turning the oranges frequently to coat evenly
with the syrup, for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the heat (and stir in the liqueur if using). Set
aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate the oranges for at least 2 hours or
overnight, turning them occasionally in the syrup. Return almost to
room temperature before serving. Spoon into a serving dish or
individual dishes and garnish with mint sprigs (if using). _ From:
``James McNair's Favorites'' (Chronicle Books, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 170 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 43 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Armagnac Truffles
</P>
<P>
   Makes 100 truffles
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5-7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   There's hardly a more direct chocolate experience than these
truffles. They can be messy and time consuming, but they're oh, so
worth it. When the chocolate begins to melt in your hands, stick it
in the freezer for 5 minutes. This recipe calls for a 1/4-inch
pastry tip, but I simply used a pastry bag without a tip. You can
also substitute cognac, rum, Grand Marnier or Kahlua for the
Armagnac.
</P>
<P>
   Truffles:
</P>
<P>
   17 ounces bittersweet chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 tablespoons Armagnac or cognac
</P>
<P>
   Coating:
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces bittersweet chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups unsweetened alkalized cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   For the truffles: Place the chopped chocolate and corn syrup in
a large bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, bring the heavy cream to a boil. Pour the
hot cream over the chocolate and let stand for 30 seconds. Whisk
until smooth. Whisk in the Armagnac or other liqueur. Let cool to
room temperature, stirring occasionally, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chocolate mixture in the refrigerator, stirring
occasionally, until it is the consistency of pudding, about 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Have a baking sheet lined with parchment paper ready. Fill a
pastry bag fitted with a 1/4-inch plain tip with the chilled
chocolate mixture. Pipe out 3/4-inch mounds of the mixture onto the
baking sheet. Chill the mounds for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the coating: Fill a medium saucepan 1/3 of the way with
water and bring to a simmer. Place the chocolate in a medium bowl
and place it over the simmering water. Stir until the chocolate is
completely melted.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cocoa powder in a shallow dish or pie pan. Using your
palms, roll the chocolate mounds into balls. Dip the truffles, one
at a time, into the melted chocolate. Remove the truffles with a
fork, allowing the excess chocolate to drip off. Using a fork,
immediately roll the truffles in the cocoa powder, coating them
completely. Store the truffles in an airtight container in a cool,
dry place for up to 2 weeks. _ From: ``Simply Sensational
Desserts'' by Francois Payard (Broadway Books, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 57 calories, 1 gram protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 77), 5 grams carbohydrates, 7 milligrams
cholesterol, 3 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
