<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Blind' sees the light and spices up sound a bit
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salacious and smug and with an ingratiating hook (that
``doot-doot-doot'' line) that quickly turned annoying as it
saturated radio, Third Eye Blind's 1997 breakthrough hit
``Semi-Charmed Life'' epitomizes the disposability of alternative
rock in the late 1990s. Sure, the song rocks, but in a generically
catchy way. When it came out, it seemed barely distinguishable from
other alterna-hits of the time, by equally faceless groups such as
matchbox 20 and the Goo Goo Dolls.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco quartet admirably tries to spice up its sound
on its sophomore release, adding a dash of AC/DC here (``1000
Julys''), a dollop of the Velvet Underground there (``Never Let You
Go''). Unfortunately, the references only show how much less
interesting Third Eye Blind is than its influences.
</P>
<P>
   The group does distinguish itself in one category: With his
perpetual sneer and dicey philosophies (``Wounded'' takes a
disturbingly cavalier attitude toward domestic violence) lead
vocalist and songwriter Stephan Jenkins is the most off-putting
frontman in rock right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue''
</P>
<P>
   Third Eye Blind. Elektra. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
