<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-DOOBIE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doobie Brothers: So easy to just listen to the music
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With funky Fu Manchu mustaches, muttonchop sideburns and hair
that hung toward the floor like pairs of shaggy drapes, the Doobie
Brothers are often framed in music history as the personification
of silly rock 'n' roll excess, real-life Muppets bouncing their
heads to twin drums and stoned-out guitar solos.
</P>
<P>
   While grooming may not have been the band's thing (at least not
in the beginning), it's not so easy to parody the Doobie's sound.
From the beer-chugging, chucka-chucka guitar rock of hits such as
``Listen to the Music'' to the jazzier, smooth Dewars sounds of
``You Belong to Me,'' the one-time bar band from Santa Cruz,
Calif., is perhaps one of the most under-appreciated groups in rock
history. No Hall of Fame nominations, no fawning young mimics (such
as Lenny Kravitz doing Jimi Hendrix), not even a ``Behind the
Music'' special on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the music of the Doobie Brothers, carefully archived in this
new boxed set from Rhino, is the essence of what rock 'n' roll is
(or was) supposed to be _ an emotional celebration of life from the
gut, whether it's longing for a lover, blowing your paycheck at a
bar with friends on Friday night or just ``feeling good to you and
you feeling good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some bloated boxed sets that are crammed with nuisances
like studio chit chat and drunken outtakes, this package is a
streamlined, chronological look at the band, its 14 musicians, 15
albums, and 16 Top 40 singles. Accompanied by an entertaining
booklet packed with flashback photos and album covers, it traces
the Doobie Brothers from their roots in roadhouse biker bars, where
they spewed out seductively slurry party hits such as ``Long Train
Runnin','' to the slick, adult contemporary sound that ultimately
put the group on smooth jazz playlists.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme dichotomy of the band's sound has never been more
apparent than in this package, where the jerky change in musical
direction seems to come overnight. (Actually, it happens between
track No. 5, April 1975's ``Take Me in Your Arms (Rock Me),'' and
track No. 10, March 1976's ``Takin' It to the Streets''). That was
when original lead singer Tom Johnston (1970-1975) had rocked down
the highway of excess just a little too long and was replaced by
pianist/vocalist Michael McDonald (1975-1981). This is one of those
rare moments where a split personality turned out for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Train
</P>
<P>
   Runnin': The Doobie Brothers 1970-2000''
</P>
<P>
   Rhino. 4-CD boxed set, 78 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
