r e BC-VIDEO-GORGEOUS16-COX     12-15 0194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GORGEOUS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beauty pageant spoof has some teeth to it
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drop Dead Gorgeous'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   A cheerfully mean-spirited spoof of beauty pageants, this movie
bombed at the box office. But it's a guilty-pleasure rental.
Kirsten Dunst is a wrong-side-of-the-tracks teen competing against
toothy, perfect and vicious Denise Richards in their small-town
beauty pageant. And, as the big show nears, contestants start to
turn up dead. The movie plays as a hybrid of 1975's ``Smile''and
the 1993 cable flick ``The Positively True Adventures of the
Alleged Texas Cheerleader-Murdering Mom.'' It stoops to obvious
sight gags and way-broad performances (especially from Kirstie
Alley as Richards' scheming mom). But the film's unevenness is
covered by the energetic young cast, and a couple of crack
performances from the adults, including Ellen Barkin as Dunst's
trailer-trash mom and scene-stealer Allison Janney as Barkin's best
pal.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
