<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX     12-15 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By John Blake, Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakin' not Stirred''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hughes. Sylvan House Music. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakin' not Stirred'' is the appropriate title for this
smooth-as-a-martini contemporary jazz album.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, a 43-year-old Canadian guitarist, blends a grab bag of
musical styles _ Latin rhythms, hip-hop grooves and traditional
jazz _ for his fifth, and most complete, solo album. He combines
the muscular chords of Wes Montgomery with the melodic
inventiveness of another one of his influences, Pat Metheny. But
his most distinctive musical quality, displayed on songs like the
snappy ``For You,'' is a playful exuberance that's amplified by his
love of Latin percussion. Hughes adds a muted trumpet and some
sparkling acoustic piano on songs such as ``There She Goes'' and
``Man About Town'' to give his album the feel of a smoky club.
</P>
<P>
   On songs such as the achingly romantic ``On Moonless Nights,''
Hughes shows he's as good with ballads as he is with uptempo songs.
This is an album that's as self-assured as its title.
</P>
<P>
   _John Blake
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Tha G Code''
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile. Cash Money/Universal Records. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Just as the mainstream finally catches on to Juvenile's 13
month-old second album ``400 Degreez,'' the New Orleans rapper
releases a third CD even early converts may take a minute to get.
The first single, ``U Understand,'' is instantly familiar because
it uses the title like a period, as did ``Ha,'' his infectious 1998
breakthrough single. But for the next six tracks it's as if usually
imaginative producer Mannie Fresh gets stuck in the '70s soul world
of wah-wah guitars and strings, eventually swallowing up Juvenile's
muscular voice. But the bounce that taught the 3 million people who
bought his last album to ``Back That Thang Up'' returns on the
unabashedly sexual ``Catch Your Cut'' and nothing goes splat after
that.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``White Sky''
</P>
<P>
   Archer Prewitt. Carrot Top. 9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Because it's outside the realm of MTV, VH1 and commercial radio,
many think independent, underground music must be difficult, noisy,
inept or socially unacceptable. Not true.
</P>
<P>
   Archer Prewitt, a member of Chicago's the Sea and Cake, delivers
sumptuous pop that cribs from such masterful tunesmiths as Burt
Bacharach, Todd Rundgren (in his ``Runt''/``Something/Anything''
mode) and Alex Chilton. Hardly the stuff to scare parents.
``Motorcycles'' and ``Shake'' might rock a bit, but not in a
lock-up-your-daughters way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raise on High'' kicks things off with a strolling guitar
jangle and crescendoing horns before the strings and a decidedly
un-rock clarinet line take over for the coda. ``Summer's End'' and
``Walking on the Farm'' conjure the pastoral in more than just
title. Enchanting details abound, and Prewitt's soft, sweet voice
sounds so intimate it seems he's letting you in on a secret.
</P>
<P>
   _John Blake, Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
