r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS16-COX     12-15 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Mini movie reviews
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' (PG-13) _ As high school movies go,
it barely makes a passing grade. Three high school kids (including
Katie Holmes of ``Dawson's Creek'') take their evil history teacher
hostage in her home and then try to figure out how to get out of
the mess they've created. It ends up being a wishy-washy remake of
1980's silly ``9 to 5.'' As the tied-up teach, Helen Mirren is
pretty good. Her young co-stars, however, fail to match her talent.
Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The General's Daughter'' (R) _ John Travolta stars as a
military investigator trying to search out the killer of a
general's daughter, a sexy lieutenant with kinky tastes. The movie
is really a morally dubious, deeply distasteful charade that
pretends to be in favor of women in the armed forces, but mainly it
luxuriates in shots of the murder victim staked naked to the
ground. The wasted cast includes Timothy Hutton and James Woods,
who plays a character whose gayness is telegraphed by the fact
that, gasp, he cooks and has candles at his house. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Red Violin'' (unrated) _ Francois Girard's
centuries-spanning saga is as florid and emotional as his
``Thirty-Two Short Works About Glenn Gould'' was spare and
sophisticated. The film follows the fortunes _ and, more often,
misfortunes _ of those who come in contact with the so-called Red
Violin, carved in 1681 by an Italian master. Holding the different
stories together is a present-day auction during which violin
expert Samuel L. Jackson struggles to unravel the instrument's
tragic secret. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Harmonists'' (R) _ Director Joseph Vilsmaier can't find
a way to make this rags-and-riches biopic of a Berlin singing group
persecuted by Nazis resonate beyond its own outline. And he makes
some groaner choices, like intercutting the illicit first kiss of
secret lovers with the bloody slugs of a boxing match. ``The
Harmonists'' is smartly acted, but it's by-the-numbers. Like the
group's own songs, it's charming, pleasant, but not memorable.
Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie write
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
