<HEADER>
A9608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WASHTEST-HNS &LR;      12-15 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHTEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     (EDS: Repeating for all needing)    U.S. AND RUSSIA WORK TO
PREVENT THE ULTIMATE Y2K PROBLEM    (For use by New York Times News
Service clients.)    By ERIC ROSENBERG    c.1999 Hearst
<TEXT>
Newspapers &LR;  &QC;  WASHINGTON _ A small group of U.S. and Russian
military officers won't be doing much New Year's Eve cork-popping
as the millennium arrives at midnight on Dec. 31. Instead, they
will be guarding against the end of the world. Their concern is the
ultimate Y2K catastrophe: Computer glitches causing the launch of
nuclear-tipped ballistic missiles. The U.S. and Russian governments
have been working to fix the potential Y2K glitches in their
missile systems and early warning defense equipment. And officials
from both countries stress that the likelihood of a mistaken Y2K
missile launch is extremely remote. But to reassure a jittery world
public and further cut the risk of a Y2K accident, the governments
of the two nuclear superpowers have set up a joint command center
at Peterson Air Force Base at Colorado Springs, Colo., to help
protect against such an accident. The year 2000 problem, commonly
called Y2K, refers to the possibility that computers programmed to
read only the last two digits of a year might interpret the change
from 1999 to 2000 as going from 1999 to 1900. This could cause the
computers to crash; interfering with utility services, banking,
aviation and any other sector that relies computers. While most
essential civilian and military computers in the United States have
been deemed ``Y2K-compliant,'' other countries, including Russia,
are having difficulties. In fact, the State Department is so
worried about computer troubles there and in three former Soviet
republics that it is withdrawing hundreds of employees through the
New Year period. But the ultimate Y2K mishap would be nuclear war.
That's why, for three weeks starting Dec. 22, some 33 Russian and
U.S. military officers will stand around-the-clock vigils over
consoles and computer screens that would alert them to missile
launches around most of the world. Their information will be
collected from a network of radars and satellites operated by the
nearby Cheyenne Mountain Operations Center of the U.S. Space
Command. During the Cold War's superpower standoff, the Cheyenne
Mountain center was the headquarters of U.S. efforts to detect any
Soviet missile attack. The mission of the Y2K command post, dubbed
the Center for Year 2000 Strategic Stability, isn't to detect a
missile attack against the United States. Instead, it is designed
to reassure Moscow that U.S. missiles aren't attacking Russia _ if
that's what aging Soviet-era military computers incorrectly
indicate because of a Y2K computer glitch. That mistaken perception
could prove deadly because Russian policy calls for launching a
nuclear counter-strike if Moscow believes it is under nuclear
attack. The mission of the Y2K command center is designed to
protect against that theoretic possibility. Even if Moscow's
computers failed and incorrectly indicated an U.S. attack was
underway, Russians in the Y2K command center eyeing the consoles
could tell the Kremlin that U.S. radar and satellite pictures
showed no such attack. Thus, there would be no need for retaliatory
strikes against the United States. ``''We will prevent that from
occurring,'' said Air Force Lt. Col. Jon Wicklund, the head of the
Y2K center. ``We will be sitting side-by-side with our Russian
counterparts and they'll be viewing the U.S. missile information.
They will have that view that says a launch is not occurring.''
Three-man crews of Russian officers, who will be in direct contact
with their leadership back in Moscow via a secure phone link, will
stand watch with three-man U.S. crews. The three-man teams will
rotate so that the center is on alert 24 hours a day. Each crew
will include a linguist to enable team members to converse. The
Russians, many of whom are likely to be culled from Russia's
strategic rocket force, an elite branch of the Russian military,
are due to arrive at the Air Force facility on Dec. 21 and begin
training on the equipment Dec. 23. The center is expected to be up
and running no later than Dec. 30. The center also has a certain
public relations mission. ``The bottom line is that it's important
for the U.S and Russia to show the rest of the world that former
Cold War adversaries can come together and work as a team,'' said
Wicklund. The warm relations only extend so far. Partly for
security reasons, the Russians won't be allowed inside Cheyenne
Mountain, the heart of the U.S. missile-warning network, buried
1,800 feet underneath the Front Range of the Rocky Mountains. In an
assessment last year of Russia's potential Y2K problems, the
Pentagon singled out for particular concern the Russian early
warning system designed to detect incoming missiles. But even
before Y2K worries took hold, U.S. officials were worried about the
capability of Russia's missile defense system. In 1995, Russia
initially interpreted the launch of a Norwegian scientific rocket
as the onset of an U.S. nuclear attack. President Boris Yeltsin
activated his ``nuclear briefcase'' in the first stages of
preparation to launch a retaliatory strike before the Russian armed
forces realized its mistake. Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a leading
foreign policy spokesman in the Senate, said the incident
underscored that ``Russian early-warning capabilities continue to
deteriorate, and this deterioration will be compounded by the
transition to the year 2000.'' Should a glitch occur during the New
Year period, ``we want them to understand that their problems are
Y2K-related and not a result of U.S. hostile action for which they
need to respond.'' The Y2K center also is designed to make up for
problems in the ``hotline'' communications links between Moscow and
Washington. The hotlines give military and political leaders
immediate communications if needed, particularly in time of nuclear
crisis. As recently as October, six of seven such links failed Y2K
tests, according to Edward Warner, assistant secretary of defense
for strategy and threat reduction, who said the problems are
believed to be on the Russian side. ``Assured communications
between U.S. and Russian leaders is a priority at all times, and of
particular concern over the millennium date change,`` Warner
said.Because computer scientists warn that Y2K problems might take
several weeks to materialize, the Y2K center and the U.S.-Russian
cooperation will extend through mid-January. ``Not all of the data
corruption that may be engendered by Y2K is going to manifest
itself on New Year's Day,'' said John Pike, a military expert with
the Federation of American Scientists here. ``Some of this stuff
may take several weeks to propagate through the system.'' Russian
officials maintain that any Y2K concerns are dramatically
overstated. Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Bulgak said the Y2K
problem would not threaten his country's nuclear missiles or its
nuclear power stations.The U.S. and Russia last year began
discussions to set up the Y2K center but temporarily broke off
talks after NATO bombed Serbia, a Russian ally, during the conflict
in Kosovo. To guard against any future computer glitches or
potentially deadly mistakes like the 1995 incident, the two
countries are planning to open a permanent joint missile warning
center in Moscow next year. As far as the U.S. nuclear arsenal is
concerned, Pentagon officials say the chances are ``extremely
remote'' that there could be an accidental launch caused by
military computers confused about the date change. The White House,
in its final report on the readiness of U.S. computers, debunked
worries about a misfired nuclear missile. ``Y2K problems will not
cause nuclear weapons to launch themselves,`` it said. ``Nuclear
weapons launch requires human intervention.``Computers are the
backbone of the U.S. military, arrayed on key weapons like nuclear
missiles, tanks, jets and rocket launchers. In fact, the Pentagon
is the largest user of computer systems in the world. In
preparation for Y2K, the Pentagon has sunk $3.7 billion in upgrades
to deal with the problem. The U.S. military has 2,107 so-called
``mission critical'' systems _ those considered essential for
waging war _ deployed on weaponry and command posts. Defense
Secretary William Cohen vowed that all will be ``Y2K compliant'' by
the New Year. Lt. Col. Gary Warren, the Y2K program manager for the
Air Force's Space Command, which is responsible for maintaining
U.S. missile-detection radars and satellites, said the service has
worked three years on updating its computers. ``We've checked them,
we've rechecked them. They're ready,'' Warren said.  &UR; --- &QL;  &LR;  (Eric
Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail address
eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</TEXT>
</BODY>
