 LEWIS LAPHAM 
 The Carlyle Hotel dining room  
 Madison Avenue at 76th Street 
 &HT;    A high-ceilinged room decorated with the signs of serious money:
English hunting scenes by Fores on walls faced with brown velvet,
fresh flowers (Casablanca lilies and curly willow) against a
background of old botany (the engravings by Redoute), the pattern
of the breakfast china matched to the chintz on the center
banquette, the coffee priced at $5, the poached eggs on smoked
salmon at $22.50. Rising from the table near the door, _ Robert
Rubin, recently resigned as the secretary of the Treasury, and
Richard Holbrooke, newly confirmed as the ambassador to the United
Nations, gather their papers and close their briefcases. They nod
to people in remote corners of the room, and as they walk out into
the lobby, the maitre d'hotel bows to them with a grateful smile.
 &HT;     (Lewis Lapham is the editor of Harper's Magazine and the
author, most recently, of ``Lapham's Rules of Influence.'')
 &HT;    
 -0- 
 CHANG-RAE LEE  
 Le Monde gourmet deli, 38 West 48th Street 
 &HT;    Seung-lae Lee, the proprietor, presides over his short-order
cooks cracking eggs onto the griddle, two by two.
 &HT;    ``Pretty busy this morning,'' he says.
 &HT;    And so it is.
 &HT;    Customers line the front counter, waiting for their breakfast
sandwich or bagel to be wrapped in foil and passed over the
gleaming glass case. They stand, watching the action, with an
uncommon New York patience, for they know it'll be just another
minute. Behind the counter, the talk is flying forth in Spanglish
and English and Koreanese. Lee's wife is shouting, ``Yo, amigo,''
and ``Yes, ma'am,'' and ''Coffee, coffee, ha-rha-buh-gee (grandpa
in Korean)?'' her addresses wholly indiscriminate and sweet.
 &HT;    Somehow, everyone understands.
 &HT;     (Chang-rae Lee is the author, most recently, of ``A Gesture
Life,'' a novel.) 
 -0- 
 ELEANOR RANDOLPH  
 Astor Place 
 &HT;    In his compact green newsstand, Jerry DeLakas is surrounded by a
panorama of urgent headlines. ``VIRUS SCARE GROWS'' shouts The
Daily News' Page One _ mosquitoes have caused an outbreak of
``encephalitis,'' three deaths in a city of 7 million people.
Newsday features a postman with bug spray in his mailbag.
 &HT;    DeLakas smokes, a hazard made worse by his habit of storing his
burning cigarette in the middle of a stack of magazines.
 &HT;    ``My truck stop there,'' a man rushes up. ``No make me get
ticket!'' He pays for a copy of the Spanish daily El Diario and
then begins running back to the street.
 &HT;    Next, a lean man darts into the newsstand, grabs The New York
Times, The New York Post and The Wall Street Journal. He leaves a
small wad of bills. Engrossed in his cell phone, he waves off the
change. Only once does he slow down _ to explain to me that he
cannot stop.
 &HT;     (Eleanor Randolph is a member of the editorial board of The New
York Times.) 
 -0- 
 ALEX WITCHEL 
 Grand Central Terminal 
 &HT;    Her flowered skirt sways above her ankles, like curtains in a
breeze. She makes her way intently around the circular beacon that
is the Information Booth in Grand Central Terminal, oblivious to
the hordes of men rampaging off the escalators, wielding briefcases
big and battered. She takes some schedules, one of each _ Westport,
Greenwich, Tuckahoe _ as if choosing fruit. She passes through the
crowd, puts the schedules carefully inside her shoulder bag. Now
knowing how to get to every New York suburb at any hour of the day,
she turns her back and heads toward the city subway.
 &HT;     (Alex Witchel reports on style for The New York Times.) 
 -0- 
 CHARLES SIEBERT  
 Brooklyn Bridge  
 &HT;    A well-heeled woman stops to wrestle a homeless man, who just
spilled a trash can onto the promenade. She thrashes him with her
briefcase, picks up the scattered newspapers and drops them back
into the can as the man canes his way toward the next one. In the
mounting heat, all the people grimace; the traffic is dense. The
sun slides into view. From unseen roadway scaffoldings below, the
jackhammers whine.
 &HT;     (Charles Siebert is the author of the forthcoming ``Angus,'' a
memoir of a dying dog.) 
 -0- 
 JOHN BERENDT 
 Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn 
 &HT;    In the shadow of an imposing bronze statue of the goddess
Minerva, Charles Higgins, the inventor of India ink, slumbers in a
heavy, banklike mausoleum. Behind him, the remains of the musician
Leonard Bernstein lie under a simple marker set flush into the
ground. Five small stones have been placed on it. Half a million
people are buried in this cemetery, New York's ``Garden City of the
Dead.'' Five more are lowered into it every day. About 135
groundskeepers maintain these 478 lush acres, but all I know is not
a single living soul came into view during the minute I stood
watch.
 &HT;     (John Berendt is the author of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good
and Evil.'') 
 -0- 
 HARVEY SHAPIRO 
 Brooklyn Promenade 
 &HT;    Directly beneath me, commuter traffic
 &HT;    of the Brooklyn-Queens Expressway.
 &HT;    Across that, on the Brooklyn docks
 &HT;    one lone forklift tractor, loaded with steel rods,
 &HT;    jockeying back and forth
 &HT;    before the Strober Bros. Building Supply Depot.
 &HT;    Across the water, dimly descried,
 &HT;    a perky yellow Staten Island Ferry.
 &HT;    The buildings pulsing in their various
 &HT;    shades of white,
 &HT;    these mighty presences,
 &HT;    dominate our day
 &HT;    as if they had been fixed there forever.
 &HT;    They stand before us
 &HT;    like tribal gods meting out success and unsuccess _
 &HT;    all that we have to lift our eyes to.
 &HT;     (Harvey Shapiro is the author, most recently, of ``Selected
Poems.'') 
 -0- 
 &HT;    
 SUSAN MINOT  
 West Ninth Street  
 &HT;    In the lobby, a fan is going on the battered desk. No doorman. A
sign: ``They are working on the Elevator. Out of order.'' I step
outside. A building down the street was the model (built in a
Hollywood studio) for ``Rear Window,'' Hitchcock's ode to
voyeurism. Now the clock on the brick tower of the library, which
used to be a courthouse, says 9:09. Walking toward me with a brisk
pace is the shrink I used to see, someone who has peered in the
window of many people's dramas and imbroglios and minutiae, mine
included. Now she races by, not meeting my eye.
 &HT;     (Susan Minot is the author of ``Monkeys'' and, most recently,
``Evening.'') 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 DARCY FREY  
 West 72nd Street  
 &HT;    LOCATION: Small, well appointed office, decorated with sprawling
vines and South American artifacts in an apartment building. Two
men face each other in leather armchairs. On an ottoman between
them sits a tape recorder.
 &HT;    PATIENT: Last night I had all sorts of performance-anxiety
dreams.
 &HT;    ANALYST: Such as?
 &HT;    P: Well, I dreamt I was in some sort of stage production and I
couldn't remember any of my lines.
 &HT;    A: Yes?
 &HT;    P: And the woman I was doing the scene with, she couldn't
remember any of her lines either. (THROUGH THE OPEN WINDOW COMES
THE SQUEAL OF TRUCK BRAKES.) To be honest, I think it's about my
doubts and anxieties about being in therapy.
 &HT;    A: Let's stay with the dream for a moment. Where does the dream
take place?
 &HT;    P: I can't remember.
 &HT;    A: And the woman -- who was she?
 &HT;    (THE PIERCING CRY OF A CAR ALARM IS HEARD.)
 &HT;    P: I can't remember.
 &HT;    A: Well, what did she look like?
 &HT;    P: I can't remember.
 &HT;    A: Well, was she someone you were romantically involved with?
 &HT;    (A JACKHAMMER STARTS UP. ANALYST AND PATIENT RAISE THEIR
VOICES.)
 &HT;    P: No, she was someone I'd been paired with artificially.
 &HT;    A: And why do you think this is about therapy?
 &HT;    P: Well, talk about an artificial situation!
 &HT;     (Darcy Frey is the author of ``The Last Shot.'') 
 -0- 
 PHILLIP LOPATE  
 Carroll Park, Brooklyn  
 &HT;    Four hefty Italian-American moms sit at the picnic benches,
drinking iced espressos while their kids dash around. A father,
middle-aged like me, tenderly picks up his boy to take him to the
bathroom in the dignified stone park house. Another father lifts
his tan-frocked daughter up to grab the parallel bars, then says,
``play with something else,'' and heads for a bench. He's teaching
her ``independence,'' meanwhile grabbing a few private moments. She
skulks over the standard-issue climbing bars, probably thinking,
Why do adults insist on pretending it's fun to play by yourself?
 &HT;     (Phillip Lopate is the editor of ``The Art of the Essay,'' an
annual anthology.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     All c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
