<SLUG> BC-WOM-COACHES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA PLAYERS LEARN THE COACHING TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Jennifer Rizzotti, who got married in July on
one of her days off from playing basketball with the Houston
Comets, could now be (1) enjoying her honeymoon, (2) looking for a
house, or (3) working out at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was going to be my down time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rizzotti, dressed in black and red sweats, spends her
days sitting in an office at the University of Hartford, watching
tapes of the next opponent that will face the Hawks, or holding
practices with the team. With her team.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Rizzotti's life has been through as many
unpredictable moves as she and her teammates at UConn used to dish
out to their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago Rizzotti was in her third year as starting point
guard for the New England Blizzard in the American Basketball
League. Then, the week before Christmas, the Blizzard folded when
the ABL disbanded, and Rizzotti was unemployed. Five months later,
she was drafted by the other women's league, the WNBA, and was sent
to Texas to join the Houston Comets. During the season, Rizzotti
got married.
</P>
<P>
   But the honeymoon is still on hold as Rizzotti's life kept
unfolding. After the season, she had an offer not to play
basketball, but to direct it, and now she is Hartford's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Including Rizzotti, three current or former WNBA players are
with America East programs _ Cindy Blodgett, of the Sacramehto
Monarchs, is an assistant coach at Boston University, and Nicole
Andres, who played with the Charlotte Sting for two years, is at
the University of Vermont. Six other WNBA players coach at college
teams over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But Rizzotti stands out among them for being the only head
coach, and, at 25, for being the youngest of any Division 1 coach.
</P>
<P>
   The progession of girls playing basketball used to be much more
basic _ the path went from AAU and high school teams, then on to
college. That was it, in America. If the women still wanted to
play, they had to do it Europe. Later, they might come back and
coach a college team.
</P>
<P>
   Now the women can stay in this country and play for a WNBA team.
Some of them are even joining college staffs before their playing
days are over, thanks to the WNBA summer season that doesn't
conflict with the college schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And universities realize that in addition to the talent the
women offer, their well-known names can help put fans in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is putting her mark on the image of the university,'' said
athletic director Pat Meiser-McKnett. ``I've had an eagle eye on
her since she was in high school,'' said Meiser-McKnett, associate
AD at UConn before coming to Hartford seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people attended the press conference to announce
Rizzotti's appointment this September, and 759 fans attended the
school's home opener _ more than twice the average attendance (330)
last year. In addition, the school had 26 season ticketholders last
year; this year there are 100.
</P>
<P>
   The name-attraction is not lost on Rizzotti. The 5-foot-6 point
guard who grew up in New Fairfield, Conn., played on UConn's
1994-95 undefeated team that went on to win the national
championship. The next year. Rizzotti was named Associated Press
Player of the Year. However, Rizzotti said she's also aware that
the marquee value could be short term after her team went 8-19 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the fans to come, and if they want to see me coach,
that's great,'' she said. ``But I think that you've got to find a
way to keep them here. People aren't going to come back game after
game for the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzotti said it has always been a goal of hers to coach . . .
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought about getting into it, and how I would do
things, but I didn't think I was going to do it this year,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And she never considered being an assistant, which is the usual
way to enter the career. No, there would be no second-banana job
for the point guard. If she could orchestrate a team on the court,
she figured, she could do it off the court, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if I would have to (be an assistant), but I knew
that I didn't want to,'' she said. ``I wanted to be in charge,
totally. I wanted to do things my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzotti said she and her assistants, Mimi Walters and Brian
Mik, work well together on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to be the one that made the decisions, that did
all the talking in practice, that got the kids to play the way I
wanted to,'' she said. ``And you can't do that as an assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison Macca, the co-captain of the Hartford Hawks who grew up
in Southington, Conn., was a senior in high school when Rizzotti
was a senior at UConn.
</P>
<P>
   When Macca heard in the fall who was going to be her coach, she
said she was ``shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited, but shocked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Macca said she's still excited, even though Rizzotti is hard
driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has high expectations, but I think that's good for us,
especially after coming off last year,'' Macca said, adding that
the new coach has added to the prestige of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's more positive and excited to be out there, and
people around campus know us more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzotti, who will be back at her job with the WNBA when
Hartford is in the height of its recruiting time next summer,
refused to speculate on her future, but denied that she feels like
a short-timer in her coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not taking this lightly at all,'' said Rizzotti, who has
already signed one recruit for next year. ``Whatever I do, I will
coach this season as if I were to coach here forever. That's the
only way you can be good at something. So I'm recruiting hard,
trying to get good players in here, trying to raise the standards
of the kids that are already here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Blodgett, also a WNBA player and also a college star, has
landed a job at college, too, as as assistant at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Blodgett, who was drafted by the Cleveland Rockers in the WNBA
the year after she graduated from the University of Maine, said she
has had to adjust to giving the orders instead of taking them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I still struggle with that from time to time,'' she
said. ``I'm not a yeller to begin with, so I would never see myself
as yelling at people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's trying to find what's best for me, like how to get my
point across,'' Blodgett said. ``So it's still kind of very new,
and I try to pay attention to, like, facial expressions, things
that kids are going to look at, and you've never thought of before.
I've been on the other end, and I've seen how coaches react after
I've done something.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Margaret McKeon, who is also in her first year at BU,
had previously coached at George Washington University, and became
familiar with Blodgett's college history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cindy was pretty much well-known all over the country as a
high school player,'' McKeon said. ``So I knew quite a bit about
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Blodgett helped lead her high school in Maine to four state
championships, then helped the university win four conference
tournaments and make four trips to the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Cindy I felt we needed someone who had a presence of
winning, knew about the league, and was very successful, and that
the players could relate to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blodgett's experience is helpful, and so is her age, McKeon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can communicate with the kids and they can relate, because
a lot of kids that are in my program have seen her play and they
know Cindy is very special,'' MeKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more importantly, Blodgett can offer them a look beyond
college into their basketball careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's young and playing in the WNBA,'' said Annie Tomasini, a
sophomore on the team. ``As a college player, that's the next stop
that you think of.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she played in our conference, so it makes you think dreams
can come true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
