<SLUG> BC-MONROE-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADCLIFFE GETS SEVERAL BOOKS ONCE OWNED BY MARILYN MONROE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bodacious, blond, and blowing the inevitable lipsticked kiss,
Marilyn Monroe has always been Hollywood's ultimate sex icon. But
the curvy actress apparently fancied more than just men and fame.
</P>
<P>
   She collected literature. Everything from the selected works of
Spanish poet Federico Garcia Lorca to the collected works of
Sigmund Freud.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 of Monroe's books were auctioned off for thousands
of dollars with much of the rest of her remaining property in New
York in October. And now, in a move that could encourage a deeper
understanding of a cultural figure known more for child-like
innocence than intellectual striving, an anonymous donor has
presented a collection of Monroe's books by women authors to the
Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so interesting is that so many people think of Marilyn
Monroe merely as a sexual object,'' said Barbara Haber, book
curator at Radcliffe's Schlesinger Library, which has the world's
largest collection of women's history books. ``It indicates that
Marilyn had the side to her that aspired to be an educated person,
a person who dealt with ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   That side was known to those who have written about Monroe,
including biographer Carl Rollyson, author of ``Marilyn Monroe: A
Life of the Actress'' and an English professor at the City
University of New York's Baruch College. ``Actually, she read quite
a bit . . . in spurts and starts. She was self-educated. And like
many self-educated people, she was ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   The five works given to Harvard by a Boston woman who purchased
them for $10,000 are timeworn with dusty spines, crumpled pages and
tattered jackets. The books _ Willa Cather's ``My Antonia'' and
``Lucy Gayheart,'' Carson McCullers's ``The Ballad of the Sad
Cafe,'' Grace Paley's ``The Little Disturbances of Man,'' and ``The
Portable Dorothy Parker'' _ are in no better shape than the
standard fare at any used bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   While the books bring no specific evidence with them of what
Monroe might have thought of them, or even if she specifically read
each, one of the five, Cathers' ``Lucy Gayheart,'' came with a note
from a New York friend of Monroe's. ``This is the book I spoke to
you about and think you might like,'' scribbled Ralph Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many of the themes the books explore, according to
academics and biographers of the actress, seem to fit the epic
sadness and frustration that tortured Monroe before she died from
an overdose of sleeping pills at age 36.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Parker's poems and stories also appear to reflect the
world of Monroe. Titles of some of the powerful poems in her
collected work include ``The Same to Me are Somber Days and Gay,''
``The Ladies Men Admire I've Heard,'' and ``There Was a Rose That
Faded Young.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Monroe was an orphan who was farmed out to 12 sets
of foster parents, dropped out of high school and married for the
first time at age 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cather's work about a woman trying to construct an identity
has its natural appeal,'' said Rollyson. ``Marilyn Monroe really
identified with victims, people who were striving to better
themselves. Some of those books carry those scenes. She was also
drawn to other scenes in these books, which feature ambitious and
successful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Another source of Monroe's literary interests, often obscured by
her famous marriage to baseball star Joe DiMaggio likely came from
her marriage to Arthur Miller, the Pulitzer Prize-winning
playwright, Rollyson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was influenced by the many people she met and especially
by her marriage to Miller,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe died Aug. 5, 1962. She left all her belongings, including
gowns, scripts, furniture, jewelry, furs, photographs, and awards
to her acting coach and mentor, Lee Strasberg. He died in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The collection had been in storage accumulating layers of dust
for four decades until October. Christie's auction house in New
York put everything from Monroe's oven mittens to a diamond ring
given to her by DiMaggio up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day auction of some 1,000 of her belongings netted more
than $13 million. The highest bid came for the dress Monroe wore
when she sang ``Happy Birthday'' to President Kennedy at New York's
Madison Square Garden in 1962. The snug dress pulled in $1.3
million from a store called `` Gotta Have It!''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the books from Monroe's library, which featured first
editions including Jack Kerouac's ``On the Road'' and French
existentialist Albert Camus' ``The Fall,'' were listed for prices
between $800 and $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   But once the bidding got going, the prices soared. The anonymous
donor, for example, originally intended to buy two of Monroe's
cookbooks, ``The Fannie Farmer Cook Book'' and ``The Joy of
Cooking.'' But when the starting price for the two books jumped
from about $2,000 to $37,000, according to Haber, the woman set her
sights on the women's books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
