<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO: MAKING WAVES AT EEOC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS BOSTON GLOBE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ida L. Castro was growing up in New York and Puerto Rico,
her father took her argumentative behavior as a sign: He thought it
showed a natural inclination toward law.
</P>
<P>
   Papa was right.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, the chairwoman of the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, has spent much of her 20-year legal career making
waves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Castro was appointed director of the Office of Workers'
Compensation Programs, where she managed a 1,500-member staff. Two
years later, she became acting director of the Women's Bureau at
the US Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, who is in her 40s, was sworn in as chairwoman of the
EEOC in October 1998, the first Hispanic woman to serve in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Castro spent her first year concentrating on bolstering the once
ailing and cash-strapped federal agency. She has hired 450 new
staff, including paralegals, mediators, attorneys, and
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, these new hires have helped to reduce the
agency's 110,000-case backlog to 40,000. In addition, the EEOC has
collected $290 million in damages, settlements, and back wages over
the last year, up from $34 million in 1997 and the highest amount
in its 35-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Having received a $37 million budget increase for fiscal 1999,
Castro now manages an agency with 2,800 employees and a $282
million budget.
</P>
<P>
   The agency now categorizes cases according to importance. Prior
policy required that every charge be examined. These days, the most
egregious cases _ now 65 percent of the caseload _ are targeted for
litigation or referred to mediation. Complaints filed after the
statute of limitations expires are dismissed, and cases brought
under the wrong federal statute are referred to the appropriate
agency.
</P>
<P>
   One result, say some attorneys: Cases that used to take years to
resolve are now being seen, reviewed, and resolved within months,
with the agency's final recommendations or findings coming within
90 days of the first filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had 110,000 cases, the policy was to investigate each
and every one, whether or not it had merit,'' said Castro, who was
in Boston Thursday to speak at a luncheon sponsored by the
Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every charge was investigated, hence the backlog. Now, we
prioritize.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Griffin, executive director of the Disability Law
Center in Boston, which litigates cases under the Americans with
Disabilities Act, described Castro as a ``breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has made a significant impact,'' Griffin said. ``She has
supported more outreach into communities. She has gotten attorneys
out into the field, and she is doing much more litigation. The
agency seems much more proactive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, where the EEOC office once relied on agency lawyers
from New York to prosecute local cases, Castro hired two lawyers
and a mediator. The agency also provides $1.4 million to the MCAD,
the EEOC's local partner.
</P>
<P>
   Under Castro, regional officers were required to develop plans
for tackling their backlogs through mediation, case dismissal, or
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Boston lawyer Dahlia Rudavsky of Messing &AMP; Rudavsky said she had
had mixed experiences with the EEOC. ``Some of the investigators
were diligent, and others were not,'' she said. ``But my most
recent contact with the new lawyers has been very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC was formed in 1964 to protect workers from
discrimination on the job. These days, the fastest-growing type of
claim involves employer retaliation against workers who have
brought workplace harassment or discrimination claims. Such cases,
Castro said, have increased from 7,900 in 1991 to 18,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said most employers have no idea that firing a person for
filing a claim with the agency, denying promotions, or ignoring and
condoning ill treatment of a claimant by co-workers could land them
in court.
</P>
<P>
   Most employees, she said, find the decision to file a complaint
with the agency a difficult one, requiring a lot of courage.
``People fear being branded. They fear retaliation, and they fear
job loss,'' Castro said. ``This is why one of our top priorities
will be to resolve these cases. . . . We have to protect the right
of people to pursue a claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Manhattan in the 1950s, Castro is the daughter of Puerto
Rican immigrants who had each moved to the city before the Great
Depression. After working at several jobs, the couple opened a
small bodega, or grocery store, in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   When Castro was 6, her parents returned to Puerto Rico because
``they wanted me and my brother to learn the Puerto Rican
culture,'' she said. ``They also stressed education. They felt it
was a bridge to a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro's brother, Ramon, is now an engineer in Puerto Rico, the
first in her extended family. She is the family's first lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   At 20, Castro became the youngest person and only woman to sit
on the municipal cabinet in Carolina, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, who holds master's of science and doctoral degrees from
Rutgers University in New Jersey, was the first Hispanic woman to
gain tenure at the university's Institute for Management &AMP; Labor
Relations.
</P>
<P>
   A single mother, Castro said her daughter was a ``latch-key kid.
There was no other way of doing it. I had friends and colleagues,
but there was no family. They were in Puerto Rico. There was very
little day care, and it was expensive. So, I took my daughter to
meetings and to picket lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro's daughter, now 28, is a social worker and advocate for
AIDS patients in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always said I should become a lawyer, because I was
always debating him,'' Castro said. ``But at the time, my only
perception of law was from the show `Perry Mason' and from a
neighbor who was a real estate lawyer. I knew I couldn't be Perry
Mason. But I didn't want to be like our neighbor, because he was
very dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I did what most teens do: I didn't pay any attention to
what my father said.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until she began delving into labor law while teaching labor
relations at Rutgers did Castro realize her calling. In 1979, she
enrolled in Rutgers School of Law, earning her degree in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Contact Diane E. Lewis at work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
