<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PITCH FOR FISK FOR THE HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 2000 Hall of Fame ballot is considerably lighter than last
year's edition. The 1999 sheet was weighed down by the monumental
achievements of George Brett, Robin Yount, and Nolan Ryan. Those
three were locks for immediate entry into Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   New England's own Carlton Fisk is the heavy holdover from the
1999 ballot and is certain to join brothers Brett, Young, and Ryan
when the 2000 tally is made public early next year.
</P>
<P>
   There are 30 names on this year's ballot, and Fisk may be the
only one to gain entry via the conventional method (being named on
75 percent of ballots cast). Makeup calls for old-timers and Negro
leagues players aren't announced until March.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk deserved to make the cut last winter but was overwhelmed by
the other names on the ballot. Perhaps it is better this way. He'll
have the stage to himself when the results are announced, and it's
been a long time since a native New Englander made this much
baseball noise.
</P>
<P>
   Omitting worthies such as Tony Perez, Jeff Reardon, Jim Kaat,
Jack Morris, Steve Garvey, Bert Blyleven, and Bruce Sutter, your
humble servant has checked the names of Fisk, Rich Gossage, Jim
Rice, Luis Tiant, and Gary Carter. I expect Fisk will be the only
one to get the required 75 percent. Perez has an outside chance.
</P>
<P>
   Voting for the Hall of Fame is a great privilege. Along with
voting for MVP and Cy Young, it is the only important function
served by the Baseball Writers Association of America. Your servant
takes the responsibility seriously and is ever-willing to explain
his ballot and welcome all dissenting opinion. Hall of Fame
arguments are part of what makes baseball great.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk: He should have waltzed in with George, Nolan, and Robin.
He was named on 66.4 percent of the ballots in his first year of
eligibility. The pride of Bellows Falls, Vt., cauQ.7 more games and
hit more homers than any other catcher in baseball history. That
should do it right there. He was an 11-time All-Star, a Gold Glove
winner, and hit one of the most famous homers in baseball lore.
Mark your calendar for Cooperstown next summer. Catcher Carlton is
a lock.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage: He is the only ``new'' candidate getting my vote.
Gossage saved 310 games in 22 seasons, pitched in three World
Series, and was named to nine All-Star teams. Statistically, he is
less than Sutter (who has struggled to get 25 percent of the votes)
or Reardon, another first-time candidate. But if you watched
baseball over the last 25 years, you would put Gossage ahead of
those guys. Sutter was dominant and invented the split-finger
fastball. Reardon racked up 367 saves. But Gossage was the true
closer. Remember him getting Yaz to pop up in 1978? The Goose gets
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rice: He's not going to make it. His vote total went from 203 in
'98 to 146 last year. He needs more than twice that to make the
cut. Rice's 10-year domination falls shy (like Tony Oliva's) for
most voters, and his churlish personality hasn't helped. I probably
vote for him because he was so uncooperative, just to avoid that
tag that ``poor Jim''is kept out by bitter writers who never got
good interviews. As it is, Rice stands alone with his numbers, and
they are borderline by Hall standards for outfielders. Ralph Kiner
(look him up) makes the best case for Rice, but Kiner shouldn't be
in there, either.
</P>
<P>
   Tiant: Voting for three Red Sox players, I feel a little like
George ``Home Cooking'' King of the New York Post (the man who
stiffed Pedro). Tiant has no chance and will be turned over to the
old-timers committee in two more years, but his career numbers are
equal to or better than those of Hall members Don Drysdale and
Catfish Hunter, both of whom played on better teams. Plus, we all
know Luis was the man you wanted in a big game.
</P>
<P>
   Carter: The more you look at it, voting for Fisk requires one to
vote for Carter. He is almost Fisk's equal in every offensive
category, won three Gold Gloves, and made 11 All-Star teams. Need
we remind Boston fans that Carter's two-out single off Calvin
Schiraldi started the Game 6 rally that hospitalized hundreds in
Greater Boston? Why does this man get half the votes Fisk gets? It
isn't right.
</P>
<P>
   I try to vote for the same people every year. Retired players
don't get better or worse from year to year _ and the idea of
making anyone wait is stupid. I voted for Ron Santo until he left
the ballot (after 15 years, they turn players over to the
old-timers committee) and will hang with Tiant to the finish.
Through the years, I have changed my mind on a few players. NL
folks talked me out of voting for Garvey and Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez may make it in 2000. He was named on 302 ballots (60.8
percent) last year and should benefit from a weaker ballot and
renewed support. A pro-Perez group has been lobbying hard. They
sent me a stat sheet and T-shirt. Sorry, he knocked in a ton of
runs, but his life was made easier by table-setters Pete Rose and
Joe Morgan. He was never as dominant as Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Morris is a worthy candidate and was a terrific big-game pitcher
(remember the seventh game of the 1991 World Series?), but a 3.90
ERA is too high for the Hall. Kaat (283 wins) is probably a better
candidate and has never gotten a sniff. Blyleven (287 wins, 3.31
ERA) is a better choice than both, but can't get voters' attention.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it means so much. You can win 280 games and hit 360
homers in the big leagues. You can win a couple of MVPs (Dale
Murphy) and set the all-time save record. But Cooperstown is
reserved only for the truly great. And as much as I'd like to vote
for Bruce Hurst and Dave Henderson, they were Hall of Famers only
in the hearts of Red Sox fans for one brief moment in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
