<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CHRISTIAN-MEDIA-TV-BO     12-15 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-MEDIA-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN MEDIA OFFER MORE THAN TV NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative Christians looking for religious-oriented sources
of news and entertainment do not have to be satisfied with Pat
Robertson, or even Pat Boone.
</P>
<P>
   --Direct satellite service. Sky Angel, a Florida company, was
licensed three years ago to broadcast from a satellite, whose
signal ``cannot be interrupted or influenced by secular media `gate
keepers.' '' Sky Angel bypasses secular television and cable
stations in favor of 24 Christian channels.
</P>
<P>
   --Curse-free TV. A computer made in New Orleans scans
closed-captioning signals and mutes a list of 100 offensive words.
The system retails for about $150, and has ``Strict'' and
``Tolerant'' settings, as well as a ``Religious'' setting that does
not screen out words like ``God,'' ``Jesus,'' and ``Christ'' when
used in the context of a sermon, rather than an exclamation.
</P>
<P>
   --Christian Internet service providers. Dozens of companies
provide self-censoring, competitively priced alternatives to
Internet service providers such as America OnLine and Yahoo.
William Bennett and Ralph Reed helped launch this.com in July; the
server filters out flesh tones, which could indicate pornography,
and hate speech. Pat Robertson's son, Tim, announced his service,
FamilyClick.com, the same month.
</P>
<P>
   --Video games. With The War in Heaven, which went on sale in
October, Eternal Warriors introduced a Bible-based alternative to
PC-based ``first-person shooters'' like Doom and Quake. Another 3-D
shooter is Saints of Virtue, which challenges players to fight
their way through the Mall of Worldliness, the Amphitheater of
Apathy, and the New Age Nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   --On-line shopping. On-line shopping malls like Gospelnet.com
have created a vast gateway for Christian books, music, movies, and
tapes, as well as specialty products such as Happy Hank, a stuffed
hound programmed to say 15 Christian phrases including ``Rejoice!
You're a son of the King!''
</P>
<P>
   --Long-distance carrier. Among the companies offering Christian
long-distance service is Missionlink Communications, which
contributes a percentage of its revenues to missionaries in Asia
and Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CHRISTIAN-MEDIA-ART-B     12-15 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-MEDIA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEDIA LET CHRISTIANS SEE NO EVIL, HEAR NO EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERVILLE, Maine _ Taki Pilitsis is knee-deep in media. While
his mother checks financial markets on her laptop across the room,
he sits in front of a personal computer, legs poking out of
cavernous shorts, pounding keys that control a prowling warrior.
His bedroom is papered with posters of athletes captured in midair,
sweat flying. Although he has spent most of his life in central
Maine, he has a favorite rapper.
</P>
<P>
   But look closely, and note that he is shooting his way through
The Mall of Worldliness and defending himself with exploding Bible
verses; the lyrics he sings could be mistaken for hip-hop romance
but actually refer to Jesus. And at 12, Taki has only dim
impressions of the Backstreet Boys, Pokemon, Doom, or Snoop Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   At an age when boys turn eagerly to popular culture, he lives in
a media world carefully built by his mother, Allison Pilitsis, who
became a born-again Christian eight years ago after a long
conversation with a Baptist manicurist. Conservative Christians
like Pilitsis have long been able to turn to ``The 700 Club'' for
Pat Robertson's take on the news, but in recent years, technology
and investment have pushed this niche market into overdrive.
Increasingly, they have the option not only of supplementing
secular media, but of replacing it _ with religious Internet
service providers and religious long-distance carriers,
Christian-centered sports journalism, Bible-based financial advice,
Christian-only direct satellite broadcast, and Christian combat
computer action games.
</P>
<P>
   All of which allows Pilitsis to remove her children from the
influence of most popular culture without making them feel cut off.
``They're doing all the things that other kids are doing, but
they're doing them in their own realm,'' said Pilitsis, 49, who
attends the Faith Evangelical Free Church in Oakland. ``So I don't
think they're missing out.''
</P>
<P>
   When talking about the technology that makes it possible to
raise faithful children in a secular world, Pilitsis closes her
eyes in gratitude. Other parents interviewed _ united by the fear
that younger and younger children are buffeted with images of
violence and sex _ spoke with optimism about the loosening grip of
network news and the daily paper. Scott Somerville, an attorney
with the Virginia-based Home School Legal Defense Association, said
that he can now look into the future and envision the development
of a rich Christian ``countermedia'' _ a ``ghetto'' in the best
sense of the term, giving communities the ability to preserve their
faith in the face of ``a hostile dominant culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many others look warily at this development, arguing that
Christ called his followers to work in the world, not run from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's getting to the point where technology will allow
you to create a bubble around yourself so you don't need to
interact with the outside world, the `fallen world,' '' said Greg
Boyd, a professor of theology at Bethel College and pastor of
Woodland Hills Church in St. Paul. ``You develop a whole culture of
people who are completely incapable of holding a conversation with
someone who doesn't hold their world view.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are hoping to bridge that gap with products that can
compete with mainstream offerings. Taki and his 9-year-old brother,
Alex, are the kinds of customers that Theo Beale, 31, was thinking
of when his company, Eternal Warriors, unveiled The War in Heaven,
a Christian-themed, 3-D combat, action-video game that pits zaftig
blond angels against demons with clubs and cloven hoofs. Beale
intentionally designed the game to satisfy teenage players of
``first-person shooters'' like Doom and Quake. And Boyd, who has
test-marketed The War in Heaven with his 14-year-old son, said
Beale's game is a vast improvement on more conservative Christian
computer games, such as one whose goal was fitting as many animals
as possible on Noah's Ark.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that The War in Heaven, with its vivid,
rapid-fire, hand-to-hand combat, is violent. But Beale says
Christian publishers cannot ignore popular culture. ``If you want
to reach people, you have to speak the Gospel to them in their
language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Beale, who also writes Christian fantasy novels, recent
developments have expanded the market into a playground of
opportunity. Part of this expansion is pure capitalism _ as a niche
market, the country's 80 million active, churchgoing Christians are
increasingly hard to ignore. The average children's department in a
Christian retail store last year grew by 22 percent, according to
the Christian Booksellers' Association, and Christian-themed
fiction is the fastest-growing genre in publishing, according to
Salem Communications.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of crossover hits for adults _ the
``Assassins'' has spent four months on the New York Times'
best-seller list; Hollywood was shocked when the film ``The Omega
Code'' was lofted by church-centered promotion into the 10
top-grossing films; and the Christian-influenced rock band Creed
made it to No. 3 on the Billboard alternative singles chart in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, technology has made publishing far easier. ``If I had
wanted to print a book up 10 years ago, I could have spent my life
savings and made a crappy little vanity press thing,'' said Beale,
in a telephone interview from his home in Switzerland. Now ``for
three or four bucks a copy, I can produce a nice-looking paperback
that is every bit as good as the national media can do. . . . The
giants can no longer control what other people are printing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, anymore, can they control what people are reading.
Pilitsis, who left town in 1972 riding high as a former Miss
Waterville, returned 23 years later, newly divorced and with two
young children. After working overseas for most of that time as a
travel executive, she returned to a United States that shocked her
with its sloppy dress, contempt for authority, and embrace of
premarital sex and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Raised on network news, she began to question the objectivity of
mainstream media. Then she gave up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it, and I can't get away from it, so I'm just going
to do without it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions about the media are a central battleground for many
conservative Christian parents, said others interviewed. Susan
Blake of Brewer said her 11-year-old son relies heavily on reruns
of ``The Waltons'' and ``My Three Sons''; Calvin Lawson of the
Cherry Valley neighborhood in Leicester, Mass., makes sure his
children can balance the ``secular news'' with the conservative
reporting of WorldNetDaily. Most parents agreed that the battle
grows harder with age. Eric Unsworth, a Hamilton, Mass., father,
said as his children grew into teenagers, separating them from the
``cultural smog'' proved ``less doable than we hoped,'' giving rise
to case-by-case negotiation about music and movies.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Pilitsis has succeeded in what she set out to do. A
year ago, she canceled her subscription to the Waterville Morning
Sentinel because she did not want her children to read coverage of
the Monica Lewinsky scandal. She is boycotting Disney, and has
soured on the Public Broadcasting System, whose approach to
religion strikes her as scholarly, rather than faith-based, and put
a block on Nickelodeon, which she criticizes as ``very
evolution-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Investors' Business Daily _ which she needs for her
on-line trading _ Newsweek, and two children's sports publications,
Pilitsis' subscriptions are explicitly Christian. On her wish list
is Sky Angel, a satellite broadcasting package that will allow her
to receive 24 Christian channels, bypassing all other channels, and
that, its advertisement promises, ``cannot be interrupted or
influenced by secular media `gate keepers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is little longing for forbidden media in the Pilitsis
household _ in large part, Pilitsis said, because her sons are
rarely exposed to it and ``there's not a lot of discretionary time
for them to be where I can't see them.'' For the last three years,
she has floated the idea of home-schooling them, but they have
resisted the idea, she said. As it is, they go to a Christian
school, attend a Christian youth group, play in a Christian
basketball league, and the only time they spend with children
outside their faith is when they play with their cousins in a local
soccer league. She has heard secular radio stations playing
upstairs, but only a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for kids to be able to stand up for what they
know is right when they've got kids around them that might ridicule
them,'' she said. ``It's a battle for the kids, no matter what we
do at home.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who see an answer in a Christian ``countermedia,'' it
is less a new world than a re-creation of an old world _ one that
is irretrievably lost. ``As recently as 1962, a child would go to
school and read the King James Bible, say grace before dinner, and
then watch `Father Knows Best,' and everyone went to Sunday
school,'' said Somerville. ``We've shifted from a society that
enforced generic Protestant norms to, in the last 20 years, a kind
of multicultural idea. So what if the Protestant minority decides
to create its own counterculture?''
</P>
<P>
   Pilitsis says her battle to protect her family has mostly been a
winning one. But in the back of her mind is the worry that the same
technology that makes her all-Christian-all-the-time household
possible also poses a danger. A few weeks ago Taki, on the brink of
becoming a teenager, asked to be allowed to watch the latest James
Bond film, and was denied. ``I just kind of got over it,'' he said,
but the next dilemma is already lined up: He wants his own e-mail
account with his own password. Pilitsis sighs, looking slightly
exhausted. She has passed on Taki's request to her pastor, and she
is waiting for him to call back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
