<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF REPUTATION PRECEDES THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stewart O'Nan has an interesting, if bleak, essay in the current
Boston Review on the literary fortunes of the late novelist Richard
Yates. Yates was once the talk of the town, a National Book Award
finalist hailed as a giant talent by the likes of Tennessee
Williams, Dorothy Parker, and Ann Beattie. Now, well, if his name
showed up on ``Jeopardy,'' it would certainly go unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his work was neglected during his lifetime, after his death
it has practically disappeared,'' writes O'Nan, himself a novelist.
``To write so well and then to be forgotten is a terrifying
legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sic transit gloria mundi. Why do writers write? ``No man but a
blockhead ever wrote except for money,'' Samuel Johnson famously
said. Yet Johnson himself penned occasional sermons, gratis, for
his bishop pals. Yes, some authors write with an eye toward
salvation, but most writers write for a different reason: to be
read, and to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why the politics of reputation are so ferocious. For
dead white males, the canon is shrinking, and you can hear the
beams squealing as the House of Fame collapses inward. Somerset
Maugham and Graham Greene _ who they? A recent article by Roger
Kimball in the New Criterion bemoans the shredding of T. S. Eliot,
arguably the most influential writer and critic of the century.
Kimball's little quip: ``Mistah Eliot _ he dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The American West has always entered special pleadings in this
category. The minute you cross the Sierra Nevada, you hear of
nothing but the S-Men _ Steinbeck, Stegner, and Saroyan _ cast down
by the New York critics. Each case stands separately. Steinbeck,
his claque insists, supported the Vietnam War, and thus forfeited
the cachet that only the left-leaning, New York intelligentsia can
confer. It is true, incredibly, that the New York Times
editorialized against Steinbeck's Nobel Prize, the day after he won
it. The award ``raises questions about the mechanics of selection
and how close the Nobel committee is to the main currents of
American writing,'' quoth the newspaper of record.
</P>
<P>
   Saroyan was a talented feuilletonist now unjustly neglected _ it
is said, absurdly _ because of his Armenian nationality. Stegner's
biographer, Jackson Benson, claims his subject was ``possibly the
most accomplished person of American letters in our time,'' yet
complains that he ``has been ignored, even belittled as a
Westerner.''
</P>
<P>
   What bosh. The most revered author in the American canon, Mark
Twain, was also a Westerner, albeit one who came East and broke
bread with the grandees of the New York-Boston literary axis. (As
did Stegner.) Stegner was good, real good, and he had a Pulitzer
Prize and a National Book Award to prove it. Yes, he suffered some
bad treatment. The Times never reviewed his Pulitzer-winning novel,
``Angle of Repose.'' After it won, their chief literary critic
complained that the Pulitzer should have gone to John Updike for
``Rabbit Redux.'' But just as good news travels perhaps too slowly
from the Left Coast, so, too, does bad news. The embarrassing
plagiarism revelations that tarnished ``Repose'' were mostly the
stuff of Bay Area salon gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The tide of reputation, of course, flows both ways. T. S. Eliot,
ironically, brought John Donne and the metaphysical poets back into
the ``core curriculum'' that has bedeviled liberal arts majors for
decades. Herman Melville passed on not knowing that he had written
the proverbial Great American Novel. William Faulkner owed Malcolm
Cowley a debt of gratitude for repackaging his work for a new,
larger public.
</P>
<P>
   Reputation is all about debt, and hope, as O'Nan makes clear at
the end of his essay on Yates: ``For now, writers will have to keep
the novels and stories of Richard Yates alive, rescuing copies from
used bookstores and passing them along to students and fellow
writers. . . . We shouldn't have to do it, but we will, gladly.
Perhaps in the future, if we're lucky, someone will do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
