u a BC-LAWYERS-VALUES-BOS &LR;      12-15 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-VALUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER'S WEDDING BELLS RAISE LIFESTYLE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The invitation landed in David Levenstein's mailbox in
late June, doubling his reasons to celebrate: just weeks before he
was to be married, the Amherst man was offered a coveted spot on
the law review at Western New England School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Levenstein was jubilant _ until he realized that his wedding, an
out-of-state affair, conflicted with orientation. And the school
wouldn't budge. No orientation, no law review. So Levenstein, 36,
chose to take his vows and sacrifice the plum position, a decision,
he believes has already cost him one job offer.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, the incident seemed little more than a regrettable
footnote in one aspiring lawyer's career. Then, word of
Levenstein's dilemma spread beyond the Springfield campus, becoming
a cause celebre of the Boston Bar Association, which recently
released a study damning the legal profession for its emphasis on
work over family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just totally horrified,'' said Lauren Rikleen, immediate
past president of the BBA, whose Task Force on Professional Values
and Family Needs found that 43 percent of new associates quit
within three years, largely because they felt they had to choose
between a career and a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be no better example of what it is we're trying to
adddress _ the idea that work matters above all else, that there
are no other values in life,'' Rikleen said. ``I mean, this was his
wedding!''
</P>
<P>
   Levenstein's law review invitation, dated June 29, 1999, arrived
roughly seven weeks before he was to be married in Lancaster, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding was scheduled for Aug. 22, a date that had been set
the previous December. Flowers had been ordered. A caterer,
photographer, and band had been hired. Invitations to nearly 120
friends and family members, some from out of the country, had been
mailed.
</P>
<P>
   Law review orientation, meanwhile, ran from Aug. 21 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing he had a conflict, Levenstein dashed off an e-mail to
the journal's faculty adviser, Leora Harpaz, explaining his
dilemma. Her answer: make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Levenstein e-mailed again, this time suggesting alternatives. He
offered to study beforehand, tape the orientation sessions, and
listen to them later. In response, Harpaz withdrew her invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Levenstein's experience became fodder for the
student newspaper, which chronicled the case in a story headlined
``Marriage Plans Cause Stormy Romance With Law Review.''
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion piece accompanying the story, Howard Kalodner,
Harpaz's husband and the school's former dean, justified the
administration's decision by writing that law review takes ``a
willingness to submerge one's personal priorities to the priorities
of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   At most law schools, an invitation to join the law review _ a
scholarly journal that covers a broad range of legal issues _ is a
prestigious honor offered only to the creme de la creme. It is a
sought-after line on a resume, since many law firms heavily recruit
law review participants.
</P>
<P>
   Kalodner was out of town and could not be reached for comment,
according to a school spokesman, and Harpaz was also unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Dunn, dean of the law school, called the situation
``unfortunate,'' but said law review orientation is ``extremely
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the only thing I could say is that our law review was
not especially flexible,'' said Dunn. ``But the individual involved
was not flexible at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said, for example, that he offered to use school funds to
fly Levenstein to and from Massachusetts the day before his wedding
so he could attend one day of orientation. He said Levenstein
rejected the offer, calling it impractical.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn also promised Levenstein a law review position in his third
year, and has placed a letter explaining the situation in
Levenstein's student file, which goes to all prospective employers.
</P>
<P>
   But Levenstein, who believes he lost out on a summer position at
a Hartford law firm because he could not tout law review among his
accomplishments, said the position is more influential in his
second year, when he is interviewing for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And he scoffs at school officials' reasoning that he should have
anticipated a law review invitation and planned his wedding at a
different time, noting that his marriage was scheduled months
before the academic calendar was set.
</P>
<P>
   At Shatz, Schwartz and Fentin, the Springfield law firm where
Levenstein works as a part-time law clerk, his colleagues support
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's true, in general, that your personal life
sometimes has to take a backseat to your professional life,'' said
Levenstein's boss, Mark Bluver, a partner in the firm. ``But
suggesting that he should have changed his wedding date so he could
make a week of orientation is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Levenstein's dilemma so incensed Boston attorney Nancer Ballard,
chairwoman of the Boston bar's work-family task force, that she
plans to ask the group that accredits law schools to include
work-family balance in its evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really does stand as a dramatic example of the
work-family conflict issue,'' said Rikleen. ``What could be more
stark than someone having to choose between his wedding day and
something that has life-long implications for his career?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1343EST &QL; 
