<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GOLAN-SETTLERS-BOS &LR;      12-15 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-SETTLERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN FRIENDS, NO EASY ACCORD ON GOLAN HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBBUTZ MEROM GOLAN, Golan Heights _ They are best friends, and
have been for a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Zelzion and Shefi Mor, both 40, served in the same Israeli
infantry unit and were stationed on this strategic plateau in the
mid-1970s when they embraced the Zionist dream of the kibbutz
movement.
</P>
<P>
   So they stayed at Merom Golan. They married here. They raised
children.
</P>
<P>
   And now they are faced with the prospect of Israel returning the
Golan Heights to Syria after capturing it in the 1967 Six Day War.
The Syrian-Israeli talks set to begin in Washington Wednesday _ the
highest level peace negotiations ever between two countries that
have been bitter enemies for 50 years _ leave the two friends
deeply worried about the fate of their homes, their families, and
the lives they've built together. It also leaves them deeply
divided.
</P>
<P>
   For Zelzion, giving up the Golan, with its cattle ranches,
vineyards, and crucial water resources, is an insane risk and an
unforgivable betrayal of the goals of Zionism. For Mor, returning
the terraced hills where 18,000 Israeli residents live is a painful
but necessary sacrifice to allow future generations to reap the
benefits of a lasting peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want peace just like everyone else,'' said Zelzion. ``But
land for peace does not work. I don't trust Syria. You have to
build trust. Why are we running so fast?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these negotiations will be good for all of Israel,''
countered Mor, the financial administrator for the kibbutz's
agricultural operation. ``The problem is not my private problem, it
is the problem of the whole state of Israel. . . . Even if it means
we have to give up our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men were sitting in the bar of the kibbutz's Country
Style Restaurant Tuesday, the end of a day that marked the 19th
anniversary of Israel's 1980 annexation of the Golan Heights.
Israel captured the area in 1967 and then held onto it in a round
of even more intense fighting in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   A cold rain pounded against the tin roof. They drank beer,
listened to American rock 'n' roll, and ribbed each other as they
always do. They have the same mannerisms, the same thick beards.
They say a lot to each other without uttering a word. And like many
close friends, they joked about how they've become ``a couple of
old ladies disagreeing about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is more than a political argument. It is a disagreement
about the future of their lives, about their homes, about the lives
they have built together. It's about what, in the end, all the work
they have put into the kibbutz, into its cattle ranch and orchards,
means to them. It is about whether or not they still believe in
their country.
</P>
<P>
   As Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak begins talks in Washington
with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa, not only the two
friends but all of Israel seems divided over the prospect of a
land-for-peace deal, which could also be a key first step toward
disentangling from the civil war in neighboring Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zelzion and Mor served in Lebanon in their many years of
army reserve duty. They agree on the importance of getting out of
Lebanon, a conflict that is widely viewed as a proxy war for Syria,
which has some 35,000 troops stationed there and provides support
to Hezbollah guerrillas fighting the Israeli occupation of a
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' within south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends want to see the bloodshed stop. Like many Golan
residents, they are very secular and very liberal within the
spectrum of Israeli politics. And it is uncomfortable for them to
see hawks like Likud party leader Ariel Sharon speaking on their
behalf in the parliament, and religious Zionists of the ``Yesha''
settler movement coming to their defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Golan question has both forged strange alliances in Israel
and caused new political divisions in the Golan community, as the
nation prepares for a looming political battle if Barak reaches an
agreement with Syria and brings it to a national referendum, as he
has vowed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us feel uncomfortable with this,'' said Zelzion as he
contemplated a battle to keep the Golan. ``Who do we need to
support us? We need the middle class, the classic Labor Party
voters. As soon as they see us with Yesha, they will vote against
us. This is how we will lose.''
</P>
<P>
   A pullout from Golan would end a way of life for families who
settled here over the last three decades. Israel's finest wines
come from lush vineyards that dot the hillsides. The city of
Kazrin, with a population of 7,000, is proceeding to construct new
neighborhoods and a $7 million Teachers College. The hotels and
bed-and-breakfasts perched on the hills do a brisk business.
</P>
<P>
   Merom Golan, with 500 residents the oldest and largest kibbutz
in the Golan, is in the heart of this community. Three generations
have tilled its apple orchards, mined its volcanic rock quarries,
labored in an engine factory, and tended to its livestock.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine Israel abandoning a place like Meron
Golan or displacing the 18,000 Israelis who live in the network of
settlements and newly constructed towns. At the very least, it
would be a traumatizing and expensive endeavor. And not
surprisingly, the renewed talks with Syria leave those who staked
their claim here feeling betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here with the pure Zionist dream. We came here because
we believed in it, and because the government encouraged us to
believe in it,'' said Zelzion, who is raising three children, ages
7 to 12, and who runs the ``Coffee in the Clouds'' cafe on a
hilltop where he once served as a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then everything that you believed in, everything you have
fought for and worked so hard for is collapsing,'' he added. ``And
the government tells you that you are an obstacle to peace. We have
been used. And I am bitter about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mor, who has children the same ages as his friend and has seen
the younger generation become best friends as well, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't feel that way,'' he said, casting a sharp look at
his friend. ``There wouldn't be any peace process if the kibbutzim
hadn't been here for 32 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he does not feel betrayed, and that it is time for
those who came here to see that their role is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look to the future for all of Israel, and for our
children,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
