<HEADLINE>
KIMBERLY JENSEN'S FINAL, ELUSIVE JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kimberly S. Jensen didn't call her husband until she reached
Ocean City, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen, the number two executive in Mortimer Zuckerman's
publishing empire, was questioned Nov. 4 by company officials about
what appeared to be improper use of an expense account she
controlled at the Atlantic Monthly in Boston. When she failed to
appear at a meeting with a lawyer in New York a week later to
discuss the allegations, her husband reported her missing.
</P>
<P>
   Her call came a day later. She wouldn't tell him where she was
but said simply that she was ending her life.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted by her husband, Steven Fuchs, New York City police
traced the call to a beachfront hotel in Ocean City and alerted
local police. She convinced them there had been a mistake and that
she had no intention of harming herself.
</P>
<P>
   After the police left, the 44-year-old executive called her
husband again, warning him not to tell anyone where she was.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses saw Jensen wandering the beach the next day, Nov. 12.
At 12:45 p.m. on Nov. 13, a maid discovered her body on a bed in
her hotel room. A plastic bag was tied around her head. Jensen left
no note. This week, Ocean City police ruled her death a suicide,
listing her cause of death as asphyxiation ``aided'' by alcohol and
Benadryl, a common cold medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why she felt she had to do it,'' said Fuchs
during a telephone interview last week from the couple's home in
Killington, Vt. ``But it's not what people might want to think. It
wasn't the money. I know it wasn't the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her colleagues agree. Those who knew her well say they
don't believe the demanding, talented, and highly respected leader
would have killed herself because of the allegations, even if they
are true. ``She was too tough, too smart, and in the end it just
wasn't that big a deal,'' said an Atlantic employee.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been deeper reasons for her actions, others say.
Despite having advanced from a low-level position at US News &AMP;
World report to one of the most visionary forces in Zuckerman's
company, Jensen appeared to have been driven by a thirst for some
unattainable success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that she was a happy person,'' said a former
co-worker at the Atlantic. ``She was an amazingly hard worker and
also intensely private, so it was hard to get a fix on her. But I
got a feeling sometimes. Something she'd do or say would just make
me wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jensen went to work for the Atlantic in 1988, moving to Boston
from suburban Washington, D.C., where she had attended George Mason
University, had a failed marriage, and worked as an assistant
treasurer at US News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Her impact at the Atlantic was almost immediate. She was among
the first at the magazine to perceive the importance of the
Internet, and recruited young workers at the magazine to help bring
the Atlantic on line, former employees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an absolute visionary,'' said Lowell Weiss, a Clinton
administration speech writer who was an Atlantic intern when Jensen
persuaded him to join the Atlantic full time and explore the
possibilities of an on-line magazine. ``She saw something in me
that I didn't see in myself. She gave me the vision of what we were
doing and convinced me I could do it. She was very special in her
ability to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But while she won a loyal following, particularly among young
people who felt she had taken an interest in their careers, she
also became known for publicly berating those she felt were not
living up to her standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had no problem excoriating people, I mean really letting
them have it,'' said a former Atlantic employee. ``It was pretty
well known that you didn't want to get on her bad side.''
</P>
<P>
   And many felt she was cold and remote, speaking only on business
terms and avoiding personal conversations in the hallways, favoring
solitary work in her office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she caught the attention of corporate executives who
moved her steadily upward at the magazine and eventually tapped her
to help launch the Internet monthly, Fast Company, based in Boston.
She is credited with writing a business plan for the magazine that
was instrumental in casting it as a hipper-than-hip journal of the
new economy. Claiming a friendship with writer Hunter S. Thompson,
a former editor said, she selected one of his quotes as the
magazine's motto: ``Go faster and faster until the fear of death is
overcome by speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while Jensen's magazine career was advancing, she began to
pursue another love _ music. Friends said she was obsessed with
popular music. She once camped overnight for Pearl Jam tickets and
often went to bars in Boston and Killington to see new bands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she saw a Virginia band called Genghis Angus perform at
an Irish pub in Killington. The band played a folksy rock called
``no depression,'' which is ``all about hope and redemption,'' said
Guy Burlage, who was a friend of Jensen. ``She was raptured by it
from the very beginning, really taken in.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, she introduced herself to the band's leader and
main songwriter, Allen Kitselman of Berryville, Va. The two
immediately hit it off, Kitselman said, and he confessed to her
that he was worn out and planned to quit.
</P>
<P>
   But over the course of the next several weeks, Jensen talked him
out of it. ``She believed in me,'' Kitselman said. ``She gave me
the gift of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen told the band she would take them on as a personal
project, and one member recalled that she said, ``We are going to
make America love you.''
</P>
<P>
   She formed a record company called Adrenachrome, named after the
fictitious hallucinogenic drug in Thompson's novel ``Fear and
Loathing in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   She put together slick press materials, including a Web site,
and worked record industry contacts she had made. She persuaded the
producers of pop star John Mellencamp to produce a Genghis Angus
album.
</P>
<P>
   She also pumped money into the endeavor. David Galinsky, the
booking agent Jensen hired to schedule shows for the band, said she
paid him a salary that he declined to disclose but that was ``good
enough for me to get by on.'' He said she paid for promotional
expenses and the production and manufacture of the album and she
paid for part of the tour, all of which totaled ``probably about
$150,000 over the course of a couple years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my expenses I just sent to her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her support and the recognition she won for the band,
her management style didn't always sit well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very strong-willed,'' Galinsky said. ``It was her way
or the highway. We went through a number of people in the band.
She'd say, `This guy doesn't sound right. It's just not working
out, and he's got to go.' '' Galinsky said Jensen once told him the
band was like a surrogate family, taking the place of children she
was unable to have on her own. ``She said, `Maybe I'll adopt all
you boys and you can be my kids.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she landed a deal with a Boston label, Eastern Front
Records, and the band went on tour _ financed in part by the record
label, partly by Jensen, and partly by Fast Company, which signed
on as a sponsor. But the album didn't sell, and in December 1998,
she parted with the band, telling Kitselman, ``It doesn't make
sense to put any more money into this.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
