<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JENSEN-SUICIDE-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-15 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENSEN-SUICIDE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... into this.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month later, Jensen was promoted and moved her offices to
Zuckerman's headquarters in New York. The new job required her to
juggle frenetic demands. To oversee the magazines in her command _
Fast Company, the Atlantic, and US News &AMP; World Report _ she flew
up and down the East Coast each week, spending a few days in
Boston, New York, and Washington, before beginning the circuit
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exhausting schedule,'' said a Zuckerman company
spokeswoman. ``But she seemed to us such a professional person,
very controlled and able to absorb tremendous amounts of stress.''
</P>
<P>
   There were growing signs of some deep discontent, however. She
began to weep one day while discussing the impending sale of
Atlantic Monthly with another executive in Zuckerman's New York
offices. On rare weekends with her husband at home in Killington,
she slept constantly, her husband said. She complained to him that
her job had become increasingly unpleasant. And yet she felt
compelled to work even more and advance further in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year things got harder,'' Fuchs said. ``But she was a
woman working in a man's world. She had things she wanted to do,
things she wanted to prove. She wasn't going to turn down more
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Still she had a strong distaste for some elements of her new
job, he said. Last summer, she was put in charge of Atlantic
Monthly's pending sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worried about what would happen to the magazine,'' her
husband said. ``She worried about people losing their jobs. She was
afraid they would all hate her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Zuckerman company officials confronted Jensen about the use
of the Atlantic account, the company had found about $100,000 of
what it called ``personal expenses,'' such as credit card payments,
rent, and expenses accrued by the band, the company spokeswoman
said. Jensen's husband, who said he has culled her financial
records, said the figure was closer to $10,000 and that ``she knew
every penny and would have paid it back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jensen seemed dispirited and drained. ``She was just
tired,'' Fuchs said. ``She told me that it seemed like all the time
and care she's put into the company didn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen never went back to work. On Nov. 6, two days after the
meeting with company officials, she went with her husband and a
friend to a Killington bar to watch a new songwriter she was
backing, Jeff Black.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, she drove the songwriter to the airport outside
Providence. After dropping him off, she drove into the city and
attempted suicide by inhaling exhaust fumes from her car, police
say. She was taken to a Rhode Island hospital, where she
recuperated and underwent psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   She was released Nov. 10, and according to police told her
husband she would meet him in New York to consult with a lawyer.
True to her word, she went to New York but instead of attending the
meeting, police said, she flew to Washington, rented a car, and
made the three-hour drive to Ocean City, a tourist trap on the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why Ocean City,'' her husband said. ``All I know
is she didn't like it. She hated the place. I think she went there
as a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   She checked into a Comfort Inn a few hundred yards from the
beach. On Nov. 12, the day of her death, she wandered the beach and
went to a drugstore, where she bought cold medicine.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived shortly after noon on Nov. 13, she had been
dead for about 24 hours. And officers were struck by her apparent
peacefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rather calm scene,'' Ocean City police Lieutenant
Kevin Kirstein said. ``You could say serene.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the news, her guitarist friend Burlage would
recall being with her the last night she was in Killington watching
Jeff Black perform. On the way home, he had caught her gaze and
found something peculiar in it. He would later wonder whether she
had already made a decision about her fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked almost like a little girl,'' he said. ``She looked
innocent and happy. It was the first time I ever saw her when she
didn't look like an automaton, the first time I really saw her look
alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
