<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-KEEPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCKING EVERY MOVE YOU MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the multitudes who battle traffic each morning to get to
jobs tied to office desks, the concept of telecommuting has a
certain allure:
</P>
<P>
   Get off the road and work from home. Choose your own starting
and quitting times. Take time off when personal needs require.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as your schedule doesn't get in the way of anyone
else's, no one need be the wiser.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds good _ but don't count on it. The punch-clock
mentality lives on.
</P>
<P>
   Moving only slightly behind the speed at which the Internet is
penetrating the workplace and home life, two Massachusetts
companies are racing to produce the electronic equivalent of time
clocks that can keep track of you wherever you might be.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been around a while, and the paths each has taken to
deal with technological and social change offer timely
illustrations of how companies must periodically restructure and
revise their business plans to compete and survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reinvented ourselves four times now,'' says Mark S. Ain,
56, chairman and chief executive of Kronos Inc. of Waltham, founded
in 1979 and the first in its field to adopt computer chip
technology to manage unwieldy payroll data.
</P>
<P>
   Kronos, which had $254.3 million in sales in the fiscal year
that ended Sept. 30, is widely considered the market leader in
``time and attendance'' office equipment. The company has about
1,500 employees, half in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But Simplex Time Recorder Co. of Gardner, which dates
</P>
<P>
   to founder Edward G. Watkins's first time-clock patent in 1894,
is pushing hard to close the market gap after a shakeup in 1997
that included buying a software company and a new name for its
timekeeping division: ``Workforce Solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still owned by the Watkins family, Simplex also makes security,
fire-alarm, and fire-suppression systems. It has about 7,000
employees worldwide, most in sales and service roles. About 1,500
work at its factory in Westminister and at offices about to move
from Gardner to Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Simplex had $736 million in sales in 1998 and
projects 1999 revenue to increase 12 percent, but refused to break
out revenues by divisions _ making comparisons impossible.
</P>
<P>
   As most workers who have contact with timekeeping systems today
know, time clocks that sound a hearty ``ka-chunk'' or ring a bell
as each employee punches in or out are candidates for museums.
</P>
<P>
   In their place, computerized systems actuated by employees'
magnetically coded identification badges or keyboarded data have
taken over at most large companies that keep such records.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond recording hours worked and simplifying payroll processing
by storing each employee's wage scale and other details, these
systems deliver reams of data used by supervisors to write work
schedules and by strategic planners who want to optimize use of
facilities and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, says Ain, large law firms, which typically bill
for their services by the hour, have been looking at these systems
to replace handwritten records that track how much time lawyers and
paralegals spend on each case and client.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants who follow the timekeeping and time management
industry are far from unanimous about its future.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Phelan, a consultant with Gartner Group Inc., believes the
spread of the Internet is bound to bring into the timekeeping fold
thousands of workers at locations far from the home office whose
hours and activities may now only be estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is where the growth is going to be,'' she says. The
onrush of wireless technology, which allows coded transmissions
from cellular phones and soon will have capacity to carry detailed
work reports generated on laptop computers, will put both
white-collar telecommuters and blue-collar field service workers
within keystrokes of the home office's watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
   But David Weaver, with The Survey Group in Wakefield, sees
work-force management moving away from strict timekeeping, in
assembly-line companies as well as business offices.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver says his evidence is in two surveys his company made, in
1996-97 and in 1998-99, each involving 256 companies with a total
of more than 200,000 employees. The number of firms that required
manufacturing employees to punch in and punch out each day fell 13
percent. For office workers and low-level managers not subject to
union rules, the decline was 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing less punching of time clocks and less writing
down times of arrival and departure,'' Weaver said. The second
survey also found 21 percent of companies kept no time records
whatsoever aside from absences and vacations _ more than twice the
number in the 1996-97 survey.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, introduction of Microsoft Corp.'s Windows
operating systems; the appearance of large, multipurpose corporate
software systems such as those by Oracle, SAP; and most recently
the development of the Internet all have widened opportunities for
new time-based applications.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to capitalize on these events, more than two dozen small
software companies have emerged nationwide that develop
time-management and time-recording software for specific
industries, from casinos to hospitals to hotels.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no industry-wide statistics, Kronos, which is
the only large player that is publicly traded and reports sales
numbers, estimates it holds about half the market among companies
that buy timekeeping systems from outside vendors.
</P>
<P>
   That group constitutes about half of all businesses, Kronos
marketing director James Kizielewicz says. The large companies that
develop their own systems make up another 25 percent of the market,
he says. The rest either use old-style time clocks and time cards
or keep handwritten records.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this last group are unlikely to change their ways soon,
he says. Reinforcing this, Ain points out that thousands of
Kronos's earliest digitalized time clocks, manufactured between
1979 and 1992, are still in use. But as users have grown and bought
new systems, orders for the time cards that these units use have
fallen from 90 million in 1992 to just 10 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1992 when Kronos began its string of ``reinventions,''
introducing DOS- and Unix-based timekeeping systems that could move
the data they collect from employee ID cards into larger systems
for direct payroll processing.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later Kronos adapted again with Windows-based
software, adding more data analysis capability as it did so. Last
spring it expanded this line further with the acquisition of one of
its small upstart rivals, CrossWind Technologies Inc. of Santa
Cruz, Calif., which specialized in applications that fit into the
popular Microsoft Outlook office systems software.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the Internet has proved more daunting than Kronos
anticipated: An expected October shipping date has slipped while
last-minute bugs are worked out, Kizielewicz says.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan, the Gartner Group consultant, says Kronos is
``definitely behind the curve'' with its Web-based product. But she
says also Kronos is unquestionably dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have permeated pretty much every industry there is to get
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, while Simplex's market position may not be clear,
there is no question it is racing forward. While the company was
the longtime leader in electromechanical time clocks, its push into
digital products took full shape only with the introduction of a
Windows-based system in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Simplex made a strategic decision to sell its
systems as a package _ including magnetic card readers,
touch-screen data-entry terminals, and other hardware that it makes
itself in a 700,000-square-foot plant in Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   Kronos, which once made most of its own hardware, now turns to
outside suppliers for much of the equipment its systems require.
</P>
<P>
   Simplex's big move came in 1997, when it acquired a small,
35-employee Cambridge company, Information Marketing Business Inc.,
that had been making timekeeping and scheduling software for retail
stores since 1982. Its products included software for analyzing
work patterns and forecasting staffing needs based on prior store
experience.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition came IMB's founders, Frank Perlmutter, 41,
now division vice president, and Geoffrey Palmer, 42, now in charge
of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Perlmutter sees a strong sales future in consumer-related
industries such as health care, entertainment, hosptality, and
banking _ sectors that, like retailers, have staffing needs that
fluctuate by day, week, month, and year.
</P>
<P>
   Simplex also is developing lines that incorporate features from
the company's security products, including use of biometric devices
that identify employees by fingerprint or palm-print.
</P>
<P>
   Biometrics are under review at Kronos, too, but the firm does
not see much demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks good on TV and people like to talk about it,'' says
Lacy. But Kizielewicz says personnel managers seem to ``be moving
away from the big-brother climate, from wanting to watch what
people are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
