<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSER OF THE DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you had invested $1,000 in Reebok International at the
beginning of the decade it would be worth just $420 today.
</P>
<P>
   Like you, I salivated reading that if we had invested $1,000 in
EMC Corp. at the start of the '90s, it would be worth a
mind-boggling $697,385. Or $612,881 if we had put our dough in CMGI
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the other side of investing, the dogs of the
'90s. Among the name-brand Massachusetts companies, Stride Rite is
down 62 percent; Polaroid, down 61 percent; Reebok, 58 percent; and
Stone &AMP; Webster, 57 percent. There is one thing, however, that
distinguishes Reebok from its fellow hound dogs: Stone &AMP; Webster,
Stride Rite and Polaroid have replaced their chief executives, some
more than once, in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   At Reebok, Paul Fireman still reigns supreme. What does this man
have to do to get fired? (Hint: It doesn't hurt that Fireman and
his wife still own 20 percent of the company.)
</P>
<P>
   This was a company that in the late '80s overtook mighty Nike as
the largest athletic footwear company in America. In the last
decade, Reebok has fallen to number three in the world market,
steadily losing share to Nike and other reinvigorated brands such
as Adidas. Sales have gone nowhere since 1994; profits have
declined every year since then. The stock, which peaked at 52 in
1997, is at 8 today, placing it fourth from the bottom among
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies over the decade. Employment stands
at 6,000, down from 6,950.
</P>
<P>
   When the history of business in the '90s is written, any list of
best quotes has to include this recent jewel: ``We have gotten off
course over the last eight to 10 years,'' Fireman told analysts
three weeks ago, ``and I want to bring it (Reebok) back.''
</P>
<P>
   Off track for eight to 10 years! Try that one on your boss.
</P>
<P>
   Fireman has long expoused the idea of chaos as a way of
management, his belief that constant change and turmoil creates
energy. Chaos is just what he's gotten. In a business where brand
and image is critical, Reebok's brand stands for nothing. Nike
means performance and winning. Nike's stock, by the way, is up
roughly 600 percent this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok's message of the moment is Traxtar, a high-tech gimmick
that uses a computer chip to measure how fast children run and how
high they jump. The shoes come complete with lights and music,
which is played off an oval pod on the tongue of the shoe. Who
knows what will strike Fireman's fancy next week?
</P>
<P>
   Managing through chaos has produced a revolving-door among
executives, most of whom quit in frustration with his flip-flops
and meddling, which can go right down to fiddling with the menu in
the company cafeteria. According to one list I have, the number two
post in the company has turned over nine times since 1986, with
Fireman himself holding the position three times. Ten different
executives have headed US/North American operations. The top
marketing person, a key spot in a brand company like Reebok, has
turned over and incredible 13 times since 1985.The one constant
through the mess: Paul Fireman.
</P>
<P>
   There's no one else to blame, except maybe the board, which has
been Fireman's enabler. For the record, here is that board: Thomas
M. Ryan, chairman of CVS Corp.; Mannie L. Jackson, chairman of the
Harlem Globetrotters; William G. Glavin, president emeritus of
Babson College; Richard G. Lesser, executive vice president of TJX
Cos.; Geoffrey Nunes, former senior vice president of Millipore
Corp.; retired Reebok executive Paul Duncan; and Fireman.
</P>
<P>
   Failure is relative at a certain level in Corporate America. As
the decade closes, Fireman is about to move Reebok into a new
headquarters in Canton, himself into a 27,000-square-foot palace
off the 11th green at The Country Club in Brookline. But you would
be hard-pressed to find a top executive still drawing a paycheck at
a major Massachusetts company who has done worse in the '90s. Abe
Gosman comes to mind, but then he's gone from Meditrust, too. It's
time _ past time _ that Reebok found a message and stuck with it.
My suggestion: Fire Fireman.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a certain ring, no?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach me at 617-929-2902 or sbailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
