<HEADLINE>
KRONOS' TIME CLOCK WAS AHEAD OF ITS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKEREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Two years ago, when he was named chairman of
Kronos Inc.'s Year 2000 committee, Paul Lacy dreaded what he might
face.
</P>
<P>
   But as his internal committee reviewed the dozens of product
lines that Kronos had put on the market to record and analyze time
and productivity, it made a fortuitous discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Almost by chance, one of Kronos's engineers had anticipated 20
years in advance that these products would still be in use when the
calendar turned from 1999 to 2000, and that they should be
programmed to withstand that millennial change.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, while Kronos will have two dozen employees on duty
New Year's Eve and well into New Year's Day to answer calls from
any customers who encounter Y2K problems, Lacy plans to be on
vacation at an unidentified Gulf Coast resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have my cell phone with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer responsible for the find, Larry Krakauer, says he
was not looking for Y2K difficulties nor did he anticipate any. ``I
didn't realize what a big deal it was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was how to keep Kronos's first product, a
card-punching digital time clock that stored payroll data in
embedded computer chips, from occasionally locking up and refusing
to move ahead when it was supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at the software I saw that it was reading time
internally in the same way people do _ in minutes, hours, the day
of the month, the month itself, and then the year.'' This meant the
system required several mathematical bases to compute dates _ 60
for minutes, 12 for months, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it and said, `This is a mess. This is not the way
to do it,' '' Krakauer recalls. ``So I changed the representation
of time inside to the number of minutes elapsed since Jan. 1,
1900.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more work was needed to ensure that this time would be
converted accurately to calendar time. But testing proved the
revisions would pass 2000 with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must confess I didn't go all the way,'' he said. ``I used
the rule that every fourth year is a leap year. I knew that our
clocks would malfunction in 2100.'' In fact, because of a small
revision made since then, they could lock up as soon as 2079.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we haven't really tested for this yet,'' Krakauer said.
``Our hands have been full, testing all the products we have put
out since then'' that might have other Y2K bugs.
</P>
<P>
   For those, Kronos either has distributed new software or patches
designed to correct them, or warned customers that their problems
might not be repairable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
