<HEADLINE>
THESE DAYS, DON'T THINK A $100 STOCK HAS TO SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when you could buy at least one share of practically
any stock in America for under $100?
</P>
<P>
   Those days, though still a relatively fresh memory, are gone.
That fact doesn't mean much on its own, but it says a lot about
changes in the investing world and in stock markets themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The number of US stocks that would have been considered
unusually expensive on a per-share basis just a few years ago is
exploding to levels that appear to be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   An unofficial Boston Capital survey this week turned up 115
common stocks that traded at prices in excess of $100 per share, a
level once exceeded by only a rare few companies. In that pricey
company, 19 traded above $200 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a time in 15 years of trading small stocks
when I've seen so many with absolute prices that are so high,''
said Stephen Demirjian of Westfield Capital Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those stocks are new to the market in 1999, initial
public offerings that took off, such as Sycamore Networks Inc. of
Chelmsford (239 1/4 per share) and Akamai Technologies Inc. of
Cambridge (217 per share). More often than not, they are the shares
of technology companies focused on the Internet,
telecommunications, or other hot areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's illustrative of the speculative frenzy in the
market,'' said Syl Marquardt, research director at John Hancock
Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Investors measure a company's actual value by mutiplying its
per-share price by the number of shares outstanding. So the
influence of per-share prices alone falls into the realm of
psychology rather than financial fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, companies whose stocks rose to a high level
declared a stock split that lowered the per-share price, with no
effect on the actual value of the company. There were simply more
shares trading at a lower price.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom suggested that very high per-share prices,
generally over $100, discouraged people from buying stock. It was
easier to imagine a $50 stock appreciating, while many investors
would feel they had already missed an opportunity at $150 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no textbook to look this up in, but there really was a
sense that at $100 you ought to consider splitting,'' said Jim
Weiss, chief investment officer for equities at State Street
Research &AMP; Management. ``That notion is gone, but nothing has
replaced it.''
</P>
<P>
   What changed? Explosive run-ups in many tech stocks made the
appreciate-and-split timetable hard to follow and all but
eliminated any psychological barriers inhibiting investors from
buying at high per-share prices.
</P>
<P>
   Here's all you need to know: Both Sycamore Networks and Akamai
traded above 200 the very first day they hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a class of stocks now that you'd call the
nouveau riche,'' said Karl Mills, vice chairman and investment
strategist at Jurika &AMP; Voyles.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said the 56 stocks included in the Russell 1000 index that
trade above $100 per share have appreciated, on average, by 265
percent this year. The rest of the stocks in the index are up about
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. Stocks with expensive per-share prices
actually seem to enjoy a certain cachet in today's market, stamped
as champions in a new-economy world.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few of the stock market's huge winners and how they
are dealing with splits. Commerce One Inc., which went public in
July at 21 and now trades at $423, is planning one for later this
month. So is Ariba Inc., a June IPO that hit the market at 23 and
now trades at 234 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   But both splits will create reduced per-share prices that still
exceed $100, based on current valuations. Rather than a price
ceiling that should not be exceeded for long, the $100 per share
figure appears to be a floor for many newer technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have seen $100 stocks go to $200 or $300 or $400,''
said Weiss. ``It isn't automatically suggested as a top as it might
have years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the glitz, there is a darker reason why some companies
are less inclined to reduce the price of their shares through
splits. What happens if a company splits its stock to a lower
per-share level and then sees a market correction bite 40 percent
out of its value?
</P>
<P>
   That is a distinct possibility when companies with no profit
and, sometimes, practically no revenue, trade at
multibillion-dollar valuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the thing gets destroyed, what do you end up with?'' asked
Demirjian. ``You've got a $10 stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors tend to think of aggressive technology companies like
Qualcomm Inc. (421 1/4), Juniper Networks Inc. (330 1/4), and CMGI
Inc. of Andover (211 7/8) when it comes to high share prices. But
that old $100 barrier is being broken by well-established older
companies as well.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. (111 9/16) and even Dow Chemical Co. (123
5/16) are on a long list of older companies that carry historically
high per-share prices today.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric Co. split its stock 2-for-1 twice this decade,
in 1994 and 1997. In both instances, GE took the action about four
months after its stock price cracked 100, always before it reached
110.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way it's working out this year. GE shares, which
finished Tuesday at 149 7/8, have closed below 100 just 15 times in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
