<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VF REVISITS `VALLEY OF DOLLS'; RS VIEWS Y2K FROM A TO Z 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dirty little secret about the '60s is that they weren't
really The Sixties _ you know, long hair, revolution, and all that.
Most people supported the war. Most rock groups sold fewer records
than Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass. Wilhelm and Charles Reich
together didn't have a tenth of the readers Jacqueline Susann did.
In fact, to plumb the egregious heart of mainstream '60s popular
culture you could do worse than look to the author of ``Valley of
the Dolls'' and ``The Love Machine.'' Amy Fine Collins gives Susann
her dishy due in the January Vanity Fair. Her look back at La
Jackie (who died in 1974) is but the latest instance of how VF
occasionally has managed to refresh its formula of oohing and
aahing over Eurotrash and the latest Miramax discovery. Think of
such comparably offbeat and intelligent pieces as Nick Tosches's
meditation (for lack of a better word) on Sonny Liston or Michael
Herr's memoir of Stanley Kubrick.
</P>
<P>
   Also of note here, Marjorie Williams shows why Terry McAuliffe
is the perfect man to be Bill Clinton's wealthiest best friend _ or
should that be best wealthiest friend? _ and why McAuliffe's
aptitude does neither man much credit. On the cover is Cameron Diaz
(don't be fooled by the black hair).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Y minus 17 and counting: This
year-end/century-end/millennium-end stuff just won't go away. So
Rolling Stone (Dec. 30-Jan. 6) quite sensibly turns the whole
business into a party. The editors invited an impressively eclectic
guest list, from A (Amos, Tori) to Z (Zinn, Howard), to weigh in on
matters millennial. It's a clever conceit, one that makes what's
basically an old-fashioned symposium seem like something far
sexier. The artwork plays up the party angle with a Sgt. Pepperish
cover and an array of suitably festive drawings (one of them
manages to make U2's Bono look like _ I'm not making this up _
Nelson Rockefeller). As with any party, the true highlight of the
evening is the post-mortem: deciding who was best dressed, worst
behaved, and so on. So here goes.
</P>
<P>
   Most surprising statement. ``Heroes: Sen. Strom Thurmond has
been able to stay afloat all these years, and he's great for our
country'' _ James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Least surprising. ``Hardest thing in the world when I wake up in
the morning is to say, `I feel good' '' _ ditto.
</P>
<P>
   Scariest thought. ``Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young records will
be listened to for many years'' _ David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   Least likely to request ``Under My Thumb.'' ``I don't think that
our music is sexist, but I think there are a couple of lines that
might be so construed'' _ Mick Jagger.
</P>
<P>
   Least likely to request a Shania Twain song. ``All the new
female country singers sound alike, and the songs don't say
nothing. And who wants to see a navel?'' _ Loretta Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to request ``Convoy.'' ``I'd like to see the whole
Web thing brought down to size, to what it really is, which is, of
course, CB radio'' _ Bill Maher.
</P>
<P>
   Best millennium product placement. ``I use Viagra and am dating
twins. . . . Would I do ads saying that I'm doing this? You
betcha!'' _ Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest party pooper. ``I find the whole millennium thing really
arbitrary. Billions of Chinese people are celebrating the year 5970
or whatever'' _ R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest in-your-face to readers. Putting the magazine's table of
contents on Page 33 (How about a new slogan, Jann: ``All the
advertising that fits'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The RS preceding this one was a special photo issue, and
rightfully so. One of the things that sets rock apart from every
other kind of music _ except for maybe (God help us) show tunes _
is the importance of the visual element. You can listen to Johannes
Brahms or Jacques Brel or a Javanese gamelan, and if the experience
is purely aural, that in no way detracts from a listener's
appreciation. But try to imagine listening to Elvis unaware of his
sneer or Parliament unacquainted with P-Funk couture or (God help
us, again, but for different reasons) Marilyn Manson minus the
Marilyn Manson-ness: unh-unh.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz is a special category. While not beholden to appearances,
it has a sumptuous visual side _ everything from Dizzy's bent
trumpet to Lady Day's gardenia _ that has attracted many talented
photographers. Roy DeCarava, Herman Leonard, William P. Gottlieb,
William Claxton, Milt Hinton, Francis Wolff, and Chuck Stewart are
only the best-known among them. How could they resist? The music is
epic chiaroscuro, an endless interplay of light and dark (there's a
reason all the great jazz photos are in black and white),
beautifully suited to the ministrations of light meter and lens. It
comes as no surprise, then, to learn that W. Eugene Smith, one of
the most admired American photojournalists of the century, tried
his hand at jazz photography, too. DoubleTake (Fall) reports on
Smith's involvement in the New York loft scene during the '50s _ he
lived in a building where several prominent musicians had rehearsal
space _ and how he came to obsessively photograph his friends and
neighbors. Two-dozen examples of his work are printed here. Also in
this issue, two very short stories by that most distinguished
senior practitioner of the genre, William Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You have to be fairly old _ or have your clicker preset to
American Movie Classics _ to have an idea who Victor Mature was.
Perhaps the best way to describe him is Sylvester Stallone with a
sense of humor. For a decade or so, he was a very big star _ and
then, well, a big grin and an even bigger set of pecs would take
you only so far in Hollywood during the late '40s and early '50s.
He did have his moments, though even in his triumphs he got
sidetracked somehow. In ``Kiss of Death,'' Richard Widmark pushes a
wheelchair-bound old lady down the stairs (in 1947!), so that's
what people remember instead of Mature's uncharacteristically
affecting performance as a crook trying to go straight. In ``My
Darling Clementine,'' as Doc Holliday, he's history's beefiest
consumptive (when Mature coughs blood into a handkerchief, it's a
respiratory eruption), but one can argue that that very haleness
makes the beautiful abstractness of Henry Fonda's Wyatt Earp seem
all the more ethereal. Mature, you might say, was not so much great
as the cause of greatness in others.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he died last summer _ don't expect him at RS' New Year's
party _ and in Film Comment (Nov./Dec.) David Thomson takes his
risible/robust measure. At a time when it seems every other
Hollywood release gets treated by Premiere and Entertainment Weekly
with a bated-breath awe worthy of ``Citizen Kane,'' it's no small
satisfaction to see a career of such amiable junkiness appreciated
for just what it was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
