<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MUD-BOS &LR;      12-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTANTINE'S `MUD' IS A GRITTY MASTERPIECE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BLOOD MUD 
By K. C. Constantine 
Mysterious Press, 375 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Blood Mud'' is the 15th novel K. C. Constantine has written
about Rocksburg, a town in central Pennsylvania that is still full
of ethnic particularity but that also reflects every general
problem facing America and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning, the series, centered on police chief Mario
Balzic, has always pushed the envelope of the genre because the
pseudonymous Constantine appears to be a policeman or a public
official in a town very like Rocksburg. Constantine is more erratic
than other writers of mystery series because he refuses to repeat
himself or to turn his most successful books into a formula for all
the others. Instead, as Balzic ages and the society around him
changes, Constantine incorporates these factors into the stories.
His failures result from the same cause as his extraordinary
successes: Some kind of reality is always exploding through
genre-based expectations. ``Reality,'' remarks a policeman without
illusions, ``is way . . . better at makin' up stuff than I'll ever
be.''
</P>
<P>
   This new book, which is some kind of masterpiece, virtually
leaves crime fiction behind _ though shady characters abound, and
Balzic has emerged from restless retirement to investigate the
robbery of a gun store out at the mall. The book offers a really
boffo beginning, when a sleazy city councilman delivers a classic
1973 Mustang of dubious provenance to the girlfriend he met behind
a glass wall in an adult entertainment center. She could care less
about the beauties of a car that is probably older than she _ why
should she want to be reminded of how much mileage she has on
herself? She makes it clear that her councilman is going to see no
further action until she gets the brand new, bright red car she's
bargained for. Once again, Constantine tells this story in the kind
of raw-nerve, character-exposing dialogue in which his only real
rivals have been Elmore Leonard and the late George V. Higgins.
``For givin' you back your hope and your courage and your energy
and your stamina, for this I get a secondhand car? I don't think
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Balzic's investigation is proceeding in the kind of disorderly
order one expects from him when there is a surprise. He's on his
way to to interview someone, but wakes up in the Conemaugh General
Hospital after suriving an ``event'' an earlier generation would
have called a heart attack. Balzic's clogged arteries, silted by
``blood mud,'' are described in graphic detail, and so are the
medical procedures by which they are cleared. That takes only a few
pages: Clearing the mud from his psychology becomes Balzic's
principal task, and the job is not complete by the time the book is
done. Balzic can change his diet, but it's hard to change the way
his mind functions, and it's hard not to feel the stress when
trying to operate out of principle in a society that doesn't have
many any more, and where politics have messed up priorities _ there
aren't enough policemen anymore because politicians have diverted
so much money into stadiums for profit-making sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Balzic's tenuous hold on life parallels society's weak
allegiance to principle and values; society is silted up with
greed. There are comic set pieces in ``Blood Mud'' to rival the
opening row between the singleminded councilman and his determined
doxy, and there's lots of tough, dirty talk, and ultimately a rough
and approximate sort of justice, which is at once satisfying and
disturbing. Although Balzic is finally able to piece together what
went down out there at the mall, there's almost nothing he can do
about it; officially, what happened there never happened at all. As
the unillusioned cop says to Balzic: ``Only ones we put away are
the ones have to take a number and get in line in the public
defender's office, that's all. Yeah.'' All Balzic can do is a few
good turns along the way, but he can't save anyone, really _ except
maybe himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all that is bleak and black, Balzic's saving
grace is his own character, and his relationship with his wife,
Ruth. Some Mario/Ruth episodes in the previous books have gotten a
little sticky, but one of the miracles of ``Blood Mud'' is how
Constantine can make us feel the sustained deep harmonies of love
that lie below a surface ruffled by steady bickering _ harmonies
that lie below the level of hearing, but which you can feel.
Constantine's unobtrusive achievement in these scenes, and in most
of ``Blood Mud,'' is well beyond anything that anyone but a major
novelist would attempt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
