<HEADLINE>
STOVESIDE READING, 1999 STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Marion Cunningham until her 50th birthday to find
something she loved. ``I barely got out of high school,'' she says.
Afterward, she worked at all sorts of things. At one point she was
a switchboard operator, then she worked on the stock exchange in
San Francisco, and she had a brief stint at an insurance company.
``I was too hyper to sit,'' says the 77-year-old cookbook author
known as the modern Fannie Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came World War II. She saw a sign at the Union station near
her house. ``Replace a man,'' it read. So she did. She pumped gas
for two years. ``I was going to buy a service station at one
point,'' she said during a recent visit to Boston. ``But my husband
said, `No matter how many baths you take, you will still smell like
40-weight oil.' '' She leans across the dinner table and says
softly, ``I never go to the station and not pump my own gas.''
</P>
<P>
   That must be quite a sight. Tall, slim, and elegant, Marion
Cunningham lives in Walnut Creek, Calif., and puts 2,500 miles a
month on her Jaguar, driving it into the city for dinner, mostly to
accompany San Francisco Chronicle restaurant critic Michael Bauer
on his rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham began cooking seriously when she flew to Oregon to
take a class with the late James Beard. The class was a way for her
to overcome social phobias that had plagued her for years and kept
her close to home. Beard was so impressed with her that he asked
her to become his assistant and travel around the country with him.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she writes, cooks, and teaches in the modest house that
she and her late husband built 38 years ago. It sits on an acre. A
160-year-old oak tree graces the property, and she loves the place
and won't ever sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen is very small. People come in and say, `Where's
your lab?' '' In it, she tested all the recipes for the 1979
revision of ``The Fannie Farmer Cookbook,'' ``The Fannie Farmer
Baking Book,'' ``The Breakfast Book,'' and, just recently,
``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   Working on ``Learning'' showed her how the world has changed.
Her students didn't know what saute meant, nor shred, nor simmer.
``Forget blanch. Fold? They didn't know that either,'' she said. A
recipe called for soft butter, and one student she was teaching, a
woman who ran an immensely successful business, searched the dairy
case in the local supermarket for ``soft butter.'' Another wanted
``to learn to cook because I stand up to eat at night. I want to
sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the baking powder biscuits that turned them around, she
said. ``When they saw those blobs of dough go puff in the oven,''
it gave them courage to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham herself has kept up incredible momentum all these
years, largely by staying involved with her colleagues, keeping in
touch with them by phone, and working hard to stay fit.
</P>
<P>
   She rises at dawn and walks Rover, her yellow Lab, by the creek
that gave her town its name. ``Then I swim every day in an outdoor
pool. It sounds more rugged than it is. Actually it is cold when
it's cold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shop every day whether I need to or not.'' Because she works
at home, grocery shopping gives her a break. ``And I talk on the
phone a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   These days her talk is about a cookbook she and many other Bay
Area pastry chefs are working on. They're all part of the Baker's
Dozen, a 10-year-old project that collects no dues and writes no
newsletter. Each member pays $5 a year for stamps, and the group
runs without a leader. ``The project is to learn from one
another,'' said Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, members began compiling a book of their recipes, which
they sold to Broadway Books for a large advance. They may buy a
retirement community for bakers, said Cunningham. ``I'm the point
person on the book.'' It keeps her on the telephone for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I die,'' she said, ``you better put a mobile phone in
that coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grace Young was raised in a Cantonese household not too far from
San Francisco's Chinatown, when most of California's Chinese
families were Cantonese. The Youngs were so traditional, she says,
that ``the recipes my parents cook today are the same recipes my
grandparents and their grandparents cooked.'' Like any red-blooded
American teenager, Young made sure she broke the chain, first by
eating pizzas and hamburgers, then, as an adult, by incorporating
many non-Chinese dishes into her repertory. By the time she was
living in New York on her own, all the rice she needed was stored
in a 5-pound canister beside the sugar and flour.
</P>
<P>
   Then her mother came to visit. ``Where is the rest of the
rice?'' she asked her daughter. ``A pound of rice was all I ever
needed,'' writes Young in ``The Wisdom of the Chinese Kitchen:
Classic Family Recipes for Celebration and Healing'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster). ``But, in that moment,'' Young continues, ``I realized
how far I had journeyed from my Chinese roots.'' Rice meant many
things. A 100-pound sack assured the family that there was enough
to eat. When fruit wasn't ripe, Young's mother would bury it in the
rice overnight. Her father mashed cooked rice with water when the
children needed glue.
</P>
<P>
   Young wanted to know more. She began by asking a friend to
photograph the traditional New Year's celebration at her parents'
home. Then she asked all her cousins which of their childhood
dishes they ate as adults and whether they knew how to cook them.
The cousins knew as little as she did.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of going over the recipes with her mother, other
things came to life. She learned her family history, and she
finally understood why her mother would serve certain dishes and
insist they were good for her. At the time, of course, she was only
half listening.
</P>
<P>
   Now she wishes she had been paying attention. ``The women in my
family are body fortunetellers,'' said Young during a recent visit
to Cambridge, Mass. to address the Radcliffe Culinary Friends.
``They can look at anyone and tell what soup they need.'' The
Cantonese, she said, have taken soup to an art form.
</P>
<P>
   They used them for healing and balance according to the ancient
theory of yin and yang. ``Yang foods are warming, invigorating, and
powerful,'' she writes. ``Many are high in fat and spicy.'' Typical
yang foods are butter, chicken, lamb, and ginger. ``Yin foods are
cooling, soothing, and mild, and characteristically more
vegetarian.'' These include crab, watermelon, cucumber, tofu, and
bean sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Steaming, poaching, and boiling tend to be yin. Sauteing,
roasting, and barbecuing are yang.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the people in the West are yang,'' she said.
``Coffee is yang. The American diet is yang. One has a tendency to
over-yang oneself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fundamental to keep yin and yang in balance,'' she
continued. To do this, you can eat whole grains, which are
considered neutral, or any of the ``neutral'' or healing soups from
the Cantonese diet. Pasta, which Americans live on, is ``barely
neutral,'' she said, because it's been processed.
</P>
<P>
   Young's family sips ``yun'' (soothing) soups, which are said to
restore balance in the body, ``like a cough drop that soothes a
parched throat,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Some soups are drunk year round, others during the season in
which the vegetables are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   As a girl, Young preferred Campbell's chicken noodle soup to
most of her mother's soups, especially one made with mustard greens
and sweet potato, also simmered for three hours and thought to ward
off flus. She decided to make it again while she was writing
``Wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To my surprise, I found it soothing and comforting,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still living in Manhattan, Young is nearly back to the diet of
her childhood, which is a challenge, considering she's test kitchen
director and head of food photography at Rebus Inc., a book
packager that specializes in cookbooks and health news letters. ``I
used to eat Thai, French, Chinese, and Tex-Mex food. Every time I
went home to my parents, the foods agreed with me more.''
</P>
<P>
   American cooks, she said, are mixing ingredients from East and
West and ``grabbing at all these elements.'' Food is being
assembled without any strong traditions behind it.
</P>
<P>
   What she likes about Chinese cooking is the thoughtfulness that
goes into it. ``They put ingredients together that make perfect
sense,'' she said. When she stops to think about it, she remembers
what an old process this is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figured it out 4,000 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl who ate pizza came home.
</P>
</TEXT>
