<HEADLINE>
CHEF'S BOOKS PLAY TO A RAREFIED AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With Food-Recipes; 2 takes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost as soon as there were restaurant chefs, they wrote
cookbooks for the rest of us. This year's crop of experts' advice
to amateurs tells us a lot about the cuisine of some of today's
finest restaurants. But does that mean we can cook the recipes in
home kitchens? Well, yes and no, in some cases. And in some cases,
just no.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with ``The French Laundry Cookbook'' by Thomas
Keller (Artisan, $50), a monumental book dedicated to the mastery
of the restaurant's chef-owner. Weighing in at 5 pounds, 4.7
ounces, and measuring just under a foot square, it runs to 323
pages and thoroughly explains Keller's tasting-menu cuisine and his
philosophy. Going to his Yountville restaurant in the Napa Valley
is exactly like entering a shrine. For several hours, the diner is
presented with up to 10 small and elaborate dishes, each more
gravity-defying in construction. The book sets a similar tone.
</P>
<P>
   But making these flights of fancy _ and making enough of them to
feed a table of six guests _ would tax even the most expert
amateur. Here's an example: a salad of petite summer tomatoes with
tomato sorbet, garlic tuiles, and tomato coulis. The peeled cherry
tomatoes and tomato sorbet, in a zeppelin shape, are stacked ever
so delicately between a garlic crisp and a brioche crouton, all
resting in a pool of tomato coulis surrounded by a circlet of basil
oil. It's an amazing architectural feat, even following the
author's tips on trimming the tomatoes to sit flat in the stack.
Now, for you home cooks throwing a dinner party for six, after you
engineer that first tomato tower, do it five more times and get
them all to the table. Be careful the family cat doesn't trip you.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this beautifully photographed book might best be saved
for bedside reading rather than the kitchen. Anyway, that's what
I'll do.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Boulud, another giant of French cuisine in America, has
produced a very different kind of book, ``Cafe Boulud Cookbook:
French-American Recipes for the Home Cook'' by Boulud and Dorie
Greenspan (Scribner, $35). Despite the sophistication of Boulud's
restaurant cuisine, these recipes are eminently doable. I found at
least a dozen I was eager to try, and one, scallops on crushed
potatoes, sauce charcuterie, definitely has been added to my
repertory. I substituted tiny Cape scallops for the larger sea
variety, because they're impossible to resist in season, but
otherwise I followed the recipe. The sauce involves onions, red
wine vinegar, boiled ham, and tiny slivers of French cornichons; it
may sound odd, but it was wonderful with the scallops and the
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, the coauthor, said in a phone interview recently that
the chef's intention was to create workable dishes that reflect the
heritage of his family farm and village near Lyon, France. Adapting
Boulud's restaurant work involved ``deconstructing it for the home
cook, like a puzzle,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   She explains that a recipe for duck civet originally called for
marinating the duck overnight in three bottles of red wine with
many vegetables, then discarding the marinade and adding more wine
and cut-up vegetables to cook the ragout. After she and Boulud
discussed the idea that a home cook might be hesitant about
discarding so much wine, not to mention cutting up a multitude of
vegetables twice, Greenspan said, Boulud recalled a civet his
mother had made at home. In this, and in the finished recipe, the
duck is cooked right in the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   The other published powerhouse chef this year is Charlie Trotter
of Chicago, who has previously written coffee-table-size volumes on
seafood, vegetables, and desserts. This year's ``The Kitchen
Sessions With Charlie Trotter'' (Ten Speed Press, $29.95) is a
companion volume to Trotter's PBS televison series of the same
name. In his restaurant, Trotter, like Keller, presents diners with
a series of tiny dishes, imaginative and highly complicated. But,
probably because doing the television series forced him to adapt
his food to what a home cook could actually do, this cookbook is
much more accessible than his previous ones. Not easy, mind you,
but plausible. And, as Greenspan said of Boulud's recipes, you can
mix and match the components of the dishes. I found that the
tamarind and orange juice glaze on roast chicken added a lovely
tang, but decided to pass on the apple-onion-potato puree. Instead,
I caramelized the onions and apples for a sweet-savory side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Ming Tsai of Blue Ginger in Wellesley, Mass. says he benefited
from having already adapted many of his restaurant recipes for his
Food Network TV show, ``East Meets West.'' His book, ``Blue Ginger:
East Meets West Cooking With Ming Tsai'' by Tsai and Arthur Boehm
(Clarkson Potter, $32.50), covers a lot of territory, brimming over
with recipes and tips to help the home cook. It ranges from fairly
simple dishes to an ``over-the-top'' section with specialties from
his Wellesley fusion restaurant. ``I tried to make a concentrated
effort,'' Tsai said in a recent phone interview from Chicago, where
he was appearing on a 10-city book tour, ``to demystify the Chinese
pantry.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite chapter, he said, is on dim sum, his favorite way
to eat. For many cooks, even attempting dim sum seems ambitious,
but Tsai's recipes are ``not traditional'' and, as he says, would
make a good cocktail-party offering for the holidays. Tsai
simplifies and lightens salt-and-pepper shrimp, something my family
loves in Chinese restaurants, by flash-frying the shrimp in a small
amount of oil in a wok. It eliminates the need for a deep fryer,
uncommon these days in home kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Italian food, even in restaurants, is really home food, and chef
Michael Chiarello uses that to his advantage in ``The Tra Vigne
Cookbook: Seasons in the California Wine Country'' (Chronicle,
$35). His recipes weave through the seasons and present a variety
of ways to use ingredients. There are dinner party dishes like
monkfish with roasted garlic polenta and tomato broth. But others,
such as fusilli Michelangelo, which the chef named after his
mother's nickname for him, are gussied-up renditions of simple
family fare. This medley of tomatoes and mushrooms zapped with
dried tomatoes, lots of herbs, and a little balsamic vinegar is a
dish my teenagers love.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters takes the same tack as Boulud, using her cafe
recipes adapted to home kitchens in her latest book, ``Chez Panisse
Cafe Cookbook'' (HarperCollins, $34). As Waters said in an
interview earlier this year, she thinks cookbooks are read on
several levels, sometimes by cooks creating the dish in their
kitchen and sometimes for enjoyment or learning. So her recipes
range from mere lists of ingredients with a plan for using them to
fairly complicated procedures for making head cheese.
</P>
<P>
   My colleague who made Waters's braised beef short ribs with
gremolata reported that they were wonderful. The restaurant-style
instructions on browning the ribs before braising were clever, and
the gremolata, a mixture of parsley, lemon zest, and chopped
garlic, added a great burst of flavor. But the recipe calls for
testing the meat after 1 1/2 hours, much too early, my colleague
says, since the ribs take at least 2 1/2 hours to become properly
tender.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about the book, and all her books, is that
whether simple or complex, there's no talking down to the readers.
Her plain-spoken personality shines through. Reassuring to the home
chef is the assumption that even restaurant food can be adapted for
us amateurs. As Greenspan says, good food always takes a
commitment, but ``almost anything can be done at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
