<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-RECIPES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-15 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Serves 4.  
 
SHEPHERD'S SALAD
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Italian Country Table'' by Lynne Rossetto
Kasper.
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 thin slice mild coppa, soppressata, or hard salami, cut into
thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium to large red onion, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   A 4-inch branch fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   6 large fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine vinegar, or more as needed
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, sliced into thin rings
</P>
<P>
   Ice water
</P>
<P>
   1 large head Bibb lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 large head romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups mixed wild greens or 1 small head curly endive
</P>
<P>
   2 small inner stalks celery with leaves, cut on the diagonal
into thin slices
</P>
<P>
   1 small fennel bulb, cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound Italian or American sheep cheese, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked cannellini, borlotti, or organic pinto beans or a
15-ounce can of beans
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing: Heat the oil in a 1-quart saucepan over medium
heat. Add the salami, onion, rosemary, and sage, and saute until
the onion colors. Add the garlic and red pepper and stir for a few
seconds, then add the vinegar. Boil 4 minutes. Stir in 1 cup of the
stock and boil down to nothing. Add the rest of the stock and boil
2 minutes, or until the flavors blend and deepen. Taste for balance
and season with salt and pepper. Cover the pan and set aside until
needed, or up to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad: Immerse the onion in ice water and refrigerate
about 45 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and thoroughly dry the greens, setting aside any bruised or
coarse leaves for other dishes. Arrange the greens on a large
platter. Scatter the celery over the salad and tuck clusters of the
fennel strips into it. If necessary, the salad can be covered and
chilled up to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before serving, cluster the salami strips into seven to
nine bundles, tucking them in here and there in the salad. Do the
same with the drained onions and with the cheese strips. Nest large
spoonfuls of the beans in several of the lettuce leaves. Sprinkle
the salad lightly with salt and pepper, and set it out.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the dressing to a boil. Taste for seasoning again, this
time checking if it needs a tablespoon or so of vinegar. Present it
in a deep bowl, and spoon it over the salad just before serving.
Serves 6 as an antipasto; 4 as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUSILLI MICHELANGELO
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Tra Vigne Cookbook'' by Michael Chiarello.
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dried tomatoes, not packed in oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound dried fusilli
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups diced mixed mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup loosely packed fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 cups arugula
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pine nuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper flakes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Combine the tomatoes, boiling water, sugar, vinegar, and
marjoram in a small bowl. Let the tomatoes rehydrate until soft,
about 10 minutes. Drain well, squeezing out excess liquid. Cut the
tomatoes into fine julienne. Set aside. Discard marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add salt and the pasta and
cook until al dente, about 10 minutes. Drain, reserving about 1/2
cup of the pasta cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   While the pasta is cooking, heat the oil in a large saute pan
over medium-high heat until hot. Add the mushrooms and do not move
them until they begin to brown, about 1 minute. Then saute until
brown all over, about 5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Add
the garlic and saute briefly until light brown. Add the basil and
julienned tomatoes and cook quickly, pulling the pan off the heat
as necessary so the tomatoes do not burn.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomato sauce and bring to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the pasta is done, add it to the tomato-mushroom
mixture and toss well with 1/2 cup of the cheese and the reserved
pasta cooking water. Add 3 cups of the arugula and toss until
barely wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into a warm serving bowl or onto a platter and scatter the
remaining arugula on top. Sprinkle with the nuts and dust with a
little cheese. Serve immediately and pass the remaining cheese at
the table with a shaker of red pepper flakes. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEMON CHICKEN WITH TARRAGON
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Smith &AMP; Hawken Gardeners' Community Cookbook'' by
Victoria Wise.
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves (about 1 1/2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon finely chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 saltine crackers, finely crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken in a lightly greased baking pan large enough
to hold the pieces in one uncrowded layer.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a small saucepan. Stir in the mustard, lemon
juice, tarragon, salt, and pepper and pour the mixture over the
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the crushed crackers and cheese and sprinkle over
the chicken. Bake until the chicken is cooked through and the
topping is golden, about 35 minutes. Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CAPE COD COFFEE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Family Baker'' by Susan Purdy.
</P>
<P>
   Choose one topping:
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon-sugar made with 2 tablespoons granulated sugar and 1/2
teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Or ... streusel made with 1/2 cup flour mixed with 1/2 cup
sugar, pinch of salt, 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon, 1/4 cup soft,
unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   Butter-flavor no-stick vegetable spray or solid shortening for
preparing pan
</P>
<P>
   3 cups fruit: 2 large apples, such as Golden Delicious, peeled,
cored, and coarsely chopped ( 1/2-inch cubes) plus 1 cup fresh or
whole frozen cranberries (or peeled, pitted, and cut-up peaches and
blueberries, or unpeeled, pitted, chopped plums or nectarines)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup walnuts, coarsely chopped (optional; for use with apples
and cranberries)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in the center of the oven and preheat it to 350
degrees. Coat a 9-by-9-inch pan with vegetable spray or shortening.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare one topping: Either toss together cinnamon and sugar in
a cup or make streusel by pinching together all the ingredients
with your fingers or a fork until crumbs are formed.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: In a large bowl, mix all the fruit and add the
nuts, if using.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour and baking powder,
salt, and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl with a whisk or an electric mixer, beat together
the eggs, butter, vanilla, and sugar. Stir in all the dry
ingredients and mix only until combined. Gently mix the fruit into
the batter, stirring only once or twice; do not overbeat. The
batter will be thick.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the batter into the baking pan, sprinkle on the topping,
and bake for 40 to 45 minutes, until golden brown and a cake tester
inserted in the center comes out dry. Cool the cake on a wire rack;
cut it into squares and serve it from the pan. Makes one 9-inch
cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
