<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-SHOPPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CELEBRITIES, FIRM FINDS GIFTS WITH STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAN NUYS, Calif. _ And you thought it was hard finding the
perfect gift for that special someone.
</P>
<P>
   Marnie Lerner and Cynde Cassel's holiday shopping list is packed
with someones, the sort who star in movies or make movies or have
enough money to buy whatever they want themselves. It's an entire
list of people who have everything.
</P>
<P>
   As Lerner put it, ``When we shop, sometimes we'll spend
thousands of dollars on a single item. Money is not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The money also isn't theirs. Lerner and Cassel are stand-in
shoppers known for their stand-out gifts. The recipients _ Gwyneth
Paltrow, Julia Roberts, and Jack Nicholson, to drop a few A-list
names they've power shopped for in the past _ don't even know the
pair exists. They think the gifts come from the Hollywood studios,
talent agencies, and celebrities who sign the cards.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Lerner, 27, and Cassel, 30, who were behind the
old-fashioned popcorn cart that country music star Reba McEntire
received for the screening room she added to her house. They
stocked the bassinet with chenille teddy bears and velvet pillows
for Jodie Foster's newborn son. The night-vision goggles with
infrared lighting sensors that Eddie Murphy received? Them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, we've upped our own ante,'' Cassel said. ``We did
so well for one client last year _ picnic backpacks filled with
everything from silverware and china to binoculars and a compass _
that we've got to top ourselves now.''
</P>
<P>
   While lavish gift-giving in Hollywood dates back at least to the
mid-1980s, when uber-agent Michael Ovitz began pampering stars with
presents, Lerner and Cassel have raised expectations even higher.
The friends and partners in Star Treatment, based in a Los Angeles
suburb, have mastered matching celebrities with one-of-a-kind gifts
for any occasion, from start of filming to Oscar win.
</P>
<P>
   They've taken to the Internet to bid on a vintage Barbie doll in
a cheerleader costume for actress Kirsten Dunst, hunted down
antique dealers in India for a studio head, and tested more creams
and lotions than they can count.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, couple Tom Hanks and Rita Wilson got one
of those backpacks, personalized with a bottle of wine,
an-all-in-one tool kit, and hand-crank radio. Sylvester Stallone,
along with about every celebrity in Hollywood, received a gourmet
gift basket half the size of a coffee table. The partners won't say
who's receiving $1,000 cashmere bathrobes or pashmina shawls from
Nepal this holiday season. They don't want to spoil the surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynde has been in tears most of the day,'' trying to satisfy a
client who's sending out dozens of the same elegant but obscure
items this year, Lerner said as the women took a break from writing
proposals and overseeing gift wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're just going to the supermarket to buy food
for gift baskets,'' said Cassel. ``They think it sounds so homey.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lerner, ``If only they knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The partners, in fact, say they hardly knew what they were
getting into when they launched Star Treatment 3 1/2 years ago.
Lerner, a former writer for one of her father's Spanish-language
publications, and Cassel, who was a personal shopper at
Bloomingdale's in Manhattan, met at a New York fashion show,
clicked, and suddenly found themselves in business together.
Headquarters was Lerner's parents' guesthouse (her mother, Diane,
is also a partner). Gift baskets were their specialty.
</P>
<P>
   But their naivete paid off. No one told them they couldn't
approach studios and talent agencies directly, and so they did. In
a town where valet parking is a must, and anyone who's anyone has a
stylist to select his or her wardrobe, word soon got around about
Star Treatment. Many of the major players, who spend millions of
dollars a year on gifts for stars, were happy to cede the shopping
headache to the women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not personal shoppers in the sense of department store
personal shoppers,'' Lerner said. ``We bring it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cassel, ``We really submit so many ideas that we're not
choosing for them. We're just helping them decide what they want to
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, Star Treatment has given gifts to countless
award winners, the cast and crews of scores of films, and so many
celebrities that the partners keep extensive files on them all.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Billy Crystal enjoys cigars, they included them along
with brandy and an antique crystal decanter in the gift box he
received for hosting the Oscars. Adam Sandler got an oak chest
filled with squirt guns and other toys to welcome him to the set of
``Big Daddy.'' Mike Myers got a silk smoking jacket, body oils, and
oysters when filming began on the ``Austin Powers'' sequel. Any day
now, members of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association will
receive cookies shaped like actor John Malkovich's head after
screening ``Being John Malkovich'' _ part of a package intended to
reflect the theme of the movie about getting inside Malkovich's
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a store,'' Lerner said. ``We do electronics, we do
food, we do cashmere, we do gadgets. You can find the coolest
things for people who have everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That skill has paid off nicely for the partners. Recently they
moved into an immense warehouse where more than a dozen employees
are now busy wrapping gifts seven days a week. Tables are laden
with bows and boxes; styrofoam packing balls litter the floor. The
shelves in one room are crammed with shampoos and moisturizers;
others are filled with wine and champagne. One room is devoted to
children's toys.
</P>
<P>
   The trick: paying wholesale whenever possible and charging
customers retail for gifts that range from $75 to $5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Always busy with the year-round movie business, the holiday
season is an especially hectic time. Star Treatment is sending out
as many as 200 gift baskets a day, some of them ordered from its
Web site (www.startreatment.com) where anyone with a credit card
can hire the partners or purchase the women's taste in gifts.
</P>
<P>
   As Lerner explained, ``Sometimes people say the sky's the limit,
if a major A-list star is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cassel, ``They want cashmere this, cashmere that . . .
We've been sent keys to cars to put inside gifts for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cassel and Lerner haven't had much time to enjoy their
success. They're too busy shopping for others, although now they
mostly deal directly with wholesalers or retailers and rarely have
to venture into a store themselves. Neither has bought a single
gift for their friends or relatives yet or even for each other.
Last year, Cassel got Lerner an evening bag that she then borrowed.
Lerner got Cassel a nutcracker she wanted. Right now, both dread
the idea of hitting the malls for anyone besides a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we do it, we're like the `Terminator,' '' said
Cassel. ``We can immediately see exactly what we want. You run, you
scan, you buy. We can do two malls a night that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9708 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICIOUS CYCLE FINDS PATRIOTS IN A TAILSPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sunday's game was over. For one team, the Colts, joy
and ecstasy were in the air. The upstarts had won a game another
way, the way good teams have to do, win not with their vaunted
offense but with a defensive stand.
</P>
<P>
   For the other team, the Patriots, the so-familiar emotion _
frustration _ hung in the air. Another chance gone by. Another game
in which they had played well but not well enough.
</P>
<P>
   Teams in the National Football League often win these games,
these fourth-quarter tests of will, because their big players make
big plays. One play can change all, and one play can swing the
balance. It is why big players are paid big money.
</P>
<P>
   Teams in the National Football League lose these games, these
close games, because they do not make the big play. The Patriots
did not make the big play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year at this time, as Christmas approaches, the media and
Patriot fans take out their magnifying glasses for a micro-view of
New England's playoff chances. Endless permutations are trotted
out, permutations by which the Patriots can make the playoffs. At
times, this can be fun, such as when the Patriots are a team on the
rise and are surprisingly making a run at the elite. At other
times, such as now, it is monotonous. Frustratingly so.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, though, do fans and media take the macro-view of the
Patriots franchise. It's like an investor looking merely at last
week's stock prices. Often, though, insights can be found by
looking at charts from years ago, from 10 and 20 and 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots, the long-term look at what the team has done
_ and when it has done it _ is troubling. In the 40 years of this
franchise, as their fortunes have ebbed and flowed, the Patriots
have performed well at very precise times.
</P>
<P>
   During the middle of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   And performed poorly at very precise times. At the end of one
decade and the beginning of the next.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, for instance, when the American Football League
was formed, the Patriots of 1964 were 10-3-1, losing to the Bills
at War Memorial Stadium in their final game, 24-14, and blowing a
chance to return to San Diego for the AFL title game.
</P>
<P>
   That was the high point of the decade. In 1965, the Patriots
were 4-8-2, but recovered to be 8-4-2 in 1966. Then, in the next
four seasons, from 1967 to 1970, the Patriots' combined record was
13-42-1 and the franchise collapsed with coach Clive Rush the
symbol of the team's disarray.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday in Indianapolis, the Patriots played very hard, and
cornerback Ty Law epitomized the team's effort, playing with his
broken right thumb in a cast. On one play in the fourth quarter,
when the Colts' Edgerrin James swept right end, Law came up and
tried to tackle the rookie, virtually with one arm. On the way back
to the huddle after the play, Law's right arm hung limply at his
side, like a rag doll's. But he was on the field and remained on
the field, playing hard.
</P>
<P>
   So effort is not the issue with these Patriots. Any suggestion
that the players have quit is ludicrous. Pride is still alive in
Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, makes the team's predicament all the more . .
. well, frustrating. Sunday's game might as well have been a
metaphor for the season, as well as the last few seasons, the
Patriots falling behind early and then clawing back late. But, as
usual, falling short.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, as the Patriots' cycle replayed itself, the team
was terrible early in the decade. But with Chuck Fairbanks's
arrival, the team asserted itself in the middle of the decade,
first showing hope with a 7-7 season in 1974 and then, after a 3-11
step back in 1975, progressing tremendously to the 11-3 season in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   That 1976 team still may be the best Patriot team ever. Ben
Drieth's roughing-the-passer call against Ray Hamilton in the
playoff loss in Oakland may have deprived New England of its best
chance to win a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1977, the Patriots were 9-5, followed by 11-5 a year
later. But the raucous ending to that 1978 season _ when Fairbanks
agreed to coach Colorado before the Patriots ended their regular
season _ makes Bill Parcells's departure two decades later seem
like a child's bedtime story. The sight of lawyers for the Patriots
and Fairbanks in a federal courthouse in Boston just before a
playoff game makes Parcells's ``shopping for the groceries'' remark
seem innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, to the surprise of few, lost that playoff game to
Houston. The team, shall we say, was unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the decade, unable to recover from the Fairbanks
fiasco, the Patriots gradually weakened until they hit bottom in
1981 with a 2-14 record. The cycle was repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid 1980s the Patriots were on the way back, going 9-7 in
1984, and the 1985 team went 11-5 and reached the Super Bowl. But
that team was rocked by a drug scandal and, soon enough, the
end-of-the-decade slide reappeared. By 1989, the Patriots were
5-11; in 1990, they were 1-15.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s have been just like the 1960s and 1970s and 1980s. The
team recovered from an abysmal 2-14 of 1992 and reached 10-4 in
1994 under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   But 1995 repeated 1975 as a young Patriots team fell back for a
season and went 6-10. The 1996 team, of course, went to the Super
Bowl. Once again, the Patriots' best team came in the middle of the
decade. But then came the fiasco of Parcells's departure, an eerie
repeat of the fiasco of Fairbanks's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Now another decade ends with the Patriots sliding down from the
heights. Fairbanks and Parcells have been the two best coaches in
the franchise's history, and if the lesson from Fairbanks is
repeated, the immediate future is not good.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing good has happened to any Patriots team as one decade
turns into another. The cycle has repeated itself.
</P>
<P>
   So the real frustration may not have been Sunday in
Indianapolis, or those squandered games in Buffalo and Miami. The
real frustration may come in the next few years. It is a long time,
after all, to the middle of the next decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
