<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS DON'T SAY `WALK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't expect Mark Whipple to go anywhere. At least not this
season. The University of Massachusetts coach is on the road
recruiting this week and has not heard from North Carolina State,
the one opening that might have drawn his interest.
</P>
<P>
   Although Army has a vacancy, and offers a Division 1-A position,
don't look for Whipple to jump at that. If he does make the move
from Division 1-AA to 1-A, he wants a program that he can bring
into the Top 25 on a regular basis. Army is not such a program.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State would be a perfect place for Whipple to
showcase his coaching skills. But the administration seems intent
on finding a replacement for Mike O'Cain from a group of 1-A
assistant coaches. Florida State's Chuck Amato seems to be the
front-runner right now.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity _ perhaps mistake _ in doing that is that the
greatest success the Wolfpack have had in football was after hiring
1-AA coaches, Lou Holtz from William &AMP; Mary and Dick Sheridan from
Furman (although Holtz did have experience as a Division 1-A
assistant).
</P>
<P>
   Whipple can afford to stay put. He has a good team coming back
next season, and several other jobs could open, possibly a couple
in the Big East. Rutgers is a prime possibility since coach Terry
Shea has been told that he must produce a winning season or he is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Also not going anywhere is Boston College coach Tom O'Brien. The
Virginia rumors were false and now are dead since George Welsh is
returning for another season. O'Brien might not have gone anyway,
since he has established something at BC on his own, while at
Virginia he would have been compared with Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   Look for BC officials to extend O'Brien's contract in the next
few weeks, with a little boost as a reward for this year's 8-3
season, which put the Eagles in the Dec. 31 Insight.com Bowl in
Tucson against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   BC's success also drew the attention of the Kickoff Classic.
Officials approached BC about playing in next summer's game, but
the opponent would be Michigan, so BC passed, feeling that the
program is still a year away from taking on such a challenge that
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is sound. If the Eagles were to play Michigan and
lose, they would have to win seven of the next 11 games to become
bowl-eligible, as opposed to the six wins they need in an 11-game
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   While BC's program took a turn upward this year, it is hardly at
the stage where it can be adding Top 10 type teams like Michigan to
the schedule at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Kickoff Classic will shop for another opponent for Michigan,
but if one can't be found, it might try to get what it wanted
originally, a Virginia Tech-Purdue matchup that would feature
Purdue quarterback Drew Brees against Tech's Michael Vick in what
should be an excellent duel.
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block to that has been Tech's desire to play a
home game in one of the Black Coaches Association preseason games.
The Hokies have been unsuccessful in finding anyone to come to
Blacksburg and might opt for a neutral-site game against a team
like Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible compromise matchup would be Purdue against BC.
But Purdue-Virginia Tech is the No. 1 target right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1405EST &QL; 
