u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     12-15 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' PROBLEMS STEM FROM THE RUNNING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is one of the standard questions you ask the opposing coach
about the locals before an upcoming game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do you see in the Patriots films?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is almost always: ``They've got a lot of talent. The
speed of those wide receivers scares you. The defense is quick, and
they've got guys that can make plays in the secondary . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And then the trailer always comes: ``. . . but of course, the
No. 1 thing you have to do is stop Drew Bledsoe.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no different with Andy Reid, the first-year coach of the
struggling Philadelphia Eagles, when he had his chance on the horn:
``The guy has one of the best arms in the game. He can put the ball
anywhere. If you don't take care of those receivers . . .''
</P>
<P>
   You'll find no complaints about Bledsoe from the coaches that
have to prepare for him.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill Parcells of the Jets said earlier this year, ``Let him
go to free agency and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising to this humble scribe to see Bledsoe up
front, apologizing for all of the Patriots' sins after they were
beaten by a very good Colts team in what has become a very
difficult place to play, the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can applaud Bledsoe for being a stand-up guy, what
has happened to this team has very little do to with the way he has
played. If you had to hand out the blame, Bledsoe should be
standing at the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are not a championship team. Most people picked
them to finish fourth in their own division, which is no disgrace
because the AFC East has proven to be the best division in
football. However, this team should be good enough to make the
playoffs, and if it fails to do that, it will be because it didn't
take advantage of the opportunities it was given.
</P>
<P>
   The major problem is this:
</P>
<P>
   THEY CANNOT RUN THE FOOTBALL.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that they cannot PASS the football.
</P>
<P>
   And until they find a way to run the football _ either with
better blockers, or a better scheme, or better running backs _ they
are going to be no better than they are now, which is mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   In this fall from grace over the last five weeks _ when the
Patriots tumbled from 6-2 to 7-6 after a miserable 1-4 stretch _
they have scored a total of 69 points. That's a little less than 14
points per game. Not once in those five games have they scored 20
points. Any NFL coach will tell his team before a game that they
need at least 21 points to win. The Patriots are averaging a
touchdown less than that.
</P>
<P>
   And if you look closely at those 69 points, most of them have
come in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't score a touchdown in Indianapolis until the fourth
quarter. They didn't score a touchdown against Dallas at home until
the fourth quarter. They were down in Buffalo, 17-0, before they
scored a touchdown in the final five minutes. In the last five
games, they have scored one touchdown, total, in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because they have no running game. Colts president Bill
Polian said after Sunday's game, ``We didn't even bother with their
run.'' Opponents focus on stopping Bledsoe and the wide receivers,
and they will continue to do so until New England finds a running
game.
</P>
<P>
   And the quarterback shouldn't be apologizing for that. Others
should be stepping forward to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reid's team is only 3-11, but he is upbeat about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players have played hard,'' he said. ``We told them from
the beginning this is the year we build the foundation, and I feel
we have been doing that. We're a young team, and we still need more
pieces to put together, but we are going in the right direction.
Nine of our games have been decided by a touchdown or less. We've
lost six games by 4 points or less, and we've been in those games
right to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid is not sure whether rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb will
play against the Patriots Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hurt his knee in the last game, and he's doubtful,'' said
Reid. ``He wants to play, but we are not going to put him at risk.
If I think he can be OK and do the job, then he'll play, but we
won't know that until late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been coming along well. It takes time in this league,
but he's advanced in terms of knowing what to do at this point in
his first year. He has the arm. The first few games it was too
strong. The ball was really flying out of there. It's just a matter
of time and work to get him where he wants to be and I want him to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for McNabb, and veteran Doug Peterson, is that the
Eagles do not have any wide receivers that would be considered for
the Pro Bowl. The team's first move in the draft next year is
expected to be for a wide receiver, followed by a defensive
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles can run the ball. They have a fine back in Duce
Staley, a bowling-ball type who is short but strong and can make
yardage after the first hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just keeping telling our guys this is a building year,''
said Reid. ``With a couple of breaks, we could have won a few more
games. We're still playing hard, and continuing to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots should win this game, but if they don't watch out,
the Eagles might put another brick on their load, and it might be
the one that buries New England for the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
