<SLUG> BC-SF-BROWN-AGENDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN SAYS HOUSING WILL BE PRIORITY IN NEXT TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE and RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, fresh from a landslide
victory in Tuesday's run-off election, said affordable housing in
an era of soaring real estate values would be the major challenge
of his second term.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said it was too soon to propose specific remedies,
although he intends to push a broad study of the housing market
through the governing Board of Supervisors as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems of affordability will be the challenges that I
face in the second term,'' the mayor said after his victory.
</P>
<P>
   A chronic shortage of housing and the glittering economy of the
Silicon Valley have made the real estate market in San Francisco
one of the most expensive in the nation. Soaring rents helped
propel the grass-roots campaign of Brown's rival, Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, who won a spot in the run-off
race with an unprecedented write-in campaign in the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by his big victory over Ammiano, Brown said he would use
his second term to tackle a host of nuts-and-bolts problems,
including the housing issue and repairing the aging water and sewer
system.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who begins his second and final term Jan. 8, said it was
too early to start thinking about a legacy for his years as mayor.
``I'm not so much focused on legacy as I am on solving the problems
that exist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown acknowledged that Ammiano's populist campaign put him
through the contest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Ammiano, the most liberal member of the board,
had forced him to more aggressively court moderate to conservative
voters on the city's west side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a race in which I'm battling for a constituency that I,
frankly, have never had before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Brown said he had to fight hard to keep his
base of supporters _ union workers, gays and lesbians, blacks and
Hispanics, some of whom defected to Ammiano.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that represents a dramatic change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a contentious campaign in which the mayor criticized
Ammiano's leadership and the supervisor attacked Brown's integrity,
the mayor said he would not hold a grudge and would work with
Ammiano in their roles as mayor and board president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever has the job as board president, I will endeavor on
behalf of the mayor's office and the people of this city to work
with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the housing crunch continues despite the approval of
a $100 million affordable housing bond act in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also vowed to help push the proposed stadium and an
adjoining commercial complex for the San Francisco 49ers pro
football team, a project that has been stalled by a feud among the
team owners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9727 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-15 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMOS WIN BUT ONLY AFTER AN UPHILL FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The limos won.
</P>
<P>
   The party transportation summed it up. A dozen gleaming limos
sat outside Alioto's restaurant where Mayor Willie Brown had an
election-night dinner, while outside Tom Ammiano's party at the
Roccapulco nightclub was the sign ``Free bike parking across
street.''
</P>
<P>
   The bikes never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wasn't about to let a critical mass of bicyclists and
other dissidents take him by surprise again. He ran right over
them.
</P>
<P>
   Give Brown credit for working hard, spending big, getting his
message of leadership across, ``going West,'' as he put it, to
rouse the Asian-American voters of the west side of San Francisco,
and crushing the Ammiano insurgency down to its progressive core of
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new middle class of San Francisco, replacing the Irish and
Italians, are Chinese-American families, who own homes and small
businesses and are relatively conservative,'' said David Lee,
executive director of the Chinese-American Voters Education
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown was the only candidate speaking to them. It's
ironic because Brown made his chops fighting the old Irish and
Italian politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Ammiano credit, too. He gave Brown the scare of his
political life. Now Brown has to address the issues Ammiano pounded
home during the run-off election _ housing, homeless, development
and neighborhood issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been a voice for the people who are traditionally shut
out,'' Ammiano shouted to his cheering supporters after the
election was lost Tuesday night, ``and we will be shut out no
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few years Ammiano _ who is president of the
governing Board of Supervisors _ will help reshape San Francisco
politics around district elections, and perhaps run against one of
Brown's proteges. And there will be no more coronations of mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Brown won an overwhelming mandate, but it was a mandate for
changing his ways.
</P>
<P>
   When the absentee votes were counted, it was already over. Brown
had about 70 percent of the absentees, easily a record for a
liberal in San Francisco, and at the end had about 60 percent of
the vote to Ammiano's 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the landslide was being called a win-win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great thing,'' said Supervisor Gavin Newsom. ``It's
good for the mayor, good for Ammiano and good for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside of Brown's vanity is that he is not going to allow
himself to be perceived as a failure,'' said political consultant
Jim Rivaldo, a Brown supporter who is sympathetic to Ammiano. ``He
has been energized.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll have to wait and see if Willie found God through Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Rich DeLeon, a professor of political science at San Francisco
State University, saw a connection between the surprising battle
over globalization in Seattle and ``the fracas in Frisco,'' as he
called this election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campus has been politically dead for almost 30 years,''
DeLeon said. ``Because of this election you hear students talking
about politics without their professors hectoring them to.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLeon spoke of the changing demographics of San Francisco, the
revival of the anti-development cause, and San Francisco's lively
``politics of everything,'' as he called it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm a pundit and supposed to be articulate,'' said
DeLeon, ``but when I look at what happened in the last year, I'm
speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the things that happened: Ideals are back. The
neighborhoods have been put out front. The Internet generation got
wired on politics, not just caffeine. Asian-Americans asserted
themselves at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, things are as they always have been in
politics. Willie Brown may have gone to a Chinese temple to pray,
but he didn't count on those prayers to be more important than
fund-raising appeals.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how Tom Ammiano would have done if he had
money and a machine more powerful than a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1417EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS &LR;      12-15 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSSLER'S `ATLANTIS' MAKES A BIG SPLASH
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas came early this year with the publication of Clive
Cussler's latest adventure thriller featuring Dirk Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlantis Found'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $26.95, 534 pages) is a
delightful page turner that is almost impossible to put down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1858, a shore party from a whaling ship locked in the
Antarctic ice discovers the British merchantman Madras, ice-bound
for nearly a century. In its storage room, they find a skull carved
from obsidian. When the ice pack begins to break up, the shore
party runs for their own ship, taking only the skull and Madras'
log.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, miner Luis Marquez discovers a chamber deep in an
abandoned Colorado mine. ``It looked to be a perfect cube,
approximately 15 by 15 feet, with the same distance separating the
floor and the roof. Strange markings were cut into the sheer,
smooth walls.'' Marquez also finds a obsidian skull.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patricia O'Connell, an expert in ancient languages, is asked
to fly to Telluride and try to decipher the room's inscriptions.
She is met by anthropologist Thomas Ambrose, who introduces her to
Marquez. While the three explore the room, an avalanche blocks the
mine's entrance. Then an explosion rocks the mine and water begins
to flood into the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt, who has been exploring the mountain's waterways, rescues
the three and gets them to a higher level in the mine. Before they
can get out of the mine, three men show up and tell them they will
never escape the mountain and reveal their find. Pitt knocks one
out and kills the other two after they say they are members of
``The Fourth Empire.'' Ambrose disappears, only to resurface and
try to kill Marquez, O'Connell and Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that the three will be in danger until they can discover
the secret of the Fourth Empire, James Sandecker arranges to have
O'Connell, Marquez and their families placed in protective custody.
Pitt learns of another skull and is told the story of the Madras.
</P>
<P>
   Sandecker sends Pitt to Antarctica to try to find the Madras. He
also sends Pitt's pal Al Giordino to an island in the Indian Ocean,
where a Madras passenger had found the skull.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the deciphered writings will tell the story of a
race of people who roamed the seas thousands of years before the
pyramids were built and left their history in hidden chambers
around the world. An evil family of untold wealth has known the
story of the lost race since before the beginning of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Using a prediction made centuries before, the family concocts a
plan to wipe out most of mankind. Only their most loyal followers
will survive the planned holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlantis Found'' is Cussler at his storytelling best. Not as
outrageous as some of the earlier Pitt adventures, ``Atlantis''
makes Dirk more human and less Superman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timeline.'' By Michael Crichton. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.95. 443
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton didn't set out to write another thriller. Rather he had
his sights set on a megaconglomerate. Prior to publication,
Crichton reportedly signed a groundbreaking deal for film rights to
``Timeline,'' forgoing a multimillion dollar upfront fee from
Paramount Pictures for as much as 15 percent of the movie's gross
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Timeline,'' ITC Research in Black Rock, Ariz., is the
master of quantum technology. It is also funding an archaeological
dig in the Dordogne region of France that includes a couple of
fortresses, a monastery and a mill. When an ITC representative
seems to know more about the site than the archaeologists, the
team's leader, Professor Edward Johnston, demands to be taken to
Black Rock to get some answers. Days go by without the team hearing
from Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   One day there is a collapse at the dig and an old parchment is
found and written on it is ``HELP ME 4/7/1357'' and it is
definitely Johnston's writing. Eventually, ITC will tell Johnston's
team that the company has developed a method to travel back in
time. Johnston has traveled back to the 14th century and is stuck
there. ITC asks the team to go back and rescue their professor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once they get there everything goes awry. France in
the 14th century was a very violent place and each member of the
team is in danger, especially Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   As you read ``Timeline,'' the words MAJOR MOTION PICTURE keep
flashing in your mine.
</P>
<P>
   There is a very interesting story here, but this is just an
elaborate screenplay. Nevertheless, this is a must read for
Crichton fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Highland Christmas.'' By M.C. Beaton. Mysterious Press.
$156.95. 129 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Beaton's 14th book featuring Scottish Police Constable Hamish
Macbeth is a little gem.
</P>
<P>
   Macbeth works in the dark and dreary village of Lockdubh in the
far northern Highlands. Calvinist to its core, no one puts up
Christmas lights or decorates a tree. An old biddy reports her cat
stolen and complains to Macbeth's superior that the constable is
not doing his job. Macbeth does hunt for the cat, but wants to know
why the lady is so frightened. A nearby village reports that its
tree and lights have been stolen. And Macbeth meets a 9-year-old
girl whose parents don't believe in Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, Macbeth wants to play Santa Claus and his actions
will light up many hearts in Lockdubh.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Highland Christmas'' is heaped with oddball characters that
you want to know. The dialogue moves the plot along at a steady
pace. A perfect Christmas story for any reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oxford Companion to Crime &AMP; Mystery Writing.'' Edited by
Chief Rosemary Herbert. Oxford University Press. $49.95. 535 pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Encyclopedia of Murder and Mystery.'' By Bruce Murphy. St.
Martin's Minotaur. $75. 543 pages.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for a gift for a true mystery fan, either of
these books would be a great addition to a library. Both are
arranged from A to Z.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Nancy Drew was created by a man? I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I've only paged through both works, but I know I'll use
them often.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
