<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-CULTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE PERKS MAY FUEL A CULT MENTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are provided with everything from child care to a cafeteria
to a gymnasium, and you have a dynamic leader who makes sure
everyone is strongly committed and feels empowered. So does that
make you a member of a great company or a cult?
</P>
<P>
   Probably some of each, says Dave Arnott, a professor at Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Baptist University and the author of ``Corporate Cults: The
Insidious Lure of the All-Consuming Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All organizations have some level of cultish behavior; it's
just that some have more than others,'' Arnott writes. ``A
corporate cult is an individual-level construct. Only individuals
can make their corporation into a cult.''
</P>
<P>
   When publications offer lists of the best places to work in
America, the winners are often places that make it easier for
employees to take care of essential tasks like eating and exercise
without ever leaving the corporate campus. It is convenient for
employees, Arnott says, but it also separates them from the rest of
the world and makes them more emotionally dependent on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day care and schools at the corporation, while convenient,
effectively separate the employee from the community,'' Arnott
writes. ``Not only is the worker cut off from the community, the
child is cut off as well. The employee increasingly socializes only
with other workers who are parents of children in corporate day
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child knows only the children of other workers. Whatever
cultural stereotype exists in the corporation is magnified in the
children. All the programs aimed at diversifying society by
integrating people from different ethnic and racial backgrounds are
turned on their head by corporate day care.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes that separation from the community is one of three key
elements of a cult, corporate or otherwise. Charismatic leadership
and devotion are the other crucial factors, making people feel bad
if they leave the office or go on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Arnott said he realizes that it is probably all
right and even healthy for an employee to have certain cultish
beliefs. He does in his own job. Using corporate child care might
save parents an hour a day and even let them have lunch with the
children, for example, and he acknowledges that the advantages can
outweigh the disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   Just be careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the organization offers you a cafeteria plan of, say, five
cultish activities, don't gorge on all five,'' Arnott said. ``Try
two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   He said companies aren't wrong for offering the activities;
workers just need to be careful that they don't get so immersed in
the company's beliefs that they lose their individuality. The
particularly vulnerable fall into three broad categories: those who
are new to the industry or corporation; those who have moved away
from their families or left their church; and those who have lost a
spouse through death or divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often is your organization considered a family?'' Arnott
said. ``Look at your circle of friendships and see how many are in
your organization and how many are outside it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even an entrepreneur can make up a one-person cult, he said, if
all the person's energy and friendships are work-related.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott said the increasing commitment demanded by employers
might be felt more strongly as unemployment starts to increase.
Workers who have many options now might find them limited in the
future, making them more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott said members of corporate cults can be workaholics, but
the two are not necessarily connected. People who wear a pager
constantly or check their e-mail on vacation might not be
workaholics, but could be cult members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workaholics are measured by the number of hours they work.
Cult members are measured by their level of emotional attachment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
