<HEADER>
A9733 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-15 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A MOMENT, IT LOOKED LIKE IT WAS ALL OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I feel better now. The threat to my long-standing boycott of
major-league baseball has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, this boycott that I've waged on and off for
nearly a decade was hanging by a thread as a result of the New York
Yankees' brilliant World Series victory and the Texas Rangers'
magnificent decision to trade away one of baseball's premier
overpaid brats, Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees conducted a clinic in the art of playing baseball _
and exhibited a level of class in the process that conjured up
memories of yesteryear, when ballplayers were heroic figures and
baseball was truly the national pastime. And no sooner had the
World Series celebration concluded than the Rangers shipped
Gonzalez to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The combined exhilaration from the two events nearly overwhelmed
me, prompting me to all but pledge an end to my boycott if only the
Rangers would meet two conditions. I asked them to make sure that
third baseman Todd Zeile remained a Ranger and to make equally sure
that ex-Ranger pitcher Kenny Rogers did not return.
</P>
<P>
   And what did the Rangers do?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they bungled their negotiations with Zeile, and he
signed on with the New York Mets. And the Ranger honchos can't seem
to stop talking about the possibility of bringing back Rogers, the
sniveling prima donna whose brain-dead pitching for the Mets ended
that team's hopes of advancing to the World Series last season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, just to rub salt in the wound, the Rangers announced
a gigantic price increase for many seats at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   I'm certainly disappointed that the local team will no longer
enjoy the services of Zeile, whose attitude toward the game and its
fans is a throwback to the humble baseball heroes of days gone by _
the Stan Musials, the Mickey Mantles, the Hank Aarons.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's hard work on the baseball diamond and his good
citizenship off the field will be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I must confess to being relieved, in a way, that the
Rangers failed to meet my conditions, freeing me to continue
pursuing this boycott that has become almost second nature.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that I modified the boycott two seasons ago so that I
could watch baseball on television and read about the game in the
newspaper. But in making that change, I rededicated myself to the
essence of the boycott: denying baseball the only thing it really
cares about _ money _ by refusing to contribute financially to the
game in any way. I don't attend games in person, don't buy licensed
merchandise of any kind, and do my best to avoid buying the
products of companies that advertise during baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   Any meaningful boycott is about economics, so I'm doing my small
part to punish the greedy owners and players who have turned a
once-great American institution into little more than an overhyped
commercial enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   To a lot of folks, I know, the whole idea of a baseball boycott
seems pretty silly nowadays. Fans were up in arms back in 1994,
when a strike by players wiped out the last part of the season, the
playoffs and the World Series. Even the most devoted aficionados of
the game were reluctant to return when the billionaires finally got
back to business in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans gradually drifted back to the ballparks, gradually
started coughing up their hard-earned bucks for those outrageously
overpriced tickets and concessions, gradually eased back into the
habit of supporting the home team in particular and the game in
general. And after a brief period of catering to the fans to entice
them back, the game has resumed its proclivity for abusing these
loyal customers who passively pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment there last month, it seemed as though the Texas
Rangers were heading down the less-traveled path by unloading the
self-absorbed all-star, Gonzalez, and perhaps making room for the
selfless solid citizen, Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. The Rangers flubbed the chance to keep Zeile. They
are apparently pursuing Kenny Rogers. They have increased ticket
prices _ again.
</P>
<P>
   And the boycott continues.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
