<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-15 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY ON DIFFERENT HATS BEFORE MAKING CAREER DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you face a tough career decision, think about
Richard Bachman _ a best-selling author who technically does not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Bachman himself was dreamed up by Stephen King, who usually
specializes in nightmares. After writing bestseller after
bestseller, King thought it would be fun to write with a
</P>
<P>
   different voice, under a different name, and see whether that
struggling new author could succeed.
</P>
<P>
   As Bachman became moderately successful, though, some diehard
King fans began to notice similarities between their two writing
styles. Eventually, King acknowledged that he was indeed Bachman,
but he continues to write as Bachman from time to time; some
stories just seem better when told from Bachman's voice.
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to do anything that dramatic, but it does help
to look at dilemmas from fresh perspectives. You can, and should,
ask people for help when you really need it, of course, but
sometimes just thinking about what others would do can help you
figure things out.
</P>
<P>
   That's why having a diverse network is so important. If you
listen well, you get inside the heads of people from all sorts of
backgrounds, and their approaches might help you come up with a
fresh way of doing things. Learning to see things from other
people's perspectives is a crucial career skill.
</P>
<P>
   One effective way to organize your thinking is to use ``Six
Thinking Hats,'' Edward de Bono's bestseller that has recently been
released in paperback. A consultant and author of several books on
the thinking process, de Bono suggests that individuals and groups
can limit confused thinking by using his metaphor of six colored
hats:
</P>
<P>
   _ Blue is for organizing, like a facilitator at a meeting. It's
used for determining what issues need to be discussed and what the
ground rules will be for discussing them.
</P>
<P>
   _ White is for facts and figures only, with no interpretation.
It's used to outline the essential facts and show what necessary
information might be missing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red is for the emotional view, your gut feelings about the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Black is for the negatives about the issue, the chance to play
devil's advocate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yellow is all the positives about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Green is for creative ideas. How could the issue be approached
differently, or avoided completely?
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who has been at a meeting with a few overly negative or
overly positive people should appreciate why de Bono's method has
dramatically shortened meetings at some companies. At traditional
meetings, somebody raises a point, then the negative person chimes
in. Someone else says something, the negative person rebuts it. The
dance can seem to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Using the hats, though, the person running the meeting focuses
the discussion on one hat's approach at a time. You get all the
positives brought out at once, and all the negatives brought out
together, rather than the back-and-forth than can grind meetings to
a halt. You also have a clear separation between facts and
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   As an individual, the hats can help organize your thinking.
Suppose you have a job offer, but you are torn about whether to
accept it. You don't really need the blue hat because the
alternatives are pretty clear, but here is how the other hats might
help:
</P>
<P>
   _ White: List all the objective data you have comparing the two
jobs, including salary, benefits and hours. Put in any other
crucial facts, such as whether you would be leaving your current
job before you were vested in the pension plan. When was the last
time each company laid people off? Is one company growing and the
other shrinking? Do you need more facts to help you decide? How can
you get them?
</P>
<P>
   _ Yellow: What are the best reasons for changing jobs? Is the
pay better? Will you get a chance to develop more skills? Does the
new company have a better reputation? Will you more flexibility?
The chance to telecommute? Are you stagnating at your current job?Does changing let you escape a bad boss or an unstable company?
</P>
<P>
   _ Black: Why should you turn down the offer? Will it make your
commute worse? Will you have less time to spend with your family?
Will your lack of seniority make you a likely candidate if layoffs
occur? Will you be leaving a good boss?
</P>
<P>
   _ Red: What does your gut tell you? What does your heart tell
you? Will you be heartsick over leaving the old place, or will you
be leaving skid marks in the parking lot? Don't underestimate the
power of emotion in career decisions. Often your instincts are more
powerful than your objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Green: Are there are ways to simplify your decision? Can you
push your current company for better pay or more flexibility? What
is the new company's offer missing that would make it irresistible?
How would you feel about asking for it?
</P>
<P>
   Look at whether you are even tackling the right problem. If you
consider the decision a ``lesser of two evils,'' think about
whether you ought to be changing careers rather than just jobs.
What parts of the job do you really enjoy? Is there another way to
use those talents?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether you prefer Richard Bachman or Edward de
Bono, try putting on a different hat the next time you face a
difficult decision. You just might end up feeling like a King.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
