   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ After talks on compensation for the
bombing of Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, U.S. officials here
schedule a news conference. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (Pristina) _ The top U.N. administrator in Kosovo
signed a power-sharing agreement with ethnic Albanian leaders on
Wednesday, creating a new governing body aimed at bringing more
stability to the province. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MURTHY (Bangalore) _ The extraordinary rise of N.R.
Narayana Murthy, his company and the software services industry in
India has come to represent the hope that what he calls
``compassionate capitalism'' can provide decent, desperately needed
jobs and the national wealth to improve health and literacy levels
in a country whose population has more than tripled since it won
independence in 1947. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-VOTE (Caracas) _ With Venezuelans expected to
overwhelmingly approve a new constitution _ eliminating the Senate
and giving President Hugo Chavez the opportunity to stay in office
for up to 13 years _ three months of uncertainty and conflict loom
before new elections are held and new system is in place. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-FLAG (Hong Kong) _ Steering clear of another legal
confrontation with the Chinese government, Hong Kong's top court
ruled Wednesday that defacing the Chinese flag is a crime. The
decision was a victory for the local government and reversed a
lower court ruling that said desecrating the flag was a form of
expression guaranteed by the constitution of this former British
colony. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-HUANG (Washington) _ First day of congressional
hearings on the fund-raising activities of John Huang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
