   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-MCCAIN (Washington) _ Political Memo: A look at Bradley
and McCain, the two insurgent candidates, on the eve of their joint
meeting in New Hampshire. How are their roles similar, and
different, in their respective campaigns? Are they following
similar playbooks to overcome the front-runners? By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MEDICAL (Undated) _ Al Gore releases medical records that
show elevated cholesterol levels and a skin cancer that was removed
in 1996; otherwise, his doctors say, he's in outstanding health. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-VENTURE-CAPITAL (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Venture capitalists
are scouring Latin America for opportunities in young companies,
much as they are in Silicon Valley. Many like the challenge of
non-traditional investments _ organically produced hearts of palm,
for example. Yet most venture capitalists investing in companies
with a Latin America focus, like those providing seed money to
United States ventures, are seeking out high-technology _
particularly Internet-related _ companies. The quest is complicated
by the often precarious nature of Latin America's economy as well
as a relative lack of advanced technology, along with the generally
frenetic nature of the Internet industry. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SERVICE (Undated) _ Looking at how online shopping sites
are handling customer service and fulfillment issues, and at the
frustrations of consumers in trying to make contact when things go
wrong. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MTV-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Chasing a report that the Justice
Department is investigating whether Viacom's MTV, M2 and VH1
networks violated antitrust law by obtaining exclusive rights to
music videos on release, making it nearly impossible for rivals to
enter the market. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ Exxon Mobil executives say their merger
will result in deeper job cuts and greater cost savings than
previously estimated. The company says it will cut almost 16,000
jobs by the end of 2002, an increase from the 9,000 cuts estimated
when the companies announced their plans to merge a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAX Looking at Internet tax policy in the wake of
hearing held by the Congressional Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-TECH-STOCKS (Singapore) _ The recent stratospheric climb by
the Nasdaq composite index has sparked a rush into technology
stocks on Asian stock markets. Never mind that there are few
dot-coms to speak of. ``If you talk about anything other than tech,
investors just aren't interested,'' says one analyst.
</P>
