r f BC-TAXES-ONLINE-HNS &LR;      12-15 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-ONLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKSELLERS WANT CALIFORNIA TO TAX INTERNET SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A coalition of California booksellers is urging
the state to be more forceful in collecting taxes from on-line
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering in San Francisco, the group of independent
shopkeepers took specific aim at three giants of e-commerce:
Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand the state's Board of Equalization collects sales tax
as existing law requires,'' said Hut Landon, owner of Landon Books
in Corte Madera. ``This is an instance where the state is handing
major retailers a huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The request to the state agency was made by the Northern
California Independent Booksellers Association and the American
Booksellers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly discriminatory,'' said Neal Sofman, who hosted
the event at his own store, A Clean Well Lighted Place for Books on
Van Ness Avenue. ``If this imbalance remains, we'll lose our tax
base.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the request of the bookstore owners, Board of
Equalization Chairman Johan Klehs said the state is, indeed,
enforcing the existing tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, the rules for e-commerce are the same as
catalog selling,'' Klehs said. ``If you have a nexus in California,
or employees in California, you're required to collect sales tax.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Advisory Committee on Electronic Commerce is
considering whether to tax transactions that take place on the
Internet. The 1998 law creating the study commission placed a
three-year moratorium on new taxes targeting Internet services or
Internet access services.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not exempt e-commerce companies from having to pay
state sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ross, who owns Cody's Books in Berkeley, said he first
complained to the state in July and has received little
satisfaction from the Board of Equalization so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax policy should not be politicized,'' said Ross, who went on
to accuse the Board of Equalization of bowing to Silicon Valley
pressure. ``Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com are not
collecting taxes in clear violation of the law. It's bad policy and
bad politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The state and national booksellers associations maintain that
the three on-line booksellers have a formidable presence in
California and that should count as an established nexus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that these are not California businesses is just
nonsense,'' said Bill Petrocelli, owner of Book Passage in Corte
Madera. ``Large Internet commerce people are being given a free
ride. That's simply wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Prem, a tax partner with the accounting firm of Deloitte &AMP;
Touche in San Francisco, sides with the on-line retailers, saying
they are doing nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the current tax laws work, the position that Amazon,
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders are taking is legal,'' Prem said. ``The
fact that they're not collecting sales tax is perfectly legal. The
companies have set up subsidiaries for on-line retailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Prem said a little-known or enforced tax, called the ``use
tax,'' could be the answer to the Internet taxation riddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tax that's imposed on a purchaser that buys something
from out of state and brings it into the state to use it,'' Prem
said. ``It's been on the books in California since the 1930s, but
is seldom enforced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1530EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WEBRETAILERS-TEX     12-15 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBRETAILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB RETAILERS AIRING THE WITTIEST ADS ON TV _ BUT ARE THEY
WORKING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're wondering what to call him, he's the Pets.com Puppet
Spokesdog Thing. If you're wondering what that's all about, he's
the little sock puppet who shills for Pets.com, an online pet
store, in a series of amusing TV commercials that began in August.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the Puppet Spokesdog Thing at a dog park, envying one of
his canine companions: ``Oh, boy, he's got a stuffed thing! I love
stuffed things!'' Here he is at the holiday table, conspiring with
Max, the family dog, to pawhandle a piece of turkey. Here he is
looking at stockings hung by the chimney with care, appalled at the
evil things humans do to socks: ``The horror!''
</P>
<P>
   Cute, huh? Funny, right? But do commercial campaigns like the
Puppet Spokesdog Thing make you want to log on to Web sites like
Pets.com? Online retailers and advertising companies are betting
that the answer is a hearty ``Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   They're betting a lot _ $2 billion in 1999, by most estimates _
on TV advertising. But with scores of Web sites _ or ``dot-coms,''
as they're popularly called _ flooding the airwaves, they're also
aware that for many, it will be a losing gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are roughly 8 million Web sites,'' says Anne Hollows,
senior vice president of global brand strategy for Monster.com,
which also has a striking commercial campaign. ``And they've got to
figure out a way to get noticed. ... People tend to lump dot-coms
together. We've thought of it in terms of car categories: We think
we each have a different product to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com's ad campaign, Hollows says, has drawn attention,
with traffic increasing 450 percent in the past year. The ``global
career management'' site is running a commercial with small
children expressing ironic ambitions: ``When I grow up, I want to
have a brown nose'' or ``I want to be forced into early
retirement.'' The company has spent roughly $30 million on its
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been well worth it,'' Hollows says. ``We're extremely
profitable as a company.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also been worth it at Pets.com, which may have the best
dot-com commercials running these days. It's not just the Puppet
Spokesdog Thing, but the simplicity of the Web site's name and the
cleverness of its tag line _ ``Because pets can't drive'' _ that
sticks in your head. Curiously, though, if you log on to the
Pets.com site, you won't see a much of the Spokesdog's humor, but
rather a fairly straightforward pet-supply site with articles and
care-taking tips. But the online company is using the Spokesdog's
celebrity as a gift to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see the sock puppet in stickers on boxes, in different
poses,'' says Amy Robinson, director of marketing for Pets.com.
``We're sending out holiday cards to our customers, which feature
the sock puppet in funny, clever ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers have asked to buy the sock puppet, which may be
surpassing the Taco Bell chihuahua as top commercial ``dog,'' and
one woman told the company that she wanted to dress as the puppet
for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson disagrees with the suggestion that the commercials are
``wacky,'' although that adjective is being pasted on just about
any humorous dot-com commercial. ``We actually feel like (the
Spokesdog) personifies the passion we feel toward animals, and the
way people feel about their pets,'' Robinson says.
</P>
<P>
   The clever approach has its detractors, though. Critics point
out that although humor draws attention to an ad, the humor is what
gets remembered instead of the product. Many sites are taking this
criticism to heart. Amazon.com _ a Web site with such name
recognition that it doesn't seem to need the help _ recently
changed paths from the wacky route (a commercial in which gerbils
were launched at the company logo) to the traditional (a Mitch
Miller-style singalong). Monster.com's spot, despite its ironic
humor, is filmed in stark black and white with the type of
drive-the-speed-limit editing we used to see in the pre-MTV age.
</P>
<P>
   And iCelebrate.com, an Irving, Texas-based site that sells
holiday-themed merchandise, went with the home-comfort approach: As
``iCelebrate'' is repeated over and over to the tune of ``Carol of
the Bells,'' a house (complete with cozy border collie) lights up
with Christmas flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our category is a very sentimental category,'' Julie Abdinoor,
vice president of marketing for iCelebrate, says of the holiday
site. ``We wanted our commercial to evoke very positive,
traditional feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Tami Hollis, iCelebrate's publicist, puts it in terms of hitting
a demographic target. ``What we're finding is that women are
responding to our ads,'' Hollis says. ``The Pets.com spot doesn't
necessarily appeal to me. I'm a woman, and I don't necessarily get
that humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers find fault with any ``dot-com'' advertising,
regardless of whether it's played silly or straight. Many of the
Web companies that are spending millions on advertising are
start-ups, investing more on ads than they are taking in in
revenues ``(The New York Times'' reported that send.com spent $20
million on advertising, even though at the time the gift site had
only $10 million in venture-capital funding). The belief is that
you gotta pay to play, but business writers and technology wonks
say that the real winners are the advertising agencies and TV
networks that are benefiting from all the money being spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a belief by some people that eventually there's going
to be a shakeout of some kind,'' says Jerry Preyss, president of
Playground, the Cleveland-based advertising agency that created the
iCelebrate spot. ``Many of the dot-coms that exist today won't
exist in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a sense that dot-coms, by advertising on
television, are feeding the hand that bites them even though the
media advertise in or on competing media all the time. But
Web-surfing and channel-surfing seem, on the surface, to be
incompatible, as most people don't have their computer up and
running while they're watching the tube. The question is whether
people will check out a Web site just because of a clever ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a necessary evil,'' Preyss says of TV advertising. ``The
simple fact is, if nobody knows about it, nobody's going to visit
your site. A 30-second commercial will increase your visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollows dismisses any contention that TV advertising works
against online companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's use a car analogy,'' she says. ``You may not actively be
in the buying process, or even thinking about buying. But if
commercials for a certain car company catch your attention, you'll
have that in mind when you do start to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollows says that when Monster.com ads aired during this year's
Super Bowl, the company monitored minute-by-minute traffic on its
site, out of curiosity. The results were surprising: Traffic did
surge right after the commercials aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were literally multitasking,'' Hollows says. ``I find
that bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
