<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYLIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT THE LIGHTS WENT OUT IN LITTLE ROCK _ AND WENT ON AT
DISNEY WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not that Jennings Osborne didn't want his Christmas lights.
He gave away the truly astounding display because some of his
neighbors in Little Rock, Ark., complained of the eye-popping glare
and the extra traffic they attracted.
</P>
<P>
   How bright could these lights possibly be, you ask? By 1993,
Osborne's yard had 3 million lights and could be seen by plane from
80 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas Supreme Court ordered him to cut back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massive commercial lighting displays generated by commercial
transformers are not appropriate in quiet residential
neighborhoods,'' the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how Disney World inherited 350 miles of Christmas
lights, complete with 32.2 miles of extension cables, for its own
``Residential Street'' in the back lot of Disney-MGM Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's infatuation started in 1986, when his 6-year-old
daughter asked him if he would hang some Christmas lights at their
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung 1,000 red lights that first year, and each year after
that it got bigger and bigger,'' the businessman recalled in a
recent telephone visit. ``This year, we added another million in
Orlando, so it's up to 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, there were a couple of neighbors a mile and a
half away who disapproved of all the lights. The two closest gave
me so much trouble I just bought their houses and decorated them,
too. Then some of the other neighbors took me to court, claiming my
lights were a nuisance,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   When Osborne lost in the lower courts, he took his case to the
U.S. Supreme Court, but the high court sent the case back to
Arkansas, where the judges reconvened during their 1993 Christmas
break and ordered Osborne to cut back the number of lights in his
enormous display and the hours they were lit.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to comply would mean a $10,000-a-day fine and 10 days in
jail. When he defied the order, Osborne was fined $10,000, but the
jail time was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so devastated. This was a gift we gave to the people
of Arkansas. I thought my world would come to an end,'' Osborne
says. ``As it turned out, it's the greatest thing that ever
happened. Now millions get to see our lights. We get to share our
gift with the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When news of the lights' fate spread, the Osborne family started
getting letters from people all over the world who wanted to give
the lights a new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, I got a phone call from a gentleman in Orlando who
said he had a residential street where we could put the lights,''
Osborne says. ``I asked him to put his proposal in writing, and a
couple of days later, I got a letter on Disney stationery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him back, and he clarified that Residential Street
was on Disney property, and suddenly I realized exactly where he
was talking about. I thought that was the neatest thing in the
world. We had been going to Disney World the day after Christmas
for years, and I had always said it would be neat to take our
lights with us some time,'' he says. The lights were relocated
there in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Osborne, who is an avid Elvis fan, also lit up
Graceland in Memphis, Tenn. _ but he says he only used about 2
million lights there.
</P>
<P>
   At the Disney-MGM Studios' back lot, the eight houses on
Residential Street are not only outlined in lights but totally
covered with them.
</P>
<P>
   Guests can take in all the lights through special holographic
glasses that give the display even more brilliance _ as well as a
few visual surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The display's 70-foot-tall centerpiece tree has 58,000 lights; a
30-foot tree in one of the yards has 27,300 lights; and 51 other
illuminated trees _ both real and artificial _ brighten the scene.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-D replica of the world floats above the entry to the
display, flashing the words, ``Peace on Earth.'' More than 170
angels are suspended overhead, gently fluttering their wings; two
30-foot-tall carousels grace the lawns; and three flying Santas,
each with eight not-so-tiny reindeer, hover above the rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the spectacle of lights each evening through Jan. 2
are snow flurries, generated by 66 snow machines, even on warm
Florida nights when temperatures rarely dip below 60.
</P>
<P>
   Disney says it takes 21,000 hours of manpower each holiday
season to install the lights and display pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who heads Arkansas Research, a private company that
does research for pharmaceutical companies, is pleased with the new
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lights in 32 places in Arkansas _ about 40 million
lights all together, including Orlando and Memphis,'' he says.''It
just brings tears to my eyes. The courts did the right thing after
all. They opened a million doors for me.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Information: www.jenningsosbornefamily.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
