<HEADLINE>
DON'T EXPECT THIS CAKE TO BE A FLOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader uncovered an old recipe she had for flop cake, which
called for boxes of this and boxes of that. Unfortunately, box
sizes often change, so she had no idea of proportion sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, one of the ingredients called for was Bisquick, a
product still manufactured by General Mills. Sarah Foley of General
Mills found the recipe in her archives and sent it along.
</P>
<P>
   In testing this cake, I didn't find it to ``flop,'' or sink, a
great deal, but it was good nonetheless. To get more of a flop, you
might want to shake the pan once or twice during the baking time.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERSCOTCH FLOP CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coconut
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Mix eggs and sugar; add Bisquick and mix well. Add nuts, coconut
and vanilla. Bake 30 minutes at 350 degrees in a 13-by-9-inch pan.
Let fall.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 354 calories, 13 grams fat, 56
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 71 milligrams cholesterol,
358 milligrams sodium, 33 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S FROSTED LIME CONGEAL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   2 (2.5 ounces each) packages lemon gelatin
</P>
<P>
   2 (2.5 ounces each) packages lime gelatin
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups mayonnaise (don't use low-calorie)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 pound large-curd cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup medium pecan pieces (slightly chopped)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups drained crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   Put gelatin in bowl. Add boiling water and stir until dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   In separate container, whisk together mayonnaise and milk until
smooth. Pour into the gelatin.
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large bowl halfway with ice. Put bowl with gelatin
mixture into the bowl with ice; push bowl down so its sides are
surrounded by ice. Stir occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   When gelatin mixture has thickened slightly (half set), add
cottage cheese, pecans and crushed pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into individual molds or lightly greased bundt or tube pan.
Let set in refrigerator overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 369 calories, 23 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 17 grams protein, 20 milligrams cholesterol,
191 milligrams sodium, 56 percent of calories from fat. Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bennett would like a recipe to make a spinach casserole
similar to the one served at Furr's Cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Pace is looking for the recipe for heavenly delight,
which her mother made in the early 1960s. It contained canned
peaches and Dream Whip.
</P>
<P>
   This one is a real puzzle. Jewell Susong from Johnson City,
Tenn., is trying to find a recipe for a cake her mother-in-law
always made at Christmas. It's called pork cake but contains no
pork products that she knows of. It was a rich, dark cake with lots
of nuts and was delicious with a cup of hot tea in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   A reader sends the following: ``Years ago, probably in the late
'50s, Ladies' Home Journal printed an article and picture of a
carrot pie said to be the favorite of actress Marlene Dietrich. It
was a beautiful pie, with a handsome glazed appearance, and may
have been a recipe from a German restaurant in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   I've contacted the magazine, but a flood destroyed many of its
records from that time period.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
