<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST WORD ON LAST-MINUTE GIFT SHOPPING: CENTRAL MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another day or two, it will officially be time for
last-minute Christmas shopping. It is a time with which I am
painfully familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The only way I survive is to make that desperate trip to the
local mall with the suffocating traffic, exceedingly remote
parking, overwrought and angry shoppers, and nothing but broken
packages and odd sizes on the sale tables.
</P>
<P>
   I generally announce that I'm willing to pay top prices for
useless gifts, wave my credit card and, eventually, reluctantly, a
clerk shows up to help.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year.
</P>
<P>
   I will still shop late. It's my nature. But I'm shopping at a
place I really like. A place where I can find gifts for everyone,
and I don't mind taking a lot of time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to Austin's Central Market.
</P>
<P>
   This 63,000-square-foot grocery store is the North Pole to those
of us who like to cook, and, more important, like to eat. Nestled
back among the oak trees of middle Austin, Central Market is a
giant toy store, a beckoning Santa with a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   It grabs you right at the front door where cases of Clementines
_ sinfully sweet, seedless tangerines from Spain _ are stacked like
orange-colored Nutcrackers. A gift all by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The produce section honestly smells like a refreshing rain has
just fallen. There are no sissy sprinklers spitting water on these
rows of produce. A guy with a cart comes by every few minutes to
shovel _ yes, shovel _ scoops of ice between the stacks.
</P>
<P>
   White asparagus stands at attention and portobello mushrooms the
size of hubcaps spill over from their cases. Winter squashes add
color against the greens of arugula, frisee and romaine. Stalks of
sugar cane cover one corner, next to a giant box of stem-leaf
grapefruit, a Texas variety that is sweet and low in acid.
</P>
<P>
   Central Market has more than 500 varieties of fresh produce.
Many are organically grown, some from local growers.
</P>
<P>
   Gift baskets beg to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   The meat and fish markets are just around the curve, and the
wonders continue. Whole redfish, snapper and grouper peer from
behind the counter. Thick slices of monkfish and mahi-mahi lie next
to rows of tuna and salmon. There are piles of oysters and mussels.
</P>
<P>
   Sausages are the first thing you see at the meat counter and,
believe me, there is a sausage for everyone: turkey cilantro,
andouille, Philly cheese and bright-red chorizo are on display.
Workers behind the counter show off a list of more than 60
varieties and say you only have to make your choice known a day in
advance and they'll do the preparation.
</P>
<P>
   One of their most popular is chicken, cherry and pecan.
</P>
<P>
   The bakery is another place where gift baskets plead for
filling. Large, crusty rounds of blue-cheese bread, buttermilk and
Westphalia pumpernickel lure you to the counter, where it is
apparently OK to press your nose against the glass and ogle.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever asked me to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In an adjacent area, bulk bins are filled with pastas, teas,
coffees, nuts, spices and grains. There are more than 700 varieties
of cheeses from Texas and around the world. An olive and salsa bar
offers tubs of pico de gallo, guacamole, basil pesto, hummus and
blue cheese-pancetta dip.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite place, a small, unadorned corner of the store, is
the tortilleria, where organic whole-wheat tortillas, flour
tortillas, and spicy, peppered Southwestern tortillas come right
off the hot presses. There is a butter tortilla that causes you to
slap passers-by and drag them to the counter.
</P>
<P>
   There's a floral department, a cafe, and a beer and wine
selection that literally numbers in the thousands. Central Market
caters and offers cooking classes, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to fill your own gift baskets, the store has
people who will do it for you.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, Central Market is open from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.,
seven days a week. There are two stores in Austin _ the older and
best-known is at 4001 N. Lamar Blvd.; the other is at 4477 S. Lamar
Blvd. Santa lives at both.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
