<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      12-15 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Circuits stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for Thursday,
Dec. 16:
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WORKER-MONITORING (Undated) _ In 1999, at least 45 percent
of employers said they monitored their employees' phone calls,
computer files or e-mail messages, according to the American
Management Association. That number, based on a survey of more than
1,000 human-resources managers at corporations of varying sizes, is
up from 35 percent two years ago. The monitoring is necessary,
employers argue, because of the changing nature of the workplace.
Supervisors must keep tabs on which workers are wasting company
time by surfing to entertainment Web sites, which ones are sending
e-mail messages that create a hostile environment for women or
members of minority groups, and which ones are distributing company
secrets or jamming their networks with bulk e-mail. Balancing that
desire for control with an employee's rights to privacy has never
been easy. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
