<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT GLITTERS MAY ALSO GLOW FOR THE NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Angel or devil? Millennium cutie or retro siren?
The choice in makeup style this holiday season is entirely up to
you.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic companies have tapped various trends for gala looks.
Traditionally, red lipstick was the holiday staple, but as New
Year's Eve draws nigh, red has been augmented by things glimmery,
silvery and space age.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.C, that fashion-forward company whose reds are sublime
(particularly Russian Red, reported to be Madonna's favorite), has
spun on a dime this season, promoting a snowbound look with
superfine glitter over a white-white makeup base, silver lipstick
to wear alone or over a luscious pink, a collection of mirrored,
pearly or glitter hair ornaments and false eyelashes spiced up with
a teensy band of glitter.
</P>
<P>
   Yves Saint Laurent, meanwhile, has chosen a golden glamour-gal
look polished off with one of the most beautiful red lipsticks
around. Spinning off from Queen Amidala's signature Kabuki style in
``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace,'' YSL makeup designer Terri de
Gunzberg designed a collection called One Love that is truly
original and complimentary to just about all complexions and hair
color.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of the look is Royal Glow, a ``dry oil'' with a
coppery-gold sparkle. Coupled with Shimmering Powder, an iridescent
beigy-pink also flecked in metallic, Royal Glow, the effect is a
rosy, healthy glow. Amidala's Red, the Rouge Pure No. 71, is an
intense blue-red that works magic on both blondes and brunettes.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Simonson from YSL/Saks Fifth Avenue in San Francisco used
Amidala's Red on model Tracy with a very simple, '50s-style oeil de
biche (doe-eye). In other words: She lined Tracy's eyes with black
liquid liner, popped on the M.A.C lashes, mascara'd like crazy and
from there, let the lips take precedence. The effect: Fifties
Screen Siren.
</P>
<P>
   On model Brittany, Alexis created a frosted look with pale
lavenders (Tommy Hilfiger's eye shadow pencil), shimmery ``snow
flakes'' (M.A.C's glitter) and a pale rose/lavender YSL powder
blush on the cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   Other marvelous ways to glow for the holidays:
</P>
<P>
   _ Este Lauder's fat glitter-stick that leaves a trail of pinky
copper sparkles wherever you want them; Lancme's Micro Paillettes
from last Christmas season, which can be sprinkled in the hair
(spray it first), or laid like a trail of fairy dust on the body
(over body cream or Vaseline to make it stay).
</P>
<P>
   _ Chanel's handy little pots of sheer sparkle, Cristal Glitter
(diamond-bright flecks suspended in a clear gel to put on face or
body) or Pure Frost (in either Crimson, a metallic red for cheeks
and lips, or Cristal, a pinky-white sheer cream to highlight
cheekbones, the decolletage, eyelids, whatever with a subtle,
light-catching sheen), plus Chanel's definitive silver metallic
nail enamel, Silver Bells.
</P>
<P>
   _ Versace's silver glitter eyeliner/eyelid decor, 2000 Lights on
Eyes, a silver-flecked gel that you can paint on even the most
sensitive eyelids with a self-contained brush.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to collect their look from many
different cosmetic counters, Francois Nars has put it all together
for in two specially designed millennium artist palettes, Last
Dance I (warm tones of copper, gold, peach and white pearl pared
with burnished browns for the lips and body glitter for fun) and
Last Dance II (berry tones and reds with a mixture of silver and
gold accents) at Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
