<HEADER>
A9844 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CENTURY-IN-ARTS-TEX     12-15 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-IN-ARTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP 10 ARTS HAPPENINGS OF THE CENTURY: CLASSICAL MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Till year's end, the Star-Telegram brings you a
subjective look at the top 10 moments of the century in the arts.
Today: Classical Music
</P>
<P>
   1913: In spite of a rioting audience, the show goes on at the
premiere of Igor Stravinsky's ``The Rite of Spring'' in Paris _ and
modernism in music is born, with dissonance and orchestral color
evoking a primitive past but reflecting the turmoil and energy of
the age.
</P>
<P>
   1923: Liszt meets Tin Pan Alley when George Gershwin's still
appealing combination of jazz and classical music, ``Rhapsody in
Blue'' for piano and jazz band, debuts in New York.
</P>
<P>
   1934: The melodious music of Tchaikovsky and the limitations of
his young, mostly female ensemble inspire Russian-born
choreographer George Balanchine to create ``Serenade.'' Premiered
at the estate of a wealthy Balanchine admirer, ``Serenade'' will
define ballet in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Denied, because of her race, a routine booking at
Constitution Hall, an auditorium in Washington, D.C., owned and
operated by the Daughters of the American Revolution,
African-American contralto Marian Anderson instead appears on the
steps of the Lincoln Memorial before a crowd of 75,000. In 1955,
she will become the first African-American to perform at the
Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   1941: A literally captive audience of 5,000 prisoners of war in
Germany witnesses the premiere of imprisoned French composer
Olivier Messiaen's ``Quartet for the End of Time.'' Working with a
damaged piano, clarinet, violin and cello available in the prison
camp, the composer (who plays the piano at the premiere) turns the
limitations of the instruments to his advantage, creating a unique
sound and vision of angels in the midst of international
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   1942: With Russia under siege by Adolf Hitler's armies, Dmitri
Shostakovich composes his Symphony No. 7, a tribute to the national
spirit and courage of his homeland. After the premiere of the
symphony in Russia, the score is microfilmed, carried by plane to
Tehran, Iran, and by car to Cairo, Egypt, then flown across North
Africa and the Atlantic to America, where leading conductors
compete for the right to perform it. The American debut is
presented in a radio broadcast with Arturo Toscanini conducting.
</P>
<P>
   1945: Just weeks after the end of World War II in Europe,
audiences in London see the birth of a new type of 20th-century
opera when Benjamin Britten's ``Peter Grimes'' premieres.
Extraordinary musical lyricism and profound pessimism combine to
launch the career of the most significant operatic composer of the
postwar era.
</P>
<P>
   1958: The Cold War thaws temporarily when young Texas pianist
Van Cliburn wins first prize _ and the hearts of Russian music
lovers _ at the Tchaikovsky International Competition in Moscow.
Americans respond as enthusiastically as the Russians, greeting the
new national hero with a ticker-tape parade in New York on his
return.
</P>
<P>
   1976: Scott Joplin, one of America's greatest musical geniuses
and the creator, via ragtime, of the most significant body of solo
piano music written in America, is finally honored with a special
Pulitzer Prize for music, 60 years after his death at age 48 in
1916.
</P>
<P>
   1989: American conductor-composer Leonard Bernstein celebrates
the fall of the Berlin Wall with performances of Beethoven's Ninth
Symphony. In the choral section, Bernstein substitutes the word
``''Freiheit'''' (''freedom'') for the original ``''Freude''''
(''joy''). Appropriately, soloists for the event represent East
Germany, West Germany, the United States and Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: The Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians; ``The
Companion to 20th Century Music'' by Norman Lebrecht; ``Marian
Anderson: Lady From Philadelphia,'' by Shirlee Petkin; ``Leonard
Bernstein,'' by Humphrey Burton; ``Leonard Bernstein: A Life,'' by
Meryle Secrest; The Concise Oxford Dictionary of Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
