<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Dec. 16:
</P>
<P>
   HIPPIE-THRONE (San Francisco) _ She is no longer a lithe hippie
goddess. But as she sits by the fire in her rhinestone-encrusted
living room, the colors quivering, it's clear that the spirit of
Lotus Carnation still dwells inside Lois Anderson, 72. It was
Lotus, as she was known in the late 1960s _ as opposed to Lois, now
a part-time librarian _ who created The Throne (1973), a
resplendent creation born of acid and epoxy, designed to transport
the sitter into another realm. ``We saw patterns everywhere,'' she
recalled the other day, lounging barefoot. ``We sat and listened at
the feet of every Indian guru, glommed on to every microcosm and
macrocosm, then we looked at their art. I got up one morning and
just like you say `I think I'll have a ham sandwich for lunch,' out
came the Throne.'' By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   RANCH-HOUSE (Houston) _ These days, ranch houses are an
endangered species. Once the revered symbol of postwar prosperity,
these rectangular houses, with their rec rooms and picture windows
and skinny wrought-iron balustrades, are now as dated as Melmac. In
this one neighborhood, at least 100 ranch houses have been torn
down in the last five years, replaced by today's dream: the
multistoried, Palladian-windowed, double-height ceilinged,
great-roomed mansionette; Tara on a quarter-acre lot. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MTV-BUNKER-PROJECT (Undated) _ Those pondering whether to hunker
down as the Year 2000 approaches may look to a decision by MTV to
bunker down. MTV Interactive, the online division of the MTV cable
television network, is sponsoring a stunt for New Year's Eve that
will relocate six young Americans to a dwelling that's not so much
far from home as it is deep. They will live for a week in the
bowels of Times Square as a kind of survival squad, in case the
worst-case scenarios of the millennial Jeremiahs come true. That
stay in their redoubt is being called the Bunker Project _ ``The
Real World'' meets the end of the world. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NUNNERY-ROCKIES (Virginia Dale, Colo.) _ For a moment, Sister
Ancilla Armijo seemed like any proud new homeowner. Looking
heavenward, she swept her hand across the towering, domed ceiling
to the skylight windows of the new chapel here, and extolled the
virtues of simplicity. She scoffed at suggestions that stained
glass be installed where there are now views of snowy mountaintops.
``Why do we need those things?'' she asked. ``The land is
beautiful, the building is beautiful _ it just lifts you up to
prayer.'' In this most dramatic American setting, where the Great
Plains meet the Rocky Mountains, a vision of the most improbable
sort is materializing: a 21st-century Benedictine abbey. Last
month, Sister Ancilla and the 20 other nuns of the Abbey of St.
Walburga moved into the nunnery, which was designed and built for
them here in northern Colorado. By Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
