<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WORKER-MONITORING (Undated) _ In 1999, at least 45 percent
of employers said they monitored their employees' phone calls,
computer files or e-mail messages, according to the American
Management Association. That number, based on a survey of more than
1,000 human-resources managers at corporations of varying sizes, is
up from 35 percent two years ago. The monitoring is necessary,
employers argue, because of the changing nature of the workplace.
Supervisors must keep tabs on which workers are wasting company
time by surfing to entertainment Web sites, which ones are sending
e-mail messages that create a hostile environment for women or
members of minority groups, and which ones are distributing company
secrets or jamming their networks with bulk e-mail. Balancing that
desire for control with an employee's rights to privacy has never
been easy. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WORKER-PRIVACY (Undated) _ The legal status of privacy in
workplace. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ On the perils of last-minute on
line shopping. By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CITY-PLANNING (Undated) _ Using software to visualize and
plan cities and buildings. By Nina Teicholz.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly computer column:
Viruses are getting nastier, but there are clear ways to cope with
them. By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NEWS (Undated) _ Techno news and notes: Free version of
Eudora; bidding on presidential candidates; stock trading at
mid-mountain for upscale skiers.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ARTSJOURNAL (Undated) _ Artsjournal, with links to other
sites. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SANTA-LETTERS (Undated) _ And essay: Letters to Santa arrive
via e-mail. By Elizabeth Stone.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MOOG (Undated) _ Profile of Dr. Moog, synthesizer inventor.
By Frank Houston.
</P>
<P>
