<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(EDS: Replace (AT) in the last graf with the typographical
symbol.) 
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using Linux To Run a PC
</P>
<P>
   Q: What exactly is the Linux system and what can the average
person do with it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Linux, a computer operating system created by Linus Torvalds,
a Finnish programmer, has been getting a lot of attention as an
alternative to Windows. Linux is open-source software, which means
that the program's source code is made public. It is available free
to anyone who would like to use it or modify it. Commercial
versions of Linux, like one released by Red Hat, can be purchased
from software vendors, and many Linux books also include a CD-ROM
containing the program.
</P>
<P>
   Linux devotees say that it crashes less often that Windows, and
several companies have released programs to run on the platform,
like WordPerfect by Corel. You can also find other applications for
Linux. You can install it on the same computer on which you run
Windows and choose which system to use when you start up.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't nearly as much software available for Linux as there
is for Windows, however, and some feel that the system interface
isn't as user-friendly as the Macintosh or Windows platforms. If
you want to know more, there are plenty of Web sites devoted to
Linux. The Linux Online site (www.linux.org), with links to dozens
of Linux resources, is a good place to start. There is also a
version of Linux for the Macintosh Power PC, and more information
on it can be found at www.linuxppc.org.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
