<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HOT IN VIDEOGAMES FOR KIDS THIS HOLIDAY SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents, it could be worse. It could be 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year when you not only had to sweat which video
games your kid wanted for Christmas, you had to figure out which
system they wanted. There were three new ones, Sony PlayStation,
Nintendo 64 and Sega Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the system picking's easier. The only new one is
Sega's impressive Dreamcast. Sequels to the PlayStation and N64
aren't expected until next year. Whew, you should say to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   But picking out games can be just as frazzling: ``Is this the
right Pokemon game?'' ``Didn't I get him Tomb Raider last year?''
``Wasn't Donkey Kong the bomb when I was a kid? This must be old or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   So many games, so many questions. That's why we've come up with
this guide to the top 10 hottest, most popular game titles of 1999.
These are the ones your child wants for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Toy Story 2
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Tots to teens.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Action/adventure games.
</P>
<P>
   System: Nintendo 64 and Sony PlayStation
</P>
<P>
   Price: $50-$60
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: If you've seen the movie, you've played the game. As
sci-fi action figure Buzz Lightyear, you gotta rescue your cowboy
pal Woody before an evil toy collector sells him on eBay or
something.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Spectacular; you could swear you're watching the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: A kids' game, but cool enough for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Toy Commander
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Young guns
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... A good challenge _ and a good fight.
</P>
<P>
   System: Sega Dreamcast
</P>
<P>
   Price: $55
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Totally cool premise: Neglected, old toys rebel
against shiny new ones. Players maneuver toy cars and planes
through the kitchen, bedroom, garage and other household areas,
battling things like wind-up mice. Some of the challenging missions
_ drop sugar cubes into the cocoa from a plane _ are dumb, but the
amusing fighting sequences make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: The crisp, animated graphics are almost identical to
those in Toy Story, adding to the confusion between the two games.
Tom Hanks is nowhere to be found here, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Loads of fun, but definitely for younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Donkey Kong 64
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Everyone's gonna love this one.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Well, Mario 64.
</P>
<P>
   System: Nintendo 64
</P>
<P>
   Price: $55
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Old story, new game. Donkey Kong's stash of bananas
has been stolen, so it's up to the Kongs to gather 'em up and nab
the freak who took 'em. Like past Kong titles, DK64 is two games in
one: You spend most of the time picking up bananas and tromping
through jungles and other terrains, but there are also several
minigames in which winners are awarded extra 'nanas.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Pretty much what you can expect from any N64 title
these days: impressively smooth and colorful.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: One of the best N64 titles. Good luck finding one.
</P>
<P>
   Games: NBA 2K and NFL 2K
</P>
<P>
   Age range: All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... B-ball and football
</P>
<P>
   System: Sega Dreamcast
</P>
<P>
   Price: $55
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: These two games _ one's basketball, the other
football _ have set a new standard for sports games. To put it as
simply as possible, they're why people are scooping up the
Dreamcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: The line between fantasy and reality just got erased.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Musts.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Spyro: Ripto's Rage!
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Young and the restless.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Cute-little-creature-hero games like Rayman
and Crash Bandicoot.
</P>
<P>
   System: PlayStation
</P>
<P>
   Price: $50
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Spyro's an adorable little dragon whose first,
self-titled game was a worthy sleeper hit. A little older, Spyro's
back, scurrying through 30 pitfall-filled, enemy-laced levels. Ya
can't let this guy die. He's so cute!
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Strong game for the under-13 set.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Tomb Raider: The Last Revelation
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Teen guys who have a crush on Lara Croft _ and
blowing stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Indiana Jones-type adventure games.
</P>
<P>
   System: PlayStation
</P>
<P>
   Price: $50
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Wearing her trademark tight shorts/shirt combo,
evil-fighter babe Lara Croft returns for what is supposedly her
last adventure. As usual, she's gotta blow to bits zombies, mummies
and other monstrous pains while trying to make her way through
ancient ruins and spooky caverns.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Best yet, with an emphasis on details, like light and
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Easily the best of the Raider bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Resident Evil 3: Nemesis
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Dawson's Creek-age kids, although we know younger
ones are hot to play it.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Gory, gruesome,
walk-around-and-waste-everything games.
</P>
<P>
   System: PlayStation
</P>
<P>
   Price: $55
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: RE 3 picks up where the first RE left off, with
heroine Jill Valentine getting the heck away from the
zombie-infested mansion. In RE 3, she's gotta fight her way through
Raccoon City, doing what she does best: saucing zombies. Certain
choices will affect the game's outcome, making it far less
predictable than the first two.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Carrying on the Resident Evil tradition, the graphics
are disturbingly realistic, full of unsavory imagery.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Not for the fainthearted or very young.
</P>
<P>
   Game: NHL Championship 2000
</P>
<P>
   Age range: 13 and up
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Knocking out someone's teeth.
</P>
<P>
   System: PlayStation
</P>
<P>
   Price: $55
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Like you need instructions here: Body check, cross
check, push and trip your way to the net.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Among the mountain of new hockey titles, this one's
one of the best, thanks to the sharp, detailed, realistic graphics.
It's not as fast as the EA series, but it looks _ and, to some
extent, plays _ much better.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: We have no choice but to love it _ Dallas Stars
center Mike Modano is on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Pokmon Pinball
</P>
<P>
   Age range: All ages _ and we mean that.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... Well, pinball.
</P>
<P>
   System: Game Boy Color
</P>
<P>
   Price: $35
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: You don't need to be a Pokmon expert _ or even know
how to pronounce Pikachu _ to play this pinball game. Only real
Pokmon reference is that the game allows you to capture Pokmon as
you nail them with your ball.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Not bad for a Game Boy game, which can sometimes be
unplayable.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Probably the only time a parent will pick up a
Pokmon game.
</P>
<P>
   Game: Pokmon Yellow
</P>
<P>
   Age range: Pokmon knows no limits.
</P>
<P>
   Kid's gotta like ... More like, kid's gotta be able to play
other two Pokmon games, Red and Blue.
</P>
<P>
   System: Nintendo Game Boy
</P>
<P>
   Price: $30
</P>
<P>
   Game plan: Train Pokmon, walk around and do stuff _ don't look
at us, we don't know how to play this thing.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: Horrible, but does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: You're probably on your way to pick one up right
now.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
