<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MOOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATHER 'ROUND THE ELECTRONIC PIANO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK HOUSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Moog may not have created MP3 files or hip-hop
sampling. But he may be the person who made the world safe for
electronic music.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the release of the Moog synthesizer in 1965, Moog
has helped popularize the strange, unworldly sounds of electronic
music and, in the process, taken the music synthesizer out of the
lab and put it into the hands of aspiring musicians.
</P>
<P>
   And so there is an inescapable irony behind Moog's latest
project, the Van Koevering Interactive Piano. The piano, which was
developed with an entrepreneur, David Van Koevering, combines
computer technology with the elegant craftsmanship of a fine
concert piano.
</P>
<P>
   The design is important because Moog wants his instrument to
accommodate the social aspect of music, to encourage people to
``gather 'round and sing, play, dance or listen.''
</P>
<P>
   So the inventor who helped artists make music in the isolated
obscurity of home studios now believes that people just don't spend
enough time together playing music?
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a very long trend away from music as a social
activity,'' Moog said in an e-mail interview. ``Before the radio
and the electric phonograph, people made their own music, for
themselves and for each other. What I see now is that, more and
more, we're all in our own little boxes, using the fruits of
technology to make or listen to music in isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added about his new piano, ``it looks good in a living
room.''
</P>
<P>
   The early synthesizers were hardly so domestic. When RCA created
the first modern synthesizer in 1955, the machine filled an entire
room. Engineers fed it binary codes on a paper roll, since there
was no keyboard for an interface, and an oscillator generated a
sound wave with a particular timbre, pitch and volume.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after RCA built its synthesizer, Moog introduced the
Moog synthesizer, the first to use attack-decay-sustain-release
(ADSR) envelopes, sets of parameters that control a sound's onset
and fade. Moog's envelope generators, like many of his other
designs, became a standard component on later synthesizers and
programmable keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone realized that was the way to do it,'' said Joel
Chadabe, president of the Electronic Music Foundation. ``It was
superb engineering, beautifully put together, excellent in every
way _ flexible, simple, durable.''
</P>
<P>
   While RCA synthesizers had cost at least $100,000, the new Moog
sold for $11,000 in 1967. ``It had a tremendous impact on many
people and brought electronic music to many composers, both popular
and academic,'' said Jeffrey Hass, the director of the University
of Indiana's Center for Electronic and Computer Music.
</P>
<P>
   The Moog's breakthrough came in 1969, when the musician Walter
Carlos had a huge, Grammy-winning hit with ``Switched-on Bach,''
featuring renditions of J.S. Bach performed on a Moog. The Canadian
pianist Glenn Gould called it ``the finest performance of any of
the Brandenburgs _ live, canned or intuited _ that I've ever
heard.'' The Moog then turned up in ``Because,'' by The Beatles,
and in the score to ``A Clockwork Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog followed up with the performance-minded Minimoog, which
helped spread the Moog sound into musical genres from the
avant-garde to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a Minimoog would make it a lot easier to get a job
playing the local Ramada Inn,'' Moog said.
</P>
<P>
   The first digital synthesizer, the Synclavier, had been
introduced in 1975. By the early 1980s, digital sampling, computers
and MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital Interface) standardization
heralded a second wave of innovation in electronic music.
</P>
<P>
   But Moog was an analog inventor who mostly parted ways with
digital revolutionaries. He made innovative control devices for
electronic instruments, such as a flat touch plate and a highly
touch-sensitive keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moog has been interested in the possibilities of extending the
traditional keyboard,'' Keislar said. But ``most people want to
press a button and hear music come out. Such systems are probably
destined to remain experimental, even if elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog, now 65, wants to capture the public's imagination at home
with the Van Koevering piano, which sells for $8,000 and up. There
are no strings under the lid, only a Windows-powered computer, a
120-watt amplifier and a half-dozen stereo speakers. An intuitive,
laptop-size touch screen takes the place of sheet music.
</P>
<P>
   The piano's educational software might give piano teachers a run
for their money. It will transcribe any composition onto the screen
(or onto paper, if you attach a printer) as fast as you can play
it. It offers 128 different sounds, including a digitally sampled
Steinway grand, and 256 tracks for recording. Full orchestration
can be added at the touch of a few on-screen buttons, and a CD
burner can be attached to make copies of the resulting symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Moog said he designed the piano for the home. Electronic
instruments have long been limited by their less-than-user-friendly
shells. Moog, who has ``always liked the social aspect of music,''
says instruments that were once ``hardware-intensive, with dozens
upon dozens of buttons, lights, and switches'' can now be updated
with interactive software, like the Van Koevering's touch screen,
``which is highly intuitive, so that anyone can figure out how to
use it just by looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As an engineer, I've spent a lot of time with high-tech
equipment,'' he said, which starts off being a source of amusement.
``But by the time the amusement wears off, the solitary musician
may begin to realize that something basic and low-tech _ playing
together _ is missing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
