<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VERTICAL-KEYBOARD     12-15 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VERTICAL-KEYBOARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERTICAL TYPING EASY ON WRISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (Circuits)  
(af) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last decade, the computer industry has been haunted by
the fact that typing on a keyboard for long periods can often lead
to painful conditions called repetitive stress injuries, including
carpal tunnel syndrome, one of the most painful and potentially
damaging.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Cornell University supports the idea that the
problem may be prevented or treated by having people use a vertical
keyboard design that lets them hold their hands in a more
comfortable position.
</P>
<P>
   The tendons and nerves that connect the arms to the hands travel
through a narrow passage called the carpal tunnel. Excessive
typing, particularly in certain positions, can irritate the nerves
and impair the use of the hands, not only in typing but also in
other activities.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, researchers have focused on the position of the
hands in the hope of minimizing the stress placed on the nerves by
the tendons during typing.
</P>
<P>
   Bending the wrists in any direction can reduce the size of the
tunnel and pack the tendons and nerves closer together, creating
more trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that training typists to keep their hands in the
position that places the least strain will reduce and perhaps
eliminate the problem of carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornell research was conducted by Professor Alan Hedge, who
said, ``If you raise your hand up just 15 degrees, you're doubling
the pressure on the nerve running through the carpal.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, done at the Cornell University College of Human
Ecology, and published on the Internet (www.typesafe.com), examined
the performance of skilled typists using a prototype of a vertical
split keyboard developed by Ergonomic-Interface of La Jolla, Calif.
The company sponsors the laboratory that performed the work.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is split into two parts that are arranged
vertically so the palms face each other during typing. The keys are
in the usual ``qwerty'' configuration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This position allows the radius and the ulna bones in the
forearm to run parallel to each other instead of crossing over,''
Hedge explained.
</P>
<P>
   That further simplifies the path for the tendons and nerves.
</P>
<P>
   In the test, the typists were wired with gloves that measured
the bending of the wrists in a 15-minute typing test. Each typist
used both a vertical keyboard and a traditional one, and the
researchers compared the positions of the wrists.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded: ``Seventy-one percent of hand
flexion/extension typing movements were in the lowest-risk zone
when using the vertical keyboard, compared with only 44 percent
when using a conventional keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the typists had little trouble learning to use
the vertical keyboard in the short amount of time given for the
test. But typing speeds dropped about 10 percent, and accuracy
dropped about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were not long enough to establish whether the typing
would return to former levels if typists used the vertical keyboard
every day.
</P>
<P>
   After the tests, many of the typists said they preferred regular
keyboards. The typists who took part in the study did not suffer
from repetitive stress injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge suggested that the keyboard was just part of an overall
solution. He said that the position of the typist's chair and the
placement of the keyboard were very important.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Udell, a computer consultant, agreed with that point. He
said he relied heavily on a specially designed chair to combat pain
in his wrists. The chair has half of the keyboard in each arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole-body approach,'' Udell said. ``The chair gets the
weight off of your neck and shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Conway, president of KMC Concepts in Santa Rosa, Calif.,
designed and patented a very flexible keyboard that allows the user
to position the two halves of the keyboard in practically any
position, including a vertical position.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said that such flexibility was ideal because ``the most
important step is to change positions frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   The research may generate more interest in split keyboards.
Although many major companies, like Microsoft, Lucent Technologies
and Apple Computer, have built adaptive keyboards, a number of
promising designs have disappeared from the marketplace. The
keyboards remain niche products that people turn to only after
severe problems emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Heisler, a partner in KeyAlt.com, an online store for
alternative keyboards, said: ``Unfortunately, more often than not,
people start feeling uncomfortable before they start looking for a
solution. Some companies are steadfastly pretending that it doesn't
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   He welcomes the new research and suggested that the flexibility
might help serve other needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met a young woman who had a deformed left arm that was only
as long as her left elbow,'' Heisler said. ``I was able to modify
one of her keyboards so she could type with her left arm and her
right arm, which was normal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-EMPIRES-GAME-NYT &LR;      12-15 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EMPIRES-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME THEORY: TECHNOLOGY AS THE GUIDING HAND OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(bl) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people see history as a set of names, dates and points on a
map. Other people see it as the evolution of ideas that drive
society: science, religion and politics. In Age of Empires 2, a
computer strategy game published by Microsoft, the grand sweep of
human events is expressed as a series of technological upgrades.
Picking up where the original ended, with the fall of Rome, the
game takes place over 1,000 years, leading up to the Renaissance,
as civilizations race to replace their hardware and software with
more elaborate versions, at considerable cost.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, Age of Empires 2 is typical of the real-time
strategy genre: you begin by foraging, then stockpile resources,
undertake construction projects according to Abraham Maslow's
hierarchy of needs (starting with houses, mills and lumber camps,
working up to universities and cathedrals), explore, create and
train an army, and vanquish computer-generated enemies or online
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In most real-time strategy games, the goal is to win by conquest
_ to take over the map. In Age of Empires 2, you can also win by
constructing a Wonder of the World that demonstrates the
superiority of your civilization and having it stand for a certain
period of time. Or you can collect all the religious relics
(showcased in your network of monasteries, the complete collection
of holy artifacts gives you a lock on the highly sought
medieval-pilgrim demographic group).
</P>
<P>
   End goals may differ. But the ramp that leads up to them is
always the same: technological evolution, achieved by plowing money
into research at every step along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting thing about Age of Empires 2, as opposed to
science fiction strategy games like Command and Conquer, is that
this process is grafted onto historical time periods. To advance
from the Dark Age to the Feudal Age, you need to build two
different Dark Age buildings and pay 500 food units. Invest the
resources, click the Advance to Feudal Age button, and you have
upgraded your socioeconomic operating system. Militiamen are
replaced by more powerful men-at-arms. New blacksmith features
become available.
</P>
<P>
   As you upgrade to the Castle Age and the Imperial Age, new
research opportunities inform your strategy. Do you want to invest
in military advancements in weaponry and armor? Or would you rather
research masonry and architecture to fortify your buildings? It's
also a good idea to invest in market technologies like coinage,
guilds and banking (medieval business-to-business applications, if
you will) to improve the efficiency of your economic system.
</P>
<P>
   All of these technological developments are rooted in medieval
chronology. In agriculture, for instance, you start with simple
foraging and cultivation. Hundreds of years later, you have an
improved horse harness, a heavy plow and crop rotation. All of that
increases your agricultural yield, providing the surplus necessary
to trade, build and fight in more expensive and sophisticated ways
and compete against your rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of play, you understand the Middle Ages as a
series of objects and their consequences. What sort of weapons were
people using? What kind of ships were they sailing? How were the
castle walls constructed?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike textbook information, nothing is learned for its own
sake. Every piece of historical information is relevant and useful
in the context of the game. It's part of a drama in which you are
the prime actor. Victory or defeat depends on the material culture
of your civilization. So there's a heavy incentive to learn about
looms and ax heads and battering rams.
</P>
<P>
   Age of Empires 2 will be responsible for a thousandfold increase
in the number of people who know the word ``trebuchet''
(TREB-you-shet). The trebuchet was a large catapult weapon with a
long throwing arm and a missile bag suspended by ropes. When
released, the arm swung up, the bag flew forward, and projectiles
were sent plunging down to shatter rooftops and towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trebuchets were expensive and complicated machines, requiring
specialists to build and operate,'' the manual explains. ``They
could only be moved in parts and required assembly before use.
Edward I of England refused the surrender of Stirling Castle in
Scotland on one occasion so that he could watch his most recently
acquired trebuchet in action.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the game, you really want a trebuchet. You also
know something about Edward I of England. And you know what you
would do in his shoes: You've got this brand-new trebuchet; it's
all unpacked, and you're about to get medieval on the lord of
Stirling Castle. Suddenly, he wants to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy, in a fit of anachronism, to imagine Edward standing
in the doorway of his battle tent, cell phone in hand: ``Yeah, it's
Ed. I'm about to wreck your castle. Surrender? You're cutting out,
Stirling. I can't hear you. Did you say `No surrender?' Well, good
luck with the salvage operation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, victory boils down to who has the best gear. ``The
people who get the technology fastest often have a decisive
advantage,'' said Bruce Shelley, Age of Empire's lead designer.
``If you've got a Feudal Age army fighting an Imperial Age army,
you're probably going to lose. It's a subliminal message, almost,
about technology _ and technology did advance quite a bit during
this time period. On a basic level, we're teaching people about
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   It's poignant to hear a computer programmer invoke the quaint
19th-century notion of progress to describe a product whose code
will be obsolete in less than a decade, and whose operating system
is under attack from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it makes you reflect on the Wonder of the World
strategy: You invest vast amounts of money and manpower to build a
cathedral. When it's finished, a clock starts ticking down, and
rival players move heaven and earth to tear down your church. When
the clock reaches zero, if the cathedral is still standing, you
win. It's a war about architecture. It ends in a siege. And it's
always more fun to be the barbarians than to defend the fortified
walls of a monument. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Age of Empires 2: The Age of Kings; CD-ROM for Windows
95 and 98; $49.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
