<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPER: THE WEB IS NO PLACE FOR LAST-MINUTE GIFT-BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In early December, I received e-mail offering me $10 off my next
purchase at Buy.com. This immediately reminded me that during this
gift-giving season, I had not bought nearly enough presents for
myself.
</P>
<P>
   Being both very extravagant and very cheap, I was excited to see
that $10 off would enable me to buy two music CDs for less than the
price of one at my local store. So I checked on the availability of
two albums I had not thought of since high school _ Billy Joel's
``The Stranger'' and Elton John's ``Madman Across the Water.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com informed me they both were in stock and usually shipped
within 48 hours, so I ordered them on Dec. 2 for a total of $11.80,
and immediately began to fantasize about blasting Joel's ``Vienna''
in the kitchen while cooking dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days passed. No CDs. I logged on to Buy.com's online order
tracking service, typed my order number and learned _ well, not
much. My order was ``processing.'' Whatever that meant, I suspected
that it was not good.
</P>
<P>
   Had my credit card been rejected? Were the items unavailable?
Had someone decided that it might be better if I didn't sing ``you
can get what you want, or you can just get old'' at the top of my
lungs while chopping onions?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the experience left me loath to turn to the
Internet, unlike many desperate last-minute shoppers. You know who
you are. You let the shopping slide, telling yourself that it is so
much more convenient to click on a Buy button than to engage in a
to-the-death struggle for the last parking space at the mall. But
then, you're probably the sort of person who thinks it might be fun
to parachute from an airplane or order grilled salmon in a chain
restaurant in a land-locked city.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call to Buy.com's toll-free number about my CDs
confirmed my fears. A customer service representative said the
items were not in stock. In fact, he said, they were on back order
until _ well, he couldn't say. Unless the items became available by
Dec. 13, he said, I should not count on receiving the order before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, a Buy.com spokeswoman, Jennifer Blanchfield,
offered a different explanation. She said the CDs were in stock,
but somehow an unspecified number of orders placed on Dec. 2 _
including mine _ were misplaced. Although she said the orders were
located and processed Dec. 8, my order status did not change until
Dec. 13, when the site informed me the order was ``completed.''
</P>
<P>
   That got me thinking about all the customer service problems I
have experienced while shopping online during this holiday season:
the Monopoly game that Amazon.com said would probably ship within
three days (it took nine), the sweaters I mailed back to Delias.com
in November ($90) and still haven't received confirmation that they
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Although these complaints may have seemed minor at the time _
even if it took the children's Prehistoric Cave Painting kit a
month to arrive, it still got here on time, after all _ we are now
heading into that annual season known as the last-minute holiday
shopping frenzy. With only nine shopping days left until Christmas,
no impediment is too minor.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the daredevil temperament necessary for online
shopping this late in the season, you should bear a few things in
mind. The quality of customer service varies wildly _ not only from
Web site to Web site but also from moment to moment. I ordered the
missing Monopoly game from Amazon.com without thinking twice
because the site had my trust. After all, I already placed and
quickly received two previous holiday orders.
</P>
<P>
   Consider just one aspect of customer service _ return policies.
In November, the market researchers at Extraprise Advisors in
Boston studied the return policies of 50 of the busiest Internet
retailers and found huge differences. For instance, don't assume
you can return items you bought online to a store to avoid paying
shipping charges to ship it back. Purchases from online retailers
like Barnesandnoble.com must be mailed back. And if you want to
return an order from Borders.com to a Borders store, call first;
stores are not required to accept online returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you shop online, you are not going to get the same
consistent customer service experience as you would at your
favorite retailer at the mall,'' said Allen Bonde, one of the
study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   Before you order, check a site's customer service policies and
take the time to phone a live, human customer-service
representative to confirm information published online. This can be
a challenge; last week I called half a dozen companies' customer
service numbers and waited on hold for periods up to 15 minutes,
except at Etoy.com, which disconnected me after 10 minutes. But
you'll be even more frustrated if you order something and it
doesn't arrive in time.
</P>
<P>
   Come next year, if you have a customer service problem, you will
be able to go to www.feedbackdirect.com, a site that will begin
operating online in January. Feedbackdirect says it will intercede
on the behalf of customers to resolve complaints with online
merchants. Or follow the advice at www.safeshopping.org, a site
affiliated with the American Bar Association, that recommends
reading a site's customer service page before buying and paying
with a credit card to limit liability.
</P>
<P>
   What about my CDs? Unless I wanted the aggravation of canceling
my entire order with Buy.com, I really had no choice. On Monday, I
went to a local music store and saw both CDs. I even held them in
my hands and felt the plastic wrap crinkle under my fingers. But
they cost $11.97 each (before tax), so I put them back on the shelf
and went home to wait. Luckily, I don't need them before Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
