<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ARTSJOURNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ECLECTIC SITE FOR ARTS NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(af) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new online arts digest is fashioning a daily journal out of
the cultural world's daily jumble.
</P>
<P>
   The site, Arts Journal, is not the first arts site, but it
illustrates the ability of one person with a good idea and a
willingness to forgo sleep to provide a useful Internet service at
little cost (www.artsjournal.com).
</P>
<P>
   Arts Journal was designed in August, went online in September
and is updated daily by Douglas J. McLennan, a former concert
pianist and arts reporter in Seattle. He got the idea as a 1996-97
fellow in the National Arts Journalism Program at Columbia. Surfing
various sites, he kept coming across interesting news in local
papers and obscure Web pages and wondering why they had not
received wider circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, McLennan scans more than 100 online publications,
selecting 80 to 120 links a week for his digest. Since Arts Journal
creates links, not reprints, he pays no royalty fees, and the links
allow audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   There are sections for music, dance, theater, visual arts, arts
publishing, arts issues and the previous week's biggest articles.
His home page has a link to a similar site, Arts &AMP; Letters Daily
(www.cybereditions.com/aldaily), which he said took a more academic
approach.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan, 41, said his site's greatest attraction was its
ability to cluster articles. ``The granddaddy of all of them is the
Giuliani-Brooklyn Museum thing,'' he said. The site's coverage of
the clash over the ``Sensation'' exhibition, which includes about
80 stories from all over the English-speaking world, is subdivided
into news, reviews, analyses and related controversies.
</P>
<P>
   Not all topical subjects work out, McLennan said, citing a page
in which he tried to focus on what he thought was the heating-up
New York auction market. ``Man, nobody was interested,'' he said.
Visual arts and music generate the most articles, he said; dance
and poetry are the hardest to find.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet workday begins at 5 a.m. for McLennan, who takes
three to four hours to update his Web site and two or three to do
technical maintenance. He also tries to deal with 50 to 100 e-mail
messages a day, many from readers asking for help. ``And then
there's a couple of hours trying to promote the site,'' mainly by
persuading other sites to link to his, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that makes the site possible is its low cost: $35 a
month for the site's host and $59 a month for a DSL line. He said
that he received about 1,000 daily visits and that he had received
offers to remain nonprofit and be subsidized by a foundation or to
become part of a larger commercial site.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan is confident that one-person sites like his are here to
stay. ``Yeah, there are these megasites,'' he said, ``but what the
megasites seem to be doing is becoming the homes of the swarms of
baby-bee sites.'' As for the artists and writers who self-publish
online, and who are linked to Arts Journal, ``their material is no
less valuable because they happen to have control of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, McLennan's site has one regular advertiser, the
National Arts Journalism Program, his old sponsor, which
coincidentally made the top-news index last month when it issued a
report criticizing the state of local arts journalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
