<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Dec. 16, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israel and Syria launched their
highest-level peace negotiations Wednesday, urged by President
Clinton at a showcase White House ceremony to make the ``hard
choices'' needed to end a half-century of hostility. (Summary from
wires) By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The United Nations agreed
Wednesday on a power-sharing deal with three Kosovo Albanian
leaders, bringing them into the official administration to help
legislate and govern the unruly province alongside U.N. officials.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-VOTE (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Venezuelans voted
Wednesday on whether to approve a new constitution that would
eliminate the senate, change the country's name and vastly increase
the power of President Hugo Chavez,`allowing him to stay in offkce
for up to 13 years. (Summary from wires) By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MURTHY (Bangalore, India) _ The extraordinary rise of N.R.
Narayana Murthy, his company and the software services industry in
India has come to represent the hope that what he calls
``compassionate capitalism'' can provide decent, desperately needed
jobs and the national wealth to improve health and literacy levels
in a country whose population has more than tripled since it won
independence in 1947. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
