<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-STAIRMASTER-BR     12-15 0227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STAIRMASTER-BRADLEY-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BRADLEY COMMENT A BOOST TO STAIRMASTER
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The road to the White House is an uphill climb for
most candidates. But thanks to a StairMaster, Bill Bradley might
have an edge.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Saturday, the former professional
basketball player praised the exercise device as his preferred way
to stay fit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bradley's comments have tripled sales inquiries to
the Seattle-based company that makes StairMaster, according to
company president Tom Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very surprised,'' Bryant said. ``We're going to send
him a note and a StairMaster shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions following the disclosure last week that
he suffered from an irregular heart beat, Bradley said he often
goes out of his way to find hotels equipped with a StairMaster.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the product endorsement, Bryant declined to say if he
will support the former New Jersey senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say how I will personally vote,'' he said.
``But having a president in the White House who would be using our
product is a very encouraging incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time for Bryant. He once served as a
president of Dunlop Maxfli Sports, the manufacturer of the golf
balls favored by former President George Bush and Vice President
Dan Quayle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
