<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PAYDAY-LOANS16-COX     12-15 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYDAY-LOANS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USERS DESCRIBE COSTS OF 'PAYDAY' LOANS
 &HT;    450&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Navy sailor told a congressional forum Wednesday
how he became one of the growing number of Americans who take out
small loans from ``payday'' lenders and then fall into a sinkhole
of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer 2nd Class Stewart A. Wilson said he had been
``desperate'' four years ago when he discovered ads for quick cash
from storefront lenders around the Naval Air Station in
Jacksonville, Fla. He took out a short-term loan for about $250 and
hardly noticed the large fees.
</P>
<P>
   When he couldn't repay the principal, he took out more
short-term loans and paid more fees. By this fall, when he found
help through a credit union, he said he had paid $5,640 in fees
over the past year on what had grown into an $800 loan.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's case focused attention on fast-growing ``payday''
lenders, who are said to lend $8.5 billion a year from about 9,000
outlets across the country. However, their fees are so high _
estimated at 400 percent if annualized _ that the practice is
banned in 21 states, according to the Consumer Federation of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who led the forum, said the
discussion ``may be particularly timely because payday lenders
enjoy a marked increase in their business during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are scanning the ads in the newspaper or out doing
your shopping _and wishing you had a little more money in your
pocket _ you may well see promotions describing the payday product
as quick and easy cash,'' he said. In fact, he said, it is is ``one
of the most expensive'' loans in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Even representatives of ``payday'' lending conceded Wednesday
that their industry needs to clean up its act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be the first to acknowledge that our industry has
problems,'' said Billy Webster, president-elect of the Community
Financial Services Association, the industry's trade group. Webster
is also president of Advance America, which claims to be the
largest ``payday'' lending company.
</P>
<P>
   Webster said the lenders should clearly disclose the real cost
of such quick loans, give customers a 24-hour escape clause, and
stop using threats of criminal prosecution against borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Webster told Lieberman that he opposed any new federal
regulation for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's revenue has grown from nearly nothing at the
beginning of the decade to a projected $2 billion next year. The
growth will continue next year as payday lending goes onto the
Internet, said Robert E. Rochford, a lawyer for another the lending
association, Financial Service Centers of America.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Although high-interest loans are banned in Texas, the industry
is finding ways around those limits, the forum was told.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie L. Pettijohn, commissioner of consumer credit in Texas,
told the forum that at least three out-of-state banks have found
agents in the Texas to provide high-interest payday loans despite
an anti-usury provision in the state's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   She said 1,300 pawnshops are now applying to become agents to
make these high-fee loans for out-of-state banks. Pettijohn said
that lenders have other inventive ways to get around the ban, such
as calling the loans purchases of the customers' home appliances,
which are then ``leased back'' to the owner for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and other states, including Georgia, have fought the
lenders in court through costly legislation, but the results have
been inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In a number of states, including Ohio, payday lending is not
prohibited. However, Rochford said the industry is expecting
Florida to ban the practice next year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most outspoken critics is Edward J. Gallagly,
president of the Florida Central Credit Union, a Tampa-based
non-profit lending company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it financial servitude,'' Gallagly said of payday
lending. He said the short-term loans are structured so that
borrowers are almost bound to mount up debt.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one study of such loans in Indiana found that 77
percent of them were ``rollovers'' from past unpaid balances.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagly said his credit union offers more realistic terms of 12
percent over 12 months for small loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The root problem is 37 percent of the public have savings of
$1,000 or less'' and have nothing in reserve for emergencies, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he had not determined whether he would back
congressional action on payday lending. At least two measures are
pending in Congress to curb the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
