<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WORKER-MONITORING     12-15 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WORKER-MONITORING-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEB: NEW TICKET TO A PINK SLIP
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Va., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(With WORKER-PRIVACY) 
(nk) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day early in October, 40 employees of the Xerox Corp.,
working in locations across the United States, received unwelcome
news: They had been caught in the act of surfing to forbidden Web
sites, nabbed not by managers or fellow employees but by software
designed to monitor their online indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   The software recorded every Web site they had visited (many of
which, it turned out, were related to shopping or pornography) and
every minute they had spent at those sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was up to eight hours a day in inappropriate visits to
Web sites,'' said Bill McKee, a spokesman for Xerox. ``Obviously
they were not doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40 workers were fired immediately, but they were not the
only ones being subjected to the watchful eye of the monitoring
software. In fact, the Web use of every one of Xerox's 92,000
employees _ in countries around the world _ is routinely monitored
by the company. The surveillance is no secret, McKee said. Xerox
workers have come to expect that they are being watched.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at companies elsewhere should begin to expect the
same: In 1999, at least 45 percent of employers said they monitored
their employees' phone calls, computer files or e-mail messages,
according to the American Management Association. That number,
based on a survey of more than 1,000 human-resources managers at
corporations of varying sizes, is up from 35 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring is necessary, employers argue, because of the
changing nature of the workplace. Supervisors must keep tabs on
which workers are wasting company time by surfing to entertainment
Web sites, which ones are sending e-mail messages that create a
hostile environment for women or members of minority groups, and
which ones are distributing company secrets or jamming their
networks with bulk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing that desire for control with an employee's rights to
privacy has never been easy. Even before the arrival of the
Internet, courts have heard cases of employers who search through
desks or listen to voice-mail messages. A spattering of laws,
including state and federal wiretap laws, have tried to offer some
guideposts. Under the federal wiretap law, for example, an employer
cannot listen to an employee's personal telephone conversations
unless the employees have been notified that their conversations
are monitored and unless the monitoring is required for business
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Now questions of privacy have moved to the electronic realm _
where laws related to workplace surveillance are nearly
nonexistent. And so far, less than a dozen lawsuits that raise
questions about an employer's right to read e-mail messages or
track Web site use have made their way to courts. In several of
these, judges have ruled that employers can do what they want with
computers they own. Some judges have said that as long as employees
are warned that they may be watched, they should not expect any
privacy in their online interactions.
</P>
<P>
   But some privacy advocates, labor organizations and lawyers
consider those arguments still largely untested. A person's home
life and work life are increasingly intermingled, they argue. At
what point is it reasonable to expect at least some privacy when
using a company's computers or network?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't define privacy as whatever the employer wants it to
be,'' said Craig Cornish, a lawyer who specializes in issues
related to workplace privacy. ``Then it's no right at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the issues revolve around technology that enables
employers to watch and record what flies over their networks.
Recent developments in software may add further complications:
Companies can now record and view everything a person does on a
computer, from typing in a word-processing document to opening an
image file.
</P>
<P>
   One new product, called Spector, surreptitiously takes digital
snapshots of whatever appears on the screen, as often as every few
seconds. ``Your employees will hate Spector,'' the Web site for the
software declares, ``because Spector records everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Spector was just released this month, John Yatsko, a
security consultant for J &AMP; J Consulting in Erie, Pa., has already
installed it at a plastics manufacturing company that he would not
name. ``If you need evidence you want to take to the police,
Spector is great for that,'' Yatsko said.
</P>
<P>
   Most employers are less heavy-handed. They say they won't
routinely read e-mail messages. And they will typically look at Web
traffic among a pool of computers without focusing on individual
use. But if something looks suspicious, they say, they have a right
to dig into an employee's electronic records.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take appropriate steps to make sure the resources
are put to appropriate business use,'' said Alan Hodel, a spokesman
for Compaq Computer, one of 4,800 companies that use a filtering
and monitoring product called Websense.
</P>
<P>
   Employers' fear of sexual-harassment lawsuits is one of the
greatest forces driving the monitoring movement, according to
companies that sell filtering and monitoring software. If employees
are surfing to pornography sites, said John Carrington, president
of Websense Inc., ``it's like having porno magazines all through
your office.'' If blocking and monitoring software is in place,
Carrington said, ``a company can say, at least we tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies that track Web use say they also watch to make
sure that employees are getting their work done. In a recent survey
of about 1,200 employers by Vault.com, a company that publishes
reports about workplace issues, 54 percent reported that they had
caught employees browsing Web sites that were not related to work.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the perceived abuse of resources, many companies
have posted policies outlining what use of e-mail and the Web is
permitted and what is not. Xerox, for example, flashes a message on
the screen every time employees log on. It tells them not to use
the Web for anything but work.
</P>
<P>
   As in the Xerox case, the repercussions of violating those
polices can be drastic: In a survey commissioned by Websense of 200
human-resources officers in mid-size and large companies, one in
three reported that their company had fired employees for misusing
the Internet. A few cases noted in the survey, taken in November,
stemmed from shopping, stock trading, gambling, sports and computer
games. But the vast majority involved pornography. Just this month,
for example, The New York Times Co. fired 23 employees in a central
processing center in Norfolk, Va., for distributing pornographic
images via e-mail, according to Nancy Nielsen, a spokeswoman for
the company. The action was not the result of monitoring but was in
response to an employee complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were made very uncomfortable'' by the
distribution of the material, Ms. Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a handful of employees have argued in court that an
employer's electronic surveillance invaded their privacy. Not one
case, according to Cornish, who has been following the subject, has
been tried by a jury. Some experts suspect that if the employees
had faced a group of their peers, they may have found a more
sympathetic audience. In addressing judges, however, employees have
failed: Not one has ruled in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The case of Mark L. Simons, a former CIA employee, is one
example. In 1998, Simons was convicted of possessing child
pornography after a network manager detected that his workstation
had called up several pornographic Web sites. While Simons did not
dispute the facts of the charges against him, he argued in court
that the agency's search of his computer was unlawful because his
employer initially looked at his hard drive without involving the
police, who would have had to obtain a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the employer was looking through his computer for a
legitimate business reason, he wouldn't need a warrant,'' argued
Marvin Miller, Simons' lawyer. ``But this was a criminal
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, James C. Cacheris of the U.S. District
Court for the Eastern District of Virginia, was not persuaded. The
agency, Cacheris wrote in his opinion, had made clear to its
employees that they were only permitted to use the company's
Internet service lawfully. And he agreed with the employer's
argument that the agency has a right to monitor its networks to
make sure that its systems are secure. Simons has appealed the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who specialize in employee rights question whether
employers can unilaterally claim the right to monitor what happens
on their computers. Just because the computers and networks are the
employers' property, they argue, does not mean that they have a
right to read everything that crosses the computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A logical extension of that,'' said Cornish, who is
co-chairman of an American Bar Association subcommittee on
workplace privacy, ``is the argument that you're using our
bathrooms, therefore we get to put a camera over the stalls.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Everett L. Bobbitt, a lawyer in San Diego, said he recently took
on a case in which an employer took the ownership argument too far.
He represented a police officer who said he had been fired after
his employer searched his computer and found a file showing he had
visited www.whitehouse.com, _ a pornographic Web site. The police
department argued that it had a right to go through the officer's
computer files partly because it owned the computer.
</P>
<P>
   But the police officer, whom Bobbitt would not name, insisted
that he had meant to type www.whitehouse.gov _ the official White
House site. He sued for wrongful termination and eventually settled
the suit for $100,000. The employer had no right to go through the
officer's files simply because they were on the company's computer,
Bobbitt argued. ``It was just a fishing expedition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy advocates wonder about the larger impact of
electronic surveillance on how people live their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more of us are working in a mixed work-and-home
environment,'' said Beth Givens, project director of the Privacy
Rights Clearinghouse, an advocacy group in San Diego. People are
using their computers for making medical appointments, sending
messages to loved ones or filling out forms for car insurance.
``Any monitoring needs to take that into account,'' Ms. Givens
said. ``There are many individuals who would feel they have a
reasonable expectation of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even everyday information-gathering _ like visiting political
Web sites or checking the news _ may be thwarted if workers are
worried about being watched, Cornish said. ``Surveillance has a
chilling effect,'' he said. ``To what extent is this going to choke
off an informed citizenry?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, many lawyers argue, employers should warn
their employees that their e-mail may be read and their Web use may
be monitored. Last summer, the American Management Association
issued a memo to its 10,000 member companies, urging them to make
their employees aware that their electronic actions and
communications ``are subject to recording and review.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks such policies should be required. In
California, Gov. Gray Davis recently vetoed a a bill that would
have prohibited companies from secretly monitoring their employees'
e-mail or personal computer records. He argued that the law would
unduly burden companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At least employees have time on their side. Employers who choose
to scan through employee files, e-mail and Web logs are in for
hours of extra work. A joke circulating on the Net, written by a
28-year-old named Joe Lavin, puts it this way:
</P>
<P>
   A manager installs monitoring software on his employees'
computers. Right away he starts reprimanding them for playing video
games, downloading Pamela Anderson photographs and sending
offensive e-mail messages. But in the end, it is the manager who is
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the past a very effective manager,'' the joke goes.
But lately ``he has been merely sitting in his office all day,
spying on other employees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
