u f BC-STATES-BIZ-AIDA-NAT     12-15 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BIZ-AIDA-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &UR; SBA Chief Backs Rule on Minority Ownership &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Jonathan Lipman &QL;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 15 - SBA Administrator Aida Alvarez backed the
federal government's long-standing definition of minority-owned
businesses this week, essentially opposing a proposed rule that the
National Minority Supplier Development Council will vote on next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The NMSDC is a business-membership group that promotes
business-to-business relationships between minority businesses and
the corporate community at large. At its next meeting, the council
will vote on allowing companies with as little as 30 percent
minority ownership to claim minority-owned status. Since 1978, the
government has used a 51 percent ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using a different and lower ratio, the MNSDC proposal
creates confusion,'' Alvarez said in a prepared statement. ``The
fact is that this proposal does not satisfy the legal standard for
federal contracting programs. It would be illegal to apply this
proposed definition to any federal contract. The minority small
business community is not well served by a resolution that flies in
the face of existing laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NMSDC contends that its regulation does not need to
agree with the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a non-profit organization and this has nothing to do
whatsoever with government,'' said NMSDC spokeswoman Donna Long.
The organization continues to support the change, she said, but
delayed its initial October vote in order to better explain the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would allow a minority-owned business to sell up to
70 percent of its non-voting stock to non-minority shareholders
without losing its status. Minorities must still hold 51 percent of
voting stock and day-to-day operations must be minority managed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
