A9925 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION1     12-15 1864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King Street corridor offers service with style
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ In this city where shoppers are treated like
royalty, you'd do well to head for King Street this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 200 shops, many in centuries-old renovated
buildings, this charming corridor has something for every type of
shopper. Need a special gift? Wander into fred _ named for shop
partner Judith Reinhard's husband _ and pick up gourmet cookware in
either black or white, the featured colors. Perhaps you want a
souvenir of your visit to this Lowcountry city. Stop by Charles
Kerrison Jewelers, where the fifth generation of the family is
running the store, and buy a Charleston plate made exclusively for
Kerrison's by Wedgwood. Or run into Bob Ellis Shoes _ which also
has a branch at Phipps Plaza in Atlanta _ for a pair of sexy Prada
sandals to wear on the last night of '99.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these hometown favorites, including tons of
antiques stores, the street is also home to such familiar national
chains as Saks Fifth Avenue, the Gap and Ann Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   King Street is downtown, stretching from the Cooper River
bridges to the Battery. It was one of the original streets of
Charleston, which was founded in 1670. Although christened
Albermarle Point, the city was later named Charles Town after King
Charles II of England and renamed Charleston in 1783.
</P>
<P>
   ``King was the choice of merchants,'' said Linda Helmly,
director of the Charleston Peninsula Business Association. ``Since
it was the highest street on the peninsula, they could keep their
merchandise dry if floods came. On the other hand, Market Street
during the 19th century, which was used as the city's fish, meat
and vegetable market, was in a creek bed and was constantly getting
flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many downtown streets, King became rundown and derelict in
the '60s and '70s but came back to life with the opening of
Charleston Place in 1986. Located on the block bordered by Market,
King, Meeting and Hasell streets, the hotel, supported by longtime
mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr., attracted shops and galleries for blocks
around. Thus it helped turn King Street back into a shopping
destination for locals and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other Charleston streets boast specialty shops and
boutiques including East Bay, Church and Broad. Then there's the
area that comprises Center Market, the Rainbow Market and the Open
Air Market on Market Street. Local artists, including those weaving
Lowcountry sweetgrass baskets, rent stalls and ply their wares.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have limited time, stick to King. You can always go
back and visit the others on another shopping foray.
</P>
<P>
   One shop on this narrow street that reflects Charleston's
worldwide shopping appeal is Norma May International. Three and a
half years ago, May moved her New York business to King Street.
``Everything in the store is made or painted by hand,'' says the
owner who describes her clothing and accessories as ``fashion
art.'' Especially during Charleston's springtime Spoleto Festival,
the shop welcomes international visitors who buy jackets made from
old kimonos, pashmina shawls and handpainted silk bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come in with an old, drab outfit and always leave with
something spectacular,'' said Judy Boehm, a Charlestonian of 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in a bench for your patio or garden, visit
the Charleston Battery Bench store. The iron bench was first made
by the J.F Riley Iron Works in Charleston during the mid-19th
century. George Birlant, purchased the original bench mold pattern
from Riley more than 40 years ago when it ceased doing business.
The design of the casting includes flora and fauna native to South
Carolina. Today, the Birlant family turns out authentic
reproductions ($229.50), which dot Charleston's historic Battery.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the finest antiques shops are on King Street, starting
at Princess Street. On a recent Tuesday, Atlanta real estate agent
Suzanne Corbett was busy ``working'' King Street, looking for
porcelain. ``I like 18th-century antiques and Charleston is the
place to find them,'' she said. Corbett visits the city every three
to four months and loves it so much she's looking for property to
buy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best reason to shop King Street is the level of
service given by the stores. ``I like to shop at Berlin's clothing
store, which has been there forever,'' said frequent visitor Dulcy
Rosenberg of Atlanta. ``The same woman always waits on me. It's so
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From downtown Atlanta, take I-20 east to
Augusta; continue on to Columbia where you pick up I-26 east and
continue into Charleston. It's about a five-hour drive from
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Mondays-Satur-
</P>
<P>
   days and noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: It's at a premium in the historic district. Leave
your car at one of the parking areas near the Charleston Visitor
Center (375 Meeting St.) and use DASH, the downtown area shuttle.
The fare is 75 cents; a one-day pass is $2.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Located in the Charleston Visitor Center; there are
also facilities in parking garages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Charleston Area Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
1-800-868-8118. Or access the Web site, www.charlestoncvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  So many options, so little time. For a cool lunch or dinner,
stop by Slightly North of Broad (S.N.O.B.). Try the maverick grits
_ local yellow grits with shrimp, scallops, smoked sausage and
country ham ($9.75). Or opt for the lunch express ($7.95), which on
a recent visit included grilled hangar steak, mashed potatoes with
bacon and onions and carrots with broccoli. Lunch: 11:30 a.m.-3
p.m. Mondays-Fridays. Dinner: 5:30-10 p.m. Sundays-Thursdays;
5:30-11p.m. Fridays-Saturdays. 192 E. Bay St. 843-723-3424.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other options: Sticky Fingers, 235 Meeting St. (843-853-7427)
is known for its ribs, chicken and barbecue. Try
</P>
<P>
   Anson, 12 Anson St. (843-577-0551), for dinner. Located in the
old city market area, it specializes in seafood caught in
Charleston waters. Dine outside in the courtyard at Blossom Cafe,
171 E. Bay St. (843-722-9200). Items include pizzas and pastas as
well as plenty of veggie dishes. For an elegant dinner of regional
favorites, go to Peninsula Grill, 112 N. Market St (843-723-0700)
in the Planters Inn Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a sense of history, stay in a bed-and-breakfast, many of
which are in renovated mansions and houses. For a list, call the
reservation service Historic Charleston Bed-and-Breakfast
(1-800-743-3583) that represents 60 properties in and around
Charleston. Rates vary depending on season. Other options: Harbour
View Inn, 2 Vendue Range (843-853-8439) is at Waterfront Park with
beautiful views and rooms starting at $99. In the heart of the
historic district, across from the city market, are the Doubletree
Guest Suites, 181 Church St. (843-577-2644). Rooms range from $119
to $159. And the Best Western King Charles Inn, 237 Meeting St.
(843-723-7451) is also in the historic district. Depending on day
of arrival, rooms start at $79.
</P>
<P>
   While browsing through King Street shops we found . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cat-shaped bronze bird feeders ($129 small; $179 large). Home
Store Carolina, 319 King St. 843-853-2319.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hand-painted silk evening bag with tassels by Mary Jane
Artwear ($395). Norma May International, 315 King St. 843-577-8884.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Floral print silk dress with fringe by Maxou ($196). Copper
Penny, 311 King St. 843-723-2999.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exclusive Charleston Plate featuring Dock Street Theatre by
Wedgwood ($40). Charles Kerrison Jewelers, 285 King St.
843-577-6104.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guzzini's coffee decanter ($49). fred, 237 King St.
843-723-5699.
</P>
