<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TLC-TBOZ16-COX     12-15 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-TBOZ16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta singer expresses herself in poems and essays
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Atlanta pop trio TLC released its ``CrazySexyCool''
album in 1994, there's been no doubt who embodies that last
adjective: It's T-Boz, Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins, who always seems
to be in control of the situations she sings about.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to controlling her emotions, forget cool. Hers
is often a cold stare frosting all onlookers from album covers and
videos.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it's Watkins who has followed pop singer Jewel's lead
and written a collection of poems and essays called ``Thoughts,''
which she'll share with autograph-seekers tonight at a Chapter 11
bookstore in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the native of Des Moines, Iowa, discusses her
father leaving home when she was 3; her delinquent high school
days; and what it was like when TLC was the best-selling female
group in the country and her lights were cut off at home.
</P>
<P>
   A rather personable Watkins, 29, talked recently about becoming
an author, how she's dealing with sickle cell anemia on TLC's first
headlining tour (it visits Philips Arena on Jan. 29) and the public
feud fellow TLC member Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes is having with her
and Rozonda ``Chilli'' Thomas in the press:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What made you write a book?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sitting around all that time in between albums. While we were
working out all of the business things like the bankruptcy, I was
still the creative person that I am. So I needed a way to get this
out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was there anyone you read who led you in this direction?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't like to read. I mean, I like stuff like (motivational
author) Iyanla Vanzant and ``Don't Sweat the Small Stuff.'' Stuff
you can skim. And I designed my book for people like me.
</P>
<P>
   I want this to be something for the kids. Maybe it will stop
them from going through some of the unnecessary pain I took myself
through. And it's a way for people to see a side of me they don't
hear in the music. How I grew up, how I've dealt with sickle cell,
the things the fans write me about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are you dealing with your illness on the road? Wasn't it
your sickle cell anemia that prevented you from touring extensively
before?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, and I'm doing much better this time. My performance has
changed a lot. I'm just walking and singing, instead of popping and
snapping and dancing all over the place like I used to.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has your diet changed in any way? In ``Thoughts,'' you
mention your love for oxtails and give readers a taco casserole
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   A: What's really funny is I take prenatal pills. I take in
everything an unborn baby could. I take folic acid. And I drink
about three bottles of Gatorade before each show. That's why I'm
wearing the kind of outfits I'm wearing. It's like forget trying to
be sexy, I might be bloated. I have to wear what's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's going on with you and Left-Eye? In the press she's
been saying things backstage are pretty bad between you.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not mad at her. I'm not mad about anything. In any family
_ and we're like sisters _ you agree to disagree sometimes. And
from what I've read, she's admitted to not showing up for things
and walking off sets. Now when a reporter is sitting there watching
her do it what could I say? ``Oh, maybe her toe hurts?'' I was
forced into telling the truth. Don't get me wrong though, I wish
baby girl the best for whatever she wants to do. But there's a way
to do everything. It's unfortunate that we have to have this
ongoing soap opera as we do it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think there'll be a TLC when this tour and record are
over?
</P>
<P>
   A: We'll see. I'd rather we stop because people don't want to
hear us anymore. Not because we can't get along.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Worst-case scenario: You guys break up. Then what for you? A
solo career?
</P>
<P>
   A: Everybody else says I should, but I don't want to. I'm
working on a cartoon with the Jim Henson Co. (``It's a Fly
World''). Me and (TLC producer) Dallas Austin are working with
(rapper/actor Will Smith's company) Overbrook to develop this movie
called ``Jellybeans'' ... basically about how we all met at a
skating rink called Jellybeans in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you thinking about leaving Atlanta for Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh no. Unless, I get married.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Married?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I may be getting engaged (to rapper Mack 10). I don't
like L.A. But he's from L.A. And if he asks, I'll go.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK SIGNING
</P>
<P>
   Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins
</P>
<P>
   Signs ``Thoughts.'' 6 tonight.Chapter 11 Discount Bookstore,
Ansley Mall, 1544 Piedmont Ave. N.E. 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
