<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-SPACE-SANTA-NA     12-15 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SPACE-SANTA-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Space Shuttle Mission Will Not Jeopardize Santa's Flight: Cape
Canaveral Ready for Kris Kringle
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Lipman
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 15 - NASA officials sought to allay fears
Wednesday by confirming that, even though the space shuttle will be
in orbit Christmas Eve, NASA will once again keep landing
facilities open in the event Santa Claus is forced to make an
emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has traditionally offered its landing strip at Cape
Canaveral to Claus in case of a mechanical failure or elf
emergency, and spokesman Bruce Buckingham said this year will be no
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landing area will still be open, both in the event of an
emergency landing from Santa or an emergency landing of the
Shuttle,'' Buckingham said. ``It's not a problem because they come
in from different trajectories. Santa's coming in from a polar
orbit and we're in an equatorial orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   Claus, who also received interstate flight clearance from the
Department of Transportation Wednesday, will be flying a
custom-built sleigh, powered by ``eight tiny reindeer, with the
addition of a possible ninth reindeer with a special air navigation
warning light in its nose, in the event of heavy fog or snow,'' the
DOT said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Since Claus added Global Positioning System hardware to his
sleigh back in the late 1970s, Buckingham said, NASA has been able
to track Claus on his Christmas Eve mission ``from the north pole
all the way down to wherever he chooses to touch down first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraging that he come first,'' Buckingham added. ``I
think he wants to start south and then work his way back north.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite unconfirmed reports that STS-103 Mission
Commander Curtis Brown has indeed been a good boy, he and the six
other astronauts will have to wait until Discovery lands on Dec. 26
to receive their Christmas presents. There are no plans for a
mid-orbit docking of Discovery and Claus' sleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep the reindeers apart,'' Buckingham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
