<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-FASHION-MILLENNIUM-TU     12-15 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MILLENNIUM-TUXEDOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUEXEDOS MAKE A Y2K STATEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: with sidebar FASHION-MILLENNIUM-CHEAP) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the biggest party of the century.
</P>
<P>
   So what are you wearing on New Year's Eve?
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, fashion friends, it's glittery, glamorous and
drop-dead stunning, or you'll look so last year at this year's
round of parties. Trust us, a party hat and feather boa are no way
to ring in Y2K. But you're on the right track, because party
invitations are likely to stress black-tie dress codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much excitement about the new millennium, that
people who haven't ever dressed up are going to this New Year's
Eve,'' says Leon Hall, spokesman for the Fashion Association and
co-host of E!'s ``Fashion Emergency.'' According to Hall, ``Excess
is good, and corsages are in again ... as long as they're pinned on
a purse instead of a gown. And so are really big tiaras.''
</P>
<P>
   Supermodel Emme, who's his co-host and also the spokeswoman for
Revlon's ColorStay cosmetics, is equally adamant about partying
with panache. ``You want to shine, whether it's glimmer on your
brow or a totally gaudy outfit, with a silver-sequined gown that
says 2000 on the chest. With matching shoes and purse,'' she says
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K fashion jokes aside, this is a fashion maven's chance to
wear more than a little black dress or traditional tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   Hall says the ivory shawl-collared dinner jacket associated with
the film ``Casablanca'' is very hip again.
</P>
<P>
   June Rau, fashion director for Nordstrom stores, says, ``We're
selling more tuxedos than in past years. And that includes velvet
and paisley smoking jackets and long silver ties instead of basic
black bow ties.'' She adds that many customers are freshening up
their tuxedos with silver vests instead of cummerbunds.
</P>
<P>
   At Gary's Tuxedo shop at Fashion Square mall in Sherman Oaks,
salesman Nir Solomon reports business is better than ever, and he's
been surprised by how many customers are requesting top hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuxedos, especially two-button styles, are selling
well,''according to Robinsons-May fashion director Milinda Martin.
``But dressy black suits are what's newest for us. They're a hit
with younger men, who are wearing them in a single-breasted,
four-button design with dress shirts but not necessarily a tie.''
</P>
<P>
   JC Penney stores aren't known for formalwear, but this year
they've got tuxedos. According to spokesman Tim Lyons, ``In
anticipation of the New Year's Eve party fever, we have opened
tuxedo shops in numerous stores, offering three styles.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't buy a tuxedo at Mervyn's, but menswear spokesman Mark
Nawrocki reports customers are snapping up their satin microfiber
shirts (think John Travolta in the '70s) to wear with tuxedo pants.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the men's fashion report.
</P>
<P>
   Women are dressing up and splurging on all the accessories
they've passed on in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footwear is a big deal,'' says Nordstrom's Rau. ``Women are
buying all types of decorative shoes that could qualify as foot
jewelry. Our best sellers are open-toed sandals with sparkles, and,
of course, high heels. The colors _ titanium, gunmetal gray and
lots of red.''
</P>
<P>
   Mervyn's womenswear expert Nicolle Dougherty agrees that it's an
accessory year, reporting that small beaded bags and wraps in
velvet with beaded trims are Mervyn's biggest sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Gowns, wraps, bags and shoes are all a-glitter with glass beads
or pricey Swarovski crystals, but real diamonds _ what Emme calls
``Big Mama diamonds''_ are the ultimate accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Once they've got the ensemble together, women are wrapping it
all up with stoles fringed in bohemian splendor. Huge rectangles
and triangles drip with fringe and beaded fringe, says Robinson's
Martin. According to her, they're a fashion-forward alternative to
pashmina stoles and much fresher than a feather boa.
</P>
<P>
   About the beads. Kevan Hall, who has dressed Sarah Michelle
Gellar and numerous other stars for the Oscars, says crystal beads
are so much more elegant than sequins, especially under the lights.
But he thinks metallic fabrics (especially silver) and anything
iridescent are worthy of New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about the ball gown for clock-watching Cinderellas.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers report it's the No. 1 choice, the billowy excess that
Hall was talking about. Really full ball gown skirts (or simply
referred to as ball skirts), topped with midriff-baring tops, tight
sweaters or spaghetti-strapped bodices can be interchanged for
maximum versatility. It's a sportswear inspiration, says
Robinson-May's fashion director, that's finally caught on in the
social-occasion department.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not an iridescent taffeta ball gown, the silhouette is
slinky and provocative like the gowns Marilyn Monroe was sewn into.
</P>
<P>
   It's the look favored by a lot of Hollywood types who have the
figure, like curvy Terri J. Vaughn of WB's ``The Steve Harvey
Show.'' For her intimate New Year's Eve dinner party at her Burbank
home, she'll be playing hostess in a silvery Versace gown with a
low back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sexy,'' says her rapper husband Derrick Carolina,
who will be wearing a tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   Although she's had a lot of practice wearing gowns in beauty
pageants and at show-biz galas, Vaughn says the secret to carrying
off a glamorous gown is feeling glamorous inside. ``You've got to
feel confident, and not be worried about it being too tight or the
straps falling off,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one more thing. Think about coordinating your ensembles.
Remember the prom, when you both wore the same color?
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest trend, say the experts. But pass on the
carnation boutonniere, unless the party's in ``Pleasantville.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
