r e BC-CENTURY-IN-ARTS2-TEX     12-15 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-IN-ARTS2-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP 10 ARTS EVENTS OF THE CENTURY: THEATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Till year's end, the Star-Telegram brings you a
subjective look at the top 10 moments of the century in the arts.
Today: Theater
</P>
<P>
   1901: George M. Cohan, a 23-year-old singer and hoofer appearing
with his parents and sister as the Four Cohans, expanded a
vaudeville skit into a full musical comedy. Audiences liked it, so
Cohan wrote more _ and became American musical comedy's first
superstar. Among his hits still performed are ``Give My Regards to
Broadway'' and ``You're a Grand Old Flag.''
</P>
<P>
   1912: Ten-year-old Robert Meredith Reiniger watches as an
itinerant salesman of band instruments beguiles a crowd in his
hometown of Mason City, Iowa. The youngster grows up, goes into
radio and changes his name to Meredith Willson. At age 55, he turns
his childhood memory into ``The Music Man,'' which ranks high among
classic American musicals.
</P>
<P>
   1916: Eugene O'Neill, the underachieving son of a famous actor,
joins the Provincetown Players and begins writing plays. He will
become America's first internationally acclaimed dramatist and,
arguably, its greatest playwright. His works include ``Anna
Christie, Mourning Becomes Electra, The Iceman Cometh'' and ``Long
Day's Journey Into Night.''
</P>
<P>
   1919: Actress Helen Westley and other members of the defunct
Washington Square Players in New York City form the Theatre Guild,
perhaps the most intellectually and artistically committed
production organization in the history of American theater. The
Guild is credited with developing the season ticket.
</P>
<P>
   1922: Actor Alfred Lunt and actress Lynn Fontanne marry,
beginning an onstage collaboration that will span 35 years and
establish them as the first couple of American theater. Lunt died
in 1977, Fontanne in 1983. They are largely unknown today.
</P>
<P>
   1927: ``The Jazz Singer'' ushers in the age of talking motion
pictures. New York stage actors flock to Hollywood, eager to
replace silent-movie stars thought to have inadequate voices. The
silent screen had already influenced the stage, as scenic and
lighting designers emulated the techniques of the camera. (A 1914
play, ``On Trial,'' was the first stage work to employ the
flashback, a popular movie device.)
</P>
<P>
   1935: The Federal Theatre Project is established as part of
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal agency the Works
Progress Administration. The Federal Theatre Project provided jobs
for writers, performers and designers during the Depression. Orson
Welles, John Houseman and Elmer Rice were among the East Coast
participants. Margo Jones was assistant director of the Houston
branch. Congress abolished the Federal Theatre Project in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Composer Richard Rodgers and lyricist Oscar Hammerstein II
team up following the death of Rodgers' longtime partner, Lorenz
Hart. The first Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein show is ``Oklahoma!'' It
transforms American musical theater with its merging of song, story
and dance and begins a string of R&AMP;H hits _ among them ``Carousel,
South Pacific'' and ``The King and I.''
</P>
<P>
   1947: Margo Jones opens Theatre '47 in Dallas. She becomes a
champion of new playwrights such as Tennessee Williams, Jerome
Lawrence, Robert E. Lee and William Inge. To demonstrate her
commitment to fresh works, Jones ``renamed'' her playhouse
annually. It was host to premiere stagings of ``Summer and Smoke''
and ``Inherit the Wind,'' among others. Jones died in 1955. Her
theater survived for four more years.
</P>
<P>
   1950: Sen. Joseph McCarthy begins his infamous investigation of
communist influences in government and show business. His
persecution of actors, writers and directors wrecked many stage and
film careers.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
