<HEADER>
A9937 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOOK-BIGTOBACCO-TEX     12-15 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BIGTOBACCO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S STILL A SMOLDERING FIGHT OVER TOBACCO'S DAMAGE TO HUMANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Assuming the Risk: The Mavericks, the Lawyers and the
Whistleblowers Who Beat Big Tobacco''
</P>
<P>
   by Michael Orey
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to provide an upbeat summation of ``Assuming the
Risk,'' Michael Orey's surprisingly lively litigation expose
delivered with surprising clarity and even some humor.
</P>
<P>
   It would have gone something like this: Torched by scruffy
whistle-blowers and lawyers with street-fighter instincts to would
put even novelist John Grisham's heroes to shame, Big Tobacco
finally goes up in smoke. I had my reasons, not the least of which
was Aunt Dale, who smoked heavily and died of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Orey's fine effort does establish the whistle-blowers' courage
as they bucked the multibillion-dollar industry, and some lawyers'
scrappiness and idealism and greed and generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, a happy ending, at least to date, remains a hope rather
than an accomplishment. Legal realities are rarely so clean and
simple.
</P>
<P>
   You heard, perhaps, that the $368.5 billion settlement on
smoking-related Medicaid costs went up in legal smoke. It had been
a deal reached in 1997 between the tobacco industry and a team of
lawyers and attorneys general from 40 states. You probably know
that this litigation had initially flared up in Mississippi, and
that Texas' $3.3 billion settlement has been mired in a dispute
over the private lawyers' share.
</P>
<P>
   But did you know the legal roots of the claims for Medicaid
damages tied to smoking?
</P>
<P>
   Orey tells of the toe chomped on in a plug of chewing tobacco
that led to a legal-groundbreaking Mississippi Supreme Court
decision in a product-liability suit _ and delves into asbestos and
other product-liability history.
</P>
<P>
   In the toe case, the judges found in 1918: ``We can imagine no
reason why, with ordinary care, human toes could not be left out of
chewing tobacco, and if toes are found in chewing tobacco, it seems
to us that somebody has been very careless.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you recall the names of the lawyers and whistle-blowers at
the heart of this ongoing courtroom drama and out-of-court
bargaining?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Dick Scruggs and Don Barrett, the Southern lawyers
representing both whistle-blowers and cancer victims. Barrett and
Scruggs aimed to win, no matter what their personal costs.
</P>
<P>
   There was two-pack-a-day Nathan Henry Horton, whose smoking
habit would end with him choking to death on his own blood.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Merrell Williams, the frazzled paralegal researcher at
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., waddling past the cigarette
maker's security checkpoints. He was smuggling, often down in his
baggy pants, documents that incriminated all the major cigarette
makers in a cover-up of nicotine's hazards and their marketing
strategies to attract underage smokers.
</P>
<P>
   As his personal life and finances fell apart, Williams had to
find a way to reveal the documents to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Orey has given us a clear, concise and humanized account of what
could have been a dry recitation of legal issues and jargon.
</P>
<P>
   He sums it up:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cigarettes are a legal product. States have allowed and
profited from their sale. True, they could be addictive; true, the
industry had been deceptive. But using individual court cases to
resolve such a complex issue _ a legal product that causes grievous
harm to millions of people's health when used as intended _ makes
no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mississippi lawyers, Orey tells us, were the pioneers along
the legal trail leading to removal of Joe Camel from our public
scrutiny. Even now, as we see in current headlines, efforts have
resumed to reach another legal settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco remains the villain. The much-anticipated agreement
dissolved. But ``Assuming the Risk'' is much more than a tirade
against the absurdities of smoking and a morally corrupt industry.
If it remains a tale left incomplete by history, it is at least
informative and entertaining as it takes us up to the present.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
