<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WINTERNOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN-TO-EARTH ADVICE ON ENTERTAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolyne Roehm, the former fashion designer, made expensive
clothes for a limited audience of ladies who limo. Carolyne Roehm,
the author, is much more egalitarian. Her new ``Winter Notebook''
(Harper Collins, $25, hard cover) is about parties, planning,
gardening and entertaining. It is one of a series based on the
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   She has put her life's work into this compendium. She is the
girl from the Midwest who always wanted to wear a tiara. She is
Oscar de la Renta's enthusiastic assistant. She is the wife of
master-of-the-universe Henry Kravis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is no longer any of those people, yet she taps all of
them for her notebook. She shows us how to throw wonderful
Christmas parties and a New Year's Day lunch. She shows us how to
set the table and make the place cards and the centerpiece. Plus,
she shares her resources.
</P>
<P>
   Entire chapters are devoted to potato and soup recipes, and she
shares them like a good neighbor leaning over the backyard fence.
</P>
<P>
   She helps with the gift-giving chore _ shows us inventive
wrappings and then gives us a workbook page to list gifts,
recipients, mail-order resources, and who gets gratuities and how
much.
</P>
<P>
   Roehm is generous with her book; she shares the pages with her
readers, giving them room to record notes and personal
observations. Pockets are included on the end sheets so they can be
stuffed with clippings and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other authors of books of this nature, Roehm graciously
praises the people who helped her, listing them by name and
contribution. She also includes a list of resources and helpful Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
