<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FORT WORTH FAVORITES ROLL OUT MUSICAL MILESTONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas arrives early this year _ as in today.
</P>
<P>
   Why? After 26 years, Fort Worth's Space Opera has released its
second record, ``My Father's Bongos.'' Orders are being accepted
today on the band's Web site, www.spaceopera.net, and
vocalist/guitarist Scott Fraser says the CD will be available for
over-the-counter purchase at Record Town before the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stylistically, it will sound like Space Opera in a '90s
context,'' says Fraser. Inspired by ``The Beatles Anthology''
television show and CD, he floated the idea of a reunion in 1997.
``We haven't tried to reinvent ourselves _ we evolved naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   The band (Fraser, vocalist/guitarist David Bullock, bassist
Philip White and drummer Brett Wilson) played its first gig at The
HOP in Fort Worth in 1969 and became Cowtown's hottest band during
the early '70s, opening for Jethro Tull, Jefferson Airplane and
Johnny Winter and releasing an eponymous LP on CBS in 1973. The SO
sound was, and is, an artful, highly eclectic blend of influences,
from the Beatles to Frank Zappa to classical and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning reunion show at Fort Worth's Caravan of Dreams in
December 1997 was the band's first in 17 years; keyboardist Jeff
Ward, who played that night, contributes to the CD, as does
woodwind player Jon Shipley. The bulk of ``Bongos'' was recorded in
May and August of this year at Eagle Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Caravan show, Fraser says, ``Bongos'' is one continuous
piece of music; there are 14 individual parts, and the connecting
thread is four verses of ``Awake, Awake,'' an ancient Scotch/Irish
poem.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser anticipates the band doing a concert within two months,
and says that there has been some interest in the new CD from two
labels, one in England, one in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our way of documenting ourselves and our continuing
dedication to being in a band regardless of any profit,'' he says.
``We realize we are not a capitalist enterprise. We just want to
make music as well as we can and make it available.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We know there are more than enough Christmas CDs out there, but
here's one you absolutely must get: ``Christmas in Cowtown,'' a
10-track collection featuring stalwart Cowtown bluesmen such as
Buddy Whittington, Holland K. Smith, Raleigh Smith, James Hinkle
and Johnny Guadarrama.
</P>
<P>
   The CD's daddy is Bobby Counts, the bassist who leads Count
Blue, which has held down a Thursday-night residency at the Keys
Lounge for two years.
</P>
<P>
   A friend suggested a homegrown yuletide blues collection in
August, and Counts immediately began calling old pals to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just came together,'' Counts says. ``I called
Holland, I called Dave, and every time I asked if they had a
Christmas song, they said, `Yeah, I got one for ya.' I feel like
I've been touched by heaven above.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowtown'' was recorded every Tuesday from the middle of August
to the end of September at Sounds Great Production, and the result
is a funky, down-home CD.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Millsap does Clarence Carter's ``Back Door Santa,''
Whittington burns on Albert King's ``Santa Claus Wants Some
Lovin','' and Guadarrama chips in a delightful take on ``The
Christmas Song.''
</P>
<P>
   James Hinkle does a cool recitation of ``The Night Before
Christmas,'' Kenny Traylor tackles Freddie King's ``Christmas
Tears,'' and Raleigh Smith and Millsap combine for an acoustic
version of Lightnin' Hopkins' ``Merry Christmas.'' There are also
original songs by Counts and Holland K. Smith, and Patsy Green
doing ``Merry, Merry, Christmas, Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the first conglomeration Christmas CD to ever
come out of Cowtown _ I can't think of another one,'' says Counts,
who plays bass on nine of the 10 cuts. ``It all just fell in my
lap.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD is on sale at Record Town and Borders, and at all of
Millsap's and Count Blue's shows.
</P>
<P>
   And next year should see Volume Two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna start after the first of the year,'' Counts says.
``I want everything finalized by the end of the summer. We're
thinking about making this a tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
