<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JAN. 2, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am building a raised wood deck in my backyard that will be
about 2 feet above the ground. The ground slopes quite a bit in
this yard, but I want the deck to be level. I don't have a very
long level that will go across the width of the deck, so I'm not
sure what is the best way to go about doing this. What can you
suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the simplest and most effective methods is to use a
long length of clear plastic tubing that is filled with water. Use
tubing that is 1/2 inch to 1 inch in diameter and long enough to go
from one end of the deck to the other, plus enough length to reach
up to a little above the top of the corner posts, as indicated in
the illustration. After filling this tube almost full with water,
have another person help you hold each end against opposite corner
posts (one downhill from the other). Then, mark the height of the
water that is in the tube on each post. Since water always seeks
its own level, the marks will be perfectly level with each other _
no matter how far apart they are.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The two large springs that counterbalance my overhead garage
door and run along the top of the track on each side seem to have
lost much of their tension. They no longer hold the door in place
when it is partially open. Do these springs have to be replaced to
correct this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: In most doors with horizontal springs on each side there is a
steel cable attached to the end of the spring. This cable comes up
over a pulley attached to the frame above the door and has a hook
at the end that snaps into one of a series of holes in the bracket
attached to the door frame. When the coil spring loses some of its
tension all you need do is move the hook forward one or two holes,
thus stretching the spring tighter. If moving the hook to the last
hole isn't enough, then you can still increase tension by
disconnecting the hook from the end of the cable and then cutting
the cable shorter. (CAUTION: Before disconnecting the cable, prop
the door open with a heavy post to keep it from crashing down
accidentally.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: My house has radiant heating in the ceilings and we have a
continual problem with the ceiling plaster cracking. I am thinking
about covering the plaster ceilings with one of those heavy raised
wallpapers that I've seen in some older buildings, but I wonder if
this will cut down on the amount of heating coming through. What do
you think?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not quite sure what type of wallcovering you are
referring to, but it sounds as though this material would probably
reduce heat radiation from the ceiling. To make certain, I suggest
you contact the manufacturer of this wallcovering to see if they
can supply more accurate information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The old paint used in my apartment many years ago apparently
had lead in it (I checked this with a kit available from a local
dealer). There are no children in our household and I plan to wear
protective goggles and a suitable respirator when I do some
sanding, but my wife is still concerned about health risks from
exposure to this lead when I do this sanding. Are there any
additional measures I can take when preparing these surfaces for
repainting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lead is a hazard mainly when it is ingested (that's why
children are at risk) or inhaled _ as when sanding. Wearing a
suitable respirator should be adequate protection and safety
goggles should always be worn while sanding, but don't do any more
sanding than necessary. Then prime with a lead-free paint before
applying your finish coats of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING A LIQUID LEVEL ON DECKING
POSTS'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Water-filled plastic tube will serve as a perfect level
which can then be marked on posts for a deck to be built on sloped
ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
