<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYOR-LOSER-HNS &LR;      12-15 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-LOSER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AMMIANO SEES VICTORY IN ELECTORAL LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Resending for those needing.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tom Ammiano, who rode a populist campaign to win
the right to challenge Mayor Willie Brown in Tuesday's run-off
election, will never say he lost the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is still president of the governing Board of Supervisors
and a more recognized figure _ locally and nationally _ with his
unsuccessful bid for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano may be the most liberal of the 11 supervisors, but his
demonstrated ability to spark a movement of discontented voters
could mean he will wield more influence, especially as district
elections approach next November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown helped me get the limelight because I stood up to him,''
Ammiano said Tuesday night after getting 40 percent of the vote to
Brown's 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is very cruel,'' he continued. ``In two years people
will look at the mayor as a lame duck. ... The beauty for me is I'm
not out of office ... and I'm backed by a very energetic movement
that's concerned with more open government and really scrutinizing
the districts because the districts are where the independents come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano conceded at 12:15 a.m. Wednesday during at a nightclub
in the city's Mission neighborhood, where several thousand
supporters chanted ``2003,'' the year of the next mayoral election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my birthday, and I feel like I've given birth. I've given
birth,'' he said gesturing to the crowd. ``There is not a mayor who
won't listen to us again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano turned 58 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the results, Ammiano has gained political stature and a
place in San Francisco history. He ran the city's first successful
mayoral write-in campaign, which he launched just three weeks
before the Nov. 2 general election. That effort helped him into a
second-place finish _ ahead of former Mayor Frank Jordan and Clint
Reilly, the former political consultant who spent almost $4 million
on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And the attention Ammiano attracted has positioned him for a
re-election bid for the board in November 2000. Then, he said, he
would run for mayor again or maybe the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ammiano will have elevated political stature in this city as
the leader of a new progressive political force,'' said Rich
deletion, chairman of Political Science Department at San Francisco
State University.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-off campaign, Ammiano faced the former longtime
Assembly speaker who spent more than $3 million _ six times more
than Ammiano _ and benefited tremendously from millions of dollars
more in expenditures by independent groups. Businesses and the
state Democratic Party hammered Ammiano in mailers and television
advertising, particularly over tax increases he proposed in his
first year as a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's camp, however, doesn't concede that their candidate's
late start or lack of cash hurt him. Ammiano spent about $300,000
to Brown's $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes you be more creative, more thoughtful and harder
working,'' said Ammiano campaign strategist Robert Holland.
</P>
<P>
   What really hurt Ammiano, according to political consultant and
Brown supporter Robert Barnes, was the supervisor's reliance on his
established base of support base on the east side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe Ammiano ran a citywide campaign,'' said
Barnes, a member of the Alice B. TKOs Lesbian and Gay Democratic
Club, which endorsed Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime political consultant David Looman, who did not work for
anyone in this race, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started from a very narrow base, largely white, liberal,
tenant base,'' Looman said. ``And his job obviously was to broaden
that out and broaden it very fast. Part of what got lost in the
miraculous accomplishment of his coming in second with a write-in
campaign is that he finished 28,000 votes behind the mayor. ...
People have been concentrating on how far he'd come and not how far
he had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   If Looman had worked for Ammiano, he said he would have
emphasized trying to reach Asian-Americans, who make up 34 percent
of the city's nearly 735,000 residents and 18 percent of its
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the hammer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano also could have been hurt by history: San Francisco
rarely elects a supervisor as mayor (Dianne Feinstein, who now
represents California in the Senate, was the last in 1979.) And
voters don't like to change course during boom times, Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ammiano had a more effective and compelling message to
renters, who are feeling insecure about the housing crisis,''
Barnes said. ``But renters also are part of the citywide community
... and Brown scored more points for showing he could be trusted
with the economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
