<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-RANCH-HOUSE-ART-1     12-15 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANCH-HOUSE-ART-1,035(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S LONG AND LOW AND GETTING LONELIER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By   TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The little suburban ranch house, with its pinkish
bricks and turquoise door, sits snugly on its luxuriant lawn in the
middle of a 1950s subdivision called Braes Heights. Stripped of
everything, including the wall-to-wall carpet and kitchen cabinets,
the house is an empty shell. Even the brass numbers on the door are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   This house is slated for demolition, due to be replaced by a
clone of one of the larger-than-life-size mansions that crowd it.
Four Georgian-style palazzos have risen to one side, in a seemingly
inexorable march to take over the street. The builder's sign is
already planted in the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad,'' said Joni Calkins, about the house where she and
her husband, David, raised their two young children. ``This is the
only home our kids knew.'' But the Calkins sold out: The house was
too small and the money too good.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ranch houses are an endangered species. Once the
revered symbol of postwar prosperity, these rectangular houses,
with their rec rooms and picture windows and skinny wrought-iron
balustrades, are now as dated as Melmac. In this one neighborhood,
at least 100 ranch houses have been torn down in the last five
years, replaced by today's dream: the multistoried,
Palladian-windowed, double-height-ceilinged, great-roomed
mansionette: Tara on a quarter-acre lot. When the ranch houses were
first built in Braes Heights, they cost $5,900. The house that will
replace the Calkins' is already on the market for $519,000.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, as in so many other places in the country, the
Calkins' land grew in value _ but their 1,500-square-foot ranch
house did not. As the family got bigger, the Calkins considered
adding on, but decided to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Will their next house be a ranch?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Mrs. Calkins replied. ``I admit I'm kind of
traditional. I grew up in a 1920s English cottage kind of house,
and that's what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband nodded and said, ``We want a two-story house.''
</P>
<P>
   So do a lot of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Association of Homebuilders does not
separate out ranch houses from other one-story dwellings, the trend
is clear: In 1971, 73 percent of the houses built were one story.
By last year, that figure fell to 48 percent. In the Northeast, the
difference is even more pronounced: only 20 percent of new houses
built in 1998 were one story.
</P>
<P>
   And of those one-story dwellings, very few are the classic ranch
house, built on the site by a crew of carpenters, plasterboarders
and plumbers. In many parts of the country now, they are ``ranch
style'' modular homes fresh from the factory, spotted on the
superhighways on the backs of tandem trailer trucks, cut into
sections like a scantily-clad magician's assistant and _ presto! _
reassembled on a waiting lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in business for 22 years,'' said Randy Wine, an
agent with Burgdorff Realtors ERA in Ridgewood, N.J., ``and I
haven't seen them build a new ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, Frank Newbold, the manager of the East Hampton
branch of Sotheby's International Realty, said that his customers
``won't even get out of the car'' to look at a ranch. When his
company does list one, he added, it is advertised as a ``one-story
traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the ranch, the comfortable, predictable,
quintessential suburban house? It came to represent the passe past,
not the classy past, the way Palladian villas and Romanesque
Revival palazzos do. And that, in fact, is what many new home
buyers are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch houses were ``plopped on the site, with a picture
window that looked out at the road, usually with a hurricane lamp
in the center and those awful flowery curtains,'' said Robert A.M.
Stern, the architectural historian and architect. ``The ranch house
has no attitude. America is a country of house-proud people.
Jefferson made that clear with Monticello.''
</P>
<P>
   S.I. Morris remembers when the first ranch house developments
were going up in Houston, probably some of the largest in the
country. He remembers because he was the architect for hundreds of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got out of college in 1935, and shortly after that they
started making a lot of noise about ranch houses,'' he said. ``They
started building them out on the suburban edge whedy lived;
an inexpensive ranch house with a car port for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Building ceased during World War II. Morris was married in 1945
and, shortly after, started to build the houses ``a new, cheaper
way,'' he said, adding, ``We introduced a new foundation system, no
basement, just a concrete slab.''
</P>
<P>
   There were five similar models; each sold for $8,000. ``They
were pretty much snapped up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the kitchen of the '50s Modernist house he designed
in the Museum District in Houston, Morris, 85, conceded that many
of the tract ranch houses ``weren't very well built.''
</P>
<P>
   The ranch houses ``needed a lot of lumber,'' he said. ``An old
friend drove his truck to East Texas and loaded it with 2 by 4's
and 2 by 6's, and a lot of them were so warped they just weren't
useful,'' he continued. ``But we used them anyway!''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, there is another problem: The earth beneath the
houses is a clay the natives call gumbo. Because of the soupy soil,
those 50- and 60-year-old slab foundations are cracking.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't the real problem with the ranch house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranch house just isn't as pretentious to look at,'' said
Kenneth T. Jackson, an urban historian at Columbia University and
the author of ``Crabgrass Frontier: The Suburbanization of the
United States'' (Oxford University Press, 1985).
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Americans wanted a big front yard. As a status
symbol, Jackson said, ``the yard was created in the middle of the
19th century, but is now playing itself out.'' The ranch, with its
substantial greenery, is being replaced by bricks and mortar, or
clapboard and nails, built right to the property line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a kind of internal luxury,'' Jackson explained.
``Americans in general are turning inward, with heavy drapes,
central air-conditioning and central heating that never matches the
temperature outside; with VCR's with 500 channels and Jacuzzis in
each of the giant bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For every movement, there is a countermovement.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston two years ago, an architecture group sponsored a tour
called ``Rancheros Deluxe,'' which lauded the best of the city's
ranch houses. At that time, there was some mention of putting a
whole district of ranch houses on the National Register of Historic
Places, but not much was done about it, said Stephen Fox, an
architectural historian who teaches at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from a few aficionados', there is no sense that the
ranch house is a vanishing species that needs special protection,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where the ranch house was born, the architect
Cliff May is often credited with inventing the one-story ranch
house. But others dispute that, pointing out that the tiled-roof
courtyard houses May popularized in San Diego in the early '30s
were adaptations of indigenous architecture. (William Wurster, an
architect working in San Francisco at the same time, designed
similar houses.)
</P>
<P>
   One problem, said Ken Bernstein, the director of preservation
issues at the Los Angeles Conservancy, is that so few neighborhoods
of ranch houses remain intact. Across the country, as late as the
'80s, the ranch house, with its easily-adapted sheetrock
partitions, was changed to suit growing families and, as such,
became a favorite ``starter home'' for the baby-boom generation. As
families grew, the little houses' low ceilings became cathedrals,
their carports became bedrooms and their kitchen walls were knocked
out and new, double-size ``gathering rooms'' punched their way into
back yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Levittown,'' Bernstein said, ``where the houses were
designed to evolve.'' The current debate, he said, ``actually is
changing the traditional views of what intact is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the preservation debate centers on the
architect-designed Modernist ranches, like those in the Crestwood
Hill section of Brentwood _ certainly not on the mass-produced
builders' ranches that conquered so many blocks in suburbias across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to educate politicians and homeowners to even
accept the  &UR; idea  &LR; that the 1940s or '50s can be looked at through a
preservation prism,'' Bernstein said. ``But there is a growing
recognition that we are losing the very best examples. It'll be
like the neighborhood after neighborhood of Victorian houses that
were torn down because they were viewed as overly ornamental and
too dark. They came back into favor in the 1970s, but by then,
cities all over the country had lost entire Victorian
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The best way to preserve a ranch house may be to live in it.
</P>
<P>
   Peter and Fan Morris, S.I. Morris' son and daughter-in-law, are
bucking the trend. Six years ago, they moved with their three
daughters from a 1920s brick French-style manor house with a
circular driveway to a 1959 ranch designed by Lucian T. Hood Jr., a
well-known local architect. Although she agreed with her husband
that their first house was just too formal for the family, Mrs.
Morris said she nevertheless had to be ``pried out'' of it. But
since then, she has fallen in love with the ranch _ in all its '50s
allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked in, I thought it was atrocious,'' Mrs. Morris
said. ``There was a 50-50 chance we'd tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the vast glazed red and bright blue brick free-form
swimming pool in the courtyard, with its round hot tub and spouting
fountain, Sarah Morris, 23, said: ``I thought the `glamour girl
pool' was so tacky. It reminded me of `The Parent Trap.''' Ms.
Morris, who just graduated from college, is back home with her
parents, hanging out in the former maid's room in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually, the house grew on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that this house has an intelligence that is at war
with my aesthetics,'' Mrs. Morris said. ``But because of it, I am
now a freer person _ I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house is almost a celebration of tacky,'' she continued.
``See this really tacky gold switch plate? And then there's this
silver one. It's really liberated my personal style. See these
flesh-colored tiles? I wanted to tear them out, but my architect
said: `You need an even stronger pink for the cabinets!''' She
gestured to the bubble-gum-pink Formica kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   There are also flesh-colored tiles in the period bathroom a few
miles away, in the ranch house owned by Carol Mancusi-Ungaro, a
paper conservator at the Menil Collection here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mancusi-Ungaro wasn't even looking for a ranch when she
started house hunting way back in 1988. ``They call them
ranch-burgers,'' she said. ``A ranch house doesn't even have the
cachet of a bungalow or a craftsman cottage.''
</P>
<P>
   But she, too, fell in love, and has decorated the house _ which
still has the original '50s &UR;  &LR; blond wood built-in cabinets in the
kitchen and the original pull-out bar in the family room _ in
period furnishings. She recalled when her son and his high school
friends sat 12 around the celadon Naugahyde sectional sofa,
watching the NBA playoffs on the dated (but not period) television
set.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mancusi-Ungaro said she is lucky, because her house is
strongly built. ``The structural engineer said it would last
forever,'' she said. But one thought gives her pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sell my house,'' she said, ``they'll probably tear it
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
