<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ Historic Israeli-Syrian peace talks
got off to a rocky start Wednesday, when Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa used opening remarks to assail the West for
``ignoring'' the plight of Arabs since Israel's birth. President
Clinton urged Sharaa and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to look
beyond their differences and into a future fresh with the promise
of peace. ``The road to peace is no easier, and in many ways it is
harder than the road to war.'' said Clinton. ``There will be
challenges along the way, but we have never had such an
extraordinary opportunity to reach a comprehensive
settlement.''Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Will move in the (w) Washington and (i) International
categories.
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAY-LOANS _ WASHINGTON _ Increasingly, workers in need of a
quick $100 or $200 just before payday are turning to lending
operations that will give them an advance _ for a big fee. For
many, the loan turns out to be a first step toward paying 400
percent annualized interest and falling ever deeper into debt. A
Senate forum examines the fast-growing national trend and hears
from critics and industry defenders. (Malone, Cox News Service).
22.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SIERRALEONE-TURNER _ BO, Sierra Leone _ A microcredit program
funded by Turner is teaching women skills and allowing them to buy
looms, sewing machines, and cassava graters that are supposed to
permanently improve their ability to support themselves. (Melvin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-SHOPPERS _ SAN MARCOS, Texas _ More and more Mexicans
are coming to Texas to shop. The holiday season brings visitors
from across the border, where prices are higher and selection is
not as good. (Pletz, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS. Eds:
Moving in both International (i) and Financial (f) categories.
MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEWT-DIVORCE _ Former U.S. House speaker Newt Gingrich and his
wife Marianne will sit down in the same room Thursday to talk about
a possible divorce settlement. It will be their first face-to-face
meeting in the case since they split this summer. The court-ordered
mediation will take place at the offices of Marianne's lawyer, John
Mayoue. Settlement remains unlikely, however, because Marianne
still hasn't deposed her husband's lover, Callista Bisek. That
deposition is considered a cornerstone of Marianne's effort to get
what she feels would be a fair settlement. Gingrich's attorneys say
he's ready to split the couple's existing assets in half and move
on. (Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
