<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIPS FOR MILLENNIUM TRAVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For those brave enough to travel over the New
Year's Eve weekend, the travel industry has a few tips to avoid any
millennium-sized headaches from the Year 2000 computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really think anything is going to happen, but it's
just one of those situations where people shouldn't take any
chances that could end up ruining their vacation,'' said Kristina
Rundquist, spokeswoman for the American Society of Travel Agents.
The Alexandria, Va.-based travel industry association, which has
nearly 29,000 members in more than 170 countries, said people
traveling between Dec. 31 and Jan. 3 should follow these tips to
help prevent any problems:
</P>
<P>
   _Obtain, and carry, a written confirmation of all travel plans
including confirmation numbers. If you are traveling to a resort or
destination that is booked to capacity, reconfirm your hotel
reservations by contacting the resort directly before you leave
home.
</P>
<P>
   _Before departing on an overseas trip, contact the State
Department or visit its Web site at
http://travel.state.gov/y2kca.html to check on your destination's
overall Year 2000 readiness. Check to see how prepared that
country's aviation industry is for the glitch that could disable
computers unable to distinguish 2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   _Consider obtaining traditional printed tickets rather than
electronic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _Take out extra cash or travelers' checks before departure,
rather than relying on Automated Teller Machines (ATMs) once you
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   _Think about purchasing trip cancellation insurance. However,
before you buy any, make sure the policy covers Y2K-related
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _Make at least two copies of all pertinent travel-related
documents including your passport, visas, driver's license, front
and back of credit cards, medical/eye prescriptions and important
phone numbers. Keep one copy in a separate but secure section of
your carry-on luggage and give the other copy to a close friend or
relative who can provide you with the information if needed.
</P>
<P>
   _Be sure to keep all essential items _ including prescriptions,
toiletries and a change of clothes _ in your carry-on luggage.
</P>
<P>
   _As with all peak-travel periods, anticipate possible delays.
Bring a book, water and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Rundquist said millennium travelers should take the attitude of
people ``heading into a storm and arriving in a place that was just
hit by a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   She also suggested that travelers consult a professional travel
agent to help with their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel agents will make sure all of your documents are safe,
and if problems arise, they can likely get you on another flight or
book you another hotel room faster than you could do it on your
own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
