<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS COLUMN MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY BY SUBSCRIBERS
TO ``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30 CROWD, WRITTEN
BY JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH INTELLIGENCE. FOR
INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CHARTER CLIENT _ OR TO SEE MORE SAMPLES _
CALL YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES REPRESENTATIVE AT (888)
269-8796. EDITORS WHO SIGN UP BEFORE THE END OF THE YEAR WILL GET A
COPY OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA REPORT,'' WHICH FOCUSES ON
WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH GENERATIONS X AND WHY?  
 (FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 THE NEXT CAREER: LIFESTYLIST
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get ready for a new profession that builds on our increasing
need for self-awareness, individuality and balance: LifeStyling.
Lifestyling does not exist yet, but from what I see these days,
it's a career whose birth is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   People today have an almost manic need to figure out who they
are. They want to create a life that reflects their true selves,
and this desire is reflected in their choice of what to wear, buy
and how to live. By bringing these elements together through a
series of deliberate consumer choices, they create a total vision
of living and being.
</P>
<P>
   Young people put on and take off whole new identities with ease.
They frequently experiment with who they are, and who and what they
would like to be. Today they can quickly outfit their lives to
reflect the most recent persona they have created.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Every mall in America offers the same cookie-cutter
lifestyle. It's the same J Crew, Banana Republic, Gap, Pottery
Barn, Crate &AMP; Barrel. Walk into any home, and you can spot the same
faux vintage candlesticks, gourmet salad dressing and basic white
t-shirt. And designers are not just outfitting our bodies, but our
entire lives. If you want to live the Ralph Lauren dream, paint
your house with Polo Blue. If just smelling and looking like the
epitome of Calvin Klein isn't enough, buy the sheets, dishes and
sofa covers to outfit your apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But as creating a persona becomes easier, finding out who you
truly are becomes harder. Indeed, part of the need for
individuality comes from a need to rediscover what happiness and
success mean for the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are too many choices and no right answers. Are you
more JCrew or Banana Republic? Can you really know yourself if
you're living a designer's package-deal life? And who are you if
you look like every one of your friends?
</P>
<P>
   As one 18-year-old male said ``I need to find something that
makes me feel like I'm not just a page out of some freaked-out
catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the LifeStylist who can help an individual understand who
he really is. The LifeStylist of the future will help you create
not just a look, but a life that is truly your own. Part
psychologist, stylist, trainer and interior designer, your
lifestylists will understand your wants, interpret your needs and
reinvent a life to reflect your inner self. He (or she) will sort
through your closet, and bring you clothing to select from small
boutiques. He will coordinate your house with your wardrobe,
analyze your Palm-Pilot and show you how much time you're spending
on negative energy. He'll create a workout that doesn't need a
trainer and a diet that doesn't need a workout. He'll setup
automatic order systems so that your home will always be
well-stocked. And he may even makes plans for the child that you
aren't even planning for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Your life will be customized to fit your vision of success and
happiness. A vision of not only who you truly are, but who you are
meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Some savvy stores and magazines are showing signs of early
LifeStyling _ providing a full vision of the life in which you
would use the products they sell. Language, a store in downtown
Manhattan, caters to the shopper's full life experience. Created
with three sections, the front-third features an eclectic mix of
designer apparel, the second offers furniture designed by the
store's owner, as well as jewelry, fragrances and other
accessories. The back section is a stark white gallery space that
features rotating exhibits of photography, sculpture and painting
by up and coming downtown artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the store is a lifestyle,'' says Mary
Keehbauch, store manager. ``We offer a complete package of how a
person would like to present themselves and their home. It's about
how a person perceives themselves and would like others to perceive
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Language is geared toward people who want to be perceived as
''very cutting edge, very much what's happening at the moment in
fashion,'' Keehbauch says.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing popularity of Wallpaper magazine also reflects
this trend. Wallpaper treats interior design, fashion, travel, food
and architecture as equally important elements of a larger picture
_ the life that someone wants to live. It doesn't depict actual
apartments or places, it creates perfect artificial versions of the
way things should be.
</P>
<P>
   LifeStyling offers a variety of expressions. As we seek more and
more to understand and express our individuality, the need for
knowing oneself will continue to grow, and so will the need for
people to help us get that knowledge and translate it into how we
live.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth
Intelligence, a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to
35-year-old market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a
comprehensive survey focused on identifying emerging trends among
Generations X and Why?) &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
