<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     12-15 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOONER OR LATER, YOU'LL HAVE TO DEAL WITH CLOGS IN YOUR DRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sooner or later, the drain lines in plumbing systems develop
clogs. These are frustrating and annoying because they require
immediate attention and removing the blockage can be messy. Many
homeowners first try a liquid drain opener. Sometimes these
products can be effective, but if they don't free the blockage, you
are left with a basin full of caustic solution that can be
difficult to work around.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to dislodge a block in the drainpipe is
mechanically. For this you'll need a few basic tools: a plunger, an
auger and a few wrenches. Every homeowner should have a plunger on
hand. The best type of plunger is a funnel-type one with a flexible
extension tube. The tube is designed for plunging a toilet, but it
can be folded back into the cup to plunge sink drains.
</P>
<P>
   The plunger is the first tool to reach for to unclog a drain. If
the clog is relatively minor, this tool can free it in a few
minutes. To clear a clogged sink, remove the stopper or strainer,
then stuff a wet rag into the overflow opening on the side of the
sink if there is one. Place the plunger in the basin so the cup
covers the drain opening, then fill the basin with enough water to
cover the cup. Vigorously work the plunger up and down several
times before pulling it abruptly from the drain. In most cases,
this should clear the drain. If not, you'll have to work below the
sink.
</P>
<P>
   Place a bucket under the sink and unscrew the slip nuts that
hold the drain trap in place. Sometimes you can loosen them by
hand; if not use an adjustable wrench. Most lavatories have drains
with chrome-plated pipes and nuts. If you are working on this type
of fixture, wrap the jaws of the wrench with masking tape. This
will keep the wrench from marring the finish on the slip nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the water in the trap into the bucket. If the trap is
filled with sediment, remove it with a stiff-bristle bottle brush.
This may clear the clog and you can reassemble the trap. If the
trap is clear, however, then the obstruction must lie within the
drainpipe in the wall. Switch to the sink waste auger to clear this
part of drain.
</P>
<P>
   The sink waste auger has a long coil of flexible steel cable
with a boring gimlet (essentially a steel spring with a hook on the
end), and a handle with a locking screw. It is not difficult to use
this tool. First, remove the horizontal drainpipe and feed the
auger cable into the stub-out (the short piece of pipe projecting
from the wall) until you meet with resistance. Pull about a foot of
the cable out of the drain, tighten the lock screw on the handle,
then push the cable back into the drain pipe as you crank the
handle clockwise. If the cable catches on something, don't force
it. Instead, reverse the handle direction and pull the cable back a
bit to free it then continue as before.
</P>
<P>
   This technique should break up the blockage. In some cases, it
may push the obstruction farther down the drain line. At that
point, pull the cable out again, loosen the lock nut to feed more
cable into the drain and continue as before. When you have cleared
the pipe, remove the cable and reassemble the drainpipe.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the basin with the hot water, then see if it drains
satisfactorily. If it seems slow, it could be that some of the
sediment from the broken-up obstruction has settled and is impeding
the water flow. Use the plunger to push it through.
</P>
<P>
   One word of caution about the auger; the flexible steel auger
spring will not harm modern drains, but the pipes in some older
houses may have bends and traps made of soft metal, like lead.
Pushing the auger into these sections can rupture the soft walls of
the pipe. Work carefully and avoid pushing the auger with excessive
force when trying to clean an old drain.
</P>
<P>
   Toilet clogs usually form at the top of the trap in the bowl.
Sometimes you can generate enough pressure with the plunger to push
the obstruction through. If not, you will have to use a closet
auger. The closet auger has a flexible steel snake that is partly
contained in a long tube. The snake comes out at one end of the
tube, and there is a crank handle on the other. Push the auger end
into the bowl as you crank the handle clockwise. Gradually force
the snake through the tight curves of the toilet trap and push the
obstruction through.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
