<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Dec. 16 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israel and Syria launched their
highest-level peace negotiations Wednesday, urged by President
Clinton at a showcase White House ceremony to make the ``hard
choices'' needed to end a half-century of hostility. (Summary from
wires) By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MURTHY (Bangalore, India) _ The extraordinary rise of N.R.
Narayana Murthy, his company and the software services industry in
India has come to represent the hope that what he calls
``compassionate capitalism'' can provide decent, desperately needed
jobs and the national wealth to improve health and literacy levels
in a country whose population has more than tripled since it won
independence in 1947. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRANSIT (New York) _ The tentative contract that the transit
workers' union reached early Wednesday calls for an 18 percent
increase in take-home pay over three years, giving New York City's
subway and bus workers the largest wage increase received by the
city's public-sector workers in more than a decade. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOBACCO-TAX (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. George Pataki and
Democratic leaders in the legislature are expected to reach an
agreement day that calls for raising the state's cigarette tax by
50 cents a pack in an ambitious effort to provide health coverage
for more than 1 million uninsured New Yorkers. By Raymond
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-STOCK-FRAUD (Washington) _ The SEC filed charges
Wednesday against three Southern California residents, including
two recent UCLA graduates, for driving up a company's stock price
by posting false information on the Internet. The trio reaped
$364,000 in profits from their actions, the SEC alleged in a civil
complaint. (Summary from wires) By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WORKER-MONITORING (Undated) _ In 1999, at least 45 percent
of employers said they monitored their employees' phone calls,
computer files or e-mail messages, according to the American
Management Association. That number, based on a survey of more than
1,000 human-resources managers at corporations of varying sizes, is
up from 35 percent two years ago. The monitoring is necessary,
employers argue, because of the changing nature of the workplace.
Supervisors must keep tabs on which workers are wasting company
time by surfing to entertainment Web sites, which ones are sending
e-mail messages that create a hostile environment for women or
members of minority groups, and which ones are distributing company
secrets or jamming their networks with bulk e-mail. Balancing that
desire for control with an employee's rights to privacy has never
been easy. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
