<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CONDUCTIVE-EDUCATION-     12-15 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDUCTIVE-EDUCATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDUCTIVE EDUCATION GIVES CHILDREN WITH CEREBRAL PALSY NEW HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ They sit snuggled with their mothers at the end of
three slatted tables.
</P>
<P>
   Timea Molnar, a young woman wearing a black T-shirt with the
words ``Making a Miracle Happen,'' moves among them offering
instruction and encouragement in a thick, Hungarian accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, sit up nice and tall, everyone,'' she says. ``I want to
see your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, responding to the soothing tones as the moms and Molnar
sing ``We are soldiers standing tall, one, two, three, four, five,
we are soldiers standing tall,'' the children _ Sean DuPree among
them _ sit up.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting with their backs straight may seem like a small feat to
most of us, but for Sean and the other children, it represents
progress bordering on the miraculous. Three years ago, Penny DuPree
had no hope that her son would ever sit, dress or eat without her
help.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who was delivered via an emergency Caesarean section Nov.
18, 1996, was eight weeks premature and had cerebral palsy, a
neurological disorder resulting from injury to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, DuPree enrolled Sean, now 3, in an intensive
program of exercise and learning called Conductive Education of
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Sean could not sit up on his own. He could not crawl or talk. He
kept his right hand balled into a fist so tight that his nails cut
into his palms.
</P>
<P>
   When DuPree told Sean's neurologist about Conductive Education,
he told her she'd be wasting her money but to try it anyway, so
that she wouldn't have any regrets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mansfield mother, a registered nurse and administrator for a
home-care agency, says she was skeptical at first. But after five
sessions with Molnar, Sean could sit up in a shopping cart at the
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the seventh, he was able to sit in a high chair in a
restaurant,'' DuPree said, recalling the day employees at Cha Cha's
cheered her son's success.
</P>
<P>
   DuPree's tears of joy are understandable. And this is only one
of almost a dozen stories being played out at Conductive Education.
Parents who had no hope of their child ever leading a ``normal''
life, now see progress they never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hoped and prayed,'' DuPree said. ``But I didn't
expect to see results so soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Conductive Education is a holistic approach to teaching designed
to improve the children's motor skills so that, ultimately, they
can succeed in a regular school program and even college. Dr.
Andras Peto of Budapest, Hungary, developed the system more than 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although popular in Europe, the approach wasn't introduced in
the United States until the late 1980s. American Conductive
Education was formed in 1992 to broaden awareness. There are now 50
programs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas branch was founded in 1997 by Tamala Day and
Elizabeth Osborne, shortly after Day learned about Conductive
Education on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Day said that through Conductive Education, her son Jaxsen
progressed from using a walker to walking with a cane, which
requires better balance and coordination.
</P>
<P>
   She attributes the program's success to the continual physical
training. The program also incorporates academics, speech, feeding
and social skills that help shape the child's progress.
</P>
<P>
   Conductive Education teachers are called conductors because Peto
wanted to distinguish them from therapists, whose skills focus on
specific aspects of development, not overall progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not physical therapy,'' Day said. ``It's a method of
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Inter-American Conductive Education Association said that
about 500,000 adults and children nationwide have cerebral palsy.
And the United Cerebral Palsy Association estimates that about
5,000 children are born with the disorder each year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of growing demand, Aquinas College in Grand Rapids,
Mich., has formed a partnership with the Peto Institute in Budapest
to train conductors in a graduate and undergraduate program
beginning in August _ the first of its kind outside Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got involved as a result of having some pilot programs
happening in our community and the parent's strong desire to have
this established as a program option for their children,'' said
Kathy Barker, director of the Aquinas-Peto School for Conductive
Education at the private liberal arts school.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said that there are fewer than 500 conductor-teachers in
the world and that those individuals come primarily from the Peto
Institute.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 a.m., the ``Mom and Baby'' class that DuPree and Sean
have been attending the last two months is almost over, and the
pre-kindergarten/kindergarten class is about to begin. A class for
school-age children is from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows mothers to play a major role in their
children's education, encouraging them to help their children make
movements impeded by brain damage. They use a gentle but firm
hands-on coaching approach to teach their children to roll over,
sit and stand. The smallest success is accompanied with nursery
songs and encouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, four boys are writing the alphabet on miniature
blackboards while soaking their feet in hot sage water that helps
to relax their muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Doyel sits nearby, watching her son Devin, who is 4. She
radiates pride.
</P>
<P>
   Doyel and her husband, Darren, had been told that Devin would
always be in a wheelchair, and that as he got older he'd become
more deformed. At 3 1/2, he wasn't potty-trained, couldn't sit up,
and couldn't feed or dress himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been around the wheel looking for someone to help him,''
she said. ``My husband actually found Tamala on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of when Devin first came to Conductive Education
of Dallas, he was potty-trained. He has now exchanged his walker
for a cane, and he brims with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just really neat to see him feeling like he's on the same
level as everyone else,'' Doyel said. ``It's extraordinary the
difference we've seen in him.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
