<SLUG> BC-SKI-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S TALK ABOUT THE WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Bill Callen, Albany Times-Union; originally sent Dec. 9)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vice president of a large ski company commented privately
the other day: ``This is getting scary.'' Of course, he was talking
about the current lack of snowpack in the northern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing new about warm autumns, or December meltdowns. Nothing
new about an upper air pattern that blocks the cold Arctic air out
while the warm soup spreads from the South all across New England .
. . and sits for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen this before. But, what if this is new?
</P>
<P>
   What if there is a permanent warming going on? So far as anyone
can tell amid all the political wrangling about global warming, no
one really knows. Or at least no one has been convincing one way or
another.
</P>
<P>
   Certain pieces of data seem unsettling - the shrinking of the
polar ice cap; the fact that some species of migrating waterfowl
from the Canadian maritimes do not range as far south to their
ancestral wintering grounds anymore (just ask the fifth generation
goose hunters from Maryland's Eastern Shore who see a fraction of
the birds that used to return for winter).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, we humans are semi-schooled at best in the long
rhythms of climate and geological evolution and do not know whether
we are dealing with a real change in the planet's climate or merely
moving through cycles heretofore unrecognized. After all, in terms
of accurate record-keeping, meteorology is a relatively new
science.
</P>
<P>
   Our long-term memory often proves untrustworthy in recreating
accurate pictures of our past. A week-long power outage caused by a
blizzard in February when we were 8 years old will color our
memories of winter for a lifetime. We might conjur up images of the
Klondike, home of Sergeant Preston and King, as we remember and
long for our nostalgic past.
</P>
<P>
   In those ringing days, there was always deep fresh morning snow
after nightly blizzards. The skiing was limitless. The winter life
as gay and robust as some old David Niven movie set in a Tyrolean
resort.
</P>
<P>
   But, back to the dismal reality of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sure there have been winters, and starts of winters, like this
one. Warm autumns, with unrelieved weeks of tepid soup that retards
natural cycles even of flower and insect. Check out your backyard.
</P>
<P>
   But no, we'll skip the global warming for now and take the easy
explanation. The warm autumn is just that, and made all the worse
because of heightened expectations of skiers with pent-up energy
carried over from last year's stingy season. And with the Christmas
week fast approaching, the collective knot in the stomach of the
ski industry is apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Peak, one of the most naturally snowy mountains in the
Northeast, intends to open its new lift, the Green Mountain Flyer,
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,500-foot lift, designed to carry 2,600 skiers per hour,
was going to provide some free skiing Saturday for those attending
the opening celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Not now. The celebration will take place sans the skiing and
boarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but with a little cold weather we'll have the
skiing going hopefully for the holidays,'' said Jay Peak spokeman
Conrad Klefos.
</P>
<P>
   The American Skiing Company, with its six New England and two
Rocky Mountain resorts, has put forth a bet with skiers. By the
holidays, says ASC chairman Les Otten boldly, ``We will have
snow.'' ASC areas have often touted guaranteed skiing, but this
year they are making an even greater promise to vacationing skiers
and boarders: ``If we can't give our guests at least 70 percent of
their mountain, we'll activate the guarantee,'' says Otten.
</P>
<P>
   The guarantee will give guests a 25 percent price reduction on
their next visit this season and a voucher worth up to $500 toward
a vacation at The Canyons in Utah or Steamboat in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is made to guests reserving a ski vacation between now
and Dec.
</P>
<P>
   24 and is good for vacations between Christmas and Jan. 2, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, according to ASC spokesman Skip King, the
resorts are taking the risk out of booking a ski vacation during
the holidays. ``We know people down there are concerned with the
amount of snow they're going to find,'' said King. ``Our bottom
line is if you go skiing over the holidays you'll have a good
time.'' The ASC guarantee applies to Sunday River, Sugarloaf/USA,
Killington, Mt.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, Sugarbush, and Attitash/Bear Peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some resorts we can open four to six trails a day,'' said
King. ``And we're looking for some natural snow, too. We'll have
the stuff. If not we'll activate the guarantee.'' Hmmm, with 26 of
120 trails currently open at Sunday River, King is hoping that the
forecast for cold weather after this weekend will come true. With
about two weeks to Christmas, even at the rate of 4-6 trails a day,
70 percent coverage seems ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' says King. ``We've got our work cut out for us.
But if people get here, they'll have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SKI-COLUMN &QL; 
By Tony Chamberlain, Globe Staff &QL; 
SPEED LIMITS IN PLACE; RESORTS GET SERIOUS WITH `HEADS UP' MOVE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago at Killington, a speeding skier or
snowboarder might get a mild reprimand from a ski patroller. It was
a somewhat casual enforcement, patrol officials acknowledge, and
whenever the question of lifting a ticket came up, ``we'd give
skiers every benefit of the doubt,'' according to Killington
spokesman Steve Wright.
</P>
<P>
   This was pretty standard policy throughout ski country: Try to
maintain safe conditions, but also let skiers have their fun. At
the sprawling twin resorts of Vail and Beaver Creek in Colorado,
the Wild West spirit of point-'em-straight-down-and-go was widely
hailed as a skier's creedo for many years.
</P>
<P>
   But times change. This year at Killington, says Wright, ``the
ski patrol has the freedom to pull someone's ticket immediately if
they see the person acting recklessly.'' And at Vail, Killington's
Western counterpart, the National Ski Patrol has added a new safety
squad called the Yellow Jackets, dedicated to busting the fast and
reckless. To date this season, they have snatched more than 50
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for a new industry-wide campaign called Safety
Initiative 2000 or ``Heads Up'' may not have as much to do with
reality of skier safety, as public perception.
</P>
<P>
   Four agencies - the National Ski Areas Association, National Ski
Patrol, Profesional Ski Instructors of America, and Snowboard
Industries - all had a hand in creating the Heads Up campaign as a
unified effort to minimize skiing and snowboarding accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cornerstone of our safety message is that each one is
responsible for the choices (he makes) on the slopes,'' says Stacey
Gardner of the Ski Areas Association. ``Skiing is relatively
serious, and you have to be paying attention.'' But the campaign
has little to do with trends or fatality records. Since the 1970s,
reportable injuries on the slopes have been cut nearly in half.
</P>
<P>
   Better grooming, wider trails, and better equipment in the last
30 years of skiing's growth all are part of the safety picture.
</P>
<P>
   Skier fatalities or catastrophic accidents have been relatively
steady at about .8 per million skier visits. In an average winter,
about 50 million skiers and boarders hit the slopes, and the
average of 34 fatal crashes has been fairly constant. Last year, 39
deaths occurred in US ski country, highest number in the last four
years, but the year before, there were only 26 skier/rider
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the big safety push came because, according to National
Ski Areas of America spokesman Michael Berry, ``we're confronting
an old adage, `perception becomes reality.' `` Two years ago, when
Michael Kennedy and Sonny Bono died in ski crashes in the Rocky
Mountains, the media attention focused on skiing as never before,
Berry said. ``It didn't matter what the safety record had been up
to that time.
</P>
<P>
   Because they were celebrities, there was a new focus on skier
safety.'' Tim White, educational director for the National Ski
Areas Association in Denver and one of the architects of Heads Up,
says the campaign is largely aimed at people unfamiliar with
figures showing skiing to be among the safer outdoor sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that people are getting the wrong message about skiing
when all they hear about in the media is the most serious
incidents,'' said White. ``Our goal is to get our message out that
the industry has a wonderful safety record.'' The sport has always
suffered from the perennial broken leg joke. Just this year, said
White, a commerical was released showing a busload of happy skiers
showing up at the lodge. The next frame shows the bus returning
``with the skiers in neck braces, full body casts, and dripping
IV,'' White fumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is how perceptions are created for people outside the
sport,'' he said. ``The LA Times and Wall Street Journal printed
some negative (editorials), and that is what we're trying to
confront with Heads Up.'' White, Berry, and members of the National
Ski Patrol agree that Heads Up is not a new approach as much as an
intensification of what has been ongoing safety policy at ski
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, they point out, most ski areas have established
``slow skiing'' zones, though enforcement has been uneven.
</P>
<P>
   White does not advocate a zero-tolerance policy that would
summarily tear the tickets off speeders. He would rather see
enforcement of the safety code on a case-by-case basis, and have
judgment become a part of the ski patroller's education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps for the first time (a skier or rider) breaks the
rules, he will get his ticket marked, then get it pulled on the
second offense. It's a case-by-case thing,'' said White.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real message to people is that we are on the hill with
eyes that are watching.'' Interestingly, the National Ski Areas
Association does not take a definitive position on helmets, whose
popularity has soared the past two years, a fact often attributed
to the Kennedy and Bono deaths, which were caused by head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the position that helmets are a personal choice. A
helmet is a piece of equipment just the same as the equipment on
the feet and under them,'' said White. ``They certainly are not the
whole picture. We would be concerned if people feel a helmet is the
one answer to safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
