<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1216-CO     12-15 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1216-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISTORIC ISRAEL, SYRIA PEACE TALKS GET OFF TO ROCKY START
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Casting a hopeful gaze toward reconciliation and a
wary eye on their blood-stained past, senior Israeli and Syrian
officials huddled with President Clinton Wednesday to try to forge
an end to a half-century of enmity and war.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes talks got off to a jarring start, though, when
Syria's senior negotiator
</P>
<P>
   blamed Israel for the discord, saying Israeli occupation of Arab
land was ``undoubtedly the source of all adversities and wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conceded at midday that talks between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa
were no diplomatic picnic. Tensions ran so high that the men
refused even to shake hands at the outset of the talks, a standby
in diplomatic proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard going,'' Clinton told reporters when asked about his
morning meetings with the two officials. ``We've got work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the talks opened, Barak signaled that he was prepared to
pull troops from the occupied Golan Heights in exchange for
security guarantees and a new partnership with Syria, a country
that has fought Israel off-and-on since the inception of the Jewish
state 51 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to put behind us the horrors of war and to step
forward toward peace,'' Barak told White House reporters at a Rose
Garden ceremony opening the talks. ``We are fully aware,'' of the
price Israel must pay to get there, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lest there be any doubt, Sharaa, said his country was prepared
to embrace Israel, but only after the Golan territories _ on
Israel's northeastern edge _ are restored in full to Syrian
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that peace for Syria means the return
of all its occupied land,'' Sharaa said, as Barak stood by, his
face as stony and grey as the December skies.
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa then gave his version of the land for peace formula at
the heart of the talks _ tacking on an icy jab at Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Israel,'' Sharaa said, ``peace will mean the end of the
psychological fear which the Israelis have been living in as a
result of the existence of occupation, which is undoubtedly the
source of all adversities and wars.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Barak, who spoke before
Sharaa. However, the Syrian foreign minister's comments were not
well-received in Israel and were expected to make Barak's task of
convincing Israelis to accept a peace accord with Syria that much
harder.
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa went on to assail the Western media, saying it focused on
the plight of Israelis while ``the vision of the Arabs and their
sufferings were totally ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those tribulations, said Sharaa, was the loss of homes by
half a million Syrians who were run off by Israeli troops occupying
the Golan Heights, ``where their forefathers lived for thousands of
years and their villages were totally wiped out from existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa then revisited the origins of the 1967 war, in which
Syria joined Jordan and Egypt in attacking Israel, alleging that
Israeli provocations along its border with Syria had helped to
incite the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli forces captured the Golan Heights, strategically
valuable territory in Syria's southwest corner, during the 1967
fighting. A United Nations resolution that year called on Israel to
return the territory to Syrian control in exchange for Syrian
acceptance of Israel's right to exist within secure borders.
</P>
<P>
   That so-called ``land for peace,'' formulation remains the
framework for the peace effort Clinton hopes to push forward during
this week's talks _ largely dedicated to charting a course for more
detailed negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A peace accord between Syria and Israel is seen as one key to a
larger prize _ a comprehensive settlement between Israel and its
Arab foes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been trying since his first year in office to broker
peace among Israel and Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   He remains hopeful of helping to shepherd the parties to an
overall peace accord before leaving office 13 months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath oppressively grey skies on a cold and damp day, Clinton
led Barak and Sharaa into the Rose Garden for what he hoped would
be an upbeat beginning of admittedly difficult talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing today is not yet peace, and getting
there will require bold thinking and hard choices. But today is a
big step along that path,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in history,'' he said, ``there is a chance
of a comprehensive peace between Israel and Syria, and indeed, all
its neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the hopeful rhetoric, administration officials expected
difficulties during the talks, scheduled to continue on Thursday.
White House aides said they were encouraged that Barak and Sharaa _
the highest ranking Israeli and Syrian officials ever to negotiate
anything _ showed up at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected this to be easy. The issues are complicated,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. He said ``a lot
of work and a lot of intensive negotiations,'' lie ahead on the
road toward Israeli-Syrian peace.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``Today's meetings were indeed a breakthrough.
These are the highest level meetings ever between Israel and Syria
on any subject, much less peace between the two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Barak and Sharaa met together for half an hour in the
Oval Office. Then Clinton met separately for about an hour with
each official, first Barak and then Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   While one met with Clinton, the other conferred with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Albright then hosted further talks between the two leaders in
the Blair House, across the street from the White House, for most
of the afternoon before an early evening break. The talks were
supposed to resume at 7 p.m. EST, but White House officials said
negotiations would start up again Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Albright was scheduled to meet again with Barak in a
downtown hotel after dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to discuss the substance of the talks, other
than to say that ``Both sides made clear their desire for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a former military commander elected earlier this year
largely on his pledge to try to negotiate peace among Palestinians,
Lebanon and Syria, appeared to set a conciliatory tone.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Barak told the Knesset, Israel's parliament, that the
country must brace itself to bear the ``high price'' for peace,
meaning the return of the Golan Heights to Syrian control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fully aware of the opportunity, of the burden of
responsibility, and of the seriousness, determination and devotion
that will be needed in order to begin this march, together with our
Syrian partners,'' Barak said in the Rose Garden Wednesday, ``to
make a different Middle East, where nations are living side by side
in peaceful relationship and in mutual respect and
good-neighborliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa also struck a tone of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching the moment of truth,'' he said. ``We hope
that this is going to be the last resumption of negotiations, which
will be concluded with a peace agreement, a peace based on justice
and comprehensivity; an honorable peace for both sides that
preserves rights.''
</P>
<P>
   He seasoned those remarks, though, with his broadside attack on
Israel and its allies, continuing with a stark warning that a
failure to return the Golan would condemn the region to ``a
conflict of existence in which bloodshed can never stop.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
