<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner seed money blossoms
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BO, Sierra Leone _ The initial loan to the Splendid Farmers
Association was only 500,000 leones _ about $268. But it has been
repaid several times over, and, to hear the women in the
association tell it, the benefits from that relatively small amount
of money continue to flow.
</P>
<P>
   The money started as a tiny drop in the oceanic portfolio of
Atlanta media magnate Ted Turner. From there it went to the U.N.
Foundation, which was set up to distribute Turner's gift of $1
billion over 10 years to U.N.-related projects. From the
foundation, it went to UNICEF, the United Nations Children's Fund,
as part of a $500,000 grant ``to improve nutrition and household
food security for vulnerable groups in Sierra Leone.''
</P>
<P>
   From UNICEF, the money was given to a relief and development
organization called Africare. From there, some of it made its way,
at least temporarily, into the pockets of of an association of 150
women who had been displaced by Sierra Leone's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   That loan, in 1998, was meant to help the members of the
Splendid Farmers Association, as the displaced women called
themselves, start some petty trading activities so they could feed
their children and buy some clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of providing poor women with small, unsecured loans was
pioneered by Muhammad Yunus, a Bangladeshi banker and economic
professor who is now also a member of the U.N. Foundation board.
The theory, backed now by more than two decades of experience, is
that tiny loans can help poor women become permanently
self-sufficient _ and that they pay back the loans, with interest,
as reliably as any other group.
</P>
<P>
   The money then becomes a revolving fundF, using Turner's money,
has delivered eight of the graters, and seven more are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Cassava, a potatolike tuber, has a shelf life of less than a
week if it is not processed, said Joseph Lemor, a UN
</P>
</TEXT>
