<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changes at pinnacle of Coca-Cola a hot topic
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It seems everybody has taken a crack at explaining the
surprise retirement of Coca-Cola's M. Douglas Ivester. Now Business
Week (Dec. 20) takes its shot.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the problem, the magazine ventures, is Ivester's
background. ``An accountant by training, Ivester knew the math, but
not the music, required to run the world's leading marketing
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Also behind the move, says Business Week, is the issue of a No.
2 executive at Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   On the cover: How and why regional shopping malls are becoming
like amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   OLD DOESN'T MEAN OUTDATED
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Dec. 27) invokes the name of Benjamin Graham in offering
``eight investing rules that have stood the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, credited as the father of modern security analysis, had
a theory that flies in the face of the Internet craze but still
makes sense today, Forbes says. His theory was that you shouldn't
buy a stock just because it is rising.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Forbes: A little literary license is used to explore
what the pieces of General Electric would be worth if the company
were to be broken up after Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
Jack Welch retires.
</P>
<P>
   PICK YOUR OWN EXPERT HERE
</P>
<P>
   Every magazine seems to have its own list of ``greatest stocks
to own'' in the next millennium. Mutual Funds (January) offers a
twist.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine picked up ideas from the well-known and powerful,
including Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown economist Edward Yardeni and
Sheryl Pressler, chief investment officer for the California Public
Employees' Retirement System. The magazine then suggested a handful
of funds that represent investments along the lines each investment
pro pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 1 IN GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Who shows up as the Georgian of the Year in the December issue
of Georgia Trend? It's Gov. Roy Barnes. The issue includes the
magazine's list of 100 most powerful and influential people in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   MORE STOCK PICKS FOR 2000
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor (January) offers its list of stocks you
should own. Last year's picks, by the way, can claim a total return
of 79.7 percent, the magazine notes.
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor picked 25 stocks, in five different
``sectors,'' so to speak. The magazine identified five
``highfliers,'' those with the wind at their backs; five stocks in
the ``bargain bin''; five that haven't shown up on Wall Street's
radar; five that represent ``turnaround plays''; and five more that
analysts regard with lukewarm feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ROSIER COMPLEXIONS?
</P>
<P>
   Among the offerings from Barron's (Dec. 13): a look at computer
maker Gateway and some cautious optimism about health care stocks.
</P>
