<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nortel buying Qtera in $3.25 billion deal
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nortel Networks said Wednesday it is buying Qtera, a
South Florida optical network equipment maker, for up to $3.25
billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Canadian-based Nortel a company with no product
on the market and no revenue, but loads of potential.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is expected to close early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, Manning &AMP; Martin, the Atlanta law firm that handled
United Parcel Service's initial public offering, represented Qtera
in the deal. It has handled Qtera since the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Qtera is developing ways to send voice and data over light waves
through fiber-optic wires. Most of the data sent over fiber-optic
lines need to be regenerated every few hundred feet. Qtera's
equipment can send data over fiber-optic lines almost 2,000 feet
without regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   Firms like Qtera are developing the tools that companies like
Nortel and Lucent will use in the next generation of high-speed
networks _ which will handle increasingly heavy Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel's acquisition is the latest among several networking
equipment firms attracting attention recently. In November, Cisco
Systems bought Cerent for $7 billion. Sycamore Networks went public
in October. The Massachusetts-based company has a market
capitalization of more than $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Qtera was started in 1998. About 30 percent of the firm is owned
by its management and employees. The rest is owned by venture
capital investors, including Battery Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel executives said in a morning conference call that they
expect Qtera, which will be run as a separate business unit, to
start earning revenue within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
