<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-HITECH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner hangs on to big idea of buying broadcast network
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly 15 years after his failed attempt to buy
CBS, Ted Turner would still love to own one of the big four
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be big, then let's be big and own one of
everything,'' said Turner, referring to Time Warner Inc. ``I'd make
a great Noah. I want two of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner is vice chairman of Time Warner. He quickly added that
his company didn't necessarily share his desire for a television
network. ``This is just me speaking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner made his comments on the opening panel of the Western
Show, one of the cable TV industry's biggest conventions. It runs
through Thursday and has attracted some 30,000 industry executives.
Among those attending are executives from Atlanta-based companies
such as Turner Broadcasting, Cox Communications, Scientific-Atlanta
and the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Turner, the opening panel featured a stellar
lineup of industry leaders. They included CNN commentator Jeff
Greenfield, who moderated the panel; USA Networks Chairman Barry
Diller; and Michael Bloomberg, founder of the financial news
service that carries his name.
</P>
<P>
   The star, of course, was Turner _ and he quickly stole the show.
Asked by Greenfield what Time Warner needed, Turner quickly
responded that a broadcast network would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But doesn't Time Warner already have one in the WB?''
countered Greenfield, referring to the fledgling service that
features youth-oriented shows.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Turner. ``It doesn't have news. It doesn't have
sports. It's better than nothing, but the WB is not a true
network,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   That Turner wants to buy a network, say NBC, is no secret within
the media industry. But it's also no secret that other Time Warner
executives are skeptical. Turner has yet to marshal enough support
within his company to mount a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Turner has always enjoyed poking fun at conventional thinking,
and his target Wednesday was interactive television, touted as one
of the next big opportunities for cable. Two-way television,
available through new digital networks, lets viewers use TVs to
order products, send e-mail and even change the outcome of shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a push of a button you can change the outcome of a game
so that your team always wins,'' said Turner. ``And if you ignore
the news, you could take your team to a championship. Of course,
that's not real. People will still want to be just entertained by
television. Interactivity is not a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   With a snicker, Greenfield interjected, ``That computer would
have not helped the Atlanta Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield, a Time Warner employee based in Atlanta, was
referring to the Braves' World Series defeat this fall.
</P>
<P>
   On one issue dear to cable TV executives, Turner supported the
industry consensus. That issue is open access, referring to opening
the industry's digital cable networks to other services, such as
those providing Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, MindSpring and some government officials
advocate open access, while the cable television industry opposes
it. ``It's our wire, and we'll do what we want with it _ unless, of
course, we're forced to do otherwise,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   His fighting words were greeted with applause from the several
hundred cable TV executives watching the panel at the auditorium in
the Los Angeles Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Turner described open access as one of several big challenges
facing the industry. Another is direct broadcast satellite
providers, such as DirecTV, which has some 11 million subscribers.
It is growing by 200,000 subscribers nationwide a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of threats, but cable is holding the
distribution high ground,'' said Turner. ``The game is ours to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
