<HEADLINE>
WHAT ARE THE HIP AND HOPPING PEOPLE DOING FOR THE FAUX MILLENNIUM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DICK J. REAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so it's not technically the millennium. People who spend
their time telling us that calendars skipped a year as they went
from 1 B.C. to A.D. 1 tell us we don't hit the millennium until
next year, New Year's Eve 2000. Hooey. We're still going to party
like it's 1999, for I was dreaming when I wrote this, forgive me if
it goes astray. (Sorry, but a Y2K bug in our system inserts Prince
lyrics into every applicable story.) But will everyone be welcoming
2000 in a big way? To find out, we asked some well-known folks and
some not so well-known. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   JENSEN ACKLES, Eric Brady on NBC's Days of Our Lives and a
native Texan
</P>
<P>
   What he will be doing: Surfing in Hawaii
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``It's just what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``It's just another
year.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To make it a better year than the
last one.''
</P>
<P>
   PAULIE AYALA, World Boxing Association bantamweight champion
</P>
<P>
   What he will be doing: ``I'll be at Teaching Word Faith Center,
right off of I-35 and Sycamore.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``I'll be giving thanks to God for another year with my
family, with good health and with my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``I know that
everybody is worried about the Y2K bug, but I'll leave all of that
up to God.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To learn to speak Spanish
fluently.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Hickman, singer
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``I will be at the beach with my
daughter and husband and three other close friends, or I might be
playing an early gig in Austin. I haven't decided which yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``Because one is completely relaxing; one would help my
daughter's college fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``Please slow down!''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To continue to count my blessings
and tithe even more. And spend more time gardening!''
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Loader, documentary filmmaker
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``I am going to be partying at an
observatory on Mount Hopkins, near Tucson, Ariz.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``My husband ... will be the after-dinner speaker at this
soiree.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``... My biggest fear
is that when the new millennium arrives and nothing changes, a
whole lot of people are going to be disappointed and cross. Imagine
being stuck with all of that survival food.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``Every day, in every way, I will
get better and better, but then again, perfection is the enemy of
the good.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Maule, Dr. Tony Jones on ABC's ``General Hospital'' and a
native Texan
</P>
<P>
   What he will be doing: ``For the celebration of the millennium,
we'll be watching from the safety of our home'' in California.
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``To me, any event that has not reccurred for a thousand
years should be shared with only those closest to you. Who wants to
remember a cold $250 pre-fixed dinner for the next thousand
years?''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``The thought of the
millennium in Vegas is way too `Mars Attacks' for me. If I were
going anywhere, it would be Casa Manana.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To wait at least another thousand
years before doing this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Anne Mountz, Kay Bennett of NBC's ``Passions'' and a
native Texan
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``I'm going to be in Crested Butte,
Colo., with close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``I wanted to be somewhere where it would be snowy and
quiet. My best friends in Dallas are going camping, which is fun
but not preferable to me on New Year's Eve. So, I decided to go
somewhere cozy.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``I'm just ready for
it to get here. The hype is unreal, and I've learned that
expectations are never the same as reality.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To watch what I eat, and become
more health-conscious all around.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro, Texas Ranger
</P>
<P>
   What he will be doing: ``My wife, Lynne, and I are going to
Macon, Ga., to spend New Year's with Kevin and Candace Brown and
other friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``To spend time with good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``It's just another
year. But it is the year for us to win the World Series!''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``I don't really make resolutions,
but every year I hope to improve in all areas of my personal and
professional life.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Pena, Miguel Rodriguez on the CBS show ``Young and the
Restless'' and a native Texan
</P>
<P>
   What he will be doing: Taking a three-day cruise to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``It's nice to be out at sea. I'll be going with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``It's going to be a
great new millennium, and everything is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To enjoy the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Sansom Harris, editor Audrey Radford on NBC's ``Stark
Raving Mad'' and a Fort Worth native
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``Boarding my birds, hiring a house
sitter and heading for the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``Sheer contrariness.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``It had to happen
sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: To get out of the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Patsy Torres, Tejano singer
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``I'll be reminiscing about the year
gone by as I travel on the road to my show venue.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``Being a musician, New Year's is traditionally the biggest
party of the year, and we provide the party's entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``I look forward to
the millennium. I believe that overall, people are good and we will
prevail over the mistakes of our past. I have faith in God's love
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``I plan to slow down and better
organize my time; not let my schedule be so hectic, and take time
out for myself, my family and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Wagner, Nancy on CBS' ``As the World Turns'' and a native
Texan
</P>
<P>
   What she will be doing: ``Celebrating with my husband and
sister-in-law at the Kittle House Restaurant near home in
Chappaqua, N.Y.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``Because it is my favorite restaurant for its people and
food, and it's near home. We don't usually go out New Year's Eve,
but visitors being with us made this seem a nice celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophical thoughts on the millennium: ``It is heady to
contemplate all we've seen develop.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 New Year's resolution: ``To make none. To live every day
as well as can be done. What else, at age 81?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
