<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN AGAIN TACKLES SOFT MONEY CONTRIBUTIONS ON EVE OF TOWN FORUM 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Getting a jump on a campaign finance town
forum Thursday with Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley,
Republican contender John McCain said Wednesday that purging large
sums of money from the political system would allow his party to
better pursue its conservative goals.
</P>
<P>
   McCain used a speech in South Carolina to rebut charges from
many in his party, including GOP front-runner George W. Bush, that
his proposals to eliminate soft money contributions would make it
harder for the Republican Party to compete with Democrats, who
benefit from union money.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money refers to the unregulated contributions given to
political parties, who are supposed to use it for party building.
In recent years, both parties have used the money indirectly to
help their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that huge contributions from special interest have
made it harder for Republicans to accomplish their agenda of
trimming wasteful spending from the federal budget and ridding the
tax code of loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Washington soft-money game, big business and big labor
amplices, working together to protect the mushy middle of
big government, with plenty of special-interest plums: big unions
get big spending; and big business gets corporate welfare and
special tax breaks _ all at the expense of average Americans,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator, however, acknowledged concerns that Bush
raised in Monday night's Iowa debate that eliminating soft money
would put the GOP at a disadvantage because organized labor runs
its own independent campaigns for Democrats financed by union dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands now, the only institutions that can take your
money without your knowledge are the IRS and the labor unions,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would bar unions from taking members' dues for
political purposes without getting written permission. But he added
he would place the same restrictions on corporations that use their
shareholders' money on behalf of political campaigns and
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments provided a preview of the discussion expected
Thursday in Claremont, N.H., where both McCain and Bradley will
participate in a town meeting hosted by ABC-TV's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual bipartisan summit by two primary candidates is
taking place at the same senior citizens center where President
Clinton and former House Speaker Newt Gingrich shook hands in June
1995 and agreed to form a blue-ribbon commission on campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   That panel never materialized. Congress is in a stalemate over
campaign finance reform. The Republican leadership has blocked the
changes, including the ban on soft money, proposed by McCain and
Sen. Russell Feingold, R-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   But campaign finance advocates say McCain and Bradley are
equally shrewd when it comes to fund-raising. Both have raised
prodigious sums of money for their presidential campaign, much of
it from individuals who work for corporations who have interests in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   According to the center, McCain raised $9.2 million as of Nov.
1, much of it from executives of companies who have interest in
legislation before the Senate Commerce Committee, which McCain
chairs. His top contributors work for such communications and
financial giants as Viacom, US West, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., and
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said that the Commerce Committee has oversight over
so many companies it would be hard to avoid contributions from
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   This year, executives and the families of those who worked at
Goldman Sachs also gave $209,500 to Bradley's campaign, the biggest
bundle delivered to any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has raised $18 million so far, not far behind the $24
million collected by Gore, according to the Center for Responsive
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, soft money contributions have fattened the war
chests of both political parties.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of 1999, the Republican Party committees
raised $30.9 million in soft money, a 42 percent increase over the
fist six months of the 1997-98 election cycle, according to the
Federal Election Commission. During the same period the Democratic
Party committees raised $26.4 million, a 93 percent increase from
the last election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   By pounding on the campaign finance reform theme Bradley and
McCain have scored points with independent voters who now comprise
the largest chunk of the electorate in the first primary state of
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And analysts say that this appeal to independents has helped
McCain inch ahead of Bush and given Bradley a lead over Vice
President Al Gore in several surveys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
