<SLUG> BC-COLOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK AND WHITE IN COLOR': LOSING THE PAIN IN THE RHYTHMS OF GYPSY
MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potent testament to the infectious spirit of music is offered by
two documentaries that begin a two-week run Thursday in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-minute ``Black and White in Color,'' a Czech film
directed by Mira Erdevicki-Charap, portrays the formidable Gypsy
singer Vera Bila; and the 15-minute ``Ziganska Musica,'' a German
film directed by Joachim Kreck and Detelina Grigorova-Kreck, takes
as its subject an electric Gypsy band, Trustenik, and its
clarinetist, Philip Simeonov, called Fekata.
</P>
<P>
   If music is the strength of these films, their weakness resides
in the narrowness of their focus, in decisions that have more to do
with design that remains almost steadfastly on the visual and aural
surface of their subjects and declines to explore the personal and
ethnological questions each raises.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with Ms. Bila and Trustenik as their centerpieces, these
films are enjoyable on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bila, an enormous woman who calls herself a typical Romany,
is a force to be reckoned with. In Prague, Paris and Germany she
attracts a devoted following, but as depicted in ``Black and White
in Color,'' she lives in a shabby apartment, pawns belongings to
deal with her debts and worries about the future of a son in jail
for robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sing about the troubles I have,'' she says at one point
as she explains her soulful magic.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as Ms. Bila occupies center stage, either singing or
shopping barefoot in the streesiting a ramshackle community
where she hopes to find a wife for the betterment of her son,
``Black and White in Color'' remains arresting.
</P>
<P>
   When it turns its attention elsewhere, as to the members of her
band, Kale, its energy falters. And in portraying Ms. Bila, the
film raises questions about her and about Gypsy culture that remain
frustratingly unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziganska Musica,'' filled with the energy of folk, jazz and
rock 'n' roll, unfolds nearly wordlessly at a Gypsy wedding in
northern Bulgaria. As the busy camera darts among the sometimes
self-conscious participants while they dance, eat, sing and bestow
gifts, it also turns its attention to the band and to those
villagers who watch the proceedings with curiosity, longing and
vicarious joy from behind a fence.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the music gives pleasure, but curiosity about these
people, their lives and their customs remains unsatisfied. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BLACK AND WHITE IN COLOR'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mira Erdevicki-Charap; written (in Czech, with
English subtitles) by Katerina Ondrejkova; director of photography,
Marek Jicha; edited by David Charap; music by Vera Bila and Kale;
produced by Charap and Cestmir Kopecky; released by Czech
Television and Arcimboldo. Shown with ``Ziganska Musica'' at the
Film Forum. Running time: 58 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Vera Bila and members of the band Kale. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ZIGANSKA MUSICA'
</P>
<P>
   Produced, edited and directed by Joachim Kreck and Detelina
Grigorova-Kreck; directors of photography, Peter Herrmannsdorfer,
Pavel Schnabel, Shoro Nedelkov and Nikolai Minchev. Running time:
15 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Philip Simeonov and Trustenik. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
