<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MIDEAST TALKS &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page of coverage on the beginning of
talks between Israel and Syria and their ramifications in the
Mideast and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israel and Syria resumed peace
negotiations that stalled nearly four years ago, with the modest
goal of surviving and making plans to move beyond two days of
breaking the ice in a relationship long frozen by mutual mistrust.
By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-U.S. (Washingon) _ Peace is a costly proposition. Any
agreement reached in the current Israel-Syria talks is certain to
entail huge costs _ to monitor security arrangements, to relocate
Israeli settlers and to bolster the Syrian economy. If the past is
any guide, the United States will bear the lion's share of the
burden. And if negotiations ultimately succeed, President Clinton
will face the prospect of trying to win billions of dollars to pay
for peace from an ideologically charged Congress that is loath to
grant Clinton any victories, especially in a presidential election
year. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Two key Israeli Cabinet ministers
said they may pull their small but influential parties out of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's ruling coalition if he agrees to return the
Golan Heights to Syria. ``I think at some point that it will become
impossible to stay in the government,'' Interior Minister Natan
Sharansky, the leader of the Yisrael B'aliyah party, said Wednesday
night. Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy, head of the National
Religious Party, met with Sharansky Wednesday morning in what he
termed an effort to ``coordinate'' their opposition to a Golan
Heights withdrawal, expected to be the linchpin of the prime
minister's planned peace accord. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SYRIA (Damascus) _ It was 32 years ago that Israeli
forces drove Syrians by the many thousands from the Golan Heights.
Today, many of those same Syrians were fixing eyes and ears at
Washington, in the hope they were witnessing a watershed. ``People
are exhausted by this stalemate,'' said Ali Rahil, the headmaster
of a primary school outside Damascus, who was relying on a
satellite dish to monitor the news from abroad. ``They want the
talks to move forward.'' Still, with Israeli-Syrian negotiations
once again under way after a 45-month break, the Syrian government
has been trying to keep optimism in check. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Gary McCardell.
</P>
