<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS &LR;      12-15 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NINERS NEED NEW BLOOD IN FRONT OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ When this disaster of a season finally
ends around midnight on Jan. 3, it's imperative that the San
Francisco 49ers make the right moves toward rebuilding their
once-mighty franchise. Whether that means finding a new quarterback
or a new set of cornerbacks or a new general manager, they have to
get it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate having another year like this,'' said John
McVay, the club's director of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   At least, they hope not.
</P>
<P>
   Getting it right means having a clear idea of who's in charge
upstairs. Is it John York or Bill
</P>
<P>
   Walsh or some murky combination thereof?
</P>
<P>
   York, husband of owner Denise DeBartolo York, seems to enjoy
this ownership thing; it is, after all, a rather exclusive club.
However, he doesn't seem to be too cozy with Walsh, the general
manager who has a long history with the club juxtaposed against
York's recent involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his three-year contract, Walsh is not a lock to return
in 2000. He's 68, for one, and in charge of a fading franchise that
will take several years to rebuild. Does a man of his
accomplishments want to go through that again when the job is so
daunting?
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, there is a feeling within the 49ers' organization
that Walsh actually wants York to fire him to relieve him of the
responsibility of running the show when the show is about to be
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Two other members of the front office are also 68, McVay and
Bill McPherson, director of pro personnel. That's a lot of wisdom
and experience but is the vigor for the job still there? Not to be
ageist, mind you. As per his contract, McVay will scale back to
three days a week next year and two days a week the year after
that.
</P>
<P>
   Might a younger presence be needed here? Someone like Matt
Millen? There's nobody quite like Millen, in football or any other
perversion of life. He's an American original. This is a man who
dresses like he was tossed naked into a Salvation Army bin and told
to find some clothes. The only time he combs his hair is when he
goes on camera for a Fox broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers issued the standard denials about rumors that Millen
might be interested in working for them in an executive capacity.
The party line is that the front office will remain as it is, with
Walsh, McVay and director of player personnel/meteorologist Terry
Donahue in charge of everything above the coaching level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know from him if he put anything out,'' said
coach Steve Mariucci, who played phone tag with Millen on Tuesday.
``I certainly didn't and our organization didn't. I can understand
why some of these rumors would exist. He almost considered it last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen is as sharp as they come in evaluating football and
football players. He played the game, he knows what an NFL player
looks like, he knows absolutely everybody in the game and, with a
rare misanthropic exception or two, everybody likes him.
</P>
<P>
   He's someone you would want on your team, whether as a player or
someone in charge of evaluating players. Millen and Mariucci are
friends. It seems they'd get along if joined in common toil on the
second floor of the Marie P. DeBartolo Sports Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone were to leave the organization, obviously you want
to consider all the best candidates,'' Mariucci said. ``I don't
know if he's ready to make a move like that. He has a heck of a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   That job has made Millen a valuable resource around the league.
In his role as an analyst and broadcaster, he knows every team's
personnel. He knows whether Baltimore's long snapper is worth a
spit. He knows if Kansas City's left tackle can handle a speed
rusher. He knows who's been naughty and who's been nice. Why, if
you gave him a Santa suit he would wear it if it meant he didn't
have to buy or launder his own clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt is a very astute guy,'' McVay said. ``I like him.
Everybody loved him when he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point in their history, maybe the 49ers need a little
hybrid vigor in the form of Millen, someone who could graft onto
the organization to make the whole thing stronger and more vital.
</P>
<P>
   Everything hinges on what Walsh wants to do, or what the Yorks
want him to do. Has he had enough or does he have one more surge of
brilliance left?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have fallen so far so fast they have to be concerned
not with the big picture but with their own little division, the
NFC West. With those skilled offensive players, the Rams could be
dominant for years to come. George Seifert has the Panthers playing
well after a slow start. The Falcons should get a healed Jamal
Anderson back next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of work to do,'' Mariucci said of the coming
offseason. ``We have to be right on most of our acquisitions and we
have to work well together.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's a pointed comment directed at Walsh, the old master
better have thick skin or a padded suit. This is no time to be
jolly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
