<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS HAVE NOWHERE TO GO BUT UPWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In mock surrender, Clippers coach Chris Ford
opened his postgame _ or postmortem _ press conference Tuesday
night by leaning rigidly against a concrete wall in the bowels of
the Staples Center with one arm outstretched, as if preparing to
face a firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   If his players had been doing the shooting, his safety would
have been guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's good-humored grace under misfire aside, the Clippers
played as if they had been issued blindfolds, and as a result, they
opened new vistas of horrors, even by this franchise's execrable
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the first meeting between housemates at the new arena shared
by the two Los Angeles NBA residents, the Clippers needed to rally
in order to escape with mere humiliation in the form of a 95-68
thrashing by the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the worst franchise in league history added to
its lugubrious legacy by pouring in 19 points in the first half _
an NBA record low since the shot clock was implemented in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully knocking the New Orleans Jazz _ who scored 20 points
in a half against Seattle on Jan. 4, 1975, and eventually had to
leave town _ out of the outhouse, the Clippers piled up 3 points in
the second quarter. Only a 10-foot jumper by Michael Olowokandi at
8:28 and a free throw by Lamar Odom at 6:27 prevented the Clippers
from pulling off basketball's version of a no-hitter. Odom's
freebie ruined their bid for a dreadful double because it left them
with 1 more point in a quarter than the record low established by
their fellow NBA stalwarts, the Dallas Mavericks, against the
Lakers in 1997. Obviously, Odom, the rookie from the University of
Rhode island, has no sense of history. So the Clippers had to
content themselves with the mark for fewest points in a second
quarter, bettering (worsening?) the 5 by the Utah Jazz (they could
escape New Orleans, but not their sharpshooting inheritance) in
1981 and the New York Knicks last season.
</P>
<P>
   To Clippers guard and Providence College alumnus Eric Murdock,
the performance was worthy of ``making you want to hide your
face.'' That's what the Clippers appeared to be doing before they
took their shots _ and missed 17 of 18 _ in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't exactly light up the night, scoring just 17
points in Period 2, but they still owned a 30-point lead at the
half as the Clippers shot 18.4 percent (7 for 38), the worst ever
by a Laker opponent. In fact, Lakers coach Phil Jackson's biggest
concern was that whatever the Clippers were doing might be
contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came apart at the seams,'' he said. ``For a young team as
talented as they are, they can do a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   No NBA team has done worse, and the Clippers nearly stretched
their mastery of misery to a full 48 minutes. Improbably, they
expanded their deficit to 34 points, 80-36, after three quarters
and were on pace to fall into the cellar for post-shot-clock
scoring: 49 points by the Chicago Bulls against Miami last April.
By the time the last 12 minutes rolled around, the Laker Girls'
uniforms were getting progressively skimpier, but it was the
Clippers who were being undressed.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jackson philanthropically went to his scrubs, giving
Shaquille O'Neal (21 points, 19 rebounds) _ who had made Olowokandi
(13 points, 10 rebounds) look like a foreign exchange student when
it mattered _ the rest of the night off. Even then, it seemed to
take the Clippers about five minutes to realize that O'Neal wasn't
in the game and that trying to gain inside position was no longer a
death sentence. Once that sank in, they started hitting something
besides air, leaving the Bulls' record etched in stone hands. But
the wasted effort wasn't entirely wasted. The Clippers tied the
franchise nadir for points in a game and shot worse (26 for 80,
32.5 percent) than any other Laker opponent over the full 48.
</P>
<P>
   Ford tried to take the high road after his team bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys we were all embarrassed,'' he said, ``but
we've got to put it behind us because we've got other games coming
up to get ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   First the Clippers had a civic obligation to fulfill. Wednesday
they were scheduled to distribute toys to underprivileged children
at a suburban cinema.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't their first donation of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
