<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ARCH-WILBERFORCE-COX     12-15 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCH-WILBERFORCE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Wilberforce player learning about race and hoops
</P>
<P>
   Byc. 1999 Cox News ServiceWILBERFORCE _ He said no to Vanilla
Ice.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the season opener for the Wilberforce University
basketball team, it was Homecoming and he knew the gym would be
packed. And, as is pregame ritual, each player would take the floor
to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys wanted me to go out to Vanilla Ice,'' Jon Inrig said
with a smile, ``but I wouldn't do it. For the rest of my days here,
I didn't want to be called Vanilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a teammate suggested Eminem, a white rapper with a popular
song about a guy called Slim Shady. Inrig liked that and so did the
fans. Slim Shady, catchy name, but they wondered if the new kid had
game. Was he all hip and no hops? Was this a lot of hype and no
hoop?
</P>
<P>
   That was answered in the opener against Voorhees College when
Wilberforce coach Sean Bledsoe sent Inrig _ the only white player
on his team and the only white male undergrad on the campus _ into
the game for the nation's oldest, historically black private
liberal arts college.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I think the crowd was like, 'Oh, the white guy's
finally on the floor,''' Inrig said. ``I think they expected me to
be terrible.'' But when he got the ball, Inrig took a quick
cross-over dribble, stopped and let fly a jump shot that snapped
the net cords.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Inrig said. ``That's the loudest I've
ever been applauded in my life. The place roared.'' Bledsoe agreed:
``That's the biggest cheer I've ever heard anyone get here.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can tell, there's something more than basketball going on
in the Wilberforce gym this season. It's the ``Guess Who's Coming
to Dinner'' deal in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Inrig is a 6-foot-5 freshman from Abbotsford, British Columbia
with reddish hair, a galaxy of freckles on his pale shoulders and a
lot of questions in his path: ``Why did you come here? Where are
you from? ...And, uuh, by the way, do you have a girlfriend?''
</P>
<P>
   With that first question, Inrig said, the answer seems to change
the longer he walks around the campus. In the beginning _ after
spending a year loading trucks at an ice cream company while
dealing with some family and health matters _ he thought this was
simply an unexpected, but much appreciated, chance to play college
ball.
</P>
<P>
   It has turned out to be a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a reason I'm here and it's not just to play
basketball,'' said Inrig, sounding more wizened than his 19 years.
``This is a real learning experience for me. And I think it's the
same for the other guys on the team, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For Inrig, this is quite the odyssey. Abbotsford is 45 minutes
east of Vancouver. Inrig's father, Rick, played basketball at the
University of British Columbia, then coached in high school and
college. He was the president of Basketball British Columbia and
now is an assistant at the Mennonite Educational Institute (MEI),
where Jon starred two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The school is a basketball powerhouse in British Columbia. As a
junior, Inrig averaged 16 points per game on a provincial Final
Four team. His senior season, he averaged 24 points and seven
rebounds for a team that went 34-10.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out a year _ working and dealing with a severe
viral infection that effected his heart _ Inrig wanted to play
college ball. A Canadian recruiting agency started to spread his
name around and soon college pamphlets were arriving in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them I never even read, but it's weird, I remember
the one from Wilberforce,'' he said. ``My friends and I were
looking at it and I remember there wasn't one white face in it. I
figured that would be the last place I'd end up.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been no black players on Inrig's high school team,
although he played against blacks, was on a 3-on-3 team with two
black players last summer and said he has a few black friends at
home. ``He's always been a little different that way, more so than
a lot of kids around here,'' said MEI coach Arnie Dick. ``Jon's a
kid who suprises you. When he spreads his wings, he blossoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe _ who has another Canadian in Toronto's Calvin Meikle _
stepped up the recruitment once he cleared up one matter: ``I
wanted to make sure his family knew this was a predominantly black
institution. And I wanted to know if Jon could survive?''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Inrig said he had no doubts, though he did want to see the
school first. So over the summer father and son visited the campus
and liked what they saw. Still, Jon had no idea what he was walking
into: ``I didn't ask for any of this. I just came to go to school
and play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said the first two days of open gym, people from campus
showed up just to stand and watch Inrig: ``I think 90 percent of
the people are glad Jon's here. It's gone from 'Hey, there's a
white kid on campus,' to 'Hey, Jon's real cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   Inrig has been befriended by another freshman, Adrian Wilkinson.
Since Wilkinson has a car, he's shown Inrig the area, socialized
with him and spent a lot of time sharing ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not say it, but I know there's so much pressure on
him coming to a black college,'' Wilkinson said. ``There's a
nervousness because you feel you've got something to prove. You
want to live up to expectations. And when they see a white guy,
whether it's fair or not, they expect him to be a 3-point
shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Inrig knows the thinking: ``On both sides _ black and white _
stereotyping happens all the time. Sometimes that leads to real
misconceptions. I know white people sometimes see a group of young
black guys and think they're up to no good when they're only going
to restaurant or just having fun. And sometimes a black guy will
think white people are always out to get him when that's not it at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you, I've learned some things about racism here.
I've heard stories, heard things said to black players. I've seen
racism on both sides now and I realize how wrong it is. I also see
how much we're really alike. Truthfully, I think everyone should
experience this. Experience what it's like to be the outsider. You
feel things you never felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as his teammates are learning about him, so are opponents.
When the Kentucky State players saw him two weeks ago, they all
made mention of ``the white boy.'' Inrig said he's ``usually pretty
light-hearted'' about that, but this time he thought, ``OK, let's
go out and see.''
</P>
<P>
   In that game _ with his dad sitting in the stands next to
Wilberforce President Dr. John Henderson _ Inrig scored 22 points.
It's been his best outing. Through 11 games, he's averaging 6.2
points. Tuesday night against the University of St. Francis from
Fort Wayne, Inrig _ with the sparse crowd cheering his every move _
scored four points in a 69-64 Bulldog loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon needs to be confident out there and not hesitate to take
his shot,'' Bledsoe said afterward. ``And we've got to find some
guys to get him the ball better than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a work in progress and there are some rough spots. But
you see signs it's working when you watch the camaraderie and hear
the jokes. The best give-and-take comes with Wilkinson. ``We'll be
riding in the car, listening to the radio and all of a sudden I'll
say, 'OK, try clapping on the beat,''' Wilkinson grinned. ``Next
we'll work on his dance steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Some girls in the stands Tuesday night said they saw Jon at a
party and want to teach him the Booty Call dance. ``Oh yeah, Jon's
popular with the girls,'' Wilkinson said with a laugh. ``We'll walk
together on campus and girls who once said 'hi' to me are all
going, 'Hi Jon! What you doing, Jon?' I go, 'OK, I guess I don't
exist any more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after the Bulldogs' game with Ohio Dominican College,
Inrig will fly back to British Columbia for Christmas. ``Everybody
here is telling me, 'Jon you're not going to know how to act.
You're going to be wondering where all the black people are,''' he
said. ``They figure I'm going to get asked all the same questions
again. And I know they're wondering what I'm going to be
saying...''
</P>
<P>
   After thinking a second, he began to smile:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just be telling my old friends about my new friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
