<HEADER>
A0044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-BOS &LR;      12-15 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH DEFENDS IOC REVAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Juan Antonio Samaranch had promised he would answer
anything he was asked on Capitol Hill Wednesday _ about Olympic
corruption, his wife's $13,000 trip to Atlanta, even the cost of
his Swiss hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   And so the longtime International Olympic Committee president
did for three hours, testifying under oath and in Spanish, as
skeptical members of the House Commerce subcommittee on oversight
and investigations questioned whether the sweeping reforms passed
by the IOC last weekend would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conduct by IOC members and the bidding cities did not
spring up yesterday and it will not go away simply because there
are new rules written on a piece of paper,'' said chairman Fred
Upton (R-Mich.). ``Rules on paper, no matter how tough or complete,
are just that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 79-year-old Samaranch, who pushed through 50 proposals
covering everything from age limits for members to visits to bid
cities, insisted the reforms were sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that we deliver what we promise,'' he said
through an interpreter. But Samaranch, who will step down when his
term ends in July 2001, conceded that he couldn't guarantee lasting
reform. ``People will come after me and they may change the
rules,'' he said. ``I don't think any organization in the world can
have permanent rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the seven committee members present said that comments
from some IOC members indicated they had voted for the changes
reluctantly out of loyalty to their embattled leader. ``I fear that
the reforms will be cosmetic, merely to mask the autocratic aura
that surrounds the organization,'' said Representative Diana
DeGette (D-Colo.).
</P>
<P>
   Upton, who said previous hearings made it clear that Salt Lake
City and Atlanta were not the only bid cities engaged in a
``culture of corruption,'' charged that the IOC under Samaranch had
``consistently, arrogantly, unbelievably turned a blind eye to the
ugly truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know, what did you know and when did you know it?''
Upton asked Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who has agreed to be interviewed by FBI agents next
year, insisted he knew nothing for certain until the IOC began its
own investigation of the Salt Lake scandal a year ago. Though he
said he had heard numerous rumors and allegations about corruption,
``every time we tried to get proof, nothing that could have begun
an inquiry was ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the IOC had facts and names, Samaranch said, it moved
decisively to expel or force out 10 members, ban visits to bid
cities, and restructure itself. ``I think we clean the house,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the House subcommittee has no direct oversight over the
IOC and no power to compel him to testify, Samaranch agreed to
appear even though some of his fellow members thought it unwise _
and said he would appear again (``no problem'') if asked. ``They
ask questions, they are trying to get information,'' he said. ``I
deliver the best I can the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said he was also prepared for personal questions,
especially about the 1990 trip his wife Bibis was treated to by the
Atlanta organizers. ``Not only did I know it, I advised her to
go,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has no vote, she didn't want to see the venues,''
Representative Joe Barton (R-Texas) told Samaranch. ``She just
wanted to go to artsy-craftsy places and sample high society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are probably right, sir,'' said Samaranch, who read a
subsequent letter to his wife from then-Vice President Dan Quayle,
hoping that she had been able ``to sample some hospitality for
which the American South is famous.'' ``This is a problem of the
organizing committee. That was an invitation based on friendship
and this is all I can affirm.''
</P>
<P>
   The visits for IOC members and their families and the expensive
gifts that came with them are finished, Samaranch declared. ``That
problem has disappeared completely,'' he said. ``Gifts were closely
connected to trips. If there are no more visits, there will be no
more danger of gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said, though, that he will continue to accept gifts in
his position as IOC president and turn them over to the Olympic
museum. He also will continue to live in his two-room suite at the
Palace Hotel near IOC headquarters in Lausanne, which he denied is
luxurious or expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Though the usual rate reportedly is $960 a day, Samaranch said
the IOC is charged only $250 and just $70 when he is out of town.
``Because I am living there year-round,'' he said, ``they have a
special price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
