<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-LINE16-CO     12-15 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-LINE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons line hits rock bottom
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If last season was a dream for tackle Ephraim Salaam
and the Falcons' offensive line, this year has been a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The season-ending knee injury to All-Pro running back Jamal
Anderson in the second game made everybody's job a lot tougher. But
the bottom line is the line rarely has played well.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have rushed for more than 100 yards just three times
and rank 30th in the NFL in rushing, averaging 72 yards per game.
They've also given up 47 sacks, and their average of one sack every
9.6 passing plays is second-worst in the NFL, better than only
expansion Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Super Bowl season, the same five players started
every game on the offensive line. ``We're just not getting the job
done, and that's disappointing to all of us,'' Salaam said.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow this year came after the preseason, when coaches
decided to bench Calvin Collins and start Bob Hallen, last year's
second-round choice, at left guard. That lasted six games before
Greg Bishop replaced Hallen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Gene Williams was injured, Collins went in at right
guard. When Bishop sprained his left knee, Hallen went back in at
left guard.
</P>
<P>
   In last Sunday's 26-7 loss at San Francisco, center Robbie
Tobeck left in the second quarter with a left hip strain. Collins
moved to center, and Williams went in at right guard. Coach Dan
Reeves said Williams is still battling a sprained right ankle that
took him out of the starting lineup last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always important that you ... play the game the way you
practice,'' Reeves said. ``It caused some problems ... because the
communication is basically done by the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Does all this have an effect on the collective confidence of the
remaining linemen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it does, but you try not to let that affect you,''
Salaam said. ``If I don't know where my guard is going to be,
that's makes it tougher. But we've been playing together two years;
that shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, a seventh-round pick in 1998, is 6 feet 7 and played his
rookie season at about 290 pounds. Coaches wanted him to gain
weight, so he did, beginning this season at 303 pounds. He has
looked unsure of himself, occasionally lacking the foot speed that
was a strong suit last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of weight on real fast, and maybe I wasn't
adjusting to it right,'' Salaam said. ``But guys in this league are
getting bigger and faster. I've got to keep building. I plan to be
in this league a long while.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point for Salaam came in a 34-28 loss at Carolina two
weeks ago. On the Falcons' last two possessions, he jumped offsides
once and gave up two critical sacks to Kevin Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that Carolina game, I felt I let the team down,'' said
Salaam. ``If I had ever been blamed for a loss, I would put that
one squarely on my shoulders. I had a real good season last year,
and I'm not this year. This whole season has been hard on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
