<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANNA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISN'T IT ROMANTIC? YOU BETCHA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Embargoed until Friday, Dec. 17. Fact box at bottom) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' is an old-fashioned valentine for all
those people who say they don't make movies like they used to. The
film, with its exotic landscapes, grand sets and lush visuals,
feels as much like a fairy tale as director Andy Tennant's last
effort, ``Ever After.'' And while ``Anna'' has its share of
shortcomings _ it's a half-hour too long, for one thing _ audiences
craving romantic spectacle will undoubtedly come away satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna'' is the third movie to be based (quite loosely) on the
story of British teacher Anna Leonowens, who traveled to Siam in
1862 to teach the country's royal family. The most famous version,
of course, is ``The King and I,'' the 1956 Rodgers and Hammerstein
musical that made Yul Brynner a star and moviegoers whistle a happy
tune. Twelve years earlier, Irene Dunne and a horribly miscast Rex
Harrison matched wits in ``Anna and the King of Siam.''
</P>
<P>
   Casting is the new film's strength, with Jodie Foster starring
as the headstrong teacher and Hong Kong action star Chow Yun-Fat
playing the king of the male-dominated society of Siam. Anna comes
east with her young son, Louis (Tom Felton), looking for a change
after the death of her soldier husband. She, of course, gets more
than she bargained for in Siam, a country that treats women as
second-class citizens, condescendingly calling them ``sir'' just to
make sure they get the message.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Anna'' isn't a message movie, and Siam's sexism is
simply used to fuel a light-hearted gender battle between Anna and
the king. Anna's job is bigger than she imagined, since the number
of royal children comes to nearly 60, thanks to a bevy of
concubines. Tennant uses the kids as adorable props, used to
highlight the differences between Anna's western ideas and the
eastern ways of Siam.
</P>
<P>
   The film also has two subplots, neither of which quite work. In
one, the king's latest concubine, Tuptim (Bai Ling), has trouble
leaving behind her home and the man she truly loves. Meanwhile, the
king must contend with political and military threats to his
throne. Tennant, with no background in staging battle scenes or
adventure set pieces, is in over his head here and trades heavily
on ideas from ``The Bridge Over the River Kwai'' for his finale.
</P>
<P>
   But then, originality would be a little much to demand from a
third-generation remake. (Tennant also shows he has been paying
attention to such sweeping romances as ``Dr. Zhivago'' and ``Out of
Africa,'' among others.) ``Anna'' aspires to warm the heart and it
does so whenever it returns to the relationship between the two
title characters.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, with eyes impossibly (and improbably) blue, wavers
occasionally with her British accent, but possesses the strength
and (somewhat surprisingly) the warmth to make audiences root for
her character. Chow is the major revelation, confidently commanding
the screen with imposing stillness and impressive feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Together they are (to borrow a song title from ``The King and
I'') something wonderful, making ``Anna and the King'' the kind of
undemanding crowd-pleaser tailor-made for good tidings of the
holiday season. &QL; 
____ &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Anna and the King'' (PG-13; some violence). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Jodie Foster, Chow Yun-Fat. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR; !off! Directed by Andy Tennant. Screenplay by
Steve Meerson and Peter Krikes. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  Two hours, 26 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  Citywide. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
