u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      12-15 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIAN MINISTER LOSES LITTLE TIME IN ATTACKING ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opening the highest level talks ever between Israel
and Syria, President Clinton Wednesday urged both sides to ``write
a new chapter in the history of our time'' and seize the
opportunity to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone doubted the difficulty of the task, one indicator
_ embarrassing the president _ came a minute after Clinton finished
speaking in the misty Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking from the scripted public appearance, which originally
called for no comment from either side, Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk Sharaa launched into a two-page, single-spaced typed address
saying the world had largely ignored the Syrian plight and labeling
Israel as the aggressor and Syria the wronged party in the loss of
the Golan Heights in the Six-Day War of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Sharaa) pulled a Suha on us,'' said a US official on
condition of anonymity, referring to assertions last month by
Yasser Arafat's wife, Suha, before First Lady Hillary Clinton that
Israel was using gas to poison Palestinian women and children.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton peered over Sharaa's shoulder to try to read the
Syrian official's speech and National Security Adviser Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger puffed out his cheeks in exasperation, Sharaa said
Syria demanded the return of ``all its occupied land'' before
offering Israel a ``just and comprehensive'' peace.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharaa, speaking on behalf of Syrian President Hafez Assad,
also challenged the Arab world's thinking of its conflict with
Israel, asking whether the ``Arab side ... will wonder, after
reviewing the past 50 years, whether the Arab-Israeli conflict was
the one which solely defined Arab unity or the one which frustrated
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, in a brief statement, said
that his negotiators had come to Washington ``to put behind us the
horrors of war and to step forward toward peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Sharaa and Barak _ who didn't shake hands, a gesture
that the Israelis had hoped for and photographers at the ceremony
had yelled for _ walked together with Clinton for a half-hour
meeting at the Oval Office. Clinton then met separately with the
two leaders, who later moved across Pennsylvania Avenue at a
presidential retreat for discussions with Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright. Orginally, the two sides were to meet alone.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said both sides declined its offer to continue
talks later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters after his talks the negotiations were
``going pretty well, but it's hard going.'' Clinton privately
expressed his displeasure to Sharaa about the tone of his speech,
the US official said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that
during the Clinton meetings ``both sides made clear their desire
for peace. They expressed the importance that both sides attached
to the Syria-Israel component as critical to an overall
comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the Israeli disappointment in Sharaa's opening
comments, there were several indications that the negotiations were
on a fast track and could be wrapped up within a few months. Most
importantly, all sides said the talks picked up from where they
left off in March 1996 when Israel ended discussions following a
series of terrorist bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Those earlier talks included intensive rounds over four months
at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland. ``The entire record of
what was agreed and accomplished is written down clearly by (US
Middle East envoy) Dennis Ross,'' said Helena Cobban, who has just
finished a book, ``The Israeli-Syrian Peace Talks,'' which will be
published early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The two chief negotiators, Barak and Sharaa, know well the
details of the talks, although Barak at the time expressed serious
reservations at a deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Barak and Assad ``seem very serious'' about a peace
formula that would return the Golan Heights and withdraw soldiers
from southern Lebanon in exchange for security arrangements, the
end of guerrilla attacks from Hezbollah fighters and diplomatic,
economic and cultural relations with Syria and Lebanon, Cobban
said.
</P>
<P>
   She believes that both leaders will want to move quickly to head
off ``the anti-withdrawal forces in Israel and the anti-peace
forces in Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has called Syria's Assad more than a dozen times in
recent months to reopen talks, cautioned in his opening statement
that ``what we are witnessing today is not yet peace. And getting
there will require bold thinking and hard choices. But today is a
big step along that path.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``For the first time in history, there is a chance of
a comprehensive peace between Israel and Syria, and indeed all its
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointedly, Clinton raised the issue of the Israeli-Palestinian
peace track, which remains the central obstacle of a wider Middle
East peace with outstanding disputes of Jerusalem, Palestinian
statehood, sharing precious water and the return of Palestinian
refugees to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, the president
said: ``We see now leaders with an unquestioned determination to
defend and advance the interests of their own people.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians leaders are worried that the Syrian peace track
could leave them in a much weaker negotiating position. Barak has
said that he can negotiate with both sides simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Clinton said, there were no guarantees of success in the
Israeli-Syrian talks. After Sharaa's opening statement, several
Israeli officials attempted to put a positive gloss on his words,
saying it contained some conciliatory remarks and at least it
wasn't as bad as his comments at the opening of the Madrid peace
conference in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There, Sharaa held up a ``Wanted'' poster featuring then-Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, charging Shamir with terrorism for his
deeds before the state of Israel was created in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sharaa did strike another raw nerve Wednesday by
saying that former Israeli Defense Moshe Dayan ``himself explained
in his memoirs that it was (Israel) who insisted on provoking the
Syrians until they clashed together.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement, while not accurate, contained some truth. Dayan,
who died in 1981 without completing his memoirs, told a young
journalist in 1976 that he regretted capturing the Golan Heights
and that Israel deliberately provoked Syria before the war. ``We
would send a tractor to plow some area where it wasn't possible to
do anything, in the demilitarized area, and knew in advance that
the Syrians would start to shoot,'' Dayan said in the conversation,
which was published in Israel in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth day of the 1967 Six-Day War, Dayan ordered Israeli
troops to attempt to capture the Golan Heights after
easier-than-expected battles against Egypt and Jordan _ the two
neighbors who have since made peace with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
