u w BC-DRUG-THREAT-HNS &LR;      12-15 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-THREAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S METHAMPHETAMINE PROBLEM PART OF NATIONWIDE SCOURGE, DRUG
CZAR SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign that Houston's illegal drug problem might
be getting worse, police have recently uncovered a new narcotics
threat, the leader of an anti-drug force said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican methamphetamine has infiltrated our community,'' said
Stan Furce, who heads a combined federal, state and local anti-drug
task force in Houston. ``It wasn't there last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Furce, a retired federal Drug Enforcement Administration agent,
did not say how much of the home-made, highly addictive drug is
being smuggled into the fourth-largest city in the nation. But he
said his agents will increase their efforts to stem its importation
as well as that of other illegal narcotics into Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The city's methamphetamine problem is part of a nationwide
scourge, said Barry McCaffrey, who heads the federal Office of
National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, widely referred to as the nation's drug czar, said
federal, state and local law enforcement must combat
methamphetamine trafficking to prevent a repeat of the crack
cocaine epidemic that infiltrated inner cities in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a minority problem,'' he said, noting that many
whites, especially women, use methamphetamine. ``Drug abuse in
America affects all populations.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey also released a report Wednesday that shows Houston
remains a major transportation hub for illegal-drug trafficking,
nine years after the U.S. government began a massive crackdown on
narcotics in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ground transportation is the favored method for smuggling drugs
into Houston, according to the report from McCaffrey's office. But
the Texas Gulf Coast, with its many ports and large volume of
container cargo, also is attractive to distributors, the office
stated.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the high volume of air traffic to Houston's two
airports makes that an inviting mode of transportation for
smugglers, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Furce and McCaffrey said they remain optimistic
that the flow of illegal drugs to and through Houston can be
stopped through a massive federal, state and local police effort.
</P>
<P>
   During the 12 months that ended Sept. 30, law-enforcement
officials in Houston seized 266,000 pounds of marijuana, 37,492
pounds of cocaine, 385 pounds of methamphetamine and 122 pounds of
heroin, Furce said.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston drug problem first attracted federal attention in
1990, when the then-fledgling federal drug-control office listed
the city as a High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area. In the ensuing
years, the list has grown from five to 31 areas and includes North,
South and West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Under a federal program, U.S. law enforcement officials have
joined state and local police in each of the high-intensity areas
to fight the illegal-drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   The city's anti-drug initiative focuses on stemming the flow of
illegal narcotics by keeping close watch on the area's ports,
airports, rail stations, bus terminals and truck stops, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston program also uses undercover officers to try to
catch drug dealers who attempt to make their ill-gotten gains
harder to detect by funneling, or ``laundering'', the money through
legitimate businesses, Furce said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, undercover agents attempt to infiltrate criminal
gangs that are dealing drugs in Houston, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
