<SLUG> BC-FBC-PIONEER-RB16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scott leads Tuskegee into Pioneer Bowl
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tuskegee running back Michael Scott entered last
year's Pioneer Bowl with a chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Scott rushed for more than 1,000 yards last season and led the
Golden Tigers to the SIAC Championship, but was left off the
all-conference first team. He took out his frustration with a
touchdown in Tuskegee's 23-9 defeat of Livingstone of the Central
Intercollegiate Athletic Association.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Scott makes another return to the Pioneer Bowl as
Tuskegee (9-2) will face Winston-Salem State (7-3) at the Georgia
Dome. This time, the 5-foot-7, 175-pound Scott is not only
all-conference after rushing for 1,346 yards, but he's the SIAC
offensive player of the year and perhaps the key figure in the
SIAC's push for the third victory in a row in this postseason
showdown between the Division II conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as (Scott) is able to run, he can make some things
happen and we're in the game,'' Tuskegee coach Rick Comegy said.
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem State, hoping to become the first CIAA team to
gain a Pioneer Bowl victory, is gearing up to stop Scott and
Tuskegee quarterback Aaron James, a 6-0, 180-pound sophomore who
was recruited by both Alabama and Auburn as high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are really looking forward to this opportunity in
the Dome,'' said Winston-Salem State coach Kermit Blount, whose
team went undefeated (7-0) in conference play. ``Our defense will
be the key. It's played well all year _ stopping people and
creating turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem's defensive unit, which held its first nine
opponents to 7.7 points a game before a regular-season-ending 25-23
loss to Grambling in San Diego on Nov. 13, features tackle Thomas
Washington. A 6-4, 305-pound senior, Washington had 58 tackles 10
games _ among them 18 hits for losses and 10 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   The playmakers in the Winston-Salem's secondary are junior
Willie Crite, who led the CIAA in interceptions with six, and
senior Deryl Wilson, the team's spirtual leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Tuskegee to be aggressive because that's the nature
of Coach Comegy,'' Blount said. ``Of course we'll be eyeballing
Scott because he's pretty good. But it's probably going to come
down to the team that makes the fewest mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
