<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NAVY-VIEQUES-1STLD-WR     12-15 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-VIEQUES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NAVY SAYS IKE BATTLE GROUP WILL BE READY FOR
 &HT;    GULF  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: SUBS 5thgraf, President Clinton, to add dropped words.
Pickup: Vice Adm. William Fallon.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD USS DWIGHT D. EISENHOWER _ The Navy battle fleet led by
this aircraft carrier wrapped up training for the Persian Gulf on
Wednesday, with senior commanders declaring that the armada will be
ready for possible combat in Iraq even though the force was denied
live-fire exercises on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders said they plan final live-fire combat training at
target ranges on the Italian island of Sardinia or in Scotland as
the battle group heads for patrol duties in the Persian Gulf to
enforce the allied ``no-fly'' zone over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The force of 15,000 sailors, air crews and Marines aboard 16
ships began returning to port for the Christmas season after
concluding sharply modified combat training along the Atlantic
Coast. The fleet begins departing for the Persian Gulf on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy suspended training at the 58-year-old Vieques target
range following a fatal bombing mishap in April that rallied Puerto
Rico's political leaders to demand cessation of bombardment and
Navy withdrawal from 22,000 acres of Navy-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello failed to
negotiate an agreement that would allow the bombing range to be
reopened in time for the Eisenhower battle group's Navy strike
pilots, naval gunnery crews and Marines to conduct the three-day
combat rehearsal that has been carried out by every departing
battle fleet for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Adm. William Fallon, commander of the Atlantic-based 2nd
Fleet, and Rear Adm. John Foley III, commander of the battle group,
said that adaptations in the forces' training during the two-week
exercise completed Wednesday _ coupled with additional live-fire
training for the battle group en route to the Persian Gulf _ should
enable the armada to be fully combat ready by the time it arrives
in the Persian Gulf in March.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon, a three-star admiral, said in a telephone interview
Wednesday that the Eisenhower battle group will set sail ``not in
the state of readiness that I want.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the additional training en route should make
the force ``ready to go'' when it reaches the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   He said the training shortfalls caused by the absence of Vieques
training included air-to-ground attack, naval gunfire support and
coordinated fire support for Marines' amphibious landing.
</P>
<P>
   But after the training en route, ``They are going to be in
pretty good shape _ very good shape. They got the foundation here.
What they'll need is the end game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, the two-star admiral who commands the battle group at
sea, said he was ``comfortable taking this battle group on
deployment to the Mediterranean and the Arabian Gulf'' as long as
his forces obtained the additional training that is planned at
either Cape Wrath, Scotland or Capoteulado, Sardinia.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the eight surface warships accompanying the Eisenhower
must each fire about 100 rounds of explosive, 5-inch ammunition to
requalify for their naval gunfire support mission. Foley said he
also hopes to provide pilots additional training for air-to-ground
attacks in Sardinia and possibly stage a combined, integrated air,
sea and amphibious assault including Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crown jewel question is, `Will we be ready to deploy?'''
Foley said. ``Yes, we will be ready to deploy. That last piece of
training will do that for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley spoke on the flag officers' bridge as he surveyed
warplanes landing and taking off from the Eisenhower's 4.5-acre
flight deck during simulated U.S. combat operations in a war
scenario involving the fictitious countries of Koronan, Kartunan
and Floridian laid out along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Vieques target range, an 899-acre site on the picturesque
island located between Puerto Rico and St. Croix, has been closed
since April 19 when a Marine pilot mistakenly targeted the range
observation post, killing Navy contract security guard David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, and injuring four civilian workers on the range.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have camped out on the target range ever since,
staging a peaceful civil disobedience protest that has thwarted
resumption of combat training.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon diverted the Eisenhower battle group from scheduled
training on Vieques on Dec. 3 and ordered it to carry out its final
pre-deployment training along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Carrier-based pilots from squadrons with colorful combat
monikers such as Knighthawks, Red Rippers and Pukin' Dogs bombed
target ranges in North Carolina and Florida with explosive and
non-explosive bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Marines stormed ashore at Camp Lejeune, N.C. ,
without rehearsing battlefield coordination with warplanes, which
were forced to strike targets at a bombing range some 30 miles
away. Surface warships used computers to simulate naval gunfire
from 5-inch deck guns to support the Marines' assault, without
firing a single shell off North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Capt. Richard D. Jaskot, commander of the six dozen
warplanes aboard the Eisenhower, said his pilots have dropped only
about 40 percent of the heavy bombs and live ordnance that they
dropped on Vieques and other ranges during pre-deployment training
aboard the aircraft carrier USS John C. Stennis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jaskot said between 30 and 40 of the air wing's strike pilots
are leaving for the Persian Gulf without the benefit of
unencumbered live-fire bombing experience that has been available
on Vieques. Pilots in the latest exercise were forced to fly
tortuous bombing runs from the Eisenhower through congested East
Coast commercial air corridors to reach target ranges in North
Carolina and Florida, a task requiring pilots to constantly switch
mental gears from combat to civilian aviation to combat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jaskot said, thanks to the additional training en route to
the Persian Gulf, his pilots should be ready for possible combat
operations when they arrive there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm in the mode where I'll take whatever training I
can get, wherever I can get it,'' said Jaskot. ``We'll be ready.
We'll do everything we can to be as ready as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Cdr. Steve Kreiser, 34, an FA-18 Hornet pilot based at
Oceana, Va., says training has been less demanding without Vieques
but his squadron will be ready nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good at making do and making it work,'' said Kreiser,
who flew combat missions against Iraq during the Persian Gulf War.
``Are we still good enough to go over and do the work? Yes. But I
don't think we're as good as we could be. That's probably something
you have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft carriers operating in the Persian Gulf enforce
Operation Southern Watch, an air patrol and surveillance operation
over southern Iraq designed to prevent operations by the remnants
of the Iraqi air force. Iraqi forces routinely harass and target
U.S. warplanes with anti-aircraft radar, often provoking U.S.
pilots to respond with anti-radar missiles or bombs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. warplanes, including carrier-based Navy aircraft and
land-based Air Force planes, have engaged Iraqi forces at least 65
times so far this year, according to Pentagon statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy admirals' assessment of the fleet's eventual readiness
for combat contrasted with earlier warnings by Navy officials.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clinton administration was looking for ways to design
training for the Navy without using Vieques, Fallon had warned that
realistic live-fire combat training on Vieques was essential.
</P>
<P>
   Closure of the range on Vieques and the ``lack of suitable
substitute training ranges is severely inhibiting the ability to
prepare our people without substantial increase in risk,'' Fallon
warned the Senate Armed Services Committee's panel on seapower on
Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said on Wednesday that he did not ``like the precedent''
of sending naval forces to sea without completing all of their
final combat training. ``To send people forward without this
training is just not in our best interest. We're putting additional
risk on our people that we shouldn't be putting on their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ,
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
