<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MCCARTNEY-LIVERPOOL-2     12-15 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTNEY-LIVERPOOL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCARTNEY AT THE CAVERN: BACK TO WHERE HE ONCE BELONGED  
(bl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVERPOOL, England _ No concert by any of the former Beatles has
created quite the anticipation that attended Sir Paul McCartney's
return Tuesday night to the Cavern Club here. He gave a solid,
energetic performance at a time when he is gradually returning to
the stage after the the death of his wife, Linda, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt part of the attraction was that only 300 people were
able to squeeze into the club to catch the show live, although the
star made provision for the spillover: about 12,000 people stood in
the cold to watch via closed-circuit television in Chavasse Park
nearby, and there was an Internet Webcast, although the lines
became overloaded after a reported 3 million viewers logged on.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, though, it was the hallowed place of the Cavern in
Beatles mythology that gave the show its allure, and lured the
singer back for a performance that most people present understood
was meant to promote his new album, ``Run Devil Run'' (Capitol).
</P>
<P>
   Although the Beatles tramped through dozens of Merseyside bars,
clubs, dance halls and auditoriums during their formative years,
the Cavern _ a converted underground vegetable warehouse with low
vaulted brick ceilings and a tiny stage _ was essentially their
headquarters from 1961 to 1963. They played nearly 300 lunchtime
and evening shows in the club, where they were first heard by Brian
Epstein, who became their manager and sold them to the world. ``A
Cellarful of Noise,'' the title of Epstein's 1964 autobiography, is
a reference to the legendarily crowded, sweaty, unventilated and
poorly lighted club.
</P>
<P>
   But it is only by a technicality that Tuesday night's 50-minute
concert can be said to have happened at the Cavern. It isn't just
that the Cavern as it exists now isn't the Cavern of the early
'60s: that was demolished in 1973 as part of a plan to run a rail
line through the site. When the city belatedly discovered the
Beatles' potential as a tourist lure, after John Lennon was killed
in 1980, the railway plan was scuttled and a replica of the Cavern
was built at roughly the same location, using about 15,000 bricks
from the original.
</P>
<P>
   The replica, which opened in 1984, is where McCartney gave a
news conference _ actually a 30-second statement, with no questions
allowed _ Tuesday afternoon. The concert itself took place in a
slightly larger, wider and decidedly more modern adjacent room.
Several reasons were offered: the acoustics of the brick Cavern are
terrible, and its layout _ three tunnels connected by archways,
with a stage at one end of the middle shaft _ would have prevented
two-thirds of those present from seeing much.
</P>
<P>
   Liverpool rock fans say the new room is now regarded as the
Cavern as well. But surely anyone who expected to hear McCartney
perform in at least a facsimile of the club that the Beatles called
home _ which is to say, virtually anyone who came any distance to
see the show _ was disappointed. If it wasn't to be on that stage,
it might as well have been anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the show had other attractions. In fine voice and
fronting a band that included the guitarists David Gilmour of Pink
Floyd, and Mick Green, formerly of Johnny Kidd and the Pirates
(another old Cavern band); Ian Paice, the drummer from Deep Purple;
Pete Wingfield, a session keyboardist; and Chris Hall, an
accordionist, McCartney played a blistering set devoted mostly to
the 1950s rock oldies on his new album. Included were songs made
famous by Elvis Presley (``All Shook Up'' and ``Party''), Gene
Vincent (``Blue Jean Bop'') and Big Joe Turner (``Honey Hush'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shake a Hand,'' first recorded by Little Richard, whose
histrionic vocal style McCartney has often impersonated, Green and
Wingfield took solos that were more extensive and enlivening than
on the recorded version. And McCartney's soulful rendering of ``No
Other Baby,'' an obscure song released by the Vipers in 1958, was a
bow to the more lyrical side of his own music, otherwise kept in
check on ``Run Devil Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Also notable were two songs that are not on the album: ``Twenty
Flight Rock,'' an Eddie Cochran song that was McCartney's showpiece
when he met Lennon in 1957, and the only Beatles song in the set,
``I Saw Her Standing There,'' certainly the hardest-rocking entry
in the early Lennon-McCartney songbook.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-song set, though less than half of what the musician has
played on his last few tours, was nevertheless his first real show
since Linda McCartney's death. Since then, he has made only a few
cameo appearances: he joined a jam session at the New York ceremony
at which he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame,
played a few songs at a musical memorial for his wife in London,
and offered six of his ``Run Devil Run'' oldies at a benefit
concert in Hollywood for People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, one of her causes.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Run Devil Run'' and the Cavern show are clearly part of
McCartney's finding his way back into his work after a period of
grieving. By recording mostly oldies (the three original songs are
in a vintage rock style), he has avoided the scrutiny of listeners
keen to know how he might deal with his wife's death in his music,
particularly since he has always said that his love songs of the
last 30 years were written with her in mind.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he was hardly idle in the year between Ms.
McCartney's death and the sessions for ``Run Devil Run.'' Last
winter he completed and released ``Wide Prairie,'' the album on
which his wife had been working, and promoted it in a 90-minute
appearance on the World Wide Web. He also finished ``Rushes,'' his
second ambient music album released under a nom de plume, the
Fireman. And he oversaw a gallery show of his paintings in Siegen,
Germany. He also released ``Working Classical,'' his third album of
symphonic music.
</P>
<P>
   Although several listeners said after the show that their
fantasy had been to hear McCartney in the old Cavern (at least the
replica), most took the change in stride. The event had, after all,
taken on a life of its own. Since the former Beatle announced the
concert two weeks ago on ``Parkinson,'' a popular BBC television
interview show, it had created something close to hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 300 available tickets, half were reserved for the press
and guests of the star, and the others were distributed to winners
of a lottery. When the entry forms were made available at HMV
record shops in Liverpool, London, Birmingham, Newcastle and
Glasgow last week, several thousand were snapped up within hours.
Reports quickly followed of offers of about $3,200, vacations and
sex for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Beatlemania is a renewable resource in Britain. The Beatles have
placed high in several Millennium polls here, including one
published in November by The Independent in which 600,000 voters
named them the best band of all time.
</P>
<P>
   In the same newspaper poll, ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club
Band'' was voted best album, with Lennon as the most influential
musician (McCartney came in fifth, after Elvis Presley, Michael
Jackson and Jimi Hendrix), and Lennon and McCartney, in that order,
topping the best songwriters list.
</P>
<P>
   And it was announced over the weekend that when the new
Millennium Dome opens in London on New Year's Eve, the first song
to be performed there will be a Lennon-McCartney collaboration,
either ``All You Need Is Love'' or ``Let It Be.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here in Liverpool, the Beatles are serious business. Visitors
can take bus tours of their childhood houses and schools as well as
the Strawberry Field orphanage and the roundabout on Penny Lane,
both commemorated in song, and at least a dozen other sites. Near
the Cavern, on the once tattered and newly spiffy Mathew Street,
virtually every shop, restaurant and pub has a Beatles-related
name. Stores offer Beatles records, books and all manner of
memorabilia, and there is a Beatles museum in Cavern Walks, a mall
near the club.
</P>
<P>
   The other Beatles put Liverpool behind them as soon as they
left, but McCartney still has family here, and he has kept his
contacts warm. He performed here with his post-Beatle band Wings,
and his first classical work, the ``Liverpool Oratorio,'' was given
its world premiere here in 1991. Around then he began pouring money
into transforming his old school, the Liverpool Institute High
School for Boys, into an arts college. It is now thriving as the
Liverpool Institute for Performing Arts, and its famous benefactor
visits it periodically. In 1997 the National Trust bought his
childhood home at 20 Forthlin Road, where he and Lennon
collaborated on their first songs, and restored it to its late-'50s
working-class not-quite-splendor before opening it as a museum,
even matching the original wallpaper and vintage telephone and
radio models.
</P>
<P>
   The official reason for McCartney's return to the Cavern was
that, as he put it, ``I can't think of a better way to rock out the
end of the century than with a rock 'n' roll party at the Cavern,
singing the songs of my heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the concert was an unabashed bid to get some attention for
the new album. He released the album in October, and it spent two
weeks on Billboard's Top 50 chart before beginning a quick descent.
The entry blank for tickets included questions that could only be
answered by reading the album's liner notes. And at his news
conference Tuesday afternoon, he could not have been plainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come back because I have a new rock 'n' roll album called
`Run Devil Run' and we're plugging it,'' he said. `This is where it
all began, and for me this is where the century is going to end,
with me playing rock 'n' roll, which, if you remember, the Beatles
before the Beatles was a fabulous little rock 'n' roll band. It was
rock that held us together for so long and made us so good, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing uneasiness among Beatles fans about the
degree to which McCartney leans on the Beatles to promote his own
work. The promotional campaigns for most of his recent albums have
involved announcements that have more to do with the Beatles than
with the work at hand.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Run Devil Run,'' McCartney has been invoking the Beatles
almost nonstop. The recording sessions, he said on an interview
disc packaged with early copies of the CD, were conducted much as
the early Beatles sessions were. Now the Cavern show _ at which he
played the violin-shaped Hofner bass that was his trademark in the
Beatles days _ is tugging on Fab Four memories.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, one can hardly blame him. His Beatles music was his
best work. In that sense, he let an opportunity slip by. Had he
played under the brick arch, the concert would have been a
Barnum-quality publicity stunt with a real touch of historical
poignancy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
