<SLUG> BC-HASBRO-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASBRO THROWS DICE TOWARD THE WEB WITH ON-LINE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Go2Net is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hasbro Inc., the Pawtucket, R.I., toy maker, announced a deal
with Seattle-based on-line company Go2Net Inc. Wednesday to create
a new service built around Hasbro's stable of popular games.
</P>
<P>
   The new site, to be called Games.com, will go on line by the
middle of next year. Hasbro has signed a three-year deal to have
Go2Net operate the service, and will pay Go2Net a $7.5 million fee.
Hasbro will also spend $60 million to create Internet versions of
its games.
</P>
<P>
   The site will feature on-line versions of Monopoly, Clue, and
Risk, and traditional card and board games. In addition, users of
Hasbro Interactive computer games, such as the popular flying game
Falcon 4.0, will be able to meet each other at the site and engage
in simulated combat over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games.com will be the ultimate on-line gaming experience as we
roll out the world's favorite games to the Internet,'' said Alan G.
Hassenfeld, the chairman and CEO of Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are a number of major Internet services devoted to
on-line gaming. Perhaps the best known is Microsoft's Gaming Zone,
which often attracts over 20,000 players at a time. America Online
Inc. also draws thousands of players to the gaming section of its
service.
</P>
<P>
   But Hassenfeld said most of today's on-line gamers either play
very simple games such as checkers or bingo, or complex and
difficult computer games such as Falcon 4.0 or Microsoft's Age of
Empires. Hassenfeld believes there's an untapped market for games
that fall somewhere in between _ moderately challenging, but easy
and fun to play.
</P>
<P>
   So Games.com will feature new Internet versions of popular
Hasbro board games Hassenfeld thinks will appeal to the casual
player. ``We probably have the most formidable library ever created
in gaming,'' Hassenfeld said. ``Probably 65 to 70 percent of the
games you can think of are in our portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with popular board games, Hasbro's 1998 acquisition of
Microprose gave the company a major presence in desktop
computer-game software. And this year, Hasbro acquired Wizards of
the Coast, makers of two wildly popular card game, Magic: The
Gathering and Pokemon. These acquisitions were made partly with an
eye to future on-line gaming opportunities. ``We have been going
out and buying up whatever content we thought would be valuable for
future playing,'' Hassenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was getting the game content onto the Internet.
For this, Hasbro has chosen Go2Net. The company runs a major Web
portal site and the Dogpile and MetaCrawler search services. But
Go2Net also has a gaming service called PlaySite, which lets users
play card, board and word games free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Go2Net service relies on Java software, which can run on
many different kinds of computers. Any visitor with a Java-capable
machine can play games at the site, whether he's using a Windows
computer, a Macintosh, or a machine running Linux.
</P>
<P>
   This is different from other on-line gaming sites that generally
rely on Windows software. For instance, Mac and Linux users can't
play games on the Microsoft Gaming Zone. But Hasbro plans to use
Java software to make most of the games at the site playable by any
visitor with any type of computer. Many of the games will be free,
while others will require payment of a subscription fee. Hasbro
also expects to profit from selling advertisements on the site, and
selling merchandise to visiting gamers. Al Verrecchia, Hasbro's
chief financial officer, predicted that Games.com would bring in
$15 million next year and up to $70 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   About 38 million Americans play games over the Internet, and
will generate revenue of $105 million this year, according to
Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro executives Wednesday cited a Jupiter report that claimed
Internet gaming would be a billion-dollar business by 2002. But
Jupiter analyst Billy Pidgeon said his firm will soon release
figures that cut this estimate in half, to $545 million. The change
reflects doubts users of video game consoles like the Sony
Playstation will use them to play on-line games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pidgeon thinks Hasbro's game site will appeal to millions
of casual Internet users who may welcome the chance for a quick
game of Clue or Risk. ``A lot of the people who may have drifted
away from gaming but have fond experiences may play those games,''
Pidgeon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
