<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ECU16-COX     12-15 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ECU16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong effort pulls ECU to Mobile Alabama Bowl
 &HT;    By Alan Wooten
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Sometimes it's hard to tell if the coaching
has developed the preparation or the effort has exceeded anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina has blocked nine kicks on the way to a 9-2 regular
season, and its case is the latter _ all effort. It has to be
because the Pirates, who face Texas Christian next Wednesday in the
inaugural Mobile Alabama Bowl, don't have a coach assigned to
kick-blocking duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do _ the defense,'' said senior linebacker Jeff Kerr when
asked who coaches the unit. ``It's a pride deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just line up in practice and go after the kicks. It's not
one of those things where it's got to be a coached unit. It's just
a pride unit.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Pirates, although not nearly as proficient as Virginia
Tech, have pride in their nine blocks. Some have been more pivotal
than others, but in the three games _ Miami, Southern Miss and N.C.
State _ considered largest on this year's schedule, the Pirates got
at least one each time out and won two of the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just nothing more than a contagious disease,'' said
eighth-year head coach Steve Logan. ``You do it once and you start
thinking you can do it again. And it works the other way, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a kick blocked, the other teams see that on film
and say, 'We can do that, too.' And it becomes a manic type
mentality and you start having a loss of confidence in yourself to
protect the kick. It cuts both ways. We've done fairly well. We had
a kick or two blocked with (Andrew) Bayes, but (Kevin) Miller
hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Miller had field goals blocked by Duke and Southern
Mississippi. Bayes had two punts blocked in the first four games,
and a field goal and two extra points blocked at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pirates' defense has thrived in not allowing opponents
to score, even on what would appear to be ``gimmes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people take that play off,'' Kerr said. ``When people
line up for the extra point, they take that play off and nobody
really goes hard, especially other defenses. But for us, it's one
of the most important plays of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you deny them one point, it's going to deny them two
somewhere else. That's a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest block might have been the first _ possibly for the
contagiousness Logan speaks of, but certainly for the timing.
</P>
<P>
   Then-No. 9 Miami was trying to pad a 23-10 lead against East
Carolina in the fourth game of the season. The Pirates had just
scored their first touchdown, and a swing of momentum was hanging
in the balance of Andy Crosland's 42-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkston, Ga., senior Tohma McMillan kept it with the Pirates
when he broke through the middle and swatted away the scoring
opportunity. East Carolina went on to win 27-23, completing a
second-half comeback from 20 points behind, one of the nation's
biggest upsets this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes went inside the ECU 20 in the last two minutes,
but having to go for a touchdown eventually led to four incomplete
passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tohma and Miami, we would have lost the game right there,''
said senior Norris McCleary, who also has two blocks. ``He won the
game for us. It's a play that people take off the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Dave) Huxtable always preaches to us to deny them
points. We go all out on that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior Devone Claybrooks and McMillan also have two each. The
other block was by junior Ty Hunt on an extra point at Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where everybody has figured out the weakness is up the
middle,'' Logan said. ``I don't care if you've got a 320-pound
guard next to your center. If you put two 300-pound linemen on that
guy, you're going to push him back. And that's what people are
beginning to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put 700 pounds of people on 300 pounds of people, 700
pounds wins. Then you get somebody behind them that can get into
that block lane. There is a responsibility to the kicker. They've
got to get it up. It's a chip-shot type deal, you've got to get up
under the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   McCleary blocked a field goal and McMillan an extra point during
a tight game with Southern Miss, but the Golden Eagles eventually
won anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But the last five _ two at Houston and three against rival N.C.
State _ were all significant.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars were hanging close but had five scoring
opportunities inside the ECU 30 where they got no points. Two of
them were blocks of Mike Clarke field goals by McCleary (31-yarder
in the second quarter) and Claybrooks (33-yarder in the third
quarter).
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates got their final bit of breathing room in a 19-3
victory on an interception return for touchdown in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Wolfpack, Kerr blocked the extra point when the
Wolfpack got on the board first. With the Pirates nursing a tenuous
14-6 lead, Claybrooks blocked a 20-yard field goal try by Kent
Passingham with 9:29 to go in the third quarter and Kerr blocked
Passingham's 21-yarder with 10:32 to go in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates eventually won 23-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an effort call,'' Logan said. ``If you're going to go
block a kick, somebody has to go give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Kerr added, ``It's no science; it's all effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
