<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS &LR;      12-15 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR OVERCOMES POPULIST CHALLENGE TO WIN 2ND
TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON,  
 &HT;     ZACHARY COILE and ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, who embraced the political
center to trounce the more liberal Tom Ammiano, heads into his
second term with a convincing mandate from San Francisco voters.
</P>
<P>
   A life-long Democrat, Brown became the first San Francisco mayor
to win re-election in more than a decade by attracting Republicans,
other conservatives and middle-of-the-road voters into a new,
broader coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Brown promised his new allies a voice in his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in political campaigns now for 35 years,'' said
Brown, who served in the state Assembly for 31 years and became one
of California's most powerful politicians before winning the
mayor's job four years ago. ``I've been in every kind of campaign
that you can think of. This one, however, absolutely takes the
cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown beat Ammiano, the president of the city's governing Board
of Supervisors, by a margin of 60 to 40 percent. Although both men
are Democrats, voters from the more conservative west side of San
Francisco turned out heavily in favor of Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Those voters supported either former Mayor Frank Jordan or
political consultant Clint Reilly in the Nov. 2 general election.
Ammiano rode a populist write-in campaign to a second-place
finished in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Brown knew during the six-week run-off campaign that he would
have to broaden his political base beyond the more liberal east
side he has long cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Republican votes, Brown ran strongly among
Asian-American voters, a growing force in the city's electoral
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, 65, also spent more than $3 million in the costliest
mayoral election in the city's history and was the beneficiary of
more than $1 million spent by outside groups.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ammiano spent less than $300,000 and received
little financial help from independent sources.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's victory defies the recent past of his administration,
which has overseen a glittering economy but chronic problems with
public transportation, the homeless and the rising cost of housing.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has been campaigning for the past 13 months, said he
ran the race of his life and it paid off: Nearly three of every
five voters decided to give him another term.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said at least part of his success was his
ability to portray Ammiano as a tax-and-spend politician who would
divide the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were successful in creating a bogeyman. It scared people,
and caused them to say that Willie Brown isn't so bad,'' said San
Francisco-based pollster David Binder.
</P>
<P>
   And if the landslide victory gave Brown a mandate, it is simply
to keep the economy humming.
</P>
<P>
   Also key to Brown's win was a well-honed, and well-financed
get-out-the-vote effort that relied heavily on help from organized
labor, the Democratic Party and downtown interests.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton pitched in, making phone calls to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, 58, wooed tenant activists, younger people voting for
the first time, homeless advocates and segments of the gay
community and rank-and-file labor. He said his candidacy should not
be looked at as a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not conceding the war. I am conceding the battle,''
Ammiano told his cheering supporters early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment that one seasoned political observers said
should be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next battle is going to be district elections,'' Binder
said, refer to the November 2000 elections for the Board of
Supervisors. ``Now Brown has to work to see whether he can hold on
to his board majority. The next question is whether Ammiano puts
together a viable opposition group to challenge Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ammiano's immediate future, he remains as board
president. He said the contentious run-off campaign would not
change his working relationship with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be no different from now,'' Ammiano said. ``He feels I
never should have been elected president. He's had an aversion to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
