<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-ART &LR; - &UR; NYT &LR;      12-15 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYS OF READING OTHERS' MAIL
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Book publishing is seldom ahead of the curve. But as we get
ready to pop into a millennium of snap and speed, worrying
ourselves toward a time of communication concocted for its
abruptness, publishers seem to have caught on that there is a
longing out there for authentic personal connection. So letters are
in, and it should be acknowledged that there are few things more
fun than reading someone else's mail.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably why there are two collections of letters on
The New York Times best-seller list, two more on its extended Web
site list and several other rich ones in the bookstores. Part of it
is publishers' sensing a millennium-ending bittersweetness about
the past as we speed toward the eventual. Part is that obviously
the pleasures of gossip, voyeurism and intimacy have never left us,
but the only way to get intimate details is in a letter or a
conversation, and conversation disappears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greatest Generation Speaks'' (Random House), Tom Brokaw's
letter-collection follow-up to his ``Greatest Generation'' (Random
House), will be No. 2 on The Times' hardcover nonfiction list on
Dec. 26, and former President George Bush's ``All the Best, George
Bush'' (Scribner) will be No. 16. On the extended list is Andy
Rooney's ``Sincerely, Andy Rooney'' (PublicAffairs) and ``Letters
of the Century'' (Dial Press), edited by Lisa Grunwald and Stephen
J. Adler. The latter is in some ways the most interesting of the
collections in that its 400 letters were written by ordinary
people, politicians, scientists and writers, and the book provides
a sort of writerly syllabus to the entire century.
</P>
<P>
   Irwyn Applebaum, president and publisher of Bantam Dell, of
which Dial Press is an imprint, said that it ``connects in the way
a literary novel might, even though it doesn't have that heft.'' He
went on: ``It's the ultimate bathroom reading.'' The same could be
said of the others.
</P>
<P>
   The range of the best sellers consists of history, family and
celebrity letters, but Viking has two collections of literary
letters in bookstores, ``Henry James: A Life in Letters,'' edited
by Philip Horne, and ``Jack Kerouac: Selected Letters 1957-1969,''
edited by Ann Charters. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. has published ``Selected
Letters of Dawn Powell,'' edited by Tim Page. There is also
``Beloved Sisters and Loving Friends'' (Alfred A. Knopf), letters
of two 19th-century black women, one a teacher, the other a
domestic servant.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail may have contributed to the apparent renewed interest in
the epistolary. For although e-mail is mostly quick and terse, and
usually about as grounded in substance as a cork on water, it does
consist of putting one word after another and marching them off.
And they can be saved, so the form just might be a muted beginning
of a return to literacy after generations when it had appeared that
personal communication had taken place only over the telephone.
People seem now to seek actuality, which might be one lesson of the
best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think this craving is not real, it should be noted
that Scribner has given Andrew Carroll a $500,000 advance for a
collection he is putting together of previously unpublished letters
from soldiers in all of the nation's wars. (Carroll is donating the
entire advance and his royalties to veterans' groups.)
</P>
<P>
   Where did all this one-to-one writing start? Cicero, a prolific
letter writer, likely wrote the first of what could be called the
literary (and gossip) letters. But the genre was fixed in form in
the salons of 17th-century France where les grandes dames wrote
letters that not only contained information pertinent to the
recipient but also news and gossip about their circles of friends,
and colorful descriptions of life of the aristocracy, including
juicy stuff going on in the court of Louis XIV. The letters were
written with wit, bite and drama; indeed, Proust referred to the
``Dostoyesvskyan style'' of ``The Letters of Mme. de Sevigne,''
whose correspondence was published in three volumes about 40 years
after her death in 1696. (A Paris street is named after her.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course writers and thinkers always corresponded. Voltaire
wrote thousands of letters; Raymond Chandler spent his insomniac
nights writing letters. Carroll, whose ``Letters of a Nation''
(Kodansha International, 1997) was a best seller, feels the current
appeal of letters comes ``at a time when things seem increasingly
dehumanized and technological and fast-paced, so there's a
nostalgia for tangible handwritten expressions of love and
friendship and support.'' He added, ``Letters are almost like
poems, requiring a lot of time to read and write.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Osnos, who is publishing Rooney's correspondence, said the
book had a first printing of 60,000 and a second of 40,000. He also
used the word nostalgia for what he described as a ``time when
people reflected.'' He said, ``I noticed that when I write e-mail,
I write them the way I used to receive cables, but I sign them
`best' or `regards.''' In essence, they are getting more letterish.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Grunwald, one of two editors of ``Letters of the Century,''
which has 100,000 copies in print, explains the appeal of such
books this way: ``There's nothing like reading other people's mail,
a privilege you don't usually get. You almost expect to find
yourself when you're reading. There's a voyeuristic sense that
gives you a kind of thrill; you find some personal stroke that
connects back to you. Thoughts. Feelings. You can browse.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the nice thing about a letter is its individuality.
Implicit in a letter not sent by e-mail _ whether you write it by
hand, type it or print it out on your computer _ is a suggestion to
the recipient, put in a leisurely way, that she is worth the time.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Jefferson, who has, as on so many subjects,
the last word on the unhurried appeal of the letter. He sent this
note to his secretary of state: ``We have not heard from our
ambassador to France for three years. If we do not hear from him
this year let us write him a letter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JOYCE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     12-15 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOYCE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CAST OF CHARACTERS': PUTTING `ULYSSES' ON FREUD'S COUCH TO
SEEK CLARITY
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of literary illusion, it has been remarked that the simplest
peasant tilling the soil in a field is more complex a character
than Prince Hamlet. Yet Paul Schwaber, a practicing psychoanalyst
and a professor of letters at Wesleyan University, seems to give
the lie to that observation in his brilliant work of criticism,
``The Cast of Characters: A Reading of `Ulysses.''' The title
refers to the various dramatis personae, to what Schwaber calls the
``tenacious presence'' of the people in Joyce's great novel (as in
``the cast of a lengthening shadow''), and finally to the
``singularity within variousness'' that the characters in
``Ulysses'' achieve (in the sense of cast as the form in which
something is created).
</P>
<P>
   By examining the actions, statements and thoughts of Stephen
Dedalus, Leopold and Molly Bloom and a few of the minor characters,
Schwaber reveals their rich inner lives, thereby making them seem
not only more complex than any peasant but also very nearly as
layered and contradictory as readers of ``Ulysses'' may seem to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Joyce's novel is perhaps uniquely suited to such
psychoanalytic treatment. Not much happens in the way of dramatic
action _ in 18 episodes a troubled young aspiring writer, Stephen,
and a middle-aged canvasser for advertisements, Leopold Bloom, go
their separate ways in Dublin and eventually cross paths _ but the
reader is given an incomparably intimate view of what goes on in
the characters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   As Schwaber reminds us: ```Ulysses,' by means of
characterizations that in context make real and credible the inner
lives of fictive persons, provides _ through artistic form and
aesthetic experience _ what scientific case studies cannot manage.
For it portrays minds in action: the specificity, rhythms, ideas,
associations, feelings and recurrences that distinguish and, in the
clinical situation, reveal distinct persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he concludes, ```Ulysses' allows us to test anew the
relevance of psychoanalytic observation and interpretation to
literary character as well as the adequacy of psychoanalysis itself
when brought to the bar of great literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwaber warms up by applying his technique to a few of the
characters in the 10th episode, ``The Wandering Rocks,'' which
Joyce intended as an entr'acte dividing the early, more
realistically written chapters from the later, more stylized
episodes, and which takes the form of 19 short segments tracing the
movements of various Dubliners around the city. Schwaber, by
showing how the novel ``grants epic attention to the psyches'' of
relatively minor characters, argues that it dovetails both ``with
Freud's psychoanalysis and, for all its elite demandingness of
readers, with a liberal and democratic politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Schwaber settles down to questioning what is on the
unconscious minds of the major characters, not only Stephen and the
Blooms but also the narrator himself, whom he sees as separate from
Joyce and as increasingly asserting his quirky individuality as the
novel progresses.
</P>
<P>
   By pulling together fragments of verbal evidence that are
scattered throughout the book and that repeatedly take on a
dramatic life of their own in the climactic ``Circe'' chapter,
where Stephen and Bloom visit Nighttown, Schwaber offers some
answers. To sum them up as they apply to the three major characters
would risk a caricature in the most extreme vein of psychobabble.
Suffice it to say that they try to explain why Stephen and Bloom
are drawn to each other and why Molly's concluding soliloquy is
less an affirmation of life and love (``and yes I said yes I will
Yes'') than an extended expression of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one makes of Schwaber's analyses, their greatest appeal
lies in the process by which he arrives at them. For in gathering
his evidence he takes familiar passages and turns them from
two-dimensional words on the page into three-dimensional psychic
portraits. More than anything else, ``The Cast of Characters'' is
worthwhile as an aid to reading ``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat less satisfying is Schwaber's analysis of the novel's
narrator, whom he sees as competing ``with his characters while
eccentrically identifying with them, all the while testing the
limits of his medium and the adequacy of his readers.'' While this
theory contrasts refreshingly with the traditional view that the
style of each episode was dictated in Joyce's mind by whatever
Homeric episode he was re-enacting, its results sometimes seem
faintly far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Schwaber proposes that the styles of the chapters
from ``The Oxen of the Sun'' to the end (Episodes 14 through 18)
reflect the narrator's being unhinged by the birth of Mina
Purefoy's child described in that chapter. ``Birthing defeats him.
He cannot match it, not with the best male help in the world.''
Schwaber continues: ``The self-awareness of `Ulysses,' apparent
from the first but showing increasing skepticism about words,
narratives and comprehensibility, would dovetail with the
flamboyant ventures of form and style by which the story continues
and the narrator shines _ silently shouting, `I am here,' afraid he
may not be. Whatever else they achieve, the vaunting styles may
elaborately deny a fear of nothingness _ as continual change may
confirm it.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems a very far cry from the Dedalean ideal of the artist
as the God of his creation, ``refined out of existence,
indifferent, paring his fingernails.'' Unless Joyce is so far
removed from his narrator that he could regard the hysteria with
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schwaber's analysis of Joyce's characters remains
germane. For instance, by touching on Stephen's unrecognized need
for an understanding older man, and on Bloom's dependence on his
ill-observed Jewishness to be such a man, he suggests why Stephen's
singing a strain of Christian anti-Semitism at the climax of the
Ithaca chapter constitutes such an act of ``staggering rudeness''
as to sunder any hope of friendship between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not this is an exercise in gratuitously putting
Joyce's characters on the couch, it takes us to the heart of the
drama of ``Ulysses'' and sheds light on one of the many things that
happen in this novel of infinitely complex meaning.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CAST OF CHARACTERS: A Reading of `Ulysses''
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Schwaber
</P>
<P>
   236 pages. Yale University Press. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
