<HEADER>
A0075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS16-COX     12-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Triangle fits neatly into Jackson's L.A. plan
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So far, dominating behemoth Shaquille O'Neal, brazenly
creative Kobe Bryant and prolific marksman Glen Rice have coexisted
wonderfully, like a trifecta of kindred spirits.
</P>
<P>
   And so, they've made the Los Angeles Lakers a juggernaut that's
something less than ``Showtime,'' but NBA's best road draw
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Tied with Portland for the best record in the league at 17-5,
the Lakers amble into Philips Arena tonight to take on the Hawks.
It is quite an accomplishment considering they've overcome:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bryant's broken hand that kept him sidelined at the start of
the season; they were 11-4 without him.
</P>
<P>
   _ O'Neal's horrible foul-shooting that at one time saw him at
less than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ And the constant trade rumors involving Rice that could have
affected his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly for first-year coach Phil Jackson, the team's
best three players have played together. The concern coming into
the season was if O'Neal could be content watching Bryant go
one-on-one and if Bryant could feel free to create if O'Neal's
begging for the ball in the low post and if Rice would feel left
out in either case.
</P>
<P>
   The answers have come back to be what Jackson envisioned _ or at
least hoped for. That is, the pecking order has been established
and accepted. The offense evolves around O'Neal, the 7-foot-1,
315-pound center who has performed like an MVP _ even with the
deplorable free-throw shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who returned last week from his stint on the injured
list, plays off O'Neal, finding the open spots on the floor.
Jackson's hyped triangle offense promotes spacing, and it allows
the 21-year-old Bryant room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   And because O'Neal and Bryant both command double-team
attention, it's important for Rice to have consistent movement away
from the ball, to the open areas on the floor. One of the best
spot-up shooters in the league, Rice plays off O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, the offense was stagnant, but this year, with all
the movement, it can work with me and Glen,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice added: ``Whoever says we can't play together, that's the
most ridiculous thing I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   It works because of a few reasons. One, Jackson is the coach,
and the six championship rings he earned with the Chicago Bulls and
Michael Jordan gave him the ultimate respect of the players. In
short, they listen, something that could not be said about previous
coaches Del Harris and interim Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it will be a problem,'' Jackson said of
ball-sharing. ``Everything I've heard about, I haven't seen yet.''
</P>
<P>
   What he has not seen too much of is the Lakers operating as they
did last year as a group of one-one-one players. Bryant, in
particular, tried O'Neal's patience by looking for his shot no
matter if O'Neal had low-post position or if Rice was open. It got
so bad that O'Neal had words with Bryant, and the word traveled
around the league that the young stars were at odds.
</P>
<P>
   If that was true then, it is not now. Bryant invited O'Neal to
his birthday party in the summer, and O'Neal attended. Since
Bryant's return from the injured list, he's had only brief flashes
of the doing-too-much antics that were troublesome last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put a lot of responsibility on (Bryant), because he's a
creative player and also a very talented player,'' Jackson said.
``He fully understands the role. But I think he doesn't quite grasp
the severity of the situation, the responsibility of the whole
situation. We'll have to ... wait until Kobe braces the season
enough to have that experience to handle those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation between O'Neal and Bryant has been smooth because
of the other reason they've been successful: O'Neal has been
utterly dominant, the axile of that offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have flourished despite a deficiency at power forward
because O'Neal, 27, has been mammoth inside. He's averaging a
league-leading 28 points and second-best 14.0 rebounds. Many times,
he is so imposing, it's frightening.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of the triangle offense allows O'Neal to catch the ball
in various positions and advantagous angles that allows the big man
to use his mobility and strength.
</P>
<P>
   And he's doing it better than anyone else. ``I look at him at 27
years old, and if he's not MVP of this league so far,'' executive
vice president Jerry West said, ``I don't think the award means
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a free agent after this season, means much to the Lakers'
plans. Since Jackson's arrival, the rumors persist that he'd be
dealt, particularly for Scottie Pippen. He's battled through them
in a way that pleases Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really congratulated him on keeping himself as
professional as possible during the period of time when there's so
much speculation on his availability, his being a part of a
trade,'' Jackson said. ``I've thought he's kept his head in the
game, he's kept his mood positive, he hasn't lost his
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither has the team. It's O'Neal first, everyone else
second. O'Neal said: ``I'm like Donna Summer. I work hard for the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
