<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-FLAG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING PROTECTS CHINESE FLAG IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE HOR-CHUNG LAU AND INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a ruling that calls into question the promise to
safeguard civil rights following Hong Kong's return to China, Hong
Kong's chief justice has declared the desecration of China's flag
offensive, and warned that ``freedom of expression is not an
absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   This former British colony and financial center was returned to
China in 1997 with written guarantees that it would retain its
capitalist economy and legal system for at least 50 years, and
enjoy autonomy on most issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling Wednesday by Hong Kong's highest court that free
speech here has limits _ as well as its Dec. 3 judgment that
China's parliament has the right to interpret local law and
overrule the court _ cast serious doubt on the willingness of Hong
Kong's top justices to defend the territory's independence from
mainland rule.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the landmark case was a controversial ``flag law''
banning the desecration of Hong Kong's flag and China's flag _ a
law enacted by temporary, Beijing-appointed local legislators just
hours after Hong Kong's handover to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, pro-democracy activists Ng Kung-Siu, 25, and
Lee King-yung, 19, were arrested for scrawling the Chinese
character for ``shame'' on the national flag to protest the
killings of hundreds, or perhaps thousands, of pro-democracy
demonstrators around Beijing's Tiananmen Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were originally fined about $250 and put on
probation for 12 months. But last May, an appeals court overturned
the ruling and backed the two activists, saying the flag law
violated personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government took the case back to court, and Chief
Justice Andrew Li ruled in the government's favor, saying that
mutilating the flag is an insult to the nation's ``dignity, unity
and territorial integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the US Supreme Court struck down state laws that
prohibited the desecration of the US flag. In the last four years,
conservative Republicans in the House of Representatives have
thrice passed a proposed constitutional amendment that would ban
flag burning or desecration, but twice so far, the Senate has
struck down the plan, and is expected to do so again.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, government lawyers hailed their local victory,
with Acting Solicitor General Robert Allcock asserting the decision
does not restrict freedom of speech, but rather bans a mode of
expression.
</P>
<P>
   But Law Yuk-kai, director of Hong Kong Human Rights Monitor,
called Ng and Lee ``criminals of conscience'' and said the ruling
had far-reaching and frightening implications. It is a serious
``blow to Hong Kong's democracy ... the second disappointing
judgment within a month,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court seems to be happy to be part of the state machinery,
instead of a guardian of liberty,'' Law complained. ``The truth is
that our courts can no longer adjudicate without being tainted by
fear and favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ng's frustrated lawyer, pro-democracy legislator Albert Ho, put
it even more simply: ``Certain rights that Hong Kong people used to
enjoy before the handover can now be taken away by law,'' Ho said
in disbelief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-15 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN CRITICS GIVE CLINTON CREDIT FOR DIPLOMATIC SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was plenty of tension and no handshake, but
for President Clinton, the mere presence of Syrian and Israeli
leaders in the Rose Garden Wednesday was enough to underscore
perhaps his greatest strength as a world leader: an uncanny ability
to bring feuding parties to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   From Northern Ireland to the Balkans and the Middle East,
Clinton has used his personal powers of persuasion to persuade
leaders of warring nations to sit down together. The re-opening of
talks between Israeli and Syria Wednesday, if successful, could end
up being a cirtical part of Clinton's foreign policy legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's critics concede that the president's personal
style is unusually conciliating, even healing, quality that aids
his efforts at diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the open question is whether the president's personal pleas
for reconciliation are compelling enough to bring lasting peace to
long-troubled regions. A number of foreign policy experts say no,
and contend that the Clinton administration has frequently failed
to do the necessary follow-through after an international crisis
disappears from the front pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what he does _ he loves to make it happen. And then he
forgets about it,'' said Bulent Aliriza, a policy analyst the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington. ``He
goes all over the world trying to solve whatever problem that ever
was,'' but he does not, and probably cannot, commit the time, and
US military might, to make it stick, Aliriza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's most comfortable in his role as negotiator. The
kind of foreign policy he feels most comfortable with is a classic
confrontation,'' said Richard Haass, a scholar with the Brookings
Institution and a former Bush administration official. ``It is
somewhat analagous to his upbringing in the South, during the civil
rights movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Clinton is less successful, Haass said, is in cases where
there is no immediate crisis to solve, when the question is how to
deal with powers like China whose interests conflict with US goals,
or the economic and political troubles in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good many foreign policy problems don't lend themselves to
`let's-split-the-difference,' '' Haass said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has often voiced a deep personal commitment to bringing
harmony to all sorts of ethnic and racial groups. He preaches a
message of tolerance at home and abroad, urging an end to ethnic
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, one of the most important aspects of the president's
foreign policy, as he sees it, is the United States as
peace-maker,'' said David Leavy, a spokesman for the National
Security Council. ``There's no doubt that the president's own
personality is ideally suited for this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, Clinton gets personally involved in seeking a
rapprochement, Leavy said, almost compulsively working the phones
to convince sparring leaders to meet. In the case of Syria and
Israel, the president made 31 phone calls since July to arrange a
sit-down between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, however, the president's
can't-we-all-just-get-along message often doesn't work, analysts
said, particularly in cases where the hatred runs long and deep.
</P>
<P>
   On his 11-day trip to Europe last month, the president made
appeals for harmony to the Serbs and the Albanians, the Russians
and the Chechens, the Greeks and the Turks, and the Armenians and
the Azeris. Weeks later, Russia is still pounding Chechnya with
bombs, violence between Albanians and Serbs continues in Kosovo,
and there has been no progress in the dispute between Armenia and
Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Doure, an analyst with the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, said Clinton, who campaigned on a domestic
agenda when he won the presidency in 1992, has had a series of
international crises dumped on his desk and has mistakenly used a
domestic approach to solve them.
</P>
<P>
   The message of racial and ethnic healing ``appeals to the
American sense,'' Doure said. ``That's what his instincts are.''
</P>
<P>
   One place Clinton appears to have had some success is in the
ongoing dispute between Turkey and Greece over the divided island
of Cyprus. Turkey was recently invited to begin negotiations to
join the European Union _ a move Clinton strongly supports _ and
the Turkish press has given great credit to Clinton for his
advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   No president is capable, however, of forcing peace when two
sides are committed to fighting, analysts agree. ``There's only so
much influence the United States has,'' Leavy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
