<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-BOARD16-COX     12-15 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BOARD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daft named interim director of Coca-Cola
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta and Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co.'s board has added another director,
Douglas Daft, the new president and chief operating officer who is
expected to become chairman and chief executive officer in April.
</P>
<P>
   Daft's appointment further solidifies his position at the soft
drink company following the surprise notice last week that Chairman
and CEO M. Douglas Ivester will retire in the spring. That decision
was made at a specially called board meeting Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, 56, will serve as an interim director until the annual
shareholders meeting in April, when shareholders will vote on
whether to name him to the board permanently.
</P>
<P>
   With his addition, the number of Coke directors increases to 13.
Ivester will continue as chairman and CEO until April and will
serve as a consultant to the company afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The board also elected four company officers to new positions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary P. Fayard was promoted to senior vice president and chief
financial officer, succeeding James Chestnut, who was promoted in
October to senior vice president of operations support.
</P>
<P>
   Fayard, who has been with Coca-Cola Co. since April 1994, was
vice president and controller until Dec. 1, when he became acting
chief financial officer. He previously was a partner at Ernst &AMP;
Young.
</P>
<P>
   _ Connie D. McDaniel will succeed Fayard as vice president and
controller. McDaniel was named acting controller on Dec. 1.
Previously she had been finance director for the company's German
division.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alexander R.C. ``Sandy'' Allan was named senior vice president
in charge of the Middle and Far East Group, a position Daft held
before a management reorganization in late October. Allan,
president of the Middle and Far East Group, has been with the
company for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark D. O'Shaughnessy, a 21-year veteran of the company, was
named vice president. O'Shaughnessy has been with the company's
McDonald's Group since September 1995, and he assumed
responsibility for worldwide McDonald's restaurant business in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock, meanwhile, continued to lose ground this week
in the aftermath of Ivester's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which had shown signs of a comeback since falling
sharply days after Ivester's initial announcement Dec. 6, was down
$1.62 1/2 at $59.81 1/4 just after trading stopped for the day on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   So far this week, the stock is down about 5 percent. It traded
as low as $59.37 1/2 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
