<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ As Syrian-Israeli peace talks begin
in Rose Garden ceremonies, Syrian foreign minister Farouk Sharaa
offers a tough lecture on Arab perspectives on the peace process.
By John Donnelly. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Washington) _ Bill Clinton's greatest foreign
policy strength is his ability to bring people to the table. But
some question whether he does the follow through. By Susan
Milligan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   HONKONG-FLAG (Hong Kong) _ Court rules it's illegal to desecrate
the Chinese flag in Hong Kong. By Joyce Hor-chung Lau and Indira A.
R. Lakshmanan. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INDEPENDENTS (Undated) _ Few voters rate the issue
itself very highly. But its symbolism, that Washington needs to be
wrested from the grasp of insiders, has become a powerful elixir
for many voters and has already helped lift John McCain and Bill
Bradley into contention for their party's presidential nominations.
By Walter V. Robinson. 1370 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-POLLUTION (Undated) _ Texas will consider politically
explosive ideas Thursday to control its worst-in-the-nation smog.
But, even as Gov. George W. Bush edges toward drastic steps, his
lobbyists are trying to take away one of the main tools federal
officials have in prodding the state to clean up its act: halting
highway projects. By Scott Allen. 1200 words. &UR;  &LR; (p and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-MOTHER (Peabody, Mass.) _ The story of Lydia Hanson, the
7-year-old who spent the night in the arms of her mother's corpse
when a teacher refused to believe her claim the parent had died,
has prompted discussion among educators. Although most teachers are
trained to detect signs of abuse, most are confused when clues of
other problems are more subtle. By Marcella Bombardieri. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-CRASHES (Undated) _ With consumers expected to spend
$6 billion to $10 billion on holiday shopping this year evidence
abounds that retail Web sites are crashing and that consumers are
being disappointed. E-commerce analysts assert that on-line
shopping is proceeding about the same as shopping in the real
world, however. By Chris Reidy. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   HASBRO-WEB (Undated) _ Hasbro Inc., the world's No. 2 toymaker,
will spend $60 million next year to make games such as Monopoly and
Risk available on a World Wide Web site that will be designed by
Go2Net Inc. By Hiawatha Bray. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BOARDS (Undated) _ Women are getting more seats in
America's board rooms, but there are still 271 companies out of the
biggest 1,000 without any women directors, according to a national
study. By Diane E. Lewis. 650 words.
</P>
