<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0092 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-GAYS-EDIT-AZR &LR;      12-15 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-EDIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL' POLICY DOESN'T WORK  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN WEDNESDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The military's ``Don't ask, don't tell'' policy is a
clumsy political dodge.
</P>
<P>
   Its failures are illustrated in ugly detail by the beating death
of a gay soldier at Fort Campbell, Ky., and the threatened
dismissal of Rep. Steve May, a valuable reserve officer right here
at home.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's characterization of the policy as ``out of
whack'' is a hollow understatement from a commander-in-chief who
refused to take command of this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's call for a re-examination of the policy is another
inadequate response. The president ought to follow his wife's
example and insist that gays be allowed to serve openly in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing them into shameful silence encourages abuse and results
in demonstrable injustices.
</P>
<P>
   Pfc. Barry Winchell, for example, was bludgeoned to death in his
Fort Campbell barracks after enduring months of the kind of taunts
and harassment that are supposedly forbidden by the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than protect a gay or lesbian soldier from harassment,
the policy protects the abuser. A soldier under homophobic attack
exposes himself or herself to forced dismissal from the service by
describing the reason for the taunts.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, as Winchell's case shows, such taunts can escalate
into deadly violence.
</P>
<P>
   Simple honesty also results in negative consequences under an
idiotic policy ostensibly designed to protect homosexual service
members.
</P>
<P>
   Reservist Lt. May was characterized as ``one of the finest young
officers`` in an Army performance review. Yet May faces discharge
because he spoke openly about his sexual orientation. He revealed
that he is gay in response to an anti-gay bill at the Arizona
Legislature, where he serves his constituents with the kind of
candor the military forbids.
</P>
<P>
   If he is forced from the service under the ``Don't ask, don't
tell'' policy, the nation will lose a highly trained and effective
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The policy has cost the military many such people. The Pentagon
reported that 1,145 people were discharged last year for being gay.
That's nearly twice the number than in the year the policy went
into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Britain is moving to end its ban on homosexuals in
the military. ``Someone's sexuality is a private matter,'' British
Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon said. A new code of conduct that's
expected to be drawn up next year will prohibit sexual activity by
on-duty personnel. Sexual orientation will no longer be a reason to
exclude people from the service.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of reasoned approach Clinton and the United
States military need to embrace. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
