<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LAND-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SHATTERED MIND': A NEW ROLE FOR THE FAMILY IN CASES OF
SCHIZOPHRENIA
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Schizophrenia produces headlines when a tormented mind produces
an act of violence that is often described as senseless or random.
But the violence has its reasons, churning in brains afflicted by
delusions of threat or persecution or superiority. ``The Shattered
Mind'' offers hope in new generations of psychotropic drugs that
cannot cure the ailment but can subdue its outbreaks while
scientists strive for a better understanding of the workings or
misworkings of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   By the estimate of Friday night's A&AMP;E documentary, some 2
million people have schizophrenia, about 10 percent of them
potentially violent. Most don't acknowledge their illness, and even
those who do may not take medication for it. Dire case histories
are featured, such as the young man, in and out of mental
institutions, on drugs and off, who ran a souvenir sword through
his mother's body, killing her. A psychiatrist suggests that he
struck out in what he believed was self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Although some psychiatrists maintain that schizophrenia should
be treated by therapy and that drugs can further damage the brain,
the program reports that ``the overwhelming majority of
psychiatrists'' now put their faith in medication. Instead of
tracing the illness to a patient's family in a traditional
psychoanalytic approach, they are more inclined to see the family
as an asset in making sure that the patient takes his medicine.
</P>
<P>
   First-person testimony to the delusions of schizophrenia come in
particular from a Long Island man who had a breakdown while an art
student. He tells of believing he was King Tut, throwing bottles
and phones through windows and spending time in jails and mental
wards. Now on medication, he can laugh about his past disturbances
and evidently confines his hallucinations to his canvases.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kurtis, the host of ``Investigative Reports,'' discerns a
``unique style'' shining through his work. Viewers may differ about
the quality of the paintings, but if they offer a channel for
emotions that once threatened his own life as well as others, even
connoisseurs are not likely to quibble.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS: The Shattered Mind'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Friday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Hill, producer; Debbie Morton, associate producer;
David Huizenga, audio director. Produced by Kurtis Productions for
A&AMP;E Network. Bill Kurtis, series executive producer and host;
Nicole Ewing, Kurtis Productions supervising producer; Mark
Augustine, editor. Edward Hersh, A&AMP;E executive producer; Laura
Fleury, supervising producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
