A0103 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-RIDEWITHDEVIL-TE     12-15 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RIDEWITHDEVIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEVIL' IS A MILD RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ang Lee's masterful earnestness can reduce even a wild hare of a
novel like ``The Ice Storm'' into a droll, and eventually mild,
comedy of manners. ``Ride With the Devil,'' about young men drawn
into the Civil War, is a peculiar movie, with components
reminiscent of other weird westerns. It has the bland stateliness
of old western TV series such as ``The Virginian,'' which tried to
bring an epic sensibility to the small screen. It's also similar to
early '70s attempts to recast the western after years of
sure-footed white-man imperialism on the plains, pictures such as
``Bad Company'' and ``The Culpepper Cattle Company.''
</P>
<P>
   As in those films, much of the action takes place on the
margins, with small, intense battles rather than bigger ones.
Although those do come eventually in this movie that feels like
it's the length of the Civil War, or at least that multihour Ken
Burns documentary on the same subject.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and screenwriter James Schamus try to bring a
larger-than-life feel to confusion and the need of young men to
find action. Tobey Maguire is the son of a German immigrant, who's
looked down upon. He falls in with the rebellious scion of a rich
family (Skeet Ulrich), and they begin a swing as ``bushwhackers''
in the service of the South. They're joined by a former slave
(Jeffrey Wright), who sides with them because a former owner freed
him. Lee's attempt at a unique perspective is honorable. ``Ride''
is full of the elements that could make for a potentially
fascinating big-screen depiction of a war that people generally
have no trouble sorting their feelings about.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's interest in class and its subtle distinctions _ seen in
his earlier films such as ``Storm'' and his sly comedy ``Eat Drink
Man Woman'' as well as ``Sense and Sensibility'' _ are in full view
in ``Devil.'' It's just that his stars, with the exception of
Wright's fluky honesty and a not-bad performance by Jewel as a
widow who's looking for a different kind of action _ aren't quite
up to the task. (Jewel brings to mind a whole tradition of singing
stars slipping into movies via westerns, lining her up alongside
Ricky Nelson.) Lee's staging of action is perfectly fine. But his
purview robs the film of urgency, which is the last thing a movie
out to dramatize confusion needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ride With the Devil'' is rated R for violence, adult language
and situations.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ride With the Devil'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Ang Lee
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tobey Maguire, Skeet Ulrich, Jewel
</P>
<P>
   Length: 135 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
