<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING WITH THE DEMISE OF SANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Dec. 23)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Golden Book encyclopedia was spread open on the floor of my
son's bedroom. I picked it up and smiled as I read the entry about
Santa, the ``spirit'' of Yuletide. I carried the volume downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading up on Christmas, huh?'' I asked my 8-year-old as he
built a Lego scape.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you ... oh, I left it open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out anything interesting about Santa?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, Adam, I know that you know,'' I told him. ``I looked
it up in the Golden Book encyclopedia, too, when I was just about
your age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known since you told me about the Tooth Fairy,'' he said
indignantly. ``They're all kind of the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he asked The Question.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if I believe in the SPIRIT of Santa, do I still get
presents?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. Especially since you have a little sister,'' I said.
``You keep Santa alive for her, he'll still deliver to you, too.
Deal?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of Santa. I remember the almost physical pang of
finding out as a child that magic and reality didn't really
coexist, after all. Reality won out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did I wholeheartedly embrace Santa, the Easter Bunny
and the Tooth Fairy, I kept trying to find the right top hat to put
on my snowmen to make them dance and sing.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on my grandmother. Each summer of my childhood, she
convinced me that an elf lived in the top drawer of her dresser.
Every time we went on a trip, the drawer was empty, but when we'd
come back, a small gift for me was always tucked inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you ever notice that she would always say she had
forgotten her purse, or left a light on, and had to go back inside
for a minute?'' my mother asked me years later, when I was trying
to figure out the ruse.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I was a sucker. But when I had kids, I was all for trying
to give them that same sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   I know there's a group of dissenters out there who think the
whole Santa thing goes too far and is a cruel deception, teaching
children only that parents tell tales and can't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm firmly in the New York Sun's camp on this one: ``Santa
exists as certainly as love and generosity and devotion exist. ...
Alas! How dreary would be the world if there were no Santa Claus!''
</P>
<P>
   On the night Adam asked about the Tooth Fairy, he wanted a
straight answer. So his dad and I sat on the bed and gave him one.
He bravely shrugged it off. But not before Jim and I watched his
face fall before his cavalier recovery.
</P>
<P>
   He did, in that painful moment, realize all.
</P>
<P>
   So is it worth it? Setting your children up for disillusion and
heartbreak? All I know is, given the choice, I would rather have
believed than not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'd go back to believing in an instant, given a snowy
night and a distant jingle.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, we decked the halls. Tomorrow, we'll sprinkle the
cookies. And tonight, we read: ``... he sprang to his sleigh, to
his team gave a whistle, and away they all flew like the down of a
thistle. But I heard him exclaim ere he drove out of sight, Happy
Christmas to all, and to all a good-night.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
