<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0130 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-OBIT-LEIGH-ART-NYT &LR;      12-15 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LEIGH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS LEIGH, 92, THE MAN WHO LIT UP NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ala., Ariz., Calif., N.J., N.C., Ohio, Singapore)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Douglas Leigh, the dazzling impresario of electrical
splendor who festooned Broadway with miles of electrical signs, a
gargantuan steaming coffee pot and the celebrated giant Camel sign
that puffed real smoke, died Tuesday in a Manhattan hospital. He
was 92 and lived in Manhattan and Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh was also the man who lit up the city's Manhattan's
skyscrapers, beginning with the Empire State Building in 1976, and
who made the city's fountains flow red, white and blue for that
year's Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh, an Alabama native, hit town at 28 in a second-hand Ford
with $9 in his pocket and parlayed a soft-spoken sales ability and
a flair for the fabulous into the multi-million-dollar business of
designing and erecting breathtaking signs. The A&AMP;P coffee cup, 25
feet-high and steaming, was his. So was the Old Gold sign with its
4,100 bulbs. The Bromo-seltzer sign with actual effervescent
action? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh gave the Great White Way its legendary Camel smoke ring
sign, which ran for 26 years and expanded to 22 additional cities.
He created the Super Suds detergent sign with 3,000 large
``floating'' soap bubbles per minute. The 120-foot Pepsi Cola
waterfall was indisputably his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an idea man, a concept guy,'' he said last year, still
very much on the job at Donald Trump's building at 40 Wall Stt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Empire State Building, Leigh splashed
dazzling lights at the summits of other skyscrapers, including
Citicorp, the Helmsley and Crown Buildings and the Waldorf-Astoria
Hotel. Leigh became as dominant in the new business of lighting
buildings as he had been in designing spectacular signs.
</P>
<P>
   His life was an exuberant exercise in creative
attention-getting. He owned and operated blimps on both the East
and West Coasts to advertise Wonder Bread, Mobil Oil and other
products. In the 1960s, he owned 1 Times Square, the building where
the New Year's Eve ball is dropped. He stripped off the marble and
envisioned the building as what it has now emphatically become, a
showcase for signage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, he served as official decorator for the Democratic
convention, causing Manhattan's fountains to flow in red, white and
blue, among other effects. In 1984, he installed a 2 1/2-story
snowflake with 3,000 lights above Fifth Avenue at 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   His work extended beyond New York, and in 1987, he was hired by
Cincinnati to develop a master plan for lighting that city. He also
dealt with such seemingly prosaic, but surely profitable jobs as
for years handling the advertising on New York City buses.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh was the spiritual pioneer of today's Times Square, where
giant neon displays are required on new buildings. It was he who
bridged the gap from the Broadway of the 1880s, an industrial area
of blacksmiths and carriage factories, and the 1930s when signs
became considerably more than mere add-ons to existing buildings.
</P>
<P>
   By 1936, City Bank Farmers Trust Co. built a two-story building
with a sign that more than doubled the height of the structure. The
huge sign, the work of designer and artist Dorothy Shepard,
featured a fish blowing bubbles advertising Wrigley's Spearmint
gum. The nightclub in the building lasted only a few years, and in
1940 Bond Clothes took over much of the space.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Leigh persuaded Bond to put up a $350,000
montage rising 90 feet above the entire length of the store on
Broadway from 44th to 45th Street. At the base of the Bond sign was
an electric news zipper, about five feet high, running along the
entire facade. In Leigh's design, twin 50-foot-high figures, one
male and one female, flanked a central waterfall 27 feet high and
120 feet long. Strands of electric lights seems to clothe the
chunky classical figures at night, but by day they appeared nude.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had yet equaled the colossal exhortations of Douglas
Leigh's 1948 Bond clothing sign,'' Christopher Gray wrote in the
Times in 1997. ``It lasted only six years, but some fragments still
peep out from under the latest advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh was born in Anniston, Ala., and began selling things as a
youth. He graduated from the University of Florida where he bought
the entire advertising space in the year book for $2,000, on
credit. He then sold the same space for $7,000, making a profit of
$5,000. He immediately dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in New York in the early 1930s, and in 1933 scored
his first success. He secured the right to put up a sign at the
intersection of Fordham Road and Crotona Avenue in the Bronx. He
then persuaded the St. Moritz Hotel to put up a billboard there. He
got $50 a month, enough to eat at the Automat, as well as
stationery with the hotel's prestigious central Park South address.
</P>
<P>
   Later in 1933, he came up with the idea for the steaming coffee
cup, 15 feet wide, at the southeast corner of 47th Street and
Seventh Avenue. He began to create a comfortable niche. Within a
few years he had thrown switches in Times Square to illuminate a
blinking penguin for Kool cigarettes, a clown tossing quoits in the
shape of the Ballantine ale logo, and an animated cartoon for Old
Gold cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1941, E.J. Kahn Jr. profiled him in The New Yorker and
said he had been responsible in the preceding seven years for 32
large signs with more than 75 bulbs. ``If New York is ever
thoroughly blacked out,'' Kahn said in reference to the war in
Europe, ``no man will take it harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, wartime blackouts began, but they only stimulated
Leigh's imagination. He did not need lights to develop the Camel
billboard at the southeast corner of 44th Street and Broadway,
which puffed out 5-foot-wide rings of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh was a smallish, soft-spoken sort who said, ``yes, sir''
and ``no, sir'' to business executives and laborers alike. The New
Yorker described him as a ``Princeton freshman.'' He dressed in
tweeds and bow ties and wore a fresh boutonniere of cornflowers.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife Elsie; two daughters, Lucinda Leigh
of Phoenix, and Heidi Duke of San Diego; four stepchildren, Amanda
Borghese of Short Hills, N.J.; Pidgie Chapman of Pinehurst, N.C.;
Prudence Blair of Summit, N.J.; and Winthrop Lewis of Singapore,
and eight grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   His visions were legendary. In 1944, he told The New York Times
that he foresaw a postwar Times Square full of three-dimensional
signs in softer colors; a colossal, translucent glass of orange
juice and a huge bottle of perfume with scent puffed out on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   He saw wind machines blowing trees and flags, searchlights
playing on blimps, artificial snow and fog; the smells of coffee,
cocoa and beer, even live giraffes and other animals. Times Square
would be a spectacular performance event in the service of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   He also thought the Empire State building would make a dandy
glowing cigarette for Lucky Strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
