<SLUG> BC-MA-TROOPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOPERS' SUIT CHARGES AGE DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Eight Massachusetts State Police troopers filed a
federal discrimination suit against the state Wednesday, claiming
they were continually bypassed for promotion because of their age.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, now ranging in age from 44 to 61, were members of
the Metropolitan District Commission force who were on a waiting
list for promotion to lieutenant in 1992 when the Metropolitan,
Capitol, and Registry police were consolidated under the State
Police.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were on the list to be promoted and lost out on
that,'' said lawyer Cornelius J. Sullivan, who filed the suit on
the heels of a ruling by a federal judge that struck down a state
law requiring troopers to retire at 55. US District Judge A. David
Mazzone ruled in June 1998 that forcing someone to retire solely
based on age violated the federal Age Discrimination in Employment
Act.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling settled a lawsuit filed in December 1992 by former
Metropolitan, Registry, and Capitol police challenging the
mandatory retirement age established when the forces were
consolidated. Previously, State Police had been forced to retire at
50, while officers in the other departments could work until 65.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sullivan says the state ``demonstrated an animus against
those over 50,'' which was further evidenced by its failure to
promote the older officers. He is seeking to have the men promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has rejected the
troopers' claims that they weren't promoted because of their age,
noting that seven of the eight in the suit had scored below 70 on
the written portion of the lieutenant's exam. State law prohibits
the promotion to lieutenant of any State Police officer who scores
less than 70 on the written test.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the troopers scored differently on various tests
but had all passed the lieutenant's exam and were on a waiting list
for promotion before the consolidation of the police forces.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by Troopers Jerome Gately, 61; Richard A.
Donovan, 51; Peter J. Perez, 52; David F. Ford,44; Thomas Ryan, 53;
Edward Lee, 54; Carl Casagrande, 52; and Greg D'Aiuto, 52.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
