A0145 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-     12-15 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 19,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: GREAT-GATSBY-OPERA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Donald Trump builds buildings. I
write about them. So far, he hasn't given me an occasion to write
glowingly about his architectural projects. It would be great if
this changed. I'm not hopeful. But I love the color,
contentiousness and comedy Trump brings to the contemporary urban
scene. Adrian Stokes, the British art critic, once wrote that
``Architecture is limited to forms without events.'' I disagree. As
a social, public and urban art form, architecture can't be
separated from the events that buildings contain, shape and
provoke. Architecture criticism, in written appraisals or the
comments of sidewalk superintendents, qualifies as an event in this
sense. Even when criticism is negative, it is part of the fabric
that holds a great city together. I don't hate Trump's buildings,
but even if that were the case, I would still see them as a
challenge to examine my preferences in relation to his. By Herbert
Muschamp. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOCUMENTARY-FILMS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ The Fantasy building has
been the birthplace of cinematic flights of fancy _ to the Sahara,
to the concert halls of 18th-century Vienna, to the Amazon jungle.
But this seven-story glass and concrete structure, also houses a
different breed of filmmaker. For more than a decade, the film
producer, Saul Zaentz has offered low-cost space to local
documentarians, making his building a center for San Francisco's
growing, well-regarded documentary community. By Edward Wong.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SNOW-ON-CEDARS-FILM (Hollywood) _ ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' is
a complex story that spreads across many years and while it is, at
heart, a love story, it also contains elements of epic historical
importance, like the incarceration of Japanese-Americans in
detention camps during World War II. And there are three main plot
threads, according to Scott Hicks, the film's director. A murder
mystery (the Japanese-American fisherman is accused of murdering a
white fisherman, with whose family he had been embroiled in a
soured land deal), a love story (between Ishmael, a war veteran and
editor of the island's newspaper, and the accused fisherman's wife)
and the story of how the war had affected each of them and their
community. The film opens Wednesday. By Rick Lyman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SHOAH-VIDEO (Undated) _ Time doesn't fly in Claude Lanzmann's
monumental film; it melts. A chronicle of the Holocaust, ``Shoah''
(``annihilation'' in Hebrew) proceeds deliberately, inexorably, for
9 hours and 23 minutes, set always to the click-clack of boxcars
that carried Jews to the gas chambers and crematoriums. Released in
theaters in 1985 and now back on video after seven years out of
distribution, the documentary focuses primarily on the death camps
in the Polish towns of Treblinka and Auschwitz. By Peter M.
Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAMLET-THEATER (New York) _ What may be the very last new
``Hamlet'' of Shakespeare's millennium opens at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater Sunday night _ boards that many melancholy Danes
have trod before. This time, Liev Schreiber wears the customary
suits of solemn black, under the direction of the Romanian-born
Andrei Serban. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (New York) _ Reviews of ``Marie Christine'' by
John LaChiusa at the Vivian Beaumont Theater and Suzan-Lori Parks's
``In the Blood'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater. By Vincent
Canby. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARSONS-DANCE (New York) _ As the choreographer for ``Times
Square 2000,'' Manhattan's round-the-clock salute to the
millennium, David Parsons is putting the finishing touches on
nearly a dozen new dances by the end of the month. Colleagues say
he has kept his part of the program on track _ despite a trip to
the hospital to be treated for dehydration _ with shrewd planning,
a lively imagination and undisguised pragmatism. The outdoor
celebration will start around sunrise on Dec. 31 and continue for
24 hours. By Christopher Reardon. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LANGUAGE (subslug) (Undated) _ A musical observer a
century ago could have looked around at a number of living
composers whose works were being regularly performed wherever
Western classical music was known. And most of those composers were
relatively young. We live in a different world. Most of the
composers who are widely admired today are over 50, and some are
over 90. Once John Cage had produced his silent piece ``4' 33'',''
in 1952, there was perhaps nowhere to go but sideways. The only
progress made after that was in electronic music and in the
recovery of large form, whether by erstwhile Serialists, such as
Pierre Boulez, or by the new Minimalists, such as Steve Reich. And
even in these areas, not much has changed in the last 20 years. By
Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-CITY-CHRISTMAS (New York) _ Once my critical colleagues
have dispatched themselves to various ceremonies of carols, the
``Messiah'' of the day or the latest ``Christmas Oratorio,'' I
check to see that no one is looking and make a beeline for Radio
City Music Hall. I like the ``Radio City Christmas Spectacular''
because it tells me how the season is progressing. I like a Santa
not afraid to loosen his hips to a boogie beat. The Rockettes make
my heart beat fast. There is in this year's show a dance sequence
of multiplying Santas: so many that by the end they barely fit
onstage. It's comforting to know that there will be enough Kriss
Kringles available for every borough and congressional district in
New York City, with some left over for the immediate suburbs. By
Bernard Holland. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-MUSIC (Undated) _ Country music almost by definition
exists in a convoluted, almost duplicitous relationship with its
past. Inherently reactionary _ that's the whole point _ country on
the surface is all about roots, constancy, shared references both
in terms of the music and the lyrics. But, from its beginnings as a
commercial force country has always been an intensely marketed
amalagm of old and new, real and contrived that was willed into
existence in the 1920s by the modernizing influences of radio, new
recording technology and urbanism. By Peter Applebome. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-DECO-ANTIQUES (New York) _ As stocks soared this year, the
New York market for antiques, collectibles and 20th century objects
eclipsed even the levels reached in the boom years of the 1980s.
Auctions, fairs and exhibitions at museums and galleries attracted
new collectors and dealers as well as a new art fair to Manhattan,
heightening the awareness of the decorative arts, especially in the
Art Deco style. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-ARCHITECT (Paris) _ Having designed 30 airport terminals
around the world, Paul Andreu can hardly escape being known as an
airport architect. Not that there is anything amiss with that.
Airports today are what railroad stations were at the turn of the
century, gateways that every year provide tens of millions of
travelers with their first and last impressions of a city. And if
Andreu keeps being invited to build airports, it is because this
engineer-turned-architect enjoys a worldwide reputation for
designing visually striking and passenger-friendly terminals. By
Alan Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TOMASELLI-ART (New York) _ The painter, Fred Tomaselli, uses
cutout photos of birds, flowers, insects and pictures of lips and
eyeballs clipped from fashion magazines as materials for his
collages, which are sealed in several coats of resin. Pictorially
the work veers between the figurative and the abstract, but the
result is usually the same: eye-popping imagery that is dense,
decorative and witty. The latest and largest example, ``Gravity's
Rainbow (Large),'' is now on view at the Whitney Museum of Art at
Philip Morris on 42nd Street through Jan. 7. By William Harris.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-AMERICAN-DAUGHTER (Los Angeles) _ The scene is a brunch in an
elegant living room in Georgetown, the upper-class Washington
enclave. Christine Lahti and a half-dozen actresses and actors are
filming ``An American Daughter'' in a home in the upscale Hancock
Park section of Los Angeles. Washington _ the town's hypocrisies,
its self-important journalists and snarky politics _ serves not
only as the setting for the Wendy Wasserstein
comedy-drama-turned-television-movie but the catalyst for the
unique personal and professional pitfalls that face women in and
around government. The drama, which explores the corrosive effects
of a private life turned public before the television cameras, is
now completing production in Los Angeles, and is set to be shown
next spring over Lifetime. By Bernard Weinraub. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Travel: Surfing (and skiing) the net.
By L.R. Shannon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Telling time, from Stonehenge on;
Mexico backs down on car deposits; To visit site on Jordan call
first, be cautious; Paris's toy-filled department store windows.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Question and answers on travel. This
week: Native culture in Vancouver; Children`s literary sites; Baja
whale-watching. By Suzanne MacNeille. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ When a child travels alone. By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
