u i BC-CHECHNYA-GROZNY-BOS &LR;      12-15 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-GROZNY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 RUSSIAN SOLDIERS REPORTED DEAD IN GROZNY FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the worst setback in Russia's three-month campaign
in the Caucasus, as many as 100 Russian soldiers were reported
killed in heavy street fighting in Chechnya's capital Grozny
Wednesday night as separatist fighters beat back an assault by
federal tanks and troops into the city.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Grozny said rebel fighters surrounded an armored
column that had driven deep into the city center.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Russian armored forces had tried to move
into central Grozny since federal troops encircled the city last
month in an effort to drive out an estimated 6,000 rebel fighters.
The attack came as a senior commander predicted that the city would
fall within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's fighting indicated that the Russian commanders had
seriously underestimated the Chechens' ability to fight back,
repeating a mistake that dogged them throughout Moscow's 1994-1996
campaign that failed to defeat the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Russian officials have consistently ruled out a major
ground operation in Grozny, fearing the kind of heavy loss of life
which accompanied their troops' entry into captial at the start of
the last war.
</P>
<P>
   But reports Wednesday, which did not clarify the size of the
Russian offensive, nonetheless described a scene stunningly
reminiscent of the disastrous New Year's Eve assault on Grozny five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, seven Russian tanks and eight armored personnel
carriers managed to reach a square about a mile from the center of
Grozny. The square, nicknamed ``Minutka'' for a fast-food cafe that
was destroyed early in the last war, provided ample cover for the
ambushers and a clear shot at the tanks in a large, open rotary
surrounded by the ruins of concrete apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   News reports suggested that the Russian troops had wandered into
Minutka by mistake and were trapped there, making it easier for
some 2,000 rebel fighters in the square to attack the convoy with
their hand-held anti-tank weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two sides fought a pitched battle lasting some three hours
and I saw more than 100 bodies of dead Russian soldiers after
arriving at the scene,'' wrote Reuters reporter Maria Eismont, a
veteran Russian war correspondent who covered the last war in
Chechnya. Other reports described light rebel casualties, and as
many as 15 Russian armored vehicles carriers ablaze in the center.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene Russian commanders had vowed not to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   But five years later, the campaign in Chechnya is commanded by
many of the same generals who fought the previous war. The Russian
commanders claim to have learned the lesson of the last war, and
had avoided contact on the ground while bombing Chechen positions
from afar.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Russian advance through the lowlands,
which has taken more than two months and cost the lives of at least
400 soldiers despite tactics designed to avoid casualties, has been
portrayed as a great victory by the military, politicians and much
of the Russian press.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities have prevented most journalists from
entering Chechnya, and this week closed off the military staging
area in Mozdok to most foreign correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Russian forces kept up their round-the-clock shelling
of Grozny, where an estimated 10,000 to 45,000 hungry, freezing
civilians are trapped by the fighting. An Associated Press reporter
described plumes of black smoke rising over the city's devastated
center as salvos of Russian shells hit home. Footage from the city
showed women civilians running to hide behind walls.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has backed away from an ultimatum that it would kill
everyone left in the city after last Saturday, vowing instead to
allow civilians to leave through two ``safe corridors'' it has set
up north and south of the city. Until Wednesday, most of the heavy
ground fighting had been in the east. But only some 2,500 civilians
have dared brave the constant barrage of Russian shells and aerial
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, a top military official predicted that Grozny would
be taken in ``a matter of days.'' General Valery Manilov, first
deputy chief of the Russian General Staff, said Russian forces now
control 60 percent of Chechnya, and would take two to three months
to defeat the estimated 12,000 to 15,000 rebels throughout the
breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts like Alexander Golz of the news magazine Itogi
have been more circumspect, cautioning that the army would have to
eventually fight the rebels on the ground in Grozny. While few
analysts believe the outnumbered and outgunned rebels can hold out
in Grozny for long against the Russians' 100,000-member force, they
say Russia's command of the skies and long-range artillery would be
less of a factor in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollbaek, in the Caucasus as
head of the Organization of for Security and Cooperation in Europe,
called for talks between Russia and rebel leader Aslan Maskhadov.
But Moscow rejected the idea of talks with Maskhadov, who Russian
leaders say does not control rival rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, just hours before the unsuccessful advance into the
center, Manilov said that ``no massive strikes, no storms, no
assaults will take place ... as long as there is a single civilian
in Grozny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
