<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0178 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-FIMM_ANNA&AMP;THEKING-TEX     12-15 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIMM_ANNA&AMP;THEKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANNA' ALMOST REIGNS SUPREME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics are calling 1999 a great year for movies, largely
because of a string of films _ mostly fall releases _ made by
directors willing to break or reinvent the rules, and supported by
studios willing to gamble on those directors.
</P>
<P>
   But something remains to be said for good, old-fashioned,
traditional filmmaking, and ``Anna and the King'' delivers on that
level. It's a qualified success, the type of movie whose virtues
outnumber its flaws. But everyone involved appears to be aiming for
a romantic epic on the level of ``Titanic'' _ and ``Titanic'' had
more flaws.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get past whatever preconceptions you have about the
story, which has been filmed three times previously (including an
awful animated ``King and I'' this year). It's a chestnut, this
tale about widowed, indepedent-minded British schoolteacher Anna
Leonowens and her experiences in 1860s Siam, where she agrees to
educate the king's 68 children (by 26 wives). As in all the other
versions, cultures clash _ and romantic sparks fly.
</P>
<P>
   For the '90s, we've been given an even more forward-thinking
Anna and an even more progressive king. It was wise to cast Hong
Kong star Chow Yun-Fat as the king, and Chow is the movie's most
pleasant surprise. Best-known for action roles, Chow uses a mix of
wry condescension and guarded respect in his portrayal of the king,
who is tied to old ways even as he tries to become more ``modern.''
That Chow has knife-edged comic timing shouldn't come as a
surprise; he first made his name in Hong Kong as a comedy star.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder, though, if the filmmakers could get an Asian star
for the king, couldn't they get a British star _ or at least
Gwyneth Paltrow _ to play Anna? It's not that Jodie Foster
struggles with her British accent, it's that the accent doesn't
quite fit.
</P>
<P>
   Foster appears uncomfortable, as if her corset were cinched too
tightly. She plays her Anna with more facial tics than usual,
risking crossing over into Ally McBeal territory. She appears
slightly miscast.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone seems ideal for an adaptation of Politically Correct
Bedtime Stories, it's Anna and the King director Andy Tennant,
whose last film was the goofily anachronistic and oddly
entertaining ``Ever After'' _ which gave us a Cinderella and a
Prince Charming so '90s, you all but expected them to cram on
headphones and play computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant has grown as a director (he probably couldn't help it
after TV's ``The Amy Fisher Story''), but he and his screenwriters
can't resist occasional indulgences, such as an anti-king
conspiracy subplot that gives Chow a chance to prove that he can be
romantic and an action hero.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant has a talent for pageantry, and the movie is a triumph
of art direction, especially with the stunning, grandiose design of
the king's palace, which was replicated on a golf resort in
Malaysia. But Tennant too often lets the grandeur of the movie's
look do the work for him; ``Anna'' has moments that are static,
saved by other moments _ a banquet, an execution, the action-scene
climax _ that bring the movie to life. When Tennant is at his best,
he almost approaches David Lean levels of epic filmmaking, but he
doesn't have Lean's sustained passion.
</P>
<P>
   It's what keeps ``Anna'' from greatness. For someone whose movie
has what is reportedly the largest set since 1963's ``Cleopatra,''
Tennant lacks the commitment and confidence (arrogance, really)
that helped James Cameron steamroller past ``Titanic's'' hokey
script. ``Anna'' is fine holiday entertainment, but its art
direction aside, it's not the Oscar-bait it was rumored to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' is rated PG-13 for brief but fairly
graphic violent scenes.
</P>
<P>
   FILM: ``Anna and the King'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATING: 3 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Andy Tennant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jodie Foster, Chow Yun-Fat
</P>
<P>
   Length: 148 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
