<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIAN-ISRAELI TALKS GET OFF TO SHAKY START 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Syria and Israel opened a historic round of
high-level peace talks on a cool note Wednesday as President
Clinton sounded hopeful that the last serious dispute among
Arab-Israeli neighbors in the Middle East may finally be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Clinton's optimistic tone, the two days of talks
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa began with the two men refusing to shake
hands and al-Sharaa issuing a strong condemnation of the
32-year-old Israeli occupation of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa charged that a half-million Syrians had been uprooted
from their homes in the region and their ancient villages ``wiped
out from existence.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed contempt for what he called efforts by the
Israelis ``to muster international sympathy'' for some 18,000
Israeli settlers in the Golan Heights who will have to leave their
homes if a peace agreement is signed. He said the suffering of
Syrians who lived there before the Israelis had been ``ignored'' by
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister, speaking on behalf of ailing Syrian
President Hafez Assad, made it clear, however, that there would be
no agreement without a commitment by Israel to give up all of the
Golan Heights region it captured during the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that peace for Syria means the return
of all its occupied land,'' al-Sharaa said. He added that in
exchange Syria is prepared to provide security guarantees that will
help end ``the psychological fear (of Arab military attacks), which
the Israelis have been living in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak delivered a conciliatory, terse statement himself,
alluding to ``the horrors of war'' endured by the Jewish state
since its creation in 1948. But Barak expressed his determination
to end the Arab-Israeli conflict once and for all, saying that
Israel is ready ``to do whatever we can'' to reach an agreement
that will return the Golan Heights to Syria in exchange for
normalized relations and security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he hoped ``this march together with our Syrian
partners'' will produce ``a different Middle East where nations are
living side by side in peaceful (relations) and in mutual respect
and good neighborliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa indicated his government was ready to deal as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching the moment of truth,'' al-Sharaa said at a
brief ceremony held in the White House Rose Garden. He said the
talks promise ``for the first time the dawn of a real hope to
achieve an honorable and just peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa's remarks on the occupation of the Golan Heights
angered the Israeli delegation and Clinton administration
officials. Zalman Shoval, Israel's ambassador to the United States,
called the tone of al-Sharaa's comments inappropriate for someone
who had come to Washington ``in the spirit of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton ignored the remarks, choosing to emphasize the
importance of bringing the two sides together for the first time
since lower-level negotiations between them broke down in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing today is not yet peace, and getting
there will require bold thinking and hard choices,'' Clinton
acknowledged before al-Sharaa and Barak began their face-to-face
sessions at Blair House, a government guest residence across
Pennsylvania Avenue from the presidential mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today is a big step along that path. For the first time in
history, there is a chance of a comprehensive peace between Israel
and Syria, and indeed all its neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also stressed the importance of a Syrian-Israeli
agreement not only to the Middle East region, but to the world as a
whole and the United States in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned from experience that tensions in the region
can escalate, and the escalations can lead into diplomatic,
financial and, ultimately, military involvement _ far more costly
than even the costliest peace,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton conceded that there were no guarantees of success
going into the first round of meetings Wednesday, he said the fact
that the two sides are even talking again is an indication that
they may be ready to put aside their long history of hatred and
walk ``the road to peace'' together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be challenges along the way, but we have never had
such an extraordinary opportunity to reach a comprehensive
settlement,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed to meet in Washington following months of
diplomacy by the Clinton administration, which included numerous
visits to the region by U.S. special Middle East envoy Dennis Ross
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Clinton also put
pressure on Assad and Barak in a series of phone calls in which he
sought to gauge what it would take for peace negotiations to resume
again between them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end Clinton's pressure and timing paid off. Assad agreed
to send al-Sharaa to Washington after a meeting with Albright
earlier this month in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said a number of circumstances played a
key role in convincing Assad that the time for an agreement with
Israel is now.
</P>
<P>
   They said Assad recognized that the next U.S. president may not
be as free politically as Clinton is now in his last year in office
to push for an accord. In addition, they said Assad was also aware
that Barak, who has made it clear that he wants a deal with Syria
sooner rather than later, may be his best hope to win back the
territory lost to Israel 32 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These officials also noted that the aging Assad would like to
have the problem with Israel resolved before he dies or
relinquishes office. They said Syria's ailing economy also played a
key role in convincing Assad that he must try to normalize
relations to create more trade and other economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the two sides had made progress in talks four
years ago before they broke off was also cause for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   During those negotiations Israel all but promised the return of
the Golan Heights in exchange for specific security guarantees
aimed at preventing surprise military attacks. But there are still
a number of touchy differences that must be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Syria wants all the Golan Heights, including the
territory bordering the Sea of Galilee. But Israel relies on the
sea for water supplies, and is reluctant to give in to that demand.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also wants the Golan Heights demilitarized, and is
demanding that Assad pull his forces back to a point north of
Damascus. In addition, Israel wants to leave behind several Israeli
military ``listening posts'' to help protect its borders with Syria
and Lebanon. Syria has refused that request.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart told reporters after
the first day's talks concluded in the early evening that it would
``be wrong to minimize how difficult this is and how much hard work
needs to be done'' to resolve ``long-standing differences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president laid out how he thinks we should move forward
and where we should get to by the end of the two days. But I'm just
not going to get into the specifics of what that might be,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are scheduled to resume Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
