<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CEAUSESCU-COLLECTOR-A     12-15 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEAUSESCU-COLLECTOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANIA SELLS CEAUSESCU'S TCHOTCHKES AND THINGAMAJIGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania _ What kind of man specializes in buying up
the tchotchkes of a Stalinist dictator who was prevented only by an
untimely rendezvous with a firing squad from holding the world's
tackiest yard sale?
</P>
<P>
   The kind of man whose name is Dr. Kassem Nour of Orlando, Fla.
Or Dr. Ru Ru of Bucharest, depending on which one of his business
cards he hands you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I have more than one name,'' he says reassuringly, fishing
out a second card when the first does not match the introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Nour, or whatever, an affable man whose face can explode into a
carnival-poster smile at the approach of a camera, claims to own a
``Renoir that's not in any book'' and to have drunk cheap wine with
Salvador Dali, whose work he says he collected.
</P>
<P>
   When asked where he is from, he goes a little vague and spins
diverting family yarns. (His grandfather from Russia, a
better-late-than-never type, married at age 60, fathered 10
children by the age of 96, died age 106. Car crash. No, he wasn't
driving.)
</P>
<P>
   Nour is still childless at age 72, but evinces an obvious
appreciation for the fabled beauty of Romanian women even during
pauses while looking at the _ we will do best to call it ``stuff.''
As he and his translator play chess with one of many hand-carved
sets on sale, he makes a move: ``I love Romanian girls! I love
you!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you,'' she replies, checking him with a
skepticism that sounds even better in a Transylvanian accent.
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend saw the fourth of the continuing auctions of
stuff that once belonged to Nicolae and Elena Ceausescu, who ruled
Romania from 1965 to 1989 with iron fists concealed in custom-made
deerskin gloves. For a few of those years they were the darlings of
the West for defying the Soviet Union over its invasion of
Czechoslovakia, and they had the Buicks given them by President
Nixon to prove it. (Not to mention a tie-tack key to the city of
Chattanooga, Tenn., inscribed ``Pat Rose, Mayor.'')
</P>
<P>
   In their latter years, after a trip to North Korea, they became
obsessed with building their cults of personality; they were barely
literate but styled themselves the Great Builder and Hunter (he)
and the Great Scientist (she) as well as the Beloved Comrades of
the People. They had all sorts of stuff to prove that: A yard-tall
wood amphora carved with their portraits, gift of a local party
chapter. A microscope and a model of an atom from local schools, to
aid Elena in her ``research.'' A 9-inch model of an oil well's
pressure valve. Rugs woven with their likenesses. (The editor of a
political humor magazine bought one so his staff could tread on
it.) Several sets of deer-butchering instruments with handles made
of stag horn. And a large set of cobalt blue china from Mikhail
Gorbachev, of which Nour is the proud owner, for $320.
</P>
<P>
   He also wears Ceausescu's sealskin coat, his gray Italian woven
leather shoes and his hats. ``They fit perfectly _ his head is like
my head,'' Nour said. ``The only difference is mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   These first four auctions have raised almost $700,000 for the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Nour has bought about half the items. Asked about the source of
his income, he says he gave up life as a surgeon _ ``Where? Oh, I
operate everywhere _ America, Middle East ...'' _ to make a fortune
in marble and granite, and owns hotels in America and the Far East.
He is a bit vague about his plans for his purchases: ``I'm a
collector. I love, I love, I enjoy. I'm planning to do a museum.
They're more valuable if you keep them some time.''
</P>
<P>
   He seeks uniqueness first, but has an appraiser's eye: he
knocked down his potential bid for the amphora (floor price $500)
because it wasn't of one piece of wood. (It didn't sell.) He passed
on a Belgian cut-crystal vase because nothing about it said
``previously owned by tyrant.'' He bids higher if another household
name is attached _ the mother-of-pearl table from Yasser Arafat,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   He ignored big items like the aging yacht Snagov 2, which seats
57 but has not been gassed up in a decade. He was outbid for the
3,000-pound bronze bust of Nicolae. That went, for $26,000, to an
American who would not disclose what he planned to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably an American museum,'' said Monica Anghelovici, an
economist for the state protocol administration who helps with the
auctions because her English is fluent.
</P>
<P>
   What American museum, for Pete's sake? she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many wax museums in your country, so why should
there not be bronze museums?'' she said. ``In America, in my
opinion, anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Ceausescus had 41 residences to furnish, from ski
dachas to palaces, nothing was too mundane for them to save. One
item was described thus in the catalog, ``Round bowls of black
plastic, painted, with the inscription Niagara Falls.'' They sold
for $17. Average Romanians refer to the collection in terms that
would once have sent them to labor camps. But it was Miss
Anghelovici, perhaps speaking for the Romanian womanhood Nour so
ardently admires, who delivered the most damning assessment: ``In
my opinion, a man receives a gift as he is. I give something
special to someone who is special. And I give something stupid to
someone I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, she was asked, in this era of $30 million paintings wasn't
this sale entrusted to Sotheby's or Christie's, who are used to
moving hundreds of items quickly and could probably round up more
bidders than will trek to Bucharest? After all, Nour may be one of
a kind, but the collecting mania draws all types.
</P>
<P>
   (In the interests of full disclosure, it must be noted here that
this reporter unexpectedly discovered that he is one of those
types, and is now the dubiously proud owner of an engraved
ceremonial ax and the aforementioned oil-well thingy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Miss Anghelovici replied. ``We didn't think of
it. The government decides, and we just do what we are told.''
</P>
<P>
   Sic semper tyrannis, even in yard sales and only 7,000 items
left to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
