<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BICENTENNIALMAN-     12-15 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BICENTENNIALMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRUPY `BICENTENNIAL MAN' DEPICTS AN ODDLY LIFELESS TOMORROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A decade or so ago, critics commonly complained that Robin
Williams was too manic _ that his performances in movies such as
``Good Morning, Vietnam'' were merely extensions of his hyperactive
offscreen persona. Williams' latest movie, ``Bicentennial Man,'' is
the latest in a long line of films that shows that these critics
should have been more careful what they wished for. Once our most
irrepressible actor, Williams has come full circle to being one of
our most repressed.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' restraint follows a curious path in ``Bicentennial
Man;'' although he's playing a robot who wants to become more
human, as he starts looking more human, he acts more like a robot.
Williams spends much of the movie under heavy robot makeup, with
soulful eyes and a pleasant half-smile that make him look like a
grown-up Teletubby. When Andrew, his robot character, finally gets
a human face, he looks in the mirror with curiosity and subdued
pleasure. Williams does a nice little bit of nonverbal acting in
this scene, but instead of using it as a launching pad for bigger
things, he stays at the same level, like a TV remote that's stuck
on one volume setting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is because Andrew is merely imitating the humans
around him. Director Chris Columbus has everyone in the cast speak
solemnly, as if ``Bicentennial Man'' were the utmost in profundity
instead of a regurgitation of every Data plot on ``Star Trek: The
Next Generation'' (that it's based on an old Isaac Asimov story
doesn't make it any less familiar). Andrew is adopted by the
Martins, who treat him as half-servant, half-pet, and say he's
``one of the family'' just as people say that about their poodles
and tabbies. Andrew bonds with Mr. Martin (Sam Neill) and the
youngest Martin, whom he calls Little Miss (''Pepsi girl'' Hallie
Kate Eisenberg _ can a human be a product placement?), but works
less well with Mrs. Martin (Wendy Crewson) and sullen older child
``Miss'' (Lindze Letherman), who nearly breaks Andrew by making him
jump out a window. Maybe she's just upset that her role is so
underwritten; she all but disappears from the movie after this
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew spends several generations with the Martin family, and
their treatment of him _ and his fondness for Little Miss and,
later, her look-alike granddaughter Portia (Embeth Davidtz,
handling a dual role by doing a Julia Roberts impersonation) _
fuels his desire to be more human. This, too, is curious, because
the Martins seldom interact with one another and barely interact
with the rest of the human race; when the parties and weddings
occur over the course of this movie's 200-year period, the guests
are such filler, it's as if they were removed from storage. Nobody
in the movie acts particularly human; people rarely raise their
voice or interrupt anyone. This is Columbus' fault; maybe he
thought he cast the movie with robots.
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``Bicentennial Man'' isn't for cynics is an
understatement on a par with saying a car isn't for cliff-diving.
It's not just that the movie takes itself so seriously, or that
it's so sentimental that you could pour it over a stack of waffles.
It's the movie's impossibly idyllic vision of the future. It's a
future in which, the early attempted robotocide excepted, the worst
thing anyone does is act a little rude. A future in which Aretha
Franklin and George Gershwin songs still exist from the past (the
Celine Dion tune that plays over the closing credits won't be so
lucky). A future that's impossibly clean; not only is there no
pollution or litter, but even the beaches and deserts look as if
they've been swept by robots. It's a future that's airbrushed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a future in which all countries from the 20th century
remain intact, and the president is an African-American woman
(Lynne Thigpen) _ which wouldn't bear noting, except that the
outside world is startlingly lacking in racial diversity,
especially in terms of giving any other minority characters
speaking roles. The metaphors of Andrew's journey _ how he's a
slave who longs to be free, and then longs to be considered equal _
are mired in the movie's sap, which conceals the offensiveness of
its preaching about equality while doling out only token parts to
nonwhite actors.
</P>
<P>
   Many people might let this pass because the movie is so sweet
and gentle (which makes its occasional lapses into sexual and potty
humor an extremely uncomfortable fit), and because it looks great.
This is the second Robin Williams movie in a year and a half _
after 1998's ``What Dreams May Come'' _ in which he's upstaged by
the production design. The extraordinarily clean cities, with their
flying cars, stunning bridges and incredibly tall matte-painting
skyscrapers, look like the best parts of a travel-agency brochure
for the future. Much will be made of this movie's makeup effects,
used prodigiously to depict the characters' aging. But the makeup
is too carefully parceled out _ for instance, as the initial
Martins age, their temples gray in the exact same spots, at the
exact same pace.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Patch Adams,'' Williams' button-pushing effort from last
Christmas, ``Bicentennial Man'' will divide audiences in the way,
say, that a Celine Dion song does; millions will fall for it, while
millions of others will ignore it or plug their ears.
``Bicentennial Man'' is at least less of a screed than ``Patch
Adams;'' unlike ``Patch,'' it never harangues you, because it's too
polite. It's so nice that it's tempting not to hold too much
against it, even though it tells you exactly when to laugh and when
to cry. You can see why audiences, stressed from work or school or
too much Christmas shopping, will flock to a movie that does all
the work for them. Which means that whatever you think of
``Bicentennial Man'' as entertainment, at least it's doing its job
as public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bicentennial Man'' is rated PG for strong language and sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Bicentennial Man'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Chris Columbus &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 132 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
