<HEADER>
A0199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-NYT &LR;      12-15 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN VOTERS APPROVE NEW CONSTITUTION GIVING PRESIDENT
SWEEPING POWERS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ For the fourth time in a year, Venezuelan
voters have eagerly endorsed President Hugo Chavez's promise of a
``peaceful revolution,'' voting overwhelmingly on Wednesday in
favor of a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The new charter gives Chavez sweeping powers that he says he
will use to transform the country's political and social structure
but which the opposition predicts the president will use to to give
himself near-dictatorial powers.
</P>
<P>
   According to partial official results announced on Wednesday
evening, 71 percent of voters cast their ballots for the new
constitution. As that tally was announced, fireworks were set off
in neighborhoods all over the capital, and supporters of the
president took to the streets to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The new constitution, drawn up by an assembly in which
supporters of the president hold more than 90 percent of the seats,
increases Chavez's term of office from five years to six and allows
him to succeed himself. It also eliminates one chamber of Congress,
reduces civilian control of the military and significantly expands
government management of the economy, which is based on the largest
reserves of oil outside the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a 45-year-old former army colonel who was jailed after
leading an unsuccessful coup attempt in 1992, was elected president
a year ago this month. His platform called for junking the 1961
Constitution, which he dismissed as ``moribund,'' and replacing it
with a new charter that he said would eliminate corruption and
strengthen democracy by weakening the 40-year stranglehold on power
of the country's two traditional political parties.
</P>
<P>
   In April, voters approved Chavez's proposal to authorize a
National Constituent Assembly to draw up a new constitution. In
another round of balloting in July, they elected 131 delegates to
the body, which convened in August and, after spending its first
month trying to supplant Congress and the courts, drafted a text
with 350 articles in less than three months.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's resounding victory means that virtually every feature
of the political structure here will undergo a change, beginning
with Venezuela's name. Once the new charter goes into effect, the
country will officially be known as the Bolivarian Republic of
Venezuela, a modification that reflects the president's admiration
for the life and ideals of Simon Bolivar, the 19th-century
liberator of South America for whom Bolivia is also named.
</P>
<P>
   Though the shape of the new order that voters approved on
Wednesday is clear, the timetable for its installation is less so.
The Constituent Assembly's mandate expires on Feb. 3, but Chavez
said on Tuesday that the existing opposition-controlled Congress
would be dissolved immediately, with the constitutional panel
exercising legislative functions until new elections are held
sometime early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now comes the good part,'' said Allan Brewer Carias, a
prominent lawyer here who is one of a handful of opposition members
of the Constitutional Assembly. ``Nothing is defined and anything
is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, economic analysts have said that passage of the
constitution is likely to discourage foreign investment and
accelerate capital flight. Nearly $4 billion is estimated to have
left Venezuela since Chavez took office last February, largely
offsetting the windfall his government has enjoyed as a result of
the spectacular increase in the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also said on Tuesday that he wants elections to choose
the new Congress and pick governors and mayors to be held ``as soon
as possible,'' which he defined as ``during the first quarter'' of
2000. He said he would also stand for election, thereby creating
the possibility that he could remain in power for a total of 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Venezuelan economy contracted by nearly 10 percent
during the first half of this year, Chavez's supporters have been
patient, willing to accept his promises that things would improve
once the new system he wanted was in place. With that achieved, he
will now face pressure to deliver a quick improvement in living
standards and economic opportunities for the three-quarters of
Venezuela's 23 million people who are mired in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuela is a time bomb that can explode at any moment,
tick-tock, tick-tock,'' he warned during a news conference on
Tuesday. ``It is our task, through the power of the vote, to defuse
it now, while there is still time.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain in most parts of the country, which led to mudslides
and flooding and the deaths of more than a dozen people, appear to
have held down Wednesday's turnout. Less than half of nearly 11
million eligible voters cast ballots. The balloting, however,
appears to have been orderly and with few complaints of
irregularities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
