<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0201 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-ANNA-FEATURE-LAD     12-15 1979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANNA-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT SIMPLY SIAM IN `ANNA AND THE KING'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Embargoed until Friday, Dec. 17) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You just wanted to make a nice, slightly epic family
entertainment. You wanted to adjust a proven, beloved story's
somewhat retrograde racial and sexual politics to more enlightened
attitudes, sincere in your conviction not to offend. You got
America's most respected actress and Asia's hottest leading man in
the main roles.
</P>
<P>
   What could possibly go wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Well, lots in the case of ``Anna and the King.'' This fourth
movie version of the popular cross-cultural romantic adventure
(first filmed in 1946 as ``Anna and the King of Siam'' with Irene
Dunne and Rex Harrison, then in the 1956 adaptation of Rodgers and
Hammerstein's musical ``The King and I'' with Deborah Kerr and Yul
Brynner, most recently as a kiddie cartoon ``King and I'' released
earlier this year) stars Jodie Foster as plucky English widow Anna
Leonowens and Hong Kong action icon Chow Yun-Fat as the visionary
19th-century Siamese ruler King Mongkut.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, it's not the most flattering portrait of the
controversial Leonowens, a woman whose own accounts of her sojourn
in the court of Siam are considered highly suspect. But the chance
to reveal her personality warts was precisely what drew Foster to
the demanding part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna did a lot of exaggerating about her background _ that we
all know,'' Foster acknowledges, ``which was understandable since,
like everybody else in Victorian times, she wanted to appear to be
of better standing than she was. In terms of what she did, though,
I think she was pretty true in everything that she said. It's just
that her interpretation of things was quite exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a little self-important _ and quite hyperbolic in her
descriptions of things. I think that made her more complicated and
interesting; she was just trying to figure out how to survive with
a little kid and no money at a time when women barely went outside
the house, let alone traveled 6,000 miles to a country where she
didn't even speak the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was by no means perfect and by no means nice nor without
bitterness. And she was very judgmental, very opinionated; and even
she herself admitted that she was way too pushy. So, maybe the
difference between my version and the Deborah Kerr-Irene Dunne
versions is, in this era, we can actually create female characters
that change, that start off having a lot to learn and, by the end
of the movie, find their softness.''
</P>
<P>
   Like previous dramatic incarnations of the story, the latest
``Anna'' is founded on Leonowens' memoirs of her stint teaching
Western knowledgee to Mongkut's 58 children. But while the
Harrison-Dunne version drew heavily from Margaret Landon's highly
romanticized book on the subject, the new film's screenplay,
credited to Steve Meerson and Peter Krikes and extensively
rewritten by director Andy Tennant (``Ever After''), was more
informed by independent research.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Tennant and company tried mightily to present
Mongkut and Victorian-era Siam in an accurate and respectful
manner, they couldn't overcome the Thai government's long-standing
resentment of Hollywood's previous attempts to tell the story. Many
Thais have disliked the idea of Caucasian Harrison impersonating
one of their most venerated monarchs. And even though Brynner's
mysterious lineage likely included Asian ancestors, Thais
considered his performance as Mongkut insultingly clownish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite extensive negotiations with Bangkok officials for
permission to film on authentic locations, Tennant and company
ultimately had to move the production to neighboring Malaysia _
where the Siamese royal palace and other important sets had to be
built from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Thailand's biggest objection to the project was that
we were making it,'' Tennant jokes, not playfully. ``They still
haven't recovered from `The King and I,' they are so offended by
it. As we went in and began talking to officials, I was incredibly
sympathetic to their objections. Once you learn the true story of
King Mongkut, you realize that he wasn't the barbaric buffoon that
he'd been painted as in that movie, who had to be rescued and tamed
by a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he was a monk for 30 years, and he handled tremendous
problems during his reign. Yet, he was the only ruler to maintain
his country's independence during all the partitioning of Southeast
Asia during the European colonizing period. So he was a really
remarkable man, and we kept saying that that's the story we wanted
to tell. But they also believe that their king is a god, so
anything in our script that made the king human was objectionable.
We finally ran out of time and patience and moved to Malaysia,
which made the movie more expensive. But we were going to make it
anyway, so in the end, I think, it was Thailand's loss.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a boon, however, to the then-depressed Malaysian
economy. For their set, Tennant and production designer Luciana
Arrighi, who won an Academy Award for her work on ``Howards End,''
had to virtually reproduce the 1860s Siamese palace on the back end
of a golf course. The largest single movie set built since
``Cleopatra'' nearly bankrupted 20th Century Fox in the early '60s,
Tennant's palace not only dwarfed the real royal compound _ Chow
contends that his kingly estate is four times as large as the
current one in Bangkok _ but it had to be as practical as possible,
not just present a glittery facade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to build interiors and exteriors, since we didn't have
any soundstages,'' Tennant explains. ``And we also wanted to be
able to have the access to take somebody in and out of doorways in
the same shot. And it all had to be made out of marble; it had to
be practical because it rained every day for two hours. When (Fox
executive) Bill Mechanic came to see the set, he wanted to know why
there was 4,000 square feet of marble, why we didn't just paint it.
Then it started to rain, and he saw why.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon precipitation was hardly the only physical
inconvenience. Temperatures on the equatorial peninsula regularly
reached 120 degrees, bugs Tennant describes as ``big as Miami''
abounded, an encephalitis outbreak was taking lives throughout the
vicinity (though no one involved with the production was stricken),
and the $75 million production was always mere days in back of its
ambitious construction schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that leading lady Foster had recently given
birth and had her little boy, Charles, with her the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult working circumstance, but he had a
great time,'' reports Foster, the former child star (``Taxi
Driver'') and double Academy Award winner (``The Accused,'' ``The
Silence of the Lambs''). ``He went to butterfly farms, we took him
in the water, so it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   While not as great for someone who was wrapped up in voluminous
Victorian dresses for most of the sweltering shoot, Foster hasn't
earned her reputation as one of Hollywood's best-liked superstars
by complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the actor's condition,'' she says with a shrug.
``You're either wearing a mink coat in the middle of summertime, or
a bikini in winter. It was hard, but we all agreed that it was
better than doing a movie like `Gorky Park,' where you're supposed
to be in Russia in the middle of winter at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in the Asia of the past but with the sensibilities of
today was, as mentioned, as vital a part of ``Anna's'' atmosphere
as the physical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've got a better color tone than Yul Brynner's,'' jokes
Chow, a highly versatile leading man who's primarily known in the
West for his work in John Woo's violent crime films, ``The Killer''
and ``Hard-Boiled.'' ``And even though the actors in the two older
movies tried very hard to imitate the Thai people's manner of
speaking, it was easier for me because I already have a thick Asian
accent.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might have inferred from Chow's apolitical description,
he shares none of the Thai people's distaste for ``The King and
I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it!'' he says. ``I like the music, I like the chemistry
between Yul Brynner and Deborah Kerr. And from what I've heard, the
Thai royal family loves it, too. It's just the film-board people
who don't want any damage done to the royal name and image.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chow is a citizen of Westernized Hong Kong, ``Anna's''
second-billed Asian actor, Bai Ling, hails from the highly
politicized People's Republic of China. But she, too, finds nothing
racist in ``The King and I,'' let alone in the new production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roots are the same as Thailand's, based in Buddhism,''
says Bai (``Red Corner,'' ``Wild Wild West''). ``And the royal
systems were kind of the same, too. I didn't find `King and I'
offensive at all; in fact, I thought it was quite lovely. And while
Yul Brynner could sometimes be cruel and dangerous, his childlike
innocence I found very attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what the Thai complaints are based on. Such
sensitivity has already produced some sniping at ``Anna''; Chow's
sword style is being called too Chinese, not Siamese.
</P>
<P>
   Localized controversy over ``Anna'' will, at least, be good
training for Foster. Her next two film projects threaten to be
international lightning rods.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a fuss over ``Hannibal,'' the ``Silence of the
Lambs'' sequel that's scared off director Jonathan Demme. Foster
denies recent reports that she won't make the sequel if her
character, FBI agent Clarice Starling, joins her demented
benefactor Hannibal Lecter in cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   But she hasn't committed to the project, either, and it's
already in pre-production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to make a sequel for 10 years,'' Foster says with
apparent enthusiasm. ``We're dying to do it, Tony Hopkins and
myself. But I think all of us love these characters so much that we
want to make sure the sequel is as good _ or, at least, almost as
good _ as the original, that it really grows on the premise that
(the source novels' author) Thomas Harris and we created. Clarice
has a really strong and very specific personality; I know exactly
what she would and wouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more alarming than the prospect of a flesh-eating Clarice
is Foster's plan to star in a movie biography of Leni Riefenstahl,
the admired and reviled genius of Nazi cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a cautionary tale,'' Foster enthuses, fully aware that
even the most critical portrait of Riefenstahl will anger many,
``about the brightest career in female filmmaking, by far, but
hopefully a movie that people will learn what not to do from. The
big challenge will be to get it right, and that's what scares a lot
of people about it. I feel like there are a lot of things I don't
know, but one thing I feel really confident about is my ability to
navigate complicated moral terrain. But it's going to be a hard
job, and I'm going to be very alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of puts tangling with overly cautious Thai officials in
perspective, doesn't it? At least the makers of ``Anna and the
King'' can be confident that the fundamental romance of their story
has overcome all criticism for nearly a century and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those enduring love stories, in fantasy,'' Tennant
notes. ``The fact that everyone out there has fallen in love with
somebody they can't have, for whatever noble reason, makes movies
like this and `Casablanca' endure. Rick and Ilsa still aren't
together, and the beauty of Anna and Mongkut's characters is that
they both do the right thing for the country. So many times, in our
own lives, we're selfish and we don't make the right sacrifices, so
it's actually fun to see a movie where people actually struggle for
the greater good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
