<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-HNS &LR;      12-15 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M BONFIRE EXCEEDED HEIGHT LIMIT, MEMOS INDICATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES KIMBERLY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the time of its collapse, the Texas A&AMP;M Bonfire was 19 feet
taller than it should have been and would have dwarfed a
university-imposed height limit by the time it was finished,
according to internal memos released by the university Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonfire stood at 59 feet before it toppled Nov. 18, killing
12 and injuring 27 people on the College Station campus, according
to measurements taken from marks on the center pole.
</P>
<P>
   Because students were on the fourth of five tiers of logs, the
structure should only have been 40 feet tall at the time of the
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The students planned to extend the Bonfire an additional 9 feet
with the fifth tier of logs making it 68 feet tall at completion.
The university had set a maximum height for the Bonfire at 55 feet
in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our structural engineers in the course of their work
will be very interested in that,'' said Leo Linbeck Jr., chairman
of the commission investigating the cause of the Bonfire collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But Linbeck said the five-member Special Commission on the 1999
Aggie Bonfire would look at much more than just the height of the
Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing the very best I can not to jump to conclusions as to
what caused the collapse,'' said Linbeck, chairman of a
Houston-based commercial construction corporation that bears his
name.
</P>
<P>
   It was the responsibility of Bonfire adviser Rusty Thompson to
make sure students did not exceed the height limit of 55 feet,
according to university memos. Thompson was supposed to mark the
center pole, which supported the Bonfire, to let students know
where to stop building, according to a 1986 memo written by
Associate Vice President for Student Affairs Bill Kibler.
</P>
<P>
   Phones calls made to the homes and offices of Kibler and
Thompson were not returned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident, Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen and
Thompson said the Bonfire stack was 40 feet high when it
collapsed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; It was by measuring marks on the center pole that John A.
Weese, an A&AMP;M professor of mechanical engineering, determined the
height of the Bonfire at its collapse. Weese is the university's
liaison to the commission Linbeck chairs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to measuring marks on the center pole, Weese
interviewed the students who worked on the Bonfire, according to
the memo he prepared for the commission. Weese's memo was among the
hundreds of historical and contemporary documents related to the
Bonfire released by the university Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Weese's memo, the first Bonfire tier was 18 feet
high; the second was 16 feet; the third 14 feet; and the fourth 11
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonfire collapse was the worst on-campus disaster in Texas
A&AMP;M history. Eleven of the dead were current students; one was a
recent graduate. Of the 27 injured, only freshman John Comstock,
19, of Richardson, remains hospitalized. He is in critical
condition at the College Station Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The height of the Bonfire was long a concern for campus
administrators, internal documents indicate. The tradition of
building massive Bonfires to rally students before the annual clash
between Texas A&AMP;M and the University of Texas football teams dates
back to 1909.
</P>
<P>
   A height limit of 55 feet was established more than 20 years ago
by then Vice President of Student Affairs John Koldus because
students were striving to build taller and taller Bonfires. The
tallest Bonfire ever built was 109 feet in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, University Health and Safety Officer Harry Stiteler Jr.
recommended the Bonfire be limited to no more than 45 feet high to
further improve safety. The suggestion was rejected that same year
because there had never been a problem with the Bonfire at 55 feet
and diminishing its size might cause an uproar among students,
Kibler's memo to Stiteler indicated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
