<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MEXICO-CENSORSHIP-MOV     12-15 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CENSORSHIP-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDING UP TO CENSORS, MEXICAN FILM FINDS ITS VOICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An advertisement he read in the morning newspaper
made Luis Estrada, a Mexican film director, feel that his darkest
anxiety dream had become real.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was for the opening that same day of a movie, his movie.
It was opening at midday with no party and no fanfare at two small
art cinemas in Mexico City. He had not been invited. He had not
even been told.
</P>
<P>
   The semi-clandestine release on Dec. 3 of Estrada's latest film,
``La Ley de Herodes'' (``Herod's Law''), was part of a campaign by
the government's national film agency to bury it. The film gives a
comic but bald portrayal of the corruption of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which has controlled Mexico for decades,
calling the party by its name for the first time in a Mexican
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The national film agency, the Mexican Cinema Institute, financed
most of the film and at first approved it. But officials there
apparently began to fear that its release in the heat of the
current presidential campaign, in which the long-ruling party is
facing serious competition, might annoy some top national brass.
</P>
<P>
   In the end Estrada's nightmare faded. Eduardo Amerena, the head
of the institute, was dismissed last week for what a senior culture
official called ``erratic behavior.'' The agency sold its $900,000
stake in the movie to Estrada on very soft terms, so he can release
it again exactly as he pleases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censorship no longer exists in the political lexicon of
Mexico,'' declared Rafael Tovar y de Teresa, Mexico's top culture
official. Happily for Estrada, the scandal heightened public
anticipation of the film.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also drew attention to the recent revival of
Mexican movie-making, in which a younger generation of directors
and producers, including Estrada, 37, are restoring the vitality
and momentum to an industry that had seemed virtually paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The first jolt of new life was felt in June with the release of
Antonio Serrano's ``Sexo, Pudor y Lagrimas'' (``Sex, Shame and
Tears''). The movie played for six months in theaters around the
country and drew 5.4 million viewers, making it the most popular
Mexican film ever screened here. (It ranks third behind ``Titanic''
and Disney's ``Tarzan'' for the most-watched film over all.) The
film grossed $12.7 million at the box office, a staggering amount
for this country, and cost only $1.4 million to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexo, Pudor y Lagrimas'' offered Mexico's urban middle class
the equivalent of a Woody Allen movie. Shot largely in interiors in
two Mexico City apartment buildings, it reveals the frenetic
romantic microenvironment of six young Mexicans. Serrano, who has
worked in theater but recently oversaw two successful nighttime
television soap operas, gave the film the unvarnished, episodic
look and feel of television drama.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, a panorama of Latin angst with comic flourishes in
the style of the Spanish director Pedro Almodovar, has a little
something for every modern-day Mexican: adultery, impotence, lust,
self-loathing. The men are either smooth-talking and macho, or
brooding misfits, and the women battle their dependence on the men.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano, who also wrote the screenplay, captured the shrill
thrust and parry of discourse between the sexes here, and audiences
laughed uproariously.
</P>
<P>
   Matthias Ehrenberg, the producer, said the film benefited from
strategic marketing. The cast was carefully selected to include
actors associated with both of Mexico's national television
networks, so neither one refused to carry advertising for the
movie. The film's pop theme song by the singer Aleks Syntek was on
the radio when the film reached the theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been such heavy pessimism among Mexican
filmmakers,'' Ehrenberg said. ``But the problem was that we were
making films that had nothing to do with the public. Our public
wants to see films that show their own lives in their own
language.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, which lasted through the 1970s, the Mexican film
industry was sustained by the government and produced more than 100
movies a year for an avid national following. But as a series of
economic crises over 15 years cut into resources, the films veered
toward vulgar farce or difficult director's statements, both
unappealing to audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Now a generation of independent-minded filmmakers, raised in the
industry but with little allegiance to the state system, have come
into their own.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking in the new crop is ``Un Embrujo,'' or
``Under a Spell,'' directed by Carlos Carrera, 37. The film,
released in March, is a coming-of-age story about an adolescent boy
during the political backlash of the postrevolutionary 1920s. His
sexual initiation by a lonely schoolteacher leads to a lifelong
passion for her, until both fall victim to a hex by disapproving
Mayan townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed by the arrival of several Oscar-winning foreign
movies, the movie failed to take off with Mexican audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Another film, set in tropical southern Mexico, ``Santitos''
(``Little Saints''), did much better. The movie, directed by a
newcomer, Alejandro Springall, 33, with some financial help from
the director John Sayles, is an allegory about a young, very devout
Roman Catholic woman who cannot accept the sudden death of her
teenage daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by her patron saint, she embarks on a journey to find the
girl. The journey takes her to hellish dens of sin in Tijuana and
Los Angeles, to the discovery of her own sensuality and finally
into the arms of an angel, or at least a pure-hearted Mexican
wrestler dressed up as one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recovering our rhythm,'' said Bertha Navarro, a producer
of ``Under A Spell.'' ``We had gone 15 years without a sustained
presence of Mexican films in our theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican filmmakers still depend on the government for a good
part of their financing, and that can mean long bureaucratic and
sometimes political battles. For Estrada, the struggle to resist
censorship was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   The director says he made ``Herod's Law'' as a cri de coeur
against the political system. ``I made it out of exhaustion,'' he
said. ``My grandfather and my father both suffered under the same
regime. Now I have two children, and I don't want them to be
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, set in 1949, tells a blunt tale of a small-town
politician from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party who
discovers that graft, extortion and even political murder can all
pay handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada said officials at the national film agency allowed him
complete freedom to make the film, then balked at the result,
especially the final portrait of impunity. They tried to persuade
him to postpone its release until after the presidential elections
next year.
</P>
<P>
   But major private distributors liked the ruckus the film
created, and several have approached Estrada about releasing it in
Mexico. That will give him a chance to see whether moviegoers who
protested the attempt to stifle distribution will also want to see
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be famous,'' Estrada said. ``I want my movie
to be famous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
