<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ASIA-TECH-STOCKS-NYT &LR;      12-15 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-TECH-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ EAST: HIGH-TECH ISSUES BOOM ON ASIA'S STOCK MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ It's beginning to look a lot like NASDAQ on Asia's
stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that there are few dot-com companies to speak of.
Fever over anything to do with the growth of the Internet has
spread to this part of the world, fueling a boom in stocks of
electronics and telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the rush into high-technology Asian stocks
appears to lie in NASDAQ's record-setting jumps this month. A
technology-led rally in Singapore pushed the benchmark Straits
Times index up 8 percent to record highs. Mirrored in Hong Kong and
Seoul, the trend was repeated within a week in markets in Kuala
Lumpur and Bangkok. Even some telecommunications stocks in
Indonesia appear to be swept up in the enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk about anything other than tech, investors just
aren't interested,'' said Chang Chiew Yee, an analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ has also shown it can pull Asian stocks down.
Reacting to the 2.36 percent retreat in the NASDAQ on Tuesday, the
Straits Times index fell 1.68 percent Wednesday, the benchmark
index in Hong Kong fell 2.81 percent, and the Seoul index fell 3.90
percent. For the year, however, they all show strong performances,
comparable to the 63 percent advance in the NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's markets have long responded reflexively to big moves on
Wall Street, but it usually has been large changes in the Dow Jones
industrial average that energized investors here on the other side
of the Pacific: signs of economic health in the United States are a
good omen for Asia's export-dependent economies.
</P>
<P>
   That Asian markets are beginning to track the technology-heavy
NASDAQ market rather than the Dow average illustrates not only the
evolving character of American corporate might, but also a shift in
attitudes about where this region's economic future lies.
</P>
<P>
   The rally partly reflects the fact that computers,
telecommunications equipment, mobile phones and the parts that go
into them represent a large share of Asia's exports and the belief
that demand for such products will continue to grow. The rally also
embodies a belief that the region is transforming itself in the
aftermath of its two-year financial crisis to more closely resemble
America's so-called new economy, in which the Internet forms the
basis of an electronic marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new fascination with Internet-related
investments has been accompanied by the same nagging doubts many
market experts have about the U.S. boom, particularly the
consequences for an economy where capital accrues fastest to
money-losing enterprises. More troubling to skeptics in Asia is
that most of this region's economies, while improving, can hardly
be called healthy. The largest corporations are still buried in
debts, and many banks are feeble.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still at the talking stage for all this new-economy
stuff in Asia,'' said David Fernandez, an economist at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The mess in Asia's banks means less money is available for
corporate expansion. According to Merrill Lynch, only Singapore and
Hong Kong have regained financial health. The banking systems in
South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand are still insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   But the story for Asia's electronics exports is compelling. Most
economists foresee continued economic growth in the United States
next year, and they think that will fuel orders for Asian
electronics, which are already near their highest level in 20
years, according to Merrill Lynch. That should benefit electronics
manufacturers as well as help finance Asia's bank bailouts and its
overall economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   More demand, economists predict, is likely to come from within
Asia itself as consumer spending accelerates with economic
recovery. Asia is one of the fastest-growing markets for cellular
phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a glorious situation out there,'' said Janardan Menon, an
analyst at Kleinwort Benson Securities in Singapore. ``There's a
global shortage in semiconductors; hand-phone sales are still
shooting through the roof; PC sales are strong. All put together,
there's no signs of any weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   And in contrast to times before the crisis, when Asian companies
and banks lagged the United States in exploiting technology, most
Asian governments have adopted policies to encourage companies and
individuals to catch up with the West. Many are also trying to
create their own versions of Silicon Valley, complete with a
freewheeling entrepreneurial culture. International Data Corp.
predicts that electronic commerce in Asia will soar in the next
five years, growing from 0.01 percent of the region's gross
domestic product to 0.59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sapura Telecommunications Bhd., a Malaysian telephone
equipment maker, have risen nearly 50 percent this month. Since
October, Shinawatra Satellite of Thailand has climbed more than 60
percent, and the South Korean telephone company-cum-Internet
service Dacom has more than doubled. Investors are even buying into
the Malaysian telephone operator Telekom Malaysia, pushing its
stock up nearly 16 percent this month. Chip-company stocks are also
soaring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2040EST &QL; 
