<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SMITHSONIAN-AFRICA-AR     12-15 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONIAN-AFRICA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVERSE AFRICA AT THE SMITHSONIAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ELLEN KELLEHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One exhibit shows step by step how Nakunte Diarra,
an artisan from Mali, uses mud and other organic ingredients to dye
cloth. Another, a detailed floor plan, visually condenses the
sprawling Makola market in the Ghanaian city of Accra into a
two-dimensional rendition of its teeming activity. And a life-size
television monitor shows two Somalis, who now live here in
Washington, sharing memories of growing up in migrant herding
communities.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of dispelling some misconceptions and stereotypes
about Africa, the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of
Natural History opened a new permanent exhibition Wednesday,
``African Voices.'' The collection of vivid hands-on exhibits is
designed to illuminate the diverse African experience along a time
line stretching from the origins of humans to the growth of African
immigrant populations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This multimedia exhibition, eight years in the planning and
costing $5.5 million, is complemented by a series of visiting
lecturers and an electronic resource center. It presents ``the
diversity and dynamism of Africa and Africans,'' said Robert W.
Fri, the museum director, ``by showing how Africans have created a
variety of rich cultures and dealt actively in a complex world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sulayman Nyang, a professor of African studies at Howard
University in Washington, who helped develop the show, also
emphasized the diversity of Africa. ``I always tell people that
each time you make a statement about Africa, if I'm in the room, I
can get evidence to negate what you're saying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A collage of television screens greets visitors as they enter
the exhibit, and images flash across the screens: a flaglike yellow
banner lettered in blue denoting the nationhood of Namibia; a
victorious Nelson Mandela after his election as president of South
Africa; children on bicycles; immunization posters.
</P>
<P>
   The main gallery of the exhibition depicts a complex historical
journey illustrated by significant moments in African history. One
display is devoted to the rise of the Nubian kings in the Nile
Valley. Another explains how the Almoravids, African Muslims,
occupied Spain and Portugal in 1086. Ballots from the 1994 South
African elections are tangible reminders of the struggle to end
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Tangential exhibits are devoted to specific African communities.
The subject of ``Wealth in Africa'' is Paa Joe, a middle-aged man
from Nungua in Ghana who designs coffins to fit the personalities
of their occupants. Personalized coffins, a Ghanaian tradition for
more than 50 years, illustrate an individual's life or, in some
cases, the life a person had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   On opening day Lamidi Fakeye, an artist from Ife, Nigeria,
discussed a temporary exhibition of his wooden sculptures. Trained
in the generations-old Yoruba style of wood craftsmanship, Fakeye
proudly proclaimed his heritage: ``I am the fifth generation of
artists in my family. My great-great-great-grandfather was an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening of ``African Voices'' dovetails with the beginning
of a series of related lectures at the museum. On Friday at noon in
the Smithsonian's Baird Auditorium, Dr. Mary Jo Arnoldi, the
exhibition's lead curator, will discuss the show in detail. And, as
part of a Smithsonian-wide Kwanzaa celebration, historian Dr.
Maulana Karenga, who proposed the holiday in 1966, will deliver two
lectures on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
