<SLUG> BC-FILM-CIDERHOUSERULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR HALLSTROM AND NOVELIST IRVING MAKE A GOOD FIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably one of the more unusual director-writer combinations
can be found in ``The Cider House Rules,'' which brings together
the heightened sweetness of director Lasse Hallstrom (''My Life as
a Dog'' and ``What's Eating Gilbert Grape'') and writer John
Irving. Irving's books, such as ``The World According to Garp'' and
``The Hotel New Hampshire,'' have been made into films before. (''A
Prayer for Owen Meany''-based ``Simon Birch'' would've been perfect
for Hallstrom, given his affection for young, eccentric
protagonists.) But in the case of ``Rules,'' Irving has chosen to
eliminate the middlemen _ screenwriters who undoubtedly provided
him with frustration over their adaptations _ and to turn his book
into a screenplay himself.
</P>
<P>
   The young protagonist in eccentric circumstances this time is
Homer (Tobey Maguire), who grows up in an orphanage. Essentially,
he's raised by Dr. Larch (Michael Caine), who runs the orphanage.
Larch also occasionally performs abortions when he thinks the
situation requires it. And Homer eventually assists Larch in his
duties. Homer begins to take a position different from Larch's.
That is, until he leaves the orphanage and has to see for himself
the world he's judged.
</P>
<P>
   Irving has been as ruthless in cutting down his material for the
screen as any screenwriter adapting the work of someone else. His
work contains phalanxes of characters moving in and out, so that
the seemingly happy central figure can see his life compromised as
he meets them. (Irving's novels are like less fantastic versions of
Kurt Vonnegut's fiction _ although by less fantastic, I mean he
substitutes a benignly cruel fate for a sci-fi bent.) You'd expect
that ``Rules'' would be a sprawling four-hour work. Instead, it
comes in at just barely over two hours. On the road, Homer falls in
with migrant workers and finds himself another mentor (Delroy
Lindo, in an understated, powerful performance). Homer also finds
himself drawn into a complicated situation with a pregnant young
woman (Charlize Theron).
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, the movie version of ``Rules'' feels more
like Larch's story, even though it's told from Homer's point of
view. Homer seems impassive, a sponge soaking up the world so that
he can learn to alter the severity of his own judgments. But Larch,
well-played by Caine, is a sad-eyed figure who's constantly in
motion. He came to conclusions about what works, and what doesn't,
a long time ago. The film's material, which could be construed as
pro-choice, may be upsetting to some. But Hallstrom and Irving turn
out to be much better suited for each other in this instance than
you might expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' is rated PG-13 for profanity and adult
situations and subject matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Cider House Rules'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating; 3 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Lasse Hallstrom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tobey Maguire, Michael Caine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 131 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
