</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION OF 2 ISRAELI MINISTERS ALREADY THREATENS ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also MIDEAST-TALKS, MIDEAST-SYRIA, MIDEAST-U.S.) 
 &HT;    (DW) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Two key Israeli cabinet ministers said Wednesday
that they might pull their small but influential parties out of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's ruling coalition if he agrees to return
the Golan Heights to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at some point that it will become impossible to stay
in the government,'' Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, the leader
of the Yisrael B'Aliya Party, said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy, head of the National Religious
Party, met with Sharansky Wednesday morning in an effort to
coordinate their opposition to a Golan Heights withdrawal, expected
to be the linchpin of the prime minister's planned peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, whose party unanimously opposed the Barak's latest peace
initiative in Parliament on Monday, said he had not yet decided to
quit the coalition. ``We have to reassess our ability to remain in
the government at every stage,'' he said Wednesday. ``But the line
is clear. We are launching a public battle on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Their defection would reduce the strength of Barak's government
in Parliament from 68 members to 59, two short of a majority. More
important, it could signal concerted resistance to a peace pact
with Syria from two of Israel's most formidable constituencies:
Russian immigrants and West Bank settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister can count on support for his Syrian
initiative from 10 Arab legislators and other left-leaning members
outside his coalition, assuring him of more than the 61 votes he
needs to submit a treaty to the promised national referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But a narrow parliamentary margin and a bitterly divided cabinet
would make the referendum battle more difficult. Levy and Sharansky
said they would actively campaign against approval of a pact with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Party and Yisrael B'Aliya were also
partners in the rightist governing coalition headed by Benjamin
Netanyahu, and skeptics noted that their relationships with that
government had been similarly tempestuous.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Barak circulated documents Wednesday purporting to
show that the Netanyahu government had been prepared to withdraw
from the Golan Heights in exchange for security guarantees.
Netanyahu has denied their assertion.
</P>
<P>
   The dissident cabinet members held their breakfast meeting just
hours before Barak stood next to President Clinton and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa in Washington for the first
high-level talks ever held between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Levy and Sharansky had already signaled their discontent,
appearing at protest rallies of Golan settlers on Monday and
declining to join cabinet colleagues in a ceremonial airport
send-off of the prime minister as he left for Washington on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Party's strong following among West Bank
settlers is considered a great political asset in Barak's effort to
build support for a negotiated settlement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, though he controls just four seats in Parliament,
commands great influence as the highest ranking elected
representative of Israel's one million Russian immigrants. An
opposition Russian immigrant faction, also with four seats, is even
more adamantly opposed to a Golan withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   President Ezer Weizman, a staunch backer of the negotiating
effort, Wednesday used his elder statesman status to summon Levy
and Sharansky for private chats at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a question of a peace treaty,'' Weizman said,
defending his intervention on Barak's behalf. ``It is one of peace
and war.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli Shai, the leader of the Shas Party, whose critical 17-member
delegation abstained in the parliamentary vote on Monday, also met
today with President Weizman.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky's objection to the return of the Golan Heights does
not depend on the details of possible security arrangements or the
exact demarcation of a new Syrian-Israeli border, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the exchange of the Golan Heights for an early warning
station is meaningless,'' he said in an interview Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, once a political prisoner in the Soviet Union, said
that on philosophical and pragmatic grounds, he opposed dealing
with ``a dictatorship'' that he says cannot be a trustworthy
partner. ``The depth of our concessions should be proportionate to
the openness and transparency of Syrian society,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
