<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OUTSIDER'S DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At his Christmas party a year ago, I went up to
John McCain and asked an off-the-wall question: What would it be
like if he and Bill Bradley ran against each other for president?
</P>
<P>
   He was momentarily taken aback, because the thought had not
entered his mind. Then he grinned and answered: ``It could just
turn out to be the dullest presidential campaign in American
history.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the picture of the week in every newspaper and on
every television news show will be of Bradley and McCain, Mutt &AMP;
Jeff (Augustus Mutt was the tall one), the insurgent liberal and
the maverick conservative, coming together in Claremont, N.H. In
their ``summit of the underdogs,'' they will pledge to do
bipartisan battle against the power of big bucks in politics.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly dull. At the least, it is a dramatic stunt to
help them dominate the political world in the weekend before the
holiday whoop-de-do takes the public mind away from politics.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, it smacks conventional wisdom upside the head.
Most of us thought McCain and Bradley would compete there for the
votes of independents, who can choose to vote in either the
Republican or Democratic primaries. Whichever one took, the middle
would emerge the winner; the other would lose the other primary to
George W. Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the outsiders have chosen to join forces to enlarge the
middle. If the daring strategy of joining to press campaign finance
reform works, liberal Democrats will split between Gore and
Bradley, conservative Republicans will split between Bush and
McCain, and the expanded independent vote in the middle will elbow
Gore and Bush off the table.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working for McCain, who is doing to Bush in New
Hampshire what Dwight Eisenhower did to the GOP establishment
choice Bob Taft. Bradley has a tougher row to hoe in that state,
but he goes into his several debates with the vice president this
weekend propelled by the issue of his choice.
</P>
<P>
   In national polls at this stage, name recognition is still
decisive: the game of the name is the name of the game. But in
local races in small states, which in turn affect recognition and
national poll standings, debates and their repercussions are
replacing television spots as the most influential factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic debates, Bradley is being widely advised to
stop turning the other cheek, to take off the gloves and to slam
back at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bradley should cut the gentle whining about distortions of
his proposals. ``Stop lying about my record'' did not help Bob
Dole. Mournfully deploring demagoguery is a bore. Bradley should
get off the defensive and, quoting John Dryden, introduce a new
phase with: ``Beware the fury of a patient man.''
</P>
<P>
   But he will not beat Gore in debate by becoming a clone of Gore.
That would be to abandon the authenticity that has carried him so
far. Bradley can build on his campaign finance theme by asking Gore
if he is not ashamed of President Clinton's sale of the Lincoln
Bedroom and his own Buddhist temple fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   In all this escalation of rivalry, Bradley should remain himself
_ the good-guy counterpuncher. For hatchet work, he needs a
respected surrogate to put out the long-concealed memos of Maria
Hsia and to blast the excesses of Clinton-Gore's 1996 fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican debates, George Bush is gaining confidence but
needs work. His injection of his religious awakening into the
debate in Iowa this week _ causing a couple of minor candidates to
join in displaying their faith on their sleeves _ was dismaying.
</P>
<P>
   About the gang of four who share the platforms with Bush and
McCain: Only the voters can winnow the field, but it's up to the
media and McCain to put on the heat to arrange a series of
one-on-one GOP ``joint interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain needs the TV exposure to win the nomination, but Bush
needs the experience of high-pressure public jousting even more to
win the election. If Bush is unwilling or unable to go head-to-head
with McCain now, Bradley, or especially Gore will have his head on
a platter later.
</P>
<P>
   And if the outsiders get the nominations? A serious campaign,
surely, but far from dull.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
