<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE PANEL HEARS ARGUMENTS AGAINST A TAX-FREE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.D., Va., Texas, Utah)   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Proposals to make the Internet a tax-free zone
came under withering attack Wednesday by major retailers,
shopping-center owners and state and local officials in testimony
before a commission created by Congress to study the question.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores, Federated Department Stores, the International
Council of Shopping Centers and other members of a hastily formed
alliance calling itself the E-Fairness Coalition said it would be
wrong for government to discriminate against bricks-and-mortar
retailers and in favor of those operating online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proposals to make the Internet a sales-tax-free zone are
attractive,'' the coalition told the panel, the Advisory Commission
on Electronic Commerce, ``but have potentially devastating
economic, tax and social consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota Gov. William Janklow, speaking on behalf of state
and local governments whose largest source of revenue is sales
taxes, said, ``America can't survive if we have discriminatory
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot adopt a tax policy that assists in wiping out
small-town merchants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses spoke at the commission's third set of hearings this
year amid growing indications that the 18-member commission is
divided into three firmly entrenched camps. A consensus appears
unlikely to develop before an April deadline for the group to
recommend a national policy on taxing electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   One faction, led by Virginia Gov. James Gilmore, the commission
chairman, favors a blanket tax exemption for Internet commerce.
Declaring that the Internet's growth ``must not be thwarted by
taxation,'' he would have the federal government increase grants to
the states to make up for revenue losses.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt and other commission members favor a
plan by the National Association of Governors and by local
governments to create a national clearinghouse, financed by the
states, to process sales taxes and turn them over to the 6,527
state and local agencies that impose sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A third faction, led by Dean Andal, chairman of the California
Board of Equalization, a state tax agency, favors maintaining the
system in which online sales are subject to sales tax only when the
merchant has a physical presence, like a retail store or warehouse,
in a state where it ships goods.
</P>
<P>
   The commission heard from several panels of witnesses who said
that complying with different tax rates from place to place, and
different rules on which items are taxable, would be a costly
administrative nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk, a commission member, ridiculed those
arguments. ``These companies can reduce every color in the universe
to digits and put the complete details of building a car into a
computer but they can't handle sales taxes?'' he asked, mockingly.
``Totally incongruent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member, Grover Norquist, president of Americans for Tax
Reform, criticized state governments for going on a spending spree,
and said taxes from online sales would just allow more profligacy.
Norquist said that making the Internet a tax-free zone would force
state and local governments to lower sales tax rates, which often
total 8 to 9 percent in industrial states, to a range of 3 to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Janklow said the states had cut spending by $25 billion in
this decade, mostly by lowering income and property tax rates. He
said that making the Internet a tax-free zone would diminish the
power of the states and increase the power of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Janklow's testimony drew a rebuke from Citizens Against
Government Waste, a Washington group calling itself the nation's
largest tax watchdog. ``South Dakota governor proposes Gestapo
tactics to collect the state sales tax,'' the group said in a press
release, calling e-commerce ``the vanguard of America's current
economic growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
