<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA TRIPPS BRIDGE CLUB KNEW ABOUT SECRET TAPES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ Four friends of Linda R. Tripp, three of
them regular partners in her weekly bridge game, told a Maryland
court Wednesday that they were aware she had secretly tape-recorded
conversations with Monica Lewinsky before it was disclosed in the
news media.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Mancuso, a neighbor who is not a bridge club member,
told the court, ``I knew about the tape recorder before it came out
in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Diane O. Leasure of Howard County Circuit Court ruled on
Tuesday that to try Mrs. Tripp on charges that she violated state
wiretapping laws, Maryland prosecutors must show that they gathered
evidence independently of the independent counsel's investigation
of Mrs. Lewinsky's relationship with President Clinton. The
counsel's office gave Mrs. Tripp immunity from prosecution in
exchange for her cooperation and her handing over the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp was indicted on charges of knowingly violating
Maryland's law against taping another person without that person's
consent.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland prosecutors have said that they learned of the four
women, who testified before the grand jury, independently of the
counsel's investigation. Prosecutors have said that the women told
the grand jury that as early as October 1997, Mrs. Tripp freely
talked about taping someone named Monica who was having an affair
with Clinton and even invited Mrs. Lewinsky to a Christmas party so
the friends could meet her. Only one of the women in court
Wednesday said she had never heard Mrs. Tripp say anything about
the taping, but she suggested she was aware of it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The women were not questioned closely about their conversations
with Mrs. Tripp because they were there only for the purpose of
allowing the court to determine whether their testimony was
influenced by the barrage of news accounts about the impeachment
report to Congress by the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They all asserted that their grand jury testimony about Mrs.
Tripp was based solely on their own experience and unrelated to
news accounts. One woman, Kathy Sarkis, said she first heard about
the Starr report as ``some referral to some sexual thing, and I
didn't read about it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers worked hard to suggest that the women's accounts
were influenced by the news accounts of the Starr investigation.
</P>
<P>
   David Irwin, one of Mrs. Tripp's lawyers, asked Ms. Mancuso in
cross-examination: ``You were confused then and you're confused
now, and it's all a big blur, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Sarkis, he asked, ``Your brain had been saturated with
Ken Starr, the office of the independent counsel and all this
stuff, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-N     12-15 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S FLEDGLING ENTREPRENEURS HAVE LITTLE USE FOR POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VORONEZH, Russia _ Irina Venyaminova, who runs a family-owned
leather workshop in the center of this southern Russia city, has no
great desire to vote on Dec. 19, when Russia elects a new
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Andrei Myakinnikov, who like Irina started his own
company in the early 1990s, just as the dust was settling from the
collapse of the old Soviet state economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago these two entrepreneurs, both in their mid 30s,
were employees of the state _ as was just about everyone in Russia.
In those days they could have been arrested for doing what they do
now: running their own businesses, hiring employees, making enough
of a profit to survive the ups and downs of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Russia's new democracy stumbles into a new century, Ms.
Venyaminova, who employs 16 people in a second-floor
apartment-turned-studio, and Myakinnikov, 38, a regional
distributor of medical supplies with 90 people on his payroll, have
as little use for vote-seeking politicians as they once did for
Communist Party apparatchiks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no contact with our parliamentary deputies,''
Myakinnikov said, ``but I am sure that they don't care about the
problems I have. Politics don't interest me: What the politicians
do and say are two different things, and sometimes that is just as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   As voters go to the polls, in a warm-up for next summer's
presidential elections, many are professing apathy _ mixed with
disgust _ at the unseemly power struggle going on in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Those feelings were best summed up by a group of anarchists who
recently occupied the Lenin Mausoleum on Red Square long enough to
unfurl a banner proclaiming their choice, ``Against All of Them.''
</P>
<P>
   But among members of Russia's fledgling middle class, the mood
is not so much nihilistic as pragmatic. By their reckoning, the
powers that be have done little to help them get their businesses
up and running. And so at a time when Russia is getting ready for
another change at the top, the best they can hope for is to be left
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Russia may not be the best of all possible worlds, but its
small-business men and women are opting, like Candide in the novel
by Voltaire, to tend to their own gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who will be leading Russia in a year's time,''
said Myakinnikov. ``But in this little piece of Russia, I know what
we will do. We will improve services, we will hire new people, we
will improve salaries. These are our plans, and most of them are
realistic. We will do what we can in our own house,'' he said, in
an interview in his office in the heart of Voronezh's industrial
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to surviving,'' said Ms. Venyaminova, speaking
over the whir of sewing machines, by a window overlooking a
sidewalk market where the underemployed sell goods from shoes to
screwdrivers. ``I figure if a person works, he will find work to do
no matter who the president in Moscow is.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the czars and the Communists, the Russian state dominated
the life of its citizens. For the last decade, as President Boris
Yeltsin's team of economic reformers broke down the scaffolding of
a system that both hemmed in and propped up people's lives,
Russians have discovered the ambiguous freedom of fending for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For the estimated 897,000 small businesses operating in Russia
in early 1999, the struggle has not been easy. High taxes, greedy
bureaucrats and uncertain laws have dogged their growth, and that
does not count periodic banking and financial crises that have
undercut the value of the ruble and frozen bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Voronezh, in the heart of Russia's so-called Red Belt,
where an aging population has consistently supported Communists in
local and national elections, the region's 61,000 registered small
businesses are only now getting a sympathetic ear from a mostly
hostile local administration.
</P>
<P>
   Myakinnikov described the ordeal of renting city-owned space for
his expanding chain of private pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big problem,'' he said. ``Not all bureaucrats are
ready to agree. Some just say we don't want to, and that's it. Many
are from the old school and look on us with suspicion. And then, of
course, there are those who want bribes.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting of entrepreneurs, a local store owner listed
five infractions found by inspectors from one of the 33 agencies,
federal and local, authorized to check on his stores.
</P>
<P>
   They included citations for a Nestle chocolate bar that lacked
its ``characteristic luster'' and a can of Nescafe instant coffee
that did not list instructions on how to use the product.
</P>
<P>
   In this climate it is no wonder that so many Voronezh
businessmen are trying this year to run for the 450-seat lower
house of parliament. Half of the members are elected directly from
225 districts, with the others chosen on the basis of party lists.
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Bezdetko, 34, a clothing manufacturer and head of a
small-business association, is running as one of 18 candidates in
the so-called Left Bank district of Voronezh. He is a candidate for
Yabloko, the party headed by Grigory A. Yavlinsky, a liberal who
has spent the last eight years in opposition to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Yabloko and the Union of Right Forces, a party made up of
Yeltsin's economic reformers, are expected to collect most of the
votes of Russia's entrepreneurs. Myakinnikov, for instance, is
wavering between those parties.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to next summer's presidential election, Ms.
Venyaminova favors Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, 46, whom she sees
as a member of a generation close to her own.
</P>
<P>
   Bezdetko is not the first small-business man to run for office
in Voronezh, but he is part of a new wave making its voice heard
for the first time this year, says Aleksandr A. Slinko, a professor
of political science at Voronezh State University.
</P>
<P>
   Even more interesting, Slinko said, is a trend among the
region's governing Communists to become more pragmatic about
Russia's economic realities, shedding their old hard-line
dogmatism.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia's first parliamentary elections, in 1993, Russian
``biznismeni'' lured voters with their own money, sometimes
distributing packages of food at electoral rallies. This time,
their appeals are more subtle and more sophisticated, pitched at a
generation that wants to see government tackle government's
problems and leave business to others.
</P>
<P>
   Bezdetko recently invited voters to his Web site, enlisting the
Internet in Voronezh politics for the first time. Of the region's
13,000 Internet subscribers, 1,200 logged on.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign fliers _ featuring Yabloko's emblem, a green apple
with a slight tint of red _ offer voters, on the reverse side, a
list of local emergency telephone numbers and the routes of local
bus service.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other candidates who are promising to restore order in
Russia and loyalty to the Motherland, Bezdetko is offering a
program that is very local. His top priority is obtaining federal
funds to repair an aging sewage collector beneath the reservoir
that divides this city in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``My program is very concrete,'' he said. ``The collector is a
problem that no one, until now, has even tried to solve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
