<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR EASILY WINS ANOTHER TERM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the end, it was not even close. With a
victory margin of 20 points, Mayor Willie Brown could sit back
Wednesday and proclaim his re-election a people's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Brown, beginning a self-described campaign to be ``a
mayor for all the people,'' sounded uncharacteristically tired, and
frankly relieved, the morning after winning the hardest-fought
victory of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in campaigns for 35 years,'' he said, grinning.
``This one absolutely takes the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Tom Ammiano, defeated but hardly humbled, went
even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past two months, we have made history,'' Ammiano
said. ``San Francisco has been transformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even by San Francisco's offbeat standards, this race between two
liberal Democrats _ one African-American, one gay _ was unusual.
Ammiano, the president of the city's Board of Supervisors, had
jumped into what had been a three-candidate race as a write-in
candidate barely three weeks before the Nov. 2 election. His
populist platform, championing tenants over landlords and
mom-and-pop businesses over big chains, captured 25 percent of the
vote, becoming one of the most successful write-in candidacies in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   For Brown, the former speaker of the California Assembly and one
of the state's most powerful politicians, Ammiano's candidacy,
which energized thousands of voters disenchanted with the mayor and
his conservative rivals, seemed to pose a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   But Ammiano's fervent base of support, with many volunteers new
to campaigns, never grew. The struggling homeowners and
small-business owners whom Ammiano tried to speak to seemed scared
off by Brown's repeated assertions that a Mayor Ammiano would raise
taxes. In debates over six weeks, Brown hammered Ammiano with a
conservative-sounding barrage of complaints. Ammiano, he said, was
an inexperienced free spender who would not forge a consenus among
the city's competing interests and would send developers running
scared.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ammiano's vows to scrutinize corporate tax breaks and
fight for an $11 per hour minimum ``living wage'' did alarm
developers and corporate business owners. Mark Mosher, a spokesman
for San Franciscans for Sensible Government, a business-sponsored
political action committee, spent at least $500,000 on Brown's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   David Lee, executive director of the Chinese American Voters
Education Committee, said that in at least one voting precinct,
half the absentee ballots had Chinese surnames _ a sign that the
sensible government committee's campaign to get Asian-American
voters to cast absentee votes for the mayor had worked.
</P>
<P>
   Others helping Brown in the sometimes bitter election battle
included President Clinton, who recorded a telephone campaign call
for the mayor, and virtually every segment of the local and state
Democratic political establishment, not to mention the local
Republican Party and other special interest political action
committees. Brown's campaign received as much as $2 million from
these independent committees, including $1.4 million in the last
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The committees flooded the city with fliers and television and
newspaper advertisements. So did the mayor's campaign, which spent
$3.1 million on the election. Ammiano's campaign spent less than
$300,000, much of it on posters and fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who turned 58 Wednesday, would have been the first
openly gay mayor in what is the gay mecca of the nation. But
neither sexual orientation nor race were major issues in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, at the nightclub where Ammiano conceded at
12:15 a.m. _ long after Brown gave a 20-minute victory speech _
supporters said they were upset that the outcome had not been
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a dream to think Tom would win,'' said Serena
McClusky, a 31-year-old free-lance artist who moved to San
Francisco from New Jersey six years ago and had never voted here
before. ``But I thought the spread would be maybe 10 points or
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Close does not begin to describe the city's race for district
attorney. The incumbent, Terence Hallinan, a political progressive
who has emphasized rehabilitation programs over prison for
nonviolent petty offenders, led his challenger, Bill Fazio, a
veteran prosecutor, by 425 votes with all the precincts counted.
The Department of Elections said it would take one to two weeks to
count up to 14,000 absentee and provisional ballots, which include
ballots from voters who voted at the wrong polling place or whose
names were not on the rolls at their polling place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2112EST &QL; 
