<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-RECYCLING16-COX     12-15 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turning old computers into cash
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you can envision an industrial park as an
ecosystem with recycled computer components as links in the food
chain, you're well on your way to understanding J.D. Porter's
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Porter believes that old motherboards and monitors could not
only feed his Austin computer recycling business but the entire
Central Texas economy, and he is part of a local nonprofit group
that wants to create a place where that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Porter and other representatives of what's being called
the Computer and Electronic Disposition Eco-Industrial Park will go
before the Austin City Council to ask for support for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   As unconventional as their idea might sound, an industrial park
centered around computer recycling is already getting some serious
support. The group just won a $200,000 federal grant to study the
feasibility of the project and is being backed by researchers at
the University of Texas at Austin and the Microelectronics and
Computer Technology Corp. research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the time is right for the city to step up to the plate and
make this thing happen,'' said Porter, who is also chairman of the
city's solid waste advisory board and former executive director of
Ecology Action, an Austin recycling group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the group's plans, it would develop an industrial park
that would be anchored by a computer recycling company. The company
would remove and resell computer parts for refurbishing or scrap.
</P>
<P>
   Other tenants in the park would include companies that could use
the old components. Automakers are one example of companies that
have expressed an interest in getting easy access to recycled
plastic, Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   MCC and UT researchers would also work at the park, studying how
components could be used.
</P>
<P>
   The group would like the city to assist it in applying for more
funding, selecting a site, tackling permits and studying work force
development opportunities. A year ago, the City Council asked the
city to develop a plan for participating in the eco-industrial park
project but that plan never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Porter said he would like Austin to lead efforts to reuse those
materials and an eco-industrial park could be the cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   Computer recycling is becoming an established industry locally
and nationally, but eco-industrial parks, where businesses come
together to reduce waste and damage to the environment, are
unproven concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Eco-industrial parks have been embraced by the Smart Growth
movement and talked about in scores of cities around the country.
They are currently being developed in about 25 cities, but the
process is a slow one. Projects that were conceived in the early
1990s have only recently recruited their first tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of small community groups _ nonprofits, nongovernmental
organizations _ who have really pushed this idea have really run up
against ... how you pay for it,'' said Rick Luna, director of
communications for the Brownsville Economic Development Council,
which also explored a park where tenant companies would cooperate
to reduce and reuse waste materials in 1993 but never got it going.
It also got a federal feasibility grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling was that companies were not going to up and move
just to be in an eco-industrial park,'' Luna said. ``Something like
this could affect their bottom line but it wasn't going to drive
their relocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter's group, which is also headed by Greg Pitts,
environmental director for MCC, and local businessman Garland
Luedecke, believes it is proposing the first eco-industrial park to
focus on only one industry _ computer recycling _ and to include
facilities for research and development and a small business
incubator.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for computer recycling is growing. Americans discard
about 12 million computers a year, creating 600 millions pounds of
equipment. Environmental activists say much of that equipment, some
of which contains plastics that aren't biodegradable and dangerous
heavy metals, ends up in landfills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of opportunity here,'' said council member Daryl
Slusher, who favors the project. ``It's a problem that cities ...
are going to increasingly face of what to do with electronic
equipment that's outdated, and we know it gets outdated real
fast.'' But this may be the wrong time for an eco-industrial park
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the parks that have progressed the farthest elsewhere
have been developed in economically depressed areas of the country,
such as Plattsburgh, N.Y., and Cape Charles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   In Brownsville, Luna believes that the park was put on the back
burner as the Texas economy surged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been busy enough without this project,'' Luna said.
``The way it was told to me was, `When things slow down, this is
one of the first things we're going to look at.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
