<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-MCCAIN-FUNDRA     12-15 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-MCCAIN-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN AND BRADLEY COLLECT IMPRESSIVE SUMS FROM SOFT-MONEY
CONTRIBUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BRADLEY-MCCAIN) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as Sen. John McCain and former Sen. Bill
Bradley plan to meet on Thursday to demand an end to unregulated
corporate contributions known as soft money, executives of
companies that are among the biggest soft-money donors continue to
pour hundreds of thousands of dollars into their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley are scheduled to hold a rare bipartisan
meeting in Claremont, N.H., on Thursday to underscore their call
for an overhaul of the campaign financing system, including the
elimination of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   But employees of many of the same corporations that provide
six-figure soft-money donations to both parties also provide
substantial sums to the campaigns of McCain and Bradley, albeit in
amounts that meet the $1,000 limit to individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from corporations that include Citigroup, BellSouth,
Microsoft, AT&AMP;T and Goldman, Sachs _ companies that are among the
biggest sources of soft money for both parties _ have given scores
of $1,000 contributions to McCain and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Neither McCain, the senior senator from Arizona, nor Bradley,
the former senator from New Jersey, have proposed to outlaw or
limit these $1,000 gifts to individual office seekers; they would
only eliminate the corporations' much larger donations to political
parties, which are often used to directly support the parties'
candidates for federal office.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's problem is with the corporations, unions and
individuals who contribute $100,000 to the parties, not the
individuals who give $1,000 to candidates,'' said Howard Opinsky, a
spokesman for McCain. ``The most pernicious part of the campaign
finance law is the loophole that allows these unregulated amounts
of money to find their way into the political debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees of Goldman, Sachs have given $209,000 to Bradley and
$41,383 to McCain, according to Federal Election Commission
records. So far this year, the investment bank has contributed
$281,000 in soft money to the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup executives have given a total $100,000 to Bradley and
McCain; the company has given the parties more than $328,000.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of AT&AMP;T _ a company with significant issues before
the Senate Commerce Committee, which McCain heads _ have donated at
least $16,000 to the McCain campaign. AT&AMP;T is the nation's largest
source of soft money, with gifts to the two parties totaling
$954,000 already this year.
</P>
<P>
   While calling for an end to such unregulated soft-money
contributions to the parties, McCain has collected more than $14
million for his pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination,
more than $5 million since Sept. 30, when his slow-starting
campaign began to pick up steam.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has qualified for more than $5 million in matching funds
and will abide by the state-by-state spending limits that go with
them, Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator still lags far behind Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, who has collected more than $60 million in contributions and
has announced that he will not accept federal matching funds or the
spending caps they require.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who advocates public financing of political campaigns
and a ban on soft money, has raised more than $25 million this
year, the majority of it in $1,000 increments from wealthy donors,
according to aides and to records filed with the election
commission. But aides said successful fund-raising on the Internet
as well as a growing direct-mail operation had recently brought in
thousands of smaller donors whose donations range from $2 to a few
hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has applied for $8.2 million in federal matching funds
that will be delivered shortly after Jan. 1 for use in the
presidential primaries, said Tony Wyche, a Bradley campaign
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's campaign, which had raised $24 million
by Sept. 30, continues to hold fund-raising events and prospect for
donations though the mail and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's appearance by McCain and Bradley will focus on what
they call the evils of soft money, aides said. It is intended to
appeal to independents and to reform-minded voters whom they hope
will catapult them ahead of their better-financed opponents, Bush
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on campaign finance estimate that the two parties will
bank $525 million or more in big special-interest contributions in
this election cycle, more than double the $262 million in soft
money given to the parties in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic parties will spend at least $300
million of that to support their presidential nominees. That is in
addition to the $66 million in public funds that the major party
nominees will receive for the general election campaign in the fall
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the political money race, like the arms
race of the Cold War, produces more money than the system can
absorb. Most soft money will be spent on repetitive advertising,
which will simply bounce off a shell-shocked electorate, said Fred
Wertheimer of Democracy 21, a private group that advocates campaign
finance law revisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that in the absence of this money we
wouldn't have a very healthy, very competitive race for
president,'' Wertheimer said. ``This stuff pours in because there's
no restraint on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
