<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSIT WORKERS WIN BIG PAY INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tentative contract that the transit workers union
reached early Wednesday calls for an increase of more than 18
percent in take-home pay over three years, giving subway and bus
workers the largest wage increase received by any of New York
City's public-employee unions in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement enabled Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to declare victory
over transit workers who favored a strike, but the contract's
sizable wage increases could create problems for him in next year's
bargaining with unions representing 300,000 municipal workers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
just minutes after a threatened midnight strike deadline averted a
much-feared walkout and allowed the city to return to normal on
Wednesday, except for a few disruptions during the morning rush
hour. A strike would have left the 3.5 million riders who use the
transit system every day scrambling to find other means of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement giving transit workers a 7 percent
compensation increase on average in the first year, union leaders
immediately said it would at a minimum influence the city's
contract negotiations and might perhaps serve as a model in an era
of budget surpluses and economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   After accounting for inflation, several union officials said it
was easily the most generous contract involving city workers since
the early 1980s, except for a tentative contract reached on
Wednesday for the city's school principals. That one-of-a-kind deal
awards a 33 percent pay increase in exchange for the principals'
giving up tenure and working longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, public-employee unions have faced
lean times because of city and state budget deficits and been
forced to accept pay freezes or at best modest increases.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Local 100 of the Transport Workers Union said they
would begin mailing ratification ballots to members this week, with
the outcome announced in the second half of January. But several
leaders of a militant dissident faction said they would campaign
hard for rejection because, in their view, the contract was not
generous enough and contained concessions on work rules.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached at 1 a.m. on Wednesday after five days of
feverish negotiations, includes a 12 percent increase in base wages
over three years _ 5 percent in the first year, 3 percent in the
second and 4 percent in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also provides for a further increase in take-home pay _
amounting to more than 6 percent over three years _ by allowing
workers to greatly reduce their pension contributions.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference, Giuliani praised the union leaders
for deciding not to strike, but he took pains to argue that the
contract agreement would have no influence on the city's labor
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our settlement,'' Giuliani said. ``The Transit
Authority is a state agency, not a city agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that other unions would look to the transit
workers' contract as a model, he warned municipal labor leaders
that he would not accept a similar contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall percentages would be much too high for the city
and it would cause significant deficits that would add to a deficit
the city already has in out years,'' he said. ``Whatever pattern is
set is one for the state to have to deal with. It has nothing to do
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials said on Tuesday that they could afford the wage
increases included in the accord, adding that they had achieved
their chief goal of getting the union to agree to more flexible
work rules that would help hold down costs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, union rules that limit certain bus mechanics to
doing engine work will be loosened so that they can also do chassis
or brake repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Many commuters rejoiced on Wednesday that there was an agreement
rather than a strike. Robert Jones, a Microsoft-New York general
manager who lives in Fairfield, Conn., said, ``I mostly use cabs to
get around the city and if there had been a strike it would have
been nearly impossible to get one today, so it's a big relief.''
</P>
</TEXT>
