<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-DRUG-TRIALS-970(2TAKE     12-15 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIALS-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GROUP OF INSURERS WILL PAY FOR EXPERIMENTAL CANCER THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GINA KOLATA and KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A number of insurance companies have decided in recent weeks to
pay for experimental treatments for cancer, but only for
policyholders who participate in clinical trials sanctioned by
federal health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, virtually all insurance companies routinely refused
to pay for the care of patients in clinical research. They argued
that experimental drugs and procedures were not covered by their
policies because they had not been deemed effective.
</P>
<P>
   But with these recent decisions, the insurance industry has
begun to signal a willingness to finance medical research, a change
that would have seemed improbable just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers are acting partly out of frustration. Currently,
many researchers cannot find enough patients to volunteer for
studies that determine whether treatments work. With their new
initiatives, the insurers hope to funnel more patients into
scientifically valid studies so that the effectiveness of a
treatment can be determined more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The new programs are limited in scope, restricted to a single
state or adopted on a test basis. The most prominent effort is
expected to be announced Thursday by Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of leading health insurers _ including Oxford Health
Plans, Cigna HealthCare, Aetna/U S Healthcare and Prudential
HealthCare _ has agreed to pay for New Jersey cancer patients in
all phases of research, from the initial safety tests of a new
procedure or drug to preliminary tests of efficacy to large-scale
studies comparing a promising treatment with the standard one.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers, members of the New Jersey Association of Health
Plans, include most health insurance companies in the state, paying
or administering benefits for 60 percent of New Jersey residents,
or 4.8 million people. The plan would cover all policyholders
directly insured by the companies; employer plans administered by
the companies would be offered the benefit at no additional
premium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Coventry Health Care, a managed care company with
1.4 million members in the Midwest, South and mid-Atlantic regions,
in recent weeks began a pilot program in which it will pay for
patients who enroll in cancer studies testing the efficacy of new
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   One big insurer _ United Healthcare _ has tried this approach
with little success for a year, but experts have long argued that
the only way such a system would work would be if a broad swath of
insurance companies adopted similar strategies. This would
guarantee a large enough pool of potential test subjects in
concentrated markets to allowed studies to proceed. The decisions
in recent weeks mark the first time that a large number of
influential companies has committed to reversing these decades-old
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers and patient advocates said the new initiatives could
counteract a growing trend of doctors performing experimental
procedures outside the confines of a clinical trial. Patients have
been attracted to those studies because they were guaranteed the
experimental treatment, whereas in a clinical trial they might be
assigned the standard treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers often rejected claims for such procedures. But often
they would end up paying for them anyway, under orders from the
courts in individual cases, or because state legislatures mandated
that a particular treatment be covered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, studies that would determine if the treatments were
effective languished for lack of patients. The result, according to
cancer specialists, has been a significant slowing in the search
for cures. Cancer researchers estimate that just 3 to 5 percent of
adults with cancer enroll in clinical trials, while in New Jersey,
only 2 percent enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the new initiatives, advocates for cancer patients and
other groups were delighted, saying they would provide new
incentives for patients to participate in valid research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very good news,'' said Dr. Henry E. Simmons, president
of the National Coalition on Health Care, a group of about 80
organizations. ``It is very gratifying that we've recognized the
need to answer these questions of whether therapies work before the
American people are exposed to experimental therapies of unproven
efficacy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This should be a powerful tool to bring the problem
under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Fran Visco, president of the National Breast Cancer Coalition,
said, ``I think it's incredibly great news.'' She added:
``Ultimately, everyone benefits from this kind of policy. I think
it's a recognition that there's a human cry about quality care in
this country. But we don't know what quality is until we do
clinical trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Existing payments for clinical trials on cancer treatments vary.
For research on drugs, a pharmaceutical company typically pays only
for the drug and not for the accompanying medical care. That often
can include expensive hospital stays, diagnostic tests, antibiotics
and doctors' bills. For procedures, typically the patient is
responsible for all medical costs. There are exceptions for other
medical conditions in which the ancillary costs of research are not
high, but that is rarely found in cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   With the new programs, experimental procedures would probably
become more difficult to obtain outside trials, and doctors would
have a harder time offering them in those markets. Some patients
who want an experimental procedure might be assigned instead to a
comparison group that received the best standard care. But studies
have shown that many experimental treatments are actually less
effective than standard treatments. And, advocates for cancer
patients said, patients would benefit from the new policies because
promising treatments could be more quickly assessed and those that
work more quickly adopted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
