<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-QTERA16-COX     12-15 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QTERA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Qtera lands billion-dollar deal with Norter
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ One huge local deal, about 70 freshly minted
millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest deal ever made for a Palm Beach County company,
Nortel Networks said it will pay $3.25 billion in stock for Boca
Raton-based Qtera Corp., founded just last year with not 1 cent in
sales _ but with light transmission technology that's worth
billions.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half of the company will be millionaires,'' said Qtera
spokesman Jay Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel _ the Ontario-based former Bell Canada and world leader
in the sale of fiber optic equipment _ paid a premium price for
Qtera to grab high-speed data transmission technology that would
give it an edge over networking rivals Lucent Technologies, Cisco
Systems and Ciena Corp. The four are locked in a battle over which
can build the fastest fiber optic transmission ``pipeline'' at the
lowest cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time and speed are really of the essence here, and that's what
Qtera brings,'' Nortel Vice President Clarence Chandran said in a
teleconference with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel and Qtera plan to complete the deal in the first quarter
of next year. It needs approval of Qtera shareholders and
government antitrust regulators. Nortel expects to incorporate
Qtera's devices into its networks by mid- to late-2000, Qtera
co-founder and Vice President Bob Ade said.
</P>
<P>
   Qtera's technology is worth the billions that Nortel is paying,
analysts said. Qtera's equipment will speed light signals over
fiber-optic lines farther than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   A light signal fades after 250 to 375 miles. Then it must be
converted to electrical signals, amplified and reconverted to light
before it's sent on its way. Qtera's equipment sends the light
racing 1,500 miles before it needs amplification. The company says
it can transmit light 2,500 miles, although it hasn't yet tested
its equipment for that distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we are with optical networks today is at art form
level,'' Nortel's Chandran said. ``This is a combination of art and
science. This, in effect, allows us to push the outside of the
envelope for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sending light a greater distance without amplification
translates to lower costs to operate fiber optic networks because
less equipment is needed to boost the signal. That also means lower
costs for every network user, including Internet access providers
and cable TV and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carriers spend in the billions each year on their transfer
equipment,'' Qtera's Ade said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Nortel means not only wealth for Qtera's founders
and employees, but an expansion of its workforce in Boca Raton.
Qtera employs more than 140 people in Boca and 30 in Richardson,
Texas, a suburb of Dallas where Nortel and other telecommunications
companies have plants.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months, Nortel plans to house up to 250 in Qtera's
32,000 square feet of offices at 6100 Broken Sound Parkway in Boca
Raton, which it moved into just six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Fahri Diner will continue to run Qtera, although
the company will lose its name when it becomes part of Nortel's
Optical Networks Division. Qtera is a combination of the letter
``Q,'' the designation for high-quality transmission lines, and
``tera,'' for terabit, or 1 trillion bits a second, the industry
goal for sending data over fiber optic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Four venture capital firms pumped $43 million into Qtera for 68
percent of the company and three of its six board seats. If those
investors get 68 percent of the Nortel stock in the deal, they'll
walk away with $2.21 billion. Qtera executives and employees would
get $1.04 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much will go to venture capitalists, Qtera CEO Diner
said: ``Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Nortel will issue 30 million to 48 million shares to pay for
Qtera. The final amount will be determined by Nortel's stock price
at a given time before the deal closes.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel (NYSE: NT) closed Wednesday at $88.63, up 56 cents a
share. Based on that stock price, Nortel would issue 37 million
shares for Qtera.
</P>
<P>
   Qtera executives and venture capitalists won't be able to sell
all their stock immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a (stock) vesting schedule,'' Qtera's Ade said. ``You
have to stick around to reap all the benefits of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 15 months ago, Diner and four people he recruited founded
Qtera. His goal: to fill the data transmission market's need for
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Diner, who worked at Siemens Information and Communication
Networks in Boca Raton, believed it would be easier to develop
leading-edge technology in a small, fast-moving start-up than in a
big, bureaucratic corporation. He wanted Boca Raton to be called
Photon Beach for the particles that make up light.
</P>
<P>
   His Qtera recruits:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ade, 38, from JDS Uniphase, a telecommunications component
manufacturer in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chief Engineer Ian Haskell, 40, from Alcatel in France.
Haskell and Diner had been customers of Ade's at Uniphase.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vice President of Business Development Rick Aversano, 45, from
SkyDirect, a satellite service. Aversano and Diner had worked
together at Italian cable installer Pirelli Cables &AMP; Systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chief Scientist Xiang-Dong Cao, 36, from Siemens, where he met
Diner.
</P>
<P>
   The Qtera lineup: Diner as the visionary, Cao as the technical
wizard, Haskell as the specialist in long-haul data transmission,
Ade as the product development leader and Aversano as the venture
capital liaison. All soon will be very rich.
</P>
<P>
   Aversano also led in brokering the Nortel deal, but the others
became involved when Nortel wanted to see the technology work, Ade
said.
</P>
<P>
   Diner and Ade declined to say how long it took to make the deal,
but Ade said it began when Qtera started talking with several
companies, including Nortel, on a strategic partnership to develop
and use the technology. Cisco Systems is believed to be among the
companies Qtera talked to.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Communications, a buyer of Nortel equipment, last month
completed successful data transmission tests in Colorado of Qtera's
equipment. Qwest, a fiber optic network company, sent the light
data 1,440 miles. That changed the complexion of the talks with
Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sure heightened their interest,'' Ade said. ``The tests
were a stamp of validation, and they got a stamp of approval from a
very interested third party,'' Ade said, referring to Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel's Chadran said Qtera would begin adding to Nortel's sales
next year, but the deal isn't expected to add to earnings until
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel had $17.5 billion in sales last year and employs 71,300
people worldwide. It has spent the past year gobbling other
companies. It bought Santa Clara, Calif.-based Bay Networks last
year for almost $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Nortel-Qtera deal dwarfs the second-richest local
transaction: NBC's payment of $415 million in September for a 32
percent stake in West Palm Beach-based Paxson Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
