<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-DRUG-TRIALS-2NDTAKE-N     12-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIALS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: quickly adopted. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insurance companies said their recent decisions to pay for
clinical trials were spurred by the lessons of a recent medical
fiasco _ the efforts to determine whether one expensive and painful
experimental treatment, commonly known as bone marrow transplants,
was any better than standard chemotherapy for advanced breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In October, an article in The New York Times reported on this
decadelong struggle, describing how bone marrow transplants became
widely offered by medical centers and private hospitals even as
studies that could establish whether they were effective foundered
for lack of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Norton, head of the division of solid tumor oncology
at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York, said in
interviews for the article that when he tried to enroll patients in
a study to see whether bone marrow transplants were effective,
insurers would refuse to pay because the treatment was considered
experimental.
</P>
<P>
   But often health insurers would pay for bone marrow transplants
given to women outside the studies because courts or state laws had
deemed the procedure, when offered outside clinical trials, to be
standard care.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, when results from the studies of the procedure were
finally announced, they failed to provide solid evidence that it
was helping patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard J. Mansheim, chief medical officer at Coventry
Health Care, said his company had been considering paying for
experimental cancer therapies but the decision was ``hardened'' by
The Times' article on bone marrow transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey initiative began nearly a year ago when a group
of cancer researchers, patient advocates, drug companies, ethicists
and health insurers began asking how to increase the number of
cancer patients in clinical trials. They agreed earlier this year
to pay for the large studies to determine efficacy but only now
have agreed to pay for all phases of clinical research.
</P>
<P>
   As the group negotiated, said Ann Marie Hill, a group member who
is the executive director of the New Jersey Commission on Cancer
Research, the bone marrow transplant experience was foremost in the
group's minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very valuable example of why clinical trials need
to be supported by everyone: patients, physicians and insurers,''
she said. ``If we had to give one example that made it clear to
everyone why it's important, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both that New Jersey group and Coventry had a serious concern
about paying for clinical trials. They wanted to be sure that
coverage advanced medical science and did not just enrich medical
entrepreneurs. The problem is that once insurance coverage is
guaranteed, doctors can set up what are actually pseudo-studies,
ones that provide patients with experimental treatments for what is
often a hefty fee but that contribute nothing to the quest to learn
whether the treatments actually work.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent such abuses, the New Jersey group stipulated that it
would pay only for studies approved or authorized by the National
Institutes of Health, the Food and Drug Administration, the
Department of Defense, or the Department of Veterans Affairs.
Coventry said it would pay only for studies sanctioned by the
National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides access for people to be in clinical trials that
are real trials and not just someone deciding to take advantage of
an economic opportunity,'' said Dr. Joseph Carver, senior medical
director at Aetna/ U S Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   But the insurance companies say that theirs is only the first
step. Doctors have to start suggesting that patients enroll in
clinical trials and patients have to start signing up. The New
Jersey group hopes to facilitate patient enrollment by educating
doctors and patients about the importance of clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   One small sector of cancer research has already proven that the
approach being adopted by the insurance companies can work.
Pediatric cancer specialists organized themselves into two major
consortiums that have effectively served as seals of approval for
valid medical studies. With such quality controls in place, the
pediatricians have been able to successfully lobby health insurance
companies to pay for medical care in clinical trials for children.
In essence, the pediatricians' efforts reassured the companies that
they would not be picking up the costs for research of little
scientific value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
