<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-MCCAIN-2TAKES     12-15 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-MCCAIN-2TAKES(990)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIANCE HOLDS RISKS FOR BRADLEY AND MCCAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (With BRADLEY-MCCAIN-FUNDRAISERS) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen John McCain is a Goldwater conservative from
Arizona. Former Sen. Bill Bradley is more of a Kennedy liberal from
New Jersey. McCain is carefree (for a politician) and combative.
Bradley is calm and contemplative.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their designs on the White House, the two politicians
have virtually nothing in common. If anything, McCain and Bradley
should be eyeing each other warily as they compete for the
allegiance of independent voters in the crucial first primary state
of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the two will appear side by side in Claremont, N.H., on
Thursday, holding forth on the one fundamental issue upon which
they agree: campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation for their curious alliance is that Bradley and
McCain do share common ground in that they both present themselves
as reformers who want to transform how campaigns are financed. And
they are each trying to catch the front-runners in their parties.
To do that, they need every assist they can muster, including _
remarkably to many politicians _ each other's help.
</P>
<P>
   By standing together, McCain and Bradley hope to draw far more
attention than if either staged yet another
campaign-finance-related event (or, in the less charitable
description, publicity stunt.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It will get us that cherished national coverage,'' said Mike
Murphy, a strategist for McCain. ``We're trying to move this to the
front pages.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is not without risks. There is the chance that
one politician will outshine the other.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, the event will cause consternation in their own
parties. Already Wednesday, aides to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the Republican front-runner, questioned McCain's party loyalty by
consorting with the enemy. And aides to Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic front-runner, accused Bradley of resorting to a stunt
because he is feeling heat from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting a deal with the enemy for political advantage is not a
way to endear yourself to Republican or Democratic primary
voters,'' said Alex Castellanos, a Republican media consultant.
``The most partisan voters are the ones they need first in the
primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic strategist, said: ``They run the
risk that they'll be seen as holier-than-thou or that people will
see it as a stunt. And there's always a goody-two-shoes aspect to
anything having to do with ethics: You'd better be sure that you're
cleaner than clean _ past, present and future.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the brickbats, McCain, in a speech Wednesday in
Spartanburg, S.C., drew a distinction between himself and Bradley.
``Bill Bradley is a liberal Democrat,'' he said. ``I am a proud
conservative. We disagree on almost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But they agree, he said _ echoing Bradley's line when he retired
from the Senate in 1996 _ ``that politics is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also disputed allegations from the Bush camp that his
support for overhauling the campaign finance system would endanger
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending this assault on the taxpayer by breaking Washington's
iron triangle of money, lobbying and special interests is the
mission of this campaign,'' he said. ``That doesn't mean taking on
the Republican Party, it means a grass-roots movement to lead our
party back from a leadership that has too often forgotten our
conservative purpose and too often surrendered to Washington's
big-money-driven status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the perils, the two candidates with starkly different
goals, ideologies and personalities decided that for practical
political reasons they were better off uniting.
</P>
<P>
   It would be rash to dismiss the political instincts of both men,
each of whom has emerged from dark-horse status to having at least
a shot at toppling a front-runner. McCain and Bradley are running
neck and neck to Bush and Gore in New Hampshire. And both have
nimbly capitalized on their compelling personal stories (McCain's
service in Vietnam and Bradley's basketball days.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out there trying to ding each other,'' said Murphy,
the McCain strategist. ``We'll show that McCain has the courage to
tell the truth about what special-interest, big-monied interests
have done to our conservative agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering some gratis spin for Bradley, Murphy added: ``It allows
Bradley to put a hot foot on Al Gore for his participation in the
shameless Clinton-Gore campaign scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's communications director, Anita Dunn, sounding like her
candidate, was understated in describing the two politicians'
mutual benefit. ``It's the opportunity to demonstrate to voters
that there is the potential to actually get this done,'' she said,
``that leaders can reach across party lines _ even people who
disagree with each other on almost every other issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was first broached by the McCain camp, which may have
the most to gain. McCain has fewer resources and a smaller
political operation than Bradley, so he is especially dependent on
free attention in the press. And McCain is even more identified
with campaign finance than Bradley, so he could come off as a more
dominant figure at the event. In addition, with an important
Democratic debate in New Hampshire on Friday, any ground Bradley
gains on Thursday could quickly be overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when President Clinton and Speaker Newt Gingrich shook
hands in Claremont in 1995 and promised a commission on campaign
finance, the idea never materialized. And both men were skewered in
the press as not being duly committed to changing the system.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley could benefit from the event, though, because after
weeks of attacks from Gore, he has been on the defensive. So
sharing the stage with McCain, whose campaign has hit its stride in
recent weeks, could add some luster to Bradley. It would also
reinforce the message pushed by his image-makers that he is not a
business-as-usual Washington insider.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dunn said the campaign immediately took up the McCain
campaign's offer, though there was some discussion about how it
would play before the debate on Friday with Gore, and another one
on Sunday. ``We discussed whether it would fit into what were were
talking about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster who is not aligned with any
campaign, said McCain was viewed more as a genuine reformer than
Bradley because of his engaging personal style and because he has
pounded away for so long on campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's maverick status is more esoteric,'' she said. ``What
he's still banking on is a significant anti-Gore block of voters
that is out there.'' Because McCain is still in the Senate making
waves, she added, ``He's got more significant current battles he
can talk about where he's planted the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is determined to depict McCain not as
crusading for the people but as disloyal. ``Any time a Democrat
splits from the Democrats or a Republican splits from the
Republicans,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, ``it's
good for copy _ but it's bad for principle.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how cordial they are to each other on Thursday,
McCain, who is 63, and Bradley, who is 56, are not likely to appear
too chummy. After all, there is the chance _ outlandish as it might
seem _ that the two will face each other next November.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent forum in Florida, Bradley was asked about McCain's
prospects, and replied that he had a chance to grab the Republican
nomination despite Bush's daunting financial advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John McCain has a chance,'' Bradley said. ``I think
it's possible to raise too much money in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But mindful, perhaps, that he not come off as a McCain devotee,
Bradley added, ``I'm not endorsing him, by the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
