<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-EDUC-700&AMP;ADD-(TR     12-15 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUC-700&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO PROPOSE $115 BILLION PLAN TO IMPROVE PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Asserting that public education may be a local
responsibility but that it should be a national priority, Vice
President Al Gore will propose setting aside $115 billion over the
next 10 years for the nation's public schools as an incentive to
improve teacher quality and student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is scheduled to discuss his proposals at a school in
Nashville on Thursday, wants to establish an education reform trust
fund that would set aside about 10 cents of every dollar of the
budget surplus that is not already dedicated to Social Security or
reduction of the national debt. The surplus is now projected at
$1.084 trillion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of Gore's $115 billion proposal, or about $50
billion, would go toward providing universally available preschool
for 3- and 4-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Another chief element of his plan would provide salary increases
of up to $10,000 to all teachers in high-poverty school districts
if the districts adopted an aggressive plan to improve teacher
quality and get rid of low-performing instructors. Most teachers
would receive a $5,000 increase, paid for by the federal
government, though master teachers who met advanced professional
standards would receive $10,000 increases.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, Gore's lone rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has rarely mentioned education when talking about his
priorities. He has said that while there are things the federal
government can do, education is basically a local issue and big
initiatives should come from the states and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan thus offers Democratic voters a choice between his
proposal for a major federal commitment to education and Bradley's
centerpiece proposal of a large infusion of federal dollars to
improve health care.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who says he would not have to raise taxes to pay for his
education plan, has been pounding Bradley for his $65
billion-a-year health plan, which the former senator says he could
pay for out of the projected budget surplus. Gore, whose education
proposal would cost about a fifth of Bradley's health plan,
contends that his rival would probably have to rely on a tax
increase to pay for his initiative.
</P>
<P>
   As for education, Bradley has called for placing 400,000 more
children in Head Start programs and putting 60,000 new teachers in
rural and urban school districts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The vice president sketched the broad themes of his education
policy in a speech in May, and on Thursday he will fill in some
blanks about the costs, which his aides say can be met with a
balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is the first by a presidential candidate that
involves the federal government in paying teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking elements of the proposal is Gore's
willingness to use vast amounts of federal money and federal
control to help influence what many say is a matter that should be
determined by local school boards.
</P>
<P>
   While the federal government provides 7 percent to 8 percent of
the money for the nation's public schools, education ranks at the
top of most lists of voter priorities. Presidential candidates face
the dilemma of responding to the electorate's plea for better
schools without intruding on local control.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of Gore's proposal include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Signing bonuses to recruit people who come to teaching from
other careers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Incentives to reduce class size.
</P>
<P>
   _ Incentives for statewide exams for high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore first outlined his goals in May, Lamar Alexander, a
former education secretary and erstwhile Republican candidate for
president, said the Gore plan amounted to creating ``a national
school board.'' But it was hailed by the nation's big teachers
unions, which have since endorsed his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the leading Republican candidate
for president, has also proposed a fairly substantial role for the
federal government in education. He has said he would move Headto the Department of Education and increase Title I money for
poor schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One big difference between Gore's proposal and Bush's is their
response to failing schools, a major issue on the horizon for many
urban and rural areas. Bush has proposed that after three years of
not meeting certain standards, a public school lose federal funding
and that money be given to students for vouchers to attend private
schools. Republicans generally support vouchers as a way of
expanding educational choice and instilling competition in the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has adamantly opposed vouchers, saying they would drain the
public education system. He would respond to failing schools by
requiring them to adopt aggressive plans to overhaul themselves and
would devote extra money to providing after-school instruction to
students.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what standards Gore would use to determine
whether a school was failing or if it had sufficiently improved.
But under the Gore plan, if it had not improved enough it would be
shut down and reopened under a new principal with a full peer
evaluation of every teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's proposal, the education trust fund would also
provide signing bonuses of up to $10,000 each to help recruit
75,000 new teachers a year _ 60,000 from among the nation's annual
crop of college graduates and 15,000 from the ranks of mid-life
professionals who want to change careers. The teachers would be
selected by local schools, businesses and teachers, and the bonuses
would go to those who commit to teaching for four years in
high-poverty urban and rural schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would provide incentives to school districts that reduce
the size of classes, with a goal of creating high schools with less
than 600 students. He wants a national average of 18 students per
class in early grades and no more than 20 students in all grades.
</P>
<P>
   He would also give money to states that adopt statewide exams
that students must pass to graduate. At the moment, 26 states have
such exams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
