<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: BOSNIAN JAILED FOR LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The Bavarian state court in Munich jailed a Bosnian Serb for
life for ordering the killing of Muslims in Bosnia in 1992.
Djurdadj Kusljic, a 44-year-old former police chief, was convicted
on six counts of murder. German courts have tried several cases to
reduce the workload of the war crimes tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CRIME AND WITNESS PROTECTION
</P>
<P>
   A mobster and convicted murderer confessed to mutilating and
killing his former girlfriend while he was in the Italian witness
protection program. Paolo Canciolo told police that he repeatedly
stabbed his former girlfriend, Giustina Aggiato, 22, in Palermo,
Sicily, on Tuesday. Other so-called pentiti have committed crimes
while cooperating with law enforcement agencies, and the case is
likely to increase scrutiny of Italy's witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: CAMPAIGN SHAKE-UP
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Lagos, the presidential candidate of the ruling
Socialist-Christian Democratic coalition, shook up his campaign
staff following a disappointing first-round showing in elections on
Sunday and appointed Justice Minister Soledad Alvear as his
campaign manager. Aides to Lagos said they hoped that Ms. Alvear
would help Lagos do better with women voters in the runoff Jan. 16
against Joaquin Lavin, the conservative coalition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NARCOTICS LABORATORY
</P>
<P>
   Mexican investigators discovered a cocaine-processing laboratory
with more than 1,000 gallons of acetone, ether and other chemicals
on a ranch where they have been looking for remains of people
believed executed on orders of drug traffickers. Mexican soldiers
seized the ranch, in Chihuahua state south of New Mexico, on Nov.
29. The investigators have found eight bodies to date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ABORTION-AD-COLUMN-NY     12-15 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GROUP FAVORING ABORTION RIGHTS TO RESUME TV CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pro-Choice Public Education Project, a consortium of
abortion rights groups nationwide, will resume television
advertising for the first time in several years to expand its
efforts to reach young people.
</P>
<P>
   The group will begin broadcasting a 30-second commercial at the
end of December aimed at female viewers 16 to 25 years old. The
commercial will appear in New York and California markets and will
also be released to the project's 50 member organizations for use
in their own campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Sullivan, the project's director, said that the group
began print and outdoor advertising a year ago and is returning to
TV because of its broader reach and its ability to focus on young
people in the many new shows devoted to young viewers. While
advertising was perhaps unnecessary a generation ago, it is
increasingly required to reach young people today who are not
necessarily moved by any major issue, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's a major battle or there's a shooting, then people
do get up in arms,'' Ms. Sullivan said. Otherwise ``it's hard to
get the emotional response; we know we need to get out positive
messages, and TV advertising is a great way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The abortion rights campaign underscores the growth of
issue-oriented advertising on television. TV has become a
battleground of disparate voices because groups realize the need to
appeal to the public to effect change, said Victor Kamber,
president of the Kamber Group, a Washington communications agency
that creates many issue-oriented ads but has not been involved in
the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dollarwise, clearly there's more advocacy advertising because
special interest groups are making decisions to reach out to the
public by getting public attention to motivate legislators,''
Kamber said. ``The more you raise visibility of an issue, the
easier it is to motivate people and get them involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The television spot, created by DeVito/Verdi in New York,
features a shadowy unidentified politician who follows a girl
around and changes all her choices, from her selection of a soda in
a vending machine to her pick of television channels. A narrator
says: ``You wouldn't want some guy in Washington to make choices
for you. Why let them make the most important choice of all. Fight
for your right to a safe and legal abortion while you still have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The message continues its year-old theme, ``It's pro-choice or
no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The group did not disclose its ad budget but said it would spend
more than $1 million, using foundation and individual
contributions. The effort will also finance print and outdoor
advertising and will include a Spanish-language ad for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The existing print and outdoor advertising includes ads with
headlines like ``77 percent of anti-abortion leaders are men. 100
percent of them will never be pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shows platform shoes, a Volkswagen Beetle and a wire
coat hanger under the headline: ``Of all the things from the '70s
to make a comeback, there's one we'd really hate to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is intended to encourage young people to talk about
a highly personal issue that is often not discussed publicly, Ms.
Sullivan said. The project started its campaign, she said, because
it regards various state actions like parental-notification and
consent laws as slowly eroding abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make the link for them that if they believe in
personal choice and having access, that means they are pro-choice
and that that is OK,'' Ms. Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion groups, like the Right to Life Committee, said
they might run advertising, too, but did not give details. David
O'Steen, the Right to Life Committee's executive director in
Washington, said the group had advertised from time to time, but
that some of its advertising that focused on the process of
abortion had been rejected by media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups have run television advertising on the issue.
Pro-Choice Inc. spent $2 million in commercials through August,
according to Competitive Media Reporting, which tracks media
spending. And in 1996, the Arthur S. De Moss Foundation, a private
group, spent $18 million on anti-abortion messages, including a
well-known campaign called ``Life _ What a Beautiful Choice.'' The
foundation said it was no longer running those ads, but did not say
when they stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro-Choice Public Education Project has had some difficulty
placing its advertising, but is not expecting much trouble with
this message, said Ellis Verdi, president of DeVito/Verdi. Still,
creating the message was not a simple process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of choice is a more complicated thought than the idea
that babies are wonderful,'' Verdi said. ``The argument the
anti-choice people have is so much simpler for advertising purposes
_ who is going to argue that children aren't great? The more
complex thought is that perhaps having a child isn't necessarily
the best decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Research showed that young people especially do not like preachy
or overtly political messages, Verdi said. That is why some ads try
to get the message across in an almost lighthearted way. A print ad
that will run heavily next year, for instance, features a page from
a yearbook in which all the pictures show the same nerdy guy. The
copy reads ``Pick a boyfriend'' and goes on to discuss the problems
related to lack of choice.
</P>
<P>
   O'Steen criticized the abortion rights message as distorting the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pro-abortion movement will always seek to obfuscate the
issue,'' he said. ``The ads aren't about abortion or how it's
performed. The advertising is all geared at trying to move the
discussion away from abortion itself. Even by calling themselves
pro-choice, they don't want to talk about what's being chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamber said that while it was ``extremely difficult'' to change
someone's opinion in a 30-second spot, advertising can serve to
reach the many people who have perhaps never considered an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably a whole group of people who haven't thought
about this issue; it's not crossed their thinking process,'' he
said. ``Secondly, it's important for either side's activist groups
to see that they are fighting, not to change opinions but to
motivate the people they already have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
