<SLUG> BC-NTSB-MD11-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING FIRE RISKS, NTSB URGES IMPROVEMENTS TO MD-11 JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The National Transportation Safety Board on Wednesday
urged mandatory improvements to Boeing's MD-11 widebody jets to
prevent possible electrical fires.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same type of plane that apparently had an in-flight
electrical fire and crashed off the coast of Nova Scotia in
September 1998. All 229 people aboard that Swissair jet died.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman Jim Hall said there have been three incidents
since last year in which the forward cargo control unit, or CCU, of
an MD-11 either caused a fire or showed signs of melting.
</P>
<P>
   In one case in November 1998, a fire erupted in the forward
cargo hold of a Delta Air Lines MD-11 while the plane was parked at
a gate at Atlanta's Hatsfield International Airport. There were no
passengers or crew on the plane at the time and damage was minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety board is ... concerned about the risks of a
CCU-related fire during passenger loading and unloading, and that a
ground fire could propagate without detection until an airplane is
airborne,'' Hall wrote FAA Administrator Jane Garvey.
</P>
<P>
   He urged that the FAA issue three airworthiness directives that
would require airlines to modify the cargo control units, and also
require Boeing to improve the system's circuit protection. A Boeing
spokesman said the company is preparing two service bulletins for
MD-11 operators that will address the concerns raised by Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Only the FAA can order airlines and Boeing to take corrective
action. The safety board can only make recommendations, and a
service bulletin issued by Boeing is not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cause of the Swissair crash has not been determined,
the FAA has issued several airworthiness directives since the crash
aimed at making the jet less vulnerable to fires.
</P>
<P>
   The jet plunged into coastal waters 16 minutes after the crew
reported smoke in the cockpit and declared an emergency. Canadian
investigators found charred wires in the ceiling of the cockpit in
the Swissair wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 is built by McDonnell Douglas, which was acquired by
Boeing in 1997. Boeing is ending production of the plane in mid
2000. Only freighter versions are now being built in Long Beach,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the FAA in August ordered the replacement of
insulation material in 699 of the McDonnell Douglas planes in the
U.S. fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The fiberglass insulation is covered with metallized Mylar,
which not only can ignite much more easily than other aircraft
insulation, but can help spread a fire, the FAA said. It was a
Mylar insulation blanket that caught fire on the Delta plane at the
Atlanta airport.
</P>
<P>
   The blanket is located directly behind the forward cargo control
unit, Hall said. NTSB investigators found that wiring damage led to
excessive electrical current when power was applied to the
cargo-loading unit. Several electrical pins in the unit were
``vaporized,'' releasing hot gases that ignited the nearby Mylar
insulation blanket, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Aerospace Cargo Industries manufactures the cargo control
unit, and has received reports of 48 unit failures since 1993, Hall
said.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Hall said, Lucas advised MD-11 operators to
upgrade the unit with pins that are able to endure higher spikes in
electrical current. The Delta aircraft that caught fire hadn't been
modified to comply with the Lucas service bulletin, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Safety Board believes that the FAA should issue an
airworthiness directive requiring MD-11 operators to modify their
cargo control units in accordance with the Lucas service
bulletin,'' Hall said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   He said the board also is recommending that the FAA make
mandatory a service bulletin being prepared by Boeing that would
require airlines to install a thermal barrier between the cargo
control unit and nearby insulation.
</P>
<P>
   And Hall urged the FAA to issue a third directive that would
require Boeing make improvements in the MD-11 cargo control system
circuit protection to decrease the likelihood of an electrical
fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the three incidents the board investigated, Hall said, the
circuit breaker for the cargo control unit did not trip, indicating
the unit's circuit protection ``is inadequate in MD-11 airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing safety spokesman John Dern said the company is preparing
two service bulletins. One will recommend MD-11 operators make
changes to the circuit breaker in question. The other will
recommend the installation of a nonflammable barrier between the
cargo control unit and the Mylar-covered insulation blanket.
</P>
<P>
   The other two incidents mentioned by Hall in his latter involved
a World Airways MD-11 and a Varig Airlines MD-11. In September
1998, the control unit in the Varig Airlines plane was damaged
while it was parked. According to Lucas, there was evidence of
melting in upgraded electrical pins that had been installed by
Lucas during a prior modification, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent incident occurred in March of this year.
Maintenance workers in San Bernardino, Calif, found evidence of a
fire after they pulled up floorboards on a World Airways MD-11,
Hall said. Although the fire was blamed on chafing caused after a
wire bundle was not properly restrained, investigators determined
the cargo control unit's electrical pins, which had not been
modified, had failed.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman Les Dorr said Wednesday the agency will consider
the NTSB's recommendations. He noted the FAA has for some time been
taking a close look at the MD-11's electrical system.
</P>
<P>
   In January, FAA ordered inspections of wiring and insulation in
the cockpit and cabin of all MD-11 jets in the U.S. fleet. That
came on the heels of a similar recommendation by the NTSB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
