<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0270 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-MEDIA_SFCHRON &LR;      12-15 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MEDIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   S.F. Web Site Offers Investors Access to Financial Conferences 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Every time you turn around, a new company is finding a new way to
bring information to investors on the Internet.
<P>
   In the James Bong Building on San Francisco's Market Street,
where the halls look like a scene from a Sam Spade movie, On24 has
created a small newsroom and television-style studio, and is
posting more than 100 video and audio stories each day on its Web
site (www.on24.com).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the content is staff-produced radio and TV-style
reports. It also includes raw footage from investment conferences
and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than forcing people to sit through a half-hour financial
news show on television for the item they want, investors can
search through hours of archived video and audio footage for
tidbits on the companies they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are watching investment conferences on the Web that
they couldn't get into in person,'' said Mitch Ratcliffe, vice
president of programming. ``The ability to see (corporate
executives) so they can judge whether they believe them is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich media is the theme for next year on the Internet, no
question,'' said Larry Marcus, an Internet analyst at Deutsche Banc
Alex. Brown in San Francisco. ``You have the technologies in place.
You have the content there. You have lots of companies focused on
solving bandwidth issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus likes On24 because of its content creation. ``The key,
long term, is really going to be owning the content,'' he said. He
sees On24 as a scrappy underdog, while ``in terms of getting
real-time up-to-the-minute commentary, MarketWatch.com is the
richest, deepest site.''
</P>
<P>
   MarketWatch has a video component too, an enviable slot on the
CBS network television. But On24 claims to be trying something
different, by making its video feeds tailored directly for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the startup's success so far is its affiliation with
Internet powerhouse Yahoo, which steers online investors to On24's
video feeds.
</P>
<P>
   On24 chief executive Sharat Sharan joined the company last year
from Hearst New Media, where he worked on such sites as Women.com.
On24 boasts $7million in funding from Canaan Partners, Rho
Management, former Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale and Jim Bidzos of RSA
Data Security. Sharan plans to raise a ``substantial amount'' of
money in the next few months and bring the site up to 300 stories
posted each day.
</P>
<P>
   The daunting volume is something Web investors demand. They can
sift through the content to find what they want, without having to
rely on editors to winnow out information they might find useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The age of the sound bite is over,'' Ratcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a pretty good sound bite to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CRAIG'S MIFFED &QL; 
It looks like mediation _ if not litigation _ will be the way that
San Francisco's popular Craig's List will settle a dispute with a
former employee. Craig's List (www.craigslist.com) is a Web site
and mailing list that helps people in the Bay Area find jobs and
apartments and buy and sell items online. It's a nonprofit
enterprise run by Craig Newmark, 47, out of his Cole Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   Former employee Nancy Melone left Craig's List last year and
launched her own not-for-profit enterprise, MetroVox, in Orinda.
MetroVox (www.metrovox.com) bears a striking similarity to Craig's
List. It, too, offers job and event listings, but it covers more
cities, including Washington and Los Angeles. Also like Craig's
List, MetroVox gives some of its revenues to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Newmark launched the site as a hobby in 1995, but a couple of
years later, he brought in Melone and two other women to run it
more professionally. She called herself the CEO, but Newmark said
she never had that title.
</P>
<P>
   When Melone left, she took with her three domain names Craig's
List had purchased _ listfoundation.com, listfoundation.org and
listfoundation.net. All three Web addresses take you to Melone's
site.
</P>
<P>
   Melone said she has a signed contract proving that Newmark
agreed to let her take the names.
</P>
<P>
   Newmark said she was not supposed to keep them for herself but
was to turn them over to the Albert A. List foundation, an
unrelated nonprofit that fosters citizen participation in the
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   Newmark is encouraging his 8,500 subscribers to pressure Melone
to at least agree to mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Money is not an issue in the dispute. Personality and principle
are more like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ugly episode,'' said Newmark.
</P>
<P>
   Melone said she would consider mediation. ``You never close the
door on finding an equitable solution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUSINESS 2.0 TIMES A MONTH &QL; 
Business 2.0 has gotten so fat that the magazine has decided to go
from once a month to twice a month in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our issues are getting pretty large,'' said Jim Daly, editor
in chief. ``The December issue was 336 pages. Everybody loves the
so-called `thud' factor when it drops on a desk, but readers were
starting to look at it as a project.''
</P>
<P>
   Published by Brisbane's Imagine Media, the magazine's ad pages
are way up, from 74.5 last December to 217 this month.
</P>
<P>
   Paid circulation grew 16 percent, from 137,500 last January to
160,000 in August. January's issue will hit 210,000.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the expansion, Daly plans to increase his
editorial staff from 14 to nearly 40, including four or five people
in a new bureau in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring, Upside, the Industry Standard, Wired and Fast
Company are all shattering records, and all for the same reason:
It's the new economy, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
