r f BC-MACYS-MACY'S_SFCHRON &LR;      12-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACYS-MACY'S </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Macy's West CEO Stepping Down  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Michael Steinberg, chairman and chief executive of Macy's West
department stores, will step down at the end of this year.
<P>
   Steinberg, 71, will be replaced by Macy's West's president,
Jeremiah Sullivan, 60. Robert Mettler, 59, will succeed Sullivan as
president and chief operating officer. Mettler was president of
merchandising for Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. Rudolph Borneo, 58, will
remain vice chairman and director of stores.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments are effective Jan. 3, 2000, according to
Federated Department Stores, Macy's Cincinnati-based parent
company.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, a respected merchandiser, was lured out of retirement
to run Macy's West in 1993, when R.H. Macy &AMP; Co. was in bankruptcy
proceedings and had not yet been acquired by Federated. Steinberg
had been chairman of Foley's department stores in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A native of South Africa, Steinberg saw the division through
R.H. Macy's merger with Federated in 1994 and the integration of
Broadway Stores Inc., a Los Angeles company that Federated acquired
in 1995. Broadway Stores included the Broadway, Emporium and
Weinstock's chains.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's West operated about 40 stores when Steinberg joined the
company and now runs 100 in six states. The division's sales are
expected to exceed $4 billion this year, up from $3.8 billion in
1998 and $255 million in 1994, Steinberg's first full year with the
company. The division employs more than 25,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan and Steinberg have run Macy's West jointly for five
years, with Sullivan handling operations and Steinberg overseeing
the selection and presentation of merchandise. Sullivan said he is
not planning any major changes for the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profits are two and a half times what they were five years ago
so ... our strategy is one we don't want to tinker with, we want to
keep it going,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``this is a big transition for the company,'' said Kent
Anderson, former chief financial officer of Macy's West and now the
chief executive of Macys.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steinberg could go all the way from couture down to the
bargain basement notions department, and he understood the business
and how to present it to the consumer,'' Anderson said. Steinberg
``worked a lot of Saturdays,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's West will continue opening about three stores annually
for the next three to five years, Sullivan said. The division also
has ``an aggressive program we are rolling out to all of our stores
to be 100 percent compliant with disability-access laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled in October that Macy's Union Square store
violated regulations on issues such as aisle widths and counter
heights. A second suit involving other Macy's stores is pending.
Macy's says its Union Square location has been remodeled since the
suit was filed and now complies with all applicable rules.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, who began his career in 1965 as a trainee at
Federated's Abraham &AMP; Straus chain, said he plans to travel and
then do part-time consulting for Federated. Macy's West ``is in
good shape,'' he said. ``We've got a very, very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy's has had a presence on the West Coast since 1945, when
R.H. Macy bought San Francisco's O'Connor Moffat &AMP; Co. O'Connor
Moffat's Union Square store, now a Macy's flagship and the
third-largest department store in the country, opened in 1866.
</P>
<P>
   Federated, whose sales hit $15.8 billion last year, is the
largest upscale department store company in the United States. It
operates more than 400 locations, including Bloomingdale's,
Burdines, Lazarus and the Bon Marche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
