<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EXXON-MOBIL-NYT &LR;      12-15 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON MOBIL EXPANDS PLAN TO CUT PAYROLL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil Corp. said Wednesday that it would cut 16,000 jobs,
or about 13 percent of its work force, in an effort to increase its
cost savings to $3.8 billion a year by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The figure substantially raises the estimates given a year ago
by Exxon and Mobil when they first announced their plan to combine.
At that time, the companies said the merged entity would cut 9,000
jobs and save $2.8 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a much better understanding of what we can achieve
and how to achieve it,'' Lee Raymond, the chairman told analysts
and reporters at a meeting in New York. ``I am confident that we
can achieve at least the $3.8 billion and we can do it faster than
we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   That amount, officials said, was separate from savings and
margin-improvement actions that the two companies had already
undertaken _ amounting to $1.2 billion this year _ or any savings
from the divestiture of service stations and refineries that
regulators required.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they were impressed by the company's presentation,
which they considered more forthcoming than had been typical of
Exxon. But they were not surprised by how much the merger's
expected benefits had grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, people have been thinking that the ultimate savings
would exceed the original estimates,'' said Jay Wilson, an analyst
with J.P. Morgan Securities, especially since the company said Dec.
2 that the $2.8 billion forecast was too low. Exxon and Mobil both
had track records of ``underpromising and overdelivering,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Knuettel, an analyst with PaineWebber, said that Exxon
Mobil's $3.8 billion of pretax savings was only slightly more than
the $3.6 billion he had been assuming.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil had a combined work force last year of 123,000.
Of the 16,000 jobs Raymond said would be shed by the end of 2002,
some 2,000 came before Nov. 30, when the merger was completed. Of
the remaining cuts, 10,000 are to take place next year _ 4,000 in
the United States and 6,000 abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil shares rose 68.75 cents, to $83.0625, Wednesday in
New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its heritage _ Exxon was the successor of the Standard
Oil Co. (New Jersey) and Mobil was originally the Standard Oil Co.
of New York _ Exxon Mobil has no significant presence in the New
York metropolitan area. Tom Cirigliano, an Exxon Mobil spokesman,
said that any job losses in the region would be trivial.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 60 percent of the shrinkage is to come from the former
Exxon and 40 percent from the former Mobil. Some 10,000 employees
are to be discharged while 6,000 are expected to take ``normal or
accelerated'' retirements, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the expected casualties are about 1,000 executives, or a
third of the pre-merger Exxon and Mobil contingents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the most difficult aspect of implementing a
merger as large as this one,'' Raymond said of the loss of jobs.
``We have plans in place to help cushion the impact on those who
must separate.''
</P>
<P>
   To win regulatory approval of the merger, the company agreed to
sell 2,431 gas stations, a California refinery and various
marketing and refining stakes in Europe. Proceeds from these sales
are expected to be $4 billion to $5 billion, Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, he added, should generate a one-time net addition of
$3.5 billion to cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said Wednesday that it planned to raise
production by 4 percent next year, twice what Knuettel, the
PaineWebber analyst, said he had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The session generally seemed to reinforce analysts' view of
ExxonMobil as a blockbuster company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hit home with a lot of investors there was the incredible
position this company is in now,'' said Wilson of J.P. Morgan.
``Both functionally and geographically, it is really awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
