<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to fix time elements throughout.) 
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weather pattern that has brought frequent surges of very
mild air from the Plains to the Northeast over the last few weeks
has begun to shift. Arctic air that has been locked in northern
Canada will be drawn toward the northern Mississippi Valley as jet
stream winds from the northwest become established over the center
of the continent. As a result, the coldest air of the season will
cover parts of the upper Middle West on Wednesday and Thursday
while the temperatures in the Northeast gradually fall to seasonal
values.
</P>
<P>
   Mild air will linger near the Northeast Coast for one more day.
A front marking the leading edge of colder air will sweep off the
Atlantic seaboard Wednesday. Variable clouds and a few rain showers
will accompany the front. In the wake of the front, progressively
colder air will sweep over the Great Lakes. As the chill deepens
later Wednesday, locally heavy snow squalls will occur near the
southern and eastern shores of the lakes from Michigan to western
New York. Snow showers will also whiten portions of the northern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be mainly dry and cooler. Sunshine will be
plentiful in the interior. But high, thin clouds will streak across
the sky near the Gulf Coast. Thicker clouds and a few showers will
occur in extreme southern parts Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Light snow will occur near the path of low pressure streaking
southeast from the Dakotas to the northern Missouri River Valley.
Farther west, gusty winds from the west will deliver milder air
across the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dust Storm
</P>
<P>
   Visibility usually increases following the passage of a cold
front, but, on Wednesday, dust darkened the skies for several hours
in the wake of a front crossing southern Texas. Winds from the west
gusting over 40 mph combined with dry soil conditions from recent
drought to raise palls of dust that dropped visibility below one
mile in some areas near Austin, Texas, and San Antonio. After a few
hours, the winds subsided allowing the dust to settle. While
Wednesday's dust storm was relatively small, severe dust storms can
be reminiscent of a blizzard leaving drifts of dust several feet
high.
</P>
</TEXT>
