A0275 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSPACE-BIOSPACE_SFC     12-15 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSPACE-BIOSPACE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Visa Exec Taking Job With Biotech Web Site  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   A San Francisco Web site that caters to the biotech industry
scored the latest in a series of minor coups todaycq &LR;  by luring a
Visa executive to direct its efforts to sell experimental supplies
to laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Les Mann, who helped Visa USA push credit cards into doctor's
offices, will become senior vice president of sales for
BioSpace.com. In his new post, Mann will direct an e-commerce
effort aimed at selling everything from test tubes to rare DNA
samples to a scientific market that spends $15 billion a year on
such supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Mann joins an executive team recently bolstered by the addition
of Scott Clarke, former chief information officer at Incyte
Pharmaceuticals. Clarke came to BioSpace last month to help build
the site into a full-service portal, offering product news and job
listings as well as direct sales.
</P>
<P>
   This spate of executive recruiting was fueled by a $14 million
venture capital round, as Sanderling Biomedical, Alloy Ventures and
Brentwood Capital pumped money into BioSpace and enabled its
50-person  &LR; staff of 50 to move into new offices in San Francisco's
busy South of Market neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The venture financing also puts the company on a trajectory
toward an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   BioSpace Chairwoman Jennifer King founded the company in 1985 to
sell maps and directories to the nascent biotech industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, King moved her business onto the Internet,
working with chief executive Timothy Fredel to make BioSpace a
niche portal for 100,000 biomedical scientists in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As BioSpace's newest hire, Mann will sell experimental supplies,
including rare DNA samples that cost $2,000 a drop and patented
enzymes that can easily run as high as $200 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to crack this lucrative, complex market _ BioSpace
already lists 700,000 products for sale _ the San Francisco firm
will face publicly traded competitors like Palo Alto's Chemdex and
North Carolina's SciQuest, which already sell scientific supplies
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mann's departure from Visa marks the third time in recent months
that an executive has jumped from the staid credit card association
to the technology world and its stock options.
</P>
<P>
   In September, former Visa advertising executive Michael
Beindorff took a job as chief operating officer for PlanetRX.com,
the South San Francisco online pharmacy. Last month, former Visa
marketing executive Jan Soderstrom took over a top branding post at
Santa Clara's 3Com Corp., a network equipment vendor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
