r a BC-WTO-COALITION-SPI &LR;      12-15 1866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-COALITION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON CAUSES BRING TOGETHER LABOR, ENVIRONMENTALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT McCLURE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a downtown church here, steelworkers shared the
pews with schoolgirls in sea-turtle costumes, teenagers in baggy
jeans, elderly women in comfortable shoes and bearded
forty-somethings with graying long hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for giving me a chance to speak here today for sea
turtles that don't have a voice,'' Todd Steiner of the Sea Turtle
Restoration Project recently told the hundreds assembled to protest
the World Trade Organization. ``Today, it is the shy and gentle sea
turtles. Tomorrow it will be our forests, our ability to prevent
child labor and prison labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd clapped enthusiastically. They carried signs saying,
``Free Trade  &QC;  Dead Sea Turtles'' and ``Stop exploiting workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., exhorted the group: ``Trade
unionists are some of the most dedicated environmentalists in this
country today.'' The crowd roared again.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, organized labor and the environmental movement stood
side by side in the most visible symbol to date of a growing
confederation.
</P>
<P>
   It may prove to be a lasting effect of the WTO's visit _ if the
groups can get past some longstanding conflicts commonly boiled
down into the shorthand ``jobs vs. the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to happen,'' said David Brower, the 87-year-old dean
of the modern American environmental movement. ``We will say
`Remember Seattle' like we say `Remember the Alamo' or `Remember
the Maine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If cemented, this alliance could prove a politically potent
combination, particularly if church and consumer groups that joined
the Seattle protests come along. It's a team that would have been
hard to imagine even a dozen years ago, but that seems increasingly
likely now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turtles and Teamsters united,'' says Ron Judd, president of
the King County Labor Council AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the partnership is tentative, limited largely to issues
in which both sides perceive they have a stake: The same
corporation that locks out steelworkers also clearcuts redwoods;
displaced timber workers land jobs restoring streams; a powerful
World Trade Organization simultaneously harms sea turtles and
workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has had some success, and has already blocked some
major U.S. international-trade and -investment initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side pretends they will always agree. It seems certain,
for example, that tree-huggers will clash with dock workers who
ship raw logs to Japan. Still, as in most marriages, the partners
are willing to overlook some discord.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who philosophically oppose unions and
environmentalists acknowledge the possibilities raised by the
pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remarkable phenomenon,'' said Brink Lindsey of The Cato
Institute, a Washington, D.C.-based libertarian-leaning think tank.
</P>
<P>
   THE COALITION had been building well before tens of thousands of
union members _ longshoremen, steelworkers, even airline pilots in
dress blue _ joined environmentalists for a non-violent rally and
show of strength during the Seattle WTO meetings.
</P>
<P>
   While the coalition might not have forced the collapse of the
Seattle talks, Lindsey said, ``It was standing there at the scene
of the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? How could the beefy union man be locking arms
with the latte liberal whose VW sports a Greenpeace bumper sticker?
</P>
<P>
   Much of it can be explained by the changing _ and shrinking _
union movement. Factor in environmentalists' perceived lack of
political firepower and a growing fear that global trade is leaving
behind a wide range of Americans _ including union rank-and-file
and people who like to hike. Sometimes, these are the same people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last decade, labor came out of this shell,'' said Tom
Juravich, director of The Labor Center at the University of
Massachusetts-Amherst. ``Even rank-and-file members are ...
realizing that tree-huggers are not their enemies any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor movement was born in the latter half of the 1800s of a
concern for working people. With those populist beginnings, unions
would seem a natural ally of the environmental movement that sprang
from an outpouring of anti-government sentiment in the late 1960s
and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But as the green movement was getting underway, so, too, were
protests against the Vietnam war. The Left found itself opposed
more often than not by a union movement whose titular head was the
anti-communist, pro-war George Meaney, leader of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, environmentalists have clashed with unionists on a
number of issues: nuclear power plant construction, efforts to
reduce the timber cut, road construction, steel mill emissions _
just about any time jobs were pitted against the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the debate over the North American Free Trade
Agreement in 1993, when unions feared losing jobs to Mexico and
environmentalists braced for pesticide-laden produce to start
coming in the other direction. They lost that fight, but discovered
that they could work together.
</P>
<P>
   `It was a new and uneasy coalition,'' recalls Thea Lee, an
AFL-CIO trade policy analyst. ``We were not altogether comfortable
(together).''
</P>
<P>
   THE GROUPS KEPT lobbying together, though, and twice shut down
President Clinton in his quest to quickly and easily expand NAFTA
membership. In various spots around the country, this partnership
trickled down to the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Before Seattle, this comfort level was perhaps best illustrated
by the Alliance for Sustainable Jobs and the Environment, which
formed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Eureka, Calif.-based coalition include Earth
Island Institute, Seattle/King County Building and Construction
Trades Council, Rainforest Action Network and the United
Brotherhood of Carpenters.
</P>
<P>
   Its first target was the Houston-based Maxxam Corporation, which
owns a majority of Kaiser Aluminum and is viewed as the force
behind the lockout of some 3,000 steelworkers in Washington, Ohio
and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Maxxam subsidiary Pacific Lumber Co., planned to
cut old-growth redwoods in Northern California if the government
didn't buy the forest for $480 million. That's extortion,
environmentalists said, even as they urged the government to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maxxam is a poster child for corporate power out of control,''
said Karen Pickett, a California forest activist who helped found
the new alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's co-chairmen are David Foster, Northwest director
for the United Steelworkers of America, and Brower, former Sierra
Club president and founder of Earth Island Institute and Friends of
the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Brower likes to quote Foster on the partnership: ``If you'll
promise to make sustainable jobs a part of environmental
protection, we will promise to make environmental protection our
most important job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The trans-national corporations are trying to run the world,''
Brower says of the coalition. ``There has to be something to
balance that out ...''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett said union allies help get past the ``tremendously huge
barrier'' she faces when opponents accuse environmentalists of
sacrificing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   When environmentalists and unionists talk to each other, ``we
find out that we really do want the same things,'' Pickett said.
``That doesn't mean that it's an easy route, but in my view, this
alliance is the best chance we've had so far to smash that
jobs-vs.-the-environment myth.''
</P>
<P>
   SEVERAL FACTORS are making the labor movement more open to
environmental causes, said Margaret Levi, director of the Center
for Labor Studies at the University of Washington. It starts with a
new generation of leadership. Judd, for example, is 46.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening with the new generation both of leaders and
workers is a recognition of quality-of-life issues,'' she said.
``We are seeing the rise of a kind of social unionism ... instead
of a narrow focus on the hours, wages and the health and safety of
the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the labor movement is looking for friends because
it has shrunk so much, she said. While about one in three American
workers was in a union in the late 1950s, today it's about one in
10. And the face of the workplace is changing, too.
</P>
<P>
   The caricature of ``a big white guy in a hard hat hating and
being hated by young long-haired hippie ... is being overcome
around issues like the WTO and environment and welfare and old age
pensions and health insurance,'' Levi said. ``These are issues that
really need large political coalitions to make a dent against very
well-organized, very well-financed business interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this coalition has yet to launch an offensive on those
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on a roll, but thus far their power has been purely
obstructionist,'' said Lindsey of the Cato Institute. ``Right now
they've got a blocking coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   And down the road, this coalition could actually haunt the
centrist ``new Democrats,'' says Alan Gottlieb, president of the
Center for the Defense of Free Enterprise in Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unholy alliance to some extent and it's not that
solid,'' Gottlieb said. ``They can come together against the WTO,
but if the environmentalists are pushing the Clinton-Gore
administration for something that costs jobs, that coalition comes
apart like crazy. It's going to cause a lot of problems inside the
Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and unions will have two more chances to see
if they can work together before the next presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the Congress will have the opportunity to back
out of the WTO. Both the House and Senate would have to pass a
resolution, which Clinton would undoubtedly veto. Then both houses
would have to override the veto, Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill. and chairman of the House Subcommittee
on Trade, recently said he expects Congress to favor continued WTO
membership, ``But I think we've got to work, and you can't take
anything for granted in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the AFL-CIO and its allies are unsure whether they will
mount a fight.
</P>
<P>
   But they are virtually certain to go after China. With China
joining the WTO, there is a movement in Congress to grant China a
normal trade relations status, which it lost after the 1989
Tiananmen Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that loom issues bound to divide the coalition. For
example, environmentalists are pressing Congress to accept the
Kyoto Protocol, a treaty committing the world to reducing emissions
of carbon dioxide and other industrial gasses believed to be
unnaturally overheating the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, at least, that could cost U.S. jobs _
something unions oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not completely in sync with environmentalists on climate
change,'' acknowledges Lee, of the AFL-CIO. Even so, both partners
agree poor nations should not be let off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled to find common ground,'' Lee said. ``We have a
respectful relationship ... We try to understand each other's
constituencies and each other's positions and work together on the
parts we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
