<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-TRADE-BOS &LR;      12-15 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BRING ABOARD A TRUE TRIPLE THREAT IN EVERETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think about this while weighing the significance of Wednesday's
trade that brought switch-hitting outfielder Carl Everett to the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In the past century, they've never had a center-fielder who in
one season produced with the combination of average, power and
speed that the 28-year-old Everett did with the Houston Astros last
season, when he hit .325, hit 25 home runs, drove in 108 runs and
stole 27 bases.
</P>
<P>
   And he's 28 years old.
</P>
<P>
   You have to go back to Tony Armas in 1984, when he hit 43 home
runs with 123 RBIs, to find a Sox center-fielder who had more home
runs and RBIs than Everett, and Armas hit .268 with one stolen base
that season.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Lynn had only one season, 1979, in which he hit more home
runs (39) and drove in more runs (122) than Everett. He ated
.333, one of only two seasons with the Sox in which Lynn outhit
Everett. And Lynn wasn't a base-stealer.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Smith? He hit 30 home runs in 1971, 25 homers two years
earlier, but stole more than 20 bases just once in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who came out of the same Tampa high school
(Hillsborough) as two other former first-rounders, pitcher Doc
Gooden and outfielder Gary Sheffield, has had just one big-league
season like he put together in Houston this past year, and in the
Red Sox is joining his fifth big-league organization, the Yankees,
Marlins, Mets and Astros all preceding them.
</P>
<P>
   But based on the numbers alone, he gives the Sox a
middle-of-the-lineup presence exceeded by only two American League
center-fielders in 1999: Ken Griffey Jr. of the Mariners and Bernie
Williams of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, then, why Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette was
willing to risk trading highly touted shortstop prospect Adam
Everett, the team's No. 1 draft choice in 1998, and promising Class
A lefthander Greg Wilson for a player who could walk away from the
Red Sox after next season and declare himself a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you break down his skills,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams
said from his home in Florida, ``there looks like there's an awful
lot of talent all the way around. To me, it looks like he's
developed into an outstanding player.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand, too, why the incumbent Sox center-fielder, Darren
Lewis, is looking at either a new role with the club next season or
a new address. Lewis has given the team Gold Glove-caliber defense
and brought a winner's approach to the Sox clubhouse, but his lack
of offensive punch led Duquette to pursue the Yankees' Williams
unsuccessfully a year ago before landing Everett Wednesday. And
while Everett may not be Lewis' equal defensively, he runs better
and has a stronger arm, recording 10 outfield assists last season.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, whose agent, Jim Bronner, said he believed the player was
in Argentina on a fishing trip, is due to be paid $5.1 million over
the next two seasons by the Sox, a payout that in all likelihood
will lead Duquette to shop Lewis' services between now and the
start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the 32-year-old Lewis rates as an outstanding
extra outfielder on a good ballclub, one who could still amass 350
at-bats while platooning with Trot Nixon in right and spelling
Everett and left-fielder Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never have enough good players,'' Williams said.
``What Darren brings to the table in a lot of cases does not show
up in the stats. As far as I'm concerned, he's an integral part of
the ballclub. He's an important person, first and foremost. He
understands how to win. He knows how to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you talk about the kind of player you have in Carl
Everett, whom you traded for primarily as a center fielder, if
that's the situation when the season begins, you expand Darren
Lewis' skills. You can only play three guys at a time, but that's a
pretty good guy to be coming off the bench. But over the lonbg
scheme of things, players here get the opportunity to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronner declined to comment when asked how he thought the
Everett deal impacted on his client.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, who said he finalized the deal with the Astros
Wedneday morning, said he had spoken only briefly with Everett, and
that was just to congratulate him on the deal. Everett was not
present on the conference call announcing the trade. His agent,
Larry Reynolds, said Everett did not take part because his fifth
child, a boy, had just been born two nights earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said he has yet to gauge Everett's willingness to make
a long-term commitment to the Sox. The player, who was paid $2.4
million by the Astros this year, is eligible for salary arbitration
this winter, and would almost certainly double his salary if he
goes that route. Just as in the case of Pedro Martinez, who like
Everett was a year away from free agency when the Sox traded for
him two years ago, Duquette would like to lock up Everett in a
multiyear deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a chance to have a lot of discussion about the
long-term thing,'' said Reynolds, who also represents Lynn's Ken
Hill. ``His reaction is that he's a professional. He really enjoyed
himself in Houston. He's a very personable guy, very respected in
the clubhouse, he got close to a lot of players. This was a little
bit of a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros were in a salary crunch after signing All-Star
second baseman Craig Biggio to a long-term and facing big-money
tickets for pitchers Jose Lima and Mike Hampton and slugger Jeff
Bagwell looking at free agency after the 2001 season. The Astros
would have preferred to deal Moises Alou, but he has a no-trade
clause, and there was little interest in Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   So it came down to Everett. ``This was a big surprise to Carl,''
Reynolds said. ``But he's going to be fine. A few weeks from now,
in a few days, we'll talk to Carl about a (long-term deal).''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette moved swiftly with Martinez, signing him to a six-year
deal three weeks after trading for him. Astros GM Gerry Hunsicker
would not give Duquette permission to negotiate with Everett in
advance. ``That's because the Astros had other teams willing to
take his contract,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have reason to give up prospects to the Astros. The last
trade between Boston and Houston, the Sox sent Bagwell to the
Astros for reliever Larry Andersen, still lamented as one of the
worst deals in club history.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Everett, rated the top defensive college player in the
draft when he was picked by the Sox in '98, rose rapidly through
the team's system, finishing last season in Double-A Trenton. But
Duquette felt there were a couple of reasons the club could deal
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Nomar Garciaparra will be our shortstop for a long
time,'' he said, ``and we have another kid at shortstop, Cesar
Siba, who played in the New York-Penn League, that we like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees drafted Everett No. 10 overall in the country in
1990, then lost him a couple of years later to the Florida Marlins
in the expansion draft. The Marlins, discouraged at his slow
progress, traded him in 1994 to the Mets for Quilvio Veras, who
became their second baseman. Everett played parts of three
undistinguished seasons with the Mets before being traded to
Houston in the aftermath of an ugly off-field situation, in which
child-abuse charges were brought against the player and his wife,
Linda.
</P>
<P>
   In August, 1997, Everett's two children were taken into custody
by New York City officials after a Shea Stadium child-care worker
noticed bruises on his 6-year-old daughter, Shawna. Charges of
child abuse were subsequently dropped by a Family Court judge, who
ruled that Everett's wife, Linda, inflicted ``excessive corporal
punishment'' on their two children and the player did little to
stop her.
</P>
<P>
   In a later court ruling, the couple, who underwent counseling,
regained custody of their son but lost custody of their daughter
(Linda Everett's stepdaughter), who was placed with other
relatives. The couple have had two children since.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Sox and Everett's agent addressed questions about the
New York incident Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl addressed the issues,'' Duquette said. ``They've been
resolved. He's performed very well, he has been a very good
teammate in Houston. The Red Sox looked into the concerns and
problems he had in New York. That was in 1997. We believe he has
matured from his experience in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reynolds: ``The matter is an old issue. It came up two
years ago. It was handled, and taken care of to the satisfaction of
the people of New York. It's a nonissue as far as we're concerned.
This guy's a real special person.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he remained hopeful of signing a free-agent
pitcher before the end of the week. Asked why he didn't use Adam
Everett in a trade for as pitcher, he said: ``Because Adam Everett
alone wasn't going to bring a pitcher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
