<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEBOOKS-NOTEBOOKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Notebooks to Fill Anyone's Holiday List  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Notebook PCs still cost a lot more than full-size models, but
little by little, prices are coming down, and processing speed,
storage capacity, screen size and quality keep improving.
<P>
   Today you can get a clunky but capable Windows 98 notebook for
as little as $1,100, and for $1,500 to $2,500, you can choose from
an enormous array of models, including some that weigh only a few
pounds, some with amazing multimedia capabilities and some that
sport ultrafast processors. Communications capabilities have
improved, too: Almost every new notebook has a 56K modem built in,
and a few also come with high-speed network ports.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the right laptop, though, is still a challenge. It's a
game of trade-offs and compromises. The roomier the screen and
keyboard, the more the machine will weigh. If you want floppy and
CD-ROM (or even DVD) drives built in, your machine won't be
ultrathin. And the more processing power and features you get, the
faster your battery is apt to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   I've recently checked out five PC notebooks, each offering
something special in the way of price, design or features. This
survey is by no means comprehensive: Each of the companies
represented here also offers many other mobile models, and there
are dozens of manufacturers I didn't include, including Compaq,
Dell, Gateway and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   I also left out Apple's notebooks, because I reviewed the
PowerBook G3 and iBook earlier this year (July 15 and October 21,
respectively). Both are worth considering if you're not wedded to
Windows, as long as you're not looking for a featherweight model.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the low-down on the PC models.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Acer TravelMate 340 and NEC Versa FX. Acer's latest TravelMate 340
and NEC's new Versa FX are both part of a new class of notebooks
that combine light weight with high performance and rich feature
sets. Both include the latest generation (code-named
``Coppermine'') of Intel's Pentium III processor _ the Versa FX's
runs at 400 megahertz, the TravelMate's runs 50 megahertz faster.
Both have 64 megabytes of RAM, 6-gigabyte hard drives and bright,
clear 12.1-inch active-matrix displays. The TravelMate weighs 4.1
pounds, the Versa FX 3.5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Both come not only with an external floppy drive, but also with
an external CD-ROM drive _ an essential item, if only for
installing software, and one that's not included in the base price
of most other ultraportables. The NEC drives, even if you carry
both, are smaller and lighter than Acer's chunky combo unit. And
while the TravelMate is mostly a ho-hum gray, the Versa FX has a
trendy polished-silver exterior with subtle purple accents.
</P>
<P>
   But at $1,999, the TravelMate costs $500 less than the Versa FX.
While both have 56K modems built in, Acer also includes a 10-or
100-megabit networking port _ a terrific convenience if you take
your notebook to the office or to connect it to a cable or DSL
modem. If you want to do that with the NEC model, you'll have to
buy an Ethernet PC Card adapter for around $100.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the battery issue. Like most other ultralight
models, the Versa FX achieves its low weight in part by skimping on
battery size _ in my tests, the prototype NEC provided consistently
ran out of juice after less than 75 minutes. Acer's battery lasted
more than twice as long; still not enough, but a whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Between these two models, I'd call the TravelMate the hands-down
winner. Overall, I don't know of a better value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_IBM ThinkPad i Series 1480. Trying to transfer its prestige in the
world of corporate computing to the mass market, IBM last year
introduced a family of notebooks called the ThinkPad i Series,
which includes machines for consumers (the 1400 series) and
small-businesses (1500 series).
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried out, the i Series 1480, is a great multimedia
machine, but it has a price and girth to match: It lists for
$2,299, weighs 7.7 pounds, and measures 12.9 inches wide, 10.6
inches deep and 1.7 inches high when closed _ by far the largest
model covered in this review.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a sleek, jet-black case, you'll find a gorgeous 14.1-inch
active-matrix scene, backed by a 466-megahertz Mobile Celeron
processor, 64 megabytes of RAM and a 6.4-gigabyte hard drive. The
1480 also has a DVD-ROM drive, so you can watch movies with it, and
an S-video jack, so you can watch them on your TV or video monitor.
(The i Series 1460, with CD-ROM instead of DVD and a slightly
slower processor and smaller hard drive, is $2,099.)
</P>
<P>
   IBM also provides several nice touches, including extra,
color-coded buttons above the keyboard you can customize to launch
your favorite applications, and a small light that can illuminate
the keyboard when you're working in the dark. You can play music
CDs in the DVD drive even when the system is off; the volume dial
and other controls are located on a readily accessible panel at the
front of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this justify the cost and size of the 1480? Not for me,
since I don't see much point in a portable this big and heavy. You
can get a comparably equipped desktop PC for half the price or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I can see why some people might prefer it to a desktop
model: It takes up less space, it looks more elegant, it's light
enough to move from room to room and of course you can run it on
battery power, for about 2 hours, 20 minutes in my test.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Sony PictureBook. In the past 18 months,  &LR; ago  &LR; Sony has shaken
 &LR; shook  &LR; up the notebook world _ and more than doubled its share of
the U.S. market _ with a series of machines that combine good
looks, light weight and strong support for digital multimedia. The
best-known example is the superslim VAIO 505. But the most unusual
is the PictureBook (officially, the VAIO PCG-C1X), a 2.5-pound
minimodel that sells for $1,799.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, the PictureBook's hardware is
unremarkable. Its main chip is a relatively ancient 266-MHz Pentium
with MMX, though that's backed by an ample 64 megabytes of RAM and
a 4.3-gigabyte hard drive. The active-matrix screen is bright and
crisp, but it's only about 8 inches wide and 4 inches high _ an
unusual shape that delivers a resolution of 1,024 by 480 pixels.
</P>
<P>
   There's a 56K modem built in, and it comes with a tiny external
floppy drive, but a CD-ROM drive will cost you an extra $200 to
$300. What's unique about the PictureBook is a digital camera built
right into the top of the screen. It's housed in a cylindrical part
that rotates 180 degrees, so you can point it at anything,
including yourself (a feature my daughters loved when we took a
PictureBook along on a family vacation). One press of a special
button snaps a still image or up to 60 seconds of video.
</P>
<P>
   Because the camera captures only 270,000 pixels per shot _ only
a quarter to an eighth the resolution typical of today's
stand-alone digital cameras _ image quality falls far short of what
you'd expect from even a cheap point-and-shoot film camera. Still,
for small, informal shots, especially ones you plan to use only in
e-mail or on your Web page, the pictures looked surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   The PictureBook comes with a slew of programs to help you take
maximum advantage of the camera. Sony's Smart Write and Smart
Publisher, for example, let you combine words and pictures and
convert them to Web pages; Adobe's PhotoDeluxe Business Edition
lets you edit and manipulate your digital images; and Sony's
PictureGear can stitch a sequence of individual shots into a
360-degree panorama.
</P>
<P>
   When you're done shooting, you can e-mail your shots immediately
with the built-in modem or upload offload  &LR; them to an external hard
drive via a speedy, hassle-free i.Link (also known as FireWire or
IEEE 1394) port.
</P>
<P>
   Unless photography is a major part of what you do, you'd
probably be happier with a machine with a bigger screen and
keyboard. And if you're serious enough about photography, you'll
probably want a higher-resolution camera.
</P>
<P>
   But if you do lots of photography and being able to upload your
shots easily and quickly is more important to you than high
resolution, the PictureBook's convenience can't be beat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Toshiba Satellite 1555CDS. Toshiba has long been a market leader
in mobile computing. Among its many models, I asked to borrow its
least expensive, the $1,099 Satellite 1555CDS, because that's about
as cheap and as up-to-date as name-brand notebooks come, and I
wanted to see what you get, and give up, at that price. (A few
lowball competitors, including Emachines and WinBook, have new
models at $999.)
</P>
<P>
   The Satellite 1555 has decent features: a 380-megahertz Mobile
K6-2, a Pentium clone made by Advanced Micro Devices, plus 32
megabytes of RAM, a 4.3-gigabyte hard drive and a 12.1-inch screen.
A floppy drive, CD-ROM drive and 56K modem are built in. The whole
package weighs about 6.9 pounds, and the battery lasted just over
two hours in my tests.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough horsepower for basic applications, e-mail and Web
surfing. With only 32 megabytes of RAM, the machine has to spend a
lot of time reading and writing data on the hard drive, but you
could speed things up by boosting memory to 64 megabytes for
another $100 to $150.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem for me was the screen. It's a dual-scan or
passive-matrix display, as opposed to the TFT or active-matrix
technology used in most notebooks, including all the others in this
review. Dual-scan displays aren't as bright or sharp, and objects
on the screen cast grayish shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Those are only aesthetic problems and you might be willing to
tolerate them for the money you save. But there's another issue
that seriously reduces the usability of this machine and others in
its class: Dual-scan displays are slow at redrawing the screen when
something changes; they can't even keep up with cursor movements.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Almost every time you move the arrow pointer, it
disappears _ a phenomenon known as ``submarining.'' If I had to use
this machine regularly, I suppose I'd adjust my cursor-moving
habits. I'd also get more adept with the pointing stick that
Toshiba provides instead of a mouse. But I'm afraid this
submarining problem would remain an annoyance _ and probably a real
drag on my productivity.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I like a bargain, I find this one a false one. My
strong suggestion, if you want a Toshiba, is to save up until you
can afford the Satellite 2100CDT, a $1,699 model that's similar to
the one I tested. Itcomes with 64 megabytes of memory and an
active-matrix screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
