<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chevron Sells S.F. Offices For $189 Million  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Taking advantage of the red-hot Bay Area property market, Chevron
Corp. said yesterday that it pocketed $189.1 million from the sale
of its headquarters buildings in downtown San Francisco.
<P>
   The winning bid was submitted by New York's Tishman
Speyer/Travelers Real Estate Venture, which also owns the Chrysler
Building in New York City, among other commercial properties.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Yemma, manager of transactions for Chevron Real Estate
Management Co., a subsidiary of the oil company, said San
Francisco's sky-high property prices were a factor in the company's
decision to sell its buildings. ``We're at the top of the property
market,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   But Yemma also said Chevron is eager to focus on its oil and gas
operations, rather than on real estate assets. ``We think we can
get better future returns on oil and gas than we can on real
estate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the company's San Francisco headquarters, he said
Chevron buildings in Southern California and Texas are also for
sale, with the deals expected to close within the next couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron said in May that it was looking to cut costs by selling
off its two San Francisco towers at 555 and 575 Market St. The
company said it would move two-thirds of its approximately 1,400
employees in the city to facilities in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron said yesterday that it will lease back 11 floors in 575
Market, which will remain the company's headquarters. The company's
senior executives, financial operations and investor relations unit
will remain in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus of other workers to the East Bay already is under way
and will be completed by the end of 2000, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Yemma declined to say how many competing bids were received for
the San Francisco buildings. He said, however, that the winning
$189.1 million offer was ``within our expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   At this price, Tishman Speyer paid about $255 a foot for each &LR; 
of the  &LR; 740,000 square feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the buildings were in good shape, I'd say it's a good
price,'' said Barry Bram, vice president of TRI Commercial/Oncor
International, one of the largest commercial real estate firms in
Northern California. ``But my sense is that there's a lot of work
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Such work, he speculated, might include bringing the buildings
up to code for asbestos and electrical wiring or renovating whole
floors to attract tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Wechsler, senior managing director of Tishman Speyer
Properties, acknowledged that asbestos exists on ``several floors''
of 555 Market but said it won't be difficult to clean up. He also
said both buildings will need to be tinkered with to meet today's
power and technology needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge demand for this space from Internet companies
and other technology companies,'' he said, adding that prospective
tenants have been touring the premises since last month.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings were officially listed on the market yesterday,
with rents termed negotiable. Wechsler said he hopes to have them
up to full occupancy within a year and half.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
