<HEADLINE>
USING MARKET FORCES TO MODEL ELECTION RACES 
PUTTING IT ALL TOGETHER: HELP FOR TOY ASSEMBLY 
A VIRTUAL MOOD RING TRACKS NATION'S EMOTIONS 
LINKING WALL STREET TO THE SKI SLOPES 
CELL PHONES DESIGNED TO CALL ONLY A SINGLENUMBER: 911 
EUDORA TAKES THE PLUNGE INTO ADVERTISING SPONSORSHIP
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Iowa, Mass., Colo., N.C., Minn., Mich.)  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, professors at the University of Iowa have provided
political junkies a financial outlet for their wild speculation.
The Iowa Electronic Markets is an online system that enables people
to bid on the presidential or congressional candidates they think
are most likely to win. Anyone could jump in _ as long as he was
willing to spend at least $5 and had a Telnet connection to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Now the markets are available on the Web
(www.biz.uiowa.edu/iem), and an increasing number of
prognosticators are putting their money where their mouths are.
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Forsythe, an economics professor, and several other
Iowa professors started the project in 1988, fewer than 200 traders
got involved. This year about 3,900 people have signed up. The
total investment is more than $86,000. Anyone online can place
bids, worth up to $500, on the outcomes of the Republican and
Democratic presidential nominations, the makeup of the Senate and
House of Representatives, and the outcome in the U.S. Senate race
in New York between Hillary Clinton and, presumably, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York.
</P>
<P>
   If a selected candidate wins, the trader who bid on that
candidate receives $1 for every share purchased. For example, if
Mrs. Clinton wins the New York race, those who bid for her at 30
cents a share (her going price on Wednesday) will make a 70 cent
profit on each share.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the going price for President Clinton was only one
percentage point away from the percentage of people who actually
voted for him, a prediction that many pollsters would envy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   Putting It All Together: Help for Toy Assembly
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, there is one phrase that can strike terror
into the hearts of parents: Some assembly required. Netoy.com, a
Web-based toy retailer, isn't promising to stick toys together
before shipment. However, this month it will introduce a series of
animated drawings and assembly directions on its site,
www.netoy.com, that may make the job a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came from an observation that most tasks are easier to do
if someone demonstrates them,'' said Steve Arend, Netoy.com's vice
president for product development. The instruction sheets show
assembly step by step. Virtual tubes of plastic cement even show
where the glue should go.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions do not offer advice on how to remove the
plastic cement that strayed onto a user's keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ian Austen
</P>
<P>
   A Virtual Mood Ring Tracks Nation's Emotions
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is two kinds of ice cream, catching a firefly and,
possibly, living in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.
Dailyrating.com, a site that started up in June, tracks the
nation's emotional state based on daily messages from more than
4,000 e-mail correspondents. Dailyrating.com then maps relative
degrees of happiness three ways: state by state on a USA
Today-style weather map, on a nationwide graph and on a chart that
compares the moods of men and women. Recent results indicate that
people in Minnesota are not happy, nationally the mood appears to
mirror the Dow Jones industrial average and men have rallied to
have better days than women.
</P>
<P>
   The site, created by two North Carolina State graduates, Calvin
Tarlton and Lance Lovette, is intended to help its e-mail
correspondents (who can register free at www.dailyrating.com) to
maintain online diaries. ``We were always complaining about one
thing or another,'' Tarlton said. ``We thought it would be a good
idea to track it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   Linking Wall Street To the Ski Slopes
</P>
<P>
   First, laptop computers were dragged along on vacations. Then
came the cell phones, small enough to go anywhere and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's the stock market that is available to anyone skiing at
four different Colorado resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Vail Resorts has a three-year deal with DLJDirect, the online
subsidiary of the investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, to
provide slopeside Internet stock trading. The agreement includes
nine free computer terminals to be located at four different
midmountain lodges at Keystone, Breckenridge, Beaver Creek and
Vail, all of which are owned by Vail Resorts. Skiers will be able
to get up-to-the-minute stock quotes, as well as open new accounts
and purchase stock once they have been approved online. Day trading
will be discouraged, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of customer that typically uses online trading is
very similar to our customers,'' said Paul Witt, a spokesman for
Vail Resorts. ``The demographics match up pretty nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is one computer terminal up and running for stock
trading, and the others will be installed by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Vail Resorts is a publicly traded company, and
theoretically an investor could be trading Vail stock while on the
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the snow's looking really good, then you might be thinking,
`Buy, buy, buy,''' Witt said, jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mindy Sink
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cell Phones Designed to Call Only a Single Number: 911
</P>
<P>
   While it may resemble a sleek cell phone, the Magnavox Mobile911
can't call home or even the office. As its name suggests, it is
designed to dial only one number: 911.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath its flip-back keypad cover, the familiar set of
telephone keys has been replaced with one large, red button. When
it is pressed, the device calls a local 911 operator, linking a
user, in a toll-free call, with emergency help.
</P>
<P>
   The device, which costs $199, does not require cellular phone
service or additional fees. It also has a built-in 95-decibel
siren, which is about as loud as a car alarm. The siren is turned
on and off by pressing two buttons on the sides of the device. (The
alarm will also shut off when the device completes a 911 call.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It can make a lot of noise and call for help,'' said Mike
Bernstein, co-founder of SecureAlert, which developed the
telephone. ``These are the first two rules of self-defense.'' The
Magnavox Mobile911 is sold only online at www.mobile911.com and
through a toll-free number, (800) 584-4176.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Takes the Plunge Into Advertising Sponsorship
</P>
<P>
   Eudora, one of the leading e-mail programs on the market, is
going to introduce a version that contains advertising but is free
to users. Until now, Eudora came in two flavors: a free but
scaled-down version called Eudora Light and the much more powerful
Eudora Pro that sells for $49.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that we've turned the traditional Internet ad model
on its head,'' said Jeffery K. Belk, vice president of Qualcomm and
general manager of the Eudora division. ``Of course, using the word
traditional about something so new as Web advertisement is kind of
ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Miller, senior analyst at the Cahners In-Stat Group, a
research firm in Cambridge, Mass., thinks that Qualcomm may be on
to something. ``Users can choose the level of intrusion the ads
cause,'' he said. Miller noted that e-mail is the top application
on the Internet _ 97 percent of all Internet users use it.
</P>
<P>
   A beta version of the software is available at the Eudora Web
site (www.eudora.com). Belk insists that the advertisements will be
less intrusive than banner ads at most Web sites. ``First of all,
the ads are static, no animation will be allowed,'' he said.
``Secondly, the ads are placed in the lower left-hand corner so as
to not interfere with handling your e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the ads may be static, a series of them rotates in the ad
space (one every 75 seconds) while one is using the program. The
program caches (stores) about 20 ads, and when a cycle is complete,
the next time a user checks e-mail, a new group of ads is
downloaded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephen C. Miller
</P>
</TEXT>
