revered symbol of postwar prosperity, these rectangular houses,
with their rec rooms and picture windows and skinny wrought-iron
balustrades, are now as dated as Melmac. (Phillippe Diederich/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 15, 1999 -- SMITHSONIAN-AFRICA -- A
sculpture by Lamidi Fakeye of Nigeria in ``African Voices,'' a new
permanent exhibition at the Smithsonian Institution's National
Museum of Natural History. The collection of vivid, hands-on
exhibits is designed to illuminate the diverse African experience
along a time line stretching from the origins of humans to the
growth of African immigrant populations around the world. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) VIRGINIA DALE, Colo. -- Dec. 15, 1999 --
NUNNERY-ROCKIES-3 -- The chapel is both the head and the heart of
life in the new Abbey of St. Walburga. During early prayers, the
sisters, facing one another across the chapel, can watch the sun
rise through its many windows. On the floor between them is a cross
formed from the darkest of the red earth-toned tiles. (Kevin
Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) VIRGINIA DALE, Colo. -- Dec. 15, 1999 --
NUNNERY-ROCKIES-2 -- Sister Hildegard Dubnick in her bedroom in the
new Abbey of St. Walburga. ``You're in the chapel, but the valley
and the rocks and the trees are right there, too,'' Sister
Hildegard Dubnick says of the abbey's integration into its natural
surroundings. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) VIRGINIA DALE, Colo. -- Dec. 15, 1999 --
NUNNERY-ROCKIES-1 -- Cradled by a rocky, gray-brown bluff, the new
Abbey of St. Walburga suggests an old stone monastery. In November,
the 21 nuns of the abbey moved into the nunnery, which was designed
and built for them here in northern Colorado, about five miles from
Wyoming. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ATLANTA - Dec. 15, 1999 - GWTW-MUSEUM-2-COX -- Lynn
Watson-Powers, curator of the Gone With The Wind Museum, holds a
pair of pants which was part of Clark Gable's wardrobe during the
movie at the museum. The museum opens to the public on December 16.
(Louie Favorite/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ATLANTA - Dec. 15, 1999 - GWTW-MUSEUM-1-COX --
