<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-MEDICAL-NYT     12-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MEDICAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL REPORT ON GORE FINDS HIM IN `OUTSTANDING' CONDITION 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is in top physical condition with
excellent heart function, although his blood lipids are mildly
elevated, according to a three-page medical summary that was
prepared by the White House physician and released Wednesday by
Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``is in outstanding health'' and does not routinely use
prescription medications, Dr. Richard Tubb, the White House
physician who provides health care for the vice president and his
family, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   A routine checkup performed last May 7 at the National Naval
Medical Center in Bethesda, Md., by a panel of military and
civilian doctors showed that the 51-year-old Gore had only minor
medical problems. He had a mild high-frequency hearing loss. It
does not interfere with normal conversation and has not changed
since his last previous hearing test, in 1995. Because the hearing
loss is possibly related to exposure to loud noises from aircraft,
doctors have advised Gore to wear ear plugs at airports and
helipads. The vice president uses them periodically, Tubb said.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the medical information came less than a week after
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only rival for the
Democratic presidential nomination, canceled an afternoon of
campaigning because of an irregular heartbeat that he said caused
him no symptoms of heart problems. Bradley takes a drug, Procanbid,
twice a day to control the condition, which is known as paroxysmal
atrial fibrillation.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bonney Ratcliff, a Gore spokeswoman, said the findings
of the May checkup were issued only now because news organizations
had not requested them until recently. Results of the vice
president's periodic medical examinations are not routinely made
public.
</P>
<P>
   The results of a standard group of blood and urine laboratory
tests were normal except for his cholesterol and another lipid
measurement. Gore's total cholesterol of 231 was higher than the
ideal of less than 200, and his LDL (low density lipoprotein, or
bad cholesterol) was 157, higher than the ideal of 130 or less. His
HDL, (high density lipoprotein, or good cholesterol), was 55, above
the ideal of 35.
</P>
<P>
   Tubb said a cholesterol-lowering drug was not prescribed for
Gore because he did not have any other risk factors for heart
disease and did not meet criteria in national guidelines for such
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Use of a cholesterol-lowering drug in someone like Gore is
debatable, many doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Tubb said that he treated the vice president as he would any
other patient and that ``the lifestyle desires of the patient are
as or more important than the actual numbers'' from laboratory
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Tubb said he would check Gore's lipid values again in a few
months to determine how they responded to his diet. The doctors
have recommended that Gore eat a diet of high complex
carbohydrates, low saturated fats and high fiber to control his
cholesterol.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Malakoff, the director of the division of general
internal medicine at George Washington University Hospital, and Dr.
M. Anthony Casolaro, the chief of medicine at Arlington Hospital in
Virginia, said they agreed with Tubb's decision not to prescribe a
cholesterol-lowering drug for Gore. Tubb sent the medical summary
to the two doctors for comments to reporters. Both doctors said
they were not part of the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Antonio Gotto, dean of Cornell Medical College in New York
City and a leader in conducting trials of lipid-lowering drugs to
prevent heart disease, said he favored an aggressive approach and
would prescribe such a drug for Gore, even though he did not meet
the criteria for it in national guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's treadmill test results were excellent as he ran for a
total of 19 minutes, reaching Stage 7, and achieving 105 percent of
maximum predicted heart performance. ``He's at the level of a
trained athlete,'' said Consolaro, who is a team physician for the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Gore completed his first marathon in October 1997 and recently
climbed Mount Rainier in Washington State, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's blood pressure was a normal 110/68, his pulse 58 and
regular. He weighed 195 pounds and was 6 feet 1 inch tall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not used tobacco since 1973, when he stopped a
pack-a-day use of cigarettes that began in 1968. He has an
occasional beer but has no history of heavy alcohol use.
</P>
<P>
   No polyps were found at his last colon examination, in 1995.
Gore is due for another colon examination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore routinely uses sunscreen and has had no evidence of
recurrence of a basal cell skin cancer that was removed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He had no evidence of limitations from sports-related injuries
in the past. In a pickup basketball game in August 1994, Gore had
surgery to repair a torn Achilles tendon, which anchors the calf
muscles to the heel. But he has not had any limitations in walking
from that injury or from others, Tubb said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dislocated his left shoulder in 1958, broke his ankle in
1980 and strained his right shoulder while skiing last February. An
exercise and stretching program has relieved the low back pain that
Gore had experienced in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had surgery to repair an inguinal hernia in 1989. He wears
glasses to correct his vision to 20/20.
</P>
<P>
   Tubb said that he expected Gore to have another checkup some
time next year, but that the date was ``up in the air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
