<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0312 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SANTA-LETTERS-NYT     12-15 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SANTA-LETTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL ON THE SCREEN REPLACES LETTERS TO SANTA ON THE FRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By ELIZABETH STONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If my sons are organized about anything, it is Christmas, or at
least their Christmas wish lists. So I wasn't surprised during a
snack break in early December that they were writing their annual
letters to Santa. Or more precisely to Mrs. Santa, which is how I
think of myself at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, these scrawled lists would appear, without much
comment, posted by magnet on the refrigerator. Ah, sweet tradition.
Ah, tender little scrawls.
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget it. This year, we're talking e-mail. On a recent
morning when I sat down at my desk, a missive from each of my sons
awaited me, although I was immediately grateful that at least they
both had bypassed this year's profusion of online
fill-in-the-blanks Christmas wish lists.
</P>
<P>
   Son No. 1, Paul, had sent his list across the vast tundra
separating his attic warren from the rest of the household. A
basically reasonable person, he wanted a few T-shirts, quite a few
CDs and a variety of videos (and a car stereo, but for that one he
decided to solicit more directly). The e-mail in front of me left
nothing to chance. After his salutation ``Yo Yo, Ma,'' in red and
green letters, a sea of blue followed. Not Hanukkah blue, but
hypertext blue, which would whisk me to the precise objects of his
desire.
</P>
<P>
   All I had to do was choose among his choices. And pay. Since
none of the presents he wanted were items that had to be checked
for itchiness or smell, I can't say I minded.
</P>
<P>
   Son No. 2, Gabe, a newer teenager, was both more high-tech and
more old-fashioned. Wanting to cover all bases, he had sent his
e-mail to my primary screen name, but he had also sent copies to my
other screen name, and his father's, and his brother's. Just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   He was less pointed in a few of his choices. He, too, wanted
clothes (``make sure they're baggy'') but unlike his brother, he
had left me no hypertext trail. He wanted me to put on my coat and
go out of the house. According to his instructions, his brother was
to join me (``let Paul pick out some cool clothes'') and then I was
to pay. For the rest of his list, he named video games and
equipment, each followed by clumps of asterisks to let me know his
priorities (``the more (STAR)s, the more I like it'').
</P>
<P>
   That was how it began. The next day, he sent a second e-mail,
again with copies to all of us, including himself, in case the need
for proof in court arose. He had attached a picture of a wristwatch
he had found while surfing, one with so many luminous digits and
buttons and dials on its face it could have passed for a 747
control panel: ``i like this,'' he had written in neon chartreuse
against a black background, ``do you?''
</P>
<P>
   I was touched. These days, he generally doesn't want to know my
opinion. About anything, much less items that are proximate to his
body. It was also the kind of exchange that we never could have had
in the old days of notes posted on the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote back that I did like the watch but that I didn't know
which Web site it had come from.
</P>
<P>
   When I checked my e-mail the next morning, his third message had
arrived, this time including the necessary hyperlink. Underneath,
he had written, ``it's in the last row, second from the right _ the
analog watch with the gold and silver band and the black
background. It's $85'' and signed himself as ``gabe $.'' His last
name begins with S, so I took the dollar sign to be his recognition
that $85 was pricey.
</P>
<P>
   In a P.S., he added a final Web page with directions to a watch
that he thought I might like for myself. I did, and I told him so.
</P>
<P>
   In the next week as we window-shopped via e-mail, my younger son
and I developed the makings of a small epistolary novel. Within the
messages was a profusion of new hyperlinks, each one annotated with
a question, a comment, a retraction or a reaffirmation. Which one
to choose? As for the watch, he had picked for me, he was
encouraging. ``Go for it, Mom,'' he wrote, ``get it for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of the week brought the denouement. ``Hey hey hey, the
final decision,'' read the subject heading. His final choice was
analog, black background, silver band.
</P>
<P>
   Then, silence.
</P>
<P>
   But the following day came a new message, one I opened with some
hesitancy, given that the subject line read, ``A Message from
Amazon.com about my new Wish List.'' Was this a hoax? The use of
capital letters in e-mail violated my son's cyberliterary
conventions. I opened it. Inside was a message allegedly from my
son. ``Howdy, I've set up my holiday Wish List.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance. My son would sooner eat worms than write the word
``Howdy.'' The only sign of his presence in the whole message was a
check mark next to the portable CD player in the ``I want'' box.
But I did write him back to say that I had received the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   For now, that has turned out to be the end of the series. With a
little more than a week to go before Christmas, my fingers have
done all the shopping they are going to do. Now they're on to the
wrapping. But I'm still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
