<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IND-COMMON-PRECEPTS-N     12-15 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IND-COMMON-PRECEPTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA COUNTY SCHOOL BOARD CARVES ITS OWN CODE OF BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: optional sidebar, listing the precepts, is at end of
article)  
 (bl)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSBURG, Ind. _ Given its druthers, the school board in this
southern Indiana town would post the Ten Commandments in
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But because that would be a clear violation of the First
Amendment, the board decided to carve its own tablet of moral
behavior: the 11 ``Common Precepts.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with ``Trust in God,'' the code urges students to
respect others, save sex for marriage and avoid drugs and alcohol,
as well as tell the truth and honor their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to teach religion,'' said Robert Hooker, the
school superintendent, noting that the edict about trusting God,
taken from the words on U.S. currency, makes no reference to a
specific religion. ``With kids killing kids, and so many negative
images out there, we're just trying to put forth a positive
message.''
</P>
<P>
   If the strategy was intended to appease civil libertarians, it
has not worked. Kenneth Falk, a lawyer for the American Civil
Liberties Union in Indianapolis, said he would file suit against
the Scott County school district if it posted the behavior code.
</P>
<P>
   To Falk, the Common Precepts sound a lot like Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suspiciously tracks the Ten Commandments,'' Falk said.
``The edict to trust in God is clearly a religious notion.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the school board excised the reference to God, Falk
said, the code might still violate the Constitution. ``It would be
a much closer call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism by the ACLU has not been warmly received here in Scott
County, where corn and tobacco fields surround this little
courthouse town about 30 miles north of Louisville, Ky. Nearly all
of the 2,700 students in the schools here are Christian, and some
families have roots in Scottsburg that go back six generations.
</P>
<P>
   Long reliant on farming and factory work, people in Scottsburg
now more often commute to office jobs in Louisville, Ky., and its
suburbs. Old clapboard houses stand on the side streets, with
firewood piled high on porches. But the downtown has been gleaming
with new investments. A trendy cafe along a cobbled sidewalk serves
berry tarts and raspberry chambord. And the influx of newcomers has
boosted the population about 20 percent since 1990, to about 6,500.
</P>
<P>
   But a central force in Scottsburg is still the First Church of
Christ, which teaches the truth of the literal word of the Bible.
And some townspeople say children need training in the
old-fashioned virtues now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to instill values in our children,'' Mayor Bill Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   When two residents asked the school board to post the Ten
Commandments, the board members expressed agreement. But the school
superintendent, Hooker, said posting the Commandments would mean a
costly lawsuit and almost certain defeat. Instead, he urged the
board to approve a more secular set of common precepts, and it
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a letter from the state ACLU warning of a lawsuit,
Hooker said the school district planned to have the Common Precepts
on the school walls when students returned for the second semester
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1980 that posting the Ten
Commandments in schools violated the First Amendment ban on state
promotion of religion. The U.S. House of Representatives last year
passed a resolution calling for the posting of the Ten Commandments
in every public school room and courtroom in the nation. The
resolution did not address the constitutional ban.
</P>
<P>
   A bill now in the Indiana state Legislature would allow schools
and governments to display the Ten Commandments when it was part of
a larger display of historical records. Scott County school
officials say they intend to post such a display.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Scottsburg, named for the 19th-century railroad
founder Thomas Scott, say they do not understand how anyone could
take offense at the message of the precepts, even if it is inspired
by the Bible. Dave Davis, who runs an antiques store here, shook
his head with dismay over concerns that the code might violation
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the governor takes the oath of office, he puts his hand
on the Bible, doesn't he?'' Davis asked. ``It's just a darned shame
that we can't teach our kids values without somebody complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Colson, the manager of an automobile dealership and
president of the school board, said people of faith should make no
apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of us on the school board believe in that God,''
Colson said. ``We're not going to turn our backs on him. You've got
to draw a line in the sand somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in Scott County believes that posting the
Common Precepts is a good idea. Falk, of the state ACLU, said it
was a Scottsburg resident who called him to complain about the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Jonathan Wakeman, a pilot who lives in
Scottsburg, nothing is wrong with religious tenets _ at home and at
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the school's job to tell students to believe in
God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this won't work,'' Colson said. ``But with all the
things going on in the world, it seems to me you've got to try to
help steer kids right. You've got to stand for something.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   A CLOSER LOOK: Guiding Precepts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following are the Scott County school district's ``Common
Precepts to Promote a Virtuous and Civil School Community'':
</P>
<P>
   1. Trust in God.
</P>
<P>
   2. Respect authority.
</P>
<P>
   3. Honor your parents and family members.
</P>
<P>
   4. Treat your classmates, teachers and school staff with
respect.
</P>
<P>
   5. Speak kindly to and about others.
</P>
<P>
   6. Resolve conflicts without using violence.
</P>
<P>
   7. Tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   8. Save sex for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   9. Stay drug and alcohol free.
</P>
<P>
   10. Leave other people's property alone.
</P>
<P>
   11. Avoid being jealous of what others have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
