<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE LEGISLATION PROPOSED ON CLOSING PUERTO RICO BASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate will hold hearings next month on a bill
to close the $3 billion naval station in Puerto Rico, a move that
would clearly hurt the Puerto Rican economy, if the commonwealth
refuses to allow live-fire exercises to resume on the island of
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Puerto Rico Wednesday called the legislation a
``petty political move'' that would cause major economic damage to
the commonwealth, his spokesman said. But the bill's sponsor, Sen.
James Inhofe, R-Okla., said that naval operations in Puerto Rico
would not make sense without the use of the Vieques range.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign of the administration's concern over the
diminishing prospects for a settlement, John Podesta, the White
House chief of staff, will meet a top official in the
administration of Gov. Pedro Rossello of Puerto Rico on Thursday to
prepare for a meeting next week between the governor and President
Clinton, Puerto Rican officials said. The Clinton administration
declined to answer questions about the base closing proposal or the
upcoming meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., and chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, said in an interview Wednesday that it made sense to
close the Roosevelt Roads naval station on the main island of
Puerto Rico if the commonwealth refused to allow training on the
smaller island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly of the view that if the range is lost, it is
highly likely that we would close Roosevelt Roads,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   That naval station serves the Navy battle groups and Marines
that train in Vieques and open waters around Puerto Rico. Roosevelt
Roads provides $300 million to Puerto Rico's economy each year and
employs 2,500 civilians and 2,400 military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Clinton ordered a halt to live-fire military
training on Vieques to help resolve an eight-month dispute between
the Navy and Puerto Rico. In April, a Puerto Rican civilian guard
was killed in a bombing accident, triggering political protests
that have united Puerto Rico as no other issue has.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the Navy and Marines have been prevented for the
first time since 1941 from using the range for exercises they
consider essential training for combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello rejected Clinton's compromise offer, which included
restricting exercises on Vieques to non-explosive, or inert,
ordinances, reducing by half the number of days exercises are held
and ending all exercises there within five years unless the local
residents agreed to an extension. Clinton also offered Vieques a
$40 million economic revival package to demonstrate that the Navy
understood it must ``repair relations'' with the people of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Morey, the secretary of state for Puerto Rico, will meet
with Podesta on Thursday to arrange a meeting as early as next week
among the governor, Clinton, and Secretary of Defense William
Cohen, said Alfonso Aguilar, press secretary for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that the White House is receiving Morey, and
eventually the governor, shows the president is making a great
effort to look out for the welfare of the people of Vieques,''
Aguilar said. ``This is a positive first step showing the president
and the White House are still in the dialogue and willing to
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   But a settlement has to be reached in the next several weeks to
allow the Navy to plan for alternatives if the battle groups can no
longer train on Vieques, senior administration and military
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the pending legislation in the Senate, the Navy
would automatically examine closing Roosevelt Roads station if
Vieques was lost, a senior Naval official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between Roosevelt Roads and the mission of
Vieques range is very close,'' the official said. ``If we lose
Vieques, it would be cause for a review of the value of keeping
Roosevelt Roads.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This year the Pentagon failed to persuade Congress to approve a
new round of base closings at installations around the country that
have lost their use in the post-Cold War era but continue to cost
billions of dollars to maintain. Now several senators are proposing
to close Roosevelt Roads if there are no more exercises at Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in the position of a senator or representative
who closed a military installation,'' Inhofe said. ``Politically,
you can't resist closing down Roosevelt Roads. It's a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello was not surprised that the Senate is threatening to
close Roosevelt Roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has known for some time that this argument would
be used against him,'' said Aguilar, his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican officials said that Roosevelt Roads is important
even without Vieques, and is used in the war against drugs as well
as other military training.
</P>
<P>
   Since this summer, the Navy has been searching for alternatives
to Vieques for their training exercises. But military officials say
they have yet to find anything to duplicate the ``unique
qualities'' of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Navy and Marines put together a
``patchwork'' of training for the aircraft carrier Eisenhower and
its battle group, including a Marine detachment, which leaves for
its next assignment to the Mediterranean in February without
training at Vieques. Instead they used bases in Florida and North
Carolina for pilots to drop bombs and Marines to storm the beach,
as well as temporary naval artillery training on Cape Wrath in
Scotland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
