<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-BOEING-ORDERS-SPI &LR;      12-15 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ORDERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING DISCLOSES 163 ORDERS AND A NEW 20-JET DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ After lagging behind in this year's airplane
order race, Boeing took an $11.6 billion leap forward Wednesday,
disclosing 163 previously unannounced orders and a new deal for 20
widebody jets.
</P>
<P>
   And a senior executive said more deals are in the works and
could be finalized before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A beaming Alan Mulally, president of Boeing's Commercial
Aircraft Group, announced a new, $2.6 billion order from GE Capital
Aviation Services for 15 extended-range 767-300 jets and five
747-400 cargo airplanes. Deliveries are expected to begin in the
fourth quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Boeing significantly narrowed the lead of its
rival Airbus Industrie by changing the way it reports airplane
orders. In the past, Boeing didn't disclose orders from airlines
that didn't want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The change was a $9 billion boost to Boeing's order book,
bringing total orders so far this year to 368 versus Airbus' 430.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus also had some good news Wednesday too, receiving a $1.2
billion order for 10 A330 passenger jets from Scandinavian Airlines
System.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally said Boeing's order-reporting change was made to reflect
industry practice, giving investors more company information _ and
was not an attempt to gain ground on Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   But Airbus, which already counts orders from unidentified
customers, viewed Boeing's move as ``suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual that all of these orders come out all in one day,
in the eleventh hour,'' said Airbus spokeswoman Mary Anne Greczyn,
noting that her company has only a handful of undisclosed orders.
``We can both live happily in this industry. We don't have to throw
snowballs at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts said Boeing's order-reporting change was a
clear public relations move to ``one-up'' Airbus, others said it
was just following industry standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business about counting the airplanes is silliness,''
said Joseph Campbell, an analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``The real
question is who is gaining market share in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, he said, that appears to be Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, investors took the news in stride, as Boeing's stock
rose 25 cents to close at $38.75 Wednesday, while the Dow Jones
Industrial Average rose 65.15 to close at 11225.32.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing wouldn't give details on its previously unannounced
orders, declining to reveal customer names or aircraft models. Many
airlines prefer to withhold order announcements for competitive or
financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally shrugged off the fact that Airbus will most likely win
this year's order race and stressed that ``at the end of the day''
airplane deliveries are really what matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year is not an indication of a longterm leadership
position,'' Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted the company has delivered 582 commercial jets so far,
with 38 more expected by the end of the month. He reiterated that
the company is on schedule to deliver 620 jetliners this year. It
already has surpassed last year's record of 563 deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boeing is only concerned about deliveries then why do it,''
the Airbus spokesman said of Boeing's change in the way it reports
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, a four-nation European consortium, has delivered 266
airplanes as of Nov. 30. The Toulouse, France-based company plans
to deliver 290 to 295 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Airbus plans to increase its deliveries to 310, while
Boeing will decrease deliveries to 480.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally hinted, however, that an improving Asian market could
boost total deliveries next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a soft landing in Asia,'' he said, adding
that Wednesday's order from General Electric's leasing company is a
good indication that orders from Asia are on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference to tout Boeing's ``year-end''
accomplishments, Mulally hinted that more orders will be announced
in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some very good negotiations going on with customers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally also said Boeing was on track ``to meet or exceed'' the
company's goal of a 5-percent operating margin for commercial jets
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Boeing veteran added the company plans to launch a
new version of the 777, which is expected to have a longer range,
in the first or second quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done many times in the past, Mulally spent much of
Wednesday morning walking through Boeing's factory here
congratulating workers on a job well done. Boeing produces the 747,
767 and 777 airplanes in its Everett factory and the 737 and 757
models in Renton, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   He said the recently announced orders will go a long way in
improving job security for the company's employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a very good future for Everett,'' Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   The widebody order from GE's leasing unit will allow Boeing to
keep the production rate of its slow-selling 747 at two airplanes
per month through next year, Mulally said. Boeing had considered
reducing the 747 production rate to 1 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Airbus acknowledged Wednesday it is having production
problems on its A320 assembly lines and will delay delivery of
those models by a couple of weeks next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have been given notice,'' Greczyn said.
</P>
<P>
   She said a data entry problem at Britain's BAE Systems Plc, an
Airbus partner, caused the delay of the A320 wing production, which
in turn pushed back the delivery dates for the airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem has already been solved,'' she said, noting,
``this is a minor delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie's backlog of orders not yet delivered was 1,436
as of Nov. 30, compared with Boeing's 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to put Boeing out of business, we just want
50 percent of the market,'' the Airbus spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Paul Nyhan contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
