<HEADER>
A0331 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ONLINE-STOCK-FRAUD-1S     12-15 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-STOCK-FRAUD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ACCUSED OF FRAUDULENTLY INFLATING A STOCK VIA INTERNET MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (subs 8th graf to change Derzakarian to Derzakharian) 
 (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a case that shows both how easy it is to artificially inflate
the price of stocks on the Internet and how quickly prosecutors can
identify the culprits, two California men were charged Wednesday
with sending bogus messages over the Internet to pump up the price
of a bankrupt company.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney in Los Angeles and the Securities and Exchange
Commission contend that the men, both 23 and recent college
graduates, used the Internet to artificially propel the price of an
obscure stock from 15 cents a share to more than $15 in less than
two trading days in November, reaping $364,000 in profits for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nov. 12, according to prosecutors, Arash
Aziz-Golshani, Hootan Melamed _ the two men charged _ and a third
man, Allen Derzakharian, 26, sat down at public computers in the
University of California at Los Angeles biomedical library and
tapped into the Internet. Using 50 different Web identities, the
three men sent more than 500 messages to three hot investment Web
sites during the course of the weekend, all touting shares of NEI
Webworld Inc., a bankrupt commercial printing company based in
Dallas, calling it an imminent takeover candidate even though they
knew it was not.
</P>
<P>
   The case is among the first to illustrate how easy it is to send
stocks soaring by utilizing the Internet. But prosecutors said the
case also sends an important message to people who think the
anonymity of the Internet allows them to manipulate stocks by
posting false statements about a company. Although securities
regulators say that many people who violate securities laws have
migrated to the Internet, this case shows how quickly investigators
can track down anyone who electronically posts bogus messages about
companies or stocks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is no longer the Wild Wild Web,'' said
Christopher Painter, assistant U.S. attorney for the Central
District of California and that office's computer crime
coordinator. ``It's a new territory that law enforcement is trying
to tame. We will go after these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that the men began promoting NEI Webworld
electronically after they had purchased 97 percent of the company's
available stock for themselves at prices ranging from 5 cents to 17
cents a share. In October, there was virtually no market activity
in shares of NEI, which traded on only three of 21 trading days. On
Friday, Nov. 12, the stock closed at 13 cents a share. But
rhapsodic messages sent by the men over the weekend whipped up
investor interest in the shares and the stock opened for trading
the following Monday at $8.
</P>
<P>
   Investors eagerly bought the shares, pushing them to $15.50 in
approximately half an hour, prosecutors say. Meanwhile,
Aziz-Golshani, Melamed and Derzakharian sold their shares into the
buying frenzy at prices between 25 cents and $15.1875.
Aziz-Golshani made $152,742 in profits and Melamed and Derzakharian
realized $211,250 in gains.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz-Golshani and Melamed were arrested in Los Angeles on
Wednesday afternoon on the criminal charge. The SEC filed civil
fraud charges against them and Derzakharian, accusing them of
sending false messages. Aziz-Golshani and Melamed were charged by
the U.S. attorney's office with a single count of criminal
conspiracy to commit securities fraud. Derzakharian was not
criminally charged by the U.S. attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker, director of enforcement at the SEC, said: ``Let
this serve as a warning to con men: if you use the Internet to
manipulate our securities markets, we can and will find you. Though
the perpetrators in the case went to great lengths to hide from us,
we discovered them within a matter of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Under securities laws, it is illegal to engage in false
representations or manipulative practices when buying or selling a
security. This is just what Golshani and Melamed did, say
prosecutors. The court froze the assets of all three men.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing Aziz-Golshani is Randall Sunshine, of
Liner Yankelevitz Sunshine Weinhart &AMP; Regenstreif LLP in Santa
Monica. Sunshine said he could not comment on the complaint because
he had not yet read it.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Werksman, the lawyer representing Melamed, said: ``My
client denies manipulating the market in the way that the
government alleges. Until we know more about exactly what they
claim my client did and how the market was affected, it's too early
to tell how this case will turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, one of the men posted 10 identical
messages on various Yahoo finance message boards predicting a
buyout of NEI, whose stock trades under the symbol NEIP, by a
private company called LGC Wireless. Using the web name
`ticlopidinel,' the messages said: ``Buying NEIP early would
entitle you to a share of LGC Wireless when it goes public next
week. Look for a massive move to $5-$10 as wireless stocks are very
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors believe that Aziz-Golshani and Melamed penned the
message and based their Web name on ticlopidine, the name of a
stroke-prevention drug that had been discussed in classes that
Melamed had recently attended as a pharmacy student at Western
University of Health Sciences in Pomona, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When a skeptic in the chat room questioned the viability of a
NEI buyout, prosecutors say, Aziz-Golshani posted this answer: ``I
called on Saturday and no officers were in to answer my call, just
a receptionist who are always the last to know.'' Then, he added:
``People who know of the deal are buying in given the large volume
the last few days. ...''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But no buyout came. After peaking above $15 on Monday, Nov. 15,
NEI shares closed at 75 cents. The stock closed Wednesday at 18.75
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that securities fraud has migrated to the
Internet because stocks can be propelled there with little more
than effusive talk and rosy predictions. Before the Web became
stock-tip central, someone who wanted to manipulate a company's
shares had to employ rooms full of stockbrokers flogging stocks to
unsuspecting investors by telephone. Now an electronic message does
the trick instantly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the criminal case against Aziz-Golshani and
Melamed contend that the Internet touting of NEI was not the first
for the two men. Although Aziz-Golshani, who lives in Beverly
Hills, told prosecutors that he operates a business from his home
selling leather jackets online, messages emanating from computers
at the UCLA biomedical library last September touted shares in a
company called Justwebit.com Inc. A review of brokerage firm
account statements belonging to Aziz-Golshani and Hooshang Melamed,
Hootan Melamed's father, indicate that trades in the company were
made that resulted in profits to both. Aziz-Golshani graduated from
UCLA last spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
