<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATIN-VENTURE-CAPITAL     12-15 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BREED OF VENTURE CAPITALIST SCOUTS LATIN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Upon arriving in the big Amazon port of
Belem several months ago, Patricia Moles, the manager of a
venture-capital fund, was faced with an unusual investment-related
decision: whether to continue by boat to the hearts-of-palm
plantation in which her fund was hoping to acquire a minority
stake, a trip that would take 12 hours, or to rent a propeller
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time was a must so I chose the plane,'' said Ms. Moles, 33, a
native of Mexico, whose Brazil-based employer, Banco Axial, looks
for investments in environmentally friendly companies. Although her
trip was off the beaten track of the briefcase bankers who stick to
financial centers like Sao Paulo, it was indicative of a new
investment trend that is sweeping Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists are searching the region for opportunities
in young companies, much as they have been doing in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these financiers like the challenge of nontraditional
investments _ organically produced hearts of palm, for example,
grown from custom-selected and germinated seeds that generate a
continuing supply of palm stems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most venture capitalists investing in companies with a Latin
American focus, like those providing seed money to ventures in the
United States, are seeking out high technology _ particularly
Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   The quest is complicated by the often precarious nature of Latin
American economies as well as the relative lack of advanced
technology, along with the generally frenetic nature of the young
Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of venture-capital investing is part of the wider
trend of private equity investors focusing on Latin America, a huge
market. Though the region has quickly embraced the Internet, it
still has a long way to go in terms of wealth and technology to
catch up with the richest industrial nations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier waves of investment, most of which came from
abroad or were state-sponsored, the venture-capital investments of
the last few years have pitted some of Latin America's richest
people against foreigners, particularly from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Latin Americans are Juan Navarro, president of the
Exxel Group, one of Argentina's largest privately owned companies;
Jorge Paulo Lemann, founder of Garantia, a big Brazilian investment
bank now owned by the Credit Suisse Group, and Carlos Slim Helu,
chairman of Telefonos de Mexico. Then there are the people who work
for, or are partners in the venture-capital funds controlled by
these investors.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Bonchristiano is an example of this new breed. Six
months ago, Bonchristiano, 32, was a partner in a fund that is part
of GP Investimentos, an investment group based here, whose owners
include Lemann. His task was to seek out an appealing Brazilian
Internet company and buy it.
</P>
<P>
   What he came up with was BookNet, an online bookseller similar
to Amazon.com, and GP acquired a controlling stake. In something of
an unusual twist, Bonchristiano became the company's chief
executive, switching roles from venture capitalist to entrepreneur.
Using his knowledge of the game, he then went to New York to drum
up additional money, and returned with $14.3 million from firms
like Warburg Pincus and individual investors like Henry Kravis of
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   BookNet was renamed Submarino, and now the company's
headquarters in Sao Paulo is brimming with 50 employees working
14-hour days and relieving stress at a couple of pinball and
foosball machines. The company has opened offices in Spain,
Argentina and Mexico, and aims to become the leading online
shopping destination in the Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dreamlike for me as a Brazilian,'' Bonchristiano said
in English polished during his undergraduate years at Oxford.
``Brazil was colonized for so long, either economically,
intellectually or technologically, and the Internet is changing
that. With new access to investment and technology, the playing
field is leveled.''
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's capitalist structures are still considered
relatively backward, though. Domestic stock markets are riddled
with labyrinthine regulations that make it hard to buy or sell
securities. And some investors, including Dennis Rodrigues, a
partner in the Sao Paulo-based firm FIR Capital, see the evolution
of domestic capital markets as the key to the success of
venture-capital investing in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   But other investors, as well as many entrepreneurs, are drawn by
the possibility of leapfrogging local exchanges and listing their
companies on markets in the United States, nearly always Nasdaq,
hoping for some of the paper wealth made possible by a market
fascinated with dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Going public on Nasdaq is a lot easier with help from people who
have generous sources of capital and who also know the U.S.
regulatory environment. That is where venture capitalists from the
United States come in. Among the most active of these is Chase
Capital Partners, part of Chase Manhattan Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Flatiron Partners of New York, Chase Capital
Partners has invested in five Internet companies that focus on
Latin America. The largest, StarMedia Network, a New York-based
portal company for Spanish and Portuguese speakers worldwide that
also provides Internet access in some Latin American countries, has
been its biggest success so far. After StarMedia went public
earlier this year, the initial investment by Chase and Flatiron of
$29 million grew to well over $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   While some venture operations, like GP Investimentos, often seek
to acquire control of companies, others, including Chase, have
invested in Latin America in a way that is closer to the
traditional Silicon Valley model of providing seed capital to small
companies that then proceed through several rounds of financing
before going public. Usually, this model involves the purchase of a
minority stake in the company, through which management direction
is provided but not dictated.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
