<HEADER>
A0333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ADSL16-COX     12-15 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADSL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southwestern Bell seeks PUC blessing
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Public Utility Commission today will try
again to decide whether to bless _ as Chairman Pat Wood has put it
_ Southwestern Bell Telephone Co.'s application to start selling
long-distance service in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Getting into the long-distance business is a major goal for
Southwestern Bell. The company sees it as the last big piece it
needs if it is to sell a complete telecommunications package:
long-distance calling, local service, Internet connections,
wireless and even video.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance is also critical to the company if it is to
compete effectively in the burgeoning field of transmitting
computer data across the country.
</P>
<P>
   It had appeared that Southwestern Bell might get at least a 2-1
vote from the PUC at its Nov. 4 meeting, but the commissioners were
too badly divided to even vote.
</P>
<P>
   Final approval lies with the Federal Communications Commission,
but the FCC must consider the recommendations of the state
regulatory agency and the U.S. Department of Justice. To date, no
Bell company has won FCC approval to sell long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   What the PUC continues to hear from Southwestern Bell's critics
is that the telephone giant still has not fully opened its local
network to competitors, which federal law says it must do before it
can sell long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   That dual role for Southwestern Bell _ providing wholesale
network services to competitors even as its retail teams battle
them over customers _ has generated considerable disputes.
</P>
<P>
   And today's meeting comes shortly after two PUC arbitrators, in
a separate proceeding, issued findings that critics are expected to
say show that Southwestern Bell still discriminates against
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration pitted Southwestern Bell against two companies
wanting to sell new ``digital subscriber loop,'' or DSL service, in
Texas: Covad Communications Co., based in Santa Clara, Calif.; and
Rhythms Links Inc., a subsidiary of Rhythms NetConnections Inc. of
Englewood, Colo. DSL provides high-speed connections for the
Internet. Southwestern Bell considers DSL so important it has
launched a $6 billion project to upgrade its network so that
virtually all its customers can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Covad and Rhythms also sell DSL, but they rely on Southwestern
Bell's network to reach their customers.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the two arbitrators, Katherine Farroba and
Rowland Curry, criticized Southwestern Bell for not keeping its
wholesale and retail DSL operations separate enough.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell has asked the PUC for a new hearing in the
case, saying that DSL technology and its own procedures have
changed so much in just the past few months ``that much of the
evidentiary record is incorrect and/or incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   Dineen Majcher, an attorney for Rhythms, objected, saying that
any more delay would ``substantially harm'' its efforts to compete
with Southwestern Bell in DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   Majcher also reminded the commission that Southwestern Bell
already had paid $850,000 in sanctions in this case for its earlier
failure to provide all the required witnesses and internal
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
