<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATIN-VENTURE-CAPITAL     12-15 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-VENTURE-CAPITAL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAO PAULO: not dictated.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Being a venture capitalist in Latin America largely involves
adapting what has worked in the United States to what is realistic
in countries like Mexico and Brazil,'' said Susan Segal, head of
Latin American operations for Chase Capital Partners.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce, for instance, is as strong a lure in the region as
it is in the United States, and has accounted for some of Chase's
bets _ like its recent investment in Mercado Livre, an Internet
company hoping to reproduce online some of the fervor of a
boisterous open-air market. The Boston Consulting Group estimates
that revenue from electronic commerce in Latin America will grow to
$3.8 billion in 2003 from $167 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while most signs point to the growth of purchases over the
Internet, and of Latin American Internet use in general, obstacles
to such rosy outcomes remain. According to a report by
International Data Corp., weak credit card processing operations,
the high cost of basic Internet service and precarious and costly
shipping networks will inhibit the spread of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And the use of computers and even telephones in the region is
still relatively low, a limiting factor for all Internet
businesses. For instance, in Brazil, Latin America's largest
country, there are an estimated 12 telephone lines for each 100
people, compared with more than 50 lines for every 100 people in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And the entrepreneurial culture that speeds the creation of
start-ups in the United States is different in Latin America.
``Some entrepreneurs that are used to sealing deals with a
handshake don't realize that a lot of rigorous detail is needed to
put together a venture-capital deal,'' said Lisa Krochmal, a lawyer
in the Buenos Aires office of Morrison &AMP; Foerster, an American firm
active in new technology deals.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is the erratic nature of the Internet industry
itself. As in the United States, most young Internet companies in
Latin America lose money. This, coupled with the boom-and-bust
cycles of Latin American economies, makes some investors wary of
betting on the region's young companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to get burned when they realize that
transforming an interesting idea in Brazil into a stock appealing
to retail investors in the U.S. is no piece of cake,'' Rodrigues of
FIR Capital said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, where some people see obstacles, others see opportunities
_ opportunities that require capital to realize.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to bring Internet access to people without a phone or a
computer, an American, Terrence Danial, helped found NetKiosk, a
Buenos Aires-based company that sells stand-alone units equipped
with a PC that allows users to surf the Net for a fee. In addition
to sales of the units, which are put in places like hotel lobbies,
NetKiosk hopes to gain revenue from selling advertising that
appears on the units as well as on the company's portal page. But
NetKiosk has had trouble attracting seed money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, venture capital in Latin America still has a long
way to go,'' said Danial, adding that the seed-money industry is
not as well developed in the region as it is in the United States
and that potential backers are often warier of taking risks. ``A
lot of investors are still seeing things from traditional business
mind-sets,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
