<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-CHRISTMAS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM SAYS IT CAN MAKE THOSE HOLIDAY DEADLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Amazon.com, the world's largest Internet retailer, is
distinguishing itself among e-tailers by meeting its customers'
delivery requests in a timely manner, and it expects to keep doing
so through Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Bill Curry said Amazon can still guarantee Dec. 24
delivery on in-stock items ordered by Dec. 22 and shipped priority.
The same can't be said of some other e-tailers surveyed this week
by the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. last Thursday posted a note on its Web site
warning it can't guarantee delivery by Christmas, the Journal said.
EToys still guarantees Christmas delivery of orders placed through
Dec. 17 with priority delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 million people may shop online this holiday season,
placing 37 million orders worth as much as $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Few e-shoppers will realize that though the Internet is a better
way to place orders, it no more ensures the timely delivery of
those orders than do toll-free phone numbers, faxes or even the
U.S. Postal Service. No matter how they're placed, all merchandise
orders end up in the same `In' tray to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   So what will really distinguish an e-tailer this season is how
well its back-end order-fulfillment works.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com reports its system is working smoothly. Seven U.S.
distribution centers are operating to fill a flow of orders that
chief operating officer Joseph Galli, working his first Christmas
at the company, described Wednesday as ``record-breaking ...
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 people, nearly twice the normal number, are working
five 11-hour shifts a week in the south Seattle distribution
center. The workers _ many of them young, tattooed,
multiple-pierced, and sporting hair in colors not found in nature _
earn betwen $8.50 and $14 an hour. Working right beside them are a
smattering of company executives.
</P>
<P>
   A full inventory of books, CDs and videos is warehoused in each
of the seven centers, cutting delivery times on those items. Galli
said Amazon ordered extremely popular items, like Pokemon
characters and Sega Dreamcast video game systems, in such large
quantities that they're still in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
