<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     12-15 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAMARANCH ALSO SPEAKS STENGELESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: OLY-SAMARANCH)  
(DW) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sooner or later, just about everybody marches in
front of a Congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   The tape of Casey Stengel's jabberwocky performance (``I'm a
baseball man ...'') before Sen. Estes Kefauver nearly half a
century ago still delights baseball fans. Strip miners explain why
it's good for the ecology to blast the coal out of Appalachian
hillsides. Tobacco officials explain why it's good for the lungs to
suck up all that smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in the last scheduled committee hearing of this
century, the very fluent Juan Antonio Samaranch used interpreters
to avoid any misunderstanding between Castilian Spanish and
congressional English.
</P>
<P>
   But the cultural gap between American politics and Olympic
ethics goes much deeper than mere language. Samaranch is trying to
reassure American politicians that the Olympic movement is safe to
continue receiving American corporate dollars because it remains in
his hands, even after a worldwide scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we cleaned the house,'' Samaranch told members of the
House Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations. He was
referring to 50 reforms, including an ethics committee that reports
to _ you guessed it _ Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire structure seems based upon personality rather than
rules,'' observed Rep. Diana DeGette, D-Colo., who wanted to know
what would happen when the president was not somebody as honorable
and esteemed as his excellency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The graveyards are full of indispensable people,'' replied the
79-year-old Samaranch, who is not known for his morbid side.
</P>
<P>
   He did suggest that the International Olympic Committee, having
divested itself of 10 bad apples and taken on a similar number of
actual athletes _ if you can imagine that _ was now in a position
to resist temptations.
</P>
<P>
   The representatives, with their own peculiar American campaign
fund raising, do not have the highly personal mandate that his
excellency apparently enjoys. These representatives have voted on
the impeachment of an American president, and a few of them gave
the impression they would not have minded taking part in the
impeachment of the IOC president, if they could figure out how.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, after a grueling year, Samaranch felt compelled to
face American representatives because he knows where his rich and
fluffy croissants are baked. He actually gave a good performance,
standing up to seven members of the subcommittee who made it back
from the hinterlands in murky flying weather while Congress was in
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch comes from across a gap far wider than the Alps and
the Atlantic Ocean. He more or less shrugged off Yank-style
questions about privilege and excess. The lawmakers seemed to find
the new language ambiguous. Are all trips to bid cities banned, or
are they merely ``not necessary?'' His excellency made the rather
Mel Brooksian regal proclamation, ``No trips, no gifts,'' as if
that settled that.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch also dismissed talk of his living in a $500,000-a-year
suite in Lausanne, Switzerland, insisting it costs only $250 a day
when he is in town and $70 when he is not. (Those continental
breakfasts must be expensive.)
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers made a big deal about a trip by his wife to the
bid city of Atlanta in 1990, Samaranch was far too polite to
suggest that Maria Teresa Samaranch, who hails from Barcelona and
Lausanne, should have been paid overtime for sampling life in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   His excellency smiled politely while Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas,
disparaged the new ethics committee, ``or what we in Texas would
call a posse.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton said, ``If the sheriff sends the posse in the wrong
direction, you can call out the bloodhounds and the sharpshooters,
but you'll never find anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Samaranch heard himself praised by the former Secretary
of State Henry Kissinger and the former Sen. Howard Baker, who
recently took part in the reform process. When the trinity of
elders were dismissed, almost no spectators and only two
representatives remained to hear seven athletes give emotional
personal testimony. Bob Ctvrtlik, an Olympic volleyball player, who
was elected a delegate last week, praised the IOC for the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   While the athletes were speaking, Samaranch paused in the lobby
of the Rayburn Building and said he was treated very well, and he
predicted, ``The Games are not touched.''
</P>
<P>
   The very fluent Juan Antonio Samaranch did not need an
interpreter to hear American money still jingling merrily in the
Olympic pipeline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
