<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER WASTED SHOT IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One warm summer evening last June, for reasons we don't know, a
person we haven't captured pointed a pistol we haven't found into
the night sky and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been a few blocks south of Camelback Road and a few
blocks west of Central Avenue. Perhaps he was standing on the
street or in his back yard, or perhaps he was riding in an automo
bile. Perhaps, even, it was a she.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon was fired and the sharp si lent bullet rose into the
darkness, arching gently about a mile above the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   It hesitated there, the way a diver seems to hang for a moment
above the diving board. Then, down.
</P>
<P>
   The small metal projectile bored through the still air. One
hundred feet per second. Three hundred. Five hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Below, in a house in central Phoenix, 14-year-old Shannon Smith
chatted with a friend on the telephone. She said she heard a noise
outside, something that sounded to her like an automobile acci
dent.
</P>
<P>
   The phone was portable so she carried it with her into the back
yard. Above, the tiny slug plunged furiously toward Earth.
</P>
<P>
   There are 473 square miles in the city of Phoenix, many of them
empty unpaved desert, uncluttered by office buildings and houses,
unoccupied by men or women or little girls. But that isn't where
the bullet came to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's father found her in the yard at 10:40 p.m. &QL; 
MORE THAN WE COULD BEAR &QL; 
A day later, preparing for his daughter's funeral, Otis Smith said,
``No parent should ever go through this.'' And he's correct.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths live in a nice neighborhood in a nice house with a
9-foot block wall surrounding their back yard. Still, their
daughter was killed. It was more than they could bear. It's more
than any of us could bear.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths got together with a few members of the Arizona State
Legislature and came up with a proposed new law that would increase
penalties for ran domly discharging a firearm from a mis demeanor
to a Class 6 felony.
</P>
<P>
   A version of ``Shannon's Law'' passed the state Senate but
hasn't yet been ap proved by the House. Parents' organiza tions,
politicians, newspapers and even the National Rifle Association are
in fa vor of it. They say the new law will do something good for
all of us. And it will.
</P>
<P>
   It'll make us feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that's not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   We already have a law we could use to charge with a felony
anyone who fires a weapon in a populated area.
</P>
<P>
   The crime is reckless endangerment and the statute reads: ``A
person commits endangerment by recklessly endangering another
person with a substantial risk of imminent death or physical
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting off a pistol in a neighborhood more than qualifies. &QL; 
MESSAGE TO THE POLICE &QL; 
But, enforcing an existing law doesn't quite ease the pain. Not
when we've lost a little girl. That takes a new law. Shan non's
Law. One of those trying to get it approved in the state House is
state Sen. Chris Cummiskey.
</P>
<P>
   He told me Wednesday, ``Some neigh borhoods where random gunfire
is a reg ular occurence indicated that even with `reckless
endangerment' out there on the landscape, law enforcement has not
been coming out and pressing for some conclu sion to this in those
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes a new law would send a message to the police. Maybe
it will. That would be useful.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, sending a message to ordinary gun owners is
absolutely vital. A good advertising campaign would do that, though
it won't stop all the gunfire. If caught, the person who killed
Shannon Smith would do time for manslaughter. That won't stop all
the gunfire, either.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Shannon's Law say they, too, would like to see
more public service announcements about the dangers of fir ing
weapons into the air, but they still want their new law.
</P>
<P>
   I can't fault them. The loss of any little girl is unacceptable.
It's more than any of us can bear. But we won't keep it from
happening again by taking our own shot in the dark. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
