<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY PUTS HUMAN FACE ON AIDS IN AFRICA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique _ Mozambicans opened their newspapers one
Saturday morning here recently and gasped. There, amid the paid
death notices, was the photograph of a businessman from this
country's most prominent family.
</P>
<P>
   Under his name, a death notice read simply: ``Victim of AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   That notice, which appeared in the newspaper Noticias in late
November, and others for the businessman marked the first time a
prominent family in this country had publicly acknowledged being
touched by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The family that had finally shattered the silence and shame
surrounding the disease was none other than that of Samora Machel,
who led Mozambique to independence from Portugal in 1975 and became
its first president. It was his brother, Boaventura Moises Machel,
who died of complications from AIDS on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Six months before, the prime minister here had begged his nation
to stop hiding from the disease that is ravaging the continent and
the country. The death notices promptly touched off both cheers of
support and howls of indignation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 15 percent of the population here is believed to be
infected with the virus that causes AIDS. But here, as in many
African countries, people often conceal the disease, fearing
discrimination, rejection from family and friends, even attacks
from outraged neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find an image, a Mozambican face, for AIDS,'' the
prime minister, Pascoal Mocumbi, told reporters in July.
</P>
<P>
   But probably no one could have imagined that the Machel family
would take up the suggestion in such a dramatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Maria Tallarico, the U.N. AIDS representative in Mozambique,
was in her office that morning when she saw the solemn photographs
of Boaventura Machel, dressed in suit and tie, in the newspaper.
She was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Machel's wife, children and sister-in-law, Graca Machel, now
married to Nelson Mandela, paid for the death notices, which
appeared one on top of the other, and prominently noted the cause
of death and listed the names of grieving relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought many, many newspapers that day,'' Tallarico said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really important,'' she continued. ``Until now, we've
never seen anything like this. Now people are talking about it,
talking about the disease. We are close to people who are living
with the disease and some of them are now saying, `Maybe I also
have to speak up about myself, my status.'''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS experts say that promoting greater openness about AIDS is
critical. Since few speak openly of the disease, many people
dismiss it as something that affects only foreigners or white
people or outsiders, and many refuse to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Those who go public often pay a price.
</P>
<P>
   Many die alone, abandoned by their families. Last year, a woman
in South Africa who was an advocate for people with AIDS was beaten
to death by her neighbors after she disclosed she was infected with
HIV, the virus that causes the disease.
</P>
<P>
   One influential daily newsletter, MediaFax, said several
prominent Mozambicans, including some friends and relatives of
Boaventura Machel, were appalled by the family's decision to
publicize the cause of death. ``In life, as in death, one must
respect the privacy of the citizen,'' the newsletter said.
</P>
<P>
   But AIDS experts see some encouraging signs of change. This
year, the Sowetan, the largest daily newspaper in South Africa,
began publishing a weekly column by a young man, Lucky Mazibuko,
who is infected.
</P>
<P>
   And when Boaventura Machel's death notices appeared here, most
news accounts commended the family's bravery. Samora Machel died in
a mysterious airplane crash in South Africa in 1986, but he is
still revered here along with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Filipe Matusse, who wrote a letter to Noticias, praised the
family's ``titanic courage'' and its much needed warning to
society.
</P>
<P>
   Tallarico said she believed the death notices would help promote
a more tolerant and accepting attitude toward people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not see change immediately, maybe not tomorrow, but it
will come,'' she said. ``The reaction here is encouraging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
