<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISCLOSURE-MARKETPLAC     12-15 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCLOSURE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL ST. SNARLS AT SEC PROPOSAL ON DISCLOSURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It sounds like something that no one would support:
the selective disclosure of important information by companies.
Such a practice enables those favored with early knowledge to make
money at the expense of traders not so favored.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Securities and Exchange Commission Wednesday
offered a mild proposal on how to deal with the problem, it became
clear that selective disclosure has a constituency, and opposition
immediately appeared on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC proposed a new Regulation FD (for fair disclosure) that
would mandate that companies not divulge material information _
that is, important information that can move the stock price _
except through public disclosure. The regulation added that if such
information was inadvertently disclosed, it should quickly be
released to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The all-too-common practice of selectively disseminating
material information is a disservice to investors and undermines
the fundamental principle of fairness,'' said Arthur Levitt, the
chairman of the SEC ``This practice leads to potential conflicts of
interest for analysts and undermines investor confidence in our
markets. In a time when instantaneous and free- flowing information
is the norm, these sort of whispers are an insult to the principles
of free and open disclosure upon which the success of our capital
markets is based.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Streeters immediately warned that trying to shut off
the selective release of information could shut off any release of
information. ``The more information that comes out, and the faster
it comes out, the better it is for investors,'' said Stuart J.
Kaswell, the general counsel of the Securities Industry
Association, a trade group of investment banking firms.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that analysts should be seen as the proxies for
investors, whose job is to ``ferret out information'' and get it to
investors. ``The risk,'' he said in a telephone interview, ``is
that you will curtail information'' because officials will be
afraid to talk to analysts, for fear that if they said anything
they would then have to issue a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Such dire forecasts probably won't be borne out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophisticated companies know they have to talk to analysts and
institutional investors,'' said Michael Littenberg, a securities
lawyer and partner in Schulte Roth &AMP; Zabel. ``Pretty much all the
SEC is saying is don't selectively disclose material information,''
he said. ``That is something that securities lawyers always advise
their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Levitt has called selective disclosure a ``stain
upon our market,'' but some opponents of the regulation say they
see no evidence that there is a large problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would question the assumption that there is a widespread
practice that gives rise to this stain,'' said Edward H. Fleishman,
a securities lawyer and former member of the SEC He said he was
sure it happened sometimes, and that the SEC was frustrated that it
could not take any action under current rules. ``But that it is
widespread, that I doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rule, which includes questions about alternatives
that the SEC might pursue, offers three ways for companies to
disclose information to the public, and says any of them could be
used to rectify an inadvertent disclosure. Those methods are
through a filing with the SEC, by issuing a news release, or by
holding a conference call to which anyone, analyst or not, can
listen. Levitt said that the call could be broadcast on the
Internet, and said he disagreed with those who thought it would
chill the information flow.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it appears that the criticism of the rule _ which
the SEC has heard in recent weeks as it considered what to do _ has
already had an effect. The SEC's proposal endorsed the dubious idea
that disclosing something only in a conference call constitutes
adequate public disclosure if access to the conference call was not
restricted.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, most investors will not get in on any such
conference call. Even if they learn about it in advance, they might
not have time to call in. Perhaps they will become interested in
what was said only after the stock starts to move, following the
distribution of the news. It would therefore make sense for the SEC
to require that a way be found to make the information available
for some period of time to investors who missed the call. That is
no problem if it is released in a statement to the press or an SEC
filing, but it could be one for conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute also raises the issue of just what role analysts
actually play. To Kaswell, the industry association lawyer,
analysts are independent representatives of investors, doing their
best to learn what is going on at a company. But that independence
is sometimes illusory, all the more so now that analysts often are
compensated in part on their success in getting the companies they
follow to sign up as investment banking clients. There is a
suspicion that selective disclosures often go to the analysts who
are deemed most friendly to a company's management, putting more
pressure on other analysts not to be hostile.
</P>
<P>
   If the opponents succeed in blocking this rule, then the
situation may be worse than it was before Levitt brought up the
subject. Such a defeat by the commission would seem to ratify the
practice of selective disclosure. Then those who argue that
selective disclosure is a rare thing might find that it was no
longer so unusual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
