<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV NETWORKS INVESTIGATED FOR POSSIBLE ANTITRUST VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department is investigating MTV Networks for
possible antitrust violations, executives of MTV and its parent
company, Viacom, confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   MTV executives said that they had been asked to provide
information to the department mainly on issues related to the
acquisition by the company early this year of the cable channel the
Box, which also programs music videos, one of the staple offerings
of both MTV and of its sister channel VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Sumner M. Redstone, the Viacom
chairman, dismissed the inquiry as ``much ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view,'' he said, ``there is no antitrust issue and
there is no anticompetitive conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In an official statement, Carole Robinson, the executive vice
president for MTV Newtorks, said, ``We are cooperating fully with
the Department of Justice's review of the Box transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   How much beyond that transaction the investigation may go is
unclear. The Wall Street Journal, which published an article on the
investigation Wednesday, reported that the Justice Department was
examining the plans by the networks to offer videos in digital
format, as well as the requirements for exclusive rights to videos.
</P>
<P>
   One senior MTV executive at first dismissed the notion that the
Justice Department had any interest in MTV's Internet interests or
video rights.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Robinson later clarified that point, saying, ``There
have been incidental questions about the Internet, but it is by no
means the focus of the review by the Department of Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   About the issues surrounding exclusive rights, Ms. Robinson
said, ``We took exclusive rights to only 4 of the more than 1,000
videos used this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Redstone said that MTV pays for rights to use music videos,
which are offered free to other program services.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department declined to address the issue of what
specific practices were under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Rose, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said, ``We are
looking at the possibility of potentially anticompetitive practices
involving music video networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings of MTV Networks have never been better and the
networks are the most profitable channels in cable television, with
a near-monopoly on introducing new music to a wide television
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Music companies and film studios have expressed resentment over
the way MTV exercises its power to reach young consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior MTV executives suggested that record companies
were trying to advance the investigation. ``The record companies
have missed the boat again and again in establishing a direct link
to their customers, and they don't like it,'' one senior MTV
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Some record companies do not like the move by MTV in recent
years to draw back from reliance solely on videos, and toward
scheduled programs like ``The Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Schwartz, the chairman of RuffNation Records, a hip-hop
label, said: ``MTV wants to be like regular TV networks and use
block progamming. So they rely more on `Real World' and their
stupid game shows. I don't like that programming.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he believed MTV's acquisition of the Box would
provide an outlet for new artists to get their work seen. ``I think
that's a good thing,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
