u f BC-COLUMBIA-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      12-15 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF COLUMBIA PICTURES PROMOTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Sony Pictures Entertainment, whose Columbia Pictures
division has had a string of high-profile flops and no sizable hit
since ``Big Daddy'' in early summer, has promoted Columbia's
president, Amy Pascal, to chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Sony Pictures, John Calley _ Ms. Pascal's boss _
said that the title change, which had been expected and was made
official Wednesday, was done mainly to clarify Ms. Pascal's
position as the key person at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that given the performance of recent Columbia
movies, some in the industry might question the move. But he said
that was only because many people in the business focused on the
success of the initial run of films in the United States, which is
declining in importance in the global film industry.
</P>
<P>
   He and Ms. Pascal also said they had high expectations for the
films planned over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message is, she's done a remarkable job and this
is in recognition of and clarification of the way this place
works,'' Calley said. ``We want it to be made clear that we have
great enthusiasm for her here, and we think she has a big future
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia had a huge hit earlier this summer with ``Big Daddy,''
a comedy starring Adam Sandler, and a modest hit at the end of the
summer with ``Blue Streak,'' a comedy starring Martin Lawrence, but
otherwise the news has been bad. Some of the failures have been
high profile, including ``Random Hearts,'' starring Harrison Ford;
``Jakob the Liar,'' starring Robin Williams; and ``The Messenger:
The Story of Joan of Arc,'' directed by Luc Besson.
</P>
<P>
   Sony reported that for the quarter ended Sept. 30, revenue at
its movie division fell 19 percent compared with results a year
earlier. Sony had a 22 percent dip in the quarter ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drop in revenue, the studio remains profitable,
executives said, with net income up 3 percent in the most recent
quarter, driven by the substantial success of ``Big Daddy'' and
money coming in from home video, pay television and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Calley said the move was not intended to foreshadow who might
replace him when his contract expires in two years or to indicate
that rumors that he might retire are true. Ms. Pascal echoed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is staying,'' she said. ``This doesn't mean that John is
leaving. The last thing I would want is for this to make it seem
like that is what this is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Calley said he did not know who would run the company after he
left, whether it might be Ms. Pascal; Mel Harris, the co-president
and chief operating officer of Sony Pictures Entertainment; a
combination of them, or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Mel is running it and I hope Amy is the picture person,
but I don't know,'' Calley said. The decision will be up to his
bosses _ Howard Stringer, who runs Sony's American operations out
of New York, and the top executives of Sony in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a business in which executives often have titles that do
not correspond to their actual power or lines of authority, Sony's
structure is widely seen as particularly askew.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Pascal has been in charge of Columbia for more than
two years and has reported directly to Calley, her title of
president made her seem junior to the two vice chairmen of the
Columbia-Tri-Star Motion Picture Group, Lucy Fisher and Gareth
Wigan, who had no chairman to report to.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the confusion resulted when Sony folded its Tri-Star
operation into Columbia earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's move was intended partly to clarify the issue and
make it clear that Ms. Pascal runs the studio's movie operations.
It came less than a week after Ms. Fisher announced that she was
leaving to join her husband, Douglas Wick, and produce motion
pictures through Wick's Red Wagon Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Calley said he took responsibility for the recent box-office
failures _ although he pointed out that despite the disappointments
the studio was still turning a profit for the year, buoyed by ``Big
Daddy'' and strong video sales for ``Mask of Zorro'' and other
films.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Pascal was in control of the company's movie
operations, Calley held the ultimate vote on whether any individual
picture would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was responsible for green-lighting, so if anybody has to
take the blame it has to be me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he said, are the high expectations that the
studio has for its Christmas releases _ especially an adaptation of
E.B. White's ``Stuart Little,'' starring a computer-generated
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel immensely optimistic about the next cluster and going
on to the next two years,'' Calley said. ``We expect to do more
Stuart Little pictures. We think this is a character that will
appear on television and that will have a long life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pascal ran down some of the movies in Columbia's pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The studio's big summer pictures are Roland Emmerich's
Revolutionary War epic, ``The Patriot,'' starring Mel Gibson; Paul
Verhoeven's invisible-man thriller, ``The Hollow Man,'' starring
Kevin Bacon and Elizabeth Shue; and Martin Campbell's ``The
Vertical Limit,'' a mountain-rescue adventure starring Chris
O'Donnell. Movies for the fall are Billy Bob Thornton's adaptation
of Cormac McCarthy's ``All the Pretty Horses,'' starring Matt
Damon, and a big-screen version of ``Charlie's Angels'' starring
Cameron Diaz, Drew Barrymore, Lucy Liu and Bill Murray.
</P>
<P>
   In the works beyond that, Ms. Pascal said, are a big-budget
``Spiderman'' that the studio hopes will spawn a series; a
biography of Muhammad Ali, starring Will Smith; sequels to
``Jumanji'' and ``Men in Black;'' and Steven Spielberg's adaptation
of the best-selling ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' by Arthur Golden.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that even though this wasn't our best year, we
still made money,'' Ms. Pascal said. ``And next year looks great.
This is a company that thinks of the future. It isn't a company
that makes its strategic decisions every six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Calley agreed and said that part of the reason might be the
outlook of Sony's corporate bosses in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in their style that we don't have some maniac
constantly coming over asking why we haven't fired everybody
because a picture failed or a series was canceled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
