u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      12-15 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGREES TO PAY CHINA $28 MILLION FOR BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The U.S. government has agreed to pay China $28
million in compensation for damage to the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, which was bombed by NATO war planes last May, United
States officials said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   China, in turn, has agreed to pay the United States $2.87
million for damage to the American Embassy and other diplomatic
buildings in China during the week of anti-American demonstrations
that followed the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The two agreements promise to help bring to a close what has
been a particularly tumultuous period in United States-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 2:30 a.m., the United States and China completed
negotiations over the tragic mistaken bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade,'' said David Andrews, the lead American
negotiator, said here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the settlement will be conducive to the improvement
in U.S.-China relations,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After five rounds of difficult negotiations, the compensation
agreements were announced on the day that Joseph Prueher, the new
American ambassador to Beijing, was to present his credentials to
the Chinese government. American officials made clear that they
hoped that resolution of the compensation issue would help pave the
way for a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese were less solicitous in their nearly
simultaneous announcement of the agreement, taking the opportunity
to remind the Chinese populace, once again, of what it has
portrayed as a criminal action by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao called
the bombing ``a gross violation of the universally recognized
international law,'' according to the official New China News
Agency, which called the bombing ``a barbarous act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese announcement did not mention that the Chinese had
agreed to pay the United States for damages to American diplomatic
missions in China.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the state-controlled media characterized the
demonstrations as angry but peaceful and never published photos of
the United States Embassy in Beijing, which was left windowless and
paint-splattered after protesters spent three days hurling rocks,
ink bottles and an occasional fire bomb over its gates.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how far the $28 million will go to patch
up relations and calm the remaining Chinese popular anger over the
bombing, in which 3 Chinese were killed and 27 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese and American officials came together last month
to triumphantly announce a new bilateral trade agreement to ease
China's entry to the World Trade Organization, other joint
initiatives have been on hold since the bombing, including military
exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has apologized for what it has called a tragic
and unfortunate accident, but neither the Chinese government or its
people have really accepted the American explanation for the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Both NATO and American officials said the embassy became a
target after a string of errors involving out-of-date maps and an
incomplete computer data bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese announcement of the agreement once again called on
the United States government to ``conduct a comprehensive and
thorough investigation into the bombing, severely punish the
perpetrators and give a satisfactory account of the incident to the
Chinese government and people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also not clear when the money promised under Thursday's
agreements will be paid. The $28 million promised by the United
States requires congressional approval and will be part of the
fiscal year 2001 budget request, embassy officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the United States agreed to pay $4.5 million to the
victims of the bombing and their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
