<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astronomics force questionable deal
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, Derek Bell and Moises Alou must be
considered damaged goods, and brutally expensive ones to boot.
Richard Hidalgo remains largely unproven, as does Daryle Ward.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the Astros do? Naturally, they ship out their other
outfielder, their most valuable outfielder at present, for a
minor-league shortstop and a minor-league pitcher exactly when
excitement over the team reaches a crescendo because of the new
ballpark coming on line next season.
</P>
<P>
   Is this nuts or what?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, it's how baseball works today. Or, I should say, doesn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we need a salary control system,'' Drayton McLane
Jr. said Wednesday as he attempted to defend a trade that looks to
the future before his ballclub has given the city a fully
satisfactory present. McLane has said this before, of course, and
he is right.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't make an Astros fan feel any better knowing a .325
batting average, 25 home runs and 108 RBIs just got dispatched to
Boston for a kid, shortstop Adam Everett, who figures to spend 2000
in New Orleans and another kid, pitcher Greg Miller, who will be in
Round Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Worse news perhaps than Everett's exit might have been general
manager Gerry Hunsicker's sad revelation regarding Mike Hampton,
the tenacious lefty who won 22 games in 1999 and finished second in
the Cy Young voting. Hampton's agent has told Hunsicker there will
be no talk of a contract extension for his client. Hampy wants to
sample the fruits of free agency next offseason.
</P>
<P>
   So do you keep Hampton around and hope for the best, such as
another 20-win season and a possible pennant, then risk losing him
for nothing in return? Or do you trade him for quality
compensation?
</P>
<P>
   You be the general manager. You might find it resembles, for a
middle-market franchise such as Houston's, a trip to the roulette
table with a whole city watching. And everybody in said city
believing you're playing with their money.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, the baseball man, didn't want to send Carl Everett to
Boston for a prospect _ although a top-drawer one _ who will make
the exchange make baseball sense only if he becomes another Jeff
Bagwell. Hunsicker, the baseball man, wanted to punch holes in the
wall rather than let go of his slick center fielder, a guy he was
particularly proud of seeing develop into a star after enduring
troubling times personally.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't trade Bell or Alou, and he had to trade somebody
of consequence if the Astros were to keep their payroll close to a
status-quo $55 million, a hold-the-line figure mandated by the
fellow most obsessed by the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, the nerve of him, is tired of losing money after
dropping, he swears, $120 million over the seven years he has owned
the team. His goal for the Astros' residency in Enron Park is to
transform them into what he defines as a viable business, one
capable of showing a profit _ independent of ancillary revenues _
in addition to being an artistic success.
</P>
<P>
   He'll never recoup his purported losses, however huge, without
dramatic changes in how baseball operates. Be that as it may, he's
determined to dam what he calls a torrent of red ink, and who among
us wouldn't be? Winning shouldn't mandate one to squander the
family fortune.
</P>
<P>
   But because we haven't seen the books _ nor will we ever short
of a court order _ who can know for certain what the real
consequences of Drayton's naive investment in a troubled industry
has meant to his overall net worth?
</P>
<P>
   At least sacrificing Everett is survivable if Alou and Hildalgo
return healthy and Bell gets his head screwed on straight. Trade
talk put Bell in a funk last offseason, so he decided to spite the
Astros by reporting out of shape and out of sorts mentally. Unless
he's a complete fool, that won't happen again, because now he's
playing for a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, in turn, figures only to build on his successful first
taste of major-league competition, giving the Astros sufficient
outfield depth _ pending the outcome of the aforementioned ``ifs.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Everett had a career year. Maybe Hunsicker, who has
led a charmed existence as a horse trader, timed another one
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Everett, already a major-league-caliber fielder, and
Miller, 20, a 6-5, 235-pound hunk of potential, stand to patch the
biggest holes the Randy Johnson trade left in the Astros' farm
system. Presumably any deal involving Hampton would provide similar
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   McLane and Hunsicker spoke of keeping the Astros young, of
preventing peaks and valleys, and of the franchise's progression
toward a championship. It's an intellectually defensible approach
to be sure, but it's still castor oil in the mouths of fans who
have yet to taste the nectar of real success after 38 years of
waiting pretty darn patiently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0363 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TRUMP-ARCHITECTURE-AR     12-15 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-ARCHITECTURE-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: have caused.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nature Is Greater Than Art &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump has to be the center of attention. I have to turn
everything into a story. These are character defects, symptoms of
extreme narcissism, perhaps even borderline personality disorders.
But they make for a nice bond between writer and subject. The bond
has survived visits to a boxing match, two gambling casinos, a
condominium sales office and Palm Beach _ all ordeals as far as I
am concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Ricky Martin concert is another matter. Thanks to Martin,
I've been meditating on the concept of duende, a Spanish word for
which there is no exact English equivalent. Literally duende means
imp or dwarf, but it is perhaps closer to what we call soul. It's
often used to describe dancers or musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago Calatrava, the Spanish architect and engineer, says it
can also refer to the spirit of a place. He says that if you're
walking along one day and suddenly feel like singing, that's the
duende. He mentions the time of the year in Seville when orange
trees blossom and scent the air.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the duendes don't feel welcome in our part of the
world. We're all too repressed. Being imps, however, they like to
make a surprise appearance from time to time and drive us out of
our minds, as Ricky Martin has been doing in our part of the world
for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a project: making people feel glad to be alive. The
songs, the voice, the movement and the elaborate packaging have all
contributed to the success of this project. So have his
extraordinary good looks, as attested by countless magazine covers.
</P>
<P>
   For the vast majority of his fans, Martin's dreamboat looks are
a fact, a piece of good news to appreciate and fantasize about.
From a critical perspective, the singer's beauty is more
complicated. Criticism is partly an art of complicating simple
things (it's a luxury item in this sense). And beauty,
historically, has topped the list of things critics like to worry
about. It is the pivotal issue in addressing the question of
Trump's taste.
</P>
<P>
   This is something most people won't want to think about: Trump
is a beauty freak. We all like to tee-hee him about the arm candy,
the models, the showgirls. This is easy and fun. It's harder to
accept that the behavior some call womanizing is not a radical
departure from what we call art. The Greeks understood this. Their
concept of beauty derived from nature. The human body is nature's
perfect creation. The gymnasium is where this perfection is
realized. An art studio, so to speak. The old men go to the gym to
admire the young male form.
</P>
<P>
   As a universal point of reference, the body isn't bad. Everybody
has one. The classical temple takes this a step further, merging
anatomical analogies with landscape. The temple adorns a sacred
site of earth. Columns are stylized trees. Figurative sculpture
articulates the connection between architectural form and human
physique. Caryatids, a fusion of animal, vegetable and mineral,
hold up the roof. The erotic origins of art and architecture are
thereby advertised. Duendes welcome here.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Americans seldom experience union with nature outside
erotic relationships and child-bearing. Parks, zoos, wildlife
sanctuaries, adventure tours, wide-screen movies and other virtual
environments have rendered much of the rest of nature into
picturesque attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations are working to close off the sexual option as well.
Sex remains dangerous, not just because of infectious disease.
Beauty is always killing the beast. This is the idea of the sublime
developed by art theorists in the 19th century. Beauty and terror
are inseparable. They come from the same place.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason people like to describe some women as bimbos.
It takes the terror out of beauty to treat it as a joke. Bimbos are
in the eye of the beholder, in other words. Melania Knauss is
indeed beautiful, in the style of Jacqueline Bisset, but with a
less faraway look in her eyes. She and Ricky Martin make a sublime
pair. Trump has organized a trip backstage to see the star before
the concert starts. Barbara Walters can't get in. Bette Midler
can't get in. But Trump gets in, with lots of ``Mr. President!''
``Mr. President!'' along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Encolpius and I tag along and wait outside the dressing room.
Trump calls out, ``Get in here and see this guy! He's better
looking than his pictures!'' Trump does have an eye for male
beauty. Once, striding through the lobby on a tour of 40 Wall
Street, he spies an Adonis working on an elevator cab. Trump points
to him: ``What are you doing fixing elevators? You should be a top
movie star.'' Sounds like a pickup line. But in front of 20 working
hard hats?
</P>
<P>
   Walter Pater, the guru of the 19th-century Aesthetic Movement,
said art critics don't need a fixed definition of beauty. They need
only the power to be moved by it. A repressed Romantic, Pater
evidently couldn't distinguish aesthetic response from an erection.
The Greeks would be with him on that. And they understood that not
all bodies are created equal. The Greeks never took democracy that
far. We're counting on technology to level the playing field in the
beauty competition. And on politics to ensure that looks don't
count. But Pascal was right: had Cleopatra's nose been shorter, the
face of the world would have changed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich people can afford more nature than the rest of us. Then
they usually muck it up. There's no better example of this than
Palm Beach. The climate is extraordinary, the palm trees, flowers
and sunsets are magnificent, and so are many of the houses. But the
way of life is impossible. The jewelry, clothes and hairdos. The
scary gift shop bibelots. The liquor store that's as prominent as a
city hall.
</P>
<P>
   And the bodies, most of them, are far beyond the reach of any
technology we'll live to see. An anthropologist like Margaret Mead
might make sense of this, but I want to hire a sound truck and go
through the streets exclaiming, ``People, you don't want to live
this way!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm disappointed that Trump wants to spend his weekends here.
He's youthful, not stuffy, and doesn't crave isolation. Shirley
Bassey belongs on his sound track, not Rudy Vallee. An essential
part of his taste was formed watching James Bond movies, and I
regret that he hasn't carried this over into his architecture.
Those fantastic Ken Adam sets. The great Fontainebleau Hotel. The
tan young man in white trunks plunging off the high diving board
into the modern blue yonder. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mar-a-Lago is a Citizen Kane's Museum-by-the-Sea. The place is
an encyclopedia of taste cultures, with more period rooms than the
Met. You could spend two months here and pick up a good education
in the history of decorative art, moving from perpendicular Gothic
to American Federal to a child's bedroom with fairy tale scenes
hand-painted by Disney himself. Our time is scarcely represented,
except by the plutocratic desire for pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
