<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUN-MOODY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUN &AMP; BRADSTREET WILL SPIN OFF MOODY'S
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under pressure from investors to do something to increase value,
the Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Corp. said Wednesday that it intended to
separate its Moody's Investors Service credit-rating subsidiary and
its operating company into two publicly traded concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to spin off Moody's comes less than two months
after Clifford L. Alexander Jr., a director who was appointed
interim chief executive in October, publicly dismissed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Alexander indicated that an analysis
arguing in favor of such a step by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., retained
by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet as its financial adviser, had been persuasive.
``Our investment bankers made a very thorough presentation to the
board,'' he said. ``They indicated to us that the values and their
capacity to shine would be enhanced if they were each on their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Making Moody's a separate company is a risky move for the
surviving entity, the Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Operating Co.
</P>
<P>
   That company, which is the home of Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's core
credit-information business, has been floundering. Although nearly
90 percent of employees work for the operating business, the unit
generates less than half of Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's profit.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's stands in stark contrast. With fewer than 1,500
employees, the credit-rating agency accounted for roughly 51
percent of Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's operating profit in the fiscal year
that ended in September and about 28 percent of its $2 billion in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts said a spinoff would reflect the respective
value of the two franchises. ``I think Moody's by itself will sell
in the mid-$20's,'' said James D. Dougherty of Prudential
Securities, estimating the stock price. ``The operating company,
whose business is deteriorating at an accelerating rate, will sell
for a lot less than that.''
</P>
<P>
   News that Dun &AMP; Bradstreet might take such a step was first
reported Wednesday in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted positively to the news. Shares of Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet rose $2.6875, to $29.75 on the New York Stock Exchange.
Before Wednesday, the stock was down about 15 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The separation of Moody's and the Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Operating Co.
is expected to be a tax-free transaction for shareholders,
Alexander said. As such, the proposal needs to be approved by both
the IRS and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it will take six months to nine months to get all
of this done,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Big shareholders, who earlier this year said they were
considering filing resolutions to help force a sale of the company,
were guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is a constructive step toward unlocking
shareholder value at Dun &AMP; Bradstreet,'' said Henry Berghoef, an
analyst at Harris Associates LP, a Chicago money management firm
that owns nearly 13 percent of the company's stock. ``But the
biggest issue here is management, particularly at the operating
company. They need extremely capable management with strong
credibility among investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty of Prudential said that with two executives already in
place at both Moody's and the operating company, it seemed
extremely unlikely that a search would be needed to find someone to
replace Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't need a corporate chief executive,'' he said. ``John
Rutherford will continue to run Moody's and Frank Sowinski will run
the operating company. They will probably go with what they already
have.''
</P>
<P>
   William F. Doescher, a Dun &AMP; Bradstreet spokesman, confirmed
Dougherty's analysis. ``There won't be any need to look for an
outside person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dun &AMP; Bradstreet has taken steps in the recent past to increase
shareholder value by spinning off subsidiaries. In 1996, it spun
off A.C. Nielsen, the market research firm, and the technology
researcher Cognizant Corp., now Nielsen Media Research. And last
year, it spun off the R.R. Donnelley, a yellow pages advertising
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
