<HEADER>
A0367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DISHWASHER22-COX     12-15 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISHWASHER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dishwashers aren't efficient if you don't load them correctly
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you have a dishwasher, do you know where its
owner's manual is? As with any appliance, you can get the most out
of a dishwasher if you use it the way the manufacturer suggests.
But there are a few general rules that apply to just about every
brand.
</P>
<P>
   Dishwashers all work by striking dishes with a spray of hot
water and detergent. The dishwasher then pumps out the dirty water
and detergent, rinses the dishes and dries them.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Maytag Corp., three factors determine whether
your dishwasher will operate at maximum efficiency: the potency of
the detergent and rinse agents you use, water temperature and
proper loading.
</P>
<P>
   Dishwashers won't work with the dish detergents you use for hand
washing in the sink or with laundry detergent. Both these products
may produce excessive suds that can hamper the dishwasher's
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Dishwasher detergents come in one of three forms: powder, gelled
liquid and tablet.
</P>
<P>
   Granule powders, the most traditional form, are effective only
when they are fresh. Never store boxes of dishwashing powder under
the sink; the warmth and dampness there can cause caking and
weakening of the cleaning agents.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid gel detergents can separate as they age. Maytag also said
liquid detergents may cause excessive sudsing in soft water. If you
use a water softener, you may get better results from a powdered
detergent than a liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Dishwasher-detergent tablets are convenient and come
individually wrapped to stay fresh. But with powdered or liquid
detergents you can raise or lower the amount of detergent slightly
to get the best results.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse aids keep water from beading on the dishes. Without them,
water drops tend to cling to glass and metal, leaving spots as the
dishes dry.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid rinse agents are designed for dishwashers with automatic
rinse-aid dispenser. Solid rinse aids will work in dishwashers
without dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   Your owner's manual will lay out the proper loading pattern for
the dishwasher you use, but the guiding principle is that dishes
must be loaded loosely enough to allow spray to hit all dish
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Place all the items in the racks so they are facing the center.
Load silverware in such a way that matching spoons or forks can't
nest together. Don't block the top of the washer tower.
</P>
<P>
   In general, you should wait to use your dishwasher until you
have a full load to wash. Because of the volume of hot water a
dishwasher uses, it consumes a lot of energy. Washing one large
load is more energy efficient than several small loads.
</P>
<P>
   However, avoid overloading the dishwasher. The jets of water
must be able to reach all the dish surfaces, and they can't if the
dishes are too tightly packed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Power &AMP; Light Co. suggests household hot water be
kept at about 120 degrees. However, some dishwashers, particularly
dishwashers without internal heating elements, require water heated
to 130 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   To test water temperature, run the hot-water faucet nearest to
the dishwasher and allow it to build to peak temperature. Insert a
thermometer into the stream or into a glass of the water to get a
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   If the water temperature is under the temperature your machine
needs or more than 140 degrees, you should adjust the temperature
setting at your hot water heater. Water at 140 degrees poses a
scalding hazard; it also wastes energy.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting the dishwasher, turn on the hot-water tap in a
nearby sink until it runs hot. That will insure the water initially
entering the dishwasher will be hot. Avoid other activities that
deplete hot water _ showering, washing clothes _ while running the
dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   Washing in a dishwasher can kill germs about 100 times more
effectively than washing in a sink because of the heat in the
washing and drying cycles, as well as the detergent action,
according to Maytag. Be sure you wash your hands before unloading
the dishwasher or you'll just reapply germs to the dish surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Dishwashers are more effective in soft water than in hard water.
If you're not sure how hard the water in your home is, call your
local water supplier or have the water tested.
</P>
<P>
   If your water is hard, increasing the amount of detergent you
use should improve the cleaning. Dishwashers are naturally
self-cleaning, but especially hard water or water with high iron
and manganese content can leave deposits on the inside of the
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Check your owner's manual for cleaning suggestions, but you may
be able to remove hard-water stains by wiping down the wash chamber
with dishwasher detergent and vinegar. Be sure to wear rubber
gloves, because dishwasher detergent is caustic.
</P>
<P>
   To remove rust stains, start the empty dishwasher at the rinse
cycle and add a commercial soluble rust remover as the dishwasher
fills. Read the label of the rust remover carefully to be sure it
is meant for use in a dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
