<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SNOW-ON-CEDARS-FILM-A     12-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOW-ON-CEDARS-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILM DIRECTOR AND A NOVELIST OF LIFE MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19)  
 (af)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Scott Hicks was in China in 1995, an itinerant
filmmaker shooting a documentary, when he got a message from his
wife back in Australia that as relayed by the Chinese hotel clerk,
``CAM had called.'' Hicks couldn't figure out what that could
possibly mean. CAM.? Who was CAM? And why were they calling?
Finally, he got a line through to Australia. No, not CAM, he was
told, CAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, CAA!'' Mr. Hicks remembers thinking, the Creative Artists
Agency, one of Hollywood's power brokers. ``Even I knew who they
were,'' Hicks said. ``I read Premiere magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, then still a largely unknown documentarian and filmmaker
based in faraway Adelaide, Australia, was in a kind of wonderful
middle ground in his career, after he had completed his first
theatrical film, ``Shine,'' but before it had turned into a
worldwide box office smash and Academy Award nominee. He returned
CAA's call and got an agent on the phone. Well, well, he was asked,
what kind of project might he be interested in doing next?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said the first thing that popped into my head,'' Hicks said.
``I said that I had just read this fabulous book called `Snow
Falling on Cedars.''' CAA was delighted. The agency, he was told,
had arranged a deal for one of its screenwriters, Ron Bass, to
write an adaptation of the novel, by David Guterson.
</P>
<P>
   Then ``Shine'' opened, Hicks was no longer a little-known chap
from Adelaide, and everyone was trying to pitch him with ideas for
what might be his second film. He flirted with dozens of projects
but ``Cedars,'' he said, was always in the back of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, one day, out of the blue, I got a fax from David
Guterson,'' Hicks remembered. ``He said he had just seen `Shine'
and wondered if I had ever heard of his novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between an author, especially the author of a
highly regarded literary novel like ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' and
a director, especially a director with the kind of meticulous
seriousness that produced ``Shine,'' can often be a querulous one.
But when there is a meeting of the minds, as there appears to have
been in the case of ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' (which opens
Wednesday), the results can be a kind of creative rapture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consulted with Scott exhaustively,'' said Guterson. ``Every
moment in the screenplay, every line of dialogue, was subject to
lengthy discussion and work that we did together.''
</P>
<P>
   It began, Hicks said, with a trip he made to Seattle to meet the
author and get him to conduct a tour of the offshore islands that
form the backdrop of the story _ about a young, embittered World
War II veteran caught up in a murder trial involving the husband of
a Japanese-American woman he had once loved. Guterson lives in the
area, on Bainbridge Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleasantly surprised,'' Hicks said. ``David was not the
sort of melancholy type I thought he might be. He turned out to
have a wicked sense of humor. We just connected as people,
instantly.'' More important, Hicks said, the two came to realize
that they had something in common.
</P>
<P>
   Both were creative artists who had been laboring away in
semi-obscurity for many years who had recently and quite suddenly
had a huge rush of success. ``We were two men in early middle age
who had worked quietly for a long time on their own little project
that had suddenly exploded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' is a complex story that spreads
across many years and while it is, at heart, a love story, it also
contains elements of epic historical importance, like the
incarceration of Japanese-Americans in detention camps during World
War II. And there are three main plot threads, Hicks said: a murder
mystery (the Japanese-American fisherman is accused of murdering a
white fisherman, with whose family he had been embroiled in a
soured land deal), a love story (between Ishmael, a war veteran and
editor of the island's newspaper, and the accused fisherman's wife)
and the story of how the war had affected each of them and their
community.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the two men did, Guterson said, was discuss
whether they wanted to make changes in the first draft of the
script, by Bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first draft, there was a considerable amount of
voice-overs, which was Ron's attempt to bring the voice of the
narrator into the film,'' Guterson said. ``Scott and I were of like
mind about that, which was let's try to tell this story without any
abstraction or explanation, without any voice-over telling us what
it all means, what to think and feel about it. Let's let the images
do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson went with Hicks to Montana, where the director was to
meet with Bob Richardson, the cinematographer, who was then filming
``The Horse Whisperer'' with Robert Redford. Richardson lent them
the use of a mountain cabin where they hunkered down to work on a
new draft of the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott is incredibly meticulous,'' Guterson said. ``I've never
met anybody with that kind of energy. I was the author of the book
and you'd think I would be the one pushing, but we spent a few days
together in a small cabin in Montana working from dawn to dusk, at
Scott's insistence.'' Guterson said he had had dreams of taking a
little time to enjoy the Montana wilderness, but the director had
other ideas. ``We started working when the sun came up and finally,
late at night, he'd say, OK, let's go to bed. Then, in the wee
hours of the morning, I'd hear a knock on my door and Scott's voice
saying, `All right, let's get back to work.' And then he'd tell me
about some ideas he'd had during the night. During the night! I
don't know about him, but I was sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During these long hours, the author said, Hicks would describe
for him, shot by shot, how the film would look. ``Scott has this
three-ring binder, the thing is huge,'' Guterson said. ``Every
single moment in the screenplay is in it, each with its own
footnote and bibliography, with drawings, comments, inputs from
various people, research he's done. He just keeps building that
thing over time, page by page, note by note. He dreams the film,
over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, Hicks said, was to convey a great deal of information
as economically as possible without burying the audience in
exposition and without draining the emotion from the story. ``I
find in movies the plot is the Devil,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the novel is a series of mysteries. How did the
fisherman die? Why is Ishmael so bitter? What happened between him
and his former Japanese-Ameover? The plot needed to become
``a gradual revealing of the truth,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rhythm of the movie, Hicks said he wanted it to
slowly build to moments of intense emotion and then explode. ``My
idea was to build a kind of dam of emotion and release it when I
was ready to release it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At various key points in the story, Hicks would let the music
swell and the film zoom back and forth in time, intercutting shots
from Ishmael's youth, from his adolescence, from the war, from the
``present day'' in which the murder trial was taking place (the
late 1940s).
</P>
<P>
   ``The climax of the story is the letter-reading scene,'' he
said, referring to a scene toward the end of the film when Ishmael,
wounded in the war, reads a letter that resolves many of the plot's
mysteries. ``As he is reading the letter, we are cutting between
five different time frames,'' he said. ``None of this was
happenstance or decided in the editing room. It was all indicated
in the screenplay. I wanted to move back and forth in time, in the
way that your memory really works.''
</P>
<P>
   Once these mysteries are revealed, Hicks said, the story can
have its catharsis, can come to a kind of emotional resolution in
the denouement of the murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the screenplay was finished, my role became that of the
happy tourist,'' Guterson said. (The screenplay in the finished
film is credited to both Bass and Hicks.) ``I came to the set,
brought my family to the set. I'd stand there with my hands in my
pockets and stare at the monitors, make a few comments that had
absolutely no decision-making authority attached to them, then
waltz off to lunch. It was great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks finished shooting the film _ which stars Ethan Hawke as
Ishmael, Youki Kudoh as his haunted love and Max von Sydow as the
aged lawyer who defends the accused fisherman _ in 1998 and there
was, initially, some idea of releasing it a year ago. But it really
wasn't ready, Hicks said, so he spent the next several months
tinkering. ``With me, if there isn't a deadline, things sort of
trickle on, and so they trickled on for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hicks thought the film was in good enough shape to show
it to a few people, and he invited Guterson to visit him at the
Skywalker Ranch in northern California, where Hicks worked on the
film's audio mix. ``I went down there and I saw it, sitting in this
vast, cavernous, otherwise empty theater,'' Guterson said. ``Having
worked with Scott so hard through the whole process, I didn't have
any doubt it was going to be a great film. I didn't go in with any
apprehension at all. But it was an odd experience, to see actors
who were attempting to become these characters, who had been born
in my mind and were now taking human shape. It was kind of
unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, who had been a little nervous about the author's reaction
to the film, waited to hear Guterson's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just ecstatic,'' Hicks said, grinning happily. ``He
told me, `There is not one thing about the movie that could be any
better.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
