</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCUMENTARY-FILMS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW-RENT REFUGE FOR BAY AREA DOCUMENTARIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY DEC. 19)(af)  
 Edward Wong writes for The City section of The New York Times.  
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ It was where cinematic flights to the Sahara,
to the concert halls of 18th-century Vienna, to the Amazon jungle
took wing. But this seven-story glass and concrete structure known
as the Fantasy building, where the producer Saul Zaentz has
realized films like ``The English Patient,'' ``Amadeus'' and ``At
Play in the Fields of the Lord,'' is also home base to a different
breed of filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Zaentz has offered low-cost space to
local documentarians, making his building a center for San
Francisco's growing, well-regarded documentary community.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen documentary filmmakers and their crews work
here, where editing machines sit next to Sundance Film Festival
trophies and video camera bags lean against walls dotted with
Academy Award nomination plaques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communities need a mother church,'' said Jon Else, a filmmaker
who teaches at the University of California at Berkeley. ``The doc
community in the Bay Area has a couple, and the Saul Zaentz center
is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the filmmakers pay $150 to $200 a month for an office,
only slightly more than what Zaentz charged a decade ago and well
below market rates in the booming Berkeley-Emeryville area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the least paid and hardest working of everybody in
film,'' Zaentz said. ``They have something they believe in, some
passion they're working for.'' So he lets his more profitable
ventures, an Oscar-winning sound mix and design company and Fantasy
Records, subsidize the space he turns over to the documentary
makers.
</P>
<P>
   The largest documentary operation in the building is Bill
Jersey's. The hallway is lined with framed awards and
black-and-white stills of Jersey aiming his camera at guerrillas in
Nicaragua and the statue of David in Florence. He has won several
Emmys, and his film ``Super Chief: The Life and Times of Earl
Warren'' earned an Academy Award nomination in 1990, but inside the
building his claim to fame is his role as godfather of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just people who wanted to bind together out of
desperation,'' the silver-haired Jersey said as he looked over the
shoulder of his editor in a dimly lighted room. The two were
cutting a film on the Jim Crow era, and archival images of Earl
Warren and Medgar Evers stared back from the video screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like community through brownout,'' Jersey said. ``When
the electricity goes off, you either act like animals or strugglers
who share.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, he and about 10 other filmmakers began renting the top
floor of a building in nearby Emeryville for $400 a month. The
group that bonded included Connie Field, producer of ``The Life and
Times of Rosie the Riveter,'' and a former philosophy student named
Errol Morris. Michael Chandler, now a producer for PBS's
``Frontline,'' called Jersey ``the sun around which we orbited.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Bay Area documentary movement had begun
gathering momentum. As early as the 1950s, local artists had picked
up movie cameras to record the Beat phenomenon. That concern with
social change continued as the hippie culture, anti-Vietnam War
movement and civil rights activity converged on the West Coast. In
the '70s, Les Blank, now one of the most respected filmmakers in
the field, began earning critical praise for his short
documentaries, and Jersey and his friends were toiling away in
their Emeryville sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   When that site was sold, in 1982, they migrated to an old Shell
Oil building, only to see that owner sell five years later. Paul
Zaentz, Saul Zaentz's nephew and an overseer of the Fantasy
building, heard of the roving band of producers and offered them
offices at the bargain prices many of them still pay today. The
building began attracting other artists, like Marlon Riggs, who
made the landmark film ``Tongues Untied'' about black gay
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documentarians talk nostalgically of the days at the
old Shell Oil space, where they shared a single bathroom, kitchen
and lounge area. They crawled over glass dividers to borrow each
other's equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was a big disappointment to come here,'' Jersey
said. ``It was more institutional. The windows didn't open, and we
didn't have an open space to sit and have coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   But for most documentarians, finding a reliable place to settle
overrides such concerns. For instance, Chandler split from Jersey's
group years ago but recently found himself back in the Fantasy
building. ``Producing documentary films is such a fragile
enterprise, fraught with uncertainty and cyclical funding,'' he
said. ``What this place provides is stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler sat on a waiting list for two years before landing an
office on the fifth floor. On a recent morning, he flipped through
four blue notebooks filled with interview transcripts while his
dog, Shumba, slept on the floor. Because Chandler is also an
experienced editor (he was nominated for an Oscar for ``Amadeus''),
two of his neighbors, Deborah Hoffmann and Avon Kirkland, sometimes
wander into his office and ask for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmaking can be a lonely situation,'' said Kirkland, who was
in preproduction on a Ralph Ellison biography. ``And it's terrific
that so many people are around to bounce ideas off of. The two
biggest concerns of many documentary filmmakers is where to find
funds and how to make their program better. And here, you find
people who know something about both.''
</P>
<P>
   While in postproduction on ``Street Soldiers,'' his 1997 PBS
documentary about a juvenile rehabilitation group in San Francisco,
Kirkland showed a rough cut to a half-dozen fellow filmmakers,
luring them with pizza. He gave Jersey a copy on tape. After
watching it, Jersey handed the producer an audiocassette with an
hour's worth of comments.
</P>
<P>
   Such favors are returned: in 1996, Kirkland sat in on a
screening of a rough cut of Deborah Kaufman and Alan Snitow's
``Blacks and Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The political bent of the Fantasy building filmmakers can seem a
bit overwhelming. Where else could you find two producers working
concurrently on unrelated films about apartheid? It's a situation
that could explode into heated competition. But the filmmakers,
Deborah Hoffmann and Connie Field, say they have shared all kinds
of resources, from listings of archival film to names of reliable
crew members in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we take it a little bit for granted, how special and
unique this place is,'' Ms. Hoffmann said. ``I think pretty much
the most interesting docs are coming out of the Bay Area, and a lot
are coming out of this building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
