<SLUG> BC-WALLST-DIVERSITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S EMBRACE OF DIVERSITY LAUDED DESPITE ITS POOR RECORD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite their poor track record on hiring and promoting women
and minorities, firms on Wall Street deserve credit for having
started to embrace diversity, a study from the U.S. Commission on
Civil Rights stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers show a dismal lack of progress,'' said Mary
Frances Berry, chairwoman of the commission. ``It is still true
that white males dominate the most remunerative jobs and
opportunities on Wall Street. But I cannot infer, legally, that
anybody has been discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dwell on those statistics, the commission applauded
the efforts of some firms _ Citigroup, Goldman Sachs Group and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. _ to recruit more women and
minorities and to consider them for promotion to high-paying jobs,
Ms. Berry said, summarizing the conclusions of the commission's
study of economic opportunities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The report on Wall Street grew out of hearings the commission
held four years ago, Ms. Berry said. The commission gathered
employment data from the firms after those hearings, and again a
few years later, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``However slowly, change is occurring,'' she said. ``By and
large, the message is that things are a lot better than they used
to be but not as good as they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The firms accepted the report with a degree of relief in the
wake of several lawsuits that have contended that Wall Street firms
have systematically discriminated against women. The Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission is reviewing hiring and pay data
from Morgan Stanley, after a bond saleswoman at the firm claimed
that she had been denied a promotion because of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Securities Industry Association, a Wall
Street trade group, declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a prepared statement sent to firms, the group's
president, Mark Lackritz, said, ``As the report notes, we have
already made significant progress in these areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2249EST &QL; 
