<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHOSEN-PEOPLE-2TAKES(     12-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOSEN-PEOPLE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORSHIPPING JESUS WHILE WEARING A YARMULKE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Her head covered in the manner of observant Jews,
Zhava Glaser lit Sabbath and Hanukkah candles Friday evening and
recited the blessings over wine and challah in Hebrew. But her
prayers had an extra phrase not found in Jewish liturgy as she
addressed God, ``King of the universe who has sanctified us in
Yeshua, the messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   Chosen People Ministries, an organization composed of Jews who
believe in Jesus, Yeshua in Hebrew, as the messiah, celebrated the
end of Hanukkah with songs, dances, latkes and jelly doughnuts. The
group also was marking the opening of its newest outpost, a $2.2
million building on East 51st Street half a block from the Sutton
Place Synagogue, a 99-year-old Conservative Jewish congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thank you for Hanukkah and because you sent your son,
Yeshua, to die for us and rise again,'' Ms. Glaser's husband, Mitch
Glaser, the 47-year old president and chief executive of Chosen
People Ministries, said as he dedicated the three-story building
that will serve as executive headquarters and house of worship and
study. He concluded, ``Help us to be your light in a dark place in
Yeshua's name.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups like Chosen People, Jews for Jesus, Friends of Israel and
Ariel Ministries are trying to convince Jews they can believe in
Christ without renouncing Judaism, a view that is considered heresy
by the four branches of Judaism _ Orthodox, Conservative, Reform
and Reconstructionist _ as well as by secular organizations like
the Jewish Community Relations Council.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the center comes at a time when Chosen People is
subject to growing suspicion of its motives. Most recently, doubts
have been fueled by its tightening alliances with evangelical
Christians, some of whose avowed goal is the conversion of 144,000
Jews that the New Testament says must precede the second coming of
Christ. In September, Chosen People co-sponsored an evangelical
conference with the Southern Baptist Convention that was called
``To the Jews First in the New Millennium'' and that drew fire from
leaders of the entire spectrum of Judaism. Seven joint follow-up
conferences will be held in the coming months in this country and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five years, groups like this have become more
aggressive in attempts to become the fifth arm of Judaism and to
entice more Jews by the millennium,'' said Philip D. Abramowitz,
director of the Jewish Community Relations Council's task force on
missionaries, which monitors activities of Messianic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen People is one of the oldest Messianic Jewish
organizations. It was established in Brooklyn in 1894 by Leopold
Cohn, a Hungarian rabbi. Until 1986 it was known as the American
Board of Missions to the Jews. Last year, it had revenues of more
than $5.8 million derived mainly from donations, many of them from
evangelical churches and individuals. It has 15 other congregations
around the country, including centers in Yonkers, N.Y., Plainview,
N.Y., Livingston, N.J., West Hartford, Conn., and Brooklyn, where
services are mainly tailored to Jewish immigrants from Russia. It
also operates abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a number of years, Chosen People Ministries was a quiet
Hebrew Christian group that proselytized in an understated way on
the streets and through small advertisements in Christian
publications,'' Abramowitz said. ``Then Mitch Glaser, a former Jew
for Jesus, took over and built it up to be a formidable
organization. Since then it has become more and more visible. We
see its ads in newspapers, its signs on trains and buses, and it is
establishing new centers in Manhattan and Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The ads feature headlines like ``Would you settle for just half
a bagel?'' that say the whole bagel _ acceptance of Christ and not
just Judaism _ is the source of complete spiritual nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of Chosen People's new headquarters to the Sutton
Place Synagogue is often mentioned by Glaser, but how much and what
kind of interaction will occur between the group and the
1,000-member synagogue remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that this is a country where they have the right
to promote their point of view, however wrong I believe it to be,''
Rabbi Alan Schranz, the synagogue's spiritual leader, said. ``But
knowing the membership of my congregation, I do not believe they
have fertile territory here, and I hope they will be courteous and
thoughtful in the way they approach people attending services at
our synagogue. Perhaps their coming here is an opportunity to see
what a true synagogue is. Maybe they'll stop off here and get
something of true Jewish value.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though Jews, in accordance with their theology, reject the idea
that Jesus is their Messiah, many of them concede the right of
Chosen People to their views. It is the strategies used to draw new
followers that disturb them.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say their adoption of Hebrew and the Torah, their use of
skullcaps and prayer shawls is misleading, as is their street
missionary work and the way they sometimes advertise services and
programs as being Jewish without mentioning Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't challenge their right to believe as they see fit,''
said Michael Miller, executive vice president of the Jewish
Community Relations Council. ``But for a Christian to assert that
one can be a better Jew by becoming Christian is deceptive. You are
considered to have undergone conversion when you identify with
Jesus as your Lord and savior.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Jewish Community Relations Council also object to
the effort of Chosen People and other groups to attract Russian
immigrants. ``Russian Jews are prime targets because, coming out of
the former Soviet Union, they don't know much about Judaism,''
Abramowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser, who grew up in an Orthodox home, was ordained a minister
by the Conservative Baptist Association of America in 1980 and
earned a doctorate this year from Fuller Theological Seminary in
Pasadena, Calif. He sits on the board of the Russian Community Life
Center in the Kings Highway section of Brooklyn, which currently
has more than 100 people enrolled in English language and
citizenship classes as well as Bible study. ``We also give
financial aid to impoverished people,'' he said, denying that
acceptance of Christ was tied in anyway to the aid.
</P>
<P>
   In Glaser's view and in that of his followers, there is nothing
contradictory about accepting Christ as the messiah and holding
fast to Judaism. After all, Jesus, they repeatedly say, was Jewish
and so were the apostles.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that being Jewish is primarily an ethnic and cultural
label, he said: ``When Italians accepts Jesus, they remain Italian;
when Native Americans become Christian, they are still Native
American. Simply put, when Jewish people believe in Jesus, they
remain Jewish ethnically, culturally and in their communal
identification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since all Jews should be looking for the coming of the
messiah, by believing in Jesus, we are doing a very religious
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the guests at the new center's celebration, Alan
Schwab, a clothing manufacturer's representative, said he saw
nothing incongruous about the fact that he had come from the
Sabbath service at the Civic Center Synagogue, an Orthodox
congregation on White Street. ``The neighborhood rabbi needed a
minyan,'' he said referring to the required quorum of 10 men.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Ginenthal, who described herself as ``Jewish and
Christian,'' said she was born into an atheist Jewish home and
became devoutly Orthodox during a marriage that ended in divorce
partly because of the religious demands made on her. ``I was a lost
soul and called a healing ministry in Georgia for help,'' she said
at the party. ``They led me over the phone to Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she attends church. ``But I need the connections with
mishpoke that you can't get in Christian churches,'' she said,
using the Yiddish word for family. ``The church in Georgia has told
me that my steps are doubly blessed, that I am a daughter of
Abraham and a bride of Christ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
