<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-KMART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KMART AND YAHOO PLAN NEW INTERNET SHOPPING SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kmart Corp. said Wednesday that it was teaming up with the
Internet portal company Yahoo to create a new company that will
provide free access to the Internet and a co-branded shopping site.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, looking to vault its lackluster Web store into the front
ranks of e-commerce competitors, is counting on Yahoo's popularity
as well as a suite of services like free e-mail to attract traffic
to the new venture. Yahoo is betting that access to the
discounter's enormous customer base _ both through its stores and
its detailed database of shoppers' habits _ will enable it to
become a top site among mass-market consumers, a last untapped
source of potential Web users.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kmart nor Yahoo will make a cash investment in the new
company, called Bluelight.com, after the blue light specials that
became famous at Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank Venture Capital, a Menlo Park-based firm that has been
a leading investor in online companies, put up $62.5 million to get
the company started. Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc. also put
up an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart will own 60 percent of the new venture, which aims to have
a public stock offering within two years. Yahoo will own none of
the company but is receiving hefty advertising revenue in addition
to a new source for registering users.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes as big brick-and-mortar retailers and online
service providers and portals have suddenly seen the advantage of
teaming up and sharing customers. In the last month, Microsoft has
signed a deal with Tandy Corp. to promote its Internet service
through Tandy's RadioShack Stores; America Online has linked up
with the electronic retailer Circuit City to promote its Web access
service, and AOL is said to be in talks with the world's largest
retailer, Wal-Mart Stores Inc., to build a co-branded site.
</P>
<P>
   The Kmart site, which is operating but will not have a full
complement of merchandise until spring, will try to differentiate
itself from the stores by offering only the chain's most upscale
merchandise, like its Martha Stewart brand of linens and pool
furniture. It expects to earn revenue from shopping as well as
advertising. By tapping Kmart's extensive database of customer
information, it hopes to customize the site that consumers see when
they log on.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months, Kmart has developed one of the most
advanced databases tracking customer purchases. ``Not only can we
tell when you buy toothpaste,'' said Kmart chairman Floyd Hall,
``we know what brand and what size you purchased. That can tell us
a lot about your family and the types of products you'll be
interested in purchasing in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to reach people not on the Web is a major priority
for Yahoo, which makes most of its revenue from advertising. Kmart
estimates that 30 million consumers, with household incomes ranging
from $25,000 to $60,000, visit its stores weekly and that 49
percent of them do not shop on the Web. Kmart will promote
Bluelight.com with promotions in its stores.
</P>
<P>
   While Yahoo stands to gain by putting pressure on AOL, which
charges a monthly fee for Internet access, the company risks losing
its image as an exciting young brand by being tied to Kmart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2251EST &QL; 
