<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A TOOTHLESS IRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Dec. 16:
</P>
<P>
   After hearing testimony by outraged taxpayers claiming abuse by
agents of the Internal Revenue Service, Congress passed a tough
bill last year that told the IRS to treat taxpayers nicely and fire
agents who misbehave. The agency and agents got the message. In
startling interviews conducted by David Cay Johnston of The Times,
agents described how they have cut back efforts to catch cheating
by businesses and high-income taxpayers, overlooking complex issues
in a process the agents dub ``audit lite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't collect taxes anymore,'' one longtime IRS official
told The Times. ``We aren't allowed to.'' The danger of such loose
enforcement is that it will foster wholesale cheating and breed
contempt for a code that until now most Americans voluntarily
obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate held hearings in 1997 and 1998 during which outraged
taxpayers accused agents of bullying tactics, armed raids and other
abuses. Congress reacted to the inflammatory testimony by
instructing the agency to improve customer service, cut back on
aggressive tax collection tactics and fire agents who misbehaved in
any one of 10 specific ways that Congress wrote into law. Some of
the testimony was discredited, and a study by the General
Accounting Office failed to find systematic abuse. But Congress had
already cracked down.
</P>
<P>
   The results are beginning to emerge. Thousands of agents have
been transferred out of collecting revenue into customer service _
answering phones, solving problems and otherwise meeting the needs
of confused or upset taxpayers. Auditing has been cut sharply.
Fewer than one in 300 tax returns will be audited this year, a drop
of about 30 percent since 1997 and 70 percent since the early
1980s. In the year ending Sept. 30, the IRS seized property of
delinquent taxpayers 161 times. Two years ago, the number of
seizures was 10,000. Though cutting back its audits of rich
individuals and corporations, the IRS intends to pursue abuse of
tax credits for low-paid workers and people who fail to file tax
returns at all.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Charles Rossotti, appointed two years ago to clean
up the administrative mess, has clearly begun to turn that problem
around. But he issued a mission statement last year that focused
entirely on customer service and failed to even mention collecting
taxes. A Treasury official threatened to increase internal
investigations of IRS agents. That pledge was subsequently
retracted. But the chilling messages to go soft on pursuing tax
cheats reverberate through the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti appears worried that his customer-first edicts have
gone too far. He needs to act soon to counter the impression among
agents that ``no one will do anything'' to force taxpayers, even
cheats and criminals, to pay the taxes they owe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0457 </DOCNO>
