u a BC-ATHLETE-SLAYING-NYT &LR;      12-15 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETE-SLAYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE FOOTBALL PLAYER ARRESTED IN TENNESSEE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rae Carruth, the pro football player who disappeared after he
was charged with murder in the drive-by shooting death of his
girlfriend, was found hiding in the trunk of a car Wednesday night
at a Tennessee motel, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth's arrest in the parking lot of a Best Western motel near
Jackson brought an end to a search that involved investigators from
the FBI. At a news conference in Charlotte, N.C., Wednesday night,
law enforcement officials announced Carruth's capture, saying FBI
agents in Tennessee had received a tip that Carruth was staying at
the motel, about 25 miles east of Jackson. Carruth was apparently
at the motel with a woman, whose identity was not released. The
woman was not charged, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents checked the room, then searched the car parked in the
motel's lot, the law enforcement officials said. ``He was
cooperative during the course of the arrest and processing,'' said
Victor O'Korn, the FBI assistant agent in charge in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, after the death of his girlfriend, Cherica Adams,
24, Carruth was charged with murder in her shooting, which occurred
as Ms. Adams drove through Charlotte just after midnight on Nov.
16.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators say that Carruth and two friends conspired to
kill Ms. Adams, who was six-and-a-half-months pregnant with his
child. The shooting forced doctors to deliver the child by
Caesarean section. Carruth was free on $3 million bail when he
disappeared. After his arrest, he was taken to the Madison County
jail in Jackson, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth, 25, was the first-round draft choice of the NFL's
Carolina Panthers in 1997 out of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Matt Hunter, a spokesman for the Charlotte-Mecklenburg
Police Department, said the officials would try to extradite
Carruth to North Carolina, where he faces charges that include
conspiracy to commit first-degree murder, attempted murder and
shooting in an occupied vehicle. If convicted, Carruth could face
the death penalty or life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
