A0502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HELLER-NYT &LR;      12-15 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HELLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BUT YOSSARIAN LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Dec. 16:
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph Heller was growing up in Brooklyn in the 1930s, he
read the books of an American childhood then: the ``Tom Swift'' and
``Rover Boys'' series. When he also read a child's edition of ``The
Iliad,'' he thought he might want to be a writer. He became one,
and because he had a diamond eye for the phony, the funny and the
lunatic in life, and because he milled his own experience into
characters and dialogue no novelist had employed before, the young
of the last four decades have grown up with a different kind of
classic: Heller's great satire of war and American culture,
``Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1961, it challenged the conventional, heroic view
of World War II. Heller, who died on Sunday at 76, served in that
conflict as a bombardier. He made his protagonist, Yossarian, a
bombardier who was convinced that even a war others viewed as a
necessary collision between good and evil was crazy and designed to
kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the genius of the book was that it allowed readers to
grasp Yossarian's terror and cynicism even if they continued to
believe that World War II was wholly necessary. Then came Vietnam.
When young Americans began to be drafted and die by the tens of
thousands, ``Catch-22'' became a predictive allegory for a war that
truly was unnecessary and therefore deserved the resistance of the
generation it was killing. In ``Catch-22,'' then, Heller left a
very rare kind of book. It succeeded first as a work of literary
art and, for Americans of a certain age, had a forceful second life
as a powerful political document.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
