<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MALCOLM-X-THEFT-NYT &LR;      12-15 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-X-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN COURT WORKER CHARGED IN THEFT OF MALCOLM X DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan court worker was charged Wednesday with
stealing the bloodied and bullet-riddled diary of Malcolm X from a
court evidence safe and selling it to a collector for $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the court employee, Doug Henderson, stole the
diary in 1991, a quarter-century after three men were convicted of
assassinating the civil rights leader in the Audubon Ballroom in
Upper Manhattan in 1965. The diary was in Malcolm's coat pocket
when he was shot to death and it was never returned to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who was charged with grand larceny and possession of
stolen property, declined to speak with reporters as he left the
Manhattan Criminal Courts building after he was released pending a
hearing on March 2. He faces up to seven years in jail if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's lawyer, Gregory Smith, said that Henderson, 41,
attended the Horace Mann School in the Bronx, graduated from Lehman
College and is a first-year student at New York University law
school.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials were notified that the diary was
missing this spring by the editors of a Web site,
www.thesmokinggun.com. When a prominent San Francisco auction
house, Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, announced that it planned to
auction the diary and estimated that it would sell for as much as
$50,000, Malcolm's family objected and the police halted the
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said there was no evidence that the auction house or
the memorabilia dealer involved, Mark Schafler, were aware that the
diary had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney, Robert M. Morgenthau, said
Wednesday that Henderson stole the diary in 1991 from a small safe
used to store bail money in the Supreme Court clerk's office in the
Manhattan Criminal Courts building. Officials said it was routine
for such evidence to be held indefinitely if relatives do not ask
for it. Henderson sold it to Schafler, the memorabilia dealer, for
$5,000 in January 1997, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials had moved the diary into the smaller bail safe,
from a walk-in evidence safe, because they feared that it might be
stolen, prosecutors said. At the time of the theft, Henderson was a
junior court analyst in the clerk's office and did not have
official access to the safe. It was usually left open during the
day, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   It is now in Morgenthau's own office.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Fleming, a Manhattan lawyer representing Malcolm's
daughters, said the plans for the auction were the first they knew
of the diary's existence.
</P>
<P>
   David Bookstaver, a spokesman for the court system, said
Henderson, who now works in a court mediation program, would be
suspended without pay pending the outcome of the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PRINCIPALS-EDUC-NY     12-15 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRINCIPALS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY PRINCIPALS GIVE UP TENURE FOR A RAISE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The union representing New York City school
principals said Wednesday that it had reached an agreement with
city officials and the Board of Education for a new contract that
would end principals' virtually ironclad job tenure, require them
to work a longer school day and eliminate their two-month summer
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for those concessions, principals, who have not
received a pay increase in four years, would get a 33 percent raise
by next April.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Board of Education confirmed the
preliminary agreement, which extends through March 2001 and will
give the principals an average salary of $93,200. But City Hall
officials and others involved in the negotiation said the agreement
had not been signed and that the wording of some contract
provisions must be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all sides seemed to agree that there were no longer any
important issues under negotiation in a bitter contract stalemate
that had dragged on for almost four years and driven scores of
principals to leave for higher-paying jobs in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   One city official said the announcement of the contract, which
could come Thursday, was delayed so that it would not be
overshadowed by the settlement of the transit workers contract.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has made elimination of principal tenure a
strong component of his education policy.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 33 percent wage increase appears large, particularly
compared with the 18 percent increase over three years agreed to
this week by the transit workers union, principals have not had a
wage increase since 1995. The proposed contract extends through
April 2001, with the last scheduled pay increase in April 2000.
Thus, the new wage increase amounts to less than 5 percent per year
compounded annually.
</P>
<P>
   The longstanding system of principal tenure made it almost
impossible to remove an ineffective principal and required an
expensive administrative trial process that could often last years.
Union representatives say that the new system gives principals
three-year contracts and provides for annual performance reviews
that must form the basis for any principal's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   The principals will gain the right to appeal a dismissal or
demotion to an independent arbitrator, to the schools chancellor
and, for a final decision, to the state education commissioner. But
the entire process can last no more than 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   The tenure system for assistant principals and other
administrators has been preserved, both sides agreeing to stick to
an arbitration process that is supposed to last no more than 150
days but has frequently stretched much longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
