<HEADER>
A0512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AIRPLANES-INFANTS-NYT     12-15 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANES-INFANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA ORDERS TODDLER SEATS ON AIRLINERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration said Wednesday
that it would require safety restraints for small children on all
commercial aircraft, meaning that a toddler will no longer be able
to ride in the lap of an adult but must be strapped in a small seat
as though riding in a car.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA administrator, Jane Garvey, told a safety conference
that her agency was putting the regulation into effect because it
was committed to ``ensuring that children are accorded the same
level of safety in aircraft as are adults.''
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with aviation safety and the Washington
regulatory process said the regulation would probably not be
enacted for many months, given the time required for public comment
and debate.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will it be clear for some time who will provide the child
seats _ the airlines or parents or perhaps outside vendors _ or how
much allowance the airlines will make so parents do not wind up
having to pay full fare for separate seats for small children.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear Wednesday that the aviation agency's position
had changed, so that it and the National Transportation Safety
Board were essentially united on an issue that divided them for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board's chairman, James E. Hall, welcomed the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``No parents or caregiver would anticipate being in a situation
in which they are better protected than their children,'' Hall
said. ``That's exactly the predicament they find themselves in when
they and their children travel by airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he had been dismayed and amazed for years that
luggage, coffee, portable computers, even adult passengers must be
secured for takeoff and landing and during turbulence aloft while
``the most precious cargo on that aircraft, infants and toddlers,
were left unrestrained.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement by the FAA evolved at least in part
from a February 1997 report by the White House Commission on
Aviation Safety and Security, created after the July 1996 explosion
of a Trans World Airlines jetliner that killed 230 people off Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Child-safety restraints would have done no good in that
accident, but there have been several others in recent years in
which children who might have lived had they been strapped in were
killed when they hurtled through the cabin on impact.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, 1990, for instance, at least one infant who
conceivably could have survived had he been restrained was killed
in the crash of an Avianca Boeing 707 on Long Island. That crash
killed 73 of the 159 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   And on July 19, 1989, at least one unrestrained infant died as a
United Airlines DC-10 spun in flames down a runway of the airport
at Sioux City, Iowa, in a crash that killed 112 of 296 aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, safety experts at Wednesday's conference noted, a
9-month-old child was among the 37 people who died in the 1994
crash of a DC-9 at Charlotte, N.C. The mother, who could not hold
her baby, survived.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, representing major U.S. airlines,
said the lack of a uniform standard for child-safety seats on
aircraft was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in all sizes and shapes and forms,'' Ron Welding, a
passenger-safety expert for the group, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Welding said most airlines thought passengers should bring their
own child-safety seats, and not just because that arrangement would
be easier for the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child is accustomed to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, the FAA has recommended child restraints. It
recommends a backward-facing seat for children under 20 pounds,
regardless of age, and a forward-facing one for children from 20 to
40 pounds. Children over 40 pounds can be safely buckled in with a
normal seat belt, the agency says.
</P>
<P>
   One government aide who has followed the issue said that putting
the new rule into effect would be ``a mess.'' She said that
airlines have had a mixed record in handling young children and
aiding their parents and that more complicated problems lie ahead:
setting uniform standards for restraints, deciding who provides
them and under what circumstances and making sure that they can be
adapted to seats in the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board has recommended child restraints on airlines
for two decades. For much of that time, the FAA argued against
them, reasoning that if parents had to buy separate tickets for
infants they would be inclined to drive rather than fly _ putting
the child at greater statistical risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
