<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONATION-FOR-LAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND TO HELP SAVE OPEN SPACE IN NEW JERSEY, RHODE ISLAND
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to stem the loss of undeveloped land to
suburban growth in the Northeast, the Doris Duke Charitable
Foundation will give $14 million to projects protecting fields,
marshes and forests in New Jersey and Rhode Island, the most
densely populated states in the country, foundation officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money, $8.4 million, will be used over the next four
years to help private conservation groups buy at least 10,000 acres
of land or restrictive easements in parts of central and northern
New Jersey where construction threatens two important ecosystems:
the Pine Barrens and the ridge of highlands that is the state's
western backbone, foundation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They said $950,000 would be given over the same period to two
private groups in New Jersey working to strengthen local land
trusts and promote land-use planning by local governments that
focuses not just on economic growth but also on protecting wetlands
and other fragile habitats.
</P>
<P>
   A similar package of grants, totaling $4.7 million, is being
made to private groups in Rhode Island, said Peter Howell, the
director of environmental programs for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 billion foundation, based in Manhattan, was established
in 1997 by the estate of Ms. Duke to protect the environment and
support the arts and medical research.
</P>
<P>
   The $8.4 million for land protection in New Jersey will be split
over the next four years between the Nature Conservancy and the
Trust for Public Land, two national conservation groups. The grants
are contingent on the groups' raising at least $4 in public and
private money for each dollar from the Duke foundation, Howell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, representatives of the two groups said they were
confident that the prospect of the Duke foundation money would make
it easier to raise the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Harvey, the senior vice president of the Trust for Public
Land, said the extra money would come from other private donors,
from New Jersey's recent bond act for protecting open space and
from local taxes intended to preserve green tracts in crowded
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This commitment of private funds is a great example and will
leverage many more dollars,'' Ms. Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the need to protect land was greater than ever.
Housing construction, she said, is threatening the northern Pine
Barrens _ a patchwork of stream-laced woods full of rare species _
and spreading up the ridge of rugged hills, west of the state's
coastal plain, that forms a green bridge linking many parks and
sheltering many species.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the Duke foundation was welcomed by
environmental groups around the New York metropolitan region,
mainly because it would provide a spur to land preservation in a
state that has not seen many large gifts from philanthropists
intended for environmental protection, particularly compared with
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few dozen miles to the east, in the Hudson River Valley,
for example, more than $125 million has been spent over the last
decade on preserving land by a single foundation, the Lila Acheson
and DeWitt Wallace Fund for the Hudson Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see this commitment to New Jersey,'' said Joe
Martens, the president of the Open Space Institute, one of two
groups that are conduits for the Wallace fund money, which can be
spent only in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Duke foundation appeared to be establishing a
long-term commitment to the region, with the new grants following
its gift of $5 million in 1997 to secure the purchase of Sterling
Forest, a 16,000-acre wooded tract straddling the New York-New
Jersey border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of money necessary to curb sprawl and encourage
good land use is in short supply,'' Martens said, ``particularly in
places where development is heaviest and land prices are the
highest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
