<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-15 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A PERFECT TIME OF YEAR TO DO SOMETHING FOR THE COMMON GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) It's not supposed to be the Me Generation anymore, but
business managers and leaders of volunteer groups may argue.
</P>
<P>
   Workers ask (though perhaps not aloud), ``What's in it for me?''
when their participation is requested on a project beyond their
personal job descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no individual gain attached to the corporate effort,
many employees decline involvement, provided they have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   The same question or its corollary, ``What's in it for my kid?''
are prime considerations when volunteer appeals are made.
</P>
<P>
   If the cause isn't my family's disease or my kid's activity,
then the volunteer commitments are much harder to get. Just ask
volunteer group leaders to tell you who constitutes their committed
core. It's usually people with the greatest self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   The unsteady state of human interaction in the 1990s has
elicited considerable sociological rumination about America's loss
of ``social capital.'' Consensus says the connective tissue that
binds people for mutual benefit has been shredded by attitudes of
``Who cares?'' and ``It's not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss is manifested in declining membership in organizations,
declining volunteer numbers, declining voter turnouts and declining
civility among strangers.
</P>
<P>
   It shows up, too, in the vanishing of ``third place'' gathering
spots, the term some sociologists give to those nonhome, nonwork
places, such as town social halls or neighborhood bars. Those are
the places where people spend time together and get to know one
another, instead of cocooning in front of their television sets or
making solitary daily commutes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, our connective tissue runs through telephone lines
and computer screens. The impersonalization of recorded sales
messages, voice mail and e-mail makes it possible to think real
people aren't on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   And if they're not real, who cares about them?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a do-gooder message attached:
</P>
<P>
   It's a perfect time of year, if not of the century, to
contribute to the collective good.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, there are counterarguments:
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't pay me enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's doing me any favors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all I can do to take care of myself (or my family).''
</P>
<P>
   And the ever-present ``Who has the time?''
</P>
<P>
   All may be true to large or small degrees. But where would our
nonprofit and profit-making organizations be without individuals
who take the time and make the commitment to extend themselves
beyond their own self-interested orbits?
</P>
<P>
   Short answer: The institutions would be in worse shape than they
are now.
</P>
<P>
   Income levels and ``spare'' time vary mightily among
individuals. How much money or how much time one gives can't be
dictated or judged by others. It's a matter of billfold and
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet everyone prospers when some people respond to the small
voice that calls for weaving, instead of tearing, the social
fabric. The sum of individual commitment makes for better
workplaces, better communities, better schools and better families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991215.0467 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0519 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-DRUGMAKERS-MERGER-KAN     12-15 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGMAKERS-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOECHST, RHONE-POULENC ENTER NEW ERA AS LARGEST DRUGMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hoechst AG and Rhone-Poulenc SA completed
their $29 billion merger into the world's biggest drugmaker
Wednesday, signaling the start of a new era for the Kansas City
enterprise formerly known as Marion Laboratories Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The new company is known as Aventis SA, with global headquarters
in Strasbourg, France. The company's U.S. drug operations will be
known as Aventis Pharmaceuticals. Drug operations outside the
United States will be known as Aventis Pharma.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the merger, the North American headquarters of the
former Hoechst Marion Roussel pharmaceutical unit will move from
Kansas City to New Jersey, a move that will pull 900 white-collar
jobs out of the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The North American headquarters will be housed at an interim
site in Parsippany, N.J., before establishing its permanent
headquarters in Bridgewater, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   After the headquarters move, the company will retain about 820
manufacturing and related employees in Kansas City, where it makes
the Cardizem heart drug and the Allegra allergy medication.
</P>
<P>
   Aventis Pharmaceuticals spokesman Charles Rouse repeated the
company's earlier assertion that all 900 Kansas City headquarters
employees will have the opportunity to move to the new headquarters
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   However, they may have to be flexible concerning the kind of job
they move into, Rouse said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not get to go in the exact job they have now, but
there are many opportunities for which candidates are being
considered,'' Rouse said. ``Jobs are changing because the company
is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rouse said about two dozen employees, mostly senior managers,
already had accepted offers to relocate from Kansas City to New
Jersey. Top managers are being selected and they will make plans
for their divisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aventis by April will have a better idea of how many Kansas City
employees will ultimately move to New Jersey, Rouse said. The
headquarters move is expected to begin in February and take most of
2000 to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary signs displaying the new Aventis corporate identity
will go up at the company's south Kansas City complex Thursday,
Rouse said. Permanent replacement signs will be installed in coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the loss of 900 jobs, the headquarters loss will end
part of the legacy of the late Ewing Marion Kauffman, who in 1950
founded Marion Laboratories Inc. as a one-man company, operating
out of the basement of his home. Through mergers, the company later
became part of the former Marion Merrell Dow Inc. and Hoechst
Marion Roussel, which was part of Germany-based Hoechst AG.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman also was known for his philanthropy and for bringing
major league baseball back to Kansas City with the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The latest merger also hits Collegeville, Pa., where the
Rhone-Poulenc Rorer pharmaceutical unit has had extensive
operations. All 1,650 jobs at the Collegeville site will be moved
to other cities as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The merger became official after Rhone-Poulenc shareholders
backed the creation of shares to be exchanged for those of its
German partner. The new company will have more than $21 billion in
annual sales and leapfrog AstraZeneca PLC in becoming the world's
No. 1 drugmaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
