<HEADLINE>
RYDER CUP TO REVISE DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each member of this year's U.S. Ryder Cup team will receive from
the PGA of America $200,000, which will be donated to charity and
to collegiate golf developmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   A Professional Golfers Association of America official, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the plan calls for each
player and the captain Ben Crenshaw to receive $100,000 for the
charity of his choice. An additional $100,000 for Crenshaw and for
each player will be directed toward a college, or several colleges,
to finance a golf development program designed by the association.
</P>
<P>
   An official announcement is expected to be made early next year,
once players have a chance to identify their charities. The plan is
similar to the one for the Presidents Cup, whose players each
receive $100,000 from the PGA Tour toward the charity of his
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to allocate Ryder Cup profits to the players'
charities for the first time comes in the aftermath of a
controversy this year concerning the tournament's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Golf Digest reported that the PGA was expected to gross $63
million from this year's Ryder Cup at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass. The net profit was expected to be $23 million,
with $6 million going to The Country Club. Meanwhile, a large
portion of the PGA profit goes toward its Ryder Cup Outreach
Program, which includes several projects aimed at promoting
interest and participation in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Several players, most notably Tiger Woods, David Duval and Mark
O'Meara, strongly suggested that the Ryder Cup team members, who
are not paid to play, should have the right to designate revenue
from the biennial event toward the charities of their choice. Some
of them wanted the issue to be settled before this year's Ryder
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   During the PGA Championship last August, the debate became
heated. Two days before the tournament began in Medinah, Ill., team
members met with Jim Awtrey, chief executive officer of the PGA,
and Tim Finchem, commissioner of the PGA Tour, to devise a Ryder
Cup plan that would be satisfactory to the players and to the
association.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Awtrey said a plan would be in place by the
end of this year, but there were still some hard feelings. Some
players were strongly in favor of a revenue-for-charity plan. But
others insisted that the players should be worried more about
winning than about revenues, especially since the Ryder Cup did not
become a huge money maker until the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Ryder Cup began in September, the issue was not a
distraction, and the event was memorable. The United States
defeated Europe, 14{-13{, overcoming a 10-6 deficit on Sunday to
stage the greatest final-day comeback in Ryder Cup history. The
event became even more compelling, and neither the players nor the
PGA of America wanted a dispute over revenue to linger for another
two years.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
