A0522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBANS-JAIL-HOSTAGES-     12-15 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBANS-JAIL-HOSTAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN INMATES MAINTAIN TENSE HOSTAGE STANDOFF IN LOUISIANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MARTINVILLE, La. _ Nearly two decades after they were swept
ashore in the Mariel boatlift, a group of Cuban inmates is staging
a violent bid to be released or deported, holding three hostages at
knifepoint in a parish jail here.
</P>
<P>
   As many as nine inmates used hand-fashioned knives and sharpened
screwdrivers to overpower the jail warden and two deputies on
Monday afternoon, and the standoff showed no sign of easing by late
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates have apparently seized a control room of the St.
Martin Parish jail in the heart of Cajun country, because sheriff's
officials said they were unable to release or move the 80 prisoners
incarcerated elsewhere in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wednesday night marked the end of the 72-hour period
after which the inmates said they would kill their three hostages,
there was no sign that they had carried out their threat. As
heavily armed riot police surrounded the jail, FBI negotiators
continued trying to persuade the inmates to release their captives.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the Cubans allowed 39 prisoners to leave the
jail, bringing to 90 the number of prisoners who have been allowed
to leave since the beginning of the incident. The action was
praised by Kriss Fortunato, an FBI spokeswoman, who also said the
hostages appeared to be in good condition. Ms. Fortunato would not
describe the progress of the negotiations, but said officials were
pleased that there was communication.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans' grievances are similar to those that have caused
numerous uprisings in Southern prisons and jails since 1980. ``All
we want to do is leave the country,'' one Cuban told a radio
station here.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service will not release any
detainee who is deemed a threat to public safety, and though the
agency would like to return them to Cuba, the Castro government
will not let them back in.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Bergeron, director of media relations for the immigration
service in Washington, said about 2,500 Cubans were in custody
around the country, many in small county jails like the one here.
About 1,750 of those came on the Mariel boatlift in 1980, during
which Fidel Castro sent hundreds of criminals to the United States,
and Bergeron said all of the 60 Cubans in the St. Martin jail
arrived then.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 years, Bergeron said, the American government
has released 6,000 Cuban prisoners, including every detainee on the
Mariel boatlift. Any Mariel participant still in prison, he said,
has committed a crime in the United States and was then rearrested.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bergeron would not characterize the inmates who took
hostages, he repeated that all Cubans in the jail were Marielitos.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador Longoria, a Cuban American lawyer in New Orleans who
has worked with many detainees around Louisiana, said the
frustration exhibited by the inmates was typical of those caught in
the political and legal limbo of detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't be deported, and they can't be released,'' Longoria
said. ``Some of them have been in jail for years, and they see no
hope and no chance for liberty. They'll do anything to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   One inmate telephoned a local television station on Tuesday and
said he had been in jail for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be released and sent back to our country or any
other country,'' said the man, who identified himself as Jonne
Ponte. ``We don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The immigration service would not confirm the status of
individual prisoners or say on what charges they were being held.
But Bergeron said long-term prisoners could have their cases
reviewed every 90 days and were released if they could demonstrate
they had been rehabilitated or were no longer a threat to society.
Those still in prison, he said, are considered a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to gain by keeping them in jail,'' Bergeron
said. ``They are in custody because they have been convicted of
crimes, and we have to be judicious in determining who is
released.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubans being held in small-town jails around the country are
attractive to county governments because the immigration service
pays the counties an average of $55 a day for each prisoner, which
is more than the state pays for other criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
