<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGURINES-CRUELTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL CAT PELTS USED FOR SOME CAT FIGURINES, INVESTIGATION FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ ``The smallest feline is a masterpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Leonardo da Vinci
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Cats are held in high esteem in many
countries, especially in the United States. Do something bad to a
cat and you'll have an outraged cat fancier on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   So when Rick Swain, an official with the Humane Society of the
United States, boarded a plane two weeks ago to Kansas City, he
knew that he had information that would be explosive to legions of
cat lovers.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing to three Hallmark Cards executives, he laid out
the Humane Society's latest undercover investigation. The target:
those furry cat figurines that have become increasingly popular.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason that many of the figurines _ perhaps hundreds
of thousands _ looked so realistic. China was slaughtering cats and
using the pelts to make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are appalled,'' said Michael W. Brim, a spokesman for the
Cat Fanciers' Association in New Jersey, a national registry of cat
breeds.
</P>
<P>
   The figurines were sold by retailers throughout the country. The
investigation determined at least a couple of Hallmark stores sold
them, which was one of the reasons for the Kansas City briefing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Humane Society found Hallmark blameless. The
company didn't know that real cat fur was being used, and the
figurines weren't a Hallmark product. Some Hallmark stores, which
are independently operated, had apparently bought some of the
figurines from outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger story stands, said Swain, vice president of
investigative services for the Humane Society. China is killing
hundreds of thousands of cats, and about 20 percent of the cat
figurines being sold in the United States are made with real cat
hides. The rest use fake fur, rabbit pelts or other materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't help but give you pause,'' said Steve Doyal,
Hallmark's vice president of communications and one of the
executives at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The details are horrific. The Humane Society investigation,
which included an undercover visit to one of the plants in China,
found that many cats were hanged and slowly suffocated, or clubbed
and allowed to bleed to death. On occasion, the cats were skinned
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty five years of police work had not prepared me for the
level of cruelty I witnessed in China,'' Swain said.
</P>
<P>
   After the cats are stripped of their fur, the pelts are taken to
one of an estimated 20 factories. In the plant visited by the
investigator, stacks of orange and gray-tabby cat pelts were ready
to be made into figurines.
</P>
<P>
   The fur is stretched over molded plastic, and the figurines are
then finished by popping in plastic eyes and gluing on plastic
whiskers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is remarkably lifelike. Some of the cats appear to be
curled up and sleeping. Others have their paws playfully stuck up
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   And they're cheap. The Humane Society says a full-size cat
figurine costs no more than $35; some were found in the Kansas City
area for $12. A kitty figurine could be purchased for $6.
</P>
<P>
   The plant visited by the Humane Society was staffed mostly by
girls, some appearing to be no more than 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The use of child labor around the world has received plenty of
publicity in recent months. But many labor experts say very little
has actually changed, especially in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more surprised by the live cats than I am by the child
labor,'' said Judy Ancel, director of the Institute for Labor
Studies in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Some who bought the cats say they should have suspected
something was amiss. One area resident took one of the furry
figurines home, where her cat began to lick and groom it and even
played and went to sleep with it. She has put the figurine away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether to throw it away or bury it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Wolfe, owner of the Kitty Keepers pet-sitting service in
Shawnee, said that while shopping last week she saw one of the cat
figurines and petted it. The texture of the fur was similar to a
cat. But, she thought, how could it be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened my suspicions were correct,'' said Wolfe, who
didn't buy the figurine.
</P>
<P>
   For retailers, the issue now is what to do with them. Some Osco
stores have sold the figurines that may have been made with cat
fur.
</P>
<P>
   The figurines were still on the shelves of at least one area
Osco store Tuesday evening. But Karen Ramos, an Osco spokeswoman,
said Wednesday that the figurines were being removed from stores,
and anyone who bought one could get a refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously a sensitive issue and potentially disturbing
to some people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark officials sent a letter about the figurines to all its
retailers last week. Although they aren't Hallmark products,
Hallmark urged them to stop selling the figurines and offered to
help pay refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn Ferrel, owner of several area Hallmark stores, said he
found two of the figurines at his stores. He doesn't think they
were made from real cats, but he can't be sure, so he has
permanently taken them out of the stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in that kind of business'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swain said publicity would be the key to stop the selling of the
figurines. The Humane Society official believes retailers have
unknowingly sold them. As word spread, that shouldn't be an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Humane Society estimates that one out of five of the
figurines were made with real cat pelts, only an expensive forensic
test can tell. Swain's advice: Buy none of the furry figurines.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the lesson in all of this, say Wolfe, of Kitty
Keepers. If you want a furry cat, keep to the live ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer my fur to be living,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
