<HEADER>
A0527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-COL-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      12-15 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METRO MATTERS: FORGET DIVERSITY, REPUBLICAN DEBATE IS A GUY THING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This column was going to focus on the absence of even
one remark about America's cities during Tuesday's Republican
presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Tuesday's debate was held in a farm state (Iowa), but if
the six candidates could intersperse pronouncements on the family
farm and ethanol subsidies with talk of trade with China and soft
money, presumably they could have given a nod to issues like
immigration, congestion, pollution and housing.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't, and now that unfortunate silence will not be
the subject of this column anyway, because an even more compelling
theme emerged from the debate:
</P>
<P>
   It was so very male.
</P>
<P>
   If MSNBC had broadcast the event in black and white, it could
have been Pleasantville, circa 1952. The candidates were men. The
questioners were men. The network analysts and campaign pitchmen
were men.
</P>
<P>
   No plot is herewith alleged; some of the evening's maleness was
coincidence. But the opinions voiced by the candidates were no
coincidence. And to fans of real debate and diversity, aspects of
those 90 minutes were troubling.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if nobody on that stage had ever heard of the gender
gap, as if anguished moderate Republicans had never called for a
broader range of party opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not talking about what is a woman's concerns, not
thinking, `What do women think about this?''' said Tanya Melich, a
disaffected Republican who wrote ``The Republican War Against
Women'' (1996, Bantam). The candidates spoke with one voice against
abortion, and where during any of the three debates, she asked, was
a serious discussion of other matters of particular concern to
women, like gun control and education?
</P>
<P>
   The debate began with Tom Brokaw's asking what had contributed
to the Columbine shootings, at one point saying ``things are a lot
worse off now'' than when President George Bush took office.
Actually, they are not. Despite the school shootings, FBI
statistics show that crime, including violent crime, has dropped
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates might have made that point. But instead
all spoke in dire terms about the country's terrible condition,
with back-runners Gary Bauer, Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, Steve Forbes and
Alan Keyes citing the incidence of abortion as a contributing
factor. There was no discernible dissent from either of the two
front-runners, Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   When Bauer asked Bush to pledge that he would never ask anyone
favoring abortion rights to be his running mate, singling out Gov.
Christie Whitman of New Jersey, Bush said he would name someone who
could be president. At no point did he or any of the other
candidates suggest that Whitman had a right to her opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not abortion rights, yea or nay, or Republicans vs.
Democrats. It was just as disturbing a few years ago when
Democratic leaders in Albany, N.Y., opposed to a proposed ban on
late-term abortions, maneuvered to limit floor discussion. The
issue is the nature of our political debate, the pretense of the
candidates that there is no other side.
</P>
<P>
   For insight into that other side, the six candidates might pick
up a copy of ``In Our Time'' (The Dial Press), a new history of the
women's movement in which the author, Susan Brownmiller, recounts
women's harrowing search for illegal abortions in the days before
Roe vs. Wade. Ms. Brownmiller was resourceful and could afford to
pay enough to avoid a butcher. Other women could not; hence the
resort to coat hangers, often resulting in infections, sterility,
even death.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the candidates who oppose abortion have thought through
the likely ramifications of a constitutional amendment outlawing
abortions and concluded that they favor overturning Roe vs. Wade.
That is their right.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it also the obligation of the men running for
president to examine the complexity of this difficult matter?
Instead, viewers got either platitudes or silence from Bush and
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Not all women favor abortion rights. Elizabeth Dole, who ran
briefly for the Republican nomination, does not. But even her
participation in that debate would probably have made a difference.
``They would have had to respond to someone of a different gender
sitting up there with them,'' Ms. Melich said. ``A different
dynamic occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no woman on the stage in Des Moines. In fact,
there was no woman _ just as there was no city _ in the mind of any
of the performers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-99 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
