<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-PARKING-AMNESTY-NY     12-15 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PARKING-AMNESTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CANCEL PARKING TICKETS OLDER THAN 3 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WENDY GINSBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Not long ago, Warren H. Victor reached into his
mailbox in Perth Amboy and pulled out a $169 bill from the city's
municipal court. A decade earlier, a meter reader had slapped his
car with a $1 ticket.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court's records, Victor had never paid the
dollar, and it had ballooned with penalties and interest into a
staggering fine and a court summons. ``I guess I was on my way to
jail,'' he said. But after a week rummaging through old files, he
found the dusty canceled $1 check that proved he had paid the
ticket on time.
</P>
<P>
   After Perth Amboy officials admitted their mistake, they offered
to take Victor to lunch. ``I told them to keep their lunch and get
their act together,'' he said. ``There are only three crimes in the
New Jersey that don't have a statute of limitations: murder, rape
and parking tickets. I knew something had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   So Victor turned the tables on municipalities that were slow or
sloppy in collecting parking fines. He found other New Jerseyans
who had been wrongly fined and began lobbying the Legislature to
step in. The result of that two-year campaign, he says, is a bill
that would excuse drivers from paying parking tickets that are more
than three years old.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which was passed by the Senate on Dec. 6 and now
awaits a vote in the Assembly, also requires towns to notify
drivers by mail of overdue parking violations, and to warn them
that they could be arrested as scofflaws or have their licenses
suspended if they do not pay the fines.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's co-sponsor, Assemblywoman Joan Quigley, a Democrat of
Jersey City, said the idea is certainly popular. When she asked
constituents to relay their parking woes, her office was inundated
with mail for weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
