<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINOS-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI PANEL APPROVES MERGER OF HARRAH'S AND PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYLAND HEIGHTS, Mo. _ Harrah's Entertainment Inc. took another
bite of the state gambling pie Wednesday, gaining approval from the
Missouri Gaming Commission for a merger with Players International
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If Harrah's gets approval from three other states, it will take
over two Players casinos in this St. Louis suburb and others
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's is battling with Station Casinos Inc. for market
supremacy in the Kansas City and St. Louis areas. Station has a bid
pending to buy the troubled Hilton Flamingo Casino in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's, with two casinos in North Kansas City, would bring in
more than 40 percent of the state's gambling revenue if the Players
merger is approved. State financial analysts said Harrah's had a
``strong financial picture'' but restated the need to closely
monitor the company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics called the $430 million merger part of a troubling
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Louisiana attorney general recommended
that Players lose its license after executives were caught up in a
casino licensing scheme that involved kickbacks to then-Gov. Edwin
Edwards and others.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of losing its license, the company is pursuing the
merger with Harrah's. However, Players must pay the state of
Louisiana $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Taylor, executive director of St. Louis-based Casino
Watch, said gambling companies were buying themselves off the hook
again.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and others criticized federal authorities for letting
Hilton executives avoid harsh sanctions if they sold the Flamingo.
Hilton agreed to pay a $500,000 fine to the federal government to
avoid criminal charges that it provided financial rewards to Kansas
City officials in exchange for political support for the casino
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This basically amounts to license laundering,'' Taylor said.
``These buyouts allow the companies to walk away clean. If you or I
had done these things, it wouldn't be that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   After a failed bid from financier Donald Trump, Hilton is
entertaining an offer from Station to buy the Flamingo. The
commission did not publicly discuss the pending offer Wednesday.
Station had hoped to complete the Flamingo acquisition by Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also did not publicly discuss the status of
prominent St. Louis lawyer Michael Lazaroff, who resigned from his
law firm partnership earlier this month amid allegations of
misconduct. Lazaroff had represented Station on some gambling
issues in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, did come down hard on the Players
operations in Maryland Heights for recent violations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission suspended the gambling licenses of three
executives for three days for not reporting an employee's
allegation of theft in the casino's ``hard count'' room, where
tokens are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the commission fined Players $100,000 after a special
audit discovered 128 errors in counting money over a seven-month
period.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the issue of Players' legal troubles in Louisiana, other
critics have called the buyouts a bad deal for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking is that fewer companies with licenses will move
Missouri's two major markets closer to a monopoly. That will
discourage the two key players, Station and Harrah's, from offering
promotions such as cut-rate coupons and high slot payouts, critics
fear.
</P>
<P>
   But Vern Jennings, senior vice president and general manager of
Harrah's St. Louis-Riverport, said the Station-Harrah's rivalry
would ensure that both companies keep customers in mind, even after
any acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep an eye on each other,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said he expected to retain nearly all the 2,500
employees at Harrah's and Players casinos in Maryland Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members quizzed Harrah's representatives about the
company's plans. The company plans to consolidate its four St.
Louis area casinos into two. Currently, the Harrah's and Players
casinos share the Riverport facility in Maryland Heights, about 20
miles west of downtown St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The merger still needs approval from gambling regulators in
Kentucky, Illinois and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In other action:
</P>
<P>
   - The commission struck a blow for gamblers by requiring casinos
to allow card counters to play blackjack. Some casinos nationwide
had tried to ban card counters from the table.
</P>
<P>
   When a player counts cards, he or she mentally keeps track of
what face cards have been dealt. That way, a player can determine
the likelihood of more face cards and adjust bets accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling industry has tried to curtail the practice.
</P>
<P>
   - The commission also levied a $15,000 fine against Bill Grace,
principal owner of St. Jo Frontier Casino in St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said that on May 29, Grace verbally abused
security officers who were delaying patrons from boarding. Also,
Grace was disciplined for drinking wine at a restaurant that is
part of the casino's nongaming facilities. Grace did not submit a
written request to drink there, as state law requires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
