<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO CALIFORNIA MEN ACCUSED OF USING WEB TO LIFT STOCK
</P>
<P>
   In a case that shows both how easy it is to artificially inflate
the price of stocks on the Internet and how quickly prosecutors can
identify the culprits, two California men were charged with sending
bogus messages over the Internet to pump up the price of a bankrupt
company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that the men used the Internet to
artificially propel the price of an obscure stock from 15 cents a
share to more than $15 in less than two trading days last month,
reaping $364,000 in profits for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY'S INVESTORS TO BE SPUN OFF
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from investors to do something to increase value,
Dun &AMP; Bradstreet said that it intended to separate its Moody's
Investors Service credit-rating subsidiary and its operating
company into two publicly traded concerns. Stockholders reacted
positively to the news, sending shares of Dun &AMP; Bradstreet up
$2.6875, to $29.75.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY STOCKS RESUME RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft led the stock market higher, putting an end to a
one-day slump in high-technology shares. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 65.15 points, or 0.6 percent, to 11,225.32. Broader
stock indicators also closed higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index increased 10.15 points, or 0.7 percent, to
1,413.32, and the Nasdaq composite index jumped 50.29 points, or
1.4 percent, to 3,621.95.
</P>
<P>
   TELEWEST SEEN IN DEAL FOR FLEXTECH
</P>
<P>
   Telewest Communications, the British cable television company,
is expected to announce Thursday that it will pay about $3 billion
in stock for Flextech, a pay-TV channel provider.
</P>
<P>
   STUDY PRAISES PUSH FOR DIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   Despite their poor track record on hiring and promoting women
and minorities, firms on Wall Street deserve credit for having
started to embrace diversity, a study from the U.S. Commission on
Civil Rights says.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN FOR TAX-FREE INTERNET ASSAILED
</P>
<P>
   Proposals to make the Internet a tax-free zone came under attack
by large retailers, shopping-center owners and state and local
officials in testimony before a panel created by Congress to study
the question.
</P>
<P>
   KMART IS TEAMING UP WITH YAHOO
</P>
<P>
   Kmart said that it was teaming up with the Internet portal
company Yahoo to create a new company that will provide free access
to the Internet and a co-branded shopping site. Floyd Hall, the
chairman and chief executive of Kmart, is looking to push the
company's lackluster Web store into the front ranks of e-commerce
competitors. Kmart is counting on Yahoo's popularity as well as a
suite of services like free e-mail to attract traffic to the new
venture.
</P>
<P>
   MTV CONFIRMS ANTITRUST INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is investigating MTV Networks for
possible antitrust violations, executives of MTV and its parent
company, Viacom, confirmed. MTV executives said they had been asked
to provide information mainly on issues related to the company's
acquisition early this year of the cable channel The Box, which
programs music videos.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT FINISHES WINDOWS 2000
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that it had completed the development of its
Windows 2000 operating system software, the successor to Windows
NT, which is sold mainly to businesses. The often-delayed program
was sent to manufacturing plants and should reach the public Feb.
17.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT PROMOTED AT COLUMBIA
</P>
<P>
   Amy Pascal, the president of Columbia Pictures, which has had a
string of flops and no sizable hit since ``Big Daddy'' in early
summer, has been promoted to chairwoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
