<SLUG> BC--KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTERS MAKE MOTHER'S WISH COME TRUE: KEEP FAMILY TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At 5:30 p.m. in Bridgett Coburn's cozy _ some
might say cramped _ townhouse, it's dinnertime or homework time,
depending on which shift you are in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell!'' Coburn yells from the kitchen stove while dishing
up fried chicken and fries to the older children, who eat at the
table. She steps over younger children, who use candy for
accounting to do math problems on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is that boy?'' Coburn, 29, asks anyone who will answer.
Aside from a shrug or two, nobody does. Too busy eating and
figuring.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn says with a sigh: ``I'm ready for the next crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 11 children are Coburn's. Two belong to her sister.
</P>
<P>
   And seven are her brothers and sisters, the adopted children of
her mother, Audrey Hamp, who died Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn and her sister, Belinda Coburn, 36, are faced with
fulfilling their mother's Christmas wish: Keep the children
together.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenging gift to give to their dead mother. The
daughters are both single, working mothers. Both live in
two-bedroom townhouses, and neither has a car.
</P>
<P>
   One gets up at 4:30 a.m. to drive a school bus.
</P>
<P>
   How can they take on seven more children?
</P>
<P>
   Because they both remember something their mother would say at
dinnertime, when there was too little food and too many mouths _
especially when stray children from the neighborhood would come
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord will provide,'' Audrey Hamp would say.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Hamp, 11, is thankful to his older sisters and knows his
mother would be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved us a lot and would want us to stay together,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause to look at the floor, he added: ``I really miss
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, the signs of her impending death were clear, the
older sisters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama was in a big hurry to get her Christmas shopping done
this year,'' Belinda Coburn said at the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she kept telling us what the kids wanted,'' Bridgett
Coburn added.
</P>
<P>
   Hamp, 53, died of congestive heart failure. She'd had the
children more than seven years. Some came to her as crack babies;
some had been abused. She turned them into a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've come a long way,'' Audrey Hamp told her daughters
before her death. ``If anything happens to me, /{please/}, don't
send them back.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``please'' was a nice touch, but unnecessary. Audrey Hamp
was a strong, forceful woman. The daughters took her plea not as a
request but as an order.
</P>
<P>
   Even in death, these girls aren't about to cross their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Oh no, they both said shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama wouldn't appreciate that,'' Belinda Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   So their small two-bedroom townhouses, across from each other in
Blue Valley Courts just off 23rd Street, went from crowded to
/{really/} crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgett Coburn, already with two daughters of her own, took the
four girls, ages 7 to 12. Belinda Coburn, mother of two sons, took
the three boys, ages 9 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   After the holidays, they will both search for bigger places,
hopefully near each other.
</P>
<P>
   For now, they are making do. Children sleep two to a bed and
line up for the bathroom single file, just as at school. Clothes
hang in the basement because the closets are full.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters say it's easier to feed the whole bunch in one home
_ in shifts. That way, they can also help each other with homework.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cook, director of children and family services for
Catholic Charities in Kansas City, said such arrangements are
fairly common.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are situations all the time where relatives raise
children after a death,'' Cook said. ``A lot of families do this
and the state never gets involved _ as long as children thrive and
there's no abuse or neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are details that must be tended to.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance, for example.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Coburn sisters met with an attorney to ask
about keeping the children's Medicaid coverage.
</P>
<P>
   For children to receive benefits, either from Medicaid or
private health insurance, the caretaker would probably have to be
named as a legal guardian, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters plan to do that. It's just another change along with
bigger dinners, more laundry and less hot water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a struggle because they are so young,'' said
Vivian Rogers, a longtime friend of Hamp. ``But their mother gave
them roots, and these are strong girls.''
</P>
<P>
   It's early, Belinda Coburn acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm enjoying these kids right now,'' she said. ``When I
take care of them, I feel my mama's love.''
</P>
<P>
   James Meador, pastor of Hosanna Missionary Baptist Church, lays
down a challenge: ``You can't find anybody who will say a bad thing
about Audrey Hamp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right up until she got sick,'' Meador said. ``Even when she
would carry the oxygen with her, she was ready to help someone who
needed help.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those beautiful children...she had a special way with
children and you could see it in them.''
</P>
<P>
   And apparently she was the type of mother who never grew tired
of the job.
</P>
<P>
   When her four children were raised and gone from home, she
opened her door to foster children.
</P>
<P>
   But that arrangement wasn't permanent enough for her. So she
adopted the children in her care.
</P>
<P>
   People would ask, ``You raised your kids _ why do you want
more?''
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Hamp would smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``My blessing will go on,'' she would tell them.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be going on still. The children are healthy, do
well in school and they are ``Yes, sir,'' ``No, ma'am,'' ``Excuse
me'' kind of children.
</P>
<P>
   Older ones help the younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   Tasha Coburn, 13, Bridgett Coburn's daughter, says the new
arrangement has wrecked her hopes of getting a room of her own, but
that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how important is was to my Grandma for all the kids to
stick together,'' Tasha said.
</P>
<P>
   The children play together and study together. They stand in
line to brush their teeth and wash their faces.
</P>
<P>
   And at night before bed, they say their prayers. Perhaps they
give thanks for still being together.
</P>
<P>
   It was their mother's Christmas wish.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a gift that will last them a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
