<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF DAY CARE CENTERS IS ACCUSED OF OVERBILLING MEDICAID BY $62
MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state attorney general on Wednesday accused the
owner of two adult day care centers in Brooklyn of illegally
billing the Medicaid program for invented or inflated services
totaling $62 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 21-count indictment, the owner, Lawrence
Friedman, 52, and two associates churned almost 1,000 elderly
people a day through the centers during the course of three years.
They arranged door-to-door transportation, meals and entertainment
for them and billed Medicaid for their medical care, even though
many of the patients were in good health.
</P>
<P>
   Using a range of inducements, Friedman's company, the Parkshore
Adult Health Care Center in the Canarsie section of Brooklyn, lured
people, most of them Russian immigrants, to the centers,
prosecutors said. Once there, Friedman and his associates falsified
their medical records to make the registrants appear sicker,
provided them with door-to-door ambulette service that was not
medically necessary but for which the state paid. They also gave
elderly patients payments of $50, which the prosecutors called
kickbacks, for every friend they enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, the staff asked participants to ``dress down'' to
conceal their good health from Department of Health inspectors, and
even took almost 200 of them to see a movie, ``Titanic,'' in March
1998 to evade inspectors, the indictment states.
</P>
<P>
   Adult day care, a popular and cost-effective alternative to
nursing home care, is intended to provide daily physical therapy
and rehabilitation to the frail or disabled elderly who can still
live independently. In New York state, adult day care providers can
bill up to 65 percent of the normal nursing-home rate.
</P>
<P>
   However, Friedman built up his scheme so quickly that since July
1996, his billings have grown from $500,000 a year to $47 million
now, as he continually increased the number of registrants and the
amount he billed per person, said Eliot L. Spitzer, the attorney
general. In today's health marketplace, where an increase in
patients means an increase in profits, Friedman's two centers
accounted for a quarter of all state adult day-care billings.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman surrendered at the 69th Precinct in Canarsie and was
arraigned in Brooklyn Supreme Court on Wednesday, where bail was
set at $1 million. He pleaded not guilty. One of his lawyers, Randy
Mastro, a former deputy mayor, called him ``a respected businessman
and philanthropist, and a pillar of his community, who now stands
accused of crimes he did not commit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Friedman's facilities have been operated at all times in
full compliance with the applicable laws and regulations,'' Mastro
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
