<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, DEC. 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 13.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 13,
about the coming trial of Pakistan's ousted prime minister, Nawaz
Sharif, misidentified the location of Muscat, a city where Sharif
is said to have considered diverting a plane carrying Gen. Pervez
Musharraf, the army chief of staff, who later took over the
government. Muscat is in Oman, not in the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-RITALIN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 14,
about treatments for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder
misspelled the surname of the doctor who directed the study. He is
Dr. Peter S. Jensen, not Jenson.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the specialty of Dr. William Carey of
Children's Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania, who said the
drug Ritalin was overused. He is a pediatrician, not a child
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PUERTORICO-NAVY-NYT (moved on Saturday, Dec. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Dec. 4,
about the growing political power of Puerto Ricans referred
incompletely to the educational background of a Puerto Rico
Senator, Ruben Berrios Martinez. In addition to studying at
Harvard, Oxford and Georgetown Law School, Berrios graduated from
Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ART-NOTES-NYT (moved on Thursday, Dec. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Dec. 9,
misidentified the architect for the planned expansion of the Asia
Society building on Park Avenue. He is Bartholomew Voorsanger;
Edward Larrabee Barnes designed the original 1981 building.
</P>
</TEXT>
