<HEADER>
A0545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-KINGS-NYT     12-15 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CRUSH KINGS, 8-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crowd was still filing into Madison Square Garden
as the first period was winding down. The game had a rare 7 o'clock
start, and as the fans hurried to their seats, they probably did a
double-take upon seeing the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rangers 6, Kings 0. Only 18 minutes 43 seconds had
elapsed, and the game was over. The Rangers went on to an 8-0 lead
in the second period and finally to an 8-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seemed to join in the fun. Todd Harvey and John MacLean
each doubled their previous season production with two goals. Tim
Taylor, Mike Knuble, Theo Fleury and Michael York scored the other
goals as all four lines contributed at least one goal.
</P>
<P>
   The power play, a sore point all season, even scored twice for
the first time in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Watching with glee at the other end of the ice was Mike Richter,
who turned aside 31 Los Angeles shots over the first two periods
before allowing three third-period goals in stretching his unbeaten
string to five (4-0-1). Not coincidentally, the Rangers' record
over that span is a season high. The Rangers evened their home
record at 7-7-1 and, over all, they are 11-14-1 with .500 again in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to look at the standings again,'' said Taylor, who
admitted it has been embarrassing for him to do so for much of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Rangers scored six goals in one period was
Dec. 26, 1998, in a 6-3 victory at Carolina. Not since Oct. 30,
1988 _ in a 9-2 rout of Pittsburgh _ had the Rangers scored six
first-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   The most goals the Rangers ever scored in a period was eight on
Nov. 21, 1971, in the third period of a 12-1 thrashing of the
former California Golden Seals. The last time the Rangers scored
eight unanswered goals was Nov. 25, 1992, in an 11-3 victory over
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   And to think Coach John Muckler was worried before the game that
his club might be a little rusty because it were coming off a
six-day break without a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great first period,'' he said. ``It was the best
first period we've played all year. We skated well, we moved well,
we created some great chances and we scored some power-play goals.
We seemed to have a lot of jump tonight in the first period.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Rangers were facing a Kings team that had
been taken apart, 7-1, by the New Jersey Devils the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings came in with a league-leading 22 points on
the road, they did not look like one of the National Hockey
League's bigger surprises this season on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Storr started in goal, less than 24 hours after he had
been yanked after allowing three goals in one period in New Jersey.
Storr fared even worse on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey opened the scoring at 4:58 of the first period. Eric
Lacroix and MacLean were awarded assists on the play, but the
biggest assist belonged to Kevin Stevens, who did everything but
score the goal himself.
</P>
<P>
   Parked in front of the net, Stevens had two Kings on him and his
stick between Storr's legs. He also had Storr screened. Harvey's
shot went through Stevens' stick, Storr's stick, Storr's skates and
in. And the Rangers led 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Taylor's goal at 13:45, the Rangers scored two
more goals in 38 seconds; three goals in 3:01; four goals in 4:01;
five goals in 4:58. In one stretch, the Rangers scored three goals
(their third, fourth and fifth) on three consecutive shots.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Rangers scored 6 goals on 17 shots against Storr,
who was again yanked after one period in favor of Stephane Fiset.
</P>
</TEXT>
